<SLUG> BC-KID-DEATH-INDICTMENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grand jury to hear case against dead kids' mom
 &HT;    By Christian Davenport
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Williamson County prosecutors seeking to indict
Tina Marie Cornelius _ whose children died, authorities say, after
she left them injured in a creek bed _ will present their case to a
grand jury today.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius was charged with two counts of abandoning a child
after police found her in a Corpus Christi apartment April 28 _
nine days after her children were found dead in Brushy Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsies found that Amanda Lee Miller, 3, suffocated and that
Dominick Logan Cornelius, 2, died of a fractured skull. A Round
Rock couple found their bodies in the creek just south of Hutto,
about 20 miles northeast of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Ken Anderson said the grand jury, which is
expected to consider the case until the end of June, could produce
other charges, but he would not elaborate. Nor would he comment on
who injured the children or who brought them to the creek.
</P>
<P>
   He said he will call and question Capt. Linda Bunte, the head of
the county's criminal investigations division, and present about an
hour's worth of testimony starting at 11 a.m. He said he would not
call any other witnesses today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do everything we can to get all the facts and
get them correct,'' Anderson said. ``And when we get them figured
out, we'll ask the grand jury to return any charges that are
justified by the evidence. It's my hope we will find out who is
responsible for the death of these children.''
</P>
<P>
   Since her arrest, Cornelius has been held in Williamson County
Jail in lieu of $200,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   A criminal complaint filed in court states that Cornelius told
investigators she saw her children ``when they were injured and
lying in the creek bed or ditch.'' The complaint charges that she
left them there and ``indicated that she did not go back to help
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Rhea, Cornelius' court-appointed attorney, declined to
comment on the specifics of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius moved to Austin from Parker, Ariz., about two years
ago. Once here, she worked at a pizza restaurant and a beauty
supply store and as a waitress. She attended auto mechanics classes
and told her co-workers in a Wal-Mart automotive department that
she hoped one day to work as a mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   She also worked as an exotic dancer, and employees of a topless
bar, said she worked the day after her children were found lying
lifeless in Brushy Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Two daysbefore the bodies of her children were found, Cornelius
met an Austin glass installer at a downtown music festival. That
man has said she told him that her children died after falling off
a cliff while with one of the children's fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, about April 21 or 22, she went to Corpus
Christi, where Mauricio Alaniz, 31, said he met her at a carnival.
In an interview, Alaniz said she told him that her boyfriend took
her children and she did not know whether they were dead or alive.
</P>
<P>
   Alaniz said he spent almost five days with Cornelius before
police found her in his friend's apartment and brought her in for
questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Davenport writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
