<HEADLINE>
MONDESI ON THE RISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ This is dangerous ground. Everyone wants to be so
careful. It is as if they all agree upon the desired destination,
yet to actually discuss the journey is taboo.
</P>
<P>
   But with each passing week, Raul Mondesi is making it more
difficult to worry about some imagined jinx. It could be real this
time. Mondesi could be ready to take that leap from very good
player to superstar.
</P>
<P>
   The same way the Cubs' Sammy Sosa fulfilled long-held high
expectations by exploding to the next level last season, the
Dodgers right fielder could be poised for a breakout year.
</P>
<P>
   No one claims Mondesi is on the way to a 60-homer season, but he
just might be on the verge of something special, of reaching some
new rarefied air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's knocking at the door of greatness,'' said Dodgers
general manager Kevin Malone. ``Being a great player means you have
to be consistent and do it over the course of time. But he's
definitely right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi has always been considered a very good player. He oozes
ability, plays hard, loves the game. The 1994 NL Rookie of the Year
has averaged 25 home runs and 86 RBI and batted .295 during his
five full seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Yet more was always expected. For all he's done, he could appear
somewhat raw _ as if there was more to be tapped, some deeper
reservoir of ability fully surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Now Mondesi is making noise as though he were ready to hone all
that almost- envied potential. He came out of the weekend tied with
Arizona's Jay Bell for the National League lead in home runs (13),
was fourth in RBI (32) and seventh in runs (28). No Dodger has been
the NL home run champ since Duke Snider hit 43 for Brooklyn in
1956. Mondesi is also hitting .281 and has nine stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's already one of the stars of the game,'' said Cubs manager
Jim Riggleman. ``To go to the level of Sosa and (Ken) Griffey and
(Mark) McGwire, certainly I think he's going to make that next
step.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's this year or not, I don't know, but he's going to
be one of the superstars of the game. He's going to put up numbers
that just can't be ignored, because he can do it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Dodgers, though, are reluctant to discuss his rising
status, as if the pressure and spotlight could turn this into
another false start in joining the game's elite.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson seems almost uncomfortable with
the topic. ``He's hit some home runs before, hasn't he?'' Johnson
said. Johnson briefly moved Mondesi from cleanup to fifth in the
lineup last month when he appeared to press.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, 28, spoke boldly of wanting to become the NL MVP after
a strong '97 season but now is trying to eliminate boasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to try and do my job every day and not say too much,''
he said. ``I'm trying to do something different. I want to play my
game the way I've been playing. Play hard every day, try to give
100 percent each game and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   What's been happening early this season is, the less he talks
and the more he plays, the more others talk about him.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi has always been known as a wild swinger, but Dodgers
coach Manny Mota said much of his success this season can be
attributed to his finally chasing fewer bad pitches and being more
selective at the plate. He sees no limit to a disciplined Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still growing, he's still learning, still improving,''
Mota said. ``There's always room to get better, and he's doing
that. He's showing you what patience can do for you, and being
selective. And he's not losing any of his aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the potential, in my opinion, to be the best player in
the business. He has that kind of ability and tools. He can put
everything together; he has a chance do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's skills, his Dominican background and a possible
breakout season, have many comparing him to Sosa, who made a
similar jump last year with his 66-home run season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a natural comparison,'' Riggleman said.
``Physically they're quite a bit alike. They both have tremendous
power, they're five-tool players. Both of them can steal a base,
throw, play defense, hit for average, power. There are a lot of
similarities. As young players coming in, they did good things, but
they're just got better and better. ''
</P>
<P>
   Said Malone: ``I think it's a good comparison. I think Raul has
as much ability, or more. Sammy had a great year last year. I think
he's matured as a hitter himself. I mean, years ago the book on
Sammy was he would chase about anything out of the strike zone.
Last year he laid off some pitches, got some good pitches to hit
and showed a lot more discipline at the plate. And I think that's
what you're seeing this year with Raul.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi and Sosa, however, would rather avoid any comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player, a five-tool player and in some ways he
compares to me,'' Sosa said. ``Right now, he's swinging the bat
real well and doing great. But I don't let people compare me to
anybody. I never really notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on the way up. I hope he continues taking care of
business. It's a long season, there's a long ways to go and I just
hope he continues . . . doing a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi shakes his head at the mere suggestion he compares to
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why? Why do you have to do that?'' he asked. ``I want to be
Mondesi. I don't want to be like anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is saying, `You can do great this year,' and then
next year you don't do (anything). I want to play at least 10 more
years. Barry Bonds, he never hit 60 homers and he's the best player
in baseball to me. Tony Gwynn, he never hit 35-40 (homers) and he's
got 3,000 hits and is going into the Hall of Fame. You don't have
to hit 70 homers to be a great player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never hit 40, but people have a lot of respect for me.
That's what I need. I don't want to be the hero all the time. I
want to do my job and get respect from the people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 0010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1071 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      05-18 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
With the shortest NBA season giving way to a longer-than-expected
offseason, the Rockets on Monday finally had some time on their
hands.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In considering changes, they have time to plot every strategy,
study every free agent and view tape of every collegian. They can
call staff meetings until they believe themselves trapped in the
lockout again.
</P>
<P>
   But when it's time to act, they will likely find there is little
they can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever feel like our hands our tied,'' Rockets vice
president Robert Barr said. ``I always feel we'll be able to pull
something off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's the harder way. There have to be trades to change
things. We have two exceptions (to the salary cap). We're not going
to get a big-time star with a $2 million exception. But I feel we
have to do something to put us back on top. I'm not going to settle
for where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr is not alone in his hopes to change the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to need some personnel changes,'' forward
Scottie Pippen said. ``I think we can be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Pippen thinks a complete overhaul is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myself, Charles (Barkley) and Dream (Hakeem Olajuwon), we're
guys that know our way around the game,'' Pippen said. ``I don't
think age is a factor. When we play together and play well
together, we're pretty dominant.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that didn't happen as often as the Rockets would
have liked down the stretch in 1999. And their first-round playoff
exit would indicate they weren't quite the title contenders they
proclaimed themselves to be. Still, any changes will more likely
constitute tinkering rather than rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were close but just couldn't get over the hump,'' coach
Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``That was something I really wanted for
this team. I liked this team a lot. It was a great bunch of guys.
They got along very well. And I thought our chemistry was good
considering very little practice time. There wasn't much time,
especially for those young kids to get into a comfort zone to where
they worked on things and really understood the system.''
</P>
<P>
   That will change. However, the roster likely will not change
much. Already over the salary cap and with 11 players under
contract, the Rockets will try to improve with more subtle
adjustments than this past season's addition of Pippen and the
sudden changing of the guards to an all-rookie backcourt of Cuttino
Mobley and Michael Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   Under the two salary-cap exceptions, the Rockets can sign one
free agent for as much as $2 million and another for up to $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to look at our options and what they are and what
is presented,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I'm not going to say we're in a
panic situation. I think we're moving in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   In regard to their own free agents _ Barkley, Sam Mack, Anthony
``Pig'' Miller and Stanley Roberts _ the Rockets must wait for
Barkley to make a decision about retirement and will likely pursue
Mack.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said he did not want to return unless the Rockets had a
legitimate championship chance, maintaining that he, Pippen and
Olajuwon would be less likely to carry a team next season than this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles and I talked about it,'' Barr said. ``This is the
first time I felt he was kind of serious (about retiring). In time,
when the dust settles, hopefully we'll get him back. I can't
imagine him not being here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He scared me a little this time. He may hang it up. I'm real
concerned with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barkley has a history of bringing up retirement moments
after a disappointing playoff defeat and then returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we played Charles in the playoffs back in '94 and 95, he
was talking about retirement then,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I've heard
it before.''
</P>
<P>
   A key trade-deadline addition, Mack returned to the Rockets with
a more professional manner than he displayed in his first stint
with the team. But they must decide if Mack would perform as well
with the long-term deal he seeks as he did in the last season of a
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Sam Mack earned a spot,'' Barr said. ``It was a great
trade for us. He obviously can shoot the ball. Sam plays hard. He
helped us out a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   There are few high-profile free agents to chase, especially with
no more than $2 million to offer. And with few high-dollar players
on the market, teams with more money available might further
diminish the free agents the Rockets could afford.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Richmond and Terrell Brandon are the big-name guards but
will almost surely be out of the Rockets' price range. The likes of
Haywoode Workman and Sherman Douglas might be looking for the sort
of contract the Rockets could offer.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets are more likely to do their free-agent shopping
in the frontcourt, where candidates will have to accept that a
starter's spot is likely out of reach. Gary Trent could be an
attractive possibility, because the Mavericks cannot offer more
than the Rockets. Tyrone Nesby, John Wallace, Rodney Rogers, Cedric
Ceballos, Corliss Williamson or Bo Outlaw could be targeted if
interested in the Rockets' limited playing time and finances. Among
the top free-agent forwards out of the Rockets' range are Joe
Smith, Grant Long and, if he opts for free agency, Vin Baker.
</P>
<P>
   The draft offers similar limits. The Rockets have three picks,
but the first is at No. 22 in a year that figures to offer 13 to 15
players in the upper echelon. The Rockets' other two picks are in
the second round.
</P>
<P>
   So with free-agent and rookie options limited, most of the
improvement will have to come from within. But the Rockets believe
that can happen, considering they won't be rushed like they were
this season, trying to establish a role for the difficult-to-define
Pippen while integrating seven other newcomers, including two
rookie starters, into the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel with the additions we made to this team this year we
made steps in the right direction,'' Tomjanovich said. ``We
improved our win-loss percentage by 12 points. We did a lot better
defensively. Offensively, we were one of the better teams with
field-goal percentage. We improved in number of rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were still (ranked) low on offensive rebounds, turnovers
were high, and I really felt we drafted to get more athletic and to
be a running team. That's an area that we can really improve on. We
wound up getting more (fast) breaks as the year went on, but our
efficiency wasn't as high as it should have been. All those things
are things we'll try to work on in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' young guards, Tomjanovich said, will especially
benefit from a full training camp, the summer tournament that in
1998 was a lockout casualty, and the usual growth heading into a
second season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's such a tremendous jump from your first year to your
second,'' Tomjanovich said. ``This year should be even more. That
light bulb, really getting it, will turn on.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich also will have time to address changes in the
Rockets' style. Barkley, if he returns, and Olajuwon will still be
used in the low post. But Tomjanovich said he does not want to
depend on that part of the offense as heavily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we were a better pick-and-roll team,'' he said. ``(But)
first of all, the running. That's something every team I've ever
been involved with wants to do. That's something you've got to work
at. Running just to be running isn't a positive. You've got to get
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you can do in my position is go out and try to do your
best. You look at your personnel, try to put them in an environment
they can do the best we can. The system is the players we have. If
I had different players, I would be doing different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Rockets become uncharacteristically trade-happy,
however, he will for the most part have the same players. Whether
subtle changes can bring a big improvement remains to be seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
