<HEADER>
A1072 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BICKLEY-COLUMN-ELECTI     05-18 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BICKLEY-COLUMN-ELECTION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA TEAMS FACING D-DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sociologists once marveled at the healing property of sports.
How differences in class and race evaporated once fans passed
through a turnstile. How the simple act of cheering for a team
galvanized entire communities.
</P>
<P>
   Ever laughed at a neighbor who painted a team logo on his
garage?
</P>
<P>
   It is D-Day for two franchises, and now all you see are signs
stuck in the earth. Say Yes! Say No! Save Your Team! Save Your
City!
</P>
<P>
   And what once united now divides.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime earlier in the decade, sports gave birth to a terrible
trend, the publicly financed stadium. Among the greatest causes of
spectator angst, the catalyst for severed relationships between a
sports franchise and its community.
</P>
<P>
   It is out of control. In Arizona, one owner already has fallen
from grace; a politician already has taken a bullet in the backside
as payment for a pro-stadium vote. It won't stop until every
professional team in every sport has its own new facility. And it's
too late to change.
</P>
<P>
   You either build them a house or they leave, and as you leave
your own home today, that is very much the ultimatum from the
Cardinals and Coyotes. But really, no hard feelings. Eventually, it
will happen to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Ever seen a driver ride the merge lane as far as possible,
enraging every motorist patiently waiting in line? Ever noticed how
a wave of copycats inevitably follow the lead? And how they all get
there much faster than you?
</P>
<P>
   That's what is happening here. The Cardinals and the Coyotes are
not trying to set a precedent. They're trying to get in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Think, for a moment, how much smaller sports would be without
publicly financed stadiums. The game would discipline itself back
to the market. Salaries would be somewhat in check.
</P>
<P>
   But after the first ripple of con jobs, it was over. Soon, some
owners were playing with Monopoly money while others were paying
rent. Another wedge between the haves and have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   And now, every owner needs a new stadium to compete with the
colleagues who do, those who have already won their elections.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, it is a defining day in Arizona history. A day that
will shape the future of its sports. A day that will carry much
meaning for franchise thieves, out-of-state owners and
trend-watchers across the country. But win or lose, there is no
turning back.
</P>
<P>
   In football-mad Denver, a winning team and John Elway's lobbying
were enough to make a new stadium palatable. A World Series
appearance did the trick for San Diego, until owners singed voters
by gutting the team.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, the resentment is thick, and some are harking the
death of democracy, accusing Paul Allen of buying an election for
the Seahawks. The same Paul Allen who could privately finance 10
stadiums and still be one of the richest men in history.
</P>
<P>
   And in San Francisco, the good will is over. In 1997, after the
49ers won an election for their new stadium by a mere 1,500 votes,
it was discovered that nine dead people had cast votes. Activists
claim that number was more like 2,000. A lawsuit followed, a judge
turned his head and the 49ers will have their $325 million crib by
2002.
</P>
<P>
   The hostage game played by Robert Kraft and the Patriots has
splintered the Northeast. In Chicago, about 8,000 people a night
are coming to see the White Sox play at Comiskey Park, a stadium
built on notorious arm-twisting politics.
</P>
<P>
   It never ends, and it never really goes away.
</P>
<P>
   This time, there are no signs of foul play in Arizona. Just two
franchises asking for your vote. But the lingering resentment is
out there.
</P>
<P>
   The era of franchise free agency has taken over, gobbling up
everything in sight. Leaving behind waves of ill will for teams
that prevail at the polls, and waves of regret for those that slip
away.
</P>
<P>
   So it's yes or no, friend or foe, and unless a championship is
in the distance, nobody's painting their garage anymore. And while
a sports team will always galvanize its fan base, this is clearly
an era that strains the bond between franchise and community. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 0044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
