<HEADER>
A1073 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASSTEVENS-COLUMN-ELE     05-18 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASSTEVENS-COLUMN-ELECT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAYING NO CARRIES COST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time, a large city was home to a professional
football team.
</P>
<P>
   Fans loved the team. They didn't love the owner.
</P>
<P>
   The owner was perceived as miserly and not very likable. It
seemed like the only time the public saw him was when the team
called a news conference to announce the owner had fired another
coach.
</P>
<P>
   The owner went through coaches the way Henry VIII went through
wives.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the team and its faithful endured some hard
times. But there were good times, too.
</P>
<P>
   When the team won and made the playoffs, the excitement
energized the city and brought the community together as only a
winning sports team can.
</P>
<P>
   Home games sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day, the owner announced he wanted a new downtown
stadium. The owner said the place where his team had played for
years _ christened The Eighth Wonder of the World _ was inferior,
even after millions of taxpayer dollars had been spent to add seats
and suites.
</P>
<P>
   New stadium? Forget it, the public said. The mayor vowed not to
spend public money to appease greedy sports owners.
</P>
<P>
   So the owner moved the team.
</P>
<P>
   He went to another city that offered him everything he wanted. A
new stadium with 67,000 seats and 140 luxury suites and concessions
and parking revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The jilted city shrugged. Let 'em leave. Good riddance.
</P>
<P>
   What's the old country song? ``Thank God and Greyhound She's
Gone''.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs a team? Football isn't essential.
</P>
<P>
   But those who believed it was took heart in the hope that the
city would get another team soon _ as if acquiring one was as
simple as hailing the next taxi cab.
</P>
<P>
   The city began adjusting to life without the NFL. It could watch
other teams play on Sunday. Follow other teams into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The local newspaper conducted a poll. Did readers want the paper
to make their old team _ the one that had moved _ central to its
NFL coverage?
</P>
<P>
   More than 30,000 responded. Two-thirds said not no, but hell no.
They didn't want to be reminded that the team wasn't theirs
anymore. That Steve McNair and Eddie George now played for someone
else.
</P>
<P>
   Out of sight, out of mind. Forget the old team. We'll get a
``new'' one.
</P>
<P>
   A rich businessman announced he would spend $400 million to buy
an expansion team. If the NFL awarded him one, he ``guaranteed'' a
sellout at every home game for five years.
</P>
<P>
   The county voted to fund a new downtown major league baseball
stadium ``and'' a new football palace that would be built if the
NFL awarded the city a team.
</P>
<P>
   An $85,000 scale model of the proposed football stadium was
displayed at this year's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But the ready cash and stadium plans and sellout guarantee
didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL gave Cleveland one expansion team. Los Angeles, with the
nation's second-largest TV market, got the other.
</P>
<P>
   So the city without a team looked to other avenues.
</P>
<P>
   The wealthy businessman sent letters to eight NFL owners. ``Dear
Sir, are you interested in selling your team? If so, I would like
to buy it . . .''
</P>
<P>
   He mailed inquiries to the Bears, Eagles, Colts, Raiders,
Vikings, Bills, Patriots and Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no takers. The Cardinals owner said he wasn't interested
in selling and moving his team again.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wanted to stay here and play in his own new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   So Houston sits.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-largest city in the country waits.
</P>
<P>
   And pretends it doesn't miss the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Will the city get a team?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: The price tag will far exceed the cost of
keeping the team it had.
</P>
<P>
   Just something to think about when we go to the polls today. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1074 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ASUDYNASTY-AZR &LR;      05-18 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ASU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE DEVILS THEIR DUE IN NCAA GOLF  
 WOMEN'S TEAM LOOKS FOR 7TH TITLE IN '90S 
</HEADLINE>
 DYNASTY-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a women's college golf program produces 61 All-Pac-10
selections, 37 All-Americans and 14 members of the LPGA Tour, the
conclusion is pretty obvious:
</P>
<P>
   These women are good.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite all of her success stories, Arizona State Coach
Linda Vollstedt still relies on a little luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, with the talent so deep at so many schools, you
can never have enough of it,'' said the superstitious Vollstedt,
whose tournament traditions go back to 1990, the first of a record
six NCAA golf titles.
</P>
<P>
   That was the season that Steve Loy, the former ASU men's golf
coach, gave Vollstedt her ``good luck tennis shoes,'' complete with
emblems of Sun Devils mascot Sparky on the heels. That also was the
year Vollstedt urged her boss, Herman Frazier, to give her team the
first of many inspirational pep talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure why Linda wanted me to speak to the girls that
year because she is such a great motivator herself,'' said Frazier,
a former track star for the Sun Devils who is the school's
associate athletic director. ``But for whatever reason, I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember she wanted me to show them my 1977 NCAA
championship ring, maybe give them a reason to get one for
themselves. Now I'm there (at the NCAA Tournament) for Linda and
her teams almost every year. And when I don't show up, she gets
down on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Frazier hasn't missed many. He plans to report this
week to Tulsa, where Vollstedt's team will be seeking its second
three-peat in the past seven years. Although not the favorites, the
fifth-ranked Sun Devils, (Grace Park, Caroline Laurens, Jody
Niemann, Tui Selvaratnam and Keri Cornelius) are a definite threat
in the 72-hole tournament that runs Wednesday through Saturday at
Tulsa Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say there's an outside chance that Linda will have her
team ready to go,'' deadpanned Rick LaRose, Arizona's director of
golf, who this year gave up the dual responsibility of coaching the
men's and women's teams to concentrate on the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our (No. 2-ranked) women are the best team in the
country,'' LaRose said. ``But for some reason, Linda always gets
her girls up for nationals. In a sense, she's got them right where
she wants them _ again.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it the residual effects of a dynasty. Even during an
``off'' year in 1998-99, when the Sun Devils won only one
tournament, and more recently posted back-to-back, third-place
finishes in the Pac-10 and West Regional, they must be reckoned
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's hard to envision yourself 20 years down the
road,'' said Vollstedt, who became ASU's coach in 1980. ``You never
really expect to create a dynasty. But I was so determined back
then to make it work that I actually had the audacity to think
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vollstedt played for ASU when golf was a club sport during the
mid-1960s. After graduating in 1969, she went back to earn her
master's degree in math in '71.
</P>
<P>
   Her coaching career actually began in the prep ranks, where one
of her stars at Alhambra High School, Lauri Merten, and Merten's
father, George, helped Vollstedt land the job at ASU. Lauri Merten
was one of those All-Pac-10, All-America, LPGA players who was
mentored by Vollstedt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew right away that I had a passion for it,'' Vollstedt
recalled. ``But it was tough in the beginning. I only made $9,000
each of the first two years. I had to sell my stocks, dip into my
life savings, and even sell some land to keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was a turning point, she said, it was recruiting the
late Heather Farr, who had been a superstar at Xavier College
Preparatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heather really put us on the map and kept recruiting for us
after she left,'' Vollstedt said. ``A lot of good things started to
fall into place during that time (the mid-1980s), even though it
took a while to finally win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the reign came, it never ended. One good team kept
leading to another, and Vollstedt has passed Pat Summitt, the
Tennessee basketball coach, to become the winningest female coach
in college sports during the 1990s. Summitt's teams have won five
times during the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six national championships? Not in your wildest dreams,'' said
Vollstedt, who never takes anything for granted. ``For the longest
time, my only thought was, `Let's win one.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier said he knows exactly why Vollstedt's success
snowballed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linda's very competitive, but she's also very selective about
the kind of kid she takes into her program,'' he said. ``She
doesn't take just good athletes. She takes good people who have
high standards and are all business.''
</P>
<P>
   Vollstedt puts it like this: ``I'm looking for a player who
wants to play the (LPGA) tour, wants to dig deeper, loves the game
and has a great attitude. That's a tough combination to find, but I
know it when I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Park, who will be the driving force in Tulsa, is one of those
players who met Vollstedt's rules of recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks Coach is demanding, but to me, she's very
easy to talk to,'' said Park, a sophomore who might turn pro
depending on this week's results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that a lot of players on other teams don't feel like
they have very good communication with their coaches. But Linda
gets very individual with each of us, pumps us up, and makes every
one of us feel special. That's hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Vollstedt will have none of it. Far more difficult, at least to
her, is keeping her lucky tennis shoes on her feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah! I've got them packed,'' she said, getting serious at
the thought. ``But they're so old that I'm going to have to get
some new laces if they're going to stay on my feet. And they
``are'' going to stay on my feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Like everything else with Linda Vollstedt, count on it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1075 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHALE-HUNT-2TAKES-SPI     05-18 1795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALE-HUNT-2TAKES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ONE THRUST OF HARPOON, MAKAH INDIANS RETURN TO WHALING ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE, PAUL SHUKOVSKY AND MICHAEL BARBER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEAH BAY _ For the first time in the memory of all but the
oldest Makah, tribal canoes pulled a gray whale into this Indian
village on Monday after the first successful hunt of the huge
animals in generations.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of tribal members _ from elders bent with age to babies
in their fathers' arms _ lined the beach in a greeting that was
both solemn and chaotic. Prayers were spoken. One Indian did a back
flip off the 30-foot dead whale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the Makah have brought the whale home,'' tribal elder
George Bowechop told the crowd. ``From this day forward, we need to
stand behind our leaders... to be a living culture.''
</P>
<P>
   With grunts, tribal members hauled the animal ashore on Monday
night and began butchering it to the sound of an ancient Makah
song.
</P>
<P>
   The triumphant beaching of the animal was the day's culmination
of history-making events.
</P>
<P>
   It began in eight minutes of fury that will spark controversy
for years to come. Tribal hunters caught and killed the whale near
Father and Son Rocks in the Pacific off Olympic National Park about
7 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal members in a hand-hewn cedar canoe and nearby motor boats
used three harpoons and two shots from a high-caliber rifle to
accomplish the first successful whale hunt by the Makah since the
1920s. The seas around the 30-ton animal ran red with its blood as
it died.
</P>
<P>
   Protest boats that had tried for a week to interrupt the hunt
and scare off the whales were nowhere to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   No whale hunt has been launched from the lower 48 states since
the last commerical whaling stations in California closed in the
1970s. Other hunts likely will follow from this remote reservation.
Through an agreement brokered by the United States, the Makah can
kill up to 20 whales through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than more tribal hunts, individual families are now
expected to begin hunting. The family hunts will take training, and
the gray whales will soon end their seasonal migration this spring
and be in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three or four families are lining up to go hunting,'' said
Marcy Parker, a former member of the tribal council. ``We've got 19
(whales) to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In Neah Bay, the kill was a seminal event so filled with pride
and history that children abandonded their classrooms and adults
their jobs. For once, the eyes of the world focused on this
isolated, poverty-stricken Indian village for what its residents
had accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud. I'm proud of the group that did this,'' said Joe
Jimmicum, a Makah tribal member who waited earlier in the day to
help get the whale on the beach. ``This is one for the Makahs.''
</P>
<P>
   As news of the successful hunt spread, Indian tribes from around
the Northwest sent representatives to Neah Bay to help the tribe
celebrate the affirmation of its whaling rights set out in an 1855
treaty with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the outside world, however, the successful hunt was
a day of sadness and outrage. In Congress, friends and foes of the
tribe expressed regret, and some wondered whether it would hurt the
tribe's ability to get federal grants.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-whaling activists who battled the hunt with a collection of
boats small and large could express only anger at the kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, with speed boats, military weaponry and the draconian
assistance of the U.S. government in stifling all dissent, American
whalers managed to blast a whale out of existence in American
waters on the pretext of cultural privilege,'' said Paul Watson,
president of the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society.
</P>
<P>
   At a cabin in nearby Sekui, Wash., where whaling protesters have
gathered for months, Port Angeles resident Don Munson stood outside
with his head dropped in grief while others cried and embraced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so hard,'' Munson said softly. ``It's like a child
dying.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebration began just after 5:30 p.m., when five canoes
towed the carcass of the whale to the village's stoney beach. Four
of the canoes were from the Tulalip, Puyallup, Hoh and Quileute
tribes. The last was the Hummingbird, the Makah's whale-hunting
canoe.
</P>
<P>
   Theron Parker, harpooner, stood in the boat stripped to the
waist, holding his paddle aloft. Sea lions barked and played
nearby. About 125 cars lined the streets and hundreds more spilled
out into the nearby parking lots. Yellow crime-scene tape held back
dozens of reporters and photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Some tribal members in the canoes began to jump for joy into the
cold waters of the bay. Others climbed atop the whale where they
stood with arms raised.
</P>
<P>
   Whaler Darrell Markishtum raised his fist to the sky and
shouted. Makah youngsters waded into the water next to the carcass
and gingerly touched the enormous beast. Some pounded the animal
with closed fists.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal chairman Ben Johnson Jr. told the cheering crowd, ``We've
faced a lot of hostilites. We held our heads high. And now we can
go and do it all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker walked slowly from the water, wearing a ceremonial
cedarbark headgear with eagle down sprinkled on his head.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Parker spoke to reporters: ``We prepared for
about a year. We prayed to our creator.'' Monday was ``a pretty
proud day for all the Makah nation.''
</P>
<P>
   He made his way to a car in which tribal elder John Hottowe, 76,
sat.
</P>
<P>
   Hottowe clutched a shaman's rattle and said of Parker: ``He was
just starting out and did not understand the spiritual ways. He was
really very vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   At 7 p.m., the Makah pulled the whale onto the beach. Parker
followed tradition, getting the first and choicest cut of the
dorsal hump. He will dry the meat, decorate it and hang it in a
place of honor in his home.
</P>
<P>
   The next cuts went to members of the whaling crew, then the rest
of the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal members chanted ``hey yah, hey yah'' to the rhythmic
beats of elk-hide drums.
</P>
<P>
   Crew members made vertical cuts along the flank of the beached
whale. Some men had small pieces of skin and blubber in their
fingers and were chewing on the flesh. Others held the drums,
painted with totem symbols, aloft, and beat them while the skin,
blubber and meat were distributed to tribal members who encircled
the whale.
</P>
<P>
   Two teenage boys sampled the meat. One said ``this tastes
terrible.'' The other replied: ``Just stick it in your mouth and
chew it.''
</P>
<P>
   As men sweated and smoked cigarettes, they quickly cut big
chunks of steaming meat off the carcass. Chunks of blubber were
passed around the crowd and many people took tentative chews of the
rubbery fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chewy'' said one man, who described the taste as slightly
nutty.
</P>
<P>
   A number of people spit their chewy samples onto the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the whale will be saved for a potlach dinner that the
tribe plans to hold later this week for tribes around the
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Preparation for Monday's hunt began with prayers Sunday night
for better fortune.
</P>
<P>
   On May 10 and again Saturday, tribal hunters stalked the whales,
but failed to land one.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, tribal crews intended to kill a whale as they
migrated from Alaska to Mexico, but bad weather kept the crews on
shore.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe has been talking about and preparing to kill a whale
since at least 1994, when the growing number of gray whales
prompted the U.S. government to remove them from the endangered
species list.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, tribal members held a prayer circle. Tribal member
Spencer McCarty prayed for each member of the whaling crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night,'' said tribal member Joe McGimpsey, ``we had
prayers and passed around a harpoon from my
great-great-grandfather.''
</P>
<P>
   The portents were good. Andy Williams, a member of the Tulalip
Tribe in Neah Bay to offer support to the Makah, dreamed that a
whale would be taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a big celebration _ many songs and dances,'' Williams
said. ``The spirit of the water is still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The crew aboard the Hummingbird, the black and red whaling
canoe, paddled out into the Pacific early yesterday morning. At
other times, a motorized support boat towed the canoe into the
ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The early morning seas were flat, protected by an easterly wind
by the high mountains over Cape Flattery and down the coast.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:54 a.m., the Hummingbird's bow was just above a whale.
Parker drove his harpoon into the animal as it swam beneath him.
The animal swam under the canoe as it pulled out line and brightly
colored buoys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It couldn't have been any better. It was just like we prayed
for,'' said Eric Johnson, a former whaling captain following the
canoe in a motor boat.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the canoe seemed surprised that the harpoon entered
so easily, Johnson said. The whale passed under the canoe, and with
a toss of its tail could have tossed the paddlers into the ocean.
But it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Johnson in the support boat fired a high-caliber rifle at
the animal repeatedly. The first two shots missed, the second two
hit their mark.
</P>
<P>
   A government biologist said one bullet hit the whale's brain,
the other shattered its skull. The whale was a 3-year-old,
non-lactating female, meaning it did not have a calf.
</P>
<P>
   The animal thrashed, exposing its belly in the gray morning
light. The quiet and blood came next.
</P>
<P>
   In the support boats, tribal members cheered and exchanged high
fives.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the support boats, Arnie Hunter, a former Marine, a
traditional chief of Neah Bay and a whaling commission member,
raised his arms and smiled. His face showed elation and relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flooded with energy,'' Hunter said. ``This is bringing
the tribe back in a complete circle. It's the missing link in our
heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   The crew in the canoe was quiet for a moment. Soon, they began
to cheer and hug. They broke out into their whaling song, which one
tribal member said sounded like the barks of sea lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easy,'' said Markishtum, a member of the Hummingbird
crew, said from the decks of the Heidi, a fishing boat that towed
the whale back to Neah Bay. ``The whale gave up his life freely. He
didn't fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Others repeated those sentiments in town. Tradition holds that
Makah pray that the whale would give itself up to the hunter.
</P>
<P>
   That is what Joddie Johnson, owner of the Makah Maiden cafe, saw
as she and others watched the hunt wide-eyed and solemn from a
restaurant television.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have flipped that tail and overturned that canoe. The
whale just gave himself up,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   On the ocean, tribal members had to fight winds and currents,
trying to pull on lines to keep the huge animal from sinking.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   NEAH BAY, Wash.: from sinking
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Swan was supposed to dive in the water and sew the
animal's mouth shut. But he lacked the proper equipment to use his
air tanks.
</P>
<P>
   So he jumped into the frigid water wearing only a wet suit and
mask.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down and grabbed with both hands. I pulled my whole
body to the tail. I hugged it to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Swan managed to tie a bowline knot around the whale's tail. The
Heidi used the line attached to the whale's tail to tow the animal
to Neah Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The only protest boat to appear was the Sea Shepherd
Conservation Society's Sirenian, but 40 minutes late. As whaling
crew members hugged each other in relief that the stressful first
hunt was over, the mood on the Sirenian was somber. The vessel
sounded a loud mournful horn for almost 40 minutes in the distance
for the dead whale.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys got your whale, you should be happy,'' Sea Shepherd's
Watson broadcast disdainfully over the ship-to-ship radio. Late
Monday night, as his ship left Neah Bay, Watson heckled and mocked
the Makah, calling them ``Baby killers. Big, brave Makah warriors
killed a baby whale.''
</P>
<P>
   In the village, people emerged from their homes early Monday
morning, talking in small groups. Soon, car horns started honking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited, I can't event tell you,'' said Helma Ward, a
tribal elder. ``I can't even sit still.''
</P>
<P>
   Ourside the Makah Maiden, McGimpsey praised his forefathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ancient ancestors have answered our prayers. They are the
ones that secured our right to whale. They knew that someday we
would return to this whale. Our ancestors, they are magic.''
</P>
<P>
   By 8:30 a.m., tribal members began to gather in the old
community hall. Tribal Chairman Johnson announced to cheers that
the hunt had been successful.
</P>
<P>
   Then Hottowe, the tribal elder, led the tribe in a prayer song.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are an awful lot of happy Indians around here,'' one
tribal member said as he left the community hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a good feast,'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   At the local school, teachers were present but not students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children today will look back and say, `I remember the day
they brought a whale back to the beach,' '' said Steve Jimmicum.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Akin, who volunteers as a cook at the VFW Hall, brought her
TV set from home to follow the hunt. She was glued to the screen
for the live coverage, tears in her eyes, clasping her sleeping
grandson in her arms. ``I was so afraid down in my heart that
something would happen. My whole body was just shaking'' after
their success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even feel this way when I got married,'' Akin said.
``Oh, this is so beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The day wasn't joyous for all Makah. Elder Alberta Thompson, who
had publicly opposed the hunt, shed tears for the whale at her
home.
</P>
<P>
   She said she hoped the kill had made a difference. ``I couldn't
look into its eyes and not feel anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the reservation, the news of a successful hunt was
frequently greeted with alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Even an ally of the Makah in Congress expressed regret. U.S.
Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., believes tribal members have a ``public
relations disaster on their hands,'' spokesman George Behan said.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks, whose district includes Neah Bay, is the ranking Democrat
on a House subcommittee that handles appropriatations from the
Bureau of Indian Affairs and other agencies of the Interior
Department. Behan said Makah whaling could hurt the tribe's ability
to get discretionary BIA funds for such projects as economic
development.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., was ``outraged and saddened''
by the hunt, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton chairs a Senate subcommittee on Interior Department
appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   From his district office in Everett, U.S. Rep. Jack Metcalf,
R-Wash., pledged to continue to pursue a lawsuit to stop the
``barbaric'' hunts.
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf said in an interview that he worries that the Makah hunt
will spark resumed whaling by Indian groups on the west side of
Vancouver Island and by Japanese and Norwegian crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is needless. This is not about whaling or culture or
anything else. This is about the opportunity to open commercial
whaling worldwide,'' Metcalf said.
</P>
<P>
   The government of British Columbia vowed to block its tribes
from conducting similar whale hunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not sign any agreement nor entertain any discussion
about going back to the past and allowing any whale hunt in British
Columbia by aboriginal peoples,'' Premier Glen Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the International Whaling Commission began two weeks
of meetings in the Caribbean island of Grenada.
</P>
<P>
   Makah whaling is not on the agenda nor has any nation asked to
discuss it, a spokesman for the National Marine Fisheries Service
said. The U.S. is expected to give a report on the tribe's whaling.
</P>
<P>
   To the Makahs, what happens in Grenada seemed unimportant
Monday. They had their whale. They had linked with an age-old
tradition that no harsh words could break.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, still his protective clothing from his day whaling,
didn't seem to mind the protesters zig-zagging in the harbor in
small inflatable boats. Soon, the Coast Guard ordered them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't bother us now,'' he said as a Coast Guard
helicopter hovered overhead. ``It's all over.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporters Elaine Porterfield and Rebecca Denn contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
