<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ARATON-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column on the
Knicks, who now advance to the second round of the NBA playoffs,
where they will take on a resilient, but undermanned, Atlanta Hawks
team. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VENTER-GENOME (Undated) _ A Scientist at Work: Dr. J. Craig
Venter, a pioneer in the sequencing, or decoding, of DNA, is
beginning a new venture of boundless ambition. And sequencing the
entire three billion letters of human DNA by the end of 2001, a
goal first announced last May, is just the start of his grand
design. Eventually, he hopes to build a giant database of genome
sequences for thousands of that will be as essential for biologists
and physicians as the Bloomberg data terminals are for the
financial world. Now, his private venture is competing with a
similar federal government project. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT3,4) have been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OFFICE-SURGERY (Undated) _ After shifting from kitchen
tables to hospitals over the course centuries, surgery now is
moving again, this time to the less expensive settings of doctors'
private offices. This has set off an escalating nationwide debate
on how to insure patients' safety as the complicated modern
technology of anesthesia and surgery floats free of hospital
regulations back into less-restricted settings. By Abigail Zuger.
(2100 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT5,6) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WARMING-WEATHER (Undated) _ Scientists have long been
convinced that global warming would affect large-scale atmospheric
circulation _ the big, swirling global air currents that dictate
where it is warm and cold, wet and dry, and where storms go. Now a
number of researchers say the frequency of these circulation
regimes, as they are called, is changing, with potential for
enormous long-term implications for weather around the world,
including more frequent El Ninos. By William K. Stevens. (1670
words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MOTH-SEX (Undated) _ When it comes to sex there are many
males in the animal kingdom that can be counted on to contribute
little more to their mates than a moment of time and a bit of
sperm. But consider the male of the lowly rattlebox moth. This wisp
of a creature not only delivers a truly stunning sperm packet (the
proportional equivalent for a 170 pound man of a 17 pound
ejaculate) but, researchers report today, he includes within that
packet the unexpected bonus of a powerful toxin that can protect
his mate from predators for the rest of her life. By Carol Kaesuk
Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RELIGION-PRIZE (Undated) _ An essay: Despite a recent spate
of peace negotiations and displays of good fellowship by some of
the partisans on both sides, it doesn't look as if the
centuries-old row between religion and science is any closer to
resolution. The fact is that people cling to personal beliefs
regardless of debating points won or lost, and no amount of
persuasion makes much difference. But one thing that does make a
difference is cash. For most people the ultimate measure of success
is money, and by that standard religion is gaining on science. The
Nobel prizes in the sciences (which last year came to $978,000
each) have been shouldered into second place by the Templeton Prize
for Progress in Religion, which is now the world's richest award.
By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BALLET-PREGNANCY (Undated) _ The experience of ballerinas,
including Margaret Tracey, who have just returned from maternity
leaves makes it clear that it is generally far easier to get back
in shape after pregnancy or other disruptive events if one had been
in good shape to begin with. But it took special training and
programs to get them back on the floor. By Holcolm B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT7) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: Each
year, the Centers for Disease Control estimates, 4.7 million people
are bitten by dogs, 800,000 of them badly enough to require medical
treatment. At least 60 percent of dog bites and 72 percent of fatal
bites involve children. In fact, half of all children in this
country are bitten by a dog before their 12th birthday. And since
children are most often bitten on the face, many need plastic
surgery to minimize unsightly scars. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FUTURE-HEALTH (Undated) _ Every week, a group of doctors,
engineers, scientists and computer specialists get together at the
University of Rochester to talk over outlandish ideas, including
the notion that the future of medicine lies in devices that are
high-tech, cheap and controlled by patients. Like a bandage that
would screen for common infectious agents, memory glasses with a
databank of familiar faces that would whisper names into the ear,
body scanners that would check daily and report on the growth of
any melanoma. The sessions that gave rise to them has also given
birth to the Center for the Future of Health, a partnership that
signifies the growing intwinement of computer sciences and the
healing arts. By John O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FUTURE-TOILET (Undated) _ In Tokyo, Matsushita, the
electronics firm, is working on a prototype house of the future
chock-full of gadgets to keep track of the owner's health, right
down to the toilet. The model home, described earlier this month in
the Lancet, includes a bathroom equipped with sensors and
microchips that can provide a ``morning checkup'' by measuring the
user's weight, fat content and urine sugar levels. The bedroom has
an electrocardiometer, a blood-sugar meter and a thermometer, among
other gadgets, and links that can transfer their data not only to
the home computer or physician's office. By John O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PLANES-EARACHES (Undated) _ A new study finds that giving
children a decongestant does nothing to ease the earaches they
often suffer during airplane takeoffs and landings _ or,
indirectly, the headaches that some neighboring passengers sustain
from the crying that follows. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
