<HEADLINE>
POWER PLAY CHANGES, BUT RESULTS DON'T
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
ST. LOUIS _ The Blues had a new look on the power play last night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   St. Louis employed an umbrella power play, keeping three players
close to the blue line. The idea was to generate more and better
chances for players who have duck-and-take-cover slap shots, such
as defenseman Al MacInnis.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   MacInnis scored on just such a shot from just such a spot at
6:51 in the second period. But it wasn't a power-play goal.
</P>
<P>
   Time had just expired on Joe Nieuwendyk's hooking penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our power play was a little disappointing,'' MacInnis said.
``We hoped to capitalize a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes to the power play were in response to the Blues'
struggles with a man advantage in the series. They were 2-for-25
coming into last night's game, and MacInnis had yet to score
against the Stars. He had three goals and eight assists in the
Blues' first-round series against the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating,'' MacInnis said. ``You hate to think about
personal things in the playoffs, but it was frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues finished the series 2-for-28 on the power play. Injury
woes St. Louis youngster Lubos Bartecko was back in the lineup for
Game 6 last night.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a good thing for the Blues.
</P>
<P>
   Bartecko replaced Scott Pellerin, who aggravated a groin injury
he suffered in the Blues' first-round series against Phoenix.
Pellerin missed the first two games against the Stars before
returning for Game 3. He had played in the past three games but
wasn't really effective.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues' other injury of the night was defenseman Ricard
Persson. He was helped off the ice with nine minutes remaining in
regulation last night with back spasms and didn't return. Blues
finally first It took them 26 minutes, 51 seconds, but the Blues
were finally first.
</P>
<P>
   When St. Louis defenseman Al MacInnis scored 6:51 into the
second period last night, it marked the first time in this series
that the Stars didn't score the first goal.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the first time in this series that the Blues didn't
allow the Stars to score in the first period. In the first five
games, the Stars had a goal in the first 7:50. Traffic's new name:
Handzus St. Louis said it had to get more traffic in front of Stars
goalie Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic now has a name: Michal Handzus.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues' center seemed to skate right to the front of the net
every time he stepped on the ice. Handzus took his fair share of
punishment, too. The Blues had a power play five minutes into the
second period. He stepped in front of Belfour, trying to poke in a
rebound of a Geoff Courtnall shot.
</P>
<P>
   Handzus didn't succeed, but he did get a face full of the glove
of Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk. Belfour impresses Fuhr Blues
goalie Grant Fuhr has 92 postseason victories, ranking him second
among NHL goalies behind Colorado goalie Patrick Roy (106).
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Fuhr was the one marveling at the way his Stars counterpart
has played in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie's played great,'' Fuhr said about Ed Belfour in
yesterday's ``St. Louis Post-Dispatch''. ``It's the best I've seen
him play. He's really stepped up. They get a small lead and sit on
it, and if he doesn't play well, they don't sit very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been solid every game. You can't ask for more than that.
I think he's been their best player.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
