<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANTE STARTS TO GROW ON STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Mike Heika and Simon Gonzalez 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Derek Plante was buried deep in coach Ken
Hitchcock's doghouse after getting beat on Pavol Demitra's
game-winning goal in overtime of Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Plante, acquired at the trading deadline to inject quickness
into the lineup, was slowed by being a healthy scratch for Games 4
and 5.
</P>
<P>
   But he got another chance last night when Hitchcock elected to
play him instead of rookie forwards Blake Sloan and Jonathan Sim.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much speed out there, we had to go that way,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Plante made the most of the opportunity, tying the score with a
goal 13:58 into the third period and giving the Stars a chance to
win in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good just to go back in,'' Plante said.
</P>
<P>
   He scored his first goal in six postseason games after taking a
feed from Brett Hull in front of the Blues' goal. It wasn't a hard
shot, but Blues goalie Grant Fuhr was screened by Al MacInnis and
Stars forward Mike Keane, and never saw the puck slide just inside
the post.
</P>
<P>
   `I tried to throw it at the net,'' Plante said. ``It wasn't a
pretty goal by any stretch of the imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the game-tying goal, Plante might not be completely out
of that doghouse. He didn't exactly earn lavish praise from his
coach after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plante was OK at times,'' Hitchcock said. ``It was one game.
We'll see.''
Line shuffle Stars coach Ken Hitchcock shuffled his lines for much
of last night, trying to use a little of the old and a little of
the new. He played Mike Modano on a line with Grant Marshall, but
also used him on a line with Brett Hull. He used Jamie
Langenbrunner with Joe Nieuwendyk and also on a line with Guy
Carbonneau. And he used Mike Keane with Modano and also on a line
with Derek Plante.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be ready to change,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock's biggest change among the forward lines was Plante.
He played in place of rookies Blake Sloan and Jon Sim, who were
healthy scratches.
Arena dilemma Reunion Arena is scheduled to be the site of the
Champions on Ice figure skating show on Sunday afternoon. As a
result, the Stars aren't sure which day they will begin their next
series.
</P>
<P>
   Stars president Jim Lites said the Stars will have to wait until
the NHL decides.
Second-period blues The Stars won in six games even though they
were dominated in the second period all series.
</P>
<P>
   After Blues defenseman Al MacInnis scored the only goal in the
second last night, the Stars were outscored in the period overall,
8-4, and outshot, 67-45.
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig said it was mostly a matter of the
Blues having more to play for in the period. They trailed after the
first period four times in the series and were tied twice,
including last night when they faced elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had nothing to lose,'' Ludwig said. ``They had to play
hard.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
