<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-REACTION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS RELIEVED SERIES IS OVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
ST. LOUIS _ A team is supposed to show certain emotions after
winning a series to advance in the playoffs. Joy is called for.
Elation. Happiness.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the Stars knocked off the St. Louis Blues, 2-1, in
overtime last night at Kiel Center to win the Western Conference
semifinal series in six games, such things were buried beneath the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the overwhelming feeling was something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of relief,'' said Stars center Mike Modano,
who scored the game-winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   Relief that they remain alive in their quest for the Stanley
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Relief that they avoided the crapshoot of a Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   Relief that they've seen the last of these pesky, fast-skating,
hard-hitting Blues.
</P>
<P>
   And relief that they get some time off before taking on Colorado
or Detroit in the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   No Stars player wanted to play the Blues with the series tied,
even though the next game would have been at Reunion Arena, where
they are 5-0 in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Game 7 anything can happen,'' said Stars forward Brett
Hull, who assisted on both goals. ``A bad bounce, and it could all
be over.''
</P>
<P>
   They played the Edmonton Oilers in a Game 7 at home two years
ago, and lost in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to Game 7, and you just never know,'' defenseman Craig
Ludwig said.
</P>
<P>
   Especially against a team as talented as the Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that their hockey club has the best group of forwards
I've ever coached against since I've been in the league,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``Their skill and their tenacity is as
good as any group of 12 we've played against. They were relentless
in everything they did. It was a chore every game just to clear the
zone. It was just going to get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock also wanted to avoid a seventh game because some of
his players are running on empty. He wanted as much time as
possible to let bumps and bruises heal and tired legs get
re-energized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got four guys who will not skate until Saturday,'' said
Hitchcock, while declining to identify the four. ``We're in tough
shape. We've got some guys who need some time off.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Reunion Arena is booked Sunday for an ice show, the next
series might not start until Monday if the Red Wings and Avalanche
go seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get it over with, have as long a break as we
could,'' Modano said. ``There was really a push for us to get the
break.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars not only have the break, but they get to sit back and
wait for the next opponent. The Avalanche lead the Red Wings, 3-2,
with Game 6 scheduled for tonight in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Stars mouthed the standard,
``we-don't-care-who-we-play-next'' line, but not Modano. He wants a
chance for revenge against a Red Wings team that eliminated the
Stars in the conference finals last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone would love another crack at Detroit,'' he
said. ``That's what a lot of guys feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, what a lot of guys feel _ other than relief _ is the
need for rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment,'' said Stars captain Derian Hatcher when asked his
preference for the next round. ``I just want to see it go seven
games.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
