<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-DEVIL-RAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS HUNT HELP AFTER BURKETT POUNDED BY RAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Right-hander John Burkett's days as a member
of the Rangers' rotation could be over.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's performance likely served as the proverbial straw
that broke the camel's back.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett established the Rangers' single-game record by
surrendering 12 earned runs _ also the most allowed this season by
a major-league pitcher _ during an embarrassing 13-3 defeat to the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's understandable that we can't keep going on like
this,'' said Rangers manager Johnny Oates, who met with general
manager Doug Melvin after last night's game to discuss
alternatives. ``We can't keep digging holes like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't keep going to the bullpen. We can't keep playing
catch-up. We can't keep trying just to finish ballgames. The status
quo is not getting it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkett (0-3) allowed eight hits _ which included first- and
fourth-inning home runs by catcher John Flaherty and a
bases-clearing, second-inning blast by designated hitter Jose
Canseco _ in his too-painful-to-watch, four-inning appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of 25 batters reached safely, including five by walks,
as Burkett's earned-run average soared from 9.00 to 13.24 through
five starts spanning only 17 innings this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I'm late getting in here,'' Oates said of his
postgame meeting with Melvin. ``You always want to have
alternatives, but you want to give every opportunity for things to
work out. Doug and I have already visited tonight. We shared some
ideas and opinions. I'll sleep on them. He'll sleep on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkett appeared resigned to his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have had plenty of patience with me,'' Burkett
said. ``Whatever happens, happens. I have no opinion on that.
Obviously, I want to stay and work things out, but that's
ultimately their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not giving up by any means. I'm just going to keep coming
in and doing my work. I prepared as well as I ever have during the
off-season, but it hasn't paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Ryan Glynn, whom the Rangers called up Sunday from
Triple-A Oklahoma, replaced Burkett and surrendered one run on four
hits and one walk during his 2 1/3-inning appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays scored their lone run off Glynn when first
baseman Fred McGriff deposited a 2-1 pitch over the center-field
fence during the sixth inning. Glynn, who went 3-1 with a Pacific
Coast League-leading 1.85 ERA during six starts for the RedHawks,
likely will replace Burkett in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett, who went on the disabled list April 22 with bursitis in
his right shoulder, said his health was not a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fine,'' he said. ``I went into the game feeling fine, but
it was like batting practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents are hitting .422 (35-for-83) against the 34-year-old
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing out there that resembled me as a pitcher in
my past,'' Burkett said. ``It was just horrible. I didn't do
anything right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything I threw that got any of the plate at all, they
whacked it. I really don't know what to say. I stunk it up. I've
got nobody to blame right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers do, and it appears Burkett will be the first to pay
the price.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
