<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-BELFOUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMONG STARS, BELFOUR SHINES BRIGHTEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ He landed flat on his face, a collision with a Blues
player having sent him sprawling far away from where he needed to
be.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty, maybe 75 seconds, had passed in overtime and that's where
Stars goalie Ed Belfour found himself _ flat on his face and
looking on helplessly as St. Louis defenseman Chris Pronger
prepared to fire into an empty Stars goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great chance to score,'' St. Louis coach Joel
Quenneville said. ``They didn't have a goalie in net.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Belfour surprised Quenneville and Co., by springing to his
skates, scrambling back and staring Pronger down as if to dare him.
</P>
<P>
   Pronger took that dare, and Belfour squeezed the
watch-out-here-I-come slap shot between his pads. It was his 28th
and last save of the night.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't need another as Mike Modano scored not too long after
for a 2-1 victory in Game 6 that propelled the Stars into the next
round. Modano's goal at 2:21 in overtime will be called the
game-winner. Belfour's play was the game saver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game changed so many times,'' Quenneville said. ``That
certainly was one.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pronger: ``He certainly came up with big stops when they
needed him. He held them in games. They were pretty close games. He
was probably the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The fashionable question coming into the NHL playoffs was
whether Belfour was good enough to carry the Stars to the Stanley
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Blues are best able to answer that.
</P>
<P>
   They felt they had outplayed the Stars for good stretches of
this best-of-seven Western Conference semifinal series. They felt
the difference between winning and losing was as simple as Ed
Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the big saves when he had to,'' Blues center Craig
Conroy said. ``He's a great goalie. No one ever said he wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The doubters were there, though.
</P>
<P>
   Would Belfour snap as he did against Detroit last season?
</P>
<P>
   Was Belfour capable of carrying his team?
</P>
<P>
   Could Belfour win the big game?
</P>
<P>
   He did all of this and more against the Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like every other night, he was their best player,'' Blues
defenseman Al MacInnis said after Game 6. ``He came up with the big
saves when they needed them. You can't take anything away from him.
He's an experienced goalie down there.''
</P>
<P>
   The fears that maybe he wouldn't be able to handle the pressure
were unfounded. When Blues winger Terry Yake poked at him early in
the first period, he turned around and said something and then he
quickly turned back.
</P>
<P>
   He played on the edge, but he never came close to stepping over
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goalie is having fun and for me to say that about Ed
Belfour ...'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said, letting his voice
trail off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard him whistle today, just whistling. That is
unbelievable,'' Hitchcock said. ``To me, Ed Belfour was the
difference in the series. Blues goalie Grant Fuhr was good. Ed
Belfour was great.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
