<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1087 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-BLUES-TEX     05-18 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BLUES-TEX </SLUG>
 
Hull, Modano carry Stars past Blues 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
ST. LOUIS _ Give an assist to Pantera and two to Brett Hull. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And give the Stars another trip to the Western Conference
finals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hull went in with a wrecking ball last night and tore down the
house that he built as his gritty play led to Mike Modano's tap-in
goal at 2:21 of overtime, giving the Stars a 2-1 Game 6 victory
against the St. Louis Blues at Kiel Center. The Stars won the
series, 4-2, and advance to play the Detroit-Colorado winner.
Colorado leads the series 3-2. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But just as important as Hull finally shedding the ghosts of his
St. Louis past _ he starred here 11 years and was the impetus for
the construction of the new arena five years ago _ was a late
arrival from the rock band Pantera. After a request by Stars
defenseman Craig Ludwig, Pantera drummer Vinny Paul sent a compact
disc of the band's ``Dallas Stars Theme'' via airmail that arrived
just as regulation was ending. Before the overtime, the Stars
cranked up the theme, which is played before Stars home games, and
then rushed out to win their first game at Kiel Center in their
past seven tries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Things haven't gone well for us in this building,'' Ludwig
said of the Stars' 0-5-1 winless streak in St. Louis. ``So I called
him \RMonday\S morning, and he got it on a plane and got it in
here. He's 6-0 with that tune there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have won all five of their home games in the playoffs,
but players said it was important not to push their home luck in a
Game 7. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen before that anything can happen in Game 7,'' said
Modano, who scored his first playoff overtime winner at any level.
``We didn't want to take that chance.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a long stretch, it appeared the Blues were going to get that
chance. After coming back from a three-games-to-one deficit in the
first round against Phoenix and winning Game 7 of that series on
the road in overtime, the Blues held a 1-0 lead deep into the third
period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Had the Blues been able to win their fourth elimination game of
the playoffs and wrest the momentum of the series, there's no
telling what thoughts would have been circling in the Stars' minds.
The last time they had to play a Game 7 at home, they lost in
overtime to Edmonton two seasons ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys should know by now, we don't ever do anything easy,''
Ludwig said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But they do find a way to win. And out of the blue, the Stars
came back. Unlikely hero Derek Plante, who was benched for two
games after his defensive miscue led to the game-winning goal by
Blues winger Pavol Demitra in Game 3, was back in the lineup and
came up with his first point of the playoffs. After Hull worked
hard to dig a puck off the boards, Plante whipped a low shot
through a Mike Keane screen and past a befuddled Grant Fuhr to tie
the game with 6:02 remaining in the third period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr had been knocked down by teammate Al MacInnis and appeared
as if he couldn't find his bearings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of lucky, I wasn't aiming for the corner or
anything,'' Plante said. ``I'm just glad it went in.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plante's goal made another stellar night by Stars goalie Ed
Belfour mean something, and Belfour shut down the Blues the rest of
the way. His biggest stop came in overtime when he was knocked down
by Pierre Turgeon and was able to get back up quick enough to
smother a Chris Pronger shot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was huge,'' Keane said. ``But he was that way the whole
series.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just a minute after the save on Pronger, the Stars were turning
a puck over off a Craig Conroy attempt at a dump-in and making a
line change going into the offensive zone. Hull worked another puck
off the boards and sort of pushed it into the crease. There, Modano
chopped it past Fuhr to end the series. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just relieved,'' Modano said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured if we lost in overtime, Eddie would come in and tear
up the CD player and that CD,'' Keane said. ``I guess we can keep
it now.'' &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
