<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIANS-WHALE-ART-1ST     05-18 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIANS-WHALE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIVING TRADITION, TRIBE KILLS A WHALE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 4th graf for updating)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEAH BAY, Wash. _ With repeated thrusts from steel harpoons and
two finishing shots from a .50-caliber armor-piercing assault
rifle, the Makah Indian tribe on Monday conducted the first legal
killing of a gray whale in American waters in nearly 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   It was described, in joyful terms by tribal leaders, as part of
the proud resurrection of the Makahs' great seafaring traditions,
but the kill of the juvenile whale also enraged environmentalists
who had gathered in protest boats nearby and provoked a modern
media spectacle, with the whole event captured live by television
crews from Seattle hovering in helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the success of their mission, the eight hunters in a
32-foot cedar canoe, assisted by other Makah men in a motorized
boat, were not able to get to the whale in time to conduct the
traditional sewing up of its mouth, and thus the great mammal
filled with water and sank to the bottom of the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   But using a large fishing boat, tribal members managed to
refloat it several hours later and tow it ashore, with two hunters
standing atop the whale in a triumphal pose. Hundreds of Makah
gathered on a beach late Monday afternoon, near the northwestern
tip of the continental United States, for a celebratory ceremony,
and at about 8:30 on Monday night, the hunters began cutting up the
whale and handing out small pieces of meat to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The hunt was the third effort at a whale kill in the last week
by the tribe, which had gained permission from the International
Whaling Commission, official support from the Clinton
administration and a $310,000 grant from the Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   As the men circled in for the kill shortly before 7 a.m. on
Monday, many Makah gathered to watch the event on television. They
cheered as the men drove harpoons into the juvenile gray whale's
back and it rolled over. Then came the gunshots, and soon the water
turned red.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are elated,'' said Joddie) Johnson, owner of the Makah
Maiden, a diner on the main road of the reservation here, who said
she planned to sell whale meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make a whale of a burger,'' she said. ``This brings
meaning and purpose back to the Makah men. For 70 years, they had
what they did best taken away from them.''
</P>
<P>
   The successful kill ``restores a missing link in our heritage,''
said Arnie Hunter, vice president of the whaling commission, who
rode in the support boat Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But environmental groups, who had massed at Neah Bay in protest
and sent a flotilla of boats out to try to disrupt the hunt in
recent days, described the event as a tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have killed an intelligent, beautiful animal _ just blown
it away with an anti-tank gun,'' said Paul Watson, leader of Sea
Shepherd International, a conservation group. ``There's nothing
honorable about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The hunt was conducted just off the Makah's tribal land, on the
remote, storm-swept tip of Washington's Olympic Peninsula, but it
was played as huge news across much of the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's unsuccessful hunt, which led to the Coast Guard's
seizure of at least three protest boats, was broadcast live for
almost 10 hours by Northwest Cable News, prompting a Seattle Times
television critic to describe it as ``this region's own CNN-style
epoch.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray whales were driven almost to extinction by global whaling
earlier this century, and the Makah stopped hunting in the 1920s.
The United States banned all whaling of the grays in 1937, as part
of what turned out to be a successful bid to protect the species:
There are now an estimated 23,000 whales in the Pacific Ocean. The
whales' status as an endangered species was lifted in 1994,
prompting the Makah's petition for new international whaling
rights. It is the only tribe whose rights to hunt the whales are
guaranteed by a federal treaty, signed in 1855.
</P>
<P>
   Gray whales can grow to 40 feet in length and weigh as much as
40 tons. The whale killed Monday was a juvenile, and appeared to be
about half that size, though no formal measurement had been taken
as of Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional cultural clash sparked by the hunt was illustrated
Monday evening by separate gatherings called to mark the event.
</P>
<P>
   The Makah were jubilant, and many of them described the event in
mystical terms, a powerful reconnection with the whaling practice
that helped define their culture and is the source of numerous
legends, songs, traditions and tribal ceremonies. For centuries, it
was a principal male rite of passage, and many Makah said the
anticipation surrounding the hunt had been a huge inspiration for
young people in the 2,000-member tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made history today,'' said Ben Johnson, chairman of the
tribe's whaling council. ``This is a great day for the Makah
Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesters, who had come together in boats and on the shore at
Neah Bay, bearing signs that said ``Tradition can be altered'' and
``Stop the killing,'' held mournful observances near the village
and in downtown Seattle, nearly five hours away by car and ferry.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jack Metcalf, R-Wash., a bitter critic of the hunt, said
the killing could pave the way to an international assault on the
whales.
</P>
<P>
   ``These majestic, highly intelligent creatures deserve better
than to be brutally slaughtered as pawns in a political game
orchestrated by Japanese and Norwegian whaling interests and
supported by the Clinton-Gore administration,'' he said in a
statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Makah tribal leaders say they will only kill whales for
subsistence and ceremonial purposes, and said all the meat, blubber
and oil from Monday's kill would be distributed among tribal
members.
</P>
<P>
   Though they have the right under the whaling commission's
decision to kill up to 20 whales for the next five years, they said
they have no plans to try to sell whale meat or parts on the
international market, and they do not currently have permission to
do so. (Whale meat is considered a delicacy in many Asian countries
and a single gray whale can be worth up to half a million dollars.)
</P>
<P>
   The young men on the whaling team spent months last year in
training for the hunt, and tried briefly for a kill during the
whales' fall migratory season. This spring, with the whales
returning on their northward journey toward the Bering Sea, the
Makah hunters decided to go all out.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, they have paddled through the coastal fog,
passing Shi-Shi Beach and Father and Son Rock at the Olympic
National Park, as well as other stretches of wilderness beach where
carvings of whales that were made by Indian hunters centuries ago
remain.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the past week, hunters had thrown harpoons at passing
whales, but either missed or delivered glancing blows that did no
harm. They were deterred in part by protesters, several of whom
were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   At least one was charged, paradoxically, for violating the
Marine Mammal Protection Act by disturbing the route of a migratory
whale, while others were charged with throwing smoke bombs,
shooting flares and shooting chemical fire extinguishers in the
air.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
