<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-WARS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER BRACES FOR PACKED PREMIERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- It's almost zero hour for the Pacific Winnetka
20.
</P>
<P>
   Staffing at one of the nation's largest and most successful
megaplexes has been increased 33 percent, from 150 to 200
employees. Managers have ordered five times as much popcorn, soda
syrup and candy as normal.
</P>
<P>
   They're even stocking pizzas for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   All because the most hyped, most highly anticipated movie of all
time is opening Wednesday on three screens -- including Winnetka's
two 700-seat auditoriums with 72-foot screens. And while ``Star
Wars: Episode 1 -- The Phantom Menace'' is opening at 2,950
theaters across the country, including dozens in the Valley area,
few theaters will have as much traffic as the Winnetka.
</P>
<P>
   The 5,900-seat complex, one of the flagships in the world's
heaviest moviegoing region, has been cleared to devote more than a
third of its seating capacity to the tale of young Anakin
Skywalker. That's a gesture made for only the hottest hits, and
only for a few weeks at most. In this case, sold-out shows are
expected to be the norm well into the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting the best and preparing for the worst,'' said
manager John King during a quick break Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Winnetka will be showing ``Phantom Menace'' in each theater
five times a day. Already, first-day shows at 7:30, 8 and 8:30 p.m.
have sold out.
</P>
<P>
   If every ticket were sold for the first 15 showings, that would
be 10,000 customers in less than 15 hours. ``We could probably sell
out all 20 on the first weekend, but George Lucas and 20th Century
Fox aren't going for the quick kill here,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Many employees at the theater on Monday -- usually the slowest
day of the week -- were deep in ``Star Wars'' preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been kind of crazy and hectic,'' said Clifton Stewart,
the theater's general supervisor, as he navigated among massive
boxes of concession supplies on the loading dock. ``There are a lot
of things we haven't done before and a lot more stock than we
normally have.''
</P>
<P>
   Added King: ``We began ordering much heavier than usual a few
weeks ago, and our storeroom is just about bursting.'' Biggest
consumers of space are cups and popcorn tubs, with 5,000 of the
latter expected to be needed this week alone.
</P>
<P>
   Concessions are the critical driver in theater profit. At the
end of the night, operators keep only half of the $8.50 ticket
price but more than 80 percent of the money collected at the snack
bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my big worries is that when people get in the theaters,
they won't want to leave (to buy snacks),'' King said. To stimulate
spending from those customers, vendors will go into auditoriums
with ``hawker trays'' to sell popcorn, bottled Coke and the most
popular candy items (Red Vines, M&AMP;Ms, Raisinettes).
</P>
<P>
   One local entertainment analyst said ``Phantom Menace''
represents a huge opportunity for theater owners to drive up
profits with creative solutions like the one-stop ticket, in-line
carts, hawker trays and new food items.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business model for theaters is very simple -- give people
something fun to do while they drink high-margin drinks and eat
high-margin popcorn,'' said Kevin Skislock of Laguna Research
Partners. ``Still, the most effective solution for `Phantom Menace'
will be good old-fashioned staffing to keep lines as short as
possible and keep customers moving as fast as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Winnetka will not be one of the hundreds of theaters opening
for 12:01 a.m. Wednesday showings. Los Angeles-based Pacific has
made a chainwide decision to forego the late-night madness and
start showings around 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Still, King expects his staff to work long days today and
Wednesday preparing for the movie's opening. And he has told
employees to expect to work much harder than normal once the movie
starts because they'll have to clear out trash from sold-out
auditoriums, check tickets much more rigorously than normal and
deal with as many as 10 lines outside the theater at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to have questions on where to stand and when
they'll get in, so our people have to have the answers,'' King
said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
