<SLUG> BC-ORGAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAM THE ORGAN MAN PUTS LIFE BACK INTO KANSAS CITY BALLPARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH E. IGOE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Fenway Park has Ray. Comiskey Park has Nancy.
Busch Stadium has Ernie.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Kauffman Stadium has ``Sam the Organ Man.''
</P>
<P>
   After eight years of pumped-in, pre-recorded sound, this season
the Royals have brought back a live organist as part of a $14
million stadium renovation. He's Sam Beckett, a.k.a. the Organ Man,
a preacher's son who learned to pump up Sunday flocks as a child
piano prodigy.
</P>
<P>
   Returning the live player comes after years of fan requests,
said Tonya Mangels, the Royals' marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organ involves a feeling of nostalgia,'' Mangels said.
``He's a ham, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckett's skills led him to such varied pursuits as a Kansas
City youth ministry to composing music and singing ``What You Want
Is What You Get'' for McDonald's television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But baseball also is a religion of sorts for Beckett. He even
built a baseball diamond behind his Brookside house.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's ensconced in a Kauffman Stadium skybox with his
signature wink and faux tip jar featured live on the JumboTron
during the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   And the classically trained pianist is a hit with the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the organ man. It is quintessential, major league
baseball,'' said season ticket holder Chris Cole, 27. ``It really
brings the fans into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's great,'' commented Shannon Dooley, 26. ``Baseball.
Americana. Organ guy. You gotta have him.''
</P>
<P>
   As a lifelong baseball buff, Beckett is loving his latest gig _
not to mention that panoramic view above home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the funnest thing I've ever done,'' said Beckett, 33.
</P>
<P>
   Beckett first learned how to work a crowd when he was 10,
playing for his father's Southside Christian Center Assembly of God
congregation in Kansas City. By that early age, he knew how to pass
between different musical styles _ from soulful hymns to classical
ones _ with just a few chord changes.
</P>
<P>
   Beckett noticed the flock's mood changed based on what he was
playing. He experimented as people filed into services. A light and
airy tune usually resulted in cheerful pew chatter. Something
somber usually meant a silent fold, with heads bowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I got my start,'' Beckett said.
</P>
<P>
   Beckett won the coveted organist job not only because of his
skills, said Mangels, but also because he understands baseball's
varied pace and moods. He knows to play upbeat music during an
opponent's pitching change, for example, something subtle if it's
the Royals' turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be the first to admit, I'm not the best organist,'' said
Beckett, who will play the instrument during 57 out of 81 home
games this season. ``But that's not what I'm bringing to it. I'm
bringing my musical background and my love of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckett's instrument looks like a cross between a two-tiered
stand-up piano and an airplane's cockpit with its blinking lights,
switches and computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   As the game starts, Beckett dons a headset to hear directions
from the adjacent control room skybox, where the staff coordinates
everything from the JumboTron to the roving cameraman. As each
Royal is introduced, he plays rising chords, varying in rhythm:
Ta-DA. DA-ta-DA.
</P>
<P>
   When opposing teams are at bat, Beckett rests his hands on his
jeans. Quiet overtakes the stadium. Fans settle down.
</P>
<P>
   Between innings, Beckett pumps up the crowd with the ``Rocky''
theme song. For each Royals batter, Beckett playfully taps out
``Charge!'' or a funky strain like The Troggs' ``Wild Thing.''
During a pre-pitch lull, he might try to get the crowd clapping to
something whimsical like the ``Addams Family'' sitcom theme.
</P>
<P>
   Beckett celebrates base hits with a tipsy snippet like The
Champs' ``Tequila.'' A walk might earn Aerosmith's ``Walk This
Way.'' Great defensive plays merit organ riffs from Van Halen's
``Jump.'' After home runs, Beckett gets to share in the revelry,
blasting rock music as fireworks explode.
</P>
<P>
   But when he isn't at the stadium or working as an instructor at
Paseo High School, Beckett is composing anything from inspirational
music to classical concertos. A black grand piano sits in his
Brookside home and a studio work station, complete with
synthesizer, dominates the master bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Fans won't see Beckett at Kauffman Stadium on Tuesdays or
Sundays. On those days, organist Mark Morris fills in.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoons, Beckett is likely to be mowing a baseball
diamond he built last year in a vacant lot behind his house. Soon,
neighborhood kids started playing ball on the field. Then parents
dropped by to watch. Some brought food, then barbecue grills. Now
it's a Tuesday night ritual.
</P>
<P>
   On Sundays, church still comes first. Beckett plays for his
father's services, then enjoys the day with his family.
</P>
<P>
   But, with his trademark wink, Beckett said he'll keep the
Kauffman gig ``as long as it's fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
