r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     05-18 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL BURNS THE BLUES BUT NOT BRIDGES OR ARCHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ You can go home again. But why should Brett Hull
bother now?
</P>
<P>
   It's over. Been here, and now he's done that. The divorce is
final.
</P>
<P>
   Hull wins. The Blues can keep the furniture. And the golf clubs
_ they'll need them.
</P>
<P>
   If this were a fairy tale, Hull would have spanked home his
wrap-around shot in that third minute of overtime _ instead of
teammate Mike Modano poking home the Stars' game-inning rebound _
and vindication would have been sweet.
</P>
<P>
   But vindication for what, Hull seemed to ask?
</P>
<P>
   This second-round playoff series against his old team was never
about vengeance, or absolution, or proving to the people in St.
Louis that Brett Hull wasn't the reason that they lost in the
playoffs all those years.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many great memories, and that's the only thing
I've ever taken from here,'' said Hull, who signed a $24-million
contract with the Stars in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in a situation like this, you have to put all that in the
back of your mind and just try to win a series. It was just a big
win for me, and a big win for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. And all the garbage that Kiel Center fans were pelting
the ice with after the game was sweetheart roses and good-luck
chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   Hull stood there in the visitors locker room and said all the
right things. He didn't burn any bridges or arches. He even wore
the No. 14 shirt, the one with the candle in tribute to his late
St. Louis teammate Doug Wickenheiser, that he's worn under his
jersey all year.
</P>
<P>
   But let's be politically incorrect here. Blues management wanted
to wipe the slate clean after last season, and the first piece of
fat it trimmed was Hull's bulbous contract. Upsetting the Stars and
Hull in this second round of the Stanley Cup playoffs, in some
eyes, would have validated the Blues' decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about the pressure,'' Hull admitted. ``You try to
slough it off. But obviously, with me coming to Dallas and meeting
the Blues in the playoffs, this was something I obviously really
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   On a night that meant so much to his new team, let it be
recorded that Brett Hull seized the moment. He hustled and
forechecked. He scrambled and, as he did all six games, he
commanded the Blues' attention.
</P>
<P>
   It was the new Hull, beating his old team, with his new coach's
own game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably the strongest game he played the whole
series,'' Modano said. ``He was really into the game and playing
hard. I'm sure he was hungry to get it over with _ and to do it in
St. Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no coincidence that Hull figured in both of the Stars'
goals. He didn't score, but this is the new Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first goal was just a hard-working goal,'' Hull explained.
``Out of the corner of my eye, I thought I saw a defenseman take
Grant \RFuhr\S down. As the puck came back around, I wanted to take
it out in front of the net. But there was Derek \RPlante, scoring
his first playoff goal in two years\S.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning goal was all effort. Hull, playing the role of
forechecker, drove hard down the left side and around the back of
the net, harboring visions of wrapping home the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was just wanting to get it on net,'' Modano said.
``I think he didn't see me. But they kind of left me alone, and I
was able to get a couple of whacks at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The red lamp blinked, and Hull seemed to react even before
Modano. The arena instantly turned silent.
</P>
<P>
   When they saw Hull grinning and shouting, some of the fans began
to boo. The boos were quickly drowned out by cheers for the
stubborn Blues, who forced the favored Stars into overtime for four
of the six games.
</P>
<P>
   But when it came time for the traditional end-of-series
handshakes, boos for Hull were heard again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can boo me all they want,'' Hull said graciously, ``but I
know and remember all the great times we had together.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull was asked how it felt to finally, in a symbolic sense,
leave St. Louis in his rear-view mirror. A page was turned here
last night, someone suggested.
</P>
<P>
   But Hull refused to go along with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll ever turn the page I had here in St.
Louis,'' he corrected. ``So many good things happened here, so many
memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may say the page is turned now, but there will always be a
bookmark at that page.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't burn any bridges last night. He just broke some
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Say goodbye to Brett Hull, St. Louis. Surely, you could have
used him.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
