<HEADLINE>
SEN. BOND CALLS FOR EASING CLEAN-AIR LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Faced with threatened delays in highway
expansions, Kansas City needs some relief from strict
interpretations of federal clean-air laws, U.S. Sen. Kit Bond said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bond, a Republican, said he introduced legislation on Friday to
give such relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to change that law and restore the flexibility that
the EPA used to utilize to allow these projects to go forward,''
Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, Mo., on the first day of a two-day media blitz
across Missouri, Bond joined many of the state's business and
industry leaders to condemn environmental groups' recent legal
attempts to tie up highway projects in St. Louis and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're successful in cutting off highway funds, it won't
do anything to clean up the air,'' Bond said. ``There's nothing
worse for the quality of air than to have cars and trucks and buses
backed up for miles with their engines running.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond said the lawsuit seeks to withhold highway funds statewide
if St. Louis doesn't comply with federal clean-air requirements.
</P>
<P>
   But the environmental groups quickly fired back. First, they are
not seeking to tie up all of the state's highway funds, Sierra Club
spokeswoman Gina M. De Barthe said.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, she said, St. Louis has been out of compliance with
the federal limits since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. Bond should travel around the state to advance the cause
for clean air, not advance the cause of the polluters who finance
his campaigns,'' added Pat Waterston, president of the Missouri
Coalition for the Environment.
</P>
<P>
   Bond, a member of the Senate Environment Committee, announced
the launching of a drive for signatures on a petition asking the
Sierra Club to drop its lawsuit regarding St. Louis' compliance
with federal air limits.
</P>
<P>
   To Bond, threats against widened, resurfaced and safer highways
and bridges shouldn't be held over the heads of community leaders
who won't comply with requirements of the federal Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling with him were Carolyn Winkler, whose 34-year-old son
died on a two-lane road between Columbia and Moberly; Barry
Orscheln, chairman of the Missouri Chamber of Commerce; Chris Long
of the Associated Industries of Missouri; and Harriet Beard, a
member of the state's Air Conservation Commission, which is
authorized to enforce federal air regulations in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   At the press conference, Beard characterized the Sierra Club's
request for highway sanctions as ``ridiculous.'' But she
acknowledged later that the Environmental Protection Agency's
threat to withhold highway funds in the past had helped win support
in the state legislature for a new auto inspection program that
will check cars' emissions of ozone-creating chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have gotten (the inspection program) through in St.
Louis,'' Beard said. ``I would like to think that would have
happened anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the state has begun to build the new inspection stations
and is bringing less-polluting gasoline to St. Louis-area pumps
next month. ``It's in motion,'' Beard said.
</P>
<P>
   Bond said the federal agencies don't need the highway sanctions,
which can cause too great a burden on businesses that must deliver
their goods and pose too great a safety hazard if lost. ``There's
plenty of other powers to bring states and areas into compliance,''
Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator and his supporters take their petition campaign
today to Cape Girardeau, Joplin and Springfield.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
