<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1108 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORRECTION-WHALE-HUNT     05-18 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTION-WHALE-HUNT-2NDTAKE-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FIXES REPORTER'S NAME IN CREDIT TAGLINE AT END OF STORY, to
Rebekah Denn sted of Rebecca Den.
</P>
<P>
   NEAH BAY, Wash.: from sinking
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Swan was supposed to dive in the water and sew the
animal's mouth shut. But he lacked the proper equipment to use his
air tanks.
</P>
<P>
   So he jumped into the frigid water wearing only a wet suit and
mask.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down and grabbed with both hands. I pulled my whole
body to the tail. I hugged it to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Swan managed to tie a bowline knot around the whale's tail. The
Heidi used the line attached to the whale's tail to tow the animal
to Neah Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The only protest boat to appear was the Sea Shepherd
Conservation Society's Sirenian, but 40 minutes late. As whaling
crew members hugged each other in relief that the stressful first
hunt was over, the mood on the Sirenian was somber. The vessel
sounded a loud mournful horn for almost 40 minutes in the distance
for the dead whale.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys got your whale, you should be happy,'' Sea Shepherd's
Watson broadcast disdainfully over the ship-to-ship radio. Late
Monday night, as his ship left Neah Bay, Watson heckled and mocked
the Makah, calling them ``Baby killers. Big, brave Makah warriors
killed a baby whale.''
</P>
<P>
   In the village, people emerged from their homes early Monday
morning, talking in small groups. Soon, car horns started honking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited, I can't event tell you,'' said Helma Ward, a
tribal elder. ``I can't even sit still.''
</P>
<P>
   Ourside the Makah Maiden, McGimpsey praised his forefathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ancient ancestors have answered our prayers. They are the
ones that secured our right to whale. They knew that someday we
would return to this whale. Our ancestors, they are magic.''
</P>
<P>
   By 8:30 a.m., tribal members began to gather in the old
community hall. Tribal Chairman Johnson announced to cheers that
the hunt had been successful.
</P>
<P>
   Then Hottowe, the tribal elder, led the tribe in a prayer song.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are an awful lot of happy Indians around here,'' one
tribal member said as he left the community hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a good feast,'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   At the local school, teachers were present but not students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children today will look back and say, `I remember the day
they brought a whale back to the beach,' '' said Steve Jimmicum.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Akin, who volunteers as a cook at the VFW Hall, brought her
TV set from home to follow the hunt. She was glued to the screen
for the live coverage, tears in her eyes, clasping her sleeping
grandson in her arms. ``I was so afraid down in my heart that
something would happen. My whole body was just shaking'' after
their success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even feel this way when I got married,'' Akin said.
``Oh, this is so beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The day wasn't joyous for all Makah. Elder Alberta Thompson, who
had publicly opposed the hunt, shed tears for the whale at her
home.
</P>
<P>
   She said she hoped the kill had made a difference. ``I couldn't
look into its eyes and not feel anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the reservation, the news of a successful hunt was
frequently greeted with alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Even an ally of the Makah in Congress expressed regret. U.S.
Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., believes tribal members have a ``public
relations disaster on their hands,'' spokesman George Behan said.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks, whose district includes Neah Bay, is the ranking Democrat
on a House subcommittee that handles appropriatations from the
Bureau of Indian Affairs and other agencies of the Interior
Department. Behan said Makah whaling could hurt the tribe's ability
to get discretionary BIA funds for such projects as economic
development.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., was ``outraged and saddened''
by the hunt, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton chairs a Senate subcommittee on Interior Department
appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   From his district office in Everett, U.S. Rep. Jack Metcalf,
R-Wash., pledged to continue to pursue a lawsuit to stop the
``barbaric'' hunts.
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf said in an interview that he worries that the Makah hunt
will spark resumed whaling by Indian groups on the west side of
Vancouver Island and by Japanese and Norwegian crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is needless. This is not about whaling or culture or
anything else. This is about the opportunity to open commercial
whaling worldwide,'' Metcalf said.
</P>
<P>
   The government of British Columbia vowed to block its tribes
from conducting similar whale hunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not sign any agreement nor entertain any discussion
about going back to the past and allowing any whale hunt in British
Columbia by aboriginal peoples,'' Premier Glen Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the International Whaling Commission began two weeks
of meetings in the Caribbean island of Grenada.
</P>
<P>
   Makah whaling is not on the agenda nor has any nation asked to
discuss it, a spokesman for the National Marine Fisheries Service
said. The U.S. is expected to give a report on the tribe's whaling.
</P>
<P>
   To the Makahs, what happens in Grenada seemed unimportant
Monday. They had their whale. They had linked with an age-old
tradition that no harsh words could break.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, still his protective clothing from his day whaling,
didn't seem to mind the protesters zig-zagging in the harbor in
small inflatable boats. Soon, the Coast Guard ordered them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't bother us now,'' he said as a Coast Guard
helicopter hovered overhead. ``It's all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Post-Intelligencer reporters Elaine Porterfield and Rebekah Denn
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
