<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOYS MOVEMENT LEADER BRINGS HIS MESSAGE OF NURTURING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Michael Gurian shivered when he heard news
reports of an alleged plot by four boys to carry out a massacre at
their Port Huron, Mich., school. But he wasn't surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``America's adolescent males are in trouble,'' said Gurian, a
family therapist in Spokane, Wash., and a leader in the nationwide
``boys movement.'' Millions of boys aren't being nurtured the way
they should, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys are emotionally fragile, perhaps even more so than
adolescent girls,'' he said. ``But we've been ignoring them. For
the last few decades our cultural microscope has focused on the
oppression of girls and women. Now the lens must focus on boys,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurian, author of several books on boys, including his latest, A
Fine Young Man: What Parents, Mentors and Educators Can Do to Shape
Adolescent Boys Into Exceptional Young Men, was a keynote speaker
Monday at the national convention of the Court Appointed Special
Advocate Association. He spoke to more than 1,000 people at the
Hyatt Regency Crown Center hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Gurian's idea of nurturing boys is part of a larger movement
sweeping the nation, in part because of violence erupting in the
nation's schools _ violence committed by boys.
</P>
<P>
   Gurian says the violence is predictable but preventable.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of nurturing boys is gaining nationwide acceptance.
Beginning this fall several school districts in the Kansas City
area are going to try some of Gurian's ideas.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Gurian will teach a three-day seminar at the
University of Missouri-Kansas City, said Robert Henley, retired
superintendent of the Independence School District.
</P>
<P>
   The seminar, called the Gurian Institute, is part of the Safe
School Initiative. Five districts have signed up so far:
Independence, Hickman Mills, Grandview, St. Joseph and Kansas City,
Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known for years that boys are in a higher risk group for
all sorts of problems,'' Henley said. ``But we've continued to
treat boys and girls as if they have exactly the same issues.
There's never been a real attempt to put special programs in for
boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what the answer is, but we want to learn
Michael's ideas and apply them to some actual school environments
and just see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   For 15 years Gurian has researched the idea that boys and girls
are vastly different aside from the obvious physical differences.
</P>
<P>
   Competition is hard-wired into boys, he said. So are quick
problem-solving and physical risk-taking. It's testosterone, not
attitude, that makes them aggressive, Gurian said.
</P>
<P>
   Society teaches them violence, he said, because it is not aware
of a boy's risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched a couple bring their 3-year-old son to the movie
`Saving Private Ryan,' '' he said. ``I was horrified because I knew
the damage those parents were doing to their son. So I went over
and told them. We're a society in transition and need to be aware
of how boys function. No one has ever taught us this before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
