<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXERCISE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCESS TO ROAD IS GAIN FOR EXERCISERS, PAIN FOR AIRPORT OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE RICE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For in-line skaters Nicole Calton and Melissa
DiMauro, the road that circles the Downtown Airport has everything.
</P>
<P>
   It's flat. It hardly has any traffic. It has a nice view of the
downtown skyline. With all that, the 3.8-mile stretch of road has
become a hot spot for skaters, joggers, bicyclists and wheelchair
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that it was never intended to be a skating track, or
that airport officials _ citing the potential dangers _ really
don't want anyone exercising there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really the only place where you can safely Rollerblade,''
said DiMauro, a veterinary technician from Kansas City, North. ``No
one's down here.''
</P>
<P>
   The parking lot on the airport's west side, which abuts the
Missouri River, is so desolate that bicyclist John Maynard feels
comfortable about changing his clothes in his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work at Hallmark and live in the Northland,'' he said after
work one recent afternoon, ``so this place is very convenient.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, its proximity to downtown has made the airport a popular
lunchtime exercise hangout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me a good hour of stress relief,'' said Ryan Pals, a
sales manager for Premium Standard Farms who has walked and jogged
on the airport road nearly every day for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   The oval perimeter includes Richards Road, which abuts U.S. 169
and the airport's east side, and Lou Holland Drive, which serves
several hangars and businesses on the airport's west side.
</P>
<P>
   Maynard, a triathlete, rides his bicycle for about an hour and
then runs. He and his fellow bicyclists even rode there on New
Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   The road, Maynard said, is ideal for the high-speed training of
serious runners and bicyclists.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a flat course to train,'' Maynard said.
``And, it's kind of cool to see the planes land.''
</P>
<P>
   Some would like to see organized skating and bicycling events
held there. And despite the airport's proximity to railroad tracks,
a water treatment plant and other industries, exercisers said they
rarely encounter any foul odors.
</P>
<P>
   But airport officials are not pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dangerous situation,'' said Ed Noyallis, the airport's
general manager. ``People can be blinded by the headlights from
other cars, especially if they are going north on Richards Road at
twilight. And there's a blind corner on the south end.''
</P>
<P>
   Noyallis said he believes the exercisers en masse discovered the
airport road sometime in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The city briefly closed the road to nonmotorized traffic and
pedestrians in 1993 after a bicyclist was killed there. He slammed
into a curb and was not wearing a helmet.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, some bicyclists interfered with the repair of
the river's levee after heavy rains, Noyallis said, adding that one
bicyclist even rode through barricades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to be ogres,'' he said, ``we're just
concerned about people's safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Meisinger, president of Executive Beechcraft Inc., which has
its office on the southeast end of the airport, said the fitness
buffs are not annoying. Vehicular traffic, he said, does not travel
at high speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Meisinger shared some of Noyallis' concerns. ``There is
bound to be an incident because they are in the street.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pals said motorists have always been nice. ``They usually
wave at us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs along Lou Holland Drive and Richards Road that
say in-line skating is prohibited. But Noyallis said the city only
enforces the rule ``on occasion,'' when someone requests it.
</P>
<P>
   Calton and DiMauro said they have never been cited. Another
skater, Brad Max, who works for a Kansas City investment firm, said
he had never had problems with airport personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are nice as long as you don't behave inappropriately and
don't block the road,'' Max said.
</P>
<P>
   Maynard disagreed with claims that the exercisers are reckless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are safety-conscious,'' he said. ``We won't ride with
anyone who won't wear a helmet.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Teresa Loar, who heads the City Council's Aviation
Committee, said the situation shows a citywide problem _ the need
for more biking and jogging trails and skating parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned for their safety,'' Loar said. ``We need to
provide a facility for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Cozad, a physician who lives in Kansas City, North, said
the airport road is one of the few bicycle-friendly places in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many drivers here are inattentive and, at worst, malicious,''
said Cozad, who bikes and jogs at the airport three times a week.
``I think the people here at the airport have gotten used'' to the
exercisers.
</P>
<P>
   Although there has been no talk about banning recreational
activities from the airport road, such concern from city officials
troubles the exercisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would miss it if it went away,'' Maynard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
