A1113 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERGER--2TAKES-KAN &LR;      05-18 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGER--2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN RESOURCES, KCP&AMP;L IN FINAL STRETCHES OF A MARATHON MERGER
COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Photos of former utility regulators stared
from one wall. On the other side loomed the Great Seal of the State
of Kansas. In the middle sat three current members of the Kansas
Corporation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't an unfamiliar setting for Drue Jennings, head of
Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co. As the veteran utility executive sat
in the hearing room's witness box two weeks ago, he deftly handled
questions about why his utility should merge with Western Resources
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings was at ease, and at times he even had the room
chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   But as the day progressed, there was no mistaking his
seriousness on one point: Jennings wanted this deal. This was his
third shot at merging KCP&AMP;L with another utility.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he was asked whether he would go through with the
merger even at Western's then-stock price of just over $27 a share.
That figure, which represented a reduction in the amount that KCP&AMP;L
stockholders would receive, would also give the utility the option
to walk away from the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, said Jennings, who last August cashed out 80 percent of his
KCP&AMP;L stock options _ 97,146 shares _ at $29.29 per share. He would
go ahead with the merger, as long as regulators didn't tinker with
the deal in a way that would reduce revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do I sign?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   If only it were that easy. More than two years have passed since
the utilities announced merger plans after a long takeover fight.
The process has dragged on so long that a federal regulator
recently complained that some information submitted with the merger
application was too old to be of use.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the end of the game may be nearing in Kansas, where
regulators are in the middle of their hearings. Missouri will begin
similar hearings in July. The biggest hurdle could be federal
regulators, who say consideration of the matter could stretch well
into next year.
</P>
<P>
   However, the utilities recently worked out a compromise with the
staff of the Kansas Corporation Commission, and they insist the
merger will be completed this year.
</P>
<P>
   Will the merged company be so large it will edge out potential
competitors? Are consumers shouldering too much of the risk and
receiving too few of the benefits in the merger?
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the questions that regulators ponder. And
growing numbers of critics vow that the fight against the merger is
not over yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger has become a can of worms,'' said Walker Hendrix,
counsel for the Citizens' Utility Ratepayer Board in Topeka, a
group that represents consumers on utility issues. &QL; 
 &QL; 
--- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's no small irony that the two utilities want to merge,
given the enmity they've often had for each other over the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L struck first in 1990, when it made an unsolicited bid for
Kansas Gas &AMP; Electric. Western snatched KGE away with its own
offer. In the mid-'90s, KCP&AMP;L rejected a merger overture from
Western.
</P>
<P>
   A truce existed until 1996, when KCP&AMP;L decided to combine with
UtiliCorp United Inc. of Kansas City. Western reacted with an
unsolicited bid for KCP&AMP;L and made it the first successful
hostile-takeover fight of an electric utility in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Egos were a factor in the contest. No one accused Jennings and
then-Western Chairman John Hayes of being buddies. But economics
and a changing utility industry were pushing them together.
</P>
<P>
   The looming prospect of deregulation and the eventual loss of a
utility's monopoly were forcing change. Electric utilities hoped to
reap the benefits of greater economies of scale. Larger companies
would have the capital to build more plants and buy power on the
wholesale market. And by lowering costs and rates, they could
retain customers.
</P>
<P>
   A merged KCP&AMP;L-Western would be the 32nd-largest utility in the
country. KCP&AMP;L and Western's KPL and KGE utilities would combine in
a company to be called Westar Energy, based in Kansas City. It
would have 1 million customers and $8.2 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, 52, would be Westar's first chief executive, though he
says he hopes to retire in his mid-50s.
</P>
<P>
   The merger effort has been an enormously expensive process. By
the time they reached an agreement, the two utilities had spent
$160 million on merger expenses. For KCP&AMP;L, those expenses in the
past three years have reached $100 million, including a $53 million
payment to UtiliCorp for not completing that deal.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his previous distaste for Western, Jennings
told regulators that Western was a different company now. For
instance, it now owned most of {Protection One}, a
monitored-security service.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's great potential there,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
