<SLUG> BC-HOME-SALES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. HOME PRICES UP; SUPPLY SHRINKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With an assist from confident consumers, home
prices in the San Fernando Valley soared 14.1 percent during the
12-month period ending in April, and while sales slowed slightly,
the real estate market remained robust, a trade group said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the median price _ the point at which half the homes
sold for more and half for less _ hit $211,000, a gain of $26,000
in the last 12 months. Meanwhile, escrow closed on 1,208
single-family homes, a 1.1 percent decline from April 1998, said
the Southland Regional Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in number of homes sold was neither a surprise nor
disturbing. After all, last month's total is the second highest
ever for an April; the highest was April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, industry officials said the only thing holding back
sales is tight product supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demand is still ahead of supply, even if the red-hot frenzy of
last year has cooled ever so slightly,'' said Jim Link, the
association's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   During April, there were 24 fewer new listings recorded, a
decline of 1.3 percent, from the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   While the current price run-up is good news for consumers, it
does not compare to what took place in the late 1980s and early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price escalation back then was actually faster than this
one. These prices are coming back strong because they are making up
for a lot of lost ground in the mid-1990s,'' Link said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the peak median price hit $245,000 three times
during 1989. The highest it got during this decade was $244,000 in
April of 1990. So the current price appreciation is replacing value
lost during the deep recession of earlier this decade, and there is
still a way to go to full recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Link said the rising prices are a reflection of a very strong
overall economy.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Sommer, the association's president, predicted this year's
market will end up looking a lot like 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to just stay a drop below the 1998 rate of sales,
and the reason we're not selling more is because we don't have
enough listings,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bray, national marketing director at the Meyers Group, a
real estate consulting service in Santa Monica, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inventories are tight, so obviously pricing continues to go
up,'' he said of the Valley's market. ``We think it's going to be a
strong year and pretty similar to last year.''
</P>
<P>
   One result of the rising prices is increased activity in the
condominium market.
</P>
<P>
   During April, Realtors reported selling 331 units, an increase
of 13.4 percent from a year ago. The median price of $127,500
gained 18.6 percent from the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Nima Nattagh, an analyst at First American Real Estate Solutions
in Santa Ana, said the market continues to run on momentum that was
building last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first quarter is actually a continuation of a good market
we saw in 1998, but I suspect there will be some slowing down as we
progress throughout the year'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller Santa Clarita Valley turned in a more robust
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of existing single-family homes there totaled 264 units,
up 18.4 percent from April 1998. The median price of $225,000
gained 18.1 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
   Escrow closed on 118 condominiums, up 49.4 percent from a year
ago, and the median price gained 15.3 percent to $134,900.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
