<SLUG> BC-MERGER--2nd </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN RESOURCES, KCP&AMP;L IN FINAL STRETCHES OF A MARATHON MERGER
COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (``There's great potential there,'' he said. &QL; )
 &QL; 
--- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Western and KCP&AMP;L are something of a corporate odd
couple.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L had dabbled in some deregulated businesses such as
WorryFree, which leases furnaces and air conditioners. But it's
best known among analysts for being a capable and low-cost provider
of power.
</P>
<P>
   Western, of course, has KPL and KGE, and it owns part of Oneok
Inc., a natural gas company. But it has quickly built its
deregulated business mainly by purchasing Protection One, investing
millions in it, and creating what is now the second-largest
monitored-security service.
</P>
<P>
   Even Western's leadership differs from tradition. David Wittig
was brought in to help Western acquire companies and forge its
entrepreneurial strategy. Originally from Prairie Village, Wittig
has also worked in New York, where he was an investment banker.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he is Western's chairman, president and chief executive
officer _ making him point man for promoting and explaining the
merger. That new mission brought him before the Kansas Corporation
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   As questioning from regulators lingered late into a recent
evening, Wittig tilted his head and put his hand on his cheek. As
the questions continued, he began to sigh with each answer until
his lawyer objected to the inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   One questioner asked about transmitting power from the Wolf
Creek nuclear plant in Burlington, Kan., to KPL. Couldn't be done,
Wittig said, because there were no lines from the plant to KPL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to get it through thin air,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jennings, Wittig wants the merger and has something to
prove.
</P>
<P>
   Wittig, who received $2.5 million in compensation from Western
last year, says that most of the pieces are in place and that he
has no plans for buying more companies. But completing the merger
with KCP&AMP;L is an important part of the company's plan to expand the
electric business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to meet the challenges of the future,'' Wittig told
regulators. &QL; 
 &QL; 
--- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For that to happen, state and federal regulators must approve
the deal. And signs of skepticism are rife.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Kansas Corporation Commission staff expressed
concerns about the deal. But Gov. Bill Graves noted the day the
staff disclosed its concerns that he didn't want too many
restrictions to kill the merger. A couple of months later, staff
members came to an agreement with Western.
</P>
<P>
   A commission spokeswoman said that there was no pressure on the
staff and that the terms of the settlement were good. But the
compromise angered critics, who said it fell far short of
protecting consumers, and some blamed political pressure for the
turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``Western has mastered the political culture of Topeka,'' said
Mayor Bob Knight of Wichita. He wants more relief for KGE
customers, who pay higher rates than customers of KPL and KCP&AMP;L.
</P>
<P>
   While some criticized it, the Kansas agreement dealt with issues
that have troubled critics of the merger. Western and KCP&AMP;L wanted
to ditch traditional rate proceedings and replace them with an
incentive plan that would give Westar a 13.5 percent return on
equity and a piece of any additional profit.
</P>
<P>
   The incentive plan, critics said, would effectively stop
consumers from reaping any of the cost savings of the merger and
saddle them with paying the $870 million acquisition premium that
Western paid for KCP&AMP;L. The premium is the amount over the book
value of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The staff's agreement would give Westar $300 million of the
acquisition premium from Kansas consumers. The compromise would
allow it to keep all the merger savings in the first four years of
Westar's existence.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the incentive mechanism would be shelved and there
would be a rate moratorium for four years. In addition, there would
be $45 million in rebates over three years, spread among customers
of KPL, KGE and KCP&AMP;L. Originally, the staff recommended $27
million a year in rate relief going to KGE customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Corporation Commission has yet to approve the merger,
though the agreement is expected to smooth the way. The going could
be tougher with Missouri and federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The staff of the {Missouri Public Service Commission} also is
critical of the incentive-rate plan that Western and KCP&AMP;L want.
And it recommends that none of the acquisition premium be collected
from ratepayers. Indeed, such a premium has never been collected
from utility customers in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The {Missouri Office of Public Counsel}, which represents
consumers before the commission, would like to see the deal killed.
But Ryan Kind, an economist with the public counsel's office, said
Western could still come out ahead because he suspects a major
reason for the deal is that Western simply wanted to stop KCP&AMP;L
from merging with UtiliCorp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win-win situation for Western Resources,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the federal regulators. The Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission's staff said preliminary indications were
that the merged company would have too much market power. They
called for hearings that are to begin in October, although there is
still a possibility of settlement.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of mergers before federal regulators don't go to
hearings. Instead, they are settled with an order. At a meeting
discussing the case, Shelton Cannon, director of the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission's Office of Electric Power Regulation, said
the staff had given as much guidance as possible to Western and
KCP&AMP;L, according to /{Foster Electric Report/}, a trade publication
that covered the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Were Western and KCP&AMP;L not listening, asked one of the
commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would suggest that's part of it,'' Cannon said. (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
