<SLUG> BC-WEST-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN RESOURCES REPORTS LOWER FIRST-QUARTER EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Western Resources Inc. on Monday reported
lower first-quarter earnings, largely because of moderate weather
and the absence of some one-time gains posted last year.
</P>
<P>
   Continued losses in the company's Protection One subsidiary also
affected quarterly results.
</P>
<P>
   The Topeka utility company reported 1999 first-quarter net
income of $20.7 million, compared with $29.8 million for the same
period last year. Western's sales were $461 million for the first
quarter, compared with $382 million for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings for the first three months this year were 31 cents per
share, compared with 44 cents per share for the same period last
year. But 12 cents per share of last year's earnings were from
one-time gains that included life insurance proceeds. Before
accounting for the one-time gains, Western earned 32 cents per
share in the first quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Profit from Western's electric utilities, KPL and KGE, rose 1
cent per share for the first quarter this year because of higher
wholesale and retail sales. Earnings from Western's investment in
Oneok Inc., a natural gas company, dropped slightly because of a
warmer-than-normal winter.
</P>
<P>
   Western's investment in Protection One, which sells
monitored-security services, accounted for a loss of 4 cents per
share, compared with a loss of 3 cents per share for the same
period last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
