<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1117 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOBIZ-KAN &LR;      05-18 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBIZ-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI'S `CHRISTMAS TREE BILL' FULLY DECKED OUT THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Every year an economic development measure in
the Missouri General Assembly suddenly becomes a magnet for similar
bills stuck in committee or languishing on debate calendars.
</P>
<P>
   Some call this annual exercise in cut-and-paste lawmaking ``the
Christmas tree bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon it are hung sales tax breaks, income tax credits,
government grants, cheap loans and other fiscal goodies to benefit
favored government agencies, single cities, private companies or
entire industries.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Kansas City's side of the tree was a little bare. But
companies such as Harley-Davidson and TWA and developers of Kansas
City's Power &AMP; Light District project were left with something to
cheer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have as many ornaments as in past years,'' agreed
Bill Gamble, the council's longtime lobbyist in Jefferson City.
Then again, he noted, not all ornaments get hung on the Christmas
tree.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's business community won huge victories in other bills,
including this year's pro-business centerpiece that exempts an
estimated 20,000 small employers from the state's franchise tax and
slashes the tax rate for others.
</P>
<P>
   Another provides tax credits for businesses making contributions
to a new state ``seed loan'' fund to help qualified but struggling
new companies with start-up expenses. Rockhurst College in Kansas
City is in line to be one of this area's seed loan administration
centers.
</P>
<P>
   If there are fewer ornaments on the 1999 Christmas tree, Gamble
said, he's just as thankful for the one he didn't have to hang.
</P>
<P>
   An effort by a rural lawmaker to restrict bonding authority for
neighborhood improvement districts statewide threatened to deliver
an inadvertent but possibly fatal blow to developers of the Power &AMP;
Light District project in downtown Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being able to sell up to $176 million worth of
low-interest bonds _ a key source of financing to be repaid from
project revenue _ the developers would have been limited to raising
just $1.2 million, Gamble said.
</P>
<P>
   The restrictive legislation died Friday, the last day of the
session, but not before Gamble and others were ready with an
amendment that would have exempted all of Kansas City's designated
neighborhood improvement districts from the bond restriction.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City and the metropolitan area ``had really strong
packages the last three years,'' said Rep. Henry Rizzo, a Kansas
City Democrat who sponsored this year's bill. He said that helped
explain why local interests got fewer provisions this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's legislation included Centertainment tax breaks and a
$5 million slice of the riverboat-casino pie to help repair the
Liberty Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Gamble said, separate state-budget appropriation
bills funneled $2 million to help retire city bond debt for Bartle
Hall and $3 million more for maintenance and repairs at the Truman
Sports Complex.
</P>
<P>
   Repair and patchwork on existing state laws are mostly what the
1999 Christmas tree bill accomplishes.
</P>
<P>
   Among its provisions, House Bill 701:
</P>
<P>
   _ Adds airports and air terminal service facilities to business
ventures qualified for enterprise zone tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   That Kansas City-inspired language was intended mostly to
benefit TWA in Kansas City and St. Louis, Rizzo said, if either
city government chooses to declare some or all of its airport an
enterprise zone. Kansas City officials are trying to extend TWA's
maintenance base lease, which is to expire next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Authorizes a satellite enterprise zone for Independence to
develop its Fairmont neighborhood in the city's northwest area with
tax credits and other incentives to attract businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been really difficult to make things happen'' in the
area, said city development director Bruce Hahl.
</P>
<P>
   Enterprise zone tax incentives might be the missing piece of the
puzzle that finally attracts real estate developers to that area,
Hahl said. And, he added, one is already waiting in the wings with
a plan for senior housing and a clinic.
</P>
<P>
   That section also permits new enterprise zones in Randolph,
Callaway and Barton counties and expands zone population limits for
Kansas City to accommodate more and larger districts.
</P>
<P>
   It also provides assurances that businesses in enterprise zones
created since 1990 will remain in line to claim their promised 15
years of tax credits and other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble said a lawsuit decided earlier this year cast some doubt
over the legality of those long-term agreements made by cities and
counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives those companies some sense of security,'' Gamble
said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main beneficiaries will be Kansas City's new
Harley-Davidson manufacturing plant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expands the current law's definition of film producers
eligible for up to $500,000 a year in annual income tax credits
when they film in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a cash cow for the city and the state to get them in
here,'' Rizzo said. ``But we're not competing right now. A majority
of the movies happening in the Midwest are being made in Illinois.
... I'm trying to establish Kansas City as a movie set.''
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while, somebody hangs a lump of coal on the
Christmas tree. One of the final amendments added Friday was just
that for Missouri business owners.
</P>
<P>
   Under that change, any business discovered with undocumented
immigrants on the payroll can lose its state tax credits, tax
abatements or loans and be declared ineligible for such state aid
for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Undocumented immigrants ``have been flying into Missouri in
record numbers,'' Rizzo said. ``Rural areas are feeling it. We're
feeling it in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very big problem that is hard to track. We have to have
some accountability. ... There's going to be a price to pay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
