<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1129 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-BAGWELL-HN     05-18 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BAGWELL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Some things are unexplainable, and five years later Jeff Bagwell is
no closer to finding the words to describe his extraordinary,
can't-go-wrong season of 1994.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``1994 was kind of a crazy year for me,'' Bagwell said Sunday
night as the Astros prepared for a six-game West Coast swing that
begins tonight in Los Angeles. ``Everything that could go right for
me did that year.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time major-league players went on strike Aug. 12, 1994 _
wiping out the Astros' final 47 regular-season games, the playoffs
and the World Series _ Bagwell was on his way to being the runaway
choice for National League Most Valuable Player with a .368 batting
average, 39 home runs and 116 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a lifetime? An oddity?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing to myself some of the things that happened that
year,'' said Bagwell, the only Astro ever to be named league MVP.
``Everybody, every once in a while, has one of those years you
can't believe _ and that was my year.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting seven weeks into this season that a Bagwell
MVP watch should begin running in the newspaper, least of all
Bagwell. But with nearly one-fourth of this season in the books,
the 30-year-old first baseman's statistics are comparable to his
'94 totals.
</P>
<P>
   Through 36 games, Bagwell is batting .326 with 10 homers and 35
RBIs. At the same point in '94, Bagwell was batting .328 with nine
homers and 37 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bagwell is cautious. He has seen quick starts give way to
dreadful summers. One minute the balls are dropping for base hits
and sailing over the outfield walls at incredible clips. The next
minute every ball finds a glove, and every pitcher resembles a Cy
Young Award winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think too many people win the MVP award without
everything going right,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said.
``There are a lot of guys in the league that are pretty good. When
you win that award, it has to be a career-type year. Some people
are capable of more than one of those years. He might be one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to compare him to '94. I don't think it is
likely that anybody will repeat what was done before. It might be
better; it might be worse. Just because it's the same now doesn't
mean it will be the same way at the end (of the season). I hope it
is. From this point forward in 1994, he got better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell said what makes his MVP year stand out from his other
professional seasons is not just the start but how he maintained it
and actually improved over the course of 4{ months.
</P>
<P>
   After batting .330 over the first two months of '94, Bagwell
caught fire. From June 1 on, he batted .399 with 27 homers and 68
RBIs before suffering a fractured left hand two days before the
strike halted play.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell had an 18-game hitting streak, and his average never
went below .323. He led the league in RBIs, runs (104), total bases
(300) and slugging percentage (.750). His power was the biggest
surprise to Bagwell, who hit 20 homers in 1993 and had 53 in his
first three Astros seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``For three months _ and for the first and only time in my life
_ I can actually say I was a good player,'' Bagwell joked. ``I got
a lot of hits and drove in some runs for the first six to eight
weeks. I really didn't feel that great at the plate. All of a
sudden, right before June started, I kind of clicked, and after
that I got in the batter's box the same way every single day. I
felt real comfortable in there for the longest period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding that hitting groove _ and keeping it _ can be
hit-or-miss.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Bagwell batted .337 in April and .360 in May and hit 18
home runs during the two-month opening stretch. He dropped to .277
in June and .230 in July. He had only 13 homers over the final four
months.
</P>
<P>
   In '97, Bagwell opened with a .326 batting average for the first
two months. In July and August, he hit just .239.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Bagwell struggled through one of the worst starts
of his career, batting .236 with 22 RBIs through May. He hit .320
or better in three of the final four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look back, I never quite found that feeling when I got
into the batter's box every day and did not have to do much to
alter things during the course of the year,'' Bagwell said. ``(In
1994) I could just make a small adjustment within an at-bat, and I
was back where I needed to be. For those other couple of years, it
didn't happen. Some days I get there; some days I don't. When I go
on a long streak of hitting well, I'm usually pretty comfortable,
and I don't have to think about it too much. All I have to think
about is getting a good pitch to hit. This game is so weird,
because every year is different, and you never know what's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to this year and the possibility Bagwell could
be on his way to duplicating his feat of five years ago. He had a
productive spring, which involved a slight adjustment in the way he
grips the bat. And with the exception of the first week of the
season when the Astros' entire offense struggled, Bagwell has
noticed himself doing the things that made 1994 magical.
</P>
<P>
   Since April 16, his average has gone as high as .396 and not
dipped below its current .326. He has hit safely in 30 of the first
36 games, including 14 in a row at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell ranks in the top 10 in the NL in 13 categories,
including RBIs (35), runs (31), walks (25), hits (43) and home runs
(10).
</P>
<P>
   Need further proof of the similarities between '94 and '99 to
date? Bagwell had a three-homer game in both seasons, accomplishing
the feat April 21 at Chicago this year when he moved to the top of
the Astros' all-time home-run list.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a totally complete player,'' Dierker said. ``He's one of
those guys you would say was born to play baseball. This is what
he's meant to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And with the addition of Moises Alou last season and Ken
Caminiti this year to add more power to an already potent lineup,
Bagwell doesn't feel the same kind of pressure to produce at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   However, that hasn't stopped him. In the four seasons after his
MVP campaign, Bagwell averaged 32 home runs, 113 RBIs and a .299
batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty tough on myself and have a certain standard of how
I should be playing every single night and through the course of
the year,'' Bagwell said. ``Last year when I was struggling so bad,
it made it easier on me because we won. But no matter what happens,
I still want to be able to do the things I'm capable of doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 0151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
