<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1131 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-18 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL BUSS LET RAMBIS BUILD CHAMPIONSHIP TEAM?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I'd like to trade places with Jerry Buss for a day
and not just so I could unleash my inner child without having to
worry about cleaning up after it.
</P>
<P>
   Put me in charge of the Lakers and the first thing I'd do is
take that interim label that Kurt Rambis has been wearing and dump
it in the trash along with Buss's bulging black book.
</P>
<P>
   I realize there are people ready to install Chuck Daly or Phil
Jackson in the seat Rambis has been keeping warm since late
February. Rambis must recognize it, too. How else to explain why he
treats most postgame interview sessions as though they're being
moderated by Procrustes?
</P>
<P>
   Rambis' testiness is understandable, given his uncertain future.
Not that he'll admit to being the least bit fazed. He professes not
to look beyond the next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens, happens,'' he says. ``I know I want the job,
but whether I get the job is completely out of my control.''
</P>
<P>
   So many things have been out of his control this shortened
season, it's a wonder he hasn't gone screaming into the night. Then
again, Rambis never was one to shy away from a challenge. As a
player he distinguished himself with his enthusiasm, his
doggedness, his grasp of the game and his allergy to the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   These are the same qualities he brings to coaching. And if he's
feeling his way on the bench, well, all I can say is the Bulls'
dynasty under Jackson wasn't built in a day. Rambis is going to
take a team a long way some day. Wouldn't it make you sick if it
weren't the Lakers?
</P>
<P>
   All year we've seen the changing of the guard: from Michael
Jordan to Allen Iverson; from John Stockton to Jayson Williams;
from Chicago to Philadelphia; from David Robinson to Tim Duncan. So
why shouldn't the old give way to the new in coaching, too?
</P>
<P>
   Let it start with Rambis. I feel for him. I really do. Right now
in Texas, only George W. Bush has any idea what it's like to
audition for a job in such a public manner. When Rambis was named
to replace the deposed Del Harris, he couldn't have foreseen how
literal the title of ``head'' coach would turn out to be.
</P>
<P>
   Goodness knows Rambis has spent more time adjusting psyches than
plays. He worked harder at exorcising Dennis Rodman's demons than
did Rodman. In the end, Rambis didn't fail Rodman so much as Rodman
failed himself. If that makes Rambis a bad coach, as Rodman
asserted at the time of his release, well, good luck to the very
talented, very troubled forward in his search for someone more
capable.
</P>
<P>
   As if dealing with Rodman weren't a sufficient test, Rambis also
had to deal with the fallout of a major trade and the
post-traumatic stress syndrome that Glen Rice and J.R. Reid
experienced upon arriving from Charlotte. It's no small selling job
Rambis pulled off, getting Reid to buy into the notion of putting
his energy into defense instead of scoring.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are reaping the dividends. Reid made life in the low
post miserable for Houston's Charles Barkley in the first round of
the playoffs and he was the reason Tim Duncan got off to a slow
start in the first quarter of a Western Conference semifinal game
the San Antonio Spurs went on to win, 87-81.
</P>
<P>
   Rice is a piece that Rambis continues to try to fit into the
puzzle. He was the Hornets' top scoring threat but finds himself
the No. 3 option with the Lakers, after Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe
Bryant. It's not as though Rambis has expunged Rice from the team's
diet. He has called plays for the forward, who returned to the
lineup Monday after sitting out Saturday's first-round finale
against the Rockets with a stiff elbow. Unfortunately, Rambis is
helpless to set the screens that make his scribblings come alive.
</P>
<P>
   Say this about Rambis: He doesn't hesitate to control what he
can. I love that he purged the practice gym of all security escorts
and assorted other hangers-on. If grade-school-age kids can make it
through a practice without their mommies, why can't a professional
athlete get through one without his bodyguard? Honestly, who are
they seeking protection from, anyway? Themselves, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   Rambis also has impressed me with his handling of O'Neal and
Bryant. There are coaches who would have been inclined to treat
like Faberge eggs the egos of the Lakers' two standout players.
Plenty of unproven coaches would have cut the stars a lot of slack,
lest they alienate their meal tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis hasn't been at all reluctant to hold the reins of
authority. He has shattered a clipboard in disgust and shouted back
at a defiant Bryant. He has benched O'Neal and Bryant to drive home
their deficiencies, gutsy moves that had the effect of amplifying
their respect for him even as they sat silently cursing him.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie head coach would be the first to tell you he has a
lot to learn. The encouraging thing is, he doesn't pretend to be
omniscient. Rambis owns up to his mistakes and in doing so, sets an
example of accountability for O'Neal, Bryant and Co.
</P>
<P>
   That's why there's every reason to think the Lakers can recover
from Monday's setback. On Wednesday, look for hot-shooting Spurs
guard Avery Johnson to have a hand in his face whenever he has the
ball. Expect Bryant to penetrate more on offense. Count on seeing
less of Duncan and more Lakers' points off the fast break.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis will show them the way. And the Lakers, not wanting to
let him down, will take it from there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
