<HEADER>
A1133 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     05-18 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS SLASH LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The three-inch reddish scratch just below
Shaquille O'Neal's neck told the tale he would not. O'Neal was
poked, prodded, battered, scratched and generally manhandled by the
Twin Towers of the San Antonio Spurs on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Fair or foul, it worked.
</P>
<P>
   With Tim Duncan and David Robinson muscling up in tandem, the
Spurs completely disrupted O'Neal, and in turn, the Los Angeles
Lakers, to forcibly take an 87-81 victory in Game 1 of the Western
Conference semifinals at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   When all the banging subsided, O'Neal turned to desperate
measures. He chewed out referee Steve Javie until Derek Fisher and
coach Kurt Rambis intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Missing 13 of 19 shots has that kind of effect on a big man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got real frustrated,'' Robert Horry said. ``You can tell
when he gets frustrated, because he doesn't say anything. That's
when he's at the point of no return. At one point he just stopped
saying stuff and got back down the court.''
</P>
<P>
   That stance carried right into the postgame session.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who actually had a better shooting rate at the
free-throw line (9 of 14), claimed he was not upset, in a rare show
of self-restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. We've seen how they're going to let us play, so we just
have to make adjustments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not upset with the calls?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just missed some shots that I usually make.''
</P>
<P>
   So, that lecture to Javie?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just missed some shots that I usually make.''
</P>
<P>
   Not frustrated?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never get frustrated. You guys see what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Horry said what O'Neal wouldn't. Despite Spurs' rare shutdown of
the league's premier center, he was unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want the truth, they didn't do a good job at all,''
Horry said, ``because if you look at the fim, a lot of times they
(committed) fouls, there was no call. So in my opinion they didn't
do a good job. It's just that they was at home, and they had some
home-cookin'.''
</P>
<P>
   They also had a lot of fouls to give, sending Malik Rose and
Will Perdue at O'Neal when Robinson and Duncan didn't go.
</P>
<P>
   Once O'Neal was derailed, the Lakers wilted.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan was nearly unstoppable, deftly surviving double-teams to
score a game-high 25 points on 11-of-24 shooting. And he was
devastating on defense, blocking six shots, misdirecting plenty
more.
</P>
<P>
   His job was made all the easier by a Lakers offense that fell
into disarray as O'Neal broke down.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was more frank about the Lakers' chances to come back in
Game 2 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best they can play and we still had a couple
opportunities to win the game,'' he said. ``Once we pick our level
of play up we're gonna be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Lakers was the return of Glen Rice, who
had been suffering from a sore and stiff right elbow since Friday
and skipped the Lakers' series-clinching game against Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Rice scored 21 points on 8-of-17 shooting. Kobe Bryant added 21
points.
</P>
<P>
   Down 0-1 in the series, the Lakers now to turn to the well-worn
steal-one-on-the-road approach. But Rambis said there was no
particular agenda aside from the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play every game to win every game,'' he said. ``To me,
it's just become cliche-ish to say that we just wanna win one out
of two, and then if you win the first one, `Well all we gotta do is
win the second one.' ... You wanna win every single ballgame. The
quicker you win four, the better off you are. So it's not a matter
of just trying to get a split. Plus, the situation our team is in,
we're still developing, improving and growing as a team. So we want
to keep playing better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until less than an hour before tipoff that the Lakers
determined Rice would be available. He shot earlier in the day, for
the first time since Friday, but the Lakers were cautious and held
off on a decision until the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he looked all right (at shootaround), but it's not
like we went hard and everything,'' Rambis said. ``That's not a
good criteria to base whether someone should play or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
