<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKUPS MUCKING UP ANGELS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ If you want to know how injuries have changed
the Anaheim Angels, check this: The team's starting left fielder
Sunday night was Dave Silvestri. Its right fielder was Tim Unroe.
</P>
<P>
   Because of injuries to shortstop Gary DiSarcina, center fielder
Jim Edmonds and, most recently, right fielder Tim Salmon, players
who are normally utility or backup players are starting for the
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   How long can names such as Silvestri, Unroe, Orlando Palmeiro,
Reggie Williams, Andy Sheets and Jeff Huson appear in the lineup
before the team falls out of the pennant race altogether? Angels
manager Terry Collins said he doesn't concern himself with things
beyond his control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about anything except what I got, anything
except the 25 guys here,'' Collins said. ``I write down position by
position, and all of a sudden, there's today's lineup. I don't sit
there and say to myself, `I wish I had that guy,' or `Gee,
so-and-so isn't playing, maybe we can get him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That's general manager Bill Bavasi's job. And with Salmon
(sprained left wrist) and DiSarcina (broken bone in left forearm)
out until early July, and Edmonds (shoulder surgery) out until
August, there is definitely a need for replacements. Bavasi,
though, wouldn't call it an urgent need out of respect for the
players he has now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always looking,'' he said. ``We always have to look.
We're lucky to have the guys we have. The guys filling in are good
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you can improve your club, you have to. We'll always
make attempts to get better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 0203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1135 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-REDSOX-BLUEJAYS-BOS &LR;      05-18 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 BBA-RED SOX-BLUE JAYS-BOS  
 SOX GET IN THEIR LAST LICKS
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   TORONTO _ Perhaps this is what they mean by the ultimate secret
weapon. It's the one unrecognized not only by the enemy, but by the
good guys, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ever heard of Brian Daubach, Jimy Williams was asked, before the
Red Sox signed him last winter?
</P>
<P>
   ``To be very honest, no,'' the manager said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   First time Mike Stanley heard the name? Spring training, when
Daubach was one of the huddled masses on the other side of the
aisle in the clubhouse in Fort Myers. Same for John Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure most of these guys never heard of me,'' said Daubach,
the 27-year-old minor league lifer who will require fewer
introductions after hitting a three-run home run in Monday night's
8-7 win over the Toronto Blue Jays that not only was his first home
run in the big leagues, but was delivered with exquisite timing.
</P>
<P>
   The Belleville Basher (the nickname is on loan from fellow
townsman Jimmy Connors, the tennis player) broke a 4-4 tie in the
ninth by treating Toronto reliever Graeme Lloyd with the same
impundence Connors showed many another Aussie, swatting Lloyd's
first pitch on a blistering line over the right-field fence with a
two-handed forehand.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach didn't see the ball clear the wall and land in the Red
Sox bullpen until he'd already reached first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I wanted to do was show anybody up,'' Daubach
said with some embarrassment, ``but I gave it a little fist pump.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't against (Lloyd). It was for nine years' worth of
work in the minors.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, sitting quietly at one end of the winners' clubhouse,
seemed to take as much pleasure in the crowd gathered around
Daubach as the center of attention himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's so exciting,'' Stanley said. ``To get your first home
run, and have it be a game-winner. Do I remember my first one?
Yeah, and it sure wasn't a game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll never forget the first one. He'll never forget who it
was against, and the special meaning it had, being a game-winner.''
</P>
<P>
   In his joy for Daubach, the first baseman overlooked a salient
point. At the time, Daubach's home run looked like a game-winner,
but the run that ultimately made the difference was delivered by
Stanley himself, who followed Nomar Garciaparra's double off Lloyd
with a single off another reliever, Tom Davey.
</P>
<P>
   That was the fifth run of an inning that had begun with the Sox
trailing, 4-3, after Shawn Green's 13th home run off reliever John
Wasdin in the seventh. But the Sox' third win in four games here _
and their first this season that came in their last at-bat _ did
not come without a final dollop of suspense, as Tom Gordon was
clipped for three runs in the bottom of the ninth and put the
winning run on base before striking out Kevin Witt to end it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sure not going to get any easier,'' said Stanley, already
looking ahead to a three-game set that begins Tuesday night at
Fenway Park against the Yankees, who are a half-game ahead of the
Sox in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees are coming to town, then these guys (Blue Jays)
come back to our place, then we go to New York and Cleveland. This
is a tough little stretch that began with this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't sit on our laurels with what we've done here. We've
got to turn the page and get after it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had tied the score in the ninth when gimpy-legged John
Valentin, delivering a pinch hit for the first time in more than
three years (April 14, 1996), singled after Lloyd hit Damon Buford
with a pitch to open the inning. Jose Offerman followed with his
fourth hit of the night, an RBI single to tie the score. It was
Offerman's second four-hit game of the season, the other coming in
his Sox debut April 5 in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto manager Jim Fregosi ordered Jeff Frye walked to set up
the lefty-lefty matchup he wanted, Lloyd vs. Daubach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into that at-bat, I'd had a pretty rough night,'' said
Daubach, who hadn't gotten the ball out of the infield in four
previous at-bats but still managed to be accused of stealing signs
by Blue Jays starter Chris Carpenter after reaching base twice on
errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty good, the way I was able to turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Daubach could just as easily have been
back home in Illinois, playing softball on his brother's team,
Demo's Sports Bar, as he was here, getting regular playing time as
part of Williams's no-apparent-rhyme-no-apparent-reason platoon in
the No. 3 hole.
</P>
<P>
   His home run came, incidentally, on the same day the former
occupant of the No. 3 spot in the Sox order, M. Vaughn, was named
the American League's Player of the Week for his efforts on behalf
of Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   That mattered little to Daubach. He was looking forward to the
fact that his mom and dad were making the trip from Belleville to
Yawkey Way Tuesday night. He had a little souvenir he wanted to
show them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him walk in with the ball,'' Stanley said. ``I told him
Tim Wakefield had the best handwriting. I told him to get him,
maybe not tonight, but in the next few days, and get himself a nice
little insignia.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that they've gotten acquainted, Stanley said what he likes
most about Daubach is his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, gosh,'' he said, ``it seeps.''
</P>
<P>
   The Basher vs. The Bombers. Pedro vs. Cone. 7:05, Yawkey Way.
There are, after all, no secrets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 0204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1137 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-SPURS-HNS &LR;      05-18 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SPURS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN ANTONIO _ The meek may inherit the earth, but they're not going
to win many NBA championships.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's a lesson the San Antonio Spurs have apparently finally
realized, and they were quick to show the Los Angeles Lakers their
newfound toughness Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, employing strong-arm tactics that would make Hulk
Hogan blush, slapped the Lakers silly, taking an 87-81 decision
before 25,297 at Alamodome. The win gave San Antonio a 1-0 lead in
the best-of-seven series, which resumes here Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers blew into town as the biggest, baddest bullies on the
NBA's block, especially after manhandling the Rockets. So the
Lakers had a bit more swagger in their step as they looked ahead to
the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Put it this way: If the Lakers were rap, the Spurs were elevator
music. They were the league's two-ply, squeezably soft good guys.
The guys who made turning the other cheek an art form.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. At least if Monday's game was any indication.
</P>
<P>
   When they decided to get physical, the Spurs obviously had
Shaquille O'Neal in mind. After having his way with the Rockets,
O'Neal was roughed up by the Spurs, one reason he made just six of
his 19 field-goal attempts. He was able to get the rest of his 21
points from the foul line, where he hit nine of 14 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a great defensive ballclub, and we have to take
advantage of that,'' said Mario Elie, who has added some
much-needed toughness to the Spurs. ``We sent a lot of guys at Shaq
to try and wear him down. He can beat you. I watched that Houston
series, how he dominated them (averaging 29.5 points in four
games), and I thought we did a good job clamping down not only on
him but everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal shrugged off the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played great basketball tonight,'' he said. ``They
outplayed us. They played more aggressively, and we made a lot of
mental mistakes. But we still had a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to make some adjustments and come back Wednesday.
They had double and triple teams coming at me really quick tonight,
and I missed a lot of shots I usually make.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't even ask what the Spurs were doing to Kobe Bryant, a
defensive scheme that bordered on child abuse. Any time Bryant, or
any other Laker, took off to attack the basket, the Spurs made sure
they put a body on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we did a much better job of that tonight,'' said David
Robinson, who finished with 15 points and eight rebounds for the
Spurs. ``That's a really good cut-and-slash team, and if you take
away some of those opportunities, then it makes the game a little
tougher for them. I thought we did a better job of that. That was
good. That was a key tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant shook off the whipping to score 21 points but struggled
down the stretch, missing several easy shots around the basket in
the final five minutes as the Lakers were trying to rally. And
O'Neal looked just as drained, grabbing only one of his 15 rebounds
in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of the game,'' said Bryant of the physical play.
``It's a different brand of basketball in the playoffs. When you go
up against Robinson and (Tim) Duncan, you just have to make up your
mind what you are going to do before you make your move and they
can spread their wings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, and Duncan in particular, were feeding off the
transfer of power, going to the basket as often as they pleased.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan powered his way to a 25-point, seven-rebound night,
hitting 11 of his 24 shots and blocking six shots. And Robinson,
whose manhood has been questioned by O'Neal several times over the
past few years, was up to the challenge, shaking off early foul
trouble to finish strong, often challenging the Lakers with strong
drives to the basket instead of settling for the outside jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Not so Glen Rice. Despite finishing with 21 points, Rice was
pretty much a non-factor offensively, shying away from drives when
he saw the defensive tactics the Spurs were utilizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is really being able to do the the physical stuff but
also staying focused on what you're trying to do,'' Robinson said.
``You don't want to get crazy, but at the same time you have to
protect your space.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither team shot well, with the Lakers hitting just 38 percent
from the floor (30 of 79) and the Spurs only 41.9 percent (31 of
74). The difference was the bench play. With Robinson in early foul
trouble, Will Perdue came in and finished with six points and a
team-high nine rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead 67-58 entering the final period, the Spurs expanded that
lead to 15 points on a jumper from Antonio Daniels with 7:20 to
play. The Lakers were forced to call a timeout to regroup, and they
did.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant had two straight baskets, including a 360-degree dunk off
a steal, to spark an 8-0 run by the Lakers _ a streak that was
fueled by three straight San Antonio turnovers. Rice drilled a
baseline jumper that pulled the Lakers within 79-72 with 5:16 left,
and Robinson finally stopped the bleeding with a free throw 22
seconds later, giving the Spurs an 80-72 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers couldn't chip away any more, though, until it was far
too late.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Spurs were the picture of offensive efficiency,
turning the ball over nine times and missing seven free throws in
the fourth quarter. All that allowed the Lakers to get within five
points with under 20 seconds to play, but Robert Horry missed a
3-pointer with 17.8 seconds left to play, and Elie dropped in a
free throw to bump the lead up to 85-79.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're much better when we play team defense like that,'' said
Spurs coach Gregg Popovich. ``We're so much better when we're
rotating well and aggressive. That's the way we have to play
defense if we hope to beat this Laker team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 0212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1138 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-18 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN ANTONIO _ The Diesel blew down I-10 with a full head of steam.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal had just slammed the Rockets in four games and
never looked bigger, stronger or badder. It was a runaway Shaq
Daddy, the road was clear, and there were the San Antonio Spurs,
like their mascot Coyote, looking like potential road kill.
</P>
<P>
   What about the Spurs' David Robinson? What about Tim Duncan?
</P>
<P>
   ``They can see me on the court or off the court,'' O'Neal
mumbled. ``They can't do nothing with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Give The Diesel credit. Individually, neither Robinson nor
Duncan indeed stood a chance, much less his ground, against the
7-1, 330-pound Shaq on Monday night. But amid all the bodacious
buildup to what figures to be a tough and emotional Western
Conference series, take notice of how O'Neal said nothing about the
Spurs' Will Perdue and Malik Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should he have.
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of reasons why the Spurs swept to an 87-81 win
over the Los Angeles Lakers in the semifinal opener, not the least
of which was the Spurs' own unstoppable force. Duncan gave Lakers
forwards J.R. Reid and Robert Horry everything but nervous twitches
on the way to sliding up, under, around and over their poor excuses
for defense for 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank goodness we had Tim,'' Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said.
</P>
<P>
   But it was on the defensive end, where Hack-a-Shaq has become
all the NBA's rage against the monstrous O'Neal, where the Spurs
seemed to perfect the strategy and definitely clinched the game.
</P>
<P>
   And it was Perdue and Rose _ Big Ugly and Little Ugly _ who were
the most unlikely of heroes. In a critical first-half run that
finally gave the Spurs an edge after a sluggish start, Perdue and
Rose lent a hand _ and a knee, elbow, chest, thigh and seemingly
even a few small yard tools on occasion _ to Robinson and Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the night, after O'Neal managed just 6-of-19
shooting from the field, the Spurs had knocked around his senses so
much that he even began hitting free throws. It was a virtually
Rick Barry-like 9-for-14 from the line for the big fellow if you're
keeping track. And O'Neal's 21 points and 15 rebounds showed
nothing if not resiliency.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spurs showed how it's done against the most powerful
force in the game. And in the process, they might have shown why
they'll have an edge against the Lakers that the Rockets never
showed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make him work harder than he has, and we did,''
Popovich said. ``Not only did (Perdue and Rose) guard and rebound,
but they scored and gave us some good minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing that goofy faceguard and slouching over and gasping for
breath during breaks, Perdue might have looked overmatched against
O'Neal. And it might have looked like anything but a fair fight
when the 6-7, 240-pound Rose started trying to push O'Neal out of
the lane.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout the early run that brought the Spurs from as many
as 10 points down to a six-point halftime lead, it was Perdue and
Rose doing the dirty work, while Robinson, Duncan or both swept in
at the last moment to swipe at an O'Neal shot.
</P>
<P>
   Eight times, Duncan and Robinson blocked shots in the
impressively defensive game. Four of those blocks came against
O'Neal, unheard of in the Rockets-Lakers series.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Kurt Rambis said he never had seen O'Neal roughed
up as much as he was in Monday night's game. Rambis thought more
fouls should have been called.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time the Spurs finally put away the Lakers with late
free throws and big stretch-time buckets by Robinson (15 points,
eight rebounds), it was clear this was a perfectly executed
execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game 1 is over. That's all I can say,'' O'Neal said. ``We have
to see how the (officials) are going to let us play. The Spurs have
players. They played pretty good. They were the aggressors.''
</P>
<P>
   On the way into San Antonio, O'Neal lost his luggage. But the
weakness of this Lakers team wasn't exposed, naked, until the Spurs
used a pair of seven-footers as a second line of defense while
Perdue and Rose hacked away.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, if Glen Rice (21 points) is the only outside threat the
Lakers have, which he was Monday, Robinson and Duncan might
continue to pay only cursory attention to Reid, Horry and the like
while collapsing on O'Neal after he makes his move.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't even close to a beautiful game. But it looked
wonderful to the Spurs. The Lakers hit just 38 percent of their
shots, and everyone got into the act for San Antonio. Perdue scored
six points and grabbed nine rebounds in O'Neal's face, for
goodness' sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good win for us because of how we did it,'' Popovich
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hack-a-Shaq redefined. Just imagine how the Spurs might
have rolled if O'Neal wasn't stroking those free throws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
