<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1141 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS2-LADN-(SLA     05-18 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS2-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS SLASH LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 WRITETHRU (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The three-inch reddish scratch just below
Shaquille O'Neal's neck told the tale he would not. O'Neal was
poked, prodded, battered, scraped and generally manhandled by the
Twin Towers of the San Antonio Spurs on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Fair or foul, it worked.
</P>
<P>
   With Tim Duncan and David Robinson muscling up in tandem, the
Spurs completely disrupted O'Neal and, in turn, the Lakers, to
forcibly take an 87-81 victory in Game 1 of the Western Conference
semifinals at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   When all the banging subsided, O'Neal turned to desperate
measures. He chewed out referee Steve Javie until Derek Fisher and
coach Kurt Rambis intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Missing 13 of 19 shots has that kind of effect on a big man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got real frustrated,'' Robert Horry said. ``You can tell
when he gets frustrated, because he doesn't say anything. That's
when he's at the point of no return. At one point he just stopped
saying stuff and got back down the court.''
</P>
<P>
   That stance carried right into the postgame session.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who actually had a decent shooting rate at the
free-throw line (9 of 14), finishing with 21 points, claimed he was
not upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. We've seen how they're going to let us play, so we just
have to make adjustments,'' he said, in a rare show of
self-restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Not upset with the calls?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just missed some shots that I usually make.''
</P>
<P>
   So, that lecture to Javie?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just missed some shots that I usually make.''
</P>
<P>
   Not frustrated?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never get frustrated. You guys see what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Horry said what O'Neal wouldn't. Despite the Spurs' rare
shutdown of the league's premier center, he was unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want the truth, they didn't do a good job at all,''
Horry said, ``because if you look at the film, a lot of times they
(committed) fouls, there was no call. So in my opinion, they didn't
do a good job. It's just that they was at home and they had some
home cookin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Once O'Neal was derailed, the Lakers wilted.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan was nearly unstoppable, deftly surviving double-teams to
score a game-high 25 points on 11-of-24 shooting. And he was
devastating on defense, blocking six shots and misdirecting many
others.
</P>
<P>
   His job was made all the easier by a Lakers' offense that fell
into disarray as O'Neal broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice, returning from a sore elbow, and Kobe Bryant both hit
8 of 17 shots for 21 points each, as the Lakers shot 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After taking an early 12-point lead, the Lakers let the Spurs
take control with an endless series of forced shots and bad passes.
They committed 10 turnovers, with just 13 assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had built a 24-12 lead with 1:39 to go in the first
but were then held without a field goal for eight minutes. San
Antonio closed out the quarter with an 8-0 run, climaxing with a
31-foot 3-pointer by Jerome Kersey at the buzzer to cut the lead to
24-20. The Lakers never led again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got down a couple of times, they made some runs and we
started to rush things,'' said Derek Fisher, who scored 13 points.
``We were searching for the home runs. If we had kept our poise a
little bit during certain stretches of the game, we would have been
in great position. But this is Game 1, and we feel very confident
coming back in here Wednesday night that we can get a win.''
</P>
<P>
   That confidence stemmed in large part from the fact that, as bad
as the Lakers were, they had a chance down the stretch. They
trailed by as much as 15 in the fourth quarter but got it down to
five with a minute left and were within four, 83-79, with 24.4
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   But Horry airballed a baseline jumper, O'Neal missed a
two-footer and the rally fell shot.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was almost cocky in his assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best they can play,'' he said, ``and we still had a
couple opportunities to win the game. Once we pick our level of
play up we're going to be fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 0219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
