<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1142 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     05-18 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS IN MIDDLE OF BASEBALL'S FREE AGENCY MESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If Timberwolves forward Kevin Garnett and his $120
million, franchise-bending contract was what scared the pants off
NBA owners, forced the re-opening of the collective bargaining
agreement and sent the league into a long lockout that lasted until
a new deal that capped costs was inked at the 11th hour, what about
Alex Rodriguez?
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three years after the dawn of baseball free agency, could
the 23-year-old Mariners shortstop be the gifted, young superstar
whose next contract sends the final, knee-knocking shiver down the
weak spine of major league baseball?
</P>
<P>
   We all know A-Rod is destined for greatness, so why not let his
impending free agency (after 2000 when the guess is he goes for
$150 million) be the one that topples baseball's disastrous
business model _ or lack-thereof.
</P>
<P>
   One can only hope such an industry-altering upheaval is on
baseball's horizon. The Mariners are waiting. Otherwise, without
some sort of drastic reform, the future of the Mariners and almost
every other team that isn't in New York, Chicago or Los Angeles
will have to settle for playing in the Little League World Series
with Taiwan and Taipei and Tom's River, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Dodgers and Yankees or Braves and Orioles will
battle it out each November on some super cable empire pay-per-view
station for the New Interplanetary World Series.
</P>
<P>
   If you think ``Star Wars'' is creating a buzz ...
</P>
<P>
   This week, it seems especially appropriate to ponder the fate of
A-Rod, the M's, small-market (or have-not) teams and baseball's
inexcusable inability to put together some sort of industry-saving
plan.
</P>
<P>
   No, they can't ruin the game of baseball. The game is perfect.
But that doesn't mean there won't be a day when fans wake up and
their local ``major league team'' has flat out folded, disappeared,
gone out of business because it was impossible not to succumb to
the ravages of an industry that can no longer succeed.
</P>
<P>
   If the Penguins are bankrupt in the NHL, how far behind is
Montreal or Pittsburgh's Pirates or maybe even the Mariners, whose
debt load is about $300 million and the owners already know the new
stadium won't be the answer?
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, one of our favorite annual reports was released.
Forbes magazine has discovered that 14 of major league baseball's
30 teams lost money in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we all know a franchise losing money is not a good sign _
though there are some baseball owners who deserve very little
sympathy for this tide of red ink.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers lost $11.7 million on an estimated $108 million in
revenue. Poor Rupert Murdoch, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams with operating losses were Kansas City ($10.9
million;) Toronto ($9.5 million;) Milwaukee ($8.8 million;)
Mariners ($8.6 million;) Padres ($8 million;) Cubs ($7.9 million;)
Boston ($7.6 million;) Minnesota ($7.1 million;) San Francisco
($6.4 million;) Mets ($5.2 million;) Houston ($3.7 million) and
Anaheim ($200,000.)
</P>
<P>
   The real problem with so many teams losing money is that it has
created this chasm between the haves and the have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see the disparity growing, both in terms of gross
revenue and payroll,'' baseball commissioner Bud Selig said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, disparity is the No. 1 problem we have. It's only
getting worse. It's a problem that has to be dealt with,'' Selig
said.
</P>
<P>
   Selig's comments came not long after the Dodgers signed pitcher
Kevin Brown to a deal last December that pays Brown $15 million a
year and makes him baseball's first $100 million player.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone is well accustomed to saying that the sky is falling
for baseball, but the Dodgers' deal with Brown _ plane rides home
in the Fox jet and all _ was legitimately seen as the latest,
gravest break in the economic barrier.
</P>
<P>
   If Brown is worth $100 million, what is Ken Griffey worth? What
is A-Rod worth? How can the M's possibly sign one of the them, let
alone both, unless the M's are praying baseball institutes
something like a salary cap so that parity is achievable, like in
the NFL, NBA and NHL.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, when baseball can no longer provide fans and
players the chance that their team starts opening day as a
contender, the game is in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one has to question whether there already is something
inherently unfair about this game. The answer seems obviously
``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, baseball's new executive vice president of
operations, went so far as to propose that some small-market teams
should be up front and tell fans that their home team is merely an
entertainment product, not a competitive opponent, since there is
little hope their team will beat the Yankees, Braves or Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Seattle, where the payroll is holding at about $50
million, it is a daily struggle to wonder how much of the M's woes
are because of poor trades by vice president of baseball operations
Woody Woodward or because Mariner owners might as well spend $20
million if they aren't going to spend $80 million _ the going rate
these days for a contender.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mariners are lucky, baseball will be brought to its knees
before A-Rod's Darth Vader agent brings them to theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 0220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0055 </DOCNO>
