<HEADLINE>
HALAMA, MARINER BATS SHINE IN ROUT OF TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ They scored 15 runs and challenged a pair of team
records Monday night, but with the '99 Mariners, the most
significant stuff always happens on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   While 25,710 fans at the Kingdome watched the M's bash six
homers in beating the Minnesota Twins 15-5, manager Lou Piniella's
thoughts turned to his pitching staff. Five strong relief innings
from John Halama convinced him to give the rookie a chance to
start, and 21/3 erratic innings from starter Mac Suzuki convinced
him to put Suzuki, another rookie, back in long relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to get (Halama) in the rotation, but we've only
had one left-hander in the bullpen,'' Piniella said. ``But now that
we've got (Jordan) Zimmerman, we can do something with Halama and
give him a chance to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Also moving to the rotation is Ken Cloude, who started Saturday
when Freddy Garcia had to be skipped because of a bruised shoulder.
Cloude will start Saturday in Kansas City and Halama Tuesday in
Minnesota, setting up Jamie Moyer, Cloude, Garcia, Jeff Fassero and
Halama as the Mariners' rotation when they start a six-game road
trip Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to be a starter in this game,'' said Halama, who
was supposed to start in New York May 9 but was forced into relief
instead. ``But if that doesn't happen, as long as I can contribute
and give my team some quality innings out of the pen, I'm going to
be happy with that.''
</P>
<P>
   After a home run by Edgar Martinez gave the M's a 3-0
first-inning lead, Suzuki lost it by allowing a homer on the first
pitch of the second inning and three runs on three hits in the
third.
</P>
<P>
   Halama worked out of trouble in the third, then returned to the
mound with a 7-4 lead in the fourth. A run-scoring single by Butch
Huskey and a three-run homer by Jay Buhner had given the M's a
four-run third and chased Eric Milton (1-4).
</P>
<P>
   Buhner's blast scored Martinez for the second time, and the
Mariners' designated hitter would score three more runs, tying Ken
Griffey Jr.'s single-game club record with five.
</P>
<P>
   Huskey drove in seven runs Monday, one shy of the club record
shared by Alvin Davis and Mike Blowers. He belted his first career
grand slam in the sixth, then added a two-run shot off former
Mariner Bob Wells in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   It was Huskey's first seven-RBI day at any level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling to be able to go out there and do that
when you're not playing as much as you'd like to,'' he said. ``It's
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Huskey has been caught in the Mariners' outfield crunch in
recent weeks. Since acquiring Brian Hunter _ who ``had his leg
wrapped,'' according to Piniella, and was a late scratch Monday _
to fill their long-vacant leadoff spot, the Mariners have had seven
outfielders on the roster. That has left them with only 10
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The M's are the only team in baseball with just 10 pitchers, and
Piniella reiterated his hope that the M's will add an 11th soon.
It's almost a necessity, as going from a four-man rotation to a
five-man rotation creates another hole in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can spot-start (Halama) from time to time against a team
that has more left-handed hitters, and use Suzuki when a team has
more right-handed hitters, and just mix and match that way,
depending on what our needs are,'' Piniella said. ``That's the
advantage of having more pitchers, especially with our staff, where
some of my starters aren't giving you innings. You can go out and
get them and put someone else in there and give yourself a chance
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama left the game after a Marty Cordova bouncer nicked the
tips of his fingers. The injury was not serious, and it gave
Zimmerman a chance at his first major league outing. The
24-year-old, who was called up Sunday from Class AA New Haven,
retired both hitters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't nervous at all,'' said Zimmerman. ``David Segui came
over to me and said, `Is it your first time out there? Don't worry
about it _ almost all the fans have left.' After that, it didn't
bother me at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
