<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1265 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GADGETS-CAMERA18-COX     05-18 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GADGETS-CAMERA18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New camera simplifies taking good pictures
 &HT;    EDS: RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO NEED IT.
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you were lucky enough to give birth on
Mother's Day, the coincidence probably made an already magical
event even more special.
</P>
<P>
   The people at Kodak want to help you celebrate the occasion by
sending you a free camera to capture images of the new addition to
your family.
</P>
<P>
   And the camera they're offering is one of the sweetest little
gadgets I've seen in years. Kodak sent a sample of its Advantix
T550 camera, and I took it along on a recent assignment to cover
the Star Wars Celebration in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The camera is incredibly simple to use, it takes good pictures
under a variety of conditions, it's smaller than a pack of
cigarettes and about as lightweight, and it takes pictures in three
formats: classic, group and panoramic.
</P>
<P>
   The camera uses drop-in Advantix film cartridges. To load, you
flip a switch and a port pops open. Drop the cartridge into place
and the camera threads itself and sets up for the first picture.
</P>
<P>
   The camera has automatic focus features and allows distant shots
or close-ups from as near as 16 inches. The built-in flash also is
automatic and has red-eye reduction circuitry.
</P>
<P>
   The T550 can be set to stamp the time and date automatically on
the backs of prints. It also comes with special-occasion captions
such as birthday or vacation that can be automatically stamped on
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The T550 doesn't have the flexibility of more complicated
cameras. It doesn't have shutter speed or aperture adjustments, for
example, and it can't zoom in and out to get close-ups from a
distance or wide-angle shots.
</P>
<P>
   But for photographers who are intimidated by complexity, it's a
capable device.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit expensive, however. The T550 package offered to
mothers has a roll of film with free processing, a battery and a
coupon for a free picture CD and has a value of $150, according to
Kodak.
</P>
<P>
   Processing also is a bit pricey. To get double prints on a roll
of 15 shots cost me about $9, including an index print.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't give birth on Mother's Day, and you're interested
in buying the camera, it is a new model that is still difficult to
find. Keep an eye on the camera departments of department stores,
discount stores and electronic retailers for the T550 and similar
models. You're less likely to find Advantix cameras in photographic
specialty stores.
</P>
<P>
   Free camera for giving birth on Mother's Day
</P>
<P>
   If you had a baby May 9 or adopted May 10, you can receive a
free T550 camera. Send a certified copy of the newborn's birth
certificate or adoption papers to Kodak Advantix Picture Perfect
Mother's Day, P.O. Box
</P>
<P>
   5431, Young America, MN 55558-5431. Call the Kodak Information
Center at (800) 242-2424 for additional information.
</P>
<P>
   James Cummings writes for the Dayton (Ohio) Daily News .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
