<SLUG> BC-HKN-FIX-SPCL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Even now, 51 years later, Milt Schmidt, Woody Dumart, Pat Egan,
Fernie Flaman, and their Boston Bruin teammates don't know some of
the most basic details of the National Hockey League's greatest
gambling scandal. Two Bruins on the 1947-48 team were barred for
life for betting on a Boston game in Chicago Stadium on Feb. 18,
1948, the only NHL players ever handed hockey's death sentence for
gambling. Now, the scandal's full story is told, in a three-part
series by Globe sportswriter Michael Madden.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HKN-FIX-I-SPCL (Boston) _ After conspiring with teammate Billy
Taylor to bet on games the Bruins were likely to lose, Don
Gallinger heads for a date with destiny in Chicago. By Michael
Madden. (3 takes.)
</P>
<P>
   HKN-FIX-II-SPCL (Port Colborone, Ontario) _ Gallinger makes
contact with a nefarious figure, establising a connection that will
mean the end of his days in the National Hockey League. By Michael
Madden. (3 takes.)
</P>
<P>
   HKN-FIX-III-SPCL (Boston) _ Armed with transcripts of a wiretap
that recorded Gallinger's call, league president Clarence Campbell
conducts his investigation and metes out the penalties. By Michael
Madden. (3 takes.)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   HKN-FIX-PRATT (Boston) _ MVP Babe Pratt of Toronto knew a good
bet when he saw one. By Michael Madden. 510 words.
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  All stories will bear the BOS
designator and move under the Sports (s) category code.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
