<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1295 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FIX-PRATT-BOS &LR;      05-18 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FIX-PRATT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRATT NETTED A PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In the annals of the National Hockey League, few games
can match the Boston-Toronto contest in Maple Leaf Gardens Nov. 27,
1943, for bizarreness. It also demonstrated how flagrant gambling
was in the league at the time, particularly by Toronto's Babe
Pratt, who would be MVP of the NHL that season.
</P>
<P>
   World War II had ravaged the rosters of all teams except the
Montreal Canadiens (Quebec had voted against universal
conscription). Boston's goalie was veteran Bert Gardiner, whom many
of his ex-teammates described as an alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gardiner would walk into mirrors (in hotels),'' said Don
Gallinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a goalie with the DTs,'' is how Bep Guidolin put it.
</P>
<P>
   Gardiner had started the 1943-44 season poorly. A week before
the game in Toronto, he gave up 13 goals to the Canadiens, an NHL
record at the time.
</P>
<P>
   When the team boarded its train at South Station for Toronto,
Bruins players recalled, coach Art Ross smelled alcohol on
Gardiner's breath and angrily threw him off the train. The problem
was, when the Bruins arrived in Toronto, the team had no goalie;
teams did not carry spare goaltenders then.
</P>
<P>
   Ross asked his friends in Toronto for suggestions, and the
goalie he found was George Abbott, a 47-year-old minister who had
some amateur experience. When Boston trainer Win Green answered a
knock at the door of the locker room, he saw an aging man who said
he was the Bruins' goalie for the game that night. Green threw him
out, saying, ``What's going on here?''
</P>
<P>
   It got worse. Abbott was so nervous, Bruins players recalled,
that he began to put his skates on the wrong feet. After he finally
dressed, he was so anxious to go on the ice that he opened the door
and went into the crowded lobby of Maple Leaf Gardens, clomping
about among the fans.
</P>
<P>
   In warmups, Bruins players lobbed their softest shots at Abbott,
but the pucks would be in the net before he moved his glove or
stick. Watching all this was Pratt, the star defenseman of the
Maple Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a betting ring at Maple Leaf Gardens then, up on the
top floor,'' said defenseman Pat Egan, who joined the Bruins later
that season. ``That was well known; you could bet on anything you
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened next soon became lore. As Egan recalled the story
as told to him, Pratt returned to his locker room, ``takes his
skates off, puts on his overcoat over his uniform and goes upstairs
and bets $500 on the Maple Leafs.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto won the game, 7-4. Newspapers back in Boston reported
that ``Gardiner had been stricken with influenza,'' forcing the
Bruins to use ``a rookie netminder.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that season, Abbott wrote a letter to Ross asking for a
second chance; the Maple Leafs, for their part, offered to pay
Abbott's expenses to Boston. Alas, Abbott's career in the NHL
lasted just that one game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1296 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FIX-II-SPCL-3RD &LR;  &UR;      05-18 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FIX-II-SPCL-3RD </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 PORT COLBORNE, Ontario: ... free man.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tamer also had been a suspect in the 1937 Thanksgiving Day
barroom slaying of Harry Millman, a member of Detroit's notorious
Purple Gang that refused to turn over to mobsters its proceeds from
various rackets. Tamer's name also had been mentioned in connection
with the 1945 murder of Michigan State Sen. Warren G. Hooper. But
he was not charged in either murder.
</P>
<P>
   Tamer's parole term was about to expire, on Feb. 29, 1948. Both
the Detroit police and Michigan parole officials thus intensified
their investigation of Tamer and focused their attention on his bar
at 543 Woodward Avenue in downtown Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Police installed an illegal wiretap, a listening device that
used copper wire instead of the tape recordings that are common
today. Bourke had been monitoring Tamer's activities since January
1947, along with Michigan Liquor Control Commission investigators,
in an attempt to uncover the gangsters' hidden ownership of Detroit
bars. Bourke also was interested in Tamer's bookmaking, numbers,
and any other activities of the man soon to be known as ``Detroit's
No. 1 gangster.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 18, 1948, the bombshell fell. Police eavesdropped on a
phone call to Detroit from Chicago by a man wishing to bet on the
Chicago-Boston hockey game. After that call, police were more
amazed when a call was placed from Tamer's bar to a hotel in New
York City, a person-to-person call, apparently to Billy Taylor, now
of the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Taylor also would like to bet on the Black Hawks to beat
the Bruins. A $500 bet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after the phone calls, the puck was dropped for the
opening faceoff at Chicago Stadium. Egan, as he always did in
Chicago, skated over to Black Hawks star Doug Bentley the first
chance he got and pointed to the Indian on Bentley's sweater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to get him mad,'' said Egan, ``we'd say, `Hey, Bentley!
Is that your picture on the sweater?' Because he had a nose on him,
a bloody nose, and he'd go on a spree.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what Gallinger expected. In Gallinger's mind,
Chicago always started fast in the first period, with Bentley
leading the way, ``and we always seemed to be down, 2-0, after the
first period.''
</P>
<P>
   The Black Hawks, as Gallinger expected, quickly scored first, as
Gus Bodnar tallied after 6:21 of play. But a minute later Dumart
whipped an unassisted goal past young Chicago goalie Emile ``The
Cat'' Francis. Former Bruin and Maple Leaf Roy Conacher next beat
Brimsek with a 60-foot backhander to give Chicago the lead, 2-1, at
10:03. But Grant ``Knobby'' Warwick tied it again late in the
period.
</P>
<P>
   For Gallinger, and for Taylor 900 miles away in New York,
Warwick's goal was a most painful irony. It was Warwick who had
come from the Rangers two weeks earlier in the trade for Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game starts and, all of a sudden, we're not dominating the
game,'' is Gallinger's recollection.
</P>
<P>
   But, he went on, ``I knew that wasn't safe because of the way
the game was blowing. Because when that Bentley line flies in the
first period, they win the game by the first period with two or
three goals and then you have a hell of an uphill battle against
that line and the rest fall in and they're hard to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   In Gallinger's memory of the game that changed his life, he was
thinking in the second period, ``I don't like the way the game is
flowing. And now when the second period ends, it's 2-2, so we've
come back since the first period.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, his memory is incorrect. The Bruins had taken a 3-2
lead by the end of the second. Gallinger's memory is even more awry
when he recalls the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, we go into the third period and that thing stayed tied
until about the eight- or nine-minute mark to go,'' said Gallinger,
``and then I broke over the center ice line and I fed a pass to the
winning goal, and we move ahead, 3-2.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, rookie Ed Sandford had given the Bruins the lead on an
assist from Dumart at 16:37 of the second period. And the Bruins'
final goal of the game came with less than two minutes left, when
Dumart took a pass from Sandford and beat Francis.
</P>
<P>
   Very few of the Bruins who played in this game can remember many
details. Sandford, for instance, had replaced the injured Schmidt
as the center of the top line, ``but I don't remember anything
about the game,'' he said. Dumart, for his part, can remember
little of it except, ``I scored two goals.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one thing, though, that all the Bruins remember: They
won the game, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt anything,'' claimed Gallinger. ``All I knew was
what was happening, that I was losing $1,500 or $3,000. And, before
that game was over, I sat on that bench and I said, `Gallinger, you
can be as hard-nosed as any sonofabitch. You've seen a lot of
hard-nosers in your life and now maybe it's your turn to be
hard-nosed.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At game's end, Gallinger skated behind the goal to the door that
led down the steps to the basement of Chicago Stadium and into the
locker room. By the time he reached the locker room, Gallinger had
made up his mind. He was not going to pay Tamer the $1,500 he had
lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blew that goddamned bet,'' said Gallinger. I said, `If I
don't give them the damned money, then it's always in my bank
account or in my pocket.' And I said, `Gallinger, this may be the
greatest lesson you've ever learned and you surely don't ever want
to do it again.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I did it. I've never paid that wager to this day.''
</P>
<P>
   The players dressed. A pleased Dit Clapper, the coach, conducted
his usual postgame ritual after road games, giving $4 each to the
four ``cab captains,'' who had the responsibility of corraling
three other players to share a cab.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you what happened after that game in Chicago, and
this is all I remember of it,'' said the Bruins' Kenny Smith.
``Galley and (Paul) Ronty and (John) Peirson all came back from
Chicago Stadium in the same cab with me. I was the cab captain. And
I remember Galley said we had to stop, that, `I've got to make a
phone call.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Smith distinctly recalled Gallinger hurrying into the LaSalle
Hotel as the others waited outside. Gallinger returned ``and he
never said anything (about the call) to us,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Was he calling Taylor in New York for advice on what to do?
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger said he did not remember making a call after the game.
</P>
<P>
   The game the Boston Bruins won.
</P>
<P>
   The game Don Gallinger lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1299 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FIX-III-SPCL-3TAK     05-18 1762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FIX-III-SPCL-3 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLUCKY BETTOR IS TAPPED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- At 11 o'clock on the morning of Feb. 25, 1948, the
Bruins' Don Gallinger was back in his childhood hometown of Port
Colborne, Ontario. When the Bruins were in to play the Maple Leafs,
Gallinger always left Toronto for a visit home, a mere two hours
away.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger was downtown in the Victoria Sweets Shop, drinking a
soda and schmoozing with old pals still impressed with stories
about life in the National Hockey League. Port Colborne seldom sent
any boys to the NHL, but now this town of 11,000 or so had two _
and two good ones at that: Gallinger, a star with the Bruins; and
Ted Kennedy, the tough, driving force of Ontario's joy, the Maple
Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   The pride of the town couldn't be greater. Wasn't it just a
while back that Maple Leaf Gardens held a ``Port Colborne Night''
for a Bruins-Maple Leafs game and presented Gallinger and Kennedy
with expensive watches? Gallinger would keep that watch in its
satin-lined case for a half-century, treasuring it.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger had almost _ but not quite _ forgotten about the
$1,500 bet he had made a week earlier in Chicago, betting on his
own team to lose to the Black Hawks. Gallinger had been positive
the Bruins would lose; instead, they won, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger's mind was not wracked by ethical debates; his
thinking was merely that he had made a bad bet. Gallinger was a
gambler, and, as all gamblers learn, bad bets are made from time to
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at it as if a tout had given me a horse at a race
track,'' Gallinger would say, ``and I had bet on the horse. And the
horse didn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   His concern was not that the bet had been made, but with his
decision that he would not pay the $1,500 to James Tamer, the
Detroit bookie and gangster who had taken the wager. There might be
problems on the Bruins' next visit to Detroit. For sure, Billy
Taylor, the former Bruin now with the New York Rangers, would be
hounding Gallinger to pay Tamer. It was Taylor who had first
broached the subject of betting on Bruins games with Gallinger in
1947, and Taylor who had introduced Gallinger to Tamer.
</P>
<P>
   After the Bruins had won _ and Gallinger had lost _ in Chicago,
the Bruins took the long train ride to Montreal and dispatched the
Canadiens Saturday night in the Forum, 3-1. The Bruins hastily but
happily left the Forum after the game for their Pullman car parked
in the Montreal rail yards and headed south for a Sunday night game
in New York, where the Rangers beat them, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   On the next day, the Bruins again were headed north, this time
to Toronto and, as usual, Boston general manager Art Ross allowed
any of his players from the Toronto area to go home.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Wednesday morning when Gallinger was in the Victoria
Sweets Shop, exactly one week after he had made his bet in Chicago.
If there was one thing about that bet of which Gallinger was
certain, it was that no one would ever know he had made it except
he and the man who took it, Tamer. Gallinger had gone over the
phone call in his mind time and again, and he was positive he had
hidden his identity.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Doan walked into the coffee shop at the corner of King and
Clarence streets. When they were boyhood chums, Doan remembered,
Gallinger ``was a great gambler even then.''
</P>
<P>
   Doan was working for the electric company reading meters that
morning, he recalled, ``and I came into the Victoria. Galley used
to hang there. And that's where I gave him the news. I was the
first one to tell him.''
</P>
<P>
   Doan said he told Gallinger, `` `I heard it on the radio, about
these fellows caught gambling in the NHL,' '' adding that the story
had come out of Detroit. ``He said he didn't know anything about
it. He seemed surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said something about gambling in the NHL,'' recalled
Gallinger recently from his one-room apartment in Burlington,
Ontario. ``And I said, `Can you define it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   What followed were words that shocked Gallinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just said there was some sort of big gambler in Detroit who
had been caught on wiretap and they didn't have too much to say
other than there was gambling in the National Hockey League.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it all came together for Gallinger. His mother had told him
just before he headed downtown that an urgent call had come from
Ross at the Royal York Hotel in Toronto. The message was that all
players were to report to Ross's suite as soon as possible. And
Gallinger was told _ no, ordered _ to take the next train to
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger had not known what to make of this message.
</P>
<P>
   Now he did.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, on that same morning, Tamer was four days away from
total freedom. On March 1, his parole for a bank-robbery conviction
in 1934 would be expired and the Michigan Parole Board would no
longer be able to use its extraordinary powers to yank him off the
street on any pretense, such as ``associating with disreputable
characters,'' and send him back to the state prison.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Detroit that morning, the Red Wings were practicing at
the Olympia, but few minds were on hockey. The newspapers screamed
in end-the-world-sized headlines, ``Hockey Probes `Fix' Rumors,''
and every newscast on every radio station was reporting the
shocking news. The story had been leaked by a Detroit policeman to
a reporter, though which teams or players were involved was not
revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Adams, general manager of the Red Wings, had called every
player into his office and asked them, ``Did you bet on a hockey
game?'' Clarence Campbell, the NHL president, had sent urgent word
from Montreal for all teams to question all players. The NHL had
little or no security apparatus then; the questioning would be done
by general managers and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   More than a few players immediately suspected at least one
possible culprit. And right there in Detroit, as the Red Wings
practiced, they talked among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Bep Guidolin, who had been traded from the Bruins to Detroit for
Taylor at the start of that season, recalled, ``Guys were saying,
`Betcha Billy's involved, betcha Billy's involved.' Billy, you
know, bet on horses, racetracks, knew some bookmakers, he has that
pool room in Oshawa.''
</P>
<P>
   Guidolin was friends with Billy Taylor, had been in the same
Canadian Army barracks in Newmarket, Ontario, with Taylor during
World War II, had listened to Taylor tell of his gambling tales
during those boring Army days. But Guidolin's closest friend in the
NHL was Gallinger, his former teammate with the Bruins, and
Guidolin felt his stomach sink when he heard the gambling reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were skating around the ice, nobody ever mentioned
Galley's name to me,'' said Guidolin. ``Now, I'm the only guy who
knew Galley, and I never said a word. I just said to myself,
`Please, God, don't let Galley be involved. Please, God.' Galley
needed the dough, and he liked to bet.''
</P>
<P>
   After practice, Guidolin headed home to his wife, Ellie, a
former skater in ice shows. It had been Gallinger who introduced
Guidolin to Ellie back in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got home and I asked my wife, `Did you hear the news?' ''
recalled Guidolin.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she had.
</P>
<P>
   Both feared the worst.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger got a ride to Welland, Ontario, the next town over
from Port Colborne, but not before buying the paper. The train to
Toronto left from Welland and, by the time it pulled out, Gallinger
had virtually memorized the newspaper story. His mind was racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time I got to Toronto,'' recalled Gallinger, ``I'd had
time to think. I had a chance to think about everything I'd read in
that paper and, then, all of a sudden, I said, `Well, there's no
proof I can be tied to this evidence in any way, shape, or form.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger played over and over in his mind the call to Tamer to
make the bet. He was positive he could not be identified, wiretap
or no wiretap. Tamer, the gangster, surely would not talk to
police, Gallinger reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that always crossed my mind was the only person
who could involve me in this was Billy Taylor,'' said Gallinger.
``And I said to myself, `Billy Taylor would never do that; he'd be
double-barreling himself. He'd be only putting himself in deeper.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger's mind was made up by the time he arrived in Toronto.
He would deny all.
</P>
<P>
   As the Bruins gathered in the foyer of Ross's suite at the Royal
York Hotel, the players also had their suspects. And the name of
Don Gallinger was prominent.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Pat Egan, for one, thought back to Gallinger's many
gambling incidents, from placing bets with the bull gang at Boston
Garden, to ``the next thing, Gallinger starts taking the bets and
covering them himself'' in the locker room on races at Suffolk
Downs and Rockingham Park, to myriad card games. Egan, like all the
Bruins, mentally went up and down the roster for possible suspects.
</P>
<P>
   All the youngsters _ such as Ed Sandford, Paul Ronty, Ed
Harrison, and John Peirson _ were immediately cleared, as were
Woody Dumart and Milt Schmidt, players beyond reproach on and off
the ice, and goalie Frankie Brimsek.
</P>
<P>
   Many Bruins, though, would come back to one teammate: Don
Gallinger.
</P>
<P>
   As the players waited to be questioned, Gallinger arrived, and
he recalled defenseman Johnny Crawford saying to him, `` `Galley,
aren't you going to put an end to all this? Where's it all going to
end?' Crawford would say, `Galley, it's got to be you. You're the
only man who would do something like this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Peters had been with the Bruins only two months, but he
spoke his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all looking at each other,'' Peters recalled. ``I can
remember telling Don Gallinger, `I'm going in there to tell the
truth and you'd better go in there and you better tell the truth,
too.' I was mad. I can remember that to the very end of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the players entered the suite, they were met by Ross, the
stern general manager himself, as well as coach Dit Clapper and
Harold ``Baldy'' Cotton, the chief scout who had signed many of
them. Ross knew enough to immediately dismiss some players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember going into the room like it was yesterday,''
said Sandford, a rookie that season. ``Ross said, `You don't know
anything about this guy (Tamer), do you? I hope you don't, but if
you do, you'd better let me know.' I said, `Mr. Ross, I don't know
what anybody is talking about. I have no knowledge of this.' And he
said, `Get the hell out of here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1300 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FIX-III-SPCL-2ND &LR;      05-18 1829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FIX-III-SPCL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... of here.' ''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Other players have similar memories, though a few don't remember
the questioning at all. Gallinger remembers Ross, Clapper, and
Cotton ``sitting in three chairs in a little semicircle,'' and
``once I got in there, Ross took over.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger had worked out his plan. He would admit only what any
witness might corroborate and deny everything else. Gallinger knew
he could not deny meeting Tamer because teammate Wally Wilson had
been present in Detroit when Gallinger and Tamer talked three weeks
earlier. Also, Gallinger and Taylor had met Tamer much earlier in
the season at a nightclub outside Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger recalled telling Ross, `` `Yes, I met that man only
once. You say, Do I know him? No, I don't know him. I met the man
only once after a game in Detroit when (Taylor) took me out in the
country some 25 miles to a dance hall, and Taylor introduced him to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   This seems perplexing, though, since Taylor's name apparently
had not been brought up in the scandal yet, so Gallinger, in
effect, would be telling the NHL that Taylor also knew Tamer.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger denied any more involvement. When he left Ross's
suite, he recalled, ``I felt relieved. I was in my pattern of
control. Nobody was ever going to control me, to get any knowledge
from me. I knew what I was going to say and not going to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger also recalled thinking, `` `I wonder if there is
anybody (else) on this club who might be involved.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The man had bet against his own team a week earlier. Now he was
searching for phantom conspirators. And so it would go for a
half-century.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NHL was in chaos. The Bruins were in chaos. Gangsters in
Detroit were in chaos (hundreds of them would be cleared from the
streets in the next few days). Detroit and Michigan politicians
were in chaos. And Don Gallinger's mind was in chaos.
</P>
<P>
   That night, the Bruins lost in Toronto, 4-2. After the game,
back in the Royal York Hotel, Gallinger noticed something strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Assistant trainer) Hammie Moore was my roommate that night,''
said Gallinger. ``They put Hammie Moore in with me to be a mole. He
was spying on me on behalf of the club.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger could not sleep that night, and he would not sleep for
many more nights, he said. So he clearly heard the phone ring at
2:30 in the morning and heard Moore take the call from Clapper, the
coach. Ross wanted to talk to Gallinger _ now.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Gallinger recalled, Ross was not asking questions but
making accusations. Ross ``had some scotch in him,'' said
Gallinger, and was confrontational. Ross accused Gallinger of
betting on hockey games. Gallinger continued to deny all.
</P>
<P>
   Weston Adams, the Bruins owner, flew out to try to get to the
bottom of this chaos. Campbell, the NHL president, traveled to
Detroit, where police briefed him. Still, no players had been
named. No teams, either. Rumors were rampant.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' final game of the five-game trip was on Sunday
night, Feb. 29, back in Chicago, the scene of the crime. The
players were grilled. Adams and Clapper questioned operators at the
LaSalle Hotel about calls that might have been made 10 days earlier
by hockey players. Hotel officials, maids, and other workers were
queried about anything that might have been the slightest bit
unusual during Boston's previous visit.
</P>
<P>
   By now, reports from Detroit indicated that unidentified players
on the Bruins and Rangers were involved. A Toronto newspaper
reported that a member of the Black Hawks was involved. Facts,
though, were scarce.
</P>
<P>
   Adams and Clapper were able to track down the operator who had
placed calls to Detroit on Feb. 17 and 18, but she could not
identify the caller as a hockey player. Clapper said he would go to
Detroit to help police identify the voices on the wiretaps.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger recalled ``a two-man personal meeting'' with Ross in
Chicago at which Ross became very emotional, saying how he had
helped found the Bruins, how he had spent 25 years of his life with
the Bruins, how the Bruins meant so much to him, and how it would
break his heart if any Bruin had bet on games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ross said he would quit forever the National Hockey League if
this was true,'' Gallinger recalled. ``And I believed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gallinger also saw this as a ploy by Ross, a counterpoint to
the confrontational approach four days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Gallinger, ``I came within an inch of confessing,''
and he would have ``if he had made a statement of what he was
prepared to do for me,'' in terms of possibly a short suspension.
``But he never opened the final door.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, though, Gallinger's memory may be mistaken. Ross had
fallen ill in Toronto, returned home to Boston, and did not
accompany the team to Chicago. But the words Gallinger claims Ross
spoke to him in that private meeting in Chicago _ about quitting
the league if the allegations were true _ actually appeared in
print, as told by Ross to reporters in Toronto. John Ross, Art's
son, remembered his father as being ``very quiet'' during these
days. Others go further, saying this incident broke Ross's heart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins finally returned home after the two-week trip. The
pressure was enormous in Boston and throughout the NHL, but facts
still were scant. Michigan officials now denied there had been a
wiretap on Tamer's phone, possibly because it was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, March 2, Gallinger recalled, he was playing a
friendly game of cards in his room at Ruthie Hatch's boardinghouse
in the Back Bay when he received a call from a sometimes-tout and
sometimes-friend of Bruins players who had hung around the dressing
room. The man instructed Gallinger to come to his apartment near
Kenmore Square.
</P>
<P>
   When he reached the apartment, Gallinger said, the man told him
that Taylor had called from New York, that his message to Gallinger
was to stay mum, that Taylor was not going to talk, and that if no
one talked, no one in the NHL could prove anything. Gallinger left
that meeting more determined to deny everything, even though later
that night he was summoned to Ross's Chestnut Hill home and again
accused of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The next night, the Bruins were back in the Garden, again
playing Chicago, and 13,909 fans shouted their backing of the
beleaguered team, which had Schmidt, their captain, back for the
first time in five weeks. The game ended in a 4-4 tie. Gamblers
continued to prowl the East Lobby of the Garden before the game,
not scared off by the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   As the Bruins left for Montreal the next day, a Thursday, they
learned that Campbell would be in Boston over the weekend to
question the team personally. First, he would be in New York
Saturday to grill the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Walter Winchell, one of America's most famous
columnists and broadcasters, was prepared to write in a New York
newspaper and repeat on his national radio show that he had learned
the identities of hockey's gamblers _ one a Bruin and one a Ranger.
Their initials, Winchell reported, were ``B.T.'' and ``D.G.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt vividly recalled what happened when the Bruins left the
Montreal Forum, after a 1-1 tie, and headed to their train.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little cliques (of players) had been forming and they'd say,
`Do you think it was Galley?' and `Do you think Galley did this?'
But nothing was definite then,'' said Schmidt. ``You couldn't point
a guilty finger at him. You didn't really know, in all honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   But soon after the team boarded, Schmidt recalled, a group of
players was in the smoking car and one picked up a New York Mirror
with Winchell's column.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember one of the players showing it to Galley and
yelling,'' said Schmidt. ``There was an awful loud voice by Don
Gallinger then as to how he was going to sue (Winchell).''
</P>
<P>
   Egan recalled that he was the player shouting at Gallinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 10 of us in the smoking car,'' recalled Egan.
``This (expletive) Gallinger is sitting right there and Milt and
somebody else said something (about Winchell's identification) and
he turns the color of that (red) flower. And I said, `Don, if
you're not guilty, then you're a millionaire because you can sue
that damned Winchell for everything he's got.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `It's not me; damn it, you know it's not me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, March 6, 1948, Clarence Campbell arrived in Boston
with the ostensible smoking gun in his briefcase: transcriptions of
wiretapped conversations between two hockey players and Tamer, the
Detroit bookmaker. The problem for the NHL president was finding
the triggerman. Taylor had not been forthcoming in New York that
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor had yet to play a home game at Madison Square Garden for
the Rangers after his trade a month earlier from Boston; he never
would.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell had sent word ahead to Ross that he wanted to speak to
six players: star forward Dumart, rookie forward Wilson, young
forward Kenny Smith, veteran forward Peters, defenseman Egan, and
forward Gallinger, the Bruins' budding star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was furious that Campbell had called me up to that hotel
room,'' said Dumart, still angry some 51 years after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Egan was more irate. He immediately told Campbell that he was
insulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I know nothing about this, and I'm disappointed in
you that you didn't realize from the way I played the game, that if
a guy came up to me and asked me to throw a game, he'd either kick
the (expletive) out of me or I would kick it out of him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Peters earlier had told Ross that he had met Tamer, and Ross
clearly passed the information to Campbell. All Peters could
remember of his meeting with Campbell was that ``I wasn't in there
too long; he asked what did I know and I said, `I don't know
anything.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Smith does not remember being called in by Campbell. Wilson, who
is dead, most likely was questioned because Gallinger had told
Bruins management about a meeting in a Detroit bar with Tamer at
which Wilson was present.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, recalled Peters, was shaken by the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember we were in Ruthie Hatch's boardinghouse and I
found Wally Wilson in his bed, crying,'' said Peters. ``I said,
`Wally, what's the problem?' and Wally said, `They're accusing me
of this gambling thing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The final Bruin to be called was Gallinger, who had rehearsed
his words, his strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger said he would know ``from the very first question
Clarence Campbell asked of me whether he had the goods on me.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure was on Campbell. The very reason he was in that
hotel room was because the NHL had whitewashed a burgeoning
gambling scandal involving the Maple Leafs two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Mervyn ``Red'' Dutton, Campbell's predecessor as NHL president,
had expelled Toronto star Walter ``Babe'' Pratt for ``conduct
detrimental to hockey,'' stating that Pratt had ignored warnings to
cease his gambling.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1302 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FIX-III-SPCL-3RD &LR;      05-18 1870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FIX-III-SPCL-3RD </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... his gambling.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The expulsion caused an uproar throughout Canada, particularly
in Toronto, where newspapers defended Pratt by saying that he was
far from alone in being an NHL gambler.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL president was fighting a losing battle, especially
against the Maple Leafs, the jewel team, and their powerful general
manager, Conn Smythe.
</P>
<P>
   After being out of hockey for all of 16 days, Pratt was
reinstated. By the start of the next season, Campbell would be NHL
president and Pratt would be traded to the Bruins, where he would
play with Gallinger for 31 games of the 1946-47 season before being
sent to the minors. He eventually would be voted into the NHL Hall
of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   No news organization attempted to delve into the extent of
betting by Pratt and other Maple Leafs. Neither did the NHL. It
would not be until decades later that books published in Canada
alleged that not only Pratt, but also Billy Taylor, Ted Kennedy and
possibly other Leafs had been betting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Gallinger recalled the meeting, which lasted more than two
hours, Campbell said that because he had already admitted meeting
Tamer, that was reason enough for punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Mr. Campbell, this is a flimsy piece of evidence,' ''
Gallinger said. ``All players rub shoulders with these types of
characters.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Gallinger, Campbell said to him, `` `If it isn't
you (on the wiretap), then who is it?' I said, `That's not fair and
I don't like it. I don't know who it is and I don't care who it is,
but it isn't me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As the meeting was ending, Campbell opened the door and told
Gallinger he would be suspended from hockey indefinitely _ for
associating with a gambler, not for betting on a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said, `It's still not fair,' '' said Gallinger. ``And he
said, `That's the way it'll be.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger said he left the Statler Hotel and headed immediately
to Ruthie Hatch's boardinghouse on Bay State Road. He said was
thinking of committing suicide by jumping into the Charles River.
</P>
<P>
   But, in fact, Gallinger went to Boston Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember that.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he played against the Maple Leafs that Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember that.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he played his last game ever in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember that.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he scored a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember that.''
</P>
<P>
   Several teammates recalled him scoring a goal that night, but as
nemesis-to-be Schmidt put it, Gallinger most likely played extra
hard precisely because it was his last chance to shine.
</P>
<P>
   If, said Schmidt, he had known that night what had been said
between Gallinger and Campbell that afternoon and what Gallinger
had done two weeks earlier in Chicago, Gallinger would never had
gotten out of the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be telling you the truth if I didn't say I felt
betrayed and angry due to the fact we were giving every ounce of
blood we have, every ounce of sweat, trying to win a hockey game,''
said Schmidt, ``and two of your teammates are betting against you.
But we never knew the details for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have killed him if I had known for sure,'' said Egan.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Gallinger does not remember playing that final game,
he still insists that sometime that night he thought of jumping off
a Charles River bridge. He said his life was saved by Ruthie Hatch,
who ran the boardinghouse where he lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``She talked me out of anything desperate,'' he said. ``She said
she had noticed how determined I was on the ice and she said, `You
can carry that determination from hockey to the rest of your life.
I said, `I'll keep that with me the rest of my life.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Gallinger was summoned by Ross to the Bruins'
offices and informed him that ``a phone call from Detroit'' had
been received there. The message was that Gallinger had better pay
the money he owed to a certain someone in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' heart was crushed. And Ross knew deep in that broken heart
that he might have had a role in this, that he had brought Taylor
and Pratt to his Bruins, one a known gambler and the other a
suspended gambler. Ross's blood rival was Toronto's Connie Smythe.
The two despised each other, and each was keen on proving he was a
smarter hockey man. Smythe had dumped Pratt and Taylor, and Ross
apparently thought he would prove Smythe wrong for giving up on the
two; instead it was Ross who was burned by Smythe's rejects.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Gallinger began the long drive back to Ontario,
and Campbell announced that Taylor had been barred from hockey for
life and Gallinger suspended indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next 50 years were bitter, painful, and brutal for
Gallinger, who now lives as a virtual recluse, his family, his
fortune, and his future gone.
</P>
<P>
   First, he worked at a miniature golf course in Port Colborne. He
had had baseball tryouts with both the Red Sox and Boston Braves in
1946, and he wrote to baseball commissioner Happy Chandler, but
baseball, like hockey, would have no part of a suspended gambler.
</P>
<P>
   In time, he would confess to Campbell the full details of what
happened in Chicago on Feb. 18, 1948, but Campbell did nothing.
Then he went to Smythe and poured out his soul for hours. To no
avail.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly there was a double standard in hockey, as Smythe's Pratt
had been suspended for only 16 days for his gambling, and Gallinger
had no hope. And all the NHL could prove was that he had associated
with James Tamer.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly _ very briefly _ Gallinger coached a junior hockey team
in Ontario. When the team traveled to Sarnia, in Western Ontario,
for its first game, the opposing coach pulled his team from the ice
in protest. And the Ontario Hockey Association backed him up.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Gallinger's roadblock would be as much Ross as anyone
in the NHL, in terms of reinstatement. Ross was broken-hearted by
Gallinger's betrayal of his beloved Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in 1970, Smythe gave the go-ahead to Campbell to show
leniency. Smythe had met Taylor at a banquet in Oshawa, felt sorry
for his former player, and suggested that Campbell lift the
lifetime ban. And if Taylor were reinstated, Gallinger would have
to be, too.
</P>
<P>
   But no one knew where Gallinger was. He had been selling shirts
in the Toronto area, but it was believed that he had left for
California. Campbell rather coldly said it was of no concern to him
that Gallinger could not be found for the NHL to personally deliver
the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can read about it in the paper,'' said Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Taylor would be hired as a scout by Pittsburgh, and
Schmidt would hire Taylor as a scout for the Washington expansion
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always liked Billy,'' Schmidt said. ``I was also always very
careful to keep a close eye on Billy's expense sheets.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schmidt would not hire Gallinger, neither in Boston nor in
Washington, and friction between the two grew.
</P>
<P>
   All this time, Taylor would never publicly discuss what he had
done, and the NHL would never disclose what Taylor and Gallinger
had done to warrant expulsion. All this time, many of the Bruins of
1947-48 never knew exactly what their two disgraced teammates had
done, not even knowing whether they had bet on the Bruins to win or
the Bruins to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Months before Taylor died eight years ago, recalled Peters, ``We
gave Billy a jacket from the (NHL) alumni group. And Billy was so
happy to get that jacket.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger, now estranged from his family and from life, is still
attempting to cash in on the bet he made in Chicago 51 years ago,
the bet he lost, the bet he never paid. He is looking for a book on
his life, a reward for his humiliation. ``There's big money to be
made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tamer is still alive. Within days of the disclosure of the
wiretap that caught Gallinger's bet, Tamer was returned to prison
and served nine more years. He was released in 1957, but less than
a year later was arrested again, this time in Terre Haute, Ind., on
federal income tax charges. He was sentenced to five years for
evading taxes on a betting syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   Tamer was arrested again in 1966 on contempt charges for
refusing to answer questions before a grand jury in Michigan
investigating Mafia leaders in the Detroit area. In 1978, he was
arrested by the FBI in Las Vegas as part of a conspiracy to
illegally run the Aladdin Hotel. He was found guilty in 1979, and
in 1980, the Nevada Gaming Commission asked federal officials to
keep Tamer, then free on bail, out of Las Vegas and away from
negotiations to sell the Aladdin. Tamer served his sentence at a
federal facility in Florida, and while there, he and several others
bought the Hillcrest Country Club in Mt. Clemens, Mich., for about
$6.5 million in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Tamer was asked to give his recollections of the
hockey scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a long time ago,'' said Tamer, now 87 and still working
at his golf club in Mt. Clemens, some 30 miles north of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Tamer declined to reminisce, saying, ``Be careful
what you write about me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But three other men were very precise in what they wished to
say. In Barrie, Ontario, Bep Guidolin lit up when he was asked
about his friend, Don Gallinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was dead,'' said Guidolin.
</P>
<P>
   His greatest regret in life, said Guidolin, was that he had been
traded from the Bruins in 1947 ``because my heart has always been
with the Boston Bruins for the last 50 years. And I know, I just
know if I was with Galley that season, he would never have gotten
involved in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger said that at times he wishes he had crossed that final
inch between himself and Ross during the first days of the scandal
when he was close to confessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ross had only said what he would have done for me, I would
have done it,'' said Gallinger. ``But Ross never would say it.''
</P>
<P>
   All these men are in their 70s and 80s now, and their memories
vary. But the sharpest of memories may be that of Ed Sandford, now
a stockbroker in downtown Boston. His memory is one from 35 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art Ross, in his last years, was living in Kenmore Square, in
the Hotel Kenmore,'' said Sandford. ``By this time in his life, he
was blind. So one day, in the summertime, I say, `Gosh darn, I want
to see if I can say hello to him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sandford and Ross swapped memories, and then, according to
Sandford, Ross said, `` `My biggest disappointment in life, Eddie,
was that we weren't able to help Gallinger,' and I said, `Well,
that's too bad.' And he said, `Eddie, do you know the story?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sandford replied that he still didn't, even after all these
years.
</P>
<P>
   `` `I don't really know much about it,' '' I said, ``and then
Mr. Ross said, `We had all the evidence against him.'
</P>
<P>
   `` `I had talked to (Detroit's) Jack Adams and (Toronto's)
Connie Smythe and the other board of directors and we had it all
set up, that if this kid would say, I did it, I'm sorry, he would
be suspended for a year and he would be reinstated.'
</P>
<P>
   `` `But,' Ross said, `I couldn't tell him that unless he told me
he was sorry, and that son of a gun would never do it. What a sin
it was when all he had to do was say he was sorry.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1305 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FIX-I-SPCL-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     05-18 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FIX-I-SPCL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... said Gallinger.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``He learned all this betting firstly and initially with the
Toronto Maple Leafs,'' Gallinger went on. ``He owned a pool room in
Oshawa that was run by a friend or two of his, and it would take
bets, and that went on for years while he played with the Toronto
Maple Leafs.''
</P>
<P>
   So Gallinger's ears perked up halfway through the game when,
according to Gallinger, Taylor asked him, `` `Don, how would like
to make some easy money?'
</P>
<P>
   `` `If you want to supplement your salary by another $10,000 to
$12,000, on top of your salary, you're going to have a nice summer,
aren't you?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Easy money, always a lure to Gallinger, was all the more so now,
considering Gallinger's Boston annual salary of $7,500.
</P>
<P>
   The cards were dealt. Taylor talked. More cards were dealt.
Gallinger listened.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very precise but slow, and he weaved himself in and he
did it with words,'' Gallinger recalled. ``But what he didn't know
was that I was already a bettor. I was already a gambler in many
ways _ now, I wasn't fixing hockey games _ and then he said, `What
if I told you how we could make a lot of money over a period of
time like a slow boat to China?' And it would only encompass six or
seven games over the entire schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor almost certainly had to know Gallinger liked to
gamble; Gallinger was well known as a gambler in Port Colborne, the
same hometown as Ted Kennedy, a star with the Maple Leafs and
former teammate of Taylor. Also, each and every Bruin knew
Gallinger to be a heavy gambler. And the whispers along the NHL
grapevine more than likely had reached Taylor's ears in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Even more, Taylor and Gallinger had a common friend, Bep
Guidolin. Taylor and Guidolin had been bunkmates at the Canadian
Army base in Newmarket, Ontario, near Toronto, during World War II
in 1944 and '45, and Taylor had often told Guidolin of his gambling
exploits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, from the stories I got from Billy Taylor,''
recalled Guidolin, ``I heard there was a lot of betting going on in
the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   Guidolin and Gallinger had joined the Bruins as teen-agers in
1942 _ Guidolin, in fact, was and still is the youngest player (16
years 11 months) ever to make the NHL _ and immediately became
pals. Guidolin was well aware of how much and how often Gallinger
bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Galley would bet his salary, bet his hockey salary, and go
home broke if he had to,'' recalled Guidolin. ``Just to win some
money . . . on horses . . . ballgames . . . pool games . . .
anything. I used to say to him, `Galley, hang on to your money.
You're blowing it all!' ''
</P>
<P>
   And when Detroit general manager Jack Adams traded Taylor to the
Bruins, the player Ross sent to Detroit in exchange was none other
than Guidolin. No sooner had Guidolin bade farewell to his roommate
and close friend Gallinger in Boston than he was on the phone to
his close friend Taylor in Detroit. ``We said to each other, `I've
been traded for you,' '' recalled Guidolin. And they talked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger said he made his very first bets on Bruins games that
first year, the 1942-43 season, when he was the 17-year-old rookie.
</P>
<P>
   There was no such thing as security in the NHL in those days,
just as there was next to no security in any sport. Gambling was
blatant in every NHL arena; in Boston Garden, it went on in the
East lobby before games. ``The bookies'd sit in the seats right
above our goal taking bets,'' remembered an old Bruin. Bets on who
would take the next shot, on which goalie would make the next save,
or even whether the next puck deflected into the stands would hit a
man or a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were six of them above our net,'' recalled Guidolin.
``They were betting on every shot, every shift, on every period.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Gallinger met up with ``Peter,'' a man from the
North End who was ``a guy with a heavy black beard and a cap, a
real fruit-staller,'' said Gallinger. This is the man who would
take the bets, a friend of Guidolin's who ran a fruit stall in
Haymarket Square.
</P>
<P>
   Peter was accommodating. He would take Gallinger's bets at his
fruit stall as Gallinger was making the short walk over to Boston
Garden. Or, if Gallinger missed him there, Peter might be in the
Garden lobby near the Bruins' dressing room as the players walked
in. Finally, there would be a third chance, because Peter
eventually would wander over near the Bruins' bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd warm up and then I'd go over and maybe lean on the bench
area with him for a few seconds and ask him how he's doing,''
Gallinger recalled. ``If you had a last-second urge that you wanted
to bet, you'd say, `Peter, I want to be on; can you take it?' And
he'd say, `Sure, how much?' And I'd just tell him quietly and I'd
skate away. It'd only take a few seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger usually bet $50 on a game, sometimes $100 if he had
strong convictions. Always, he emphasized, ``I bet on the Boston
hockey club to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said to myself, `As long as I was betting on the
Boston hockey club,' I felt morally that I had done nothing
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he won the bet, said Gallinger. Sometimes he lost.
</P>
<P>
   Guidolin said he never saw Gallinger give Peter any money, nor
did he see Gallinger receive any money. Told that Gallinger had
said he bet frequently his rookie season, Guidolin was adamant in
his reply: ``I don't believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So as the cards were dealt in that upstairs bedroom on Bay State
Road, Gallinger's pose of a naive innocent listening to the ploys
of a crafty veteran might have seemed like an act wasted on Taylor.
So Taylor spun more threads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taylor says to me,'' Gallinger recalled, `` `When we play in
Toronto and when we play in Montreal, who usually wins the games,
Don?' And I said, `If we play in Toronto and we play in Montreal' _
this is me talking now _ `you already know who wins, Billy Taylor.
This is a foolhardy question. But to answer it, Montreal usually
wins in Montreal and, to be more specific, if we were to play seven
games there, if we won one and tied one out of the seven in
Montreal or in Toronto, we would have a good season in that area.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hoping to reel me in'' with the thought that if the
Bruins were to lose anyway, even with their best effort, perhaps
money could be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he said, `If we were to bet on Montreal against us, and
you already said Montreal logically would win the game, that's
called in gambling circles, Don, that's called giving the
information that you can lose without saying you're fixing,' ''
Gallinger recalled.
</P>
<P>
   More cards were dealt. The gin rummy game went on. Taylor and
Gallinger talked deeper into the plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Look, we can have the same situation in Chicago and
we can have the same situation in Detroit,' '' Gallinger recalled.
``And I said, `Well, OK, what do you think when we play in Boston
Garden?' And he said, `Well, I think we'd be absolute fools if we
bet against the Boston hockey club in Boston Garden.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger took all this in. He was not shocked by any of this
talk. In addition to the betting he claimed he did in his rookie
season, he also claimed to have sat in on a meeting with a handful
of Bruins early in the 1943-44 season when there was talk of fixing
a game, though no action was taken. Gallinger instead was thinking
of practical matters.
</P>
<P>
   For a hockey game to be lost intentionally, the goalie must be
involved, Gallinger thought. But the Bruins' goalie was Frankie
Brimsek, Mr. Zero himself, a Hall of Famer-to-be, and it was beyond
even a moment's consideration that the straightforward Brimsek
could be involved in such a plot.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the Bruins' top line, with Schmidt and Dumart?
Absolutely not, even a fool would know; they were absolutely beyond
reproach _ and approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to Taylor, `Tell me what the secret is,' '' Gallinger
recalled. ``He said, `Don't ever lose sight of the fact that I
control one line on this Boston hockey club and you will control
one line on this Boston hockey club.' ''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, Gallinger thought. While Schmidt was the center on
the top line, Taylor would be the center on the second and
Gallinger the center on the third. More and more, Gallinger was
taken by what this crafty veteran, this gambler, this Billy Taylor
was saying to him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
