<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1306 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FIX-I-SPCL-3TAKES     05-18 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FIX-I-SPCL-3 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILENCE BROKEN 51 YEARS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- That scrap of paper had been in Don Gallinger's wallet
for a week now. Undisturbed. On the paper was written a telephone
number in Detroit, but Gallinger had not looked at it since the
Detroit gangster had slipped it into his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Nor had Gallinger thrown it away.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger, the 22-year-old center of the Boston Bruins, at the
time the only player ever to make the jump directly from Junior B
to the National Hockey League, was torn. He knew exactly what the
number meant.
</P>
<P>
   If he took that piece of paper from his wallet, if he asked the
telephone operator to make the connection to that phone in Detroit,
it could mean money. Easy money. And Gallinger, a gambler since he
was a teenage pool-room sharpie in his hometown of Port Colborne,
Ontario, on the shores of Lake Erie, often found the lure of easy
money irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gallinger also was fully aware that no gamble was without
risk. The downside, if he pulled that piece of paper from his
wallet, could be immense. It could be the end of everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally looked at that piece of paper,'' said Gallinger, who
now lives like a recluse in a one-room apartment in Burlington,
Ontario, a city on the shores of Lake Ontario, about an hour
southwest of Toronto. ``No name on it, just a telephone number.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had just boarded their train at South Station on Feb.
16, 1948, for the road trip everyone despised, a daylong journey to
the farthest destination in the cozy six-team NHL: Chicago. As
usual, Gallinger quickly hooked up with Hammie Moore, the Bruins
trainer, for their game of high-stakes gin rummy, almost before the
train had left South Station.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger's mind, for once, was not on the cards. It was on that
phone number.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to myself, `We're going to have a hell of a time trying
to beat Chicago in Chicago,' '' Gallinger recalled. `` `And we're
going to be favored by a goal spread.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins team on that train to Chicago was in shambles. Milt
Schmidt, the captain and a future Hall of Famer, had blown out his
knee two weeks earlier and would be out five weeks. Clare Martin, a
defenseman, had banged his shoulder into a goalpost three days
earlier when the Bruins and New York Rangers tied, 4-4, at Boston
Garden. And John Crawford, another defenseman, was distraught that
his daughter Mary, born only three days earlier, was fighting for
her life in a Boston hospital. Few of the Bruins thought Crawford
would even make the trip to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Boston was in even more dismal shape on the ice. The Bruins had
played six of their last seven games at the Garden and had
squandered the opportunity, going a mere 1-5-1 even with Schmidt
playing in three of those games and Martin and Crawford in all of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never so cocksure in my life that Chicago would win that
game with Schmidt out and Crawford out,'' said Gallinger, whose
memory of Crawford missing that game is incorrect. ``I was cocksure
that it couldn't be any way else no matter how hard a game I
played.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only one now looking to make $3,000 on an outcome that
I felt had no variance to it,'' remembered Gallinger. ``We are
going to be beaten by that Chicago hockey club. It was always a
ringed circus to win against that club, no matter what strength you
had.''
</P>
<P>
   The risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said to myself, `Gallinger, you've been up and down like
a toilet seat. It's a nightmare psychologically and you're a fool
and it might cost you a career.' So I talked to myself that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hour after hour, the train wheels of the Lake Shore Limited
clicked west through Albany and Buffalo and onward toward Chicago
and destiny. Hour after hour, Gallinger's mind weighed risk and
reward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going out to Chicago and I'm saying to myself, `Maybe,
just maybe, I should make the killing,' '' Gallinger would think
one moment. `` `(I'm) going to go for the bundle.' '' Only to be
followed by the heart-quickening risk of it all, that he had been
gambling all his life but never for stakes this high.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' train pulled into Chicago. By the time the team
reached the LaSalle Hotel, Don Gallinger had made up his mind. He
had weighed Easy Money vs. Extreme Risk and finally decided what to
do with that piece of paper that had been undisturbed in his wallet
for a week, burning a hole, as it were, into his psyche and soul.
And, ultimately, his life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first web of Hockey's Greatest Scandal was spun on an
October afternoon in 1947 at Ruthie Hatch's boarding house at 165
Bay State Road in Boston's Back Bay, just steps from Kenmore Square
and Fenway Park. The first strand of that web was spun innocently
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you going to be around?'' Billy Taylor, the newest Bruin,
had said to Gallinger as the two passed each other on the stairs
that led to the bedrooms of the 14-room house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't think I'm going anywhere,'' Gallinger told Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   As usual in hockey, there was time to kill, even more so if you
were a Bruin playing for Art Ross, who had helped found the team 23
years earlier and never believed in practicing much. Two years
earlier, Ross had turned over full-time coaching duties to Aubrey
``Dit'' Clapper, who had been weaned on Ross's style in his two
decades with the Bruins _ Clapper was the NHL's first 20-year
player _ and also believed that fewer practices saved the legs for
the games.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger recalled, ``Taylor said to me, `Why don't you come up
to the third floor and play some gin rummy with me?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor had just arrived from Detroit in an unexpected trade that
had shocked players on both the Bruins and Red Wings. After all,
Taylor had been the No. 3 scorer in the NHL the previous season,
finishing behind Chicago's Max Bentley and the Canadiens' Rocket
Richard and a point ahead of Schmidt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought Taylor would be the stud,'' said Fernie Flaman, a
defenseman on the team. And Schmidt remembered thinking when the
trade was made, `` `We're really in clover.' Due to the fact that
Billy Taylor was a great hockey player. What a good stickhandler
and what a good playmaker. Billy was small but pretty quick.''
Billy Taylor, said Bruins defenseman Pat Egan, ``had to be one of
the 10 best who ever played.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, a team in transition, needed Taylor. Bobby Bauer had
just retired, persuaded by his wife's family that his future would
be more lucrative in the family business, fashioning and marketing
the famed Bauer skates. (He had married a hometown woman from
Kitchener, Ontario, whose maiden name also was Bauer.) ``It was a
mistake that Bobby let himself be talked into that,'' Schmidt rued.
``Bobby could have played another three or four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the famed Kraut Line of Schmidt, Bauer, and Woody
Dumart broken up after a decade of glory, but center Bill Cowley,
another Hall of Famer, also had just retired unhappily.
</P>
<P>
   So Taylor was needed by the Bruins. Yet there was some unease
deep in the minds of some Bruins veterans about Taylor because,
recalled defenseman Murray Henderson, ``Billy had a reputation (for
gambling) when he was playing junior in Oshawa (Ontario)'' eight
years earlier, when he led the Oshawa Generals to Canada's junior
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Egan, another defenseman, personally knew of Taylor's gambling.
And more than a few Bruins had heard rumors that Taylor, when he
played for Toronto, had bet on Maple Leafs games along with Toronto
defenseman Babe Pratt and possibly other Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt had been suspended 16 days by the league in 1946 for his
gambling during the 1945-46 season, a burgeoning scandal nipped in
the bud, then buried by the intercession of Toronto general manager
Conn Smythe. Smythe, in many eyes, was so powerful that he was the
de facto head of the league even though Red Dutton carried the
title of NHL president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy Taylor and Don Gallinger were one and the same,'' said
Kenny Smith, a forward on that Bruins team. ``They were gamblers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger knew of Taylor's reputation when Taylor invited him
upstairs that October afternoon for that game of gin rummy. Taylor
had begun his career with the Maple Leafs, ``and everybody in the
NHL, including myself, knew that if you mentioned Billy Taylor's
name, in their eyes he was a bookmaker,'' said Gallinger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1308 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FIX-I-SPCL-3RD &LR;  &UR; T     05-18 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FIX-I-SPCL-3RD </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... saying to him.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I said, `Look, Billy, I know you control one-third of the
lines and I know I control one-third of the lines and the two of
them should be able to control the game. And I know you haven't
talked to me about goaltending and all that and I still know that's
the greatest part of this game, but that's neither here nor there,'
'' Gallinger remembered. `` `But I'll tell you right now, I'm in.'
''
</P>
<P>
   And the easy money? How much would Gallinger and Taylor make for
betting on games in which they played. The 1919 Chicago White Sox _
the infamous Black Sox _ never had to put up money of their own to
fix the World Series with Cincinnati; instead, they were promised
$80,000 by notorious New York gambler Arnold Rothstein and others
in on the fix. The same was true for the college basketball players
who fixed games in the New York City area and other parts of the
country a few years after Taylor and Gallinger had their chat in
Boston. They never had to put up their own money.
</P>
<P>
   But for Taylor and Gallinger, there'd be no freebies. If they
wanted to bet on Bruins games, Taylor explained, they would have to
use their own money. ``So what would be the edge?'' Gallinger
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Taylor) said, `The key to us replenishing our salaries was to
give the right information on the right game at the right time,' ''
is Gallinger's recollection. ``We'd get odds at 2-1.''
</P>
<P>
   More cards were dealt. The gin rummy game went on. More details
were worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor told Gallinger that he would handle the betting himself.
Taylor said he had a friend in Detroit who would take the bets. But
he cautioned Gallinger that nothing must be said about the plot,
that they would talk about it only the day before, or the morning
of, a particular game on which they wished to bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I say, `So you've got all the ducks on the pond and you've
got it all figured out,' '' recalled Gallinger. ``And he said,
`That's right.' And he said, `Now I have to say this to you. Don't
you ever say yes, you're in, even though I'm doing all the
telephoning, all the legwork, and still consulting with you at
least the morning of the game, and hopefully in most cases, on the
day before the game . . .' ''
</P>
<P>
   In Gallinger's mind _ and the former Bruin said it was the same
in Taylor's _ the two were not fixing hockey games. They were
merely taking advantage of information they had, information about
injuries, on whether the Bruins might be playing poorly and their
upcoming opponent might be playing well _ ``judging all the
elements.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And now he slips in this final nugget,'' said Gallinger, ``and
I just looked at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said, according to Gallinger, `` `There're some things,
if we go ahead, you just better not forget. You better keep your
eye on the goddamned clock if this thing is ever getting out of
hand, because we just don't want to give our goddamned money away.
We want it to happen. So you've always got to be conscious to make
this happen if it's not happening.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And Gallinger recalled replying, `` `You don't have to be
emphatic with me, Billy Taylor.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the card game ended. The two Bruins went downstairs
in Ruthie Hatch's boarding house.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins opened the 1947-48 season with a bang. They dominated
the Rangers, 3-1, in their first game and then beat the Canadiens
by the identical score, both times at Boston Garden. Three days
later, though, the Bruins traveled to Montreal, where the Canadiens
trounced them, 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins won four of their five games in October but slipped
in November, particularly late in the month when they went 0-3-2.
Included in that dry spell was a 4-3 loss to Toronto in Maple Leaf
Gardens, a 5-3 loss to the Blackhawks in Chicago, and a 4-1 loss in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Even more alarming was that Taylor was not playing well. The new
publication, The Hockey News, had a banner headline proclaiming
Taylor as the ``next Bill Cowley'' _ a perennial top scorer for the
Bruins in the early '40s and a Hall of Famer _ but Taylor was
playing like nothing of the sort. Taylor was dismal, far from the
player who had been third in NHL scoring the previous season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had accepted him,'' recalled Egan, the Bruins' brawling
defenseman. ``We thought that was a shot in the arm for us, to get
a centerman like that. Cripes, we were sitting on top of the world.
But he just didn't seem to play (well) here.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, the defenseman, also was mystified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened with Taylor,'' said Henderson. ``He
might have been disappointed because the Bruins then were not in
the upper echelon, figuring that he had been downgraded. And
perhaps he needed somebody on the wings; he could produce, but not
all by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was with the Bruins for 3 1/2 months. In that span, said
Gallinger, he and Taylor bet roughly a half-dozen times against the
Bruins. Most intriguing is that Gallinger cannot remember the exact
number of bets, the specific games, or how much was won or lost,
except that ``we won some and we lost some.''
</P>
<P>
   By late January, Bruins owner Weston Adams announced to the
media, ``Billy Taylor never would play again for the Boston
Bruins.'' Adams and Ross were attempting to trade Taylor but could
not immediately find any takers.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was sent home to Oshawa until Ross's close friend, the
Rangers' Lester Patrick, relieved him of the burdensome Taylor for
journeyman forward Grant ``Knobby'' Warwick. After a mysterious
interlude, when Taylor claimed the Bruins had lost his skates, the
veteran finally left Oshawa and reported to New York in early
February. In his tenure with the Bruins, Taylor had four goals and
16 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger, meanwhile, claimed to be relieved that Taylor was
gone. He said he had been emotionally wrought over the betting and,
when Ross finally traded Taylor, he thought, `` `Thank God, thank
the Lord, that bastard is gone. He could never benefit me. All this
has been a dirty mess and there's never been a lot of money made.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger's actions, though, belied his words.
</P>
<P>
   On a trip that season to Detroit, Taylor invited Gallinger to go
out after the game to a ``smoky dance hall some 20 or 30 miles
outside Detroit,'' according to Gallinger. There Taylor introduced
Gallinger to the man who was taking their bets. That man's name was
James Tamer.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 8, 1948, after another Bruins-Red Wings game at the
Olympia, one of the first games the Bruins had played without
Taylor _ a game Boston won, 3-1 _ Gallinger recalled going to a bar
near the Leland Hotel, where the Bruins stayed in Detroit. Teammate
Wally Wilson, just called up from the Bruins' American Hockey
League farm team in Hershey to replace Taylor, was with him.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson had played with Taylor for the Oshawa Generals and,
according to Gallinger, ``knew everything about Taylor's
background.''
</P>
<P>
   So Wilson and Gallinger were in the bar talking, recalled
Gallinger, ``and I see something out of the corner of my eye and I
turn and I look _ you could cut the smoke _ and I said, `Jesus
Christ, that man walking toward us,' I said to myself, ``that man
looks like James Tamer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tamer, ``a small, slick'' man, walked over to Gallinger, sat
next to him, and, according to Gallinger, said, `` `Don, nice to
see you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The two shook hands, and Tamer said, `` `Billy Taylor really
likes you,' '' Gallinger remembered, ``and I said, `I think he's a
hell of a fine guy, too, but right now he's the goddamned enemy and
I don't care if I ever see him again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There was silence for a moment. Tamer then told Gallinger, ``
`Any friend of Billy Taylor's is a friend of mine,' '' and, `` `If
you ever want to do business with me someday in the same private
angle that Taylor made business, then you're welcome.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gallinger recalled Tamer giving him his phone number on a piece
of paper, saying, `` `I'm the only one who ever answers that
number,' '' and slipping the paper into Gallinger's pocket. ``
`Just look at that someday. That's all I want to say to you. It
might never happen or you might use it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   James Tamer, a bank robber, an ex-con, and one of Detroit's most
notorious gangsters, then left.
</P>
<P>
   Don Gallinger did not throw away the piece of paper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
