<HEADER>
A1341 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POLITICS19-COX     05-18 1331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recently elected Mexican leaders are shaking up old, corrupt
order
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUEVO LAREDO, Tamaulipas, Mexico _ The new mayor opened a door
in the corner of his office and climbed down the secret spiral
staircase that let him avoid the throng of people constantly
jockeying for a moment of his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My escape route,'' Mayor Horacio Garza Garza explained as he
edged down the steep stairs to the street.
</P>
<P>
   He may need it.
</P>
<P>
   With his new get-tough campaign against public corruption and
drug trafficking in this rapidly growing border city, Garza is
quickly making enemies among a police force that has become
notorious for harboring officers who participated in more crimes
than they stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Since he took office in January, Garza, an accountant and
auditor by trade, has teamed up with his new police chief,
Moctezuma Rodriguez Meza, to fire 200 police officers, a quarter of
the city force. The officers doing business with drug gangs were
easy to spot and fire because of their big houses and flashy cars,
Garza said, and the rest were shown the door after failing surprise
drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police were contaminated,'' said Garza, who also took a
drug test along with his top department heads. ``They were paid,
and they protected the interests of the gangs. It was very
evident.''
</P>
<P>
   Garza isn't the only elected official shaking things up across
the Rio Grande. From Chihuahua to Matamoros, several new border
mayors and governors are trying to make their mark with sweeping
campaigns against public corruption, alcohol-fueled disorder and
government inefficiency.
</P>
<P>
   This surge of reform comes from an unlikely source. The new
officeholders are members of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, which has earned more headlines for fostering
corruption than for fighting it.
</P>
<P>
   The new leaders include:
</P>
<P>
   _Chihuahua Gov. Patricio Martinez, who took office last October
and quickly launched a zero-tolerance policy that took aim at 26
different social ills, including bars that sell alcohol after
hours, public servants who accept improper gifts or abuse their
authority, state workers who slack off on the job and bus drivers
who show up drunk or run red lights.
</P>
<P>
   _Tamaulipas Gov. Toma(accent)s Yarrington Ruvalcaba, who was
sworn in Feb. 4 and has tried to streamline the state government,
cutting the number of state agencies from 12 to five. He has also
introduced exams and background tests for state employees and law
enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   _Reynosa Mayor Luis Gerardo Higareda, who was in office just
three months before he announced a surprise drug test April 5 for
all city police officers. More than 80 officers quit on the spot,
and 57 others tested positive and were fired; in all, the city
across the river from McAllen purged more than a third of its
officers. Less than a week later, Reynosa police set up a sobriety
checkpoint between the bar district and the international bridge
and charged 49 people _ including 37 Texans _ with drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   Observers such as Rodolfo de la Garza, a University of Texas
government professor, say a string of corruption scandals _ a
former president's brother, the nation's top drug official and
numerous elected officials have been accused of working with drug
lords _ has weakened the old guard's grip on the party and cleared
the way for a new generation of PRI reformers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they are genuinely threatened by (drug corruption),
there is a large number of the PRI that have dedicated themselves
to an anti-corruption platform,'' de la Garza said. ``The problem
is whether or not it can be done. . . . Nobody knows who the bad
guys are anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's political landscape also is changing. Party primaries
have replaced the old system of party leaders hand-picking new
mayors and governors, and in the past few years, the two main
opposition parties have won numerous governorships and now have a
significant presence in the congress.
</P>
<P>
   That means the new crop of PRI candidates is having to fight in
the electoral trenches for the first time. For example, Yarrington,
an economist who has served as a congressman and mayor of
Matamoros, defeated three other PRI candidates in the first primary
in Tamaulipas history. Martinez became the first PRI governor to
reclaim a state from an opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   The result, de la Garza said, is that this new generation of
governors and mayors has ``a genuine constituency in ways that
their predecessors did not, and they're responding to those
constituencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarrington, who said he has chopped 600 jobs from the state
payroll during his first three months in office, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe our positions to the people,'' he said. ``People are
tired of being talked down to by their elected officials, and we
have to show results.''
</P>
<P>
   And with a presidential election coming up next year, the PRI
has to look to its young reformers to help shore up the party's
image, said Dr. Gary Mounce, a political science professor at the
University of Texas-Pan American in Edinburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to do it to win,'' he said. ``If they let the
(opposition parties) take the image of this moral force, they are
left with this old dinosaur image.''
</P>
<P>
   With the border leaders still settling into their jobs, it may
be too early to separate the rhetoric from reality. But in Nuevo
Laredo, Garza's crusade, which is accompanied by hundreds of
anti-bribery posters urging citizens to say no to the ``mordida,''
is winning converts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been very, very tough,'' said Ernesto Ferrara Theriot, a
city councilman and member of the opposition PAN party. ``This is
the first time we've seen this (type of reform). The last three
years we've had such a corrupt administration, (but) we cannot keep
protecting these types of individuals. They're a bunch of rats.''
</P>
<P>
   In the space of a few hours on a Thursday afternoon in late
April, Garza held an impromptu town-hall meeting with about 50
angry colonia residents demanding basic water and electricity for
their neighborhood, then joined the City Council in filing a formal
complaint accusing the ex-mayor of embezzling public money.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by sign-waving residents of the Los Arcos colonia,
Garza ordered police to arrest the man who had sold land in the
neighborhood without the required utilities. Local officials
estimate that 30 percent to 40 percent of the city's roughly
250,000 residents lack basic services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to continue permitting it,'' Garza said to
huge applause.
</P>
<P>
   Santos Mendoza, the colonia president, said residents have lived
in the former watermelon field without basic services for six
years. Their pleas to the last administration went nowhere, he
said, but they like what they see in Garza so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``This mayor came in with a lot of energy,'' Mendoza said.
</P>
<P>
   Garza said he has received threats as a result of his purge of
the police force, but now in his second stint as mayor _ he
previously served from 1993 to 1995 _ he said he is determined to
scrub Nuevo Laredo's image as a grimy, sometimes dangerous border
town.
</P>
<P>
   He has set his sights on sprucing up the city's bustling
downtown, pushing a plan to renovate the buildings in the six-block
tourist corridor stretching from the international bridge, widen
the sidewalks and perhaps close the street to make a pedestrian
mall after the new international bridge opens upstream next year.
</P>
<P>
   Similar revitalizing plans have sat rolled up on city shelves
for nine years, but Cristobal Enriquez, the city's director of
planning and urban development, said Garza could be the mayor to
push them through.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very determined man,'' Enriquez said, ``and I have a
lot of confidence in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Harmon writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
