<HEADER>
A1342 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADES-LIFE19-COX     05-18 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-LIFE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Greenery of life returns to Everglades
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE EVERGLADES, Fla. _ The black peat lies almost naked to the
sky, except for an ocher stubble of charred saw grass. Snail shells
litter the ground. Above them stand burned willow husks, branching
like gnarled candelabra.
</P>
<P>
   In the central Everglades, reminders of fire and death linger
like the sulfur smell in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   But so do signs of new life.
</P>
<P>
   Saw grass shoots, an almost fluorescent green, sprout 8 inches
above the soil. Leaves fan out from the base of the dead trunks.
</P>
<P>
   And scooping his fingers into the peaty muck _ dry enough on the
surface to send ash clouds puffing from every footfall _ Mike
Anderson can feel moistness in the earth.
</P>
<P>
   The moisture may have saved the peat, built up over thousands of
years from the tissue of dying plants. That means hope for recovery
from the wildfires of the past month, which swept across 170,000
acres of state-owned Everglades marsh in northwest Broward County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you lose the peat, the only way to build it back up is
waiting hundreds of years,'' said Anderson, a biologist for the
Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission.
</P>
<P>
   That's still a big worry in roughly 2,500 acres of the burned
territory, where the fire gouged 8- to 10-inch-deep scars that may
need 1,000 years to heal. About 900 acres still smoldered at the
end of last week.
</P>
<P>
   For most people, the fire's worst results were all the scary
television images and the smoke that shrouded the Miami area while
closing Alligator Alley. But for biologists and conservationists,
the fire posed an even greater threat _ irreparable damage to a
part of the Everglades already ravaged by a flawed drainage system
and by the disastrous fires of the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   This time, their worst fears didn't materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Despite months of meager rain, most of the region was just moist
enough to keep the fire from burning the peat. Where the muck
caught fire, foresters worked with South Florida water managers to
flood the region with canal runoff. Now, nature is donning a green
coat to replace what the fire scraped away.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the greenest I've ever seen saw grass,'' said Suzanne
Congelosi, senior forester for the state Division of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Moller, a board member of the Florida Wildlife Federation,
calls the wildfire the most benign he's ever seen in the
Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   ``In another four to five weeks, it's going to be hard to tell
it really burned unless you've seen it earlier,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are especially pleased that the fire spared the
region's myriad tree islands, teardrop-shaped elevations that
harbor bird rookeries teeming with willows, wax myrtles, ficus and
rubber trees. Anderson said the fire burned the edges of only two
islands.
</P>
<P>
   Fire, a necessary part of the Everglades' life cycle, could even
help some species, game commission biologist Jim Schortemeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny sprouts of razor-edged saw grass are less fearsome than
the full-grown version, so deer can easily uproot them and munch on
the bottoms. Wildlife-nourishing plants such as duck potato, with
leaves like an upright spear, will have less competition for
sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   But alligators may have more trouble finding saw grass for their
nests, Schortemeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   And not all growth is good for the Everglades, which has already
been weakened by pollution and drainage.
</P>
<P>
   In a stretch of burned muck, singed cattails stand like waiting
invaders along the edges of a pool of black water. They grow in
thick clumps that offer little room for wading birds, and they
thrive in burned and polluted areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What might happen in a year from now is this whole area will
fill with cattails,'' Anderson said as he drove an amphibious
all-terrain vehicle across the water. ``It's going to be a
population explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the water pumped in to douse the muck fire could carry some
risks. Much of the water originated on cattle and sugar fields, a
source of fertilizer and manure nutrients, and lime-green algae
suds the surface in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Still, experts say the fire could have been much worse.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, the foresters might have left the fire alone if
it didn't threaten humans, Congelosi said. Moller said firefighters
even worsened fires in the early 1970s by trying to plow muck over
the flames _ a technique that allowed the fire to spread
underground.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson this time: Cooperation works, Schortemeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past with muck fires, everybody has thrown their hands
in the air and said, 'We can't do anything,' `` he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
