<HEADER>
A1345 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN19-CO     05-18 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For better or worse, money matters
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attention brides and grooms: Almost every married couple fights
about money. Among couples who don't fight, one partner often
seethes while the other spends.
</P>
<P>
   Money management is one of those little things that people don't
necessarily warn their children about.
</P>
<P>
   But trouble shouldn't be a surprise. Men and women often
disagree about money and its uses. A recent survey showed another
factor: Only one young person in every five has taken a course in
personal finance, and one of every six thinks that avoiding money
problems is mostly a matter of luck.
</P>
<P>
   And let's face it: Money is a natural thing to argue about. It's
important to our happiness, sometimes crucial to self-esteem and
always in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   Wise young people can minimize conflicts by following some
fairly simple guidelines. Check out these ideas:
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't keep secrets. It's a bad idea to conceal debts, and it's
a terrible idea to keep a secret stash of cash. Once married, you
are sharing your finances, as well as your lives. Surprises are
bad, in money or in minefields. Newlyweds should also share their
financial upbringing _ how their families handled money as they
grew up and the feelings they now have about money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Agree on goals. What do you _ both of you _ want to do first
with your money? It might be buying a car, or getting out of debt,
or saving up some cash to deal with the inevitable emergencies.
Make a list, setting out in order the things you want your money to
do for you.
</P>
<P>
   _ Develop a family budget. This will give you a sense of control
over your spending. It may also suggest places where you can
balance frivolous spending now against important things to save for
in the future. Some couples prepare for this by keeping money
diaries for a month, recording everything they spend. There is a
useful worksheet on the Internet at www.cccsatl.org/money.htm. You
type in your numbers, and the computer does the adding and
subtracting for you. The calculator has dozens of spending items,
so you're not likely to miss anything.
</P>
<P>
   When you get to the bottom line, you will be able to start
taking control. If you have extra cash at the end, you can start
using it to achieve goals. If you come up short, you have a way to
go back and look for places to cut back on spending.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep the conversation going. As your lives come together, your
priorities may change. So will your joint income. Couples need to
make sure they know how they are doing with their budget.
</P>
<P>
   _ Talk about bank accounts. Some couples toss all their money
into a joint account. Others prefer, at least at first, to have
separate accounts, or to have both. This decision seems obvious,
but it communicates a lot about the question of who controls
spending.
</P>
<P>
   _ Control your credit cards. The temptation to use them is
great, and spouses need to agree on limits.
</P>
<P>
   _ Designate a financial housekeeper. It's not terribly important
whether husband or wife balances the checkbook, pays the bills,
keeps the financial records and handles other routine chores. But
it is important that one person is responsible for getting it all
done.
</P>
<P>
   None of these is a particularly difficult chore. For many
couples, the hardest part is just getting started: talking openly
about money. It isn't at all romantic. But it beats fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
