A1348 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN19-COX     05-18 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let's treat the real problem _ adults _ not the kids
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ When folks tell me how kids have changed, I
listen with a jaundiced ear, because I'm hearing a lot of the same
things I heard from grownups half-a-century ago. And sometimes I
wonder who has really done the changing. Us or them?
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago we had a kid in our high school who liked to
blow up things. Dan started small with a couple of toilets in the
boys' restroom. Later he graduated to unoccupied houses on the
``wrong'' side of the tracks, and
</P>
<P>
   eventually, when he went for a bridge across the Miami River,
even his dad's lofty standing in the community couldn't keep him in
school and out of an institution.
</P>
<P>
   Dan was nobody's hero. He never made the six o'clock news (his
old man's clout probably kept him from it) and no reporters went
for in-depth coverage of his diaper days. Kids avoided him because
he was trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Dan never received the reward he sought with his odd
behavior. He was denied his 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   So what's wrong with kids today?
</P>
<P>
   I dunno', but why don't we consider the possibility that maybe
it's not the kids. Maybe it's us.
</P>
<P>
   Kids don't own the movie studios that crank out the crud we're
raising such hell about, and how many porn magazines are published
by teens? Television? Show me a network owned and operated by
adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   When kids are unceremoniously dumped into this world, they're a
clean slate _ the ``tabula rasa'' psychologists and philosophers
frequently refer to as the minds not yet affected by experiences or
impressions. And then what happens?
</P>
<P>
   Life happens. Grownups happen.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers, when I was one, were shallow (totally concerned with
hair, clothes, and who had a cool car), insecure (Oh God, I'm
worthless), and egocentric (everybody is looking at ME). We
disobeyed our parents, made fun of our teachers, and disdained
adult authority. Teen-agers today are shallow, insecure, and
egocentric. They are disobedient and make fun of adults.
</P>
<P>
   So tell me...what's changed?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the role models.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Fe, N.M., a 28-year-old mother of four is closing in on
her dream of operating her very own topless housecleaning service.
Yessiree, folks, these happy housekeepers will be doing their
dusting sans smock (and everything else) from the waist up. The
entrepreneur's husband will be happily looking after the couple's
children, ages 2 through 9, while his wife and her day ladies clean
up around town.
</P>
<P>
   The start-up is practically a done deal since there are no laws
on the books prohibiting such a venture. Now, the soon-to-be
mopping mogul is shopping insurance companies for coverage (pun
intended). She's found a few who may insure her service but they
need to do a bit of research first _ I'd suggest they start by
determining how many homes in the Santa Fe area still use wringer
washers.
</P>
<P>
   Now I ask you, is scrubbing a toilet topless really the
``American Dream'' we encourage our youth to pursue?
</P>
<P>
   Nice role model. Maybe her little ones can take her to school
for ``Show and Tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, federal and state governments are throwing millions
of dollars at the problem of at-risk kids. In addition to providing
identification and intervention for troubled youngsters, there are
funded programs designed to keep schools safe and drug free.
There's even an afternoon program to take kids off the streets
until someone gets home to look after them.
</P>
<P>
   We're doing all we can folks _ as long as we're locked into an
agenda that fails to identify the (SET ITAL)real(END ITAL) problem.
Maybe it's time we stop treating the symptom (kids) and go for the
illness (us).
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. E-mail:
eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
