<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1349 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN19-COX     05-18 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What kids don't hear
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When the TV is on, my youngest son is conditioned
to react to sexually connoted words and images with two words:
``Bye bye.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been on his toes a lot in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for Animal Planet, Cartoon Network and ``Brady
Bunch'' reruns on Nickelodeon, there would have been nothing on TV
this past year that didn't force him to leave the room.
</P>
<P>
   My older son built up his flexor muscles this year, in part
because he ousted the TV from his room but also because of the
gusto with which he flexed the remote every time he watched TV and
reference was made to the White House sex scandal _ push-button
thrusts sufficient to give him a wrist wrestler's forearm.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, combine all the material zapped in midsentence, and
you still have too much.
</P>
<P>
   History no doubt will see it all as a black mark. Gloria Feldt,
president of Planned Parenthood Federation of America, realizes
that within it all is an opportunity for candor, ``a teachable
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming impossible to exclude young people from the
conversation,'' she told an audience in Waco last week.
</P>
<P>
   If we've had a national dialogue in 1999, it's been of the
locker-room variety. And locker-room conversations never made
anyone smarter than the nearest roll of elastic wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Planned Parenthood is observing May, National Teen Pregnancy
Prevention Month, with an initiative and guide, ``Helping Teens
Make Responsible Choices'' _ emphasizing ways to prepare young
people to say no. Among the things featured is Planned Parenthood
of Central Texas' ``Nobody's Fool'' summer seminar on sexuality,
peer pressure and sound decisions.
</P>
<P>
   It's a reminder that conservatives and the Christian right do
not own the copyright on abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   Congress authorized $50 million in the 1996 welfare reform act
for abstinence education. That may have sounded good, but roughly
translated it has come to mean, ``Say no to sex _ and to
contraceptive education.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is dumb.
</P>
<P>
   One of the smartest things said about the subject recently came
from a movie star, of all people. Sharon Stone, participating in a
panel on AIDS and youth at the United Nations, said, ``No matter
how much we guide our children within our families, within our
churches, within our schools, we are not stronger than the power of
sexuality _ particularly to a teen-ager.'' She wasn't advocating
teen promiscuity. Face the biological facts, she was saying, and
manage them wisely.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush recently hailed a group of high schoolers
for making a vow of chastity until marriage. We can all heave a
sigh of relief for that group, and applaud lustily for making such
a choice. But it is their choice. Nobody can regulate it for them.
</P>
<P>
   Even they need to know how their bodies work and how in marriage
they can make parenthood an informed choice.
</P>
<P>
   But of course that would be a frank discussion of sex. And we
don't want to do that, frankly.
</P>
<P>
   Feldt compared America's run-from-the-discussion tendency to the
common-sense, just-the-facts attitude about sex education in the
Netherlands, which has a teen pregnancy rate one-ninth that of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that the Netherlands treats teen sexuality as
a public health issue and we treat it as a political geyser.
</P>
<P>
   Did someone say politics? Sex and politics? There you go. My
oldest has just used the zapper, and his brother has fled the room.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
