<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, May 18, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ZEDILLO-CALIF (Sacramento, Calif.) _ President Ernesto Zedillo
became the first Mexican leader to visit California's capital when
he arrived here Tuesday for a three-day tour on trade, education
and the trickiest subject of all _ immigration. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ As state attorney general, Dan
Morales was no virgin in the hardball world of Texas politics. His
boyish demeanor and strong popularity with the voters belied a
series of political controversies that often saw him at odds with
other Democratic leaders as well as Republican officeholders. But
not even Morales' political enemies would ever have predicted that
the state's former top lawyer would stand accused of doctoring
contracts to help a friend get a big piece of the tobacco
settlement pie. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   ROBBER-GRAVE (San Antonio) _ For more than 60 years, Joe Palmer,
a member of the Clyde Barrow and Bonnie Parker bank robber gang,
lay in an unmarked grave in a South San Antonio cemetery. Palmer's
anonymity is no more. Palmer's niece and a few members of Partners
in Crime, an Internet group that conducts research on
Depression-era outlaws, has dedicated a headstone over his grave.
By CARMINA DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   HOMICIDE (San Francisco) _ Police are holding David Torrente for
questioning in connection with the stabbing death of his father in
a posh Tiburon subdivision. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-TECH-CENTER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Across the country, states are
looking to universities to provide the big research that translates
into new companies and new jobs. New York has lagged behind, losing
millions of federal research dollars. A rare partnership between
the State University of New York and Cornell University hopes to
change that with the SUNY-Cornell Multiplier to Advance Research
and Technology, or SMART-NY. By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WINTER-WEIGHT (Albany, N.Y.) _ When spring arrives, many of us
notice that the scale tips more heavily after a long winter of
snacking, sleeping and trying to stay warm. Here are a few
relatively painless ways of shaping up for summer. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-HADRIAN (San Antonio) _ Former Texas Monthly writer
Robert Draper matches a guilt-ridden ex-con against his
opportunistic best friend, the warden, in Draper's first novel,
``Hadrian's Walls,'' a tangled multigenerational tale about an East
Texas prison town loosely based on Huntsville. By DAN R. GODDARD.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-SISTERS (Undated) _ Real people in familiar settings
step off the pages of Jo-Ann Mapson's ``The Wilder Sisters'' and
into your heart. This is a story about two delightful, troubled,
vibrant women _ Rose and Lily, ages 40 and 35, respectively _ who
have taken different paths since growing up in Floralee, N.M. By
JULIE COOPER.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-STAR-HYPE (San Francisco) _ I weep for the fact that no
matter what anyone says in advance of the public's seeing George
Lucas' ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' people will
go because they have to _ some just won't brave the lines for the
first few weekends. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-PREVIEW-NBC (Undated) _ Everything is supposed to look good
on paper as the TV networks unveil their fall seasons. But NBC,
which kicked off the ``upfronts'' in New York on Monday, managed to
look desperate and dead wrong in a moment normally protected by big
dreams and unbridled optimism. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Family travel specialist Eileen Ogintz
sounds a request: ``Conjure up your happiest memories. More often
than not, they center around a family vacation.'' Familes are
traveling together in record numbers. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Just what the world needs: more
cell phone users who feel free to lose themselves in conversation.
Already we don't have enough? Men and women with booming,
screeching voices? Making anyone within earshot privvy to their
every thought? They are omnipresent. In the old days it was known
as ``bad manners.'' By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE-ANNIVERSARY (Danville, Calif.) _ This week marks the
anniversary of the founding of the New York Stock Exchange. On May
17, 1792, some two dozen brokers, accustomed to casually meeting on
lower Wall Street to exchange brandy, gossip and bonds, decided to
make their arrangement permanent. The result of this humble
agreement evolved, over time, into the U.S. securities market. By
CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
</TEXT>
