<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1395 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLDWYN-HEIR-DIRECTS-     05-18 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDWYN-HEIR-DIRECTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD AS GOLDWYN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature from W magazine _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales
Executive DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent by mail or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number. Please specify that
you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 By JULIE L. BELCOVE 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Tony Goldwyn swears he was never one of those actors who really
want to direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no desire to direct,'' says Goldwyn, who, yes, is one of
the Goldwyns. ``I had always acted in movies and looked at the
director and thought, `Thank God that's not me.' They just always
had that 1,000-yard stare and looked besieged with problems. I
always thought, `I have this fun job of being an actor.'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, his route to the director's chair on the set of ``A Walk
on the Moon,'' was a circuitous one. Goldwyn decided about four
years ago that taking on the role of producer and developing
material for himself _ would boost his acting career.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a moment of leverage _ when a movie's making a
lot of money at the box office _ that's the time to capitalize on
things,'' says Goldwyn, who had one of those moments when he played
the villain in 1990s ``Ghost'' and was determined to have a project
ready to go the next time lightning struck.
</P>
<P>
   While reading through stacks of screenplays, he came across ``A
Walk on the Moon,'' a story about a young housewife in a Catskills'
summer resort who undergoes a sexual awakening in the tumultuous
summer of '69. Goldwyn couldn't really see himself playing either
the betrayed husband or the hippie lover, but the script captivated
him nonetheless, and after meeting its author, Pamela Gray, he
agreed to produce it.
</P>
<P>
   He set Gray to work on rewrites and spent the next six months
looking for a director. ``I got really cold feet about everyone I
met. I was getting a massage one day,'' he says, laughing at
himself, ``laying on the table, and I just went, `Oh, I've got to
do this myself.' Literally, it was like a flash from God or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldwyn may have been a rookie as a director, but he was no babe
in Hollywood. As grandson of both legendary producer Samuel Goldwyn
and screenwriter Sidney Howard, son of art-film producer Samuel
Goldwyn Jr., and brother of Paramount Motion Pictures president
John Goldwyn, Tony Goldwyn knew a thing or two about how to get a
movie made.
</P>
<P>
   As luck would have it, just as Goldwyn had decided not to try to
rush a deal, his agent called to tell him Dustin Hoffman's Punch
Productions wanted to talk. ``And suddenly we were in business,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Hoffman was interested in directing the movie himself
but deferred to Goldwyn. They collaborated on casting, signing
Diane Lane for the lead and Liev Schreiber and Anna Paquin for her
husband and teenage daughter. Goldwyn was intent on having Viggo
Mortensen play Lane's lover, and when the actor pulled out of
another movie, he saw his chance. ``I couldn't really speak in the
meeting because I was so shaken at how right this guy was,''
Goldwyn says.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman watched the dailies, FedExed from location in Canada,
and gave Goldwyn advice by phone. But he stayed away from both the
set and the editing room. ``I had so much respect for the work Tony
did,'' he explains. ``He has certain things you have to have, and
that's intelligence, focus, tremendous energy and real passion. And
humanity doesn't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldwyn relied on the crew for their technical knowledge and
spent a good deal of time just talking to the cast. Hoffman says he
had a natural ability to relate to the actors, helping them deliver
strong performances. About halfway through the shoot, Diane Lane
remembers, she asked Goldwyn how he managed to please everyone and
``never lose his cool once _ never.'' He replied that from his
years of experience as an actor he had imagined his ideal director
and told her, ``That's what I'm playing.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the filmmaking process proved easier than
Goldwyn's initial efforts to break into acting in the early 80s.
When he first fell in love with acting in high school, he was a
little disappointed in himself: He hadn't wanted to go into the
family business. In a kind of compromise, he moved to New York
after acting school in London. In the theater world, the name
didn't carry much clout, which he says suited him fine, as did
acting on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   But after several years as a working actor, if not a prominent
one, Goldwyn returned to L.A and landed frequent TV roles on
``Murphy Brown,'' ``Designing Women,'' ``St. Elsewhere'' and ``L.A.
Law.'' He had less luck in movies. ``In L.A., I would walk into an
audition], and they'd go, `How's your dad?' or `We had lunch with
your brother the other day,''' Goldwyn says, cringing at the
memory. ``They'd assume you were a dilettante kid who didn't really
know what you wanted to do, so you said, `Oh, I'll be an actor.' I
worked really hard. I felt very frustrated to be dismissed in that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   His big break came with ``Ghost.'' ``I forced my way into an
audition,'' he recalls. The movie was a huge hit worldwide, and
Goldwyn, with his chiseled features, melting blue eyes and serious
actor credentials, seemed poised for stardom. But he says, ``I
always felt like I was wearing someone else's clothes. I had no
instinct for being a movie star.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade after ``Ghost,'', he's still being typecast as the
good-looking villain. ``It's funny he plays such convincing bad
guys,'' says Diane Lane, ``because he's the most charming, gentle
person.'' Although he is developing three projects to direct,
because of time constraints, Goldwyn says he has no plans to give
up acting entirely. Nor does the 38-year-old intend to leave
suburban Connecticut, where he makes his home away from the
limelight with his wife, production designer Jane Musky, and their
two young daughters, Anna and Tess. Even his mother, when she was
dying of cancer, cautioned that he needed to become more adept at
playing the game. But Goldwyn has no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever opportunities I have missed as an actor I'll make up
for in spades in breadth and depth, as opposed to this obsession
with being hot, which you get into in L.A.,'' he says. ``I really
believe you have to decide how you want your life to go, and you
have to be true to that.''  &QL;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (JULIE L. BELCOVE is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
