<HEADER>
A1401 &Cx1f; tab-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCIS-MAYES-INTERVI     05-18 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCIS-MAYES-INTERVIEW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: FRANCIS MAYES INTERVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature culled from The New
York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate is
not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Sales Executive DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It still sounds like an unlikely recipe for a bestseller. A
divorced middle-aged college professor and her new companion take
much of their life savings and purchase a crumbing 13-room house in
Italy. The 200-year old Tuscan farmhouse, called ``Bramasole,'' was
``tall, square and apricot-colored with faded green shutters,
ancient tile roof and an iron balcony on the second level'' and
needed a major renovation that is painstakingly detailed. Between
reconstructing stone walls and plumbing systems, there is much talk
of eating, drinking wine and the glories of small-town Tuscan life.
 &HT;    The book, of course, was Frances Mayes' ``Under the Tuscan Sun''
(Broadway, 1997; $14), which has spent over 83 weeks on ``The New
York Times'' paperback bestseller list and has more than a million
copies in print.
 &HT;    ``I thought people would like it because it was about Italy and
food and houses and travel,'' Mayes said in a recent phone
interview from her home in San Francisco. ``But it seems like a
great many people identified with taking a risk in mid-life, with
starting over. I didn't know that it would be picked up so
strongly.''
 &HT;    Mayes, who was born in Fitzgerald, Georgia, still speaks with
the softest of Southern accents, despite living in San Francisco
since the early 1970s. A professor of creative writing at San
Francisco State University, where she has directed the Poetry
Center and chaired the Department of Creative Writing, she has
written five books of poetry and has just published ``Bella
Tuscany: The Sweet Life in Italy'' (Broadway, 1999; $25). In the
new book, she chronicles a season at Bramasole that a sabbatical
allows her and her now-husband, Ed Kleinschmidt, to enjoy.
 &HT;    ``I'm in a rural part of Tuscany and some people think I
idealize it,'' Mayes says. ``I don't. When I get there, something
heavy slides away. It feels euphoric.''
 &HT;    The major restoration work done, she writes about the rural
pleasures that colored her first book, travels to Sicily and Venice
and Lago Trasimeno, and throws open the doors once again to a
lifestyle that so many readers found enticing. One that seems
worlds away from her urban lifestyle in San Francisco.
 &HT;    ``I think the Italians have done better with the 20th century
than we have,'' Mayes says. ``They have a different sense of time,
even in their urban environments. In Cortona, where we live,
there's a very cohesive population. There's an intense sense of
community. I feel very disassociated from that in my American life.
I think everyone's feeling the want of that. But in Italy, as a
stranger, a foreigner, I get to experience that and it makes me
feel at home.''
 &HT;    It seems like a timeless world where Mayes can devote endless
days to gardening, or marketing or taking long drives in pursuit of
wine from a local grower's collective. But in the nine years since
she has bought Bramasole, Mayes says that she has done more than
simply enjoy her summer days there.
 &HT;    ``I've written two books and restored the house and done lots of
gardening,'' she points out. ''I think the siesta is why the days
seem long. They're nicely balanced. I get up early and work and
then the siesta goes from 1:30 to about 4:30. It's like two days.
It's the best time of day and I get a lot of reading done. And it
feels familiar. I grew up in the south and my parents always faded
after lunch. Down in south Georgia, they still had a big midday
meal.''
 &HT;    Mayes loves reading ''that whole genre of travel narrative. I
love Ann Cornelisen's work and I dedicated my first book to her. I
also love Freya Stark, going into Arabia when no man, let alone
woman, would go there.''
 &HT;    Readers of ``Under the Tuscan Sun'' will not be surprised to
learn that food and its role in daily Italian life feature
prominently in Mayes' new work. In ``Bella Tuscany,'' she
rhapsodizes about artichokes and tomatoes, asparagus and wild
almonds, of meals that last for hours and the pleasures of
discovering an edible plant she'd previously never heard of. She
also recounts a trip through Sicily and gives the impression that
she is traveling through an entirely different country.
 &HT;    ``Italy feels so diverse in so many ways,'' Mayes says. ``The
north of Italy is very different from Tuscany and from Apulia in
the south. It's like different countries everywhere. Remember that
Italy was chopped up into little fiefdoms. Sicily is even more
extreme.''
 &HT;    Mayes has taken a year off from San Francisco State to work on a
novel that's set in Georgia. She says she's about halfway through
it and hopes to finish it by December. She admits that she's had
her share of people writing to her and even dropping by unannounced
at her house in Tuscany, entranced by her story. But she's quick to
add that they ``have not been invasive.''
 &HT;    As for Mayes' Italian, it's getting better, she says, noting
that she and her husband study with a tutor twice a week.
 &HT;    ``But I'm probably murdering the language two-thirds of the
time,`` she confesses.
 &HT;     (EVERETT POTTER is a New York-based free-lance writer.)  
 &HT;     c.1999 Everett Potter  
