<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, May 19. If you have any questions, please call The
Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   ENERGY: Private contractors of the Department of Energy -
including Allied Signal and Midwest Research Institute of Kansas
City - are doing little to curb excessive travel costs, a recent
government audit shows. The 32 contractors failed to meet the
department's 1995 goal to cut $35 million a year in travel.
Altogether, we footed $250 million for their travel last year. Some
firms show little interest in containing costs - paying $1,000 + on
airline tickets they could get for less than half that amount and
spending $300 a night on hotel rooms. Kevin Murphy. 28 inches.
</P>
<P>
   RAPE. Folo on the reported rape of 6-year-old twin girls, who
told police on Sunday that six boys had raped them Saturday
afternoon at their babysitter's home in Kansas City, Kan. Anne
Lamoy.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS: The annual Kids Count survey is out again, and for the
first time, researchers have listed six risk factors in families
that often lead to bad outcomes for children. These include no
full-time worker in the family, parents who are dropouts, parents
on welfare, single parent families. Ten percent of Missouri
families and 8 percent of Kansas families meet the criteria for
``high-risk families,'' with at least four risk factors. These are
below the national average. Meanwhile, on the actual indicators of
child welfare, Kansas has slipped greatly over 15 years in having
more single parent families. Missouri kids are dropping out more
frequently. We localize the story at St. Vincent's child care
center, where the two nuns see lots of families with these risk
factors. Graphic. Donald Bradley. 20.
</P>
<P>
   PUMP: First it was a cheesecake calendar. Now a fire captain's
wife used a pumper, her husband's helmet, and even a Dalmatian, in
her advertisement to sell real estate for J.C. Nichols. Is this
increasing commercialization of the fire department causing any
concerns? Judy Thomas. 18. Photo of the advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   ACLU: The ACLU says it has received hundreds of complaints from
parents and children around the country, saying school officials
are overreacting to Columbine High School by sending kids home for
no good reason. The local ACLU will be sending letters to school
districts in Missouri and Kansas warning them about students'
rights. It's an example of the tension between freedom of
expression and protecting students. We'll talk to a few local
school districts for their comments. Winston Ross. 15.
</P>
<P>
   SKUL (with ACLU): Kansas City Mayor Kay Barnes meets Tuesday, as
promised, with area school officials to discuss school violence and
other issues. Gromer Jeffers and Tanika White. 15.
</P>
<P>
   CHOW (business) _ Boyd Gaming Corp. have won a decade-long court
battle against the IRS over the corporate tax deductibility of
meals provided to employees. The ruling cuts across all industries
and will avoid taxing employees themselves on the value of the
meals they recieve. Rick Alm.
</P>
<P>
   TWA (tentative) _ TWA management meets with Kansas City Star's
editorial board. By Randolph Heaster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
