<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORALES' CAREER STEEPED IN POLITICAL CONTROVERSY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As state attorney general, Dan Morales was no
virgin in the hardball world of Texas politics.
</P>
<P>
   His boyish demeanor and strong popularity with the voters belied
a series of political controversies that often saw him at odds with
other Democratic leaders as well as Republican officeholders.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was the first Hispanic elected to a nonjudicial
statewide office in Texas, Morales alienated many minority
legislators by ruling against affirmative action programs at Texas
colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   And he once even got into a shoving match with then-Lt. Gov. Bob
Bullock during a heated, private debate over redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   But most of Morales' political enemies would never have
predicted that the state's former top lawyer would stand accused of
doctoring contracts to help a friend get a big piece of the tobacco
settlement pie.
</P>
<P>
   His longtime supporters, meanwhile, were shocked when his
successor, Attorney General John Cornyn, raised the allegations in
a federal court filing this month.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Dusek, Morales' former press secretary, said he hopes that
pending investigations will show that Morales was guilty of nothing
worse than ``bad judgment and bungling.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the outcome, he added, ``A crowning achievement in
many persons' careers, especially Dan's, has been reduced to
shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales has angrily denied Cornyn's accusations, which stem from
his efforts to help Houston lawyer Marc Murr obtain hundreds of
millions of dollars in legal fees from the state's landmark, $17.3
billion tobacco settlement. Under investigation by Cornyn and the
FBI, Morales has declined further public comment, and so has Murr.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, who succeeded Morales Jan. 1, contends that Morales and
Murr falsified signatures and backdated two purported contracts to
mislead a federal judge deciding on legal fees in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of Cornyn's challenge, Murr abruptly withdrew a
claim for about $260 million awarded by a state arbitration panel,
which he and Morales had handpicked.
</P>
<P>
   But the Houston attorney _ who other lawyers say did little work
on the tobacco suit _ still is to receive $1 million in fees
payable by cigarette companies under a separate, national
arbitration award entered late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some Morales associates say that Cornyn, a Republican, is trying
to bury his 43-year-old predecessor politically, to remove any
possibility that the former attorney general may someday re-enter
politics.
</P>
<P>
   When he voluntarily decided to retire from public office last
year, Morales was still one of the most popular Democrats in Texas.
He said he wanted to work in the private sector and spend more time
with his new wife, whom he married in 1997, and her two children.
But he didn't rule out the possibility of eventually returning to
public life to run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and the U.S. attorney's office have refused to confirm
that there is an investigation, which Cornyn says is continuing.
Cornyn's office denies some reports that federal investigators have
concluded that there is nothing for them to prosecute.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Schaffer of Houston, president of the Texas Criminal
Defense Lawyers Association, said that backdating a contract isn't
necessarily criminal. Such an act depends on the intent of the
people who do the backdating and whether they are trying to deceive
others.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, he said, investigators may be studying the
Murr contracts for forgery or perhaps conspiracy or mail fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Morales' defenders note that he has repeatedly insisted that the
lawyers who helped him in the tobacco suit not be paid from the
state's share of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could it be that Morales was trying to help Murr get a big fee
from tobacco because he disliked those companies so much?'' one
friend speculated.
</P>
<P>
   But that scenario, if true, was torpedoed when a national
arbitration panel, which decided how much the cigarette makers
would pay the lawyers, awarded Murr only $1 million. The additional
$259 million awarded Murr by the separate, state arbitration group
represented a potential claim against the state.
</P>
<P>
   A team of five other outside lawyers with whom Morales had a
well-known contingency contract was awarded $3.3 billion by the
national arbitrators.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on Morales' tenure as attorney general, Ed Martin, a
political consultant and former executive director of the Texas
Democratic Party, said he had his ``ups and downs'' with Morales
and often opposed him on issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``As attorney general, he cut his own path,'' Martin said, and
often disagreed with other Democrats on key issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, he was willing to go against leaders of his own
party (on matters of principle),'' Martin said. ``This doesn't
sound like somebody who would do something (illegal) for money.''
</P>
<P>
   While hoping the allegations against their former boss are
unfounded, some former Morales staffers are, nevertheless, clearly
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter, Morales' lead state lawyer in the tobacco suit,
and another former Morales staffer, in a meeting shortly before
Cornyn took office, discussed their ``reservations'' about Murr
with the new attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Another former high-level Morales staffer, who now works for
Cornyn, went to federal investigators about that same time.
</P>
<P>
   Potter, who reportedly has also been interviewed by the FBI, had
few contacts with Murr during the tobacco suit. He told Cornyn's
office that Murr admitted to him only a few weeks before the case
was settled in January 1998 that he didn't have a contract with the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Dusek, Morales' former press secretary, said that he, like most
other people, never knew about Murr's purported contract in the
tobacco suit until after the settlement was negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am now very disappointed and feel betrayed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, when Murr became a major controversy in the weeks
before Morales left office, Dusek was uncomfortable enough to
refuse to answer reporters' questions about the Houston lawyer. He
insisted that Morales personally answer all inquiries about Murr.
</P>
<P>
   Already considered by some to behave as a ``Lone Ranger'' who
often acted without consulting other officeholders, Morales was on
his own when he sued the tobacco industry in 1996 over
smoking-related health-care costs and cigarette-marketing
practices. He has said he didn't believe the suit would ever have
been filed if he had had to ask the Legislature's permission
because tobacco lobbyists would have killed the idea.
</P>
<P>
   He also kept Gov. George W. Bush and legislative leaders in the
dark as he negotiated the details of the tobacco settlement.
Consequently, some lawmakers ``harbored a suspicion that something
wasn't right on this,'' said one former legislative staffer, who
asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Those secretive habits _ plus Morales' tendency to evade
reporters' questions or to issue misleading statements while he was
in office _ may be compounding his troubles.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, for example, Morales repeatedly insisted that a
settlement agreement he had signed in the landmark prison-reform
lawsuit had ended federal court control over the Texas prison
system.
</P>
<P>
   But it became obvious that U.S. District Judge William Wayne
Justice had retained oversight when he ordered an investigation of
one prison unit, following an inmate's complaint that a softball
field had been destroyed to make room for prison expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to ask (Morales) all the questions in the right order,
or you never got the full picture,'' the former legislative staffer
said.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation over Murr puts both Cornyn's and Morales'
reputations on the line.
</P>
<P>
   The initial reaction in state government, the former legislative
aide said, has been ``shock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The general reaction has been in a nutshell that where there's
smoke, there's fire, and let's sit back and watch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
