<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES BOND WHILE VACATIONING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Family travel specialist Eileen Ogintz sounds a request:
</P>
<P>
   ``Conjure up your happiest memories,'' she says. ``More often
than not, they center around a family vacation. That's because
these vacations represent more than just getting away from home.
They help us form family bonds. This is especially important today
when we are torn in so many directions.''
</P>
<P>
   Families are traveling together in record numbers, too. Indeed,
during a recent panel discussion about family travel in St.
Petersburg, Fla., Ogintz and other travel industry representatives
provided this food for thought (citing various sources):
</P>
<P>
   _ Americans now take more than 100 million trips annually with
at least one child, a 50 percent increase during the last 10 years.
Twenty percent of these journeys result in expenditures of at least
$2,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Family travel is no longer a summer-only pastime. Sixteen
million parents take kids from the classroom during the school year
to accompany them on trips, and 40 percent of spring and fall
vacations include children.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thirty-two million annual business trips _ or 16 percent of
all business travel _ include a child.
</P>
<P>
   _ Multigenerational travel continues to expand in popularity; 16
million trips now include one or more grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   _ Single parents, who head one-third of U.S. families, are
vacationing with their kids in growing numbers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TEENS' BLESSINGS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And an eye-opening statistic cited by Ogintz: Among more than 21
million teen-agers in the United States, 60 percent sell parents on
the family's vacation choice.
</P>
<P>
   This last trend is attributed in part to today's youths
mastering the Internet _ and its travel-related sites and chat
rooms _ faster than many parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mom and Dad are talking about taking a cruise, the kids
will go online and read about it and either give their blessing or
say, `This ship stinks,''' says Nancy Schretter, who operates the
Family Travel Network site for America Online subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a decision is made about the cruise,'' Schretter
continues, ``the kids will get back online and say, `I'm going on
such-such ship. Who else is going to be there?' When they find kids
with like interests, they'll even arrange to meet onboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is enamored of kids' increased influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think all children know what a family vacation should
be,'' says Helena Koenig of Maryland-based Grandtravel. ``We have
to be careful about how much power we vest in children. Yes, our
children today have been exposed to more than those growing up 30
years ago. But an 11-year-old in any era is still an 11-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BROADER CHOICES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No matter the main decision-maker(s), family vacation choices
now extend far beyond the traditional and still-popular weekend
campout as cruise lines, resorts, even adventure tour companies
scramble to capture a share of the lucrative market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that the concept of family travel has changed,'' says
Koenig. ``I had five children. Did I ever go anywhere without them?
Of course not. But we stayed in a tent. What's happened is that
vendors have decided that it's OK to accept children. You even find
diapers and baby food on (upscale) Holland America cruise ships.''
</P>
<P>
   Half-a-million kids vacationed at sea last year. ``That
represents one of the biggest trends we're seeing in family
travel,'' says Ogintz.
</P>
<P>
   And the new Disney Cruise Line isn't alone in soliciting young
passengers. Carnival, Royal Caribbean, Princess, Norwegian and
other major lines offer extensive youth programs.
</P>
<P>
   Back on land, ``Almost every large resort has a kids program,''
says Laura Sutherland, author of several family-oriented books.
Though programs geared to ages 4-11 are most popular, many resorts
are exploring new ways to appeal to teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water parks are especially big at resorts,'' says Sutherland.
``Offshore platforms and swim-with-the-dolphin programs are
popular, too. Many resorts conduct lessons for kids in tennis, golf
and snorkeling. Some have photography lessons for kids. And I've
seen programs in children's etiquette.''
</P>
<P>
   Resorts also are emphasizing family travel through pricing
schemes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We frequently see promotions through which kids eat free or
that offer a second room for half-price,'' says Sutherland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of all, families just want to know when planning a trip
that their kids will be welcomed. Look at Club Med: It's changed
its entire image from a singles village to a family village.''
</P>
<P>
   The adventure-travel boon has impacted families, too. Based on
studies cited by Ogintz, 40 million families have taken an
adventure-oriented vacation in the past five years. More than half
camped, hiked or fished last summer. More than half of snowboarders
and one-fourth of skiers are under 18.
</P>
<P>
   At Grandtravel, a company that books only kids and grandparents
(with parents not invited), Koenig says that while trips to London,
Paris and Washington, D.C., are in demand, ``Our most popular tour
is a safari in Kenya.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Dave Wiggins, owner of Colorado-based American
Wilderness Experience, ``Kids want outdoor action and to have fun
with other kids. Parents want enrichment. Adventure travel answers
both. It's participatory. It's challenging. It's in a fun outdoor
setting. And more and more outfitters are adding family-focused
trips.''
</P>
<P>
   This growing diversity in family travel options poses new
challenges in arranging vacations, suggests Ogintz, who says,
``More people are planning on their own because most travel agents
don't fully understand the family market. In Paris, for instance,
there are few hotel rooms where you can fit more than two people,
so I want to know where I can go to rent a flat. Where can I find a
bistro that welcomes kids? A museum that has hands-on exhibits?''
</P>
<P>
   It would behoove travel agents _ and, yes, travel editors _ to
seek answers because family travel is clearly not a fad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
