<HEADLINE>
NOVELIST CONVICTS TEXAS PRISONS IN CELLBLOCK TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN R. GODDARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Former Texas Monthly writer Robert Draper matches
a guilt-ridden ex-con against his opportunistic best friend, the
warden, in Draper's first novel, ``Hadrian's Walls'' (Alfred A.
Knopf, $23), a tangled multigenerational tale about an East Texas
prison town loosely based on Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   Draper's Shepherdsville and its Hope Farm State Penitentiary
don't seem to have changed much since the 1930s, although the
state's prison building boom is pumping so much money into the
economy that every citizen is tainted by greed.
</P>
<P>
   The town is threatened by one entrepreneurial ex-con, Ricky
Tempesta, who plans to build a competing prison nearby. However,
the prison officials and their good old buddies in the state
legislature are painted as the true criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Hadrian Coleman, a convicted murderer at 15 and legendary
escapee at 30, is mainly concerned about getting the pardon
promised him by his boyhood friend, Sonny Hope, the smooth,
charming and corrupt prison warden. They also happen to love the
same woman, Jill Estelle, whose wealthy family fought the expansion
of the prison system _ and lost every round.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman tells his life story in the first person, peeling away
the small town's layers of hypocrisy like the skin of an onion _
ultimately revealing that he inadvertently killed a blind
pedophile, a federal judge, to save a teen-age Sonny from a fate
worse than death.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny's father, Purvis ``Thunderball'' Hope, the previous
warden, made sure Coleman did easy time for taking the rap for his
son. But Sonny eventually betrays his father, who cooked prisoners
alive in ``The Oven'' when they didn't behave. Add to this volatile
mix a crusading Houston Chronicle newspaper reporter, Sissy
Shipman, who loves exposing the sins of her hometown for the whole
state to read.
</P>
<P>
   Draper treads a fine line between Texas naturalism and Southern
gothic parody. His characters talk in an East Texas slang that
would probably make the dialogue coaches for ``Dallas'' wince.
There's not much poetry in the deep-fried cliches and scatological
metaphors that litter the book like so many cow patties. Draper may
have been aiming for Pat Conroy, but he comes a lot closer to a
Kmart Erskine Caldwell.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough writing about larger-than-life Texas characters
without making them sound like caricatures or cartoons. Draper's
overwrought, purple prose sometimes makes the story as hard to find
as a needle in the Big Thicket. The convoluted but predictable plot
is mostly revealed in flashbacks, which short-circuits the
suspense.
</P>
<P>
   The folks in Shepherdsville may not pick banjos, but they sound
a lot like the backwoods hillbillys in ``Deliverance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
