<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-SISTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM NEW MEXICO, A CASE OF SISTERLY LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE COOPER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Real people in familiar settings step off the pages of ``The
Wilder Sisters'' by Jo-Ann Mapson (HarperFlamingo, $24) and into
your heart.
</P>
<P>
   Two delightful, troubled, vibrant women _ Rose, 40, and Lily, 35
_ have taken different paths since growing up in Floralee, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Rose married young, had two kids and stayed in Floralee. When
the story begins she is widowed, having lost her husband, Phillip,
in a car wreck caused by a drunken driver. Her 20-something
children, Amanda and Second Chance (named after his maternal
grandfather), are off living their own lives while Rose is
struggling as a bookkeeper for the town veterinarian, Austin
Donavan. She doesn't just work for Donavan; she carries a torch for
him.
</P>
<P>
   But Donavan's carrying his own torch for his ex-wife, Leah, and
the only way he knows to extinguish it is to drink. The lovable
town vet is also the lovable town drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Lily is flying high as a well-paid representative for a medical
instrument company in California. Then a woman dies on the
operating table because of a doctor's incompetence and Lily flees
to the safety of her family's horse ranch in Floralee, where she
hopes to regroup.
</P>
<P>
   While lots of families have skeletons, the Wilder family's
closet is full to bursting. Lily can't forget Tres Quintero, her
first love. Sometimes she thinks about their child she aborted.
Rose can't bring herself to admit that Phillip was not a faithful
or good husband.
</P>
<P>
   I can picture in my mind every one of Mapson's characters who
fill the town of Floralee _ the colorful Wilder parents, Poppy and
Chance; Paloma, who also works in the veterinarian's office; Shep,
the head wrangler at the Wilder ranch, El Rancho Costa Plente, who
is dying of cancer; even the crazy dogs, Chachi and Buddy Guy, that
the women love.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Shadow Ranch,'' one of Mapson's previous novels, ``The
Wilder Sisters'' puts a face on everyone who comes in contact with
the sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Mapson hits the nail on the head when it comes to sisters. Lily
reminisces about the fight that has kept the sisters from talking
to each other for years and the secrets that Lily has kept from
Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``She missed her sister fiercely. There was no one else in the
world she could sit next to in the dark without saying a word and
know that she understood exactly what Lily was thinking. A person
could hate her sister forever and underneath the anger she'd still
take a bullet in her name.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep, that's a sister for you.
</P>
<P>
   There are some wonderful moments in the course of life in
northern New Mexico that flow from Mapson's pen. When the town
judge sentences Dr. Donavan to community service after a drunken
driving arrest, his punishment includes donating his services at
the New Mexico gay rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   There's the wonderful moment when the two sisters head to
Chimayo to say prayers for their loved ones, for those they've
loved and lost, and simply for love.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the food. The aromas and flavors of New Mexico
cooking are strong in ``The Wilder Sisters,'' and if your mouth
doesn't water, your eyes will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
