<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-PARTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PANAMA CANAL EVENT, FEW EXPECT A BASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY _ When the United States takes the final step in
turning over control of the Panama Canal to this country in
December, the end of the 96-year relationship will come without
fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Like Panama itself, wedged between the world's two largest
oceans, the plans for the transfer ceremony are being squeezed _
this time, by bigger end-of-year events: the millennium celebration
and the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would anyone want to come to a canal transfer at the end
of this year?'' one US official said on condition of anonymity.
``Unfortunately, I think this has lost some of its glamour.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the VIP-speckled gala two years ago when the British
handed Hong Kong over to Chinese control in an event that was
televised live worldwide, American and Panamanian negotiators have
no such expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a large celebration on Dec. 31, the day the United
States must officially complete its withdrawal from the Canal Zone,
American and Panamanian negotiators are planning a ceremony
somewhere around Dec. 10. It is unclear how big the event will be
or who will attend.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers who originally wanted a New Year's Eve bash found
that many foreign dignitaries were unwilling to miss millennium
events in their home countries. Others expressed fears that Y2K
computer problems at airlines or airports might leave them stranded
in Panama on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the transfer ceremony have also been snagged in
domestic politics. Government officials had proposed that the
celebration happen Aug. 15, to commemorate the day the 50-mile-long
waterway was opened in 1914.
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, that date would have allowed outgoing
President Ernesto Perez Balladares to take credit for resuming
sovereignty over the canal before he leaves office Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the newly elected president, Mireya Moscoso, will have
the honor of presiding over the event, and it remains to be seen
how the new government will want to mark the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   The seeming lack of enthusiasm surrounding the transfer may
reflect how much US attitudes have changed toward Panama and the
canal. Construction of the canal was once celebrated as a feat of
American know-how and muscle at the beginning of the so-called
American Century. Now, its surrender is seen by many as a symbol of
weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that any potential presidential candidate
would want to be there and risk being associated with losing the
canal,'' said one Clinton administration official when asked
whether Vice President Al Gore might attend the handover.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that US ambivalence follows failed US-Panamanian
negotiations for a regional drug-fighting center and a small
continued American military presence, said Jennifer McCoy, director
of Latin American and Caribbean Programs at the Carter Center in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The canal simply isn't as important as it once was as a means
of transportation and commerce,'' McCoy said. ``But this is still
an important event for showing how relations between the United
States and Latin America have matured.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of organization for a December ceremony is in vivid
contrast to the quietly efficient US military retreat from Canal
Zone bases. Just five years ago, more than 10,000 troops and their
families lived here. Fewer than one third remain today.
</P>
<P>
   Handover ceremonies for emptied US facilities now happen
regularly. Balboa High and the Canal Zone Junior College, the last
of the US-run schools, graduated their final classes Saturday and
will be shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's more important than the celebrations is that the people
of Panama are finally getting back the 10 percent of their land
that belongs to them,'' said Miguel Antonio Bernal, president of
the Political and International Studies Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership of the canal must revert to Panama by noon on Dec. 31,
according to the terms of the treaty signed in 1977 between
President Jimmy Carter and General Omar Torrijos.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of scaled-down official ceremonies that day,
Panamanians plan parties on Dec. 31 regardless of who is there.
``The only ones who really need to be here are the people who are
taking it over, and that's us,'' Bernal said. ``If Clinton or some
other guests don't want to come, then they don't have to. We'll
celebrate anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
