<SLUG> BC-TV-PREVIEW-NBC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC (YAWN) BANKS ON DRAMAS TO RECAPTURE VIEWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Everything is supposed to look good on paper as
the television networks unveil their fall seasons. But NBC, which
kicked off the ``upfronts'' in New York on Monday, managed to look
desperate and dead wrong in a moment normally protected by big
dreams and unbridled optimism.
</P>
<P>
   The once-dominant Peacock is reeling after finding that much of
its development last season was pathetic _ losing viewers to CBS
and clinging to a fingernail-thin grasp of the coveted 18 to 49
demographic. It's in danger of losing the latter advantage and
falling further behind in the former unless it pulls some kind of
miracle out of a bushel of new offerings.
</P>
<P>
   NBC unveiled seven new shows for fall, and five of them are
dramas, a major reversal for a network built on sitcoms. This is
the first lineup that essentially will be the legacy of Scott
Sassa, NBC's West Coast president. The network hired Garth Ancier,
the former wunderkind programmer at The WB, but he came on too late
to make an impression for this season. If these dramas fail, he'll
hip up the network pretty quickly.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, NBC has to live with a rejiggered lineup that
has lost ``Homicide: Life on the Street,'' ``NewsRadio'' and
``Caroline in the City.''
</P>
<P>
   The network kept a couple of dogs in ``Veronica's Closet,''
which moves to a very weak Monday slot (following the equally bad
``Suddenly Susan'') and certainly will be exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, ``Jesse,'' which has little merit, was renewed
and put back in the protected Thursday slot between ``Friends'' and
``Frasier,'' a move that bumps the superior ``Will &AMP; Grace'' back
to Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   NBC continued its ill-fated practice of giving sweetheart deals
to proven producers by allowing a sitcom called ``Stark Raving
Mad'' to get the plum Thursday slot between ``Frasier'' and
``Friends.'' The sitcom comes from Steven Levitan, who produces the
mediocre ``Just Shoot Me.''
</P>
<P>
   The new dramas are: ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit,'' a
franchise spinoff that will run Mondays. What's a ``Special Victims
Unit,'' you ask? It's a task force to investigate cases deemed
``particularly heinous.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a perfect fit after ``Veronica's Closet,'' and it's
likely to get drubbed by ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Wing'' is a drama set in the White House (from Adam
Sorkin of ``Sports Night'' and John Wells of ``ER'') that airs
Wednesdays. On paper it's ``Spin City'' buffed into a drama, with
Martin Sheen playing the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third Watch,'' set for Sundays, is another effort from Wells
(whose ``Trinity'' failed miserably in the fall) and focuses on
firefighters, cops and paramedics. Apparently the three-pronged
approach is to guard against the fact that cop dramas are a dying
breed, and focusing on firefighters and paramedics working the 3
p.m. to midnight shift ought to spice things up. But it's been a
long time since ``Emergency'' was a hit, and The WB tried
paramedics and failed with ``Rescue 77.''
</P>
<P>
   Falling into the dramedy category will be ``Cold Feet,'' about
three young couples, set for Fridays. This is based on a British
series (no surprise _ its executive producer tried to get
``Cracker'' to fly here, too).
</P>
<P>
   ``Freaks and Geeks,'' also a dramedy, revolves around two
siblings going to high school in the 1980s. It airs Saturdays. On
paper, at least, it's going after the well-trod nostalgia route,
with an emphasis on not fitting in. But perhaps executive producer
Judd Apatow (``The Larry Sanders Show'') can breathe some creative
life into it.
</P>
<P>
   The comedies include ``The Mike O'Malley Show,'' about a
thirtysomething guy getting back together with an old girlfriend
(does that sound paper thin to you?). It gets a plum Tuesday slot.
The part to really worry about: He talks directly to the camera.
</P>
<P>
   And Levitan's ``Stark Raving Mad,'' starring Tony Shalhoub
(``Wings'') and Neil Patrick Harris (``Doogie Howser''), which,
even on paper, sounds disastrous. It's about a best-selling horror
writer (Shalhoub) and his ``obsessively meticulous'' editor
(Harris). Seems Doogie has to help his guy get over his writing
block by visiting him a lot in the schlockmeister's wacky
``netherworld'' apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we'll still get five nights of ``Dateline.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no other way to say it: NBC better hope it has a real
big surprise, a ``Providence,'' for example. Mondays are a crime
scene of ill-fitting shows doomed to get hammered by ``Monday Night
Football.'' Moving ``Will &AMP; Grace'' to Tuesdays makes viewers
choose between that and ``Sports Night'' _ again (unless ABC moves
the show). And Thursday remains vulnerable with ``Jesse'' and
``Stark Raving Mad.'' Rival networks have pledged to take over
Thursday for the first time in years, and if this is NBC's defense,
look out.
</P>
<P>
   The network also announced four midseason shows: A drama, ``The
Others,'' that seems to be in the mold of The WB's ``Charmed''; a
dramedy from Don Roos (``The Opposite of Sex'') called ``M.Y.O.B.''
NBC's foray into animation includes ``Sammy,'' a David Spade
vehicle, and ``God, the Devil and Bob,'' both of which feature
myriad name actors providing voices.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, NBC's schedule looks like a patchwork quilt that it
hopes won't pull to shreds before Ancier can work his magic next
season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
