r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-STAR-HYPE-HNS &LR;      05-18 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STAR-HYPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JUST A MOVIE' OR INTERGALACTIC HYPE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hype is an onion. Once the layers have been
peeled away, what's left is enough to make you cry.
</P>
<P>
   So it's for the thousands sleeping outside cineplex box offices,
blowing up Moviefone servers like they were SkyTel pagers, that I
weep. I weep for the cruel art of anticipation. I weep for the fact
that no matter what anyone says in advance of the public's seeing
George Lucas' ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' people
will go because they have to _ some just won't brave the lines for
the first few weekends.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly two decades, people have been waiting for Lucas to
drop the first chapter of the New Testament in his intergalactic
space Bible. But ``The Phantom Menace'' seems to come from a motel
King James Version.
</P>
<P>
   We've been climbing over each other just to try to touch the hem
of this garment without asking what it's made of. But that's
because no one fretted until last week when Lucas and distributor
Twentieth Century Fox started showing the film, which explains why
some newspapers and magazines acted like that student in the front
of the classroom ``ooo-ooo''-ing with a raised arm ready to blow
his answer like a geyser.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Lucas and company were right in their dismissal of
the excitement: ``The Phantom Menace'' is just a movie _ but one
whose salty aftertaste has nothing to do with the swollen,
salivating expectations ballooned around it. Even if it hadn't been
heralded as though it were the Second Coming, with Lucas positioned
as fans' personal Jesus, ``Episode One'' would still be a soulless,
infuriatingly uninvolving graphic novel.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas always imagined the ``Star Wars'' collection to be some
``Remembrance of Things Past`` or ``Fall of Western Civilization''
disguised as Saturday matinee serials _ epic, adventuresome with
myth and meaning neatly tucked between the majestic plot-summary
scroll-ups and clockwise fade-outs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the whole ``Star Wars'' franchise is both a victim of itself
and a curious, heartbreaking sign of the FX times. Industrial Light
&AMP; Magic and Skywalker Sound, Lucas' effects companies, have so
transfigured moviegoing into a digital, larger-than-life,
realer-than-real experience blurring the natural and the processed
that the humanity of the resulting product ceases to exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom Menace'' is distressingly dehumanized _ to the point
that it probably would be more fun to encounter it on a PlayStation
than at a multiplex. You want to interact with it, but access is
strictly forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tellingly sad, insipid state of affairs when halfway
through, the appearance of Samuel L. Jackson as a Jedi councilman
just sits up there. That's because he just sits there, like the
rest of the film. Besides Jackson's lukewarm stunt cameo, Lucas
tries a few other gambits to rack up street creds, littering his
special-effects carnival with Saturday morning artifacts from
cartoons and the serial matinees to the awful dubbing of Kung-Fu
bloodbaths.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a conspicuous lack of blood here _ and the sweat
and tears seem to have been spent in post-production. Lucas'
computer-generated world may hover closer to his vision, but the
voices given to some of these otherworldly creatures are naggingly,
disturbingly of this racialized one: bumbling federation
figureheads who have an ancient-Chinese-secret dialect, a wheedling
Middle-Eastern-sounding slave-owner, etc. (Yoda's Fortune Cookie
English is one thing . . .)
</P>
<P>
   Lucas' plot, which is bite-sized enough to fit in the ``long
time ago in a galaxy far, far away'' scroll-up, but stretches
itself for 130 minutes, introduces Jedi Knight Qui-Gon Jinn (Liam
Neeson) and his protege, Obi-Wan Kenobi (Ewan McGregor). They
rescue an embattled Queen Amidala (Natalie Portman), whose planet
is besieged by the Trade Federation, and befriend a digitalized
amphibious nuisance called Jar Jar Binks (a creature best thought
of as a screaming John Leguizamo drag queen as channeled by Chris
Tucker in a lizard suit _ Ahmed Best provides the voice and
physical inspiration).
</P>
<P>
   But most importantly, they discover Anakin Skywalker (Jake
Lloyd), the boy who would become Darth Vader. He's a slave along
with his mother Shmi (Bergman muse Pernilla August) on planet
Tatooine.
</P>
<P>
   It's a point of inherent fascination to see a portrait of the
monster as a young man, but all we're told about him is that his
mother has conceived him seemingly immaculately. It's the only
organic moment in this synthetic wonderland (designed by Gavin
Bocquet), and even that remains muddled in mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas would rather bask in a ``Ben-Hur'' cum ``Speed Racer'' at
Daytona moment in which Ani, as he's dollishly nicknamed, competes
in a pod race unwittingly for his freedom. It's simultaneously
exhilarating, silly and bland, if for no other reason than it feels
too easily won. Not the race, but the ovation.
</P>
<P>
   The event comes on like ``Hanna-Barbera's Digitalized Star Wars
Cantina Goes to the Colosseum,'' complete with Sesame Street
Sportscasters and Tuscan Sand People sniping. And Darth Maul (Ray
Park), the film's most haunting figure _ a horned, hell-faced ninja
vision of near-silent evil _ is relegated, along with his
double-edged light saber, to the film's action-packed margins. He
probably gets more screen time in the video game.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Phantom Menace'' plods from start to finish, the
lifelessness the actors bring to their diminished icons exacerbates
the suspicion that this entire endeavor is a collusive effort to
banish spontaneity and brush strokes from the film. McGregor's
Obi-Wan is a pallid ornament, while Portman speaks in an Anglo
monotone somewhere between Katharine Hepburn and post-Evita
Madonna. But beyond her Bob Mackie goth gowns, Alexander
McQueen-on-Skittles robes and the gall it took for the 17-year-old
to wear them, there's nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   Neeson spends the film looking vexed, like this Jedi business is
a strain on his acting _ but, hey, it's an emotion that survived an
environment hellbent on vacuuming the rest of them out.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Ford and company were clunky but endearingly fearless
throughout the ``Star Wars Trilogy,'' and the go-for-broke
infectiousness was enthralling in itself. But 22 years later, an
artificial intelligence and calculated self-consciousness have
usurped the original's homemade joy and planted profundities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
