<HEADLINE>
WHY YOUNGSTERS LOVE TO SAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for a family vacation that's guaranteed to be enjoyed by
all ages? Then take a cruise.
</P>
<P>
   We introduced our children to cruising when the youngest was 4,
the oldest 8, and they took to cruising like fish take to water.
And that was in a day when cruise lines were not particularly
family friendly. The only cruise they weren't keen on was one
aboard the original Love Boat, the Pacific Princess. The reason was
simple: They had reached their teens and there were no other kids
aboard. Fortunately, they were a foursome and provided their own
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise ships have come a long way since those long-ago days 20
years ago. Now, most cruise lines have dedicated children's
programs and facilities. And families are flocking to the ships.
Carnival reports it expects to have some 200,000 children on its
ships this year. Disney will be bringing on its Disney Wonder,
sister ship to the Magic, which sails on three- and four-day
cruises from Florida to Disney's own island.
</P>
<P>
   For families, a cruise means no worries about food likes or
dislikes: There's always something the kids will eat. Sometimes a
cruise is a great introduction to new tastes _ one son discovered
frogs legs and escargot. The kids also make new discoveries by
seeing other cultures, meeting other youngsters from around the
country and the world.
</P>
<P>
   Parents find time for themselves. What could be better? Maybe
booking a ship with a family suite with separate rooms for parents
and kids.
</P>
<P>
   Family cruising has never been better. No matter what their age,
the kids will find lavish facilities, from computer labs for even
the young set to special ``no adults allowed'' clubs for the teens.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise lines with great programs for children include
American Hawaii Cruises, Carnival, Celebrity, Costa, Disney,
Holland America, Norwegian, Premier, Princess, Royal Caribbean, and
Windjammer.
</P>
<P>
   Ask for brochures from the lines showing family cruising
facilities, and before booking, ask about how the programs work,
and when they work. On one cruise line, parents seeking a day on
shore discovered that the children's program did not begin until an
hour after they had to join their tour. That's no fun.
</P>
<P>
   Check on the onboard facilities for both children and adults,
staffing for the children's programs, hours for the programs, and
even medical facilities on board.
</P>
<P>
   Ask also about staterooms for families: While most just pack the
whole family into one room, some offer suites, others connecting
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not sure about a seven-day cruise, consider a shorter
one. Disney, Carnival, and Premier all offer shorter cruises and
combine them with a land stay. Disney's cruises are three or four
days long, and the first three or four days of the vacation are at
Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Volendam delay
</P>
<P>
   Holland America's new Volendam, which was set to do a series of
New England cruises this fall, has run into a completion delay at
the shipyard in Italy. However, because of the delay, Holland
America is moving its Maasdam out of Europe, where it is doing
summer cruises earlier than expected to fill in for the Volendam.
The Maasdam will also do an unexpeced trans-Atlantic crossing
cruise, London to Boston, on Aug. 29. The Maasdam will then do a
seven-day Boston to Montreal cruise sailing Sept. 5, then assume
the Volendam's original schedule. The change also means the first
two planned Volendam sailings have been canceled, and scheduled
passengers will be offered alternatives and compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The change also means that passengers scheduled to sail on the
Maasdam in Europe in the fall are being moved to the Rotterdam.
</P>
<P>
   The Volendam's delay could also reflect reports of a softening
of the European cruise market because of American travelers'
concerns about the war in Yugoslavia. Travelers considering a
European cruise should understand that the cruise lines sailing in
the Mediterranean are safely away from the war zones, so there
should be no concern about being in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who might be considering a European cruise, this
could be a good time because many lines may be offering discounts
to fill the cancelations.
</P>
<P>
   Also because of the Volendam delay, Holland America's next ship,
the Zaandam, will also be delayed. Its scheduled maiden sailing is
now set for March 26, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Theater cruise
</P>
<P>
   Theater lovers should applaud this year's Theatre at Sea cruise
aboard the Royal Viking Sun. Stage and screen stars will headline
the Theater Guild's 80th Birthday Celebration Sept. 10-24 on a
London to Mediterranean cruise. Among stars on board will be
Patricia Neal, Cliff Robertson, Jean Stapleton, Alan Arkin, and Zoe
Caldwell. Cruise prices begin at $2,893, air fare is extra, and
former Cunard passengers receive a 14 percent discount. For
information, call 800-752-9732.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Whales in Norway
</P>
<P>
   Whale watching safaris to see the sperm whale, the world's
largest toothed whale, are being added to selected cruises of the
Norwegian Coastal Voyage. The voyage takes in some spectacular
scenery and picturesque ports along the 1,250-mile west coast of
Norway. The whale safari is an extra $80 and will be offered on
12-day round-trip voyages beginning in mid-August. Prices begin at
$1,796 and there are savings for passengers 67 and older. For
information, call 800-323-7436.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deals
</P>
<P>
   Take your pick: free round-trip air fare or 10 nights for the
price of seven aboard selected sailings between now and September
of the Paul Gauguin in French Polynesia. The cruise calls on Bora
Bora, Moorea, and Tahiti. Ask also about a complimentary
three-night stay at the Le Meridien Hotel in Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Photo cruise
</P>
<P>
   A photo safari featuring top photographers from Popular
Photography and American Photo magazines will be featured on the
June 10-17 sailing of the Delta Queen Old South cruise leaving from
New Orleans. The Delta Queen is America's only floating National
Historic Landmark. Passengers who book by May 30 have a $99
round-trip air fare option.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Carnival hot line
</P>
<P>
   Carnival Cruises is offering the first 24-hour toll-free travel
hot line for its passengers who experience an emergency in transit
to or from their cruise vacation. Callers within the United States
can access the line by dialing 877-885-4856, and from outside the
country, call collect 305-406-4779.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
New shows
</P>
<P>
   One of the benefits of sailing on the new larger ships are the
lavish show facilities on board. Princess Cruises' Grand Princess,
the present world's largest cruise ship, is boasting it now has the
largest set and cast ever to appear on a cruise ship. The new show,
``Rhythms of the City,'' debuts this June as the ship begins its
second Mediterranean season. Princess is also introducing new shows
on its other vessels this summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Volcano watching
</P>
<P>
   A safe but exciting view of the fiery glow of rivers of molten
lava flowing down Mount Kilauea await passengers aboard American
Hawaii Cruises' Independence on its weekly sails to the big island
of Hawaii. The volcano, now in its 16th year of eruption, spews
400,000 cubic yards of lava a day. Everything, of course, depends
on the weather and Madame Pele, the mythical fire goddess.
Passengers can get closer to the volcano by taking an optional land
tour to Hawaii Volcanoes National Park. To add to the interest, the
ship offers a Thursday night ``Madame Pele's Feast of Fire,'' a
25-foot long buffet featuring island dishes and an edible volcano
that ``erupts.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For food lovers
</P>
<P>
   Menus faithfully culled from dynastic history will be featured
during the Three Emperors' Dinner on a 10-night cruise from
Edinburgh to Stockholm beginning July 4. The cruise aboard Radisson
Seven Seas' 180-passenger Song of Flower will include a reenactment
of the lavish feast enjoyed by Kaiser Wilhelm I of Germany, Tsar
Alexander II of Russia, and Alexander III at a Paris restaurant on
June 7, 1867.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
