<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRUGMAN CHIVVIES, JAPAN SQUIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Asian finance ministers met over the weekend in Langkawi,
Maylaysia and, from a distance, the forum on Asian Pacific
Economic &UR;  &LR; Cooperation at the island resort looked like the good old
days.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputed the International Monetary Fund conclusion
earlier this month that, twenty months after the maelstrom began
with a currency devaluation in Thailand, more stable conditions had
returned to global financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   There was little of the rancor over hedge fund regulation and
short-term capital controls that had marred similar meetings of
Asian nations during the period of the full-blown crisis.
</P>
<P>
   And at the conclusion of the conference, Japanese Finance
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa announced a $16-billion facility to
provide credit guarantees for longer-term debt issued by nations
affected by the crunch, including Indonesia, Korea, Maylaysia, the
Philippines, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   But in Japan, short-term interest rates are still fluttering
near zero and skeptics doubt whether Miyazawa can deliver on his
government's promise to achieve 1/2 percent of GNP growth this year
_ instead of another decline. The world's second largest economy
remains mired in a stagnation that has lasted most of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has been tougher on Japan than Paul Krugman of the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology. A currency expert with a
strong interest in how macroeconomic policy affects trade and vice
versa, Krugman was perhaps the first analyst to describe Japan as
being caught in a ``liquidity'' trap similar to the bind that
afflicted the industrial economies during the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   As the generation of the Japanese baby boom has reached
retirement, the supply of private savings simply has outstripped
the demand for investment at home and abroad, according to Krugman.
</P>
<P>
   With the private sector unwilling to spend, the public sector
can't spend enough to restart the engine _ not without blowing the
top off an already large deficit. (It has been trying without
noticeable success.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The story of Japanese macroeconomics in the 1990s is that of
the pump that refused to be primed,'' he says, ``of ever-growing
budget deficits that stave off collapse but do not generate
self-sustaining growth.''
</P>
<P>
   In a new book that surveys in some detail the recent Asian
crisis, ``The Return of Depression Economics,'' Krugman argues at
some length that the only measure that can get the Japanese economy
growing again is to deliberately inflate its currency a little bit
_ say 2 percent or so a year.
</P>
<P>
   Only if Japan's depositers know that their nest eggs are bound
to shrink will they go searching for some way to preserve
purchasing power by taking on a little much-needed risk, Krugman
argues.
</P>
<P>
   Fiscal policy _ tax cuts and public works _ has reached its
limits; only announcing explicit inflation targets or, perhaps,
``quantitative easing'' (a polite phrase meaning ``printing
money'') will do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the Japanese government don't like Krugman's ideas.
Neither do most Western conservatives. To them, the reflation plan
calls for taking an easy and dangerous way out.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation has been notoriously difficult to manage at a steady
rate, they say; usually fairly quickly it has gotten out of hand.
What Japan really needs is deregulation, restructuring, and a wave
of plant closings.
</P>
<P>
   Even without such supply-side reforms, they say, the Japanese
economy is finally poised for a strong recovery. Another few weeks
should be decisive . . .. And another.
</P>
<P>
   Krugman recently returned from Japan, more discouraged than
ever, he says. ``If you tell them . . . that there should be a
clear committment to increase the monetary base at an annual rate
of at least 15 percent, you get the feeling that you have proposed
an immoral act.''
</P>
<P>
   In an article the other day in the Financial Times, he argued
that while key policymakers ``now understand the nature of their
problems, they still lack the intellectual courage to act on that
understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What this means, I fear, is that things will have to get
considerably worse before they get better. The good news is that
this can probably be arranged, and sooner than you think.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
