<SLUG> BC-WINTER-WEIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINGTIME WALKS CAN ERASE WINTER WEIGHT GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Many Americans face a weighty surprise this time
of year, when the scale tips more heavily after a long winter of
snacking, sleeping and trying to stay warm.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, you're not wearing big bulky clothes
anymore,'' said Joyce Bagyi, a clinical dietitian at Albany Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Her advice for winter weight gainers: ``Nip it in the bud.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning the spring shake-up into a shape-up doesn't have to be
difficult. Bagyi doesn't even use the D-word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have chips with your sandwich? Switch from chips to
fruit,'' she said. ``If you use two tablespoons of cream cheese on
your bagel, cut down to one.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, Bagyi encourages healthy people to step out
of hibernation and back into their original size by walking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a 10-minute walk at lunch, take another 10-minute walk
when you get home. ``It doesn't have to be all or nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Bach of St. Paul, Minn., agrees. As the co-author of
``ShapeWalking: Six Easy Steps to a Healthier Life,'' Bach is a
nationally known fitness specialist for those of us who don't have
unlimited time and money to spend on shaping up.
</P>
<P>
   Her goal is to get more people to realize the benefits of
walking as a way to lose weight and improve cardiovascular health.
``You don't need to go to a gym,'' she said. ``You can get into
shape by walking.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent study published in the Journal of the American Medical
Association also made that point.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers found that sedentary adults who took up walking did
as well or better over a two-year period at cutting fat, lowering
cholesterol and improving aerobic fitness as those who took up
traditional exercise programs.
</P>
<P>
   One reason: Study participants who went to the gym eventually
lost interest. The walkers, on the other hand, kept walking. ``It's
the easiest to fit into your life,'' Bach said.
</P>
<P>
   Ed and Emily Koch of Niskayuna, N.Y., have made walking up to
six miles a day as routine as brushing their teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking is so much fun,'' Emily Koch said. ``It's much easier
than being on a diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides walking to stay in shape, the Koches, both 68, use it to
burn stress and socialize. They're members of the Empire State
Capital Volkssporters of Albany, a walking group.
</P>
<P>
   Walking with a partner or friends can be a good way to stay
motivated. In her book, Bach encourages people to schedule their
walks into their day, just like any other important commitment.
</P>
<P>
   While even a slow walk will help you lose weight (the average
person burns about 100 calories per mile), she challenges people to
walk in their target zone.
</P>
<P>
   That zone is reached when your perceived exertion is between 5
and 7 on a scale of 1 to 10, with one being the easiest, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A five would be the same feeling you get when you're walking
deliberately, as if you're on your way to an appointment,'' she
said. ``A six would be as if you're five minutes late for that
appointment. At seven, you're 10 minutes late.''
</P>
<P>
   By working toward doing your entire walk in the target zone, not
including your warm-up or cool down, Bach estimates you can lose 10
pounds a year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For more information about ShapeWalking, visit
http://www.heeltotoe.com on the Internet. To purchase the book,
call 800-641-6802.)
</P>
</TEXT>
