<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE NOW, TECHNOLOGY SPURRED ECONOMY IN 19TH CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What explains the durability of the bull market in stocks?
</P>
<P>
   The simple answer is that the American economy has been able to
grow steadily without generating inflation _ at least until last
Friday, when a higher-than-expected report on consumer prices
spooked the market. Skeptical that growth and low inflation could
coexist for an extended period of time, Maureen Allyn went looking
for some historical precedent. ``If I can't find a prior example of
this I'm not really going to believe it is possible,'' says Allyn,
chief economist at Scudder Kemper Investments, the mutual fund
firm.
</P>
<P>
   To her surprise Allyn found such a period _ the late 19th
century. More specifically, the period between the 1870s and 1900.
Before you start laughing or throwing up objections, you might want
to hear some of the parallels between then and now.
</P>
<P>
   It was a time after a war _ the Civil War, not the Cold War _
when new markets were opening up, when there was plenty of capital
for investment, and free markets were in vogue. Great fortunes were
made in this period (think Carnegie and Rockefeller) and the gap
between the rich and poor widened.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a time when the US economy grew at a robust pace and
prices actually fell. The force behind some of that deflation was
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Allyn has a chart that tracks metal prices between 1865 and
1900. Prices fell steadily during that era, largely because of new
technology for making steel. Oil prices also fell. So did the price
of a camera. When George Eastman began tinkering in the 1870s, a
camera cost about $50, according to Richard Tedlow, a professor at
Harvard Business School. By 1900 Eastman was selling user-friendly
Brownie cameras for a dollar. Remind you of anything?
</P>
<P>
   Tedlow and Allyn both say the two most critical breakthroughs of
the period were the completion of the transcontinental railroad and
the telegraph. The former allowed people to ship goods anywhere in
the country; the latter allowed them to track prices and sales, if
not in real time, in a much shorter time frame than anyone
previously thought possible.
</P>
<P>
   The new infrastructure created opportunities for all sorts of
other businesses. ``Who knew when the railroad was invented that
one day you would be able to slaughter meat in Chicago and sell it
in New York?'' asks Tedlow.
</P>
<P>
   The new economy also gave rise to the first truly national
brands, companies like Coca-Cola and Johnson &AMP; Johnson. For the
first time, corporations could reach a national audience with a
product and a message.
</P>
<P>
   Substitute Amazon.com and EBay for Coke and Johnson &AMP; Johnson,
and you may begin to understand what is happening today, Tedlow
suggests. ``If you want to say the Internet is a transformation
that echoes to some degree the earlier transformation you could
make that parallel,'' says Tedlow.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan also has been thinking about the late 19th
century lately. In his May 6 speech, in which he mused about the
impact of computer technology on the American economy, Greenspan
said, ``Technological change was truly awesome around the turn of
the century. In a very short number of years the world witnessed an
astounding list of new creations: electric power and light, radios,
phonographs, telephones, motion pictures, X-rays, and motor
vehicles, just to begin the list.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next breath, Greenspan concluded that the breakthroughs
of today, while impressive, probably are not as dramatic as those
of the previous century. We may well have a new economy, Greenspan
seems to say, but that doesn't mean we can grow at a breakneck pace
without triggering inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Allyn, too, found some reasons for caution after her tour
through the history books. She points out that the late 19th was a
time of both great growth and great volatility. The good times were
regularly punctuated by panics. There was a strong political
backlash against unregulated markets by those left behind. In the
last century the injured parties were farmers; today they might be
people whose jobs are lost to technology or to competitors in the
Third World.
</P>
<P>
   And there is always the problem of debt. In periods of low
inflation or deflation, says Allyn, debt that looks cheap can prove
very difficult to pay back.
</P>
<P>
   So is history about to repeat itself? Are we in the early stages
of productivity-driven boom that will last for decades? Is the
computer as important as the railroad or electricity?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows. The truth is that when you are in a period of rapid
change it is hard to know whether you are in the middle of a
revolution or merely an evolution. We may have to wait another
century to figure out which one this is.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
