<HEADER>
A1605 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      05-18 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE HUNGRY OCEAN &QL; 
 &UR; Linda Greenlaw (Hyperion, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   Linda Greenlaw's well-worn copy of Sebastian Junger's book,
``The Perfect Storm,'' falls open automatically to Page 30. That's
where Junger describes Greenlaw in terms only a commercial
fisherman could love: ``Not only is (she) one of the only women in
the business, she's one of the best captains, period, on the entire
East Coast,'' he writes. ``Year after year, trip after trip, she
makes more money than almost anyone else.'' That money, which she
brings in catching swordfish as captain of the Hannah Boden out of
Gloucester, Mass., is a source of enormous pride to Greenlaw. She
has been going to sea for 18 years now and has worked hard, in the
company of some interesting men. ``If they weren't colorful before
we left dock,'' she says, ``they surely were when we returned.''
She has never encountered any problems because she is a woman _
maybe she's thick-skinned, she says, ``or just too damn busy
working to worry about what others might think of me.'' ``The
Perfect Storm'' brought Greenlaw much attention (the Hannah Boden
was the sister ship of Junger's subject, the ``Andrea Gail,'' which
sank with six men in a terrible storm at sea in 1991). It also
brought her the opportunity to write this book, in which she tells
the story of a typicah swordfishing trip from start to finish. The
language is salty, the men are colorful and the stories are
terrific. Sadly, she ends with the death of Bob Brown, the
irascible perfectionist who owned both the ``Hannah Boden'' and the
``Andrea Gail,'' for whom Greenlaw felt admiration and affection. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE AMERICAN CENTURY: ART &AMP; CULTURE 1900-1950 &QL; 
 &UR; Barbara Haskell (Norton, $60)
</P>
<P>
   It seems we will never finish scrutinizing and defining the
closing century. Now, the Whitney Museum of American Art is at bat
and swinging for the high seats. This is the first of two volumes
accompanying the museum's nine-month exhibit devoted to America's
evolution over the past 100 years into an artistic and cultural
force. Although the exhibit itself has drawn some sniping, the book
is a visual treat _ the abundance of wonderful things to look at
takes the edge off the bravado of the title (Americans might just
decide that it isn't such a stretch after all). Haskell's text is
stodgy by comparison, but bolstered by a series of livelier
mini-essays by experts in music, dance, theater, literature and
film. All of this is presented in four chapters: ``America in the
Age of Confidence: 1900-1919,'' ``Jazz Age America: 1920-1929,''
``America in Crisis: 1930-1939'' and ``War and its Aftermath:
1940-1949.'' The companion volume, ``The American Century: Art &AMP;
Culture 1950-2000'' by Lisa Phillips, will be published in
October. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE COMPLETE ANGLER: A CONNECTICUT YANKEE FOLLOWS IN THE FOOTSTEPS
OF WALTON &QL; 
 &UR; James Prosek (HarperCollins, $30)
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't Prosek's first idea. He had tried repeatedly to
persuade Yale University to give him a traveling fellowship,
proposing, among other things, that he fish the headwaters of the
Tigris River in eastern Turkey, the site of Eden in Milton's
``Paradise Lost.'' ``I'd told the judges on the committee that I
thought I would glean some great wisdom from catching trout that
were descendants of those which had witnessed man's fall from
Paradise,'' he says. ``They didn't bite.'' So, he tried again. He
said he would fish in the footsteps of Izaak Walton, the gentle
Englishman who in 1653 wrote ``The Compleat Angle''r; behind the
Bible and the works of Shakespeare, it is the most reprinted book
in the English language, with more than 400 editions produced in
300 years. Prosek told the committee that Walton's words moved him,
that the book took the art of angling to a higher level. He lied;
at that point, he hadn't read it. But after the committee gave him
his fellowship, he picked up ``The Compleat Angler,'' and soon he
believed his lie. ``Fishing is my religion and the trout stream is
my temple,'' Prosek writes, we assume with a straight face. ``Izaak
Walton was the angler's Messiah, and I was prepared to go on this
pilgrimage to England and meet the people who were connected with
Walton's ideals.'' This book is the story of his trip. It's mostly
text with a few (not nearly enough) of Prosek's watercolors
sprinkled throughout. Those of you who follow these things will
recognize him as the author of 1996's ``Trout: An Illustrated
History,'' which was published when he was not yet 20. Now 23, he
is still fishing and still lobbying for fellowships. For his next
book, he is circling the globe, fishing along the 41st parallel,
the approximate latitude of his Connecticut home. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; A WALK IN THE WOODS &QL; 
 &UR; Bill Bryson (Broadway, $13)
</P>
<P>
   At long last, a trade paperback edition of Bryson's hilarious
account of hiking the Appalachian Trail with his long-suffering and
out-of-shape friend, Stephen Katz. Bryson's motives in undertaking
the hike were admirable. He wanted to become fit after years of
wattlesome sloth. He wanted to learn survival skills, to feel like
an equal among men with camouflage pants and Bowie knives. He
wanted to be like Daniel Boone, who, Bryson knew, not only wrestled
bears but dated their sisters. Then, he hit the trail and started
backpedaling fast. Here he alternates chapters that contain actual
information about the Appalachian Trail with very funny chapters
about his misadventures in the company of the vulgar but endearing
Katz. It's a delightful book _ if you missed it in hardcover, now's
your chance. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Reach correspondent Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson &LR; worldnet.att.net) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
