<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1611 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-PREQUELS-BOS &LR;      05-18 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PREQUELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER `STAR WARS,' PREQUELS SURE TO BE A MENACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Lucas did not invent the prequel, although ``Star Wars:
Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace'' may turn out to be Hollywood's
first billion-dollar back story.
</P>
<P>
   Larry McMurtry's ``Lonesome Dove'' _ Pulitzer-winning novel and
Emmy-winning miniseries _ spawned both a prequel (``Dead Man's
Walk'') and a sequel (``Streets of Laredo''). Director David Lynch
time-tripped backwards from ``Twin Peaks,'' a TV series few viewers
could fathom, to ``Twin Peaks: Fire Walk With Me,'' a
preamble-ulatory movie few could stomach.
</P>
<P>
   The libretto to Wagner's operatic ``Ring'' cycle was composed in
reverse chronological order, one trick even Lucas hasn't attempted.
``The Flintstones'' movie, dreadful as it was, is getting prequeled
right now _ for reasons only its producers know. Even modern
classics like ``Casablanca'' and ``Gone With the Wind,'' once
thought to be perfect as is, have undergone the by-now requisite
prequel/sequel expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Will ``Phantom Menace'' be the last word in first installments?
Don't bet on it. And don't be surprised to see these in
development, either:
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Puberty'': A prologue to ``Shakespeare in
Love,'' this romantic comedy chronicles the budding Bard's ``lost''
years at Stratford Grammar School. Will (James Van Der Beek) wakes
one morning to find his hormones raging and his teenage fancy
turning to thoughts of love. Mocked by his schoolmates (Casey
Affleck, Josh Brolin) for preferring sonnet writing to squirrel
hunting, Will moons and sulks while passing syrupy notes to comely
classmate Anne Hathway (Sarah Michelle Gellar), who is instantly
smitten. The two agree to do a senior biology project together.
Alas, the experiment gets out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, disapproving father Richard Hathway (Brian Dennehy)
dismisses young Will as a ``noxious dweeb'' until he catches the
young couple in love's embrace and challenges Will to a duel,
wherepon young Shakespeare's consummate swordsmanship wins over
both father and daughter. With Anne suddenly pregnant, Will
renounces medical college for a life in the theater. `` 'Tis my
destiny, love,'' he explains on his way out the door.
</P>
<P>
   James Cameron directs from a script by Joe Eszterhas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secedin'!'': Broadway ticket-holders are said to be already
lining up for next season's rumored smash musical, a toe-tapping
tribute to states' rights and the anti-abolitionist movement.
</P>
<P>
   See Massachusetts senator Charles Sumner (Martin Short) caned
into unconsciousness on the Senate floor to a rousing chorus of
``(He's a) Sneaking, Sinuous, Snakelike Poltroon.'' See Abraham
Lincoln (Matthew Broderick) debate Stephen A. Douglas (Nathan Lane)
while Douglas sings the haunting tune ``Abe, You're Just a House
Divided Against Yourself.'' You don't know the Dred Scott decision
until you've sampled the ska version!
</P>
<P>
   With cameo appearances by Susan B. Anthony (k.d. lang), John
Brown (Willie Nelson), and President James Buchanan (Kris
Kristofferson).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Alto-Sopranos'': A ground-breaking HBO series about a
young New Jersey housewife named Livia (Christina Ricci) struggling
to raise three headstrong teenagers (Joseph Gordon-Levitt, Kieran
Culkin, Matthew Perry) while her husband (Edward Norton) and
father-in-law (Roberto Benigni) read a bunch of Mario Puzo novels
and, confusing them with the collected works of Leo Buscaglia, gun
down everyone in the neighborhood who isn't as ``well-adjusted'' as
they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mondays Avoiding Morrie'': Memoirs of a Brandeis University
student who spends the autumn of 1975 _ his sophomore year _ in
Fenway Park, having convinced a gullible sociology professor that
he's conducting a field study of crowd behavior in the right-field
bleachers. The professor grows suspicious when the Red Sox mount a
spirited drive for the American League pennant while the student
fails to complete a single class assignment, instead leaving
mustard-smeared game summaries in his teacher's mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I really think, like, life is kinda like, you know,
baseball,'' the student observes during one awkward office visit.
``Yeah?'' the professor replies. ``And yours is looking like a
three-hit shutout, kid.'' Forward by Doris Kearns Goodwin,
afterward by Bill (Spaceman) Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Know What You Did Spring Break'': A bunch of carefree
college students (Ewan McGregor, Jennifer Love Hewitt, Freddy
Prinze Jr., Taye Diggs, Neve Campbell, Keri Russell, Reese
Witherspoon) go to Daytona Beach for spring vacation, drink a lot
of beer, smoke a little dope, go skinny dipping, borrow a
speedboat, accidently run over an old fisherman (Marlon Brando),
sink his skiff, drink some more beer, wrap the body in oilskin,
smoke more dope, stash the body in an abandoned lighthouse, walk
down to the beach, take their clothes off, go skinny-dipping by
moonlight, fly home, return to their dorm rooms, unpack, undress,
take long, hot showers, look out the window, notice it's raining,
decide to take a walk after dark anyway, encounter a menacing
stranger wearing an oilskin slicker, freak out, call each other on
their cell phones, agree to meet for sushi, swear each other to
everlasting silence, exchange nervous glances as the sushi chef
slices up a triple order of tekka maki, drink some more beer, swear
once more not to breathe a word about the boating accident to
anyone, and plan a carefree summer working as lighthouse keepers
along the Maine coast.
</P>
<P>
   Elia Kazan directs from a script by Tom Stoppard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1351EDT &QL; 
