<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1613 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDDER-LESBIANS-BOS &LR;      05-18 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDDER-LESBIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME LESBIANS FEEL LEFT OUT OF THEIR `HOME TOWN' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHAMPTON, Mass. _ In the opening of ``Home Town,'' author
Tracy Kidder, perched atop Mount Holyoke, gazes out over
Northampton, the subject of his latest nonfiction book:
</P>
<P>
   ``From the summit . . . the town seems entirely coherent,
self-contained, a place where a person might live a whole life and
consider it complete,'' he writes. ``The town below fits in the
palm of your hand. Shake it and it snows.''
</P>
<P>
   If this suggests to readers that Kidder will be describing the
key parts of this community and what makes it distinctive, then
they probably will be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Kidder's ``Home Town'' is peopled by remarkable and compelling
characters, residents said, but it isn't the Northampton they know.
They were particularly surprised by his slight discussion of the
the lesbian community, which is so prominent some have dubbed the
city ``Lesbianville.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His book doesn't reflect the everyday experience of most
people who live here,'' said Julie Pokela, a lesbian business
leader and former head of the Chamber of Commerce. ``It was more a
book about Tommy O'Connor than about Northampton.''
</P>
<P>
   Shake Kidder's book and it goes to the police.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor is a gentle, street-savvy cop whose humane dealings
with the town's underbelly form the spine of Kidder's book. Other
central figures include Alan Scheinman, a lawyer with an
obsessive-compulsive disorder; Laura Baumeister, a single mother on
welfare trying to get through Smith College; and Judge Michael
Ryan, a compassionate local judge.
</P>
<P>
   Defending his choice of characters, Kidder, who lives in
Williamsburg, explained, ``I didn't set out to do sociology or
political science. I tell the stories of people I found
interesting, people whose lives intersect with the town in
meaningful ways. I couldn't write about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   At Beyond Words bookstore, where Kidder's book was selling
``about 10 times faster than a normal best-seller,'' according to
co-owner Jeff Krauth, some readers feel slighted.
</P>
<P>
   Krauth noted that Kidder largely omits discussion of the town's
arts community (rated No. 1 in the United States in John Villani's
1998 book, ``The 100 Best Small Art Towns in America''); its
vibrant music scene; the unusually large number of professionals
devoted to holistic health and spiritual development; all the
mom-and-pop (or mom-and-mom) stores with distinctive personalities,
and more.
</P>
<P>
   But most surprising of all was the absence of a single openly
homosexual character in the book, although Kidder mentions unnamed
lesbians several times in passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest gap,'' said Sunia Hood, owner of Taxi's Dog
Bakery. ``The lesbians are hugely important in making Northampton
what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no formal count has been taken, Mayor Mary Ford
estimated that about 4,500 self-identified lesbians live in this
town of 29,000, or about one in every seven residents. Including
the surrounding area, she said the lesbian population probably
amounts to 10,000 _ an estimate accepted by several lesbian
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The influence of this female energy is visible everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Three city councilors, including its president, a local judge
and a former head of the Chamber of Commerce all are openly
lesbian. Staff at the local Unitarian church say about one-third of
its weddings are commitment ceremonies for lesbians, and the local
paper, The Daily Hampshire Gazette, regularly prints announcements
of these unions.
</P>
<P>
   Northampton has a 90-member Lesbian and Gay Business Guild, a
lesbian softball league with 15 teams, an annual lesbian parade, a
lesbian calendar of events, a bookstore that sells only books by
women, and dozens of lesbian support groups.
</P>
<P>
   A special business card offering 10 to 20 percent discounts for
lesbians and their supporters is in the offing. One phone card on
sale and advertisements in lesbian newsletters proudly proclaim
that this is ``Lesbianville, U.S.A.''
</P>
<P>
   What is most remarkable about the large lesbian presence, some
locals said, is how well it has been accepted politically,
economically and socially.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can pretty much walk the streets without being harrassed,''
said Aimee Ross, a self-described ``bearded lady'' with 27 rings
and other adornments piercing various parts of her anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Ford stressed that the fault lines in town don't break in
terms of sexual preference. ``The gay folks have never put forward
a single-issue agenda or tried to be the dominant group,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, she claimed, the typical ``we-they'' hostilities
that plague many other small towns hardly exist here.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he didn't write more about Northampton's lesbian
population, Kidder said that he didn't find anyone who was willing
to open up her life to him, although he added that he didn't try
hard to find someone. Also, he said, it ``seemed trite, or stupid,
to define someone in terms of their sexuality. I thought it wasn't
an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Some lesbians agreed, breathing a sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tired of all the public focus on our sex lives,'' said
Robyn Camarata, a volunteer at a lesbian and gay gift shop called
Pride and Joy. ``We're strong enough on our own not to need every
book that comes along to mention us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the ultimate goal of the whole movement _ not to be an
issue,'' said Jane, co-owner of an all-women's bed-and-breakfast,
who asked that her last name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   But others said the way lesbians have melted into the town is so
unusual that it deserves serious literary attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other gay enclaves, but there's no place I know
where the gay population is so integrated into the community,''
Pokela said.
</P>
<P>
   She attributed this to the conjunction of several developments
in the past 25 years: the presence of an open-minded population at
Smith and the four other colleges nearby; the growth of the gay
rights movement; deinstitutionalization of the state's mental
health wards, creating a range of human-service jobs; and the size
of Northampton, which discouraged segregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The town is too small and the lesbian population is too big to
have ghettos,'' Pokela said.
</P>
<P>
   Mulling this over, Kidder concluded, ``If there's a fault in the
book, it's that I didn't convey clearly enough how remarkable it is
that Northampton is on the way to being a place where (being
homosexual) doesn't matter any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the moral of the story, said Mayor Ford, ``is that Tracy
should write more books. Or other people should write a book about
the lesbian community here.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now, at least, most of Kidder's readers said they are
willing to forgive him his omissions. In this town where
intellectual inquiry and free-spiritedness are celebrated, many
grant an artist the license to paint the portrait he sees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his book. He gets to write about whatever interests
him,'' said Clare Higgins, the city council president, who is
openly gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much that is left out _ but that's the nature of
trying to capture what you can't really capture,'' said Carol
Edelstein, a poet and social worker.
</P>
<P>
   But what Kidder tried to do, he did tenderly and well, she and
others said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's writing in a warm and extremely humane, poetic way about
people for whom Northampton was a community before it became a hot
spot for artists and gays and people who like fancy restaurants,''
said Robert MacLachlan, a retired psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   Since the book appeared in bookstores in mid-April, it has
sparked discussion all over town about the kind of place
Northampton is, how it sees its identity.
</P>
<P>
   When Kidder appeared for a reading at the Broadside Bookshop,
450 people turned out to hear him. The conversations about ``Home
Town'' are lively but not irate, and no protests are expected by
those who feel overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about why lesbians aren't angry about being left out of
Kidder's book, Higgins pointed to the tolerant spirit that has made
Northampton what it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we all get along so well out here,'' she quipped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
