 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ The Tolbonens sent their only son,
and the family's only breadwinner, off to war in Chechnya, and he
died there. So they sued the government. Now a high court says they
cannot recoup damages for their loss. By David Filipov. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-PARTY (Panama City) _ Like Panama itself, wedged between
the world's two largest oceans, plans for the ceremony marking the
transfer of the Panama Canal are being squeezed _ this time, by
bigger end-of-year events: the millennium celebration and the Y2K
bug. By Richard Chacon. 760 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-QUAYLE (Concord, N.H.) _ John Sununu thinks Dan Quayle
``is one of the smartest politicans out there.'' Quayle thinks
Sununu was fired as White House chief of staff because others were
``trying to do him in.'' They've been friends since their White
House days, and now the former New Hampshire governor is hoping to
help Quayle as he helped George Bush in 1988. By Jill Zuckman. 1390
words.
</P>
<P>
   KIDDER-LESBIANS (Northampton, Mass.) _ In his new book, ``Home
Town,'' author Tracy Kidder explores Northampton, which he
describes as ``a perfect little kingdom.'' But in Kidder's
Northampton, certain groups are all but invisible, especially the
lesbian community. By Judith Gaines. 1460 words. (a and e coding)
</P>
<P>
   PIANO-PRODIGY (Acton, Mass.) _ Bronika Kushkuley has already cut
her own CD. Kushkuley is a child prodigy, an 11-year-old performer
who has already played Carnegie Hall and has international
competitions from Italy to Washington. By Thomas Farragher. 1750
words. (a and e coding) PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Lamoni, Iowa) _ In the first of several
orations that will sketch a post-Bill Clinton America, Al Gore's
speech to Graceland College exudes what might be called
continuity-plus. By Thomas Oliphant.
</P>
<P>
   MCGRORY-COLUMN (Boston) _ These are not good days for the vice
president of the United States, not good days at all. By Brian
McGrory.
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE-COLUMN (Undated) -- Storm has been used literally and
figuratively, with or without a direct object, to suit the purposes
of each century's rhetoric. By Jan Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-PHANTOM (Undated) _ Is ``The Phantom Menace'' sufficiently
of a piece with the first three films to make it worth seeing? Yes,
but not by much. By Jay Carr. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-PREQUELS (Undated) _ ``Phantom Menace'' may turn out to
be Hollywood's first billion-dollar back story. By Joseph P. Kahn.
970 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (t) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NEGRO (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Outdated and freighted with
ill connotations, ``Negro'' can be used only deliberately. Yet
everything about it is right for the Negro Leagues Baseball Museum.
By Thomas C. Palmer Jr. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CRUISE (Undated) -- Looking for a family vacation that's
guaranteed to be enjoyed by all ages? Then take a cruise. By Jerry
Morris. 1400 words.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN &UR;  &LR; (Undated) _ Here's a suite idea for your next
Orlando visit: Holiday Inns is opening its first all-suite hotel
there in July. By Jerry Morris.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NOTES (Undated) _ Admit it. We'd all like to be James
Bond. Well now you can be Bond . . . for a little while anyway. By
Richard Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ To some, the world of the late
20th century looks a lot like the world of the late 19th century.
Are they right? And what does it mean for investors and the rest of
us? By Steven Syre and Charles Stein.
</P>
<P>
   WARSH-COLUMN (Undated) _ From a distance, the forum on Asian
Pacific Economic Cooperation looked like the good old days. But not
through the eyes of the representatives of the world's second
largest economy. By David Warsh.
</P>
