<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1617 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIANO-PRODIGY-ART-BOS     05-18 1722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIANO-PRODIGY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 11, SHE'S HARD AT PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACTON, Mass. _ Small and boxy, the metronome that ticks away
atop the rebuilt Steinway in Bronika Kushkuley's living room does
immeasurably more than mark precise time for Haydn's ``E Minor
Sonata.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the critical clock of her young life, rhythmically
defining sharp segments of a tightly disciplined world.
</P>
<P>
   It signals when she must train as the acclaimed concert pianist
whose work already has carried her twice to Carnegie Hall. Its
silence means she can be just a kid _ a bright-eyed girl chasing
her chubby puppy across a sun-drenched lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Kushkuley is a prodigy, an 11-year-old performer who has cut a
self-titled CD, is featured on her own Web page, has performed
across Europe, and triumphed at international competitions from
Washington to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Her gift is both a blessing and a challenge. It demands a
delicate balance to ensure that her music is nurtured but does not
climb to a crescendo that overwhelms other telling tones that echo
in any preteen's world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you play the piano all day, I don't think that's a very
good idea,'' Kushkuley said last week, sitting beneath a cloudless
sky on the back steps of her parents' tri-level home here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want your music to express this day, or the springtime,
or the trees and stuff, if you don't go outside sometimes, you
can't really play that way,'' she said, ``because you won't have
the feel of it.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when some parents are under assault for paying too
little attention to the details of their children's lives,
Kushkuley's parents say they are taking care to avoid an opposing
offense common in the homes of overachievers: paying too much
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Bronika left her elementary school to concentrate on the piano,
but her parents say they are seeking to provide their daughter with
a childhood with a premium on normalcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not pushing,'' said Larissa Kushkuley, Bronika's mother.
``We're not trying to push her to make her a pianist at this age,
or to make her a concert pianist right now. We want her to get the
best education possible, which she needs. And then we'll just see
what she does.''
</P>
<P>
   What Bronika Kushkuley already has done is remarkable _
attaining a musical fluency that her Latvian-born parents scarcely
could have imagined when they immigrated to the United States in
1988, relieved to have escaped the oppression of their native land.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to raise our children without Soviet
brainwashing,'' said Larissa Kushkuley, who like her husband
Alexander, is a computer programmer.
</P>
<P>
   Lovers of classical music but not musicians themselves, the
Kushkuleys settled first in Burlington in a small apartment they
found with the help of Temple Shalom Emeth. Later, they moved to a
modest home on a quiet street here, where the television is almost
always dark and the bookshelves bear trophies topped by musical
notes and the classics of Homer and Steinbeck and Swift.
</P>
<P>
   Then, five years ago, the parents of three made a simple
decision that would rearrange their lives: They enrolled their
children in piano lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't think about great talent or anything,''
Larissa Kushkuley said.
</P>
<P>
   But after Bronika won the 1995 International Young Artists Piano
Competition in Washington, an after-school hobby intensified into a
full-time passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really gave us the idea that she really had to devote
more of her time to music,'' the pianist's mother said.
</P>
<P>
   That devotion has transported the Kushkuleys onto the unfamiliar
terrain of the talented _ a landscape where there are few clear
guideposts, many emotional land mines, and critics at every corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about this phenomenon that really bothers
most of us,'' said David Henry Feldman, a child development
professor at Tufts University who has studied child prodigies for
two decades. ``On the one hand we're admiring of it. On the other,
it gets to us. It makes us uneasy. It threatens us to some
degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Feldman said that common concerns about the loss of childhood or
the exploitation of youthful genius, while often on target, can
sometimes be misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talent changes everything,'' he said. ``We can't make them
into being just like us except for having this talent. It's just
not true. It's irresponsible. We celebrate diversity, but somehow
or another this kind of diversity we just can't grasp. It's just
different. It's like being in a different culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Winner, a psychology professor at Boston College and
author of ``Gifted Children: Myths and Realities,'' said unwilling
children pushed by their parents can emerge from the experience
sad, broken, and unable to pursue their talent into adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``But all the research shows that these kids are extremely
driven,'' Winner said. ``I call it the rage to master. You can't
tear them away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lay out all these cautions and dangers. But in some cases
it's not clear what should be done differently, because these kids
so desperately want to be spending their time focusing on their
domain of gift.''
</P>
<P>
   For up to five hours a day, that is precisely what Bronika
Kushkuley is deeply focused on, her bashful smile supplanted by a
serious resolve as her hands dance and fly across the keyboard, her
body swaying and leaning into the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think I have talent, but I don't think I'm great or
anything,'' she said. ``If you start thinking that you're a
prodigy, and you start saying, `Oh, I'm so good,' you'll start
playing worse.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't happened. Almost from the beginning, the music that
emerged when Bronika put her fingers to the piano keys was
something extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is unbelievably talented and deeply in love with the
music,'' said Julia Bernstein, an instructor at the New England
Conservatory, who has taught Kushkuley since she was 6 years old.
``I think she's one of the best of her age at least in the country,
but maybe the world, too. Other kids who have the same ability
don't have her discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   In the basement of Bernstein's home in Randolph, where Kushkuley
studies three times a week, student and teacher communicate with
each other in a lexicon of hand gestures, facial expressions,
clapping hands, snapping fingers, sung notes, and overt expressions
of displeasure or encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just loud, it's deep and serious,'' Bernstein tells
Kushkuley at one point. The student's worried visage melts into a
broad smile when Bernstein finally declares: ``Yes! Yes! Exactly!
Much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, over a cup of tea, the teacher explained: ``Everything I
blow to her, she just catches it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the solo recitals, far-flung competitions, CD recordings,
and international awards have not come without a price. The tempo
of the Kushkuley family's daily routine is kept by demands of piano
lessons for their three children, but most markedly by the rigors
of Bronika's training and a decision last year to shift her
education from the local elementary school to a home-schooling
regimen of mathematics, English, and social studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``She liked going to school,'' Larissa Kushkuley said. ``But she
really likes playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronika's connection to her old school now comes from stories
told by her 13-year-old sister, Sophie, and her 10-year-old
brother, Jacob, who she greets with a smile from her post at the
piano bench one midafternoon recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have enough time to play the piano as much as I
should play,'' Bronika explained later as her new dog Constance, a
fuzzy chow chow, played friskily at her feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a choice: Either play the piano really well or go to
school. And I decided to play the piano. I don't really miss it,
but sometimes I feel lonely. I liked that there were a lot of kids.
Like right now, I don't have a very big choice of friends.''
</P>
<P>
   But she quickly noted that an old school pal is a frequent
visitor and that she has developed a pen-pal friendship with
Francesca, a violinist she met at a festival in Germany last year.
When the piano is quiet, she's upstairs playing with her American
Girls doll Samantha, running, swimming, reading, or writing stories
and poems _ available to visitors of her Web page.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are actually thinking that we are led by her because we
never envisioned that we would home-school one of our kids,'' said
Larissa Kushkuley. ``It just somehow grew up and we don't want to
put barriers in her world. We're trying to help out and see how the
situation develops.''
</P>
<P>
   Specialists say there is no true barometer to measure whether
young talent will survive the almost unavoidable emotional strains
of adolescence and blossom into acclaim in adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because a kid is a star at the age of 11 doesn't mean
that they're going to continue to go that route,'' said Joseph
Thayer, dean of the Colburn School of Performing Arts in Los
Angeles, a distinguished school for young performers. ``Some
prodigies make it; some lose interest and do other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kushkuleys say they are preparing for either outcome, ready
to accept a career on stage or in front of a class as the teacher
of aspiring musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all our kids we don't make any distinctions about who is
better, who is worse,'' Larissa Kushkuley said. ``We don't do that.
If (Bronika) doesn't do her chores, she'd get punished. We try to
keep it as normal as possible. But people do like to hear her in
concert.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Bronika Kushkuley polishes her material for a May 22
benefit concert at Brandeis University, where she will share the
stage with renowned cellist-conductor Mstislav Rostropovich, she
said it's the music, not the acclaim, that drives her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go to some really major competitions and play my
best, but I really don't care if I win,'' the pianist said during a
break in practice sessions. ``It just doesn't matter. Because you
know (Russian-born pianist Vladimir) Horowitz? He didn't win a
single competition in his life. So, you see, it doesn't really
matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
