A1619 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-18 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM-WATCH ALL CLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It really ought to have been a dark and stormy night when Bill
Feinberg of Sharon wrote, last December, to ask for help with a
disagreement over a weather word. In fact, it was still so pleasant
that the parka retailers and skiers were wringing their hands, but
Feinberg had bad weather on his mind nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   The source of his unease was storm as a verb _ a verb he thought
should properly take a direct object, as in ``They stormed the
castle.'' His wife, though, dissented: ``She uses it in the context
such as, `It's going to storm today,' '' he wrote. ``I think this
is not quite right.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, into each marriage some rain must fall. This time it's
falling on Bill, whose strictures on the use of storm have no
historical support: One of our most ancient and adaptable verbs,
storm has been used both literally and figuratively, either with or
without a direct object, to suit the purposes of each century's
rhetoric. ``The sea stormeth'' is normal in 1564, according the the
Oxford English Dictionary; three centuries later, Henry Ward
Beecher writes of ``men who are stormed like the ocean,'' meaning
roiled, disturbed. Even the military sense of the word doesn't
demand an object: Browning has one (``You know, we French stormed
Ratisbon''), but Tennyson does without (``All the Norman foot/Are
storming up the hill''). And any of us might storm out of the room
if a language dispute got too hot.
</P>
<P>
   There is one possible excuse, though, for thinking of it's
storming as not quite proper. That ``impersonal'' construction,
standard from the 16th through the 19th century, is now much less
common in England than in America; perhaps Feinberg is watching too
much British television for the good of his marriage. But debates
over storm should not be allowed to cloud the happiness of American
households.
</P>
<P>
   Much worse, both in life and in language, is tornado _ a word
our ancestors wrenched out of Spanish and revised into a form they
thought was more logical.
</P>
<P>
   When the word was borrowed for English, in the mid-1500s, it was
ternado _ a seafarer's name for a violent thunderstorm with winds
gusting from several directions. Ternado, the OED editors say, was
already probably a mistake _ a ``bad adaptation'' or a misspelling
_ of tronada, Spanish for thunderstorm. And once this twist had
been applied, the word looked as if it might be derived from
tornar, Spanish for ``to turn.'' Thus, sucked along by the false
etymology, the sense of whirling winds grew stronger as the
centuries passed.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in America, we think of tornadoes exclusively as the
funnel-cloud-forming storms that wreak such destruction in the
South and Midwest. We even emphasize their spiral form by calling
them twisters, a US coinage dating from the late 19th century. All
this from a mistranslation of an ordinary 16th-century
thunderstorm: Tornado's violent past makes the history of storm
seem smooth sailing indeed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Write or e-mail Jan Freeman at The Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA
02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a hometown and
phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1622 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-18 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S WELL-LETTERED CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAMONI, Iowa -- In a flag-showing bus tour of a part of Iowa
that Democrats traditionally ignore _ the rural South _ Vice
President Al Gore delivered a semi-important speech about education
at a small college commencement here over the weekend. It gives us
a peek at his nascent presidential campaign that is stronger _
politically and conceptually _ than most Washington sharpies give
it credit for being.
</P>
<P>
   In the first of several orations that will sketch a post-Bill
Clinton America, Gore's speech to Graceland College exuded what
might be called continuity-plus.
</P>
<P>
   As he begins to blend substance with his politics, Gore is
anything but the George H. W. Bush of 1987 who mumbled ``kinder and
gentler'' as a code for something different than Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   He runs in unabashed pride for the Clinton-Gore record and makes
suggestions about the future that are natural extensions of Clinton
policy. Indeed, he has in part drawn on the brainpower of Secretary
Bill Riley's Education Department for his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   One of them involves saving for college, something that is very
hard for middle-income families to do under current tax laws.
</P>
<P>
   The idea Gore outlined here _ and it is a potential whopper _ is
that just as there is now a mechanism for employers to help
employees save for retirement, that same magic should help
accumulate money for job-training, additional education or a kid's
college tuition. With tax-free accumulation and other
encouragements, Gore proposes a major new savings instrument _ a
401(j).
</P>
<P>
   As an indication of how thoroughly work is done in Gore's world
_ possibly to the point of absurdity _ most people know that the
employer-employee retirement plan is called a 401(k). Logic would
indicate that a new wrinkle in the tax code for education savings
would get the next letter: (l).
</P>
<P>
   But Gore instead chose the letter ``j'' for his program.
</P>
<P>
   Now why would he do that? Since practically nothing is done in
this game anymore without a bunch of meetings and memos, it turns
out there is a reason: Because ``j'' and ``k'' rhyme, the Gore
reasoning was that using the ``j'' would make people think of the
popular retirement funds and thus make the new accounts more
attractive.
</P>
<P>
   To an ignorant generalist like me, every instinct says, ``Gimme
a break.''
</P>
<P>
   But upon reflection, it's hard not to imagine that Gore may have
a point even on this tiny detail, or worse that Clinton-Gore
pollster Mark Penn may have the research to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Details and vision clash on occasion in Gore's world. The fact
that he may be right on his details, however, shouldn't obscure the
fact that he doesn't always play the violin enough. What he talked
about in his speech would transform the family economics of
education, and yet if anything he undersold it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was much more clear and expansive about the second element
of his proposal to expand savings incentives for education. This
would take savings programs now in more than 30 states and make the
system national.
</P>
<P>
   These programs allow families to begin putting money aside after
a child's birth that accumulates tax-free for use in-state. If the
rest of the states had incentives to join, the money saved would be
available for higher education in any participating state _ a major
change for the better.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz in Washington and New York may be concerns about Gore's
headquarters staff and impolitic expressions of worry by the
president and Mrs. Clinton. But all that junk was inaudible out
here, where Gore did major business with the region's Democratic
activists as his motorcade traced a line from well south of Des
Moines east to Burlington on the Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   In tow, significantly, was the area's increasingly safe
Democratic congressman from the conservative 3rd District, Len
Boswell, who decided to back Gore even before his good buddy,
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt from neighboring Missouri, decided
not to run.
</P>
<P>
   The well-attended tour got another boost from Iowa's first
Democratic governor in 30 years, Tom Vilsack, at whose
white-shingled home in Mt. Pleasant Gore paid a courtesy call. With
a large crowd outside on Main Street, the new and officially
neutral governor chose to be gushy, not reticent, in his praise,
claiming, ``We have been working off the playbook Al Gore
essentially developed.''
</P>
<P>
   And all this was happening out here on a weekend when Gore
operatives in Massachusetts sucker-punched an overeager, not-ready
Bill Bradley operation in a straw poll at the state party's
convention.
</P>
<P>
   This is a campaign that is likely to unfold on parallel tracks
for some time _ Gore on his, Bradley on his. And its shape cannot
be known until Bradley shows more of himself and his ideas than he
has.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore is no slouch in either the ideas or the political
mechanics departments. His advantage could not be more real.
</P>
<P>
   And it will get bigger if he focuses more on the forest of
continuity-plus and less on little trees like the letter ``j.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
