<HEADLINE>
HOW SUIT _ AND REASONABLE _ IT IS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a suite idea for your next Orlando visit.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Inns is opening its first all-suite hotel here in July.
While it's called the Holiday Inn Family Suites Resort Lake Buena
Vista, it has something for everyone, from business travelers to
romantics. Families, though, will love this place not only for its
value but for its features.
</P>
<P>
   Each suite offers three rooms plus a large, full bath. Families
will be attracted especially to the Kidsuites, which offer two
separate bedrooms and a parlor. One bedroom is designed for kids
with bunk beds and a pull-out bed plus a 20-inch TV, a VCR, a
Nintendo 64, and more. The other room, with a king-sized bed, is
for the adults. In addition the parlor area comes with a pullout
sofa, a 25-inch TV, a kitchenette with a microwave, a refrigerator,
a coffee maker, an iron, a safe, a rocking chair, a game table, and
more. If that's not enough, the suites come with a full breakfast
for every member of the family. And the best part is that prices
begin at $129 a night, with a special introductory rate of $119.
</P>
<P>
   Outside there's a large play area and pool, restaurants, and
shops, plus there's complimentary transportation to Disney World
just a mile away. There's also a Parents' Night Out program
allowing parents to take in some nightime fun (complimentary pagers
are provided to keep in touch with the young set).
</P>
<P>
   OK, so how do business people and romantics find happiness among
the kids? Easy. The 800-suite inn offers a separate area with three
other suite designs: SweetHeart, Cinemasuites, Fitness, and
Business. Similar in design to the family suites, these suites
replace the kids' room with a heart-shaped whirlpool tub, mood
lighting, and a 50-inch TV; or a separate theater room with a
60-inch TV and surround sound, along with dual rocker recliners.
Five suites will feature a workout room with a cycle and other
equipment plus a TV and VCR for workout tapes; and five suites will
offer a conference room with a work station and modem line.
</P>
<P>
   The resort also offers ``classic'' two-bedroom suites for
couples traveling together or older children, as well as
residential suites with full kitchens for those staying in the area
longer (some connect with Kidsuites for larger family gatherings).
</P>
<P>
   For information or reservations, call toll-free 877-387-5437 or
visit www.hifamilysuites.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where will you be . . .
</P>
<P>
   . . . May 22? That's Chester on Track day. This western
Massachusetts town will celebrate its past as a major rail center
with a display of a state-of-the-art locomotive, along with
``speeder'' rail rides. Also on view will be railroad memorabilia
in the 1840 railroad station, a blacksmith demonstration, music,
food, and a reproduction of the 1893 Duryea auto, the first
commercially successful American car built in Springfield. Chester
was the birthplace of the abrasives industry and there will be
tours of the former facilities. Antiques, classic autos, and crafts
complete the 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. day.
</P>
<P>
   Also on May 22, Downsville, N.Y., will holds its first annual
Covered Bridge Festival. The day marks the reopening of the
Downsville Covered Bridge, the longest in New York. For
information, call 888-209-1543.
</P>
<P>
   On May 29, Old Sturbridge Village will hold a Muskets and
Militia Day from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. The sights and sounds of a
re-created early American militia day will be held in this classic
1830s New England village.
</P>
<P>
   . . . On June 19? That's the 31th annual San Francisco
Juneteenth Festival, also known as the National Freedom Day, the
oldest celebration of freedom from slavery by African Americans.
June 19, 1865, was the day that the message of freedom reached
black people in Texas. The day is now celebrated in many states.
San Francisco has expanded the celebration, which includes parades,
a carnival, a film festival, a rodeo, and more to three days June
18-June 20. For information, call 415-391-2001.
</P>
<P>
   . . . On June 20? That's the day for the 2,000th performance of
Le Grand David, the longest running resident stage magic
production/ show in the world, according to the Guinness Book of
World Records. ``Le Grand David'' runs every Sunday through Aug. 1
at the Cabot St. Cinema Theatre in Bevery (about an hour from
Boston on the North Shore). The live show runs 2 1/4 hours and
features a cast of 30 performing classic magic. For tickets, call
978-927-3677.
</P>
<P>
   On July 1 the first Scottish Parliament to have sat for 292
years opens for business. This milestone in the constitutional
history of the United Kingdom will meet in the 19th-century
Assembly Hall on the Royal Mile in Edinburgh, where the Church of
Scotland holds its annual meetings. In two years the parliament
will have a permanent home at Holyrood, a short distance away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Save money
</P>
<P>
   Wherever you go this summer, ask if there are any money-saving
coupon books. In San Diego, for example, there's a coupon book
called ``Sunny Money 1999 Super Savings'' with 100 offers good
through March 31, 2000. Discounts include admission to Sea World,
the San Diego Zoo, hotels, shopping, tours, and transportation. For
a copy, visit the International Visitor Center at 11 Horton Plaza,
call 619-236-1212, or write to the San Diego Convention and
Visitors Bureau, 401 B St., Suite 1400, Dept. 700C-99, San Diego,
CA 92101.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deal
</P>
<P>
   A nine-day independent tour of London, Paris, and Rome starts at
$1,209, including round-trip air fare from New York. The package
includes transportation on the Eurostar train from London to Paris,
and breakfasts. The package can be upgraded to superior class
hotels starting at $1,379 or first-class hotels starting at $1,749.
For details, call New Frontiers at 800-366-6387.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sellouts
</P>
<P>
   The Trolley Tours of Falmouth History, which sold out last year,
have been cited by the Massachusetts Governor's Conference of
Travel and Tourism as one of the state's 10 tourism success
stories. This year's tours, which began Wednesday, will operate on
alternating Saturdays (one tour will operate on June 11) into
December. Tickets are $10 for adults and $8 for children under 12
and include admission to the Julia Wood House museum. On June 12
the 220th commemoration of the Battle of Falmouth Harbor will be
reenacted. For information on the tours or the reenactment, call
508-548-8500 or 508-548-4857.
</P>
