<HEADLINE>
BAD MANNERS CALLING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Just as a colleague and I finished a spirited
discussion about ``runaway entitlement'' in our culture, I opened
the newspaper to find an ad for one of the worst expressions of
this nasty phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The ad, placed by a national telephone company, shows a young,
hip-looking man and woman sitting on a park bench. He stares
intently at the screen of a laptop computer; she blabs animatedly
into a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   A promotion for a contest that would award free cell phone and
Internet service, the ad said: ``It's not just about winning a year
of (the company's) communication. It's about feeling free to lose
yourself in conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what the world needs: more cell phone users who feel free
to lose themselves in conversation. Already we don't have enough?
Men and women with booming, screeching voices? Making anyone within
earshot privy to their every thought? They are omnipresent.
</P>
<P>
   They wreck meals in restaurants. They make hotel, theater and
office building lobbies sound like the floor of the New York Stock
Exchange when the Dow is tumbling. They shout in department stores
and boutiques, on street corners and escalators, on the steps of
churches and from the next seat on a public bus.
</P>
<P>
   Never, never, do they talk softly or briefly. If this is not the
freedom to lose yourself in a conversation, I don't know what
freedom is.
</P>
<P>
   The phone blabbers are the opposite of inhibited; they are in
the throes of runaway entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   Runaway entitlement is not new to our culture; cell phones are
just the latest conduit. In the old days it was known as ``bad
manners.''
</P>
<P>
   This was back when nice people, if they had to, would carry a
candy wrapper or soda can from San Francisco to Pasadena instead of
drop it on the sidewalk. This was when you didn't get cussed or
honked at for slowing down to parallel park.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting one's turn _ whatever the circumstances _ wasn't even
considered good manners. It was simply standard civilized behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I stand in line at the salad bar near my office, I
remember those years. A typical fast fresh-food establishment, the
eatery would never be mistaken for a place of genteel, leisurely
dining. Everybody in the joint is in some degree of hurry.
</P>
<P>
   But people in the throes of runaway entitlement are in the
biggest hurry of all.
</P>
<P>
   Like planes ready to launch from an aircraft carrier deck, they
rev their engines behind you, periodically nudging or bumping into
your elbow or hip. No matter your pace, it's not fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   Although I've yet to have a serving spoon actually pulled from
my hand, it's been close many times. As for someone reaching across
my outstretched hands for the sunflower seeds or bacon bits on down
the line, it's DE RIGUEUR.
</P>
<P>
   Do the bumps or reaches ever produce a ``pardon'' or ``excuse
me''? Need you ask?
</P>
<P>
   Then there are pedestrian crosswalks where runaway entitlement
is off the charts. Adult men and women _ mothers pushing their
precious cargo in baby strollers or holding the little tykes by the
hand _ arrogantly step off curbs without bothering to check
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the crosswalk, they saunter as if checking out the goods
at a village bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   Often (especially when they jaywalk) they shoot hateful looks at
the driver of the car they have halted.
</P>
<P>
   Always, I think: What sort of an example are you setting for
your treasured little offspring? Always, the same answer comes
back:
</P>
<P>
   (Bleep) you. I'm entitled.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
