<HEADLINE>
A SWEET CELEBRATION OF BASEBALL AND JAZZ 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ``Negro'' is such an authentic word. Outdated
and freighted with ill connotations, it can be used only
deliberately. Yet everything about it is right for the Negro
Leagues Baseball Museum that opened here in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As you enter the museum, without even realizing it, you must get
up on your toes to peer over a high wall to glimpse a majestic,
still, almost lifesize baseball infield, with statues of players in
place. You are denied even visual participation _ as black
Americans were denied the opportunity to join white Americans in
the all-American game until 1947.
</P>
<P>
   The authenticity of that museum, and of the Jazz Museum that
shares a new, $26 million publicly financed cultural center at 18th
and Vine, is in the richness of its exhibits, but as well in the
historical context that colors these facilities throughout.
</P>
<P>
   During segregation, this area was the heart of Kansas City's
minority community,
</P>
<P>
   Architects and designers and musicians and sports specialists
all participated in the creation of The Museums at 18th and Vine,
fulfilling a vision of the city's current and first black mayor,
Emanuel Cleaver. But the thick strain of history, of the
prohibitions and separations that today are being overcome but that
were essential to the creation of both jazz and to decades of
all-black baseball, make a visitor's experience not just
informative, not just fun, but almost essential.
</P>
<P>
   These two museums, linked by a small but well-selected exhibit
including a film of the history of the black community in the
Kansas City area, nearly remained only a dream. There was intense
opposition from some whites, and there was division within the
black population about what shape that project ``over there'' on
the east side of town should take.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Whiting, a former spokeswoman for Mayor Cleaver who until
recently handled public affairs for the quasi-government agency
that houses the museums, said even some in the mayor's own
political circle doubted. ``Don't be talking to me about 18th and
Vine,'' Whiting said she was told, only a few years ago. ``I've
been hearing it for years. It's never going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz Museum opened in September 1997 and last year
celebrated its anniversary, with Harry Belafonte, Danny Glover, Ray
Charles, George Benson, and others performing at the historic Gem
Theater nearby. Once Kansas City's only black movie house, it has
been turned into a 500-seat performing arts center as part of the
revitalization of the larger neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The Negro Leagues Baseball Museum opened a couple of months
later. Together, though they have seen a slower than predicted
start in numbers of visitors, the two museums present moving and
fascinating profiles of two vitally important pieces of cultural
black history, both national and locally.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz may not have been born in Kansas City, but it spent some
heavy adolescent years there, generating a Kansas City,
swing-style, big-bandish sound, like that extensively played in
Robert Altman's movie ``Kansas City.'' The movie was short on plot,
but the music was the real thing, and some of the sets and building
facades used in the production are still part of the attraction
here, half a block from the Jazz Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Negro Leagues Baseball was born in Kansas City, following years
of de facto segregated baseball that began after the Civil War. The
Negro National League originated in 1920 on a well-known local
street called The Paseo, a couple of blocks from the dignified
museum where it is now remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Black baseball grew to six leagues _ from New York to Houston,
from Milwaukee to Jacksonville _ in 30 cities, and lasted until
1960, a dozen years after Jackie Robinson broke the color barrier
with the Brooklyn Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt that I wasn't making the money the white players
made, or I wasn't as famous,'' Gene Benson of the Philadelphia
Stars once said. ``I just wanted to play baseball. I loved the
game. I'd have played for $100 a year, for a dollar. I'd have
played for nothing just to get out there on that grass, that dirt,
and play baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Room
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a rare jazz club in which you can't smoke. But that's the
rule at the Blue Room, by day a step-back-in-time feature of the
Jazz Museum, with display cases and a photo wall of jazz greats,
and by night a working jazz club.
</P>
<P>
   The original Blue Room was about a block away, in the Street
Hotel, where black folks stayed, not being welcome at the
Muehlebach Hotel or other fancy temporary residences in the city.
This reborn Blue Room is owned by the 18th &AMP; Vine Authority, a
quasi-independent city agency, so city rules are in effect.
Nightclub smoke would damage the artifacts too.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Room has done something no museum or any amount of
wishful thinking by city officials could do. It's brought people
back to this abandoned area at night. At a regular ``Blue Monday
Jam,'' Gerald Dunn played saxophone and hosted a session with a
four-piece house band, and locals who later on in the evening
summoned the courage to get up and play.
</P>
<P>
   The jazz is not improvisional or cutting-edge. It is
intentionally kept in the traditional, big-band vein that Kansas
City was known for. ``It's one of the things we're trying to keep
alive, but it's sprinkled with contemporary jazz,'' said Andre
Tyler, a former Stanford University and Tampa Bay Buccaneers
football player who manages the room. He married a woman from
Kansas City and now is here operating the club with Dave Winslow, a
local restaurant owner experienced in jazz and dinner clubs.
</P>
<P>
   On a wall among scores of portraits of those who played Kansas
City _ including Bessie Smith, Fats Waller, Art Tatum, Thelonious
Monk, John Coltrane, Dave Brubeck, Wes Montgomery, and Charles
Mingus _ is a stab at the definition of Kansas City Swing.
``Rhythm, drive and walking bass, combined with blues-based
instrumental riffs.'' It was ``cultivated by Bennie Moten and
Walter Page, popularized nationwide by Count Basie.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Room opened on Sept. 6, 1997, and in some ways it is
the most successful of the various pieces of revitalization going
on at 18th and Vine. There is music four nights a week, and on
Friday and Saturdays the 150-seat club routinely fills up, Tyler
said. About 40 people came on a Monday night, no cover charge. They
heard Lester Warner sing ``I Remember April,'' and a sit-in drummer
named Michael do ``Have You Met Miss Jones?'' and a talented
high-school senior named Logan Richards, who was soon heading off
to the University of North Texas to study music next year, play a
very professional sax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got over my nerves in the seventh grade,'' said Richards.
But most who step up on stage still haven't. Dunn, who books the
club as well as emcees, said Michael had ``been waiting since the
first set, if you can believe it. He's been twidling this thumbs
and rubbing his sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz Museum
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amid a neglected area that is the epitome of urban decay
populated disproportionately by black America stands a crisp, solid
new two-story building, heavy with neon and other eye-catching
artist's touches. Through a spacious oval lobby, past a souvenir
shop with delectable but expensive knicknacks, is the first museum
in America devoted to a wholly American form of music.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-minute movie almost succeeds at the impossible: defining
jazz. ``I don't have any special magic,'' says pianist Shirley
Horn. ``I sit there and play what I feel. Maybe that's a special
magic. I'm always trying to paint a picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, you meet a pleasurable multi-sensory experience.
Visually _ in colors, in shapes, in textures, in volume _ the Jazz
Museum the equivalent of the music it displays. There is something
of a ``Cabinet of Dr. Calgari'' effect in the angular shapes of the
exhibits, the panels. How very appropriate they are doesn't become
clear until near the end, when visitors pass a wall of the great
album covers of the jazz age. Miles Davis' ``Sketches of Spain'' on
Columbia Records, 1960; ``Moanin' Low,'' Torch Songs by Lena Horne
on Victor Records; ``Blossom Dearie'' on Verve.
</P>
<P>
   And the designers responsible for that distinctive jazzy look
that began in the 1940s and influenced Andy Warhol and others are
notable for their unfamiliar names: Robert Berenson's 1958 ``East
Coasting'' for Charles Mingus on Mercury; Herman Leonard's ``Dizzy
in Greece'' in 1957 for Dizzy Gillespie on Verve; David Stone
Martin's more than 250 covers, including ``The Lionel Hampton
Quartet'' in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Were it only for the objects _ the albums; the plastic saxophone
that Kansas City native Charlie ``Yardbird'' Parker used in ``The
Concert,'' May 1953 at Toronto's Massey Hall; or Ella Fitzgerald's
dress _ a visitor could do as with any other museum and choose a
fast or slow pace. Not here. Forget about rushing on as you
approach a music station, a loose-leaf set of plastic pages on a
small lectern, where you can put on headphones and choose No. 8,
Bix Biederbecke with Frankie Trumbauer and His Orchestra, doing
``Singin' the Blues ('Til My Daddy Comes Home)'' from 1927.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz Museum's central feature is its presentation of the
music. It is reverently quiet as a visitor walks through this
place, until one of the many sets of headphones is clasped on.
</P>
<P>
   Past the interactive displays devoted to each of the musical
instruments vital to jazz, there is a stop that would challenge
even many who are schooled in jazz. At ``In the Mix,'' you play the
sound engineer, literally remixing Charles Mingus' ``Fables of
Faubus'' and playing it back. Set the microphone levels on eight
instruments, from snare drum to trombone, then control the
reverberation and sound direction.
</P>
<P>
   Or choose a version mixed by a professional engineer and just
watch the lights on the mixing board change, indicating the
complexity of shaping just one song at a recording session.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1628 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-NEGRO-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     05-18 1611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NEGRO-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 KANSAS CITY, Mo.: ... recording session.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With special spaces devoted to Duke Ellington, Louis Armstrong,
and Ella Fitzgerald, as well as to jazz's component parts _
harmony, rhythm, melody, and ``thinking in jazz'' _ the museum tour
ends with the new and old together. A jazz DISCovery section
features computers for further research, and video display
terminals reflect the colorful lights of neon signs rescued from
the neighborhood in recent decades: Top Hat Grill, Pink Door
Cocktail Lounge, Fox's Tap Room, The Other Room, Elinora's Cafe,
and, of course, the Street Hotel's Blue Room.
</P>
<P>
   A door opens into the Blue Room, which is quiet by day. It holds
silent tributes to Bennie Moten's Kansas City Orchestra, Bill
``Count'' Basie, the Blue Devils of Oklahoma City and other
``territory bands,'' Kansas City swing, jook joints, bebop, and a
wall of photos of every known and unknown black musician that
played the area from the 1920s on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Negro Leagues Baseball Museum
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Formally, the segregated alternative leagues lasted from 1920 to
1960. They represented almost a nation within a nation. The Negro
National League, the Eastern Colored League _ and the East-West
League, which had the audicity not to employ a word denoting
separation in its name _ were among six black leagues. They
developed some of baseball's great players, black or white.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, Willie Mays, Satchel Paige, Hank Aaron, Roy
Campanella, Ernie Banks. They rode and slept on buses, touring
during the season. They stayed in hotel rooms that cramped even a
single bed _ one of them is recreated in the museum. The crude
gloves and uniforms and shoes are on display here, among the black
and white photographs of the stars, and of the fans that dressed up
even in the summer heat and came out to cheer them.
</P>
<P>
   This being Kansas City, the Monarchs are featured; they won the
Series in '24 and again in '42. But many other teams are recalled
with a reproduction of their uniforms, hanging in an exhibit of a
typically cramped locker room of the day. Andrew ``Rube'' Foster, a
star pitcher, manager, and owner, was the leagues' most important
figure, pulling the teams together and administering the leagues
through even tough times. One league died in the Depression, but
the golden years followed, up through 1939 when a pastime took
minds off hard times and an impending war.
</P>
<P>
   The leagues are credited with initiating night baseball.
</P>
<P>
   A year after the color line was broken _ a long overdue
development that was nevertheless met with a few bittersweet
feelings, given that it meant the end of the leagues themselves _
President Harry Truman ended segregation in the Armed Forces. Today
baseball, the military _ and of course jazz _ are among the least
racially divided corners of American life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Gem Theater
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This 1912 movie theater, its facade and neon marquee salvaged as
perhaps the most familiar artifact on the block of the segregated
age, re-opened in August of 1997, a few days before the Jazz Museum
and two months before the Negro Leagues Museum. It was gutted and
expanded and is now the Gem Theater Cultural and Performing Arts
Center, seating 500.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's anniversary performances were held at the Gem and in
the streets of the districts outside. Tagged ``Livin' on the
Vine,'' the anniversary included an event celebrating the 99th
birthday anniversary of Duke Ellington. Along with local perfomers
and the Southern Christian Leadership Conference Gospel Choir,
there were appearances by the Manhattan Transfer, James Ingram,
Patti Austin and the George Duke Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner from the Gem is the Mutual Musicians
Foundation, a truly unassuming building that not only housed the
Local 627 musicians' union headquarters but that still swings into
the early hours, after the Blue Room and another small jazz joint
in the neighborhood, the Mardi Gras, have closed their doors.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding any celebration, or any tourist group, in Kansas
City is lots of Kansas City barbeque. The most famous (though not
the best) of the barbeque restaurants, Arthur Bryant's, is a short
distance from 18th and Vine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The District
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The municipal investment of $26 million isn't made easily, or
without the hope and expectation that it is a magnet for economic
development that will reclaim a larger and larger part of a revered
but lost part of the city. The 18th and Vine Authority runs the
Gem, the Jazz Museum and Blue Room, and a visitors center. The
Negro Leagues Museum is in space leased to it by the authority and
is operated by a separate nonprofit corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Whiting, the former aide to Mayor Cleaver, said that about $2
million of the current annual operating budget is public money, a
portion that is to be reduced as attendance grows.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Archives of Mid-America _ founded by local
activist-historian Horace Peterson, who is credited with the idea
of rebuilding the area _ is relocating into a historic parks and
recreation building nearby. But it is the business interest that
creates real excitement among the area's promotors. Sprint, with
headquarters in the Kansas City area, has opened a 60-person,
welfare-to-work office across from the Blue Room. A restaurant
called Sylvia's is scheduled to open this year. And, though the
city owns most of the buildings in a six-square-block area, efforts
are being made on many fronts to get people back to 18th and Vine.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Cleaver, then a city councilman, pushed the idea of
using a half-cent sales tax as backing for bonds to build the
museums. ``It was a controversial idea,'' said Whiting, the first
real expenditure of money in an area of the city many had written
off. Eight years later, they opened.
</P>
<P>
   Another public authority, the Jazz District Redevelopment Corp.,
is working to help the area grow, advised by a large local
developer. The area is one of the federal government's so-called
enhanced-enterprise communities and has received or been promised
$14 million in loans and grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the people who have a dream of a business need some
help,'' said Whiting. A desserts chef at a large hotel wanted to
open a pastry shop in the district, ``to make stuff that's too
pretty to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Whiting said 200 proposals have been made to the redevelopment
corporation. ``For the district to survive, we need the museums as
the heart of it,'' Whiting said, but also, ``We need housing,
business, and retail.'' Mixed-income housing nearby includes the
Count Basie Courts.
</P>
<P>
   The area also needs a racially mixed population of visitors to
be successful, and _ while the overall numbers haven't met
expectations _ that diversity has come, despite a strong fear among
many in Kansas City's white suburbs that 18th and Vine is a place
best avoided.
</P>
<P>
   A distinct but unobtrusive police presence, many officers in
plain clothes at night or on bicycles during the day, makes the
area safer than some of its mostly white nightclub districts.
``Visitors are 70 percent white _ about like the population,''
Whiting said last summer. Lately, as the word has spread, black
visitors have increased, and more like 60-40.
</P>
<P>
   If the mix is right, the numbers are nevertheless disappointing
to some. A 1992 study projected that 76,000 people would visit the
Jazz Museum in the first year. Only about 35,000 did, and a delayed
opening of the Negro Leagues Museum is suspected of depressing
turnout. But officials say more 350,000 have come to the district
for one event or another in the last year, and they're encouraged
by paid admissions now running at 14,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   than 150,000 attended various performances in the district, and
they're encouraged by increasing attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Some criticism continues. The director of the Black Chamber of
Commerce of Greater Kansas City in September chastized city
officials for having a ``build it and they will come'' attitude
unsupported by a solid business plan.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kansas City Star has reported that a powerful team of
black architects and engineers with HNTB Architects to develop the
Jazz District. Last summer, business and government officials
promised $70 million to finance housing and new business in the
newly enlivened area.
</P>
<P>
   Guiding visitors to the area across the 18th Street, from the
museums to the Gem Theater, is a novel, broad crosswalk. It is
marked off with customary white paint, but the lines are thick and
wavy, and even wanderers who are not so musically inclined will
recognize it as a suggestion of a musical scale _ a touch not corny
but just right for a project whose objective is to get people
involved in the Jazz Age.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Bouchard, a senior designer at Amaze Design Inc. of
Boston, who worked on the Jazz Museum project, said he didn't know
whose idea it was to extend the musical theme onto the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trying to figure out who did that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was Rowena Stewart, executive director of the 18th
and Vine Authority. Stewart, a former Boston resident who worked
for the Harriet Tubman House in the early 1960s, said she wanted a
connection between the Negro Leagues and Jazz museums, on the north
side of 18th Street, and the Gem, on the south side. ``It couldn't
just sit over there by itself,'' said Stewart. ``We wanted to
create a kind of rhythm between the two buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tickets for admission to both museums are $8 for adults, $4 for
children. For information on the Jazz Museum call 816-474-8463; for
the Negro Leagues Museum call 816-221-1920. The 18th &AMP; Vine
Authority is at 816-871-3016.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
