<HEADLINE>
SEAN CONNERY _ THE BEST BOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Admit it, fellows, we'd all like to be James Bond, that suave
and sexy spy in the novels and movies. Well now you can be Bond . .
. for a little while anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Wyndham El San Juan Hotel &AMP; Casino is ofering a four-day,
three-night package for two that will allow you to live out your
Bondian fantasies. And you don't even need a white dinner jacket _
you can rent one for $60 for the three nights. Here's what the
package includes:
</P>
<P>
   --A limousine waiting for you at the airport with the chauffeur
holding a sign for ``James Bond.''
</P>
<P>
   --Deluxe accommodations for two. Room service will promptly
deliver a special pen that, when opened, contains secret tools. The
deliverer's name tag will read ``Q.''
</P>
<P>
   --A call from the concierge, who will reveal her identity as
``Moneypenny'' and offer to make any reservations. Restaurant staff
will welcome you as ``Mr. Bond'' and accept checks signed ``007.''
</P>
<P>
   --Several complimentary items and services, including two ``From
Russia With Love'' martinis, VIP treatment at the hotel's Babylon
Night Club and Disco, two half-hour massages, and unlimited use of
a penthouse fitness center.
</P>
<P>
   --Turndown service that on the first night includes a bottle of
champagne and chocolate-covered strawberries, on the second night
brandy, chocolate cigars, and exclusive El San Juan cigars, and on
the final night two James Bond personalized bathrobes and sauterne
wine. And nightly there will be casino chips that cleverly conceal
chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Not that James Bond would worry about the price, but through
Nov. 22, the rate for the total package $1,137 plus taxes and tips.
If you want to upgrade to the Presidential Suite of beachfront
Monarch Suite, the price jumps to $8,007. From Nov. 23 through
April 30, 2000, the price is $1,392. The suite price is the same
year round.
</P>
<P>
   There's a special number to call for reservations. Phone
800-544-3912, ext. 1474, and say, ``Bond. James Bond.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel Trivia: What is the world's northernmost capital city?
(Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a name: Austin, Texas, was originally named Waterloo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Freebie: Mousetales, the Unofficial Newsletter of Walt Disney
World, has prepared a list of dos and don'ts for visitors to Disney
World's latest theme park, the Animal Kingdom, and the advice seems
to be good. For a copy, send a self-addressed, business-size
envelope to Moustetales, PO Box 383, Columbus, OH 43216.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``I'll let you be in my dreams if I can be in yours.'' _
Bob Dylan quote, printed on a card and left on the pillow during
turndown service at the Heritage hotel in Brisbane, Australia. The
Heritage is a member of the Leading Hotels of the World, and any
hotel that quotes Dylan deserves the honor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Got a gripe? Travelers, including airline passengers, have an
easy and free way to file complaints on line. Visit
www.passengerrights.com for a list of official organizations such
as the Department of Transportation, specific airlines, hotel
companies, cruise lines, car rental companies, and even
individuals. Passengerrights directly files the complaints
electronically to all selected parties and e-mails the complainant
with a receipt once the message has been forwarded. The Web site
also contains a manifesto of passengers' rights and information on
issues such as how to sue an airline, how not to get cheated or
ripped off, and how to learn the secrets of the industry and save
money and trouble. Every month, www.passengerrights.com will select
the most horrifying story and consumer complaint and present the
Passenger Rights Victim Award.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did you guess it? Reykjavik, Iceland. (With thanks to faithful
contributor Mike Schuster of Foxborough, a recent visitor to
Reykjavik.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We have Burger King's explanation regarding a subject of
monumental significance discussed in this column: why some BK
look-alike restaurants in Australia are named Hungry Jack's while
others bear the Burger King moniker. ``The Burger King brand name
was not available for use by Burger King Corp. in 1971,'' BK says.
``The company chose an available Pillsbury pancake mix brand name,
Hungry Jack's, in its place. . . . Burger King opened its first
four company-owned restaurants (under the Burger King name) in
Sydney, New South Wales . . . in December 1997.'' So there.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Peter Clark of Georgetown, Mass., who spent five
weeks in Sydney on an educational exchange program, forwards these
fascinating facts:
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know that in New Zealand (at least in Christchurch),
McDonald's puts slices of kiwi fruit on their Big Mac's?
</P>
<P>
   ``Also . . . in the United States the Subaru Outback automobile
is advertised with an `Australian' theme that uses the Crocodile
Dundee actor and scenes from the Australian outback. . . . The
identical automobile in Australia is called the Subaru Liberty and
is advertised with an `American' theme with scenes of the Grand
Canyon in the background.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of the Grand Canyon, a reader takes issue with a
recent statement, gleaned from a Reader's Digest publication, that
said Idaho's Hell's Canyon surpasses the Grand Canyon's deepest
drop of 5,700 feet by 2,200 feet. Writes Peter Huston of Sudbury,
Mass.: ``The 1976 edition of the World Book Encyclopedia claims the
Grand Canyon drops from about 9,000 feet above sea level (at North
Rim) to about 1,850 feet above at the river's edge _ 7,150 feet
total, or virtually the same!'' To paraphrase a president, we
suspect the differences may stem from what the definition of
``drop'' is.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While in Naples, Fla., Marilyn Vecchio of Canton, Mass. spotted
an ad in a tourist magazine for ``live Main lobsters.'' She
suspects they meant ``Maine,'' but the main thing is that Maine
lobsters are mainly delicious no matter where they're eaten.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
