<HEADLINE>
RULING MEXICAN PARTY OPTS FOR OPEN PRIMARY IN 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexico's ruling party broke with 70 years of
tradition Monday by deciding that its presidential candidate for
2000 would be chosen in an open primary election.
</P>
<P>
   The Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, which, since its
founding in 1929, has controlled Mexico, traditionally has had as
its candidate the personal choice of the incumbent president. But
Mexico's current president, Ernesto Zedillo, has repeatedly pledged
to end the so-called ``dedazo''in favor of a more democratic
process. In addition, growing competition from opposition parties
has put greater pressure on the PRI to adopt reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``From now on, no one can say that the president has chosen the
candidate,'' PRI President Jose Antonio Gonzalez said in a speech
to the 300 party officials who attended Monday's marathon session.
``We will choose our own candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, all interested candidates must register by
the end of June. Candidates who currently hold public office must
resign by June 15.
</P>
<P>
   The primary campaign season would run from Aug. 1 to Nov. 3. The
PRI will not provide any funds during the primary but will impose a
spending limit, which remains to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate would be selected by a vote among all registered
voters in early November. The winner would be the candidate who
takes the largest number of the country's 300 congressional
districts.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts predicted a more open process could attract a
larger pool of candidates. Already, there are at least three
declared candidates: former Puebla Governor Manuel Bartlett,
Tabasco Governor Roberto Madrazo and former PRI president Humberto
Roque.
</P>
<P>
   Other contenders could include Interior Secretary Francisco
Labastida Ochoa, considered by many to be Zedillo's favorite, and
Veracruz Governor Miguel Aleman, son of a former president.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's decision by the PRI was a surprise to some observers
who expected the party to agree to hold a secret vote only among
its members.
</P>
<P>
   Now the party appears ready to expand a successful experiment it
tried during last year's governor's race in the border state of
Chihuahua. There, for the first time, the PRI held an open primary
to pick its candidate rather than letting party bosses decide.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI went on to win the seat, taking away an office that for
nearly a decade had belonged to the conservative opposition
National Action Party, or PAN.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing here is an extraordinary development to a
more open democracy in the PRI and for Mexico,'' said Arturo Nunez,
the head of the PRI's congressional delegation.
</P>
<P>
   None of the opposition parties has selected its candidate yet.
The two leading opposition candidates are Mexico City Mayor
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, of the leftist Party of the Democratic
Revolution, and Guanajuato Governor Vicente Fox, of the PAN. Both
of them have outpolled all potential PRI candidates in recent
surveys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
