<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ It was supposed to last three
days. Two months (EDs: Wednesday marks two months since NATO
bombing began March 24) into NATO's air war against Yugoslavia,
however, managing the campaign, the diplomacy aimed at ending it
and the unintended consequences of prolonged bombing has become a
huge and unexpected job for the White House. President Clinton has
emerged as a surprisingly engaged commander in chief, a quick
study, Pentagon officials say, who asks the right questions and
displays the correct instincts on an evolving operation, even as
he's stood fast on the mission's goals. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   w/ KOSOVO-BORDER _ LETAJ, Albania _ The ground war is well under
way. Just ask the peasant farmers in this rugged mountain village
on the border with Yugoslavia. (Holmes, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   w/ BORDER-BOX _ KUKES, Albania _ Information for a map-graphic.
(Holmes, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   w/ KOSOVO-MULE _ TASK FORCE HAWK, Albania _ Out of the black
world of helicopter special ops has come a secret weapon to defeat
the Albanian mud: a four-wheel-drive go-cart that looks like a
moon-buggy and hauls more than its weight without ever getting
stuck. (Albright, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   w/ MULE-BOX _ Information on the ``mule'' mud-buggy. (Albright,
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS _ NUEVO LAREDO, Tamaulipas, Mexico _ The new
mayor opened a door in the corner of his office and climbed down
the secret spiral staircase that let him avoid the throng of people
constantly jockeying for a moment of his time. ``My escape route,''
Mayor Horacio Garza Garza explained as he edged down the steep
stairs to the street. He may need it. With his new get-tough
campaign against public corruption and drug trafficking in this
rapidly growing border city, Garza is quickly making enemies among
a police force that has become notorious for harboring officers who
participated in more crimes than they stopped.(Harmon, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SHAS-0519 _JERUSALEM, Israel _ A day after the euphoria
of his election landslide, Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak faces a
daunting dilemma as he tries to form a coalition government? How to
deal with the biggest winner in the Israeli Parliament: the
controversial, ultra-religious Shas Party? The dilemma frames the
cultural war in Israel. The bribery conviction of the Shas Party
leader Areyeh Deri seemed to only empower this anti-establishment
movement, which nearly doubled its share of the Knesset in the
election. Developing.
</P>
<P>
   (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 6 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   FORBES _ WASHINGTON _ Republican presidential candidate Steve
Forbes lays out his plan for reforming the Social Security system
in a National Press Club speech. (Lipman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   ENCRYPTION _ WASHINGTON _ A House subcommittee hears from
Microsoft, FBI and the National Security Agency on export controls
and recommendations of the proposed SAFE Act, a measure to limit
data encryption that the industry bitterly opposes. The battle pits
personal privacy concerns against rising use of the Internet by
criminals and spies. (Glass, Cox News Service) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   SUGAR _ WASHINGTON _ Reps. Dan Miller, R-Fla., and George
Miller, D-Calif., hold a news conference to introduce a bill that
would reduce subsidies to the sugar industry. (Lipman, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-PRIMARY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Florida was supposed
to become part of a mega-state primary next year that would force
candidates to raise millions of dollars in order to win the GOP
nomination for president. Instead, Florida is likely to have the
``who cares'' primary, with the nominee chosen days earlier by
states with far fewer voters. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-LIFE _ THE EVERGLADES, Fla. _ In the central
Everglades, reminders of fire and death linger like the sulfur
smell in the breeze. But so do signs of new life. Saw grass shoots,
an almost fluorescent green, sprout 8 inches above the soil. Leaves
fan out from the base of the dead trunks. And under the ash, the
peat is moist. That means hope for recovery from the wildfires of
the past month, which swept across 170,000 acres of state-owned
Everglades marsh in northwest Broward County. (King, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CANDIDATE-COSTS _ ATLANTA _ The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals on Tuesday will hear arguments as to whether the high cost
of running for
</P>
<P>
   office excludes candidates who don't have money, effectively
functioning as a type of poll tax for would-be officeholders. A
lower court judge in Atlanta has ruled to dismiss the lawsuit. The
case centers on a claim filed by John White, a former state
representative from Albany who lost a primary bid for state Senate
in 1996 against incumbent Mark Taylor. Taylor outspent White
$270,000 to $16,000. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOTORIST-SHOT _ SMYRNA, Ga. _ A man was shot twice and killed as
he drove down I-75 toward Atlanta early Tuesday morning. Police
said several shots were fired into the driver's side of the vehicle
from outside the car. The victim was described as a Hispanic in his
late teens or early 20s. On Sunday night, police in this same
suburban county reported a Hispanic driver shot while driving on a
surface street. He was wounded in the leg. (Anderson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-FAN _ The automobile has an eloquent new defender in the
debate over sprawl and mobility. He is James Dunn, a professor of
political science and public policy at Rutgers University's Camden
campus and author of a new book titled ``Driving Forces: The
Automobile, Its Enemies and the Politics of Mobility'' (Brookings
Institution Press, $19.95). ``It's tough to beat the car with a
ridesharing mandate and a bus that may or may not arrive on time,
or a rail station that's a half-mile away from where you want to go
on a rainy day,'' Dunn said in a telephone interview. (Ledford,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS, LAYOUTS and GRAPHICS If a budget line or story is marked
with photos or graphics, those are available from the New York
Times News Service at 212-556-4204. Or call CoxNet for more
information at 404-526-5456.
</P>
