<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, May 19.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ISRAEL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 1{ pages on the continuing crisis over
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 1{ pages of coverage on the aftermath
of the Israeli election.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ Now what? The new parliament could pose
problems for Ehud Barak, the newly elected prime minister, on the
peace effort and cohesion of Israeli society. Barak goes to the
Western Wall and the grave of the assassinated prime minister
Yitzhak Rabin. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With a photo and a graphic on the composition of the new
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ Palestinian reaction to the
Barak victory. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-RIGHT (Jerusalem) _ In a challenge to Barak,
right-wingers start building on formerly Arab land in East
Jerusalem bought by a Miami millionaire, Irving Moskowitz. A look
at the right wing. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ARABS (Cairo, Egypt) _ Arab reaction to the Barak
victory. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S. (Washington) _ More on the Clinton administration's
view of the Israeli election and its import for the peace effort.
President Clinton meets with the king of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Developments on Kosovo from NATO
headquarters. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Brussels) _ There are new reports that Serbian
forces are digging up mass graves and reburying bodies in single
graves. Also, new figures from the U.S. war crimes envoy on
killings (5,000) and missing men (225,000, double the previous
estimate). By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton does not rule out
ground troops, but says that the air war needs more time. He also
says it's a ``mischaracterization'' to say the administration is
blocking the use of Apache helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Rome) _ The Italian prime minister, Massimo
D'Alema, who is under political pressure to press for peace in
Kosovo, meets Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany, who is
strongly opposed to using ground forces. Britain hastens to say
there's no rift in the alliance. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   We are considering, among others, separates on the
Talbott-Chernomyrdin meeting with Finland's president, Tony Blair's
visit to a refugee camp and a look at the emerging political
situation in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-IMMIG (Hong Kong) _ Fearful of an influx of immigrants
from the mainland, the Hong Kong government says it will ask
Beijing to reinterpret Hong Kong's Constitution to revoke the
residency rights granted to many mainlanders by a Hong Kong court.
Democracy groups react angrily. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-PORN (Tokyo) _ The Japanese parliament on Tuesday enacted
a law aimed at banning child prostitution and child pornography, a
victory for international law enforcement officials and for a band
of women legislators here who have fought for two years to overcome
strong opposition to the law on the grounds that it would inhibit
free speech and free expression. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-POLITICS (New Delhi) _ Political developments in the
aftermath of Sonia Gandhi's offer to resign as head of the Congress
Party. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Political developments on eve of the
parliament's vote on confirming Sergei Stepashin, the
prime-minister designate. Stepashin says he will ask for vote of
confidence if parliament rejects his economic program. A
no-confidence vote would enable President Boris Yeltsin to dissolve
parliament. Also, there are new concerns about Yeltsin's health as
he cancels meeting with the Spanish prime minister. By Michael
Wines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ Senate action on the juvenile crime
bill. Senators may vote on further amendments or may scrap the
whole bill. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ The House is to vote by early
evening on the $15 billion emergency spending bill. The Senate
probably will take it up on Wednesday. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND-CUTS (Washington) _ Republicans specify tens of
billions of dollars in domestic spending cuts they plan under the
``caps'' enacted in 1997 _ $10 billion from labor, education and
health; $6 billion for housing, environment and veterans; $3
billion for Commerce, State and Justice Departments; $3 billion for
Interior, and so on. Despite the rhetoric by both parties' leaders,
few believe the cuts can be accomplished without a bitter fight, an
impasse threatening a government shutdown, or a last-minute
emergency imbroglio like last year's. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ The Federal Election
Commission this week is expected to approve federal matching money
for donations to presidential candidates made by credit card over
the Internet. The policy shift signals the agency's recognition of
blossoming on-line political activity of all kinds, including
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS-WHALE (Neah Bay, Washington) _ Following the harpooning
of a whale, protestors mourn the animal's death while the members
of the Makah Indian tribe celebrate, carve it up and eat. By Sam
Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-MAYORAL (Philadelphia) _ The Democratic primary for mayor
in Philadelphia, with polls closing at 8 p.m. EDT. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-MURDER (Detroit) _ Grisly murder of a man in front of
his children at a gas station has brought protests and racial
tension with killer an Arab-American and dead father black. By
Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ The political briefs column. By B.
Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FED (Washington) _ The Federal Reserve's policy makers meet. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 2 p.m., stocks were modestly higher, with
the Dow Jones industrial average was up 50 points. Markets in
Europe were slightly higher, but Tokyo and Hong were little
changed. At midday, the 30-year Treasury bond was up slightly,
yielding 5.87 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   DELL-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Dell Computer is expected to report
1st quarter earnings after the close, with 16 cents the forecast.
By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   LOEHMANN-BANKRUPTCY (Undated) _ Loehmann's, the retail chain,
files for Chapter 11 bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   BELL-GTE (Undated) _ Looking at the Bell Atlantic-GTE merger as
shareholders vote on the deal. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The Business Travel column. By Edwin
McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLER-SMARTCAR (Frankfurt, Germany) _ About DaimlerChrysler
and its unsuccesful Smart Car. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   KANEMATSU-CUTBACK (Tokyo) _ Kanematsu, perhaps the most troubled
of Japan's nine leading trading companies, announces that it will
slice its payroll to 660 from 1,938. Over the next three years, it
plans to cut more than half of the 17,000 jobs at the group level.
By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-COPPER (Toronto) _ Canada's largest copper mine has been
shut down in a labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) - The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties.''
</P>
