A1680 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONGHORNS-HERD-TEX     05-18 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONGHORNS-HERD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR NEW STEERS TRYING TO HORN IN ON HERD ACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSCOTT RANCH, Texas _ Chocolate Chip and Carrot Top, two
massive longhorn steers who led the 1995 Great American Cattle
Drive from Fort Worth to Miles City, Mont., are vying for a place
in the Fort Worth Herd to be introduced June 12 at the city's
sesquicentennial celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Four new steers arrived at the Winscott Ranch southwest of Fort
Worth on Friday. Chocolate Chip and Carrot Top were shipped from
Sallisaw, Okla., along with two other steers, one of which also
carries the Circle 95 brand from the Great American Cattle Drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume it was on the drive, too, but we just don't have any
information on it,'' said Dennis Merrell, trail boss for the
15-head Fort Worth Herd. ``We do know that Chocolate Chip and
Carrot Top took turns as the lead steer on that cattle drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Jones, manager of the Fort Worth Herd, said the four
steers came from Richard Howe of Yorktown, Ind. Howe purchased the
animals after the 1995 cattle drive to Miles City.
</P>
<P>
   The newcomers have joined 16 other steers on the Winscott Ranch,
though on Monday morning the newly arrived four were off to
themselves several hundred yards from the other cattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Winscott, owned by Ed Bass of the billionaire Bass family,
is the temporary home for the herd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a little time to get them used to one another; we
don't want to push them,'' Merrell said. ``We're going to get the
best 15 out of this herd, and the rest will go back to their
homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrell said there is already an ``A-team'' among the steers _
five that have done everything asked of them. Included in that
group are the two other Circle 95 veterans, Ned and Curley _
donated to the city by Bob and Mary Mike McKenzie of Aledo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are absolutely great,'' Merrell said of the
top-performing steers. ``I feel like I can count on them in any
situation. The longer we're around them, the better we like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrell is hoping that the new additions will have the same
disposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take disposition over looks any day of the week,'' he
said. ``I've got to.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrell said he and his crew have been working the herd
constantly to get it accustomed to the kinds of noises and
distractions the steers are likely to encounter on the June 12
drive from downtown Fort Worth to their permanent home in the
Stockyards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had the Fort Worth Mounted Patrol come out and help
us,'' Merrell said. ``They've used blank guns, flares, and sirens.
I've driven around the steers in a pickup with a boom-box
blaring.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrell said the steers have been driven over white tarps and
under a line with newspapers and tarps hanging from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting to know them pretty well,'' he said. ``We really
don't want to get into naming them all, but it seems like we can't
help it. We've got Viejo and Boss, Blue and Lumpy. Tres Zero is our
steer that never met a photographer he didn't like. I'll swear if
the photographer tells him to move a little to the left, he'll do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the herd program is to illustrate the significance
of the cattle industry in Fort Worth's 150-year history. Cowhands
will drive part of the herd through the Stockyards to the Trinity
River each day, beginning June 14. Part of the herd will remain in
pens for display.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
