indigestion by up to 90 percent, according to a report released at
the annual Digestive Disease Week meetings.
</P>
<P>
   -- People taking the new drug celecoxib to treat inflammation
and pain from arthritis are far less likely to have bleeding ulcers
and other digestive-tract complications than if they are taking
older anti-inflammatory drugs, according to a study released here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   -- The culprit in a major U.S. outbreak of food poisoning two
years ago has been identified: a salmonella bacterium originating
in unpasteurized cheese. The bug has health officials worried, they
say, because it seems impervious to antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   --A year after the breast-cancer treatment tamoxifen was
approved for breast-cancer prevention, further research confirms
that the drug cuts some women's cancer risk, while new information
suggests it may also prevent pre-cancerous growths from becoming
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   --There may be a new option for menopausal women who experience
uncomfortable side effects with traditional hormone-replacement
therapy. Very low doses of estrogen, combined with twice-yearly
progesterone treatments instead of monthly therapy, may stave off
menopausal symptoms while avoiding side effects, researchers say.
</P>
