<P>
   WINE-BROKERS (Undated) _ On a recent trip to the Napa Valley,
when the vineyards were ablaze with carpets of yellow mustard
flowers, my friend was hoping to purchase a case of wine she had
been unable to find in New York. She thought it would take no more
than a phone call. Instead, it turned into a 90-minute odyssey that
required her to drive to the vineyard, pay for the wine, have the
case loaded into her car and then transport it to a shipping
service suggested by the winery. Welcome to the wacky world of the
50 different sets of state regulations governing interstate
shipment of wine. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congress starts to crack down even
more on wine sales between states. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The weekly wine column: Spanish wines that
aren't Rioja. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTINGS (Undated) _ A capsule wine review.
</P>
<P>
   PAPILLOTE (Undated) _ The cooking method known as en papillote _
after the parchment paper that encloses the food in an envelope _
has held its own through any number of culinary fashions. It was
especially favored in the days when haute cuisine was more
ceremonious than it is now, allowing the server to open the package
at the table in a show of erupting aromatic steam. Now, it still
maintains its place, mostly in restaurants, thanks to what is
perhaps a purer, more esthetic reason: a dish cooked in this way is
intensely yet harmoniously flavored. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With 3 recipes.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: fish baked on potatoes
with olives. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
