<HEADER>
A1741 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BORDER-0519-CO     05-18 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BORDER-0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GROUND WAR ON A SMALL SCALE: SERBS HARASS ALBANIAN BORDER TOWNS
 &HT;    600&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-CLINTON-0519.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Letaj is on the border with
Yugoslavia, due north of Kukes and due south of the Kosovo town of
Djakovica.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LETAJ, Albania _ The ground war is well underway. Just ask the
peasant farmers in this rugged mountain village on the border with
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav army snipers pepper Letaj almost every morning and
evening. In recent weeks, artillery shells have killed one
villager, wounded others, destroyed several homes and damaged the
school. Serb units also have fired ``cluster'' shells, which burst
in the sky and sprinkle tiny bomb-like mines across the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The story is much the same up and down Albania's frontier with
Yugoslavia. This harassing, sporadic warfare began last winter and
escalated after NATO began its air campaign against Yugoslavia on
March 24.
</P>
<P>
   In an ongoing sideshow to the air war, Serb-dominated Yugoslav
forces in Kosovo have badgered Albania's northern border in a
nominal but conspicuous challenge to the growing presence of U.S.
and NATO forces in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   International observers believe the Serb forces, lightly armed
ground troops occasionally backed by heavy artillery, have a double
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The first goal is to prevent the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army
(KLA), largely pushed out of Kosovo along with the refugees, from
using the Albanian border villages as bases for reentering the Serb
province.
</P>
<P>
   The second aim is to embarrass the Albanian government, whose
poorly equipped and trained government troops are powerless to
prevent the periodic Serb incursions onto its territory.
</P>
<P>
   In the highlands around the town of Barjam Curri, the exiled KLA
is mounting modest efforts at hit-and-retreat attacks against Serb
positions inside the embattled Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   In others hamlets like Letaj, where the KLA is not active, the
men in the villages have sent the women and children away and are
living as Albanian minutemen, hunting rifles and shotguns at the
ready to answer Serb shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to protect our houses. It's all we have,'' said Ismet
Kokaj, 38.
</P>
<P>
   In Letaj (pronounced, LAY-tie) the population has dropped from
900 to 150, as the men sent their families to neighboring towns
away from the fighting. Yugoslav army troops hold positions on
Albanian territory near the village, from which they fire their
rifles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs maintain a position along the ridge inside the
border of Albania. They are dug in and they have a beautiful view
of this district from which they shoot,'' said Bjorn Kunar, a
military observer based in Krume for the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
   Cross-border shelling by Serb artillery batteries in Kosovo have
forced about 5,000 people from their homes in Albanian border
towns, providing a new task for humanitarian aid officials already
coping with the nearly 400,000 refugees in this region from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the border villages have been unable to plant their
spring crops, meaning food will be scarce later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The World Food Program and the Irish relief organization Concern
have begun food-aid deliveries to the remote border region to feed
refugees from Kosovo and the Albanians forced from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Letaj's subsistence farmers, their faces deeply lined and
sun-baked from years in the fields, are poor but proud. Northern
Albania is a lawless land where guns are plentiful. The police and
army do little to keep order as bandits, led by local Albanian clan
leaders, control the territory.
</P>
<P>
   But historic animosities with the Serbs run deep and long, and
everyone has vowed to fight the intruders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't leave my village. I want to die there and no one will
move me,'' said Qazim Kamberi, 61. ``They want to provoke us, to
kill us, to destroy us.''
</P>
<P>
   The men live in bunkers and basements, and emerge only to fetch
water or walk down the hillsides to the nearby town of Golaj, less
than a mile away, to buy food and other provisions.
</P>
<P>
   About half of them have aged shotguns or hunting rifles and
occasionally they return the sniper fire. But it is a demonstration
of defiance more than any meaningful counter-attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they only want to make trouble with our government,
because if the Serbs wanted they could take these villages
easily,'' Kokaj conceded.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   They ask a visiting American reporter when the Apaches will
come, a reference to the American attack helicopters based near the
Albanian capital, Tirana, which may be used to escalate NATO's war
against Yugoslavia and protect Albania's border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conflict is not going to be sent into Albania,'' NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana said in a visit last week in
Tirana. ``I want to reassure the people of this country that NATO
will not tolerate any action against this country stemming from the
presence of NATO forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the start of NATO's air campaign, the Yugoslav army had
two infantry companies based at the Kosovo town of Djakovica, just
two miles from the Albanian border.
</P>
<P>
   NATO warplanes have been busy over the past week repeatedly
hitting Serb targets just across the border from Albania. The jets
high overhead and the thick columns of black smoke their bombs
produce are clearly visible from the Morina border crossing, the
main entry point for refugees arriving to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed Ukeperaj, governor of the local district that includes
Letaj, believes the situation will calm as NATO jets continue to
pound Serb forces dug in along the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they will come farther because every day their
army is being weakened. They can shell from a distance, but they
cannot come with ground troops,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
