<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZEDILLO-CALIF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEDILLO TO TOUT TRADE, EDUCATION IN TRIP TO CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Ernesto Zedillo became the first Mexican
president to visit the California capital when he arrived Tuesday
morning for a three-day tour focusing on trade, education and the
trickiest topic of all _ immigration.
</P>
<P>
   The last visit by a Mexican president to California was in 1993,
just before state voters approved Proposition 187, which aimed to
cut off all public services to illegal immigrants. The passage of
the initiative caused relations with Mexico to grow cold but did
little to chill the booming cross-border trade.
</P>
<P>
   One of the campaign themes of Gray Davis, the Democrat who
succeeded Republican Gov. Pete Wilson in January, was stronger ties
with Mexico, and he visited the country weeks after being
inaugurated.
</P>
<P>
   He has called Zedillo's visit ``La mano de amistad,'' the hand
of friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Although trade between California and Mexico grew at record
levels under Wilson, Davis administration officials believe
California lost a valuable opportunity to further influence trade
and immigration policy because Wilson was so confrontational.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in the framework of what I call changing attitudes,''
said Carlos Tello, the Mexican consul general in San Francisco.
``It's about taking advantage of these changing attitudes and
making sure they permeate to all levels of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis spokesman Michael Bustamante said, ``Under the previous
administration, it was much more difficult to even have a
conversation'' with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   With a doctorate in economics from Yale University, Zedillo, 47,
worked his way through Mexico's financial bureaucracy to be elected
president in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo is scheduled to speak before civic and business leaders
on Wednesday at a downtown Los Angeles hotel. He will dine at Green
Acres, the Beverly Hills estate of the grocery store magnate Ron
Burkle, who is a big supporter of Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Tello said education and trade would be first on Zedillo's
agenda, but human rights issues, namely how the estimated 4.5
million Mexican citizens who work and live in California are
treated by the authorities here, would also be discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This concerns all sorts of issues, like proper wages,
education, health, labor rights,'' Tello said, ``which of course is
related to the amount of money going from California to Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that Mexicans living in California send as much
as $7 billion a year back to their families. In terms of trade,
California exported about $13 billion in electronics and computers
to Mexico, state trade officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico would like to increase that amount through better ties
with Silicon Valley. Although Zedillo canceled a trip to San Jose,
citing scheduling difficulties, he will meet with high-tech leaders
in San Francisco and mayors from several dozen cities.
</P>
<P>
   That could lead to an announcement about further investment in
Mexico by Silicon Valley companies, and a greater push to increase
the number of Mexicans receiving H-1B visas, which allow foreign
workers to fill high-tech jobs in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On human rights, Zedillo and other Mexican officials would like
Davis to explain his position on Proposition 187, which has faced
court challenges since it was approved in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court already has ruled that illegal immigrants
have a right to public education, but several other legal issues
remain.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, to the dismay of Hispanics who supported him in the
election, decided to continue the state's defense of Proposition
187 by turning it over to a mediator to review.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Zedillo arrived in Sacramento on ``Hungry for
Justice _ Immigrant Lobby Day,'' an annual event attracting
hundreds of immigrants and advocates to the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The immigrant-rights groups said they wanted Davis to drop a
Wilson administration policy of asking about immigration status in
a variety of state programs.
</P>
<P>
   Some immigrant-rights advocates are mystified why Davis didn't
immediately drop Proposition 187 and the Wilson screening policy.
They hope Zedillo's visit will clarify things.
</P>
<P>
   By Mexican law, Zedillo had to get congressional approval to
leave the country; he could only enter U.S. airspace on Tuesday, so
his plane could not arrive until after midnight, and he must leave
the United States before midnight Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A planned train ride Wednesday from the Burbank airport to Union
Station in Los Angeles, and a Los Angeles elementary school stop,
are the kinds of populist photo opportunities that Davis clearly
relishes and the press-shy Zedillo usually avoids.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1786 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PASTA-SAUCE-2TAKES-NY     05-18 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASTA-SAUCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MEN, TWO ITALYS, TWO RAGOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MOLLY O'NEILL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the story of two men, two memories, two regions of
Italy, an adopted country and a mania for one pure thing _ real
Italian ragout.
</P>
<P>
   To Alex Goren, who grew up near Bologna and is a partner in
Goren Brothers, a money management company in Manhattan, ragout is
a meat sauce with a mere touch of tomato.
</P>
<P>
   To Sandro Manzo, who grew up in a small town south of Naples,
owns an art gallery in Rome and lives in New York City, where he
represents a group of Italian artists, ragout is predominately a
tomato sauce with some beef.
</P>
<P>
   In their adopted country, ragout (spelled ``ragu'' in Italian)
is generally associated with red stuff in a glass jar or can. As
devout home cooks, both men find these pretenders amusing. But a
few months ago, when these two longtime friends, who are both in
their early 60s, began to discuss sauces, each found his version as
different from the other's as both are from canned sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I come from, ragout means a very rich meat sauce,''
Goren said. Manzo, on the other hand, delicately suggested that no
one who knows and loves Italy could even contemplate a sauce that
is not red.
</P>
<P>
   These two styles developed over the centuries largely because of
the ingredients that were available: the Bolognese in the north had
meat, butter and cream, and the Neapolitans in the south had plenty
of tomatoes and olive oil. But clearly, pride has become a crucial
additive in each.
</P>
<P>
   The philosophical discussions between Goren and Manzo eventually
moved to an exchange of recipes and some tandem cooking sessions.
Would one be able to persuade the other even to consider the merits
of the other's sauce? Would a common ground in an age-old debate be
reached?
</P>
<P>
   Cooking side by side, the men matched each other in proficiency
and exuberance. The techniques and insistence on fine ingredients
of one mirrored the other's. One might think they were working
toward a common goal: a sauce with a deep amalgam of flavors.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually, the time comes to add tomato. In this, Goren is
as parsimonious as Manzo is unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   ``People from the north _ so fussy, so stingy,'' Manzo said in a
stage whisper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southern Italians!'' Goren exclaimed under his breath. ``No
discretion, no refinement. I don't want to say peasant, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   The rift (if it could be called that) between them ran much
deeper, apparently, than a disagreement about a few tomatoes. How
they came to possess their recipes was also a matter of some
import.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave to him my mother's recipe,'' Manzo said, with the
reverence generally reserved for early Christian relics.
</P>
<P>
   Goren, on the other hand, had spent three or four decades
relentlessly traveling and tasting throughout northern Italy in
search of his perfect ragout, which he finally found among the
family recipes of a friend-of-a-friend. He regards his discovery as
only slightly less significant than finding the Holy Grail.
</P>
<P>
   As his aromatic sauce simmered, Goren inhaled deeply. It was, he
said, ``the smell of the Italian heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the all-important taste test. Alternating bites of his
ragout (tossed with penne, in the traditional style) and Manzo's
ragout (tossed with tagliatelle, in the other traditional style),
Goren was himself _ a driven perfectionist, never entirely pleased
and not too eager to yield ground. Manzo, the art dealer who knows
that beauty can take many forms, was sanguine and diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   Goren's sauce is ``the best ragu Bolognese I've ever tasted,''
he said, adding that ``no one makes a better Neopolitan'' than
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Goren ventured that when he first came to the United States, the
only Italian pasta sauce widely available was red, a legacy of the
huge numbers of poor southern Italians who immigrated here around
the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past 15 years,'' he said, ``the Italians who come to
America are well-educated people from all over Italy, and more and
more we are getting authentic regional dishes.'' In this light, he
added philosophically, the existence of two styles of ragout ``is
not actually a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And the opinion of an impartial observer _ and taster? Both
sauces are excellent.
</P>
<P>
   Basta! Two ragouts! &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   RAGU ALLA BOLOGNESE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Alex Goren &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 4{ hours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 medium carrots, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 stalks celery, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   { pound pancetta, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 pound lean ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground pork butt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   8 cups homemade or low-sodium beef broth
</P>
<P>
   2{ cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Cooked tagliatelle or pappardelle. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large, deep saute pan, heat olive oil over high heat and
add carrots, celery and onions. Cook, stirring, until vegetables
are lightly browned, about 6 minutes. Add pancetta, and cook,
stirring, 2 minutes. Add beef and cook another 2 minutes. Add pork
and cook until meat is lightly browned, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Whisk together the tomato paste and 1 cup of the broth, and
add it to meat. Place pan over low heat so that sauce just barely
simmers. When broth has evaporated, add another cup. Continue to
cook, stirring occasionally and adding a cup of broth when stew
becomes dry, until all the broth has been added, about 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add milk and butter, and continue to simmer very gently until
milk is evaporated and sauce is very thick, about 1\ hours. Season
to taste with salt and pepper, and serve over tagliatelle or
pappardelle pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RAGU ALLA NAPOLETANA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Sandro Manzo &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 3{ hours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { cup pine nuts, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   { cup raisins, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds beef chuck, cut into slices [-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   \ cup red wine
</P>
<P>
   2 large (35 ounce) cans of high quality plum tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Cooked ziti or penne
</P>
<P>
   Grated Parmesan for serving. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small bowl, combine pine nuts, raisins and garlic. Lay
meat slices on a work surface, and season them lightly on both
sides with salt and pepper. Sprinkle pine-nut and raisin mixture on
one side of the slices. Roll slices up and secure them with a
toothpick or tie them with kitchen string. Place them in a large,
deep saute pan and add oil, onion and 4 cups of water. Place over
medium heat and simmer, uncovered, until water has evaporated,
about 1\ hours.
</P>
<P>
   2. Continue cooking, turning meat rolls with tongs, until meat
is lightly browned on all sides. Add wine to pan and cook until
evaporated. Drain tomatoes, reserving juice, and coarsely chop
tomatoes. Add tomatoes and reserved juice to pan, and bring to a
simmer. Cook until sauce is very thick, about 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove meat from pan with tongs, remove toothpicks or cut
string, and place meat on a serving platter. Season sauce with salt
and pepper, and pour it over ziti or penne. Serve with meat and
grated Parmesan cheese on the side. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
