<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MIDEAST (Washington) _ President Clinton, appearing with
King Abdullah of Jordan, pledges U.S. help in working with Israel's
premier-elect, Ehud Barak, to resume the peace process in the
Middle East. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLL (Washington) _ Mexicans blame the United States for
the flow of illegal drugs across the two nations' border and say
that the North American Free Trade Agreement has benefited
Americans much more than people in their country, according to a
Louis Harris poll. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   US-RUSSIA (Washington) _ Three Russia scholars, led by Librarian
of Congress James Billington, warn that the U.S.-led NATO bombing
campaign against Yugoslavia is fanning a backlash against the
United States across Russia. But former Ambassador Arthur Hartman,
who served in Moscow in the 1980s, disputes what he calls the
scholars' ``Chicken Little'' view. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-CROSSINGS-SENATE (Washington) _ Sen. Spencer Abraham,
R-Mich., renews his effort to kill a plan to enter into computers
the names of foreigners crossing borders into the United States. He
says implementing the system, which Congress last year put off
until 2001, would cause major delays at the borders, especially the
one with Canada, hurting business and tourism on both sides. By
JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ A proposal to bring 5 million
state and local government workers into Social Security would end
up costing those workers and their employers $25 billion over five
years, according to a study by a major union of state and local
government workers' union. It says the result would be higher taxes
or reduced government services. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SHOOTINGS (Washington) _ We cover youngsters from
schools, including Columbine High in Littleton, Colo., where
shootings have occurred, who are testifying before a House
education panel. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-Y2K (Washington) _ We look at a Senate Y2K bill, what
the measure would do and who supports it. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ELECTION (Jerusalem) _ A day after his dramatic landslide
election, Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak pledges to rekindle the
Middle East peace process, even as construction continued at two
Jewish settlements in contested Arab areas of Jerusalem. He does
not rule out a coalition with the Likud Party. By DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BARAK (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak is a
pragmatic politician who has more in common with Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, whom he has known since childhood, than with
Shimon Peres, his right-hand man. By DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HATE-CRIMES (Jasper, Texas) _ The family of dragging death
victim James Byrd Jr. holds a news conference in Jasper to discuss
the failure of the Texas Senate to approve the hate crimes act
named for Byrd. By RICHARD STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SPURS (San Antonio) _ The San Antonio Spurs vow they will no
longer be pushovers in the NBA playoffs, and they backed that up by
coming out strong in Game 1 of their series against the Los Angeles
Lakers. By MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
