<HEADER>
A1797 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-STARWARS-REVIEW-     05-18 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STARWARS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUST THE FORCE: KID-FRIENDLY `PHANTOM' HITS TARGET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As worlds-weary Qui-Gon Jinn tells young Anakin Skywalker in
``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' ``Feel, don't think.
Trust your instincts.''
</P>
<P>
   Moviegoers should do likewise.
</P>
<P>
   After a 16-year wait, bombardments of hype, grouchy early
reviews and fan mania, creator George Lucas' $115 million
preordained blockbuster has both huge momentum and the burden of
impossible expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars'' fans should love it. But even they may be divided,
especially after the buildup.
</P>
<P>
   As for critics, in their rush to judgment sparked by a backlash
to the hype they themselves helped create, some have slammed the
film for what it's not: 1977's first ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   True, that space adventure was fresher and _ partly to its
benefit _ less focused on special effects.
</P>
<P>
   But the moaners miss the point, which Lucas rightly repeats like
a mantra: ``The Phantom Menace,'' like ``Star Wars,'' is a kids'
movie at heart.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, who wrote, directed and executive-produced, also says
it's no more kid-friendly than the first. In that respect he is
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom'' is less likely to touch the proverbial kid in all of
us, if only because ``Star Wars''' Luke Skywalker was a young man,
while ``Phantom's'' Anakin Skywalker (Jake Lloyd), who here follows
much the same heroic course, is only 9. What's next? A preschooler
saving the galaxy?
</P>
<P>
   That's not to mention the ceaseless comic relief of slapstick
sidekick Jar Jar Binks (Ahmed Best), a computer-generated alien.
Clumsy and hapless, he's forever getting into pickles, then
prevailing by sheer luck.
</P>
<P>
   Kids will adore him. For adults, a little Jar Jar may go a long
way.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some kiddie zeal can be forgiven. The wow-factor action is
irresistible, and Lloyd is no less appealing than '60s Disney star
Kevin Corcoran (``Old Yeller,'' ``Swiss Family Robinson''), whose
mold he fits precisely.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the prequel trilogy's final two films promise adult
romance and disturbing darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom'' sets the stage, assembling the game pieces with a
plot tangled by murky politics (planetary blockades are ``legal,''
invasions need ``Senate approval''). More important is the man
behind it: Darth Sidious (Ian McDiarmid), the elusive puppet master
and title character.
</P>
<P>
   But feel, don't think. With so much zest and spectacle, any
tangled plot threads become as irrelevant as back-stories for
thrill rides. On with the show!
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom'' does get on with it, racing from the gate as Jedi
Master Qui-Gon Jinn (Liam Neeson) and apprentice Obi-Wan Kenobi
(Ewan McGregor) rescue clothes-horse Queen Amidala (Natalie
Portman) from her idyllic, besieged planet, Naboo.
</P>
<P>
   As fate _ or the mystical Force _ would have it, they must make
repairs on the backwater world of Tatooine. There they meet the
playful Anakin, who's amazingly strong in the Force binding the
galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   To help them, Anakin enters a ``pod race,'' a thrilling action
sequence that evokes ``Star Wars''' swoops down Death Star
trenches, not to mention ``Ben-Hur's'' chariot race.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``Phantom'' is riddled with repetition from the first
trilogy and other films, from its ``ascension guns'' (``Batman'')
to its droids imperiled on a spacecraft hull (``Silent Running'').
</P>
<P>
   Homage or stealing? You decide. At least Lucas borrows from the
best.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, he is right to satisfy fans with at least glimpses
of many familiar critters and characters.
</P>
<P>
   For all its newness, ``Phantom'' bristles with ``Star Wars''
veterans, from droids R2-D2 and C-3PO (the latter is half-built) to
Tatooine's Tusken Raiders, Jawas and Jabba the Hutt.
</P>
<P>
   Also back is tiny Jedi Master Yoda, still voiced by Frank Oz and
still depicted on-camera with puppetry, not this film's dominant
computer-animation.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas has advanced the latter technology to remarkable degrees.
``Phantom'' immerses the viewer in exotic new worlds, strange
aliens, bizarre machinery and intricate battles.
</P>
<P>
   Its finale is a rousing triumph, intercutting fights on four
fronts. One has skeletal armies of Battle Droids (cannon fodder
like Star Wars' Storm Troopers, and equally bad shots). Another has
a fierce, balletic lightsaber duel between scary new villain Darth
Maul (Ray Park) and Qui-Gon and Obi-Wan.
</P>
<P>
   But for all its energy and visual dazzle _ stirringly scored by
John Williams _ ``Phantom'' falls short of its predecessors in one
vital realm: characterization.
</P>
<P>
   It's not an actor's film.
</P>
<P>
   Only Neeson, with his strength and sad dignity, lends gravity
and conviction. McGregor, known for edgy starring roles, is wasted
in a subservient part.
</P>
<P>
   Others can do little with thin roles. As the future Darth Vader,
Lloyd doesn't even get to show a flicker of childish cruelty to
hint at his dark side to come. He's too busy shouting, ``Yipee!''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the actors don't star. Lucas' imagination does. Unfettered
by technical limits, it blossoms here like never before.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is that, like his early mimics, Lucas serves too
much flash over substance, even with his underlying spirituality.
He's so busy making our jaws drop that he neglects engaging our
minds and touching our hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, for his target audience, he delivers the goods.
</P>
<P>
   For wide eyes and innocent spirits _ for the kid we are, or want
to be _ this film's true force lies in its sheer, grand,
adventurous fun. Trust that force _ and may it be with you. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
