A1813 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBBER-GRAVE-HNS &LR;      05-18 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBBER-GRAVE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONNIE AND CLYDE PARTNER FINALLY GETS BURIAL MARKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARMINA DANINI  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ For more than 60 years, Joe Palmer, a member of
the Clyde Barrow and Bonnie Parker bank robbery gang, lay in an
unmarked grave in a South San Antonio cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer's anonymity is no more. On Saturday, Palmer's niece and a
few members of Partners in Crime, an Internet group that conducts
research on Depression-era outlaws, dedicated a headstone over his
grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not glorifying, him but he was my daddy's brother and he
was family,'' said Martha Palmer of Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Palmer was buried alongside his mother Lenora, who died in
1928, and his father, Charles, who died in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Palmer said members of the family didn't want to
acknowledge their ties to Joe until recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he had been buried in San Antonio because his father
was living here, but even as recently as five years ago, no one
wanted to talk about Uncle Joe,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick McConal, a graduate student at Texas A&AMP;M University and
a Partners in Crime member, said Palmer was so well-liked that
fellow inmates raised funds so that he could be buried in the Alamo
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want him buried in the prison cemetery, so they
chipped in for his burial in San Antonio,'' said McConal, who is
writing a book, ``Over the Wall _ The Men Behind the 1934 Death
House Escape,'' slated to be published by Eakin Press in Austin
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   A story that appeared in the San Antonio Evening News the day
after Palmer was executed in 1935 said prison officials had
instructions to ship Palmer's body to San Antonio and that burial
expenses were to be defrayed by $50 raised by other inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The simple headstone dedicated Saturday afternoon includes
Palmer's full name, his date of birth _ Sept. 29, 1902 _ and the
day he died.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer died in Texas' electric chair on May 10, 1935. Eleven
minutes later, Raymond Hamilton, another member of the Bonnie and
Clyde gang, was strapped into the chair.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper accounts said Palmer and Hamilton agreed on the same
menu for their last supper _ fried fish, cream gravy, potatoes au
gratin, corn, sweet pickles, stuffed olives, lettuce, celery, ice
cream, chocolate cake and dewberry cobbler. Hamilton's mother
arranged to have him buried in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer and Hamilton were executed for their part in the slaying
of a prison guard, Maj, M.H. Crowson, as they fled the Eastham
prison farm in January 1934. They were both convicted and sent to
the Death House in the Walls Unit at Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   They escaped one more time, in July 1934.
</P>
<P>
   There would not be another escape from the Texas death row until
Thanksgiving 1998, when Martin Gurule of Corpus Christi and six
other condemned killers tried to break out of the Ellis Unit.
Gurule was the only one who made it after climbing over two fences
topped with razor wire. His body was found floating in the Trinity
River a week later.
</P>
<P>
   Though not a major figure in the gang, Palmer was well-trusted
by Barrow, said E.R. Milner, a Denton historian and author of the
1997 book ``The Lives and Times of Bonnie and Clyde.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were not many people that Clyde Barrow trusted, but he
trusted Palmer,'' Milner said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Milner, Palmer joined the gang because of his close
friendship with Hamilton, who already was a cohort of Bonnie and
Clyde.
</P>
<P>
   Milner said there were indications that Palmer told Barrow he
had misgivings about a trip to Louisiana and told him not to travel
there. Bonnie and Clyde were killed in a roadside ambush near
Sailes, La., on May 23, 1934.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
