<HEADER>
A1817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAPILLOTE-ART-2TAKES-     05-18 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPILLOTE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ENVELOPE, PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cooking method known as en papillote _ for the parchment
paper that encloses the food in an envelope _ has held its own
through any number of culinary fashions. It was especially favored
in the days when haute cuisine was more ceremonious, allowing the
server to open the package at the table in a show of erupting
aromatic steam.
</P>
<P>
   It was ideal during the height of the healthy eating movement,
because the method requires little or no additional fat.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it still maintains its place, mostly in restaurants, thanks
to what is perhaps a purer, more esthetic reason: a dish cooked in
this way is intensely yet harmoniously flavored. Done well, it can
present itself in unparalleled and unadorned beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Georges Vongerichten, the chef at Jean Georges, uses the
technique. As do Jean-Louis Palladin, the chef at Palladin, and
Eberhard Muller, at Lutece.
</P>
<P>
   Although restaurants know how much panache en papillote brings
to a dish, there is an additional beauty, one appreciated by too
few home cooks: it is fast and uncomplicated in its execution, once
you get the knack and understand the principles that underlie the
method.
</P>
<P>
   When food is sealed in paper, it cooks in its own juices. It is
a more flavorful approach than ordinary steaming and less
restrictive than cooking in a hermetically sealed pot. There is no
water beneath and no lid above.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients cook quickly because they are surrounded by moist
heat. As the package is heated, the air inside expands, and the
flavors of the ingredients are swept into it, swirling and
mingling, with no escape. The ingredients are, in a sense, cooked
with flavored air and form a sauce purely of their own essence.
</P>
<P>
   Today, when efficiency is often valued over ceremony, the
traditional parchment (which requires some technique and time to
cut into the shaped envelope that most dishes require) is replaced
by simple crimped aluminum foil, with no loss of flavor.
</P>
<P>
   At Palladin, Palladin prepares vegetables in a foil package.
When it arrives at the table, it is not particularly attractive,
looking more like a TV dinner. It is rumpled on the edges and lies
on a bed of hot rock salt to keep it warm. The waiter just slashes
open the package and leaves you to fend for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the banks of foil is a tangle of ramps, turnips,
asparagus, baby pattypan squash and tiny mushrooms called
mousserons. What you cannot see, you smell _ grass and onions and a
heady truffle broth.
</P>
<P>
   But like many other chefs perpetually in search of an
idiosyncratic touch, Palladin embellishes on the simple method by
first simmering each vegetable individually. Then he brings them to
the foil. On the aluminum, he lays a lettuce leaf as insurance
against scorching, combines the vegetables and broth and bakes the
combination to create a superbly harmonious dish.
</P>
<P>
   Vongerichten, staying closer to the basic technique, makes a
similar but simpler dish. He brushes a piece of foil with olive
oil, and then assembles a pyramid of spring vegetables _ pea shoots
and then morels and blanched fiddleheads _ and a neat square of
black bass. Over it he lays asparagus and ramps, and seasons the
stack with salt, enriched chicken stock and vin jaune, a sherrylike
wine. He folds it up firmly but roughly. As for parchment, he said,
``I don't have the patience for that.''
</P>
<P>
   His own take on the technique is to do it on the stove top
rather than in the oven. He heats a saute pan brushed with oil, and
then lays the foil package directly on top. It inflates like a
balloon, and when it looks as if it is about to burst, he begins
counting four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The package, like a manhole, spews steam from its corners; it
ultimately becomes so inflated that just a Band-Aid size strip is
in contact with the pan. Vongerichten calls it ``Jiffy Pop for
black bass.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooking en papillote is almost always associated with fish and
vegetables. They are delicate, aromatic ingredients, and they cook
quickly. But the association is too limiting. Cooking en papillote
is a sophisticated way of preparing all kinds of foods. Meats like
lamb and chicken also benefit from cooking in paper or foil. It
just must be done more slowly.
</P>
<P>
   At Rosa Mexicano, for instance, there is a dish called mixiote
de cordero, which is lamb in parchment. It is a traditional Mexican
preparation from Tlaxcala, near Mexico City. There, meats are
wrapped in the skin of young maguey leaves and steamed, usually for
several hours.
</P>
<P>
   At the restaurant, Ruperto Cantor, the chef, uses parchment
paper rather than the leaves to cook lamb shanks rubbed with
pasilla, guajillo and ancho chilies and garlic. The same may be
done with chicken or rabbit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, pasta, one of the most time-sensitive dishes, can be
made with parchment. The pasta is not cooked in the paper but
finished in it, blending all of the flavors in the sealed package
just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Margherita Aloi, the chef at Le Madri, prepares a spaghetti dish
in her own atypical way. She cooks the spaghetti until it has just
a thin, firm core, and then swirls it with a simple tomato puree
and tiny meatballs made with veal, ricotta cheese and lemon zest.
</P>
<P>
   She wets a piece of parchment, lines a terra-cotta dish with it
and fills it with the pasta. Then she seals the paper, ``like a
seed package,'' she said, gathering the open ends and folding them
down like a brown paper bag, and she places the dish in a cool
corner of a wood-fired oven.
</P>
<P>
   The terra cotta, she said, keeps the heat even, so the bottom
doesn't scorch. When the paper browns, it is ready. When it is
finally unfolded, steam billows forth. The tomatoes and meatballs
glisten, and the pasta is perfectly al dente.
</P>
<P>
   Bondi Ristorante also serves pasta ``in cartoccio,'' Italian for
``in a bag,'' but with shellfish rather than meatballs.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking en papillote is best kept simple. Colina, an Italian
restaurant near Union Square, makes a beautiful papillote dish with
essentially three ingredients: mushrooms, Yukon gold potatoes and
rosemary. The potatoes are parboiled with garlic, tossed with
mushrooms, rosemary and a little butter and olive oil, and baked in
parchment at 400 degrees for 20 minutes. The result is earthy and
more succulent than the dish would be if it was roasted.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how simple, though, cooking successully en papillote
takes thoughtfulness and a great understanding of ingredients. You
must taste in your mind how separate ingredients will meld when
forced together in a sealed atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   You must think of how they will react to heat and how quickly
they will cook. Spinach, for instance, releases a lot of water when
steamed. Too much may dilute the natural sauce that forms inside
the package. Asparagus may take longer than ramps. Some ingredients
may turn an unpleasant color if cooked too long _ black, in the
case of basil.
</P>
<P>
   Aluminum foil is easier to use than parchment. It is simple to
fold _ you just crimp the edges shut. With parchment, you
traditionally fold the paper in half, and then make many small
folds every inch or so, at 45-degree angles, to get a tight seal
and a half-moon shape. It takes more time, and holds less securely
than foil. But it is more attractive when serving.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Foil responds to heat well and does not brown, so it will not
crumble when you open it. Parchment, on the other hand, must often
be brushed with water to keep it from browning too quickly _ though
the browning, at least, gives an idea of how quickly the contents
are cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Timing is the trickiest part of cooking en papillote. With an
oven, it's best to compare roasting times _ parchment should take
about the same time. Cooking on a stove top is roughly the same as
in a steamer.
</P>
<P>
   That drawback considered, cooking en papillote is thrilling when
it works properly. When Vongerichten assembled the vegetables and
black bass in his dish, it appeared to be nothing special. But he
had planned it precisely. The fish would take four minutes to cook.
It dictated the rest of the cooking.
</P>
<P>
   He halved the morels and peeled the asparagus so that they would
both finish cooking in exactly the same time as the fish. He
layered the components carefully: greens on the bottom for
insulation, tender quick-cooking vegetables like asparagus on top,
far from the direct heat.
</P>
<P>
   He considered flavor, too, of course. The morels softened the
green, mineral flavors of the vegetables. Enriched chicken stock
and vin jaune bonded the fish and vegetables seamlessly. Simple
ingredients and technique blossomed into an elegant dish.
</P>
<P>
   When Vongerichten cut into his dish, it was certainly no Jiffy
Pop. It was something divine. ``All the flavors are
communicating,'' he said. ``Nothing gets lost.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEAFOOD SPAGHETTI IN PARCHMENT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Salvatore Anzalone, Bondi Ristorante &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 pound spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   12 medium shrimp, shelled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces calamari, cut into rings
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   12 mussels
</P>
<P>
   12 Manila clams
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons white wine
</P>
<P>
   Juice of { lemon
</P>
<P>
   3 tomatoes, peeled, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped basil
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Nonstick cooking spray, or vegetable oil. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Bring large pot of lightly
salted water to boil. Add spaghetti, and cook until al dente, for 7
to 8 minutes. Drain well, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, in medium bowl, combine shrimp and calamari. Pat
dry with paper towels. Sprinkle flour over top, and toss to coat
lightly; shake off any excess flour. Into large deep pot over
medium-high heat, add olive oil. Add garlic, and saute for 1
minute. Add mussels and clams, and saute for 1 minute. Add shrimp
and calamari, and saute for 1 minute. Add wine, lemon juice,
tomatoes and tomato sauce. Stir to mix. Lower heat to medium, and
simmer until shellfish just begin to open up, for 1 to 2 minutes.
Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add basil; season with salt and pepper. Add spaghetti; toss
to coat with sauce.
</P>
<P>
   4. Cut 8 pieces of parchment paper into 14-inch squares, and cut
four pieces of kitchen string, each 6 inches long. To form each
parchment package, lay down two squares, one on top of the other
and at opposite angles, so that they form a star. Spray or brush
oil on the surface of the star. Place equal amounts of spaghetti,
seafood and sauce in center of each parchment star. To tie each
package, gather up the points of the star, and tie with string.
Place packages on large baking sheet, and bake until parchment is
golden brown, about 10 minutes. Transfer packages to plates, and
serve immediately, opening packages at table.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLACK BASS AND SPRING VEGETABLES IN FOIL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Jean-Georges Vongerichten, Jean Georges &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil or olive oil spray
</P>
<P>
   4 handfuls of pea shoots
</P>
<P>
   1 cup morels, cleaned
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fiddleheads, blanched (optional)
</P>
<P>
   4 6-ounce skinless fillets of black bass or halibut
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   24 ramps, trimmed and cleaned
</P>
<P>
   12 thin asparagus, ends peeled, and cut to 6 inches long; if
they are more than \ inch thick, cut in half lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons fino sherry
</P>
<P>
   { cup low-sodium chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Grape-seed or vegetable oil, to coat pan. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 1. Cut 2 rectangles of aluminum foil, each about 12 inches by
22 inches. Brush or spray each rectangle with olive oil. On half of
each rectangle, place 2 handfuls pea shoots, topped with { cup
morels and { cup fiddleheads. Season fillets with salt and cayenne
pepper to taste. Place two fillets, about two inches apart, on each
mound of vegetables. Top each pair of fillets with 12 ramps, 6
asparagus, 3 tablespoons sherry and \ cup chicken broth. Season
once more with salt.
</P>
<P>
   2. To shape packages, fold foil over fish and vegetables. Roll
open edges to seal tightly (leaving some room for air to expand),
and form a half-moon shape.
</P>
<P>
   3. Coat base of large saute pan with grape-seed or vegetable
oil. Place over medium heat until almost smoking. Add packages to
pan. When they have inflated fully in about a minute or 2, set
timer for 4 minutes. After 4 minutes, transfer packages to serving
platter, and allow to rest for 1 minute. Serve immediately, opening
packages at table.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   YUKON GOLD POTATOES AND WILD MUSHROOMS IN PARCHMENT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Jonathan Waxman, Colina &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 50 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds small Yukon gold, firm fingerlings or red bliss
potatoes, scrubbed
</P>
<P>
   12 whole garlic cloves, skins on
</P>
<P>
   { pound assorted wild mushrooms, preferably morels, porcini or
chanterelles, halved if large
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup chopped fresh rosemary, tarragon, parsley and thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 sprig rosemary
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring large pot of lightly salted water to boil, and add
potatoes and garlic cloves. Simmer until potatoes are just tender,
for about 10 minutes. Drain, and rinse with cold water. Cut
potatoes into \-inch slices; reserve garlic cloves.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In large bowl, combine potatoes,
garlic cloves, mushrooms, butter, olive oil, chopped herbs, bay
leaves and rosemary sprig. Season with salt and pepper to taste.
Cut rectangle of parchment paper about 12 inches by 24 inches, and
place it on baking sheet. Place potato mixture on half of the
paper. Fold paper over potato mixture, and roll edges together to
seal the three open sides tightly.
</P>
<P>
   3. Brush top of parchment with water. Bake until parchment is
puffed and dark brown, for 20 to 25 minutes. Transfer to serving
platter, and serve immediately, opening package at table.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
