<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISH ON A BED OF POTATOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In cooking, the whole is often greater than the sum of the
parts, and this dish is a perfect illustration. In a Mediterranean
spirit, it combines fish with four common ingredients to produce
wonderful flavor, texture and even elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are you have everything you need to make it (you'll have
to shop for fish, of course), but given the simplicity of the
process and the components, the taste is quite complex.
</P>
<P>
   You begin by cooking thinly sliced baking potatoes in flavorful
olive oil. The combination of high-heat roasting and lavish oil,
which is almost oven frying, is the easiest and most foolproof
method for producing crisp potatoes. The quantity of potatoes must
be limited so that they all brown properly _ you don't need one per
serving _ but then they are essentially a garnish for the fish.
</P>
<P>
   The potatoes also roast with a handful of bay leaves, absorbing
the flavors of both the herb and the oil. The dish is finished with
fillets of a sturdy white fish and a generous quantity of black
olives. The combination of the rather mild flavors of white-fleshed
fish and baking potatoes with the strong bay leaves and olives is
intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe can be finished with almost any firm fish fillet.
Monkfish works very well; its sturdy texture is ideal for roasting,
since it can be removed from the pan without falling apart. But
other fillets will give similar results, including red snapper, sea
bass, pollock, wolffish, even catfish.
</P>
<P>
   I've tried this dish with just about every kind of imported
olive and, although they all work to some degree, I have some
recommendations. Stay away from heavily cured, spiced or marinated
olives; you want pure olive flavor, offset by the bay leaves only.
I've also found that green olives don't work as well as black _
their flesh is firmer and doesn't soften as quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The best olives for this dish are the good-quality, oil-cured
kind, small and shriveled. They soften and plump up a bit, and
their bitterness is greatly tamed by cooking. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED MONKFISH WITH POTATOES, OLIVES AND BAY LEAVES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 large baking potatoes, about 1 pound
</P>
<P>
   { cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   15 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 cup pitted black olives
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds monkfish fillets or those of other sturdy white fish. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Peel and thinly slice the
potatoes (a mandoline works best). Cover the bottom of a
9-by-12-inch baking pan with half the olive oil, and top with the
potatoes in a single layer. It's OK if they overlap a little.
Season with salt and pepper and top with the bay leaves and
remaining oil.
</P>
<P>
   2. Roast 10 minutes. Turn the pan back to front, shaking it a
little to bathe the potatoes in oil. Roast another 10 minutes. At
this point, the potatoes should be browning; if not, roast another
5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Top the potatoes with the olives and lay the fish on top.
Sprinkle with salt and pepper. Roast another 10 minutes more, or
until the fish is tender but not overcooked. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1631EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
