<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1839 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      05-18 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRIES ENHANCED BY TARRAGON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLAUDIA FLEMING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Eds: This is the last of eight columns by Claudia Fleming, the
pastry chef at Gramercy Tavern in New York. Her collaborator on
these columns was Melissa Clark. Next week: Thomas Keller, the chef
and owner of the French Laundry in Yountville, Calif.)
</P>
<P>
   Strawberries are best eaten cool and raw, which makes them a
true harbinger of summer. It also makes them a challenge for a
pastry chef: how to serve them interestingly without obscuring
their natural, sweet-tart goodness? My first impulse for a
strawberry dessert was a bowl of berries topped with a snowy dollop
of whipped heavy cream.
</P>
<P>
   Then I thought of tarragon. To me, it's a natural pairing, maybe
a vestige of a time when I braided together red and black licorice
strands and nibbled them from end to end. Tarragon has a licorice
perfume and a sharpness that accentuates the strawberries' luscious
sweetness. I make a syrup infused with the blanched fresh herb and
use that as a glaze for the berries and as a flavoring for the
whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of piling berries and cream between two halves of a
tender biscuit, I layer them with thin, crisp shortbread rounds. (I
couldn't resist adding one more layer of tarragonlike flavor, so
the shortbread is scented with a pinch of anise.) The soft
juiciness of the berries seems better against the crumbly, crunchy
texture of shortbread than the similar softness of a biscuit.
</P>
<P>
   The result offers all the simple pleasures of a strawberry
shortcake, but far more character.
</P>
<P>
   ANISE SHORTBREAD
</P>
<P>
   Time: 50 minutes, plus 3 hours' chilling
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon aniseed
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup confectioners' sugar, plus extra for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon anise extract
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat oven to 350 degrees. In a small pan over high heat,
toast anise seeds, stirring until fragrant, about 2 minutes.
Transfer to a plate to cool.
</P>
<P>
   2. With an electric mixer, beat butter and sugar until smooth.
Add vanilla and anise extracts, and beat well. Beat in the flour,
anise seeds and salt until just combined. Form dough into a disk,
wrap in plastic wrap, and chill for at least 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   3. Divide dough in half and roll each piece between two sheets
of waxed paper to 1/8 inch thick. Cut out rounds with a 2 1/2-inch
cookie cutter, and arrange on an ungreased baking sheet. Prick
shortbread with a fork, and bake until light brown around edges, 12
to 15 minutes. Cool on a wire rack. Dust half the shortbread with
confectioners' sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 dozen.
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY AND TARRAGON CREAM FILLING
</P>
<P>
   Time: 25 minutes, plus 30 minutes resting
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fresh tarragon leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   2 pints strawberries, hulled and sliced lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon plus 2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Anise shortbread (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring a pot of water to a boil. Fill a bowl with ice water.
Plunge tarragon into boiling water for 30 seconds, then drain, and
plunge into ice water. Drain well, squeezing out any excess
moisture.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine tarragon and corn syrup in a blender, and puree. Let
rest for 30 minutes. Toss strawberries with 2 teaspoons sugar. Let
rest for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Strain tarragon syrup through a fine sieve, discarding
solids. Toss 1 tablespoon syrup with strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   4. Whip cream with remaining sugar until thickened. Add 5
tablespoons of the tarragon syrup, and whip until soft peaks form.
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, divide half the strawberries among six plates. Top
each portion with a dollop of whipped cream and a few drops of
tarragon syrup. Cover each with a plain shortbread, then repeat the
layering of strawberries, cream and syrup. Top with a sugar-dusted
shortbread. Drizzle a ring of tarragon syrup around the plate and
serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1631EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
