<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      05-18 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPAIN'S NEW VINTNERS LEAVE RIOJA IN THE DUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As long as anyone can remember, red wine in Spain has been
synonymous with Rioja, the fertile valley of the Ebro River in the
northernmost reaches of the country, not far from the western
Pyrenees and the French border. In recent years, however, Rioja has
begun to confront some formidable competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Penedes region, southwest of Barcelona, was Rioja's biggest
challenger until recently, thanks mostly to one producer, Miguel
Torres. But now other regions of Spain are clamoring for attention
and, in some cases, making wines that prove they deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   From the Old Castile region in the north central part of the
country, the quality of wines from the Ribera del Duero and Sardon
del Duero vineyards has astonished connoisseurs. Once known
principally as the source of Vega Sicilia, Spain's most famous and
most expensive red wine, the Ribera del Duero is considered by many
experts to have surpassed Rioja as the country's most important
red-wine-producing area.
</P>
<P>
   In Navarre, producers like Chivite have revived old winemaking
skills to produce wines that rival and in some instances surpass
those of neighboring Rioja. Good wines now come from Valencia, from
Valladolid and even from La Mancha, once a jug wine wasteland,
where Carlos Falco uses techniques he learned at the University of
California to make fine cabernet sauvignon.
</P>
<P>
   And then, in the rugged mountains west of Tarragona in southern
Catalonia, there is Priorato, the most exciting new source of fine
wines on the Iberian peninsula. In the last decade, a steady stream
of enological pioneers and iconoclasts have gone there to transform
the inhospitable countryside into a wine region to rival the best
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish wine has had two great moments in the sun. The first was
in the 1870's, when phylloxera devastated the vineyards of France.
Bordeaux vintners flocked to Rioja, first to buy wine and then to
make it there. Eventually, Spanish vineyards, too, were laid low by
phylloxera.
</P>
<P>
   The second surge of interest came with the end of Spain's
political and cultural isolation following the death of Francisco
Franco in 1975. Millions of visitors rediscovered the delights of
Spanish food and wine. Most of the new developments in Spanish
winemaking are a continuation of the modernization of the industry
begun in the late 1970's and early 80's.
</P>
<P>
   Some Rioja producers, of course, continue to produce wines that
are true expressions of the tempranillo grape. In the past, too
many of these wines were burdened by the cloying effects of too
much American oak. The Contino winery in Laserna knows how to
handle oak and produces some luscious, big red wines. Compania
Vinicola del Norte de Espana (CUNE) in Haro, offers plenty of oak,
but some of its best wines, like the Imperial Reserva, handle it
nicely.
</P>
<P>
   American wine drinkers have taken enthusiastically to the Conde
de Valdemar wines of Bodegas Martinez Bujanda. These wines are
light, refreshing and fruity and have virtually nothing in common
with the classic Rioja style. My friend Gerry Dawes, a wine writer
who is probably America's premier expert on Spanish wines, hates
this stuff, but he is a traditionalist. I think it's tasty. Two
other Rioja names to watch for: Remelluri and Bodegas Muga.
</P>
<P>
   In Navarre, Bodegas Julian Chivite is the best-known producer,
and its best-known wine is, of all things, a rose. That wine is
called Gran Fuego, and it's probably a good introduction to this
producer's wines. I would prefer the Collection 125 Gran Reserva, a
tempranillo wine with some cabernet and merlot, but any Chivite
wine is worth sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, in Vilafranca del Penedes, makes a huge variety of wines
from traditional Spanish grapes and some not-so-traditional ones,
including gewuerztraminer and sauvignon blanc. Recently, I tasted
several vintages of Torres' top-of-the-line Mas la Plana Black
Label Cabernet and was very impressed. This is almost always a big,
powerful wine, good for drinking five years after the vintage but
with tremendous aging potential. It is about $30.
</P>
<P>
   At the lower end of the price scale, the simple Sangre de Toro,
made from grenache and carignane, is, at $7, invariably one of the
best buys in any wine shop.
</P>
<P>
   In the Ribera del Duero, the story of Alejandro Fernandez's
ascension from winery-equipment salesman to one of Spain's
best-known winemakers is striking, but no more so than some of the
wines he makes. Pesquera, his principal wine, is deep and dark, yet
usually smooth and elegant. Dawes has aptly compared a Pesquera
Gran Reserva to a great Pomerol.
</P>
<P>
   At their best, the wines coming down the mountain trails from
Priorato are blockbusters. They bring to mind some great
Hermitages, the Barolos of Bruno Ceretto, Guigal's Cote Roties and
a couple of Helen Turley's zinfandels. Garnacha and carinena
(grenache and carignane) are the principal grapes of Priorato, with
an occasional touch of cabernet for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is small in scale in Priorato except the prices,
which can reach $200 a bottle, and the alcoholic content of the
wines, which often tops 15 percent. The vineyards are small, the
cellars are small, and so is the quantity of wine they make.
</P>
<P>
   The Clos de l'Obac from Costers del Suriana, a blend of
cabernet, merlot and traditional Spanish grapes, is a lighter-style
Priorato and a good introduction to these wines. Alvaro Palacios'
Clos Dolfi is more in the classic vein; dark, intense and muscular.
A four-year-old Clos Dolfi probably needs five more years of bottle
age. Palacios' L'Ermita sells for about $200, and his Clos Dolfi
for about $50. Both are rare. But then so are the less expensive
Prioratos like Mas Igneus Barranc dels Closos. It should sell for
about $15, if you can find it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1633EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1867 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TECH-CENTER-HNS &LR;      05-18 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TECH-CENTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SEEKS TO CREATE HIGH-TECH BRAIN TRUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Route 128 in Massachusetts. California's Silicon
Valley. The Research Triangle of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, states are looking to universities to
provide the big research that translates into new companies and new
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But for more than a decade, New York has lagged behind, losing
millions of federal research dollars. A rare partnership between
the State University of New York and Cornell University hopes to
change that. Drawing on Cornell's research horsepower and SUNY's
legislative ties, the two institutions have created the
SUNY-Cornell Multiplier to Advance Research and Technology, or
SMART-NY.
</P>
<P>
   By linking academic research to industrial applications, the
program would help stave off the exodus of SUNY graduates to other
states, said SUNY Provost Peter Salins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids go to college here and then they leave, or they go to New
York City '' Salins said. ``The rest of the state is a demographic
wasteland. Yet that's where our SUNY institutions are.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the first-year funding of the initiative remains in doubt
while state budget deliberations are under way, Salins called
SMART-NY ``an extremely high priority'' for SUNY and predicted it
would get off the ground in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative seeks $20 million and promises to double funded
research within five years. An additional $10 million is sought to
double the number of engineering students the state graduates.
</P>
<P>
   A January report by SUNY's engineering deans said New York
``dramatically lags'' states such as California, Pennsylvania and
Michigan with similarly large public university systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those states average 50 percent more engineers per million in
population and experienced dramatically greater high-tech job
growth between 1990 and 1996,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The SMART-NY money would go to Cornell, SUNY's four university
centers and 3 health science centers, as well as the College of
Ceramics at Alfred and the College of Environmental Science and
Forestry at Syracuse. SMART-NY would focus research on four areas
in which those schools are strong: advanced materials, biomedicine,
environmental science and information technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for the state,'' said Judy Genshaft, SUNY-Albany
provost. ``If you invest in research, you can leverage your
investment and create new jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from Maryland, I was surprised at how modest this
proposal was,'' added Chris D'Elia, the school's new vice president
for research. ``It's really a drop in the bucket.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to changing the research landscape of the state,
SMART-NY also seeks to change the way legislators view the link
between invention and job growth.
</P>
<P>
   Salins dismisses what he calls the ``man-on-the-moon paradigm,''
in which researchers are given an end-goal like finding a cure for
cancer. The provost said it is more productive and cost-effective
to hire top minds and then cut them loose to pursue their
individual projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most frustrating question I get is `How is it going to pay
off?''' Salins said. ``I can't say. I just want to hire the best
people and let them do their stuff. Some of that stuff is going to
pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   SMART-NY has as its symbol the bar code familiar to anyone who
has seen a price-scanner at the supermarket. Invented at the
University at Stony Brook in 1973, the bar code spawned Symbol
Technologies of Long Island, which now employs more than 2,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just stumbled upon it,'' Salins said. ``It's not like
somebody said: `How do we make supermarkets more efficient?'''
</P>
<P>
   In Salins' vision, SMART-NY also would expand SUNY's current
emphasis on free-market competition between the campuses. Instead
of doling out money ``bureaucratically,'' he said, professors would
submit proposals to be peer-reviewed on a merit basis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Given SUNY's contentious climate, the idea has rare unanimity of
support, though faculty leaders have questioned the board of
trustees' decision not to seek funding for the initiative in its
December budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we went in to the December meeting, they were looking
at an 8.2 percent budget increase, which would have funded SMART-NY
and a host of other projects'' Vincent Aceto, the Faculty Senate
president, said recently. ``By the end of the day, it became 2.8
percent. It's like they suddenly got dyslexia.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, in a February letter to leaders of the state Senate
and Assembly, Chancellor John Ryan sought a scaled-back version of
the project: $10 million for SMART-NY and $5 million to attract
more engineering students.
</P>
<P>
   SUNY officials also are hopeful they will see some benefits from
a proposed Senate package that would plug $262.5 million a year
into economic development and higher education.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely not pie in the sky and its not going to go
away,'' Salins said. ``I think it's a total no-brainer. You can do
this or pave 20 miles of highway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
