<SLUG> BC-IRVING-BERLIN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IRVING BERLIN': NOT FOR JUST AN HOUR, NOT FOR JUST A DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the opening pages of his bland but informative biography of
Irving Berlin, Edward Jablonski makes a deft imaginative leap by
reconstructing the probable route and circumstances of the composer
and his family's emigration to the United States from czarist
Russia in the early 1890s.
</P>
<P>
   With quick, incisive strokes, Jablonski conjures up the
nightmare journey of Moses and Leah Lipkin Beilin and their six
children (Irving, originally named Israel, the youngest, was age 4
or 5) by wagon and rail from eastern Russia (possibly Siberia) to
Antwerp, Belgium. The territory traversed was roughly the distance
between New York and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   With the persecution of Jews rampant in Europe and
transportation primitive, the journey was extremely arduous, but
somehow the Beilins completed it without a major mishap. Its final
leg was a grueling passage across the Atlantic in steerage crowded
with other immigrants, many of them frightened and seasick.
</P>
<P>
   These scenes, reconstructed from various accounts of the
immigrant experience of the time, are the most vivid in a dry,
scrupulously factual biography that examines the composer's life
from a respectful, almost reverent distance. They also echo through
the rest of the biography, in which Berlin emerges as a classic
outsider intuiting the mood of the culture into which he longed to
assimilate and earning inclusion by portraying that culture's
rosier dreams of itself in his songs. Berlin did it so brilliantly
and with such sincerity that he eventually became that culture's
unofficial musical representative.
</P>
<P>
   The drive to assimilate, of course, was accompanied by the usual
outsider's anxieties. Berlin was a lifelong insomniac, subject to
episodes of depression and fits of self-doubt. He was so fiercely
protective of his copyrights that in the 1960s, when Mad magazine
published parodies of his lyrics, he initiated a fruitless lawsuit
for plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irving Berlin: American Troubadour'' skips very lightly over
Berlin's paranoid, vindictive side, which an earlier biography,
``As Thousands Cheer,'' by Laurence Bergreen, explored in more
extensive and colorful detail. Except for its inclusion of excerpts
and paraphrases from ``Irving Berlin: A Daughter's Memoir,'' the
reminiscences of Mary Ellin Barrett, the oldest of the composer's
three daughters, this book reveals little of a personal nature.
Unlike so many other biographies, ``American Troubadour'' never
presumes to read its subject's mind.
</P>
<P>
   The author leaves it for the reader, given the bare facts of
Berlin's life and his enormous output, to decipher what motivated
him. Berlin's embrace of the land he entered as a little boy was
apparently passionate and absolute. The United States may not have
had streets paved with gold, as some immigrants had been led to
believe, but it was still a far better place in which to grow up
than the land left behind with its pogroms and its grinding
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin's rise from newsboy to writer of vaudeville material to
great American songwriter was swift. His first major hit,
``Alexander's Ragtime Band'' (1911), revolutionized American pop in
somewhat the same way that rock-and-roll did nearly 50 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the book's more revealing quotes are turn-of-the-century
editorials denouncing the ragtime-flavored songs that Berlin's
mega-hit ushered in. These diatribes are remarkably similar to
later screeds against rock and rap.
</P>
<P>
   Among the great songwriters of the first half of this century,
Berlin was certainly the most self-consciously all-American, having
written the classic secular commemorations of Christian holidays,
``White Christmas'' and ``Easter Parade,'' as well as that
unofficial national anthem, ``God Bless America.'' That
Americanness reached a peak of snappy sophistication in the
quasi-Western razzle-dazzle of ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' whose songs
dominated the hit parade of 1946.
</P>
<P>
   From relatively early days, Berlin's patriotism was a major
theme of his career. His two military revues, ``Yip! Yip! Yaphank''
(1918) and ``This Is the Army'' (1942), are virtually forgotten
today. But these humorous celebrations of military life, each
created for a different world war, were sensations at the time.
Berlin was so carried away by it all that during World War II he
spent three years entertaining troops overseas with ``This Is the
Army.'' By then he was in his mid-50s. And as exhilarating as that
tour must have been, it was also uncomfortable, exhausting, and
fraught with obvious physical risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irving Berlin: American Troubadour'' conveys hardly any
personal flavor of the man, but it is valuable as an official
show-by-show, movie-by-movie, song-by-song account of Berlin's
career. Every show and movie on which he worked is described and
dissected, and every major song noted. The most significant songs
are analyzed, with Alec Wilder's ``American Popular Song: the Great
Craftsmen,'' frequently cited.
</P>
<P>
   If Bergreen's 1990 biography is longer, much livelier and more
enjoyable, Jablonski's is the more thorough in its survey of
Berlin's career. Together with Ms. Barrett's personal memoir, the
three books make it possible to assemble a fairly complete portrait
of both the man and his music.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `IRVING BERLIN: American Troubadour'
</P>
<P>
   By Edward Jablonski
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 406 pages. Henry Holt &AMP; Co. $35.
</P>
</TEXT>
