<HEADLINE>
THE WORLD IS NO LONGER OUR DISNEYLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday May 25)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My sister's not going to Greece and my friend is hedging on
China. Both of them blame Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek cruise was canceled a month ago when the bombing
started. Now my sister is going to Norway and Sweden instead, which
she points out are not the same as Santorini and Crete.
</P>
<P>
   My friend's China trip was set until NATO's blooper bombing of
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade after which protesters started
throwing chunks of cement through the American Embassy windows in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The China-bound traveler loves to be daring, which I can attest
to after the night in Venice when I talked her out of going home
with an accordion player. But she doesn't aim for life-threatening.
She'd be traveling with a Chinese-born colleague who is waiting to
get the all-clear from Chinese friends and reports things are
calming down since President Clinton's apology appeared on Chinese
TV.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just because these travelers are Republicans that they
blame Bill Clinton for wrecking their summer. My friend is mad at
Clinton for being ``trigger happy.'' My sister blames the president
for being too distracted by his personal mess to pay attention to
the growing Balkan crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who you blame, the world is not as friendly to us
as it was last month.
</P>
<P>
   Someone once advised that if you go anywhere in the world and
walk into a cafe with an International Herald Tribune people will
stop and talk to you. Now, perhaps, we will bring along the Irish
Times.
</P>
<P>
   We have to walk softly these days and maybe even put a maple
leaf on our backpacks. Better to let them think you're Canadian,
I've heard, than American.
</P>
<P>
   My friend says that if she goes to China she'll wear a pin that
says Australia. She figures she could pass as Australian, and the
country's not in NATO.
</P>
<P>
   It's odd not to be welcome in the world. Odd not to be flat out
adored. Everyone loves Americans. And if you're also from
California, ``go Niners.''
</P>
<P>
   That is how it was, or how we thought it was. That is how we've
acted.
</P>
<P>
   The other day someone said, ``We better go to Europe this summer
before we're not welcome anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   It's probably not that bad. Travel agents say they're advising
nothing more extraordinary than taking normal precautions. Don't
get into political debates with strangers in bars, avoid big
crowds. One also said she'd leave the ``Made in the USA'' T-shirt
at home and steer clear of American embassies.
</P>
<P>
   There's a sign of the times. Sometimes a traveler takes comfort
walking down embassy row in a foreign city and seeing the old red,
white and blue. Even a Big Mac can take you through a homesick
period when you're on the opposite end of the globe. But on the
news this week some expert advised Americans in China to avoid
McDonald's, Starbucks and other businesses connected with American
interests.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose it illustrates our ignorance of world events and our
xenophobia to be surprised that we are not universally beloved.
Many years ago in Jamaica some men passed our group and raised
their fists, and at first I thought they were just waving. Once in
Berlin an old man stared at us in a crosswalk and muttered
``auslander,'' the German word for foreigner.
</P>
<P>
   A California friend approached a group of students in Zagreb a
few years ago to ask about conditions in postwar Croatia and was
told, ``Why don't you just leave us.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when things are going our way, we're not known for being
gracious visitors. A woman who leads small tour groups around the
world said she always tells her clients to practice a few
pleasantries in the language of the host country. Hello, thank you
and please. Especially please.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have a reputation for traveling in hordes, mowing down
the populace of a village to get to the next place in the
guidebook. We're always in a hurry. We can't read the menus and we
get impatient when the waiter doesn't understand English. And why
is there no ketchup for the french fries?
</P>
<P>
   We go into Islamic countries wearing tank tops and shorts. And
then we're shocked because German women sunbathe topless.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to make the good guest effort. I like this hint I got
from an American who travels to France a lot and has never been
treated rudely. She advises basic manners. Don't walk into a shop
and blurt out, ``Where are the umbrellas?''
</P>
<P>
   First you say, ``Good afternoon. I'm sorry I don't speak French.
Do you speak English? I'm looking for an umbrella.'' If you can say
it in French all the better. Either way, she promises, you'll get
your parapluie and win needed points for America.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
