<SLUG> BC-DULCE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LATIN CARAMEL SAUCE WENDS ITS WAY INTO THE MAINSTREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By FLORENCE FARICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dulce de Leche, a homey caramel that has long satisfied the
Hispanic sweet tooth, is suddenly finding a wider audience. It has
the potential to rival vanilla and chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   It's name literally translates to ``sweet from milk.'' It first
went mainstream as an ice cream flavor when it was marketed by
Haagen-Dazs last year. The company originally distributed it only
in Argentina and later found that when it supplied supermarkets
across the United States, it could barely keep up with the demand.
</P>
<P>
   Dulce de leche has already become the No. 2 seller behind
vanilla in some markets, said a spokeswoman for Haagen-Dazs.
</P>
<P>
   Now smooth caramel dulce de leche (pronounced DOOL-say duh
LAY-chay) has become a favorite among chefs. Not surprisingly, it
is on the menu at places that specialize in Latin-inspired cooking,
including Sonora, Bolivar, Calle Ocho, Patria and Tapika.
</P>
<P>
   It is also turning up in French and American restaurants. And
home cooks may soon find it is as handy to have in the kitchen as
chocolate sauce, to spoon over ice cream or slather on waffles, as
a substitute for honey in baking recipes or as a glaze for bananas
or cakes.
</P>
<P>
   Dulce de leche is made by simmering sweetened milk until it
turns thick and amber. In Mexico it is often made with goat's milk
and called cajeta (ca-HAY-tuh), a term derived from cajas, the
little wooden boxes in which it used to be sold.
</P>
<P>
   Peruvians know it as manjar and Colombians as arequipe. It's
served as a pudding, added as a flavoring, and used to fill cookies
or to make a fudge-like candy.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, dulce de leche is still most common as an
ice cream flavor. Starbucks developed it as one of its first
noncoffee flavors for ice cream. Ciao Bella sells its version in
its shop on the Upper East Side and at Mangia and Wall Street in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Those products all feature a caramel swirl, but Cones in
Greenwich Village offers a dulce de leche ice cream that is
intensely caramel through and through. At La Fourchette, dulce de
leche ice cream is made in house and served alongside a caramel
tart with nuts and dried cranberries.
</P>
<P>
   Dulce de leche is also turning up in other desserts,
particularly flan. Vandam, an eclectic SoHo restaurant whose chef,
Fernando Trocca, is from Argentina, serves one version. At the
Tonic, Stephane Motir, the French-born pastry chef, makes one with
passion fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Picker, the chef and owner of Campo in Greenwich Village,
uses dulce de leche. Chita Marasigan, his pastry chef, fills crepes
with the caramel and drizzles the sauce over bread pudding. At
Patria, Douglas Rodriguez makes cylindrical churros, which are
donuts, and fills them with dulce de leche.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palomino, a Colombian and the chef and owner of Sonora,
uses the caramel in a dozen desserts, not just Latin ones like
flan, but also in tiramisu, cheesecake, chocolate poundcake,
eclairs and napoleons. (No dulce de leche creme brulee yet.) The
cheesecake is sold both at the restaurant and by mail from
Palomino's new retail and wholesale company, Dulce de Leche Baking.
It will soon start selling dulce de leche oatmeal cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Dulce de leche is also an added attraction in the Peruvian-style
shortbread cookies made by Catamount Cookies in Manchester, Vt.,
that are filled with manjar and sold as Sweet Dreams. Zabar's in
Manhattan, has them for $3.99 a bag (about 3.5 ounces).
</P>
<P>
   Dulce de leche is easy to make. You can use just whole milk and
sugar, with a pinch of baking soda to help the rich color develop.
Some recipes call for cornstarch as a thickener, especially when
using goat's milk, which has a fat structure different from cow's
milk.
</P>
<P>
   Most chefs simply use sweetened condensed milk, leaving the
unopened cans simmering in water to cover for about two hours, a
process that reduces and caramelizes the milk. You might not want
to try it at home, since the cans can become overheated and
explode. Palomino said he does it that way because it's convenient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they say it's dangerous,'' he said, ``but it's the way
we always did it from the time I was a child and we never had a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Eagle Family Foods in Tarrytown, N.Y., a manufacturer of
sweetened condensed milk, warns against it. Instead, the company
suggests draining the can into a pie plate, covering it with foil
and baking it in a water bath in a 425-degree oven for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The results are quite similar to the boil-a-can method and more
custardy than when the caramel is made from scratch. I found the
caramel was better when the milk was baked two hours, with the
water bath replenished after one hour. Sweetened condensed milk can
also be turned into dulce de leche in a glass container in a
microwave oven, but the process takes more than 30 minutes and is
extremely tedious because it requires constant stirring.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way is to buy it. Dulce de leche is sold in jars, $7
for 16 ounces at Dean &AMP; DeLuca in Manhattan. Cajeta in jars is
available at Kitchen Market, $3.95 for 10 ounces, and at
Gabriela's, $3.50 for 10 ounces. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DULCE DE LECHE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Rafael Palomino, Sonora &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 quart whole milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   Pinch cinnamon. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine ingredients in a large heavy saucepan. Place over
medium heat and cook without stirring until mixture boils, 15 to 20
minutes. Briefly remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   2. Reduce heat to low and cook, stirring frequently with a
wooden spoon, 45 minutes to one hour. When mixture becomes a
caramel color and is thick enough that you can see the bottom of
the pan as you stir, remove it from heat. Use at room temperature
or cover and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   Note: For cajeta, substitute goat's milk for cow's milk, add 2
teaspoons cornstarch. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DULCE DE LECHE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Rafael Palomino, Sonora &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 quart whole milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   Pinch cinnamon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine ingredients in a large heavy saucepan. Place over
medium heat and cook without stirring until mixture boils, 15 to 20
minutes. Briefly remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   2. Reduce heat to low and cook, stirring frequently with a
wooden spoon, 45 minutes to one hour. When mixture becomes a
caramel color and is thick enough that you can see the bottom of
the pan as you stir, remove it from heat. Use at room temperature
or cover and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   Note: For cajeta, substitute goat's milk for cow's milk; add 2
teaspoons cornstarch.
</P>
</TEXT>
