 CHRON  
 
These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Food section
plans to move Tuesday, May 18, on the New York Times wire.
Questions? Please call Lesli Neilson at 415-777-6044. &HT;     
 
EL CERRITO, Calif. _  RICE  _ Six years ago, Ken Lee and Caryl
Levine went to China to find a business that would captivate them.
Any business. The young couple spent a week hanging out in
Beijing's rock-and-roll underground, exploring the idea of bringing
Western concerts to China. Instead, two months later, they returned
home with rice _ unusual kinds such as black, red and exotic white. &HT;    With sources of rice, cooking tips and recipes. 
 By Janet Fletcher 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _  &UR; DINING SOLO &LR;  _ I like dining alone. For me, a good
meal can be as restorative as a massage or a long walk on the
beach. Concentrating on the food and how it makes me feel is a rare
treat that often gets lost when I'm eating with others. But for
many people _ and the world at large _ dining solo can carry an
undeserved stigma. The implication is that, if you can't find a
dining partner, you must be unhappy. After all, would anyone really
choose to go to dinner alone?
<P>
   &UR; By Robin Davis &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _  &UR; LEARN-Lamb Shanks &LR;  _ Lamb shanks are a simple and
thrifty dish to serve for family or company _ and they taste
wonderful. With just a little preparation, they practically cook
themselves on top of the stove. You need to do very little other
than to allow them enough time.
</P>
<P>
   With tips and recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Marion Cunningham &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
