<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE :  Prepared Cookie Dough Takes All the Chips    By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
 SAN FRANCISCO _  There was a day when chocolate chip cookies were
considered so easy to make, mothers whipped up a batch just in time
for after-school snacks for the kids. But now that everyone is
looking for time-saving bdtechniques, premade cookie dough is big
business.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted seven commercial chocolate chip cookie
doughs: four refrigerated and three frozen. Some are preformed into
cookies; others must be spooned or sliced.
</P>
<P>
   The packages range in weight from 16 to 18 ounces, but prices
vary by as much as $2.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tom's &LR;  (16 ounces, $4.99 in the refrigerator case at some
markets) _ the most expensive brand _ took top honors. Three
panelists loved the added oatmeal, although one didn't like the
rough texture. Four would buy it; one might.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to &UR; Mrs. Fields &LR;  (16 ounces, $4.69 in the
freezer case at many markets). Two panelists didn't care for the
gray color, and others thought the cookie was too big and
``clunky.'' Two might buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring just below Mrs. Fields was  &UR; Trader Joe's  &LR; ($16 ounces,
$2.99 in the freezer case), one of the least-expensive brands. Two
panelists liked the chocolate chunks, but another thought the
cookies needed more of them. One panelist commented that this
cookie looked the most homemade but lacked flavor. Two would buy
it, one might buy it and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth place went to  &UR; Nestle  &LR; (18 ounces, $3.49 in the
refrigerator at many supermarkets), which was just below Trader
Joe's. If the chips were better, one panelist said, it would be the
perfect cookie. One would buy it, two might buy it and two would
not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Safeway  &LR; (18 ounces, $2.99 in the refrigerator case) came in
fifth. Two panelists thought there were too many chips, but three
others liked the texture. Others complained the flavors were
disappointing. Two might buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Pillsbury and Otis Spunkmeyer, but both
brands scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Patricia
Hart, dietitian and consultant; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For
All Seasons, San Francisco; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati,
San Francisco. All products are tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
