<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1879 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUICKCOOK-SFCHRON &LR;      05-18 1934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUICKCOOK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here is a recipe to make on the weekend, with enough
leftovers to use throughout the week in two other recipes plus
suggested ideas for other dishes. Recipes follow, plus suggestions
in optional trim. 
 &HT;     THE WEEKEND COOK: The Versatility of Salmon Fillets  &HT;     By Maria Cianci  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; From its richly textured, wonderfully flavored
meat to its silvery blue-black skin that could inspire the House of
Versace, salmon is among the world's most aristocratic fish.
<P>
   But when it comes to cooking, salmon doesn't require fancy
handling. Broiling is one of the simplest cooking methods for whole
salmon fillets. Under the broiler's intense heat, a thin layer of
exterior fish becomes crusty while the interior retains its prized
buttery-moist texture. Salt, pepper and olive oil are all the fish
needs to cook, and a spicy sauce-condiment, such as the one
included in the Master Recipe, is a fine accent to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon fillets are naturally thicker at one end, so the fish
will be cooked at different times. To ensure moist meat from head
to tail, cut each fillet into two pieces _ thick and thin _ as
described in the Master Recipe. This is easy to do, or you can have
the fish seller do it for you.
</P>
<P>
   Once cooked, the skin slides off the fillets like a glove. If
you serve the salmon skinless, save the skin and crisp it to use as
a garnish for salads. To do this, saute pieces of cooked skin in a
pan over medium-high heat, salt and pepper them and scatter them
over mixed greens.
</P>
<P>
   Other dishes for leftovers are easy, too. Salmon's flavor pairs
beautifully with many herbs and a binload of spring-into-summer
produce.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; More Ideas for Leftovers &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Broiled salmon will keep in the refrigerator for up to 3 days.
Fast weekday dishes with leftover salmon and asparagus include:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Salmon-Asparagus-Corn Soup &LR; . Flake leftover cooked salmon into
large pieces. Cut leftover cooked asparagus on the bias into 1-inch
pieces. Heat a can of corn kernels and liquid and salmon fumet from
the Weekend Recipe in a medium pan over high heat. When it reaches
a boil, add the asparagus and salmon. Simmer for 1 minute. Add
half-and-half and season with salt, pepper and chopped dill. Simmer
1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Salmon-Stuffed Tomatoes. &LR;  Hollow out large, ripe tomatoes.
Season with salt and pepper. Combine flaked salmon with minced
onion, chopped basil, finely chopped, sauteed zucchini and small
croutons. Fill the tomatoes with this mixture. Drizzle with olive
oil. Top with grated cheese. Bake at 425 degrees until heated
through and the tomatoes start to become soft, about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Asparagus with Creamed Salmon. &LR;  Saute a chopped onion until it
is golden. Add cream and simmer until it is reduced by half. Add a
little chopped tarragon, salt and pepper; simmer 1 minute. Add
finely flaked leftover salmon. Simmer 1 minute. Pour over heated
leftover asparagus spears.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Salmon-Cucumber Salad. &LR;  Halve some Sweet 100 cherry tomatoes.
Dress with chopped mint, olive oil, vinegar, salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Mince fresh mint leaves and scallions, thinly slice
thin-skinned, seedless cucumbers.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the mint, scallions and cucumbers with yogurt or sour
cream and season with salt and pepper. Transfer to a platter and
top with flaked leftover salmon. Pour the tomatoes over all.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Salmon Kedgeree. &LR;  Saute a minced onion and minced garlic clove
until the onion is wilted. Add curry powder to taste and saute,
stirring, for 30 seconds. Add a little salmon fumet from the
Weekend Recipe; boil for 1 minute. Add flaked leftover salmon and 2
minced hard-cooked eggs. Simmer 30 seconds. Season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Add cooked rice to the sauce, tossing constantly until all the
liquid is absorbed. Add some chopped parsley. Mound the rice on a
serving platter. Garnish with a hard-cooked egg cut into wedges.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN RECIPES)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MASTER RECIPE: BROILED SALMON WITH PIQUANT CHILE-HERB SAUCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Note: Seed one chile for a mildly fiery sauce or include the
seeds of both chiles for searing heat.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons bland vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 large shallots, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 fresh red chiles, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup minced cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup minced fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   1 salmon (preferably Atlantic), 10 to 10 1/2 pounds, scaled,
filleted, head, bones and trimmings reserved
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper as needed
</P>
<P>
   1 generous tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To prepare the sauce:  &LR; Combine the lemon juice, oil, shallots,
chiles and 3/4 teaspoon salt. Let stand for at least 1 hour. Five
minutes before serving, stir in the cilantro and mint. Use this
generous cup of sauce as a condiment for the broiled salmon and
asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Using a tweezers or needle-nose pliers, remove the pin bones
from the salmon fillets, pulling each thin, long bone in the
direction it runs. Using a sharp knife, cut each fillet into 2
pieces, the thicker front piece and the thinner tail piece. The
skin is difficult to cut with a knife. After you have cut through
the flesh, use kitchen shears to finish cutting through the skin.
</P>
<P>
   Place the 4 pieces of fish on a shallow-sided baking tray, the
tail ends on one side of the tray, the thick sections on the other
side. Lightly season the fish with salt and pepper, then brush with
olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Broil the fish as close to the heat source as possible until
just cooked through, 12 to 14 minutes for the thin sections, 20 to
22 minutes for the thick sections. The fish will be delicate. Using
metal spatulas, carefully transfer 1 thick and 1 thin section to a
serving tray, surround it with broiled asparagus (see recipe) and
spoon a little sauce on fish and vegetable. Serve additional sauce
on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Cool the remaining fillet to room temperature and wrap and
refrigerate it for use during the week. It will keep for up to 3
days.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6, with leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER 6-OUNCE PIECE OF SALMON: &LR;   &LR; 240 calories, &LR;   &LR; 34 g protein, 0
g &LR;   &LR; carbohydrate, 11 g fat (2 g saturated), 94 mg cholesterol, 75 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER 1 TABLESPOON SAUCE: &LR;   &LR; 40 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 g protein, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 4 g fat (1 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 101 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 0 g fiber.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKEND RECIPE: BROILED ASPARAGUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds asparagus, tough ends removed, stalks peeled
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse the asparagus spears, but do not dry them. Place them in a
single layer on a shallow-sided baking tray. Sprinkle lightly with
salt and pepper, then drizzle with olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Broil as close to the heat source as possible until
crisp-tender, 6 to 10 minutes, depending on size.
</P>
<P>
   Serve 5 or 6 spears per person, hot, warm or at room temperature
with the broiled salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6, with leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 45 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 4 g carbohydrate, 3
g &LR;   &LR; fat (0 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 2 mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKEND RECIPE: SALMON &LR;   &UR; FUMET &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Reserved head, backbone and trimmings from the salmon (Master
Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   12 cups water
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   If the backbone is in one long piece, snap it in 5 or 6 spots.
Place it with the trimmings and head in a large bowl. Cover with
cold water, remove any blood clots, swish the pieces around and
soak them for 30 minutes, draining and changing the water once.
Drain well.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the trimmings, onion and the 12 cups water in a stock
pot. (If the meaty trimmings are few, reduce the water to about 8
cups.) Cover and bring to a boil over high heat. When the water
starts to boil, reduce heat, skim the surface and simmer gently for
30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the liquid, let cool to room temperature, cover and
refrigerate for up to 5 days. The fumet may also be frozen in 1-cup
portions for up to 2 months.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 10 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CUP: &LR;   &LR; 30 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 2 g carbohydrate, 0 g
fat &LR;   &LR; (0 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 100 mg sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: SCALLOPED POTATOES WITH SALMON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Note: This comfort dish is simple, delicious and satisfying. It
should be slightly liquid. It takes longer to cook than most
Weekday Quick Cook recipes, but the baking time is unattended and
the dish is very easy to put together.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flaked broiled salmon (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons (generous) minced fresh dill
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup salmon fumet (from Weekend Recipe), or water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter + butter for baking dish
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 pounds waxy white-skinned potatoes, cut into 1/8-inch
slices
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the salmon and dill; toss thoroughly but gently.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the cream and salmon fumet in a small saucepan and scald
the mixture over high heat. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly butter the bottom and sides of an oval 14 x 9 1/2-inch
(or similar size) baking dish. Line the bottom of the dish with a
layer of slightly overlapping potato slices. Lightly season with
salt and pepper. Repeat with another layer of potatoes, seasoning
them lightly. Spread the salmon evenly over the potatoes. Top with
2 more layers of potatoes, seasoning each.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the cream mixture evenly over the top. It should reach
about three quarters of the way up the potatoes. Dot with butter,
especially the center.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until the top is browned and the cream bubbles up around
the edges, 55 to 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Let cool for 15 minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 555 calories, &LR;   &LR; 16 g protein, 45 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 36 g fat (20 g saturated), 147 mg cholesterol, 89
mg sodium, 3 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: SALMON WITH THAI-INSPIRED RED CURRY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Note: This dish comes together quickly and is especially easy
with a packaged Thai-style red curry mix. A Taste of Thai produces
a good one that is available in many supermarkets. Look for
preservative-free coconut milk at natural foods stores.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces fresh ginger, peeled and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon + 1 teaspoon Thai red curry paste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup salmon fumet (see Weekend Recipe), or water
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unsweetened coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   4 pieces skinless cooked salmon, about 4 ounces each (from
Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Process the onion, garlic and ginger in a food processor until
finely minced.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a nonstick saute pan over high heat. Add the
onion mixture; saute, stirring frequently, until it turns golden,
about 4 minutes. Add the curry paste and saute, stirring
constantly, until the color darkens, about 30 seconds. Do not let
it burn.
</P>
<P>
   Add the fumet, sugar and salt; simmer for 1 minute. Add the
coconut milk and lemon juice. Simmer for 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the salmon, basting it with the sauce. Cover, reduce heat
and simmer until the fish is just heated through, about 3 minutes.
Stir in the cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the fish with some of the sauce spooned over it.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 425 calories, &LR;   &LR; 34 g protein, 10 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 28 g fat (14 g saturated), 99 mg cholesterol, 547
mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1700EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
