<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1883 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SECRET-FILET-SFCHRON &LR;      05-18 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-FILET-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. &HT;     &HT;     By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SONOMA, Calif. _  &LR; It's a marvelous triad _ beef, lavender and black
pepper. But it took John McReynolds at Cafe La Haye to bring it to
everyone's attention.
<P>
   Most people might not even recognize the taste of lavender when
it's pressed into a filet mignon and seared, but it brings out a
hidden sweetness in this lean, tender cut.
</P>
<P>
   This charming restaurant is one of the most exciting to open in
Sonoma in the last several years. That says a lot, considering that
this 32-seat cafe, located just off the square, is so small and
unassuming.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning courses _ organic greens with blue cheese,
beets and spiced walnuts and house-smoked salmon on warm potato
cakes _ to the Meyer lemon cheesecake for dessert, the
American-inspired food is enticing.
</P>
<P>
   The open kitchen is about the size of a postage stamp, carved
out of one corner of the two-tiered interior.
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds and partner Saul Gropman, who handles the front of
the house, make a great team. Not only is the food excellent, but
the service is smooth and seamless and the prices are moderate.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Cafe La Haye, 140 E. Napa St., Sonoma; (707) 935-5994. &LR; 
 &LR; Dinner Tuesday-Saturday, brunch Saturday-Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SECRETS OF SUCCESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lavender and black pepper crust.  &LR; The spiciness of the pepper
and the herbal qualities of the herb work together to bring out a
sweetness in the filet mignon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The red wine butter.  &LR; Through intense reduction, the butter is
packed with flavor and tames any rough edges of the bold
seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SEARED BLACK PEPPER-LAVENDER FILET OF BEEF &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 filet mignon steaks, each 11/2 inches thick and about 51/2-6
ounces
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon whole dried lavender blossoms
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coarsely ground pepper (preferably Tellicherry)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Red Wine Butter (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Season both sides of each steak with salt. Mix together the
lavender and pepper and press the mixture into both sides of the
steaks.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the butter and oil in a large cast-iron frying pan over
high heat. Add the steaks and fry for 2 minutes on each side.
Transfer to the oven and roast for 5 minutes. Remove to heated
plates and let rest for 2 to 3 minutes, then top each steak with a
dollop of Red Wine Butter.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 265 calories, &LR;   &LR; 30 g protein, 0 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 16 g fat (6 g saturated), 95 mg cholesterol, 75 mg sodium, 0 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; RED WINE BUTTER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pound chuck or other stewing beef, cut into cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 celery stalk, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, smashed
</P>
<P>
   1 thyme sprig
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle (750ml) dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a heavy saute pan over medium heat. Add the meat
and brown well on all sides. Do not crowd the pan; work in batches,
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Add the vegetables and saute until they begin to caramelize,
stirring often.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the garlic and herbs, then add the tomato paste and
wine.
</P>
<P>
   Cook for about 1 hour over medium heat, or until the liquid has
reduced by three-quarters.
</P>
<P>
   When the meat is tender and the wine is reduced, pass the
mixture through a food mill.
</P>
<P>
   Mix with the softened butter, either by hand or in a food
processor.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 385 calories, &LR;   &LR; 12 g protein, 3 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 36 g fat (21 g saturated), 114 mg cholesterol, 306 mg sodium, 1 &LR; 
 &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1888 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DININGSOLO-SFCHRON &LR;      05-18 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DININGSOLO-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINING OUT ALONE CAN BE A RELAXING INDULGENCE  &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   &HT;     By Robin Davis 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; As I slid into my seat at Aqua one recent
evening, the worries of the day faded into distant memory. Now all
I had to think about was what to order. Should I start with the
black mussel souffle or the crab cake special? Should I have a
glass of wine or splurge on a half bottle? And what about dessert?
If only all decisions could have such pleasurable outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   As I mulled over the choices, my server poured water into each
of the glasses at two place settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm dining alone,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' he replied, looking momentarily startled. He apologized
for the table being set for two and immediately cleared the other
setting as though it might be an unhappy reminder of my solitary
state.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   I like dining alone. For me, a good meal can be as restorative
as a massage or a long walk on the beach. Concentrating on the food
and how it makes me feel is a rare treat that often gets lost when
I'm eating with others.
</P>
<P>
   But for many people _ and the world at large _ dining solo can
carry an undeserved stigma. The implication is that, if you can't
find a dining partner, you must be unhappy. After all, would anyone
really choose to go to dinner alone?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is a resounding yes _ for many reasons. Business
travelers often eat alone. Others cherish dinner as a private time.
Still others use a neighborhood restaurant as their kitchen away
from home, stopping in for dinner after a long day at work rather
than going to the grocery store or picking up fast food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always done this for as long as I can remember,'' says
Marybeth Beeson of Cupertino, who frequently dines alone at many
restaurants in the Bay Area and throughout the country. ``I use the
time to collect my thoughts. And often I bring materials so it's a
working-dining experience.''
</P>
<P>
   While many people stop in their local sushi bar or neighborhood
trattoria on their own, they wouldn't dream of calling a fine
dining restaurant for a single reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'd feel weird having dinner alone at Aqua,'' says
Stacy Macklin, sales manager from Los Angeles who travels
frequently for business and has eaten alone at San Francisco
restaurants like the more casual Plouf. ``That type of experience
is so amazing that I want to share it with someone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steven Okuley, a consultant from Denver who travels as much
as three weeks a month, does just the opposite. ``I seek out the
better restaurants in the cities I'm visiting,'' he says. ``I like
to see the best they have to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Different restaurants handle single diners in various ways. Some
are enthusiastic about them; others less so, seeing the empty seat
on the other side of the table as potential lost revenue. Many
restaurants try to put people eating alone in places where they'll
be surrounded by other diners, subtly implying that single diners
may feel conspicuous otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   When I made a reservation for one at Aqua, I was told that the
restaurant serves the full menu at the bar, a common response. When
I made a reservation at Chez Panisse, I was asked if I wanted to
dine in the more casual cafe upstairs. And some single diners, in
fact, do enjoy a bustling atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ``I like sitting at a counter because you're across from the
bartender so it doesn't look like someone else has to be there,''
Macklin says. ``You have more interaction with people at the bar.
It's more casual and comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Okuley disagrees. ``I prefer a table because I want to
experience the dining atmosphere as part of a meal,'' he says.
``Often it's a more quiet place to read if that's what I'm going to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   My preference depends on the situation, but I found my recent
dinner at a table at Aqua far more pleasurable than it would have
been at the bar. At 6 p.m. on a weeknight, the bar was packed with
an after-work crowd jostling for position and posturing for
co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   My table, on the other hand, afforded a view of the Financial
District, of people walking by and of the traffic in which,
thankfully, I did not have to take part.
</P>
<P>
   That placement is no coincidence. Restaurants in tune with solo
diners frequently give them seats by the window or other locations
within the dining room so they can have something to look at
besides a painting on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Bryant, manager of The Dining Room at the Ritz-Carlton
San Francisco, which gets as many as 20 solo diners a week, says he
tries to seat them near the front of the restaurant so they can
watch what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   When I ate alone at Chez Panisse, the maitre d' gave me what he
called his favorite seat in the dining room. I agreed _ it was
close enough to the kitchen to watch the dishes being prepared, and
at Chez Panisse, where food is an almost religious experience, this
is a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   However, some restaurants are less enthusiastic about single
diners taking up table space. Shaun Ellis, manager at Bizou in San
Francisco, says that while the restaurant doesn't discourage single
diners, it also doesn't want to be billed as a restaurant for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a romantic restaurant,'' Ellis explains. ``And we lose
money on single diners.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bill for one versus two people can vary widely. When I
dined at Aqua, I ordered an appetizer, entree, dessert and two
glasses of wine. The table of two next to me ordered only entrees
and iced tea, so my bill was higher.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, at Chez Panisse, where the menu is prix fixe,
I did spend less than two people would have. Yet service could not
have been more gracious. Both the maitre d' and the wine steward
stopped by my table several times, inquiring about how I was
enjoying dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Marybeth Beeson says she often finds service more attentive when
she dines alone. ``In general, service is better,'' she says.
``Waiters seem to bend over backwards and are more willing to
strike up a conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Okuley agrees. ``The wait staff is often inquisitive
about what brings you to the area,'' he says. ``I often have more
interaction with them than if I have a dining companion.''
</P>
<P>
   Roland Passot, chef/owner of La Folie in San Francisco and Left
Bank in Larkspur and Menlo Park, sees single diners as an
investment. ``For me, the single customers are very important,'' he
says. ``A lot of single diners are my regular customers. They come
here more often than parties of two or four.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Some solo customers, he says, want to be entertained, so he stops
by the table and instructs his staff to talk more to them. Others
want to be left alone, in which case he might just say hello at the
end of the meal.
</P>
<P>
   Passot believes that if single diners have a good experience,
they'll come back another time with their friends or spouses.
</P>
<P>
   As a restaurant critic, I eat out almost every night _ usually
with others _ and it's a joy. Occasionally I slide into someplace
casual by myself for a quick bite. But I've also found that solo
dining at an elegant restaurant can be a treat as satisfying as
buying a new outfit or having an all-day spa treatment. In this
case, the luxury is the food.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
