<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPMAN-TEXASATLARGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELL-DRESSED STUMP WAVES `HOWDY' TO FOLKS NEAR ROBY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   West Texans have always been known as friendly people. They wave
as they pass on the highway. They wave from the sidewalks and
storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   Out near Roby _ in the community of Busby _ north of Sweetwater,
they even have a tree stump that waves to you when townsfolk aren't
available.
</P>
<P>
   It's true.
</P>
<P>
   The weathered stump is well-known in the region, though no one
knows for sure how old it is. Sheree Hartman says her family has
been dealing with it for the past 30 years, and the old-timers at
the rest home in Rotan say they knew about it 20 years before that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started when I was 12,'' Hartman said. ``Me and my best
friend, Sharon Justice, who lives just up the road, always thought
that old stump looked like a farmer waving at us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were working together as janitors at the Longworth Baptist
Church and one day we decided to dress that stump in farmer's
clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartman said the stump remained a farmer for a long time, but,
eventually, Hartman's mother, Dorothy Thompson, changed the look.
Every holiday, Thompson, who was known in the Roby area as ``Mama
Dot,'' altered the stump's wardrobe. Santa at Christmas, different
things for Thanksgiving, Independence Day, etc.
</P>
<P>
   She soon became known as ``The Stump Lady.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to give Mama credit for creating the Stump Lady,''
Hartman said. ``She did a lot of it, but the whole family helped.
Now I do most of it with the help of my baby sister, Shelly.''
</P>
<P>
   Mama Dot died two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a holiday marked on the calendar, Hartman, her
husband and sister all go out to the stump on Texas 70, just south
of the intersection of Farm Road 57, and administer the appropriate
paint and paper, clothing and adornments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sometimes catch some of those holidays where we don't even
know what they are,'' Hartman said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Her two brothers live nearby and they also help. Another sister
used to help, but she lives in Irving now.
</P>
<P>
   The family just finished Mother's Day and is busy preparing the
stump for Memorial Day and the Roby High School graduation. Some of
the same decorations will be used for both.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman intends to use the cap and gown she saved from her
graduation at Howard College in Big Spring. They will serve for the
Roby graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the wig and foam head she uses will also sit atop the
military uniform _ boots, helmet and all _ for Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't know for sure if there will be a flag. There was one
last year, but someone stole it.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first theft. A few years ago some kids from
Breckenridge took off with the giant snake Mama Dot had designed to
celebrate the Sweetwater Rattlesnake Roundup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cops caught them,'' Hartman said. ``They told them to
bring it back, but they never did.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Hartman found a big sofa cover at the Dollar Store
and her sister made it into another snake.
</P>
<P>
   Thefts or not, she'll keep on decorating the stump, she said. It
helps to welcome travelers along the highway; it helps her remember
Mama Dot. It keeps the family working together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe our kids will do it after us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on things Texan for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail:
Artc(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
