<HEADER>
A1901 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSIC-GIMB-SFCHRON &LR;      05-18 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSIC-GIMB-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Bay Area Classics profiles food-related businesses
more than a half century old.  
 &HT;     BAY AREA CLASSICS: Your Gummy Mummies Came from Gimbal  &HT;     By Maria Cianci 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &UR; SOUTH SAN FRANCISCO, Calif. _  &LR; You may not recognize Gimbal candy
by name, but have you bought the jelly candies at See's? Or the
licorice at the candy shop in FAO Schwarz at Union Square in San
Francisco? Then Gimbal has sated your sweet tooth.
<P>
   From sour worms, gum balls and ``Ultimate'' jelly beans to Gummy
Mummies, Nonpareil Hearts and Christmas Sour Stars, Gimbal Bros.
Inc. produces 3 million pounds of the chewy, gel-based candies each
year. Gimbal's jellies are pectin-based, contain no animal products
and, says president Lance Gimbal, are the only jellies in the
United States given the strictest certified kosher rating.
</P>
<P>
   It all began in 1898. Alexander Gimbal, a Californian and the
son of a French-born Forty-Niner, bought the Pacific Steam Candy
Co., the first company west of the Rockies to use steam instead of
open-flame cooking to produce jellies. ``Steam is a safer, reusable
energy source that produces a consistent, higher-quality jelly,''
Lance Gimbal says.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander made a general line of confections, including
chocolates, hard candies, creams and jellies. A year later,
brothers Louis and Eugene joined the company, and thus was born
Gimbal Bros. Fine Candy. The company has since passed through
family hands to Alexander's great-grandson Lance and Lance's wife,
Patti.
</P>
<P>
   After several locations in San Francisco _ one, on Washington
Street, was spared in the 1906 earthquake and fire simply because,
Lance Gimbal says, ``it stood on the same block as the fire
station'' _ the company moved to its present plant in South San
Francisco in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to See's and the sweet shop in FAO Schwarz, local
customers include Macy's, Preston's in Burlingame, some of the
Disney stores and the Sweet Factory, a retail chain found in
shopping malls. The company also distributes nationally, especially
to mom-and-pop candy stores. Its biggest-selling jellies are
button-shaped orange-and-cream soft chews and quarter-size
chocolate-fudge soft chews.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, the company plans to introduce branded products
with the Gimbal name, including the Gimbal Dollar, a red-hot
cinnamon candy in honor of the company's centennial.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Gimbal's long-term plan includes more family hands. The
fifth generation is coming up _ his sons, Ross, 14, and Scott, 11,
and daughter, Marissa, 1. ``I want to build the company so that it
is available for them,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-MUSEUM-ART-     05-18 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-MUSEUM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TEACHER TAKES CHARGE OF A STIRRING HISTORY LESSON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum here has chosen
a charter member of its own staff as its director. She must preside
over a museum that has unexpectedly become one of the city's top
tourist attractions while trying to smooth over the problems
created by the acrimonious ouster of her predecessor last year.
</P>
<P>
   The new director, Sara Bloomfield, has been with the museum from
its planning stages in the mid-1980s, when the museum's mission was
first taking shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is hardly any aspect that she has not been involved
in,'' said the museum's chairman, Miles Lerman. Ms. Bloomfield, who
was appointed in February, had been acting director since the
resignation of her predecessor, Walter Reich.
</P>
<P>
   How does one prepare to direct a museum with the task of trying
to explain the murder of millions?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no course of studies,'' she said in a recent
interview. ``I'm amazed that we very much got it right, because we
were being pulled in different directions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Should it be a genocide museum?'' she continued. ``Most inside
thought no, but there were some pressures. How do you present the
Jewish centrality but also tell the story of the non-Jewish victims
of mass murder by the Nazis and the society that was able to
perpetuate this?''
</P>
<P>
   The mix that the founders came up with, presenting Jews as the
primary victims of the Holocaust but also telling of the
experiences of other victimized groups, has drawn 2 million people
to the museum every year since it opened in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether the museum's founders had any idea of the
number of visitors it would attract, she said, ``Not only did we
not have that, but we were worried that such a museum would not
attract people who were not Jewish.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum found when it opened that 65 percent of its visitors
were non-Jewish, and by last year that figure had risen to 80
percent. By comparison, Jews account for about 2.2 percent of the
U.S. population, according to the Bureau of the Census.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bloomfield said that the museum was coping with its
popularity. ``We've replaced the carpets a couple of times,
certainly at a faster pace than we had anticipated,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The director during most of the museum's successful first years
was Reich, who was forced to resign in an embarrassing episode
involving an invitation to Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader,
to visit the museum.
</P>
<P>
   First Arafat was invited, then the invitation was withdrawn, and
then he was invited again. Then Arafat declined the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Lerman blamed Reich. Reich's defenders, who included Elie
Wiesel, the Holocaust witness and Nobel Peace Prize laureate,
blamed Lerman, saying he had made Reich a scapegoat. Reich, who is
now the Yitzhak Rabin Memorial Professor of International Affairs,
Ethics and Human Behavior at George Washington University, declined
to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Sher, the former executive director of the American Israel
Public Affairs Committee, the principal pro-Israel lobby in
Washington, said of Reich: ``He was scapegoated. The blunders that
were committed by Miles Lerman regarding the Arafat debacle were
unfairly and publicly blamed on him, when the fault lay with
Lerman.''
</P>
<P>
   Lerman, however, said that Reich's departure ``was not caused by
the Arafat thing.'' Reich's ``suitability for the job was discussed
a year before,'' Lerman said. ``Elie Wiesel thought it was caused
by the Arafat dispute, but that was not the case. He was not
informed well.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bloomfield said she did not want to get drawn into the
dispute between her chairman and his critics. ``I've known Elie for
13 years, and I have a very good relationship with him,'' she said.
``Most people will judge the value of this institution by itself,
not by its personalities. Most prominent institutions have friends,
have enemies. That's the nature of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the Lerman-Reich dispute had any impact on the
museum and its fund-raising, Ms. Bloomfield said a few people had
declined to renew their memberships because of it, but the number
was minuscule compared with the 300,000-member base.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bloomfield was born in Cleveland, where she established the
first center for learning disabilities in the school system of
nearby Shaker Heights. But she decided to look for challenges
beyond the Cleveland area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had come to the point where I wanted to do something more
meaningful,'' she said, ``and there's not a lot of opportunities
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bloomfield is 48, too young to have had any direct
experience of the Holocaust. She said she first learned of it from
a Sunday school teacher at her synagogue, a former prisoner at
Auschwitz who had a number tattooed on her arm.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bloomfield grew up in a family that was active in Jewish
organizations but not very religious, she said. Her environment in
Cleveland was very comfortable, she said, and she did not encounter
anti-Semitism until she spent two years teaching in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   For one course there, Ms. Bloomfield read the class Wiesel's
moving memoir ``Night.'' ``When I was done, my best student came up
and praised it and my reading of it,'' she said. ``I told her that
my emotion was understandable because I am Jewish, and she said:
`Don't worry, your secret is safe. I won't tell anyone.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty stunned by that reaction, and later students
would say: `You're too nice. How can you be Jewish?'''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on that now, she said, ``Who knew then that I was
destined to be the director of the Holocaust Museum?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bloomfield has a bachelor's degree in English literature
from Northwestern University and a master's degree in education
from John Carroll University in Cleveland. She joined the museum's
staff in 1986, when it was in its planning stages, and has held
several positions there, including associate director. Asked
whether she was concerned that she might be dealing with a
governing board that might be aggressive in overseeing day-to-day
activities, she said she was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any memorial institution has on its board individuals whose
lives or family members' lives will have this emotional interest
that would not be there in an art museum,'' she said. ``One can
understand. They should have this interest. How could they not?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
