<HEADER>
A1906 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEARN-LAMB-SFCHRON &LR;      05-18 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARN-LAMB-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;    (Article is followed by tips and two recipes.) &HT;     LEARNING TO COOK: Lamb Shanks Practically Cook Themselves  
 &HT;     By Marion Cunningham 
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Lamb shanks are a simple and thrifty dish to serve
for family or company _ and they taste wonderful. With just a
little preparation, they practically cook themselves on top of the
stove. You need to do very little other than to allow them enough
time.
<P>
   The method of cooking lamb shanks outlined in today's recipe
brings out the best in them. First brown the shanks to develop
flavor, then slowly cook them, covered, in moist heat _ called
braising _ so they are very tender. Adding vegetables during the
last half-hour of cooking makes the whole main part of the meal
easy and, most important, very good.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN TIPS)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TIPS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Grapes.  &LR; When you buy grapes in the supermarket, ask if you can
taste one so you can be sure they are sweet. Thompson seedless
grapes are the right choice for the pleasing, simple dessert I've
included today.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Zest.  &LR; Zest is the outside, colored rind of citrus fruit. It is
the most flavorful part of the fruit and it gives food a lovely
fragrance and flavor of lemon, lime or orange.
</P>
<P>
   When removing the zest, it is important to remove only the
bright, shiny thin outer part of the peel, leaving behind the
white, bitter part of the skin (the pith).
</P>
<P>
   You can use a zester, a fine grater, a vegetable peeler or a
sharp paring knife to remove the zest. Or stack pieces of zest on
top of one another and cut very thin slices lengthwise into strips.
Chop the thin strips crosswise into very fine ``minced'' pieces.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Marion Cunningham, Bay Area cooking teacher, is the author of &LR; 
 &LR; ``Learning to Cook,'' ``Cooking With Children,'' ``The Fannie &LR; 
 &LR; Farmer Cookbook'' and ``The Breakfast Book,'' among others. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN RECIPES)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAMB SHANKS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From ``Learning to Cook With Marion Cunningham'' (Knopf, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 lemons
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   4 lamb shanks
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   6 carrots
</P>
<P>
   3 medium-size yellow onions
</P>
<P>
   4 small potatoes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Instructions: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing the Lemon and Garlic: &LR;  Grate the zest of 1 or 2
lemons to make 1 tablespoon of grated rind. After you have removed
the zest, cut the lemons in half and squeeze the juice from them.
Strain and measure about 1/4 cup.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the garlic cloves and slice each lengthwise into 4 slivers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing the Lamb:  &LR; Using a sharp paring knife, cut 4 deep
slits in the meaty part of each lamb shank, and insert a garlic
sliver into each slit.
</P>
<P>
   Put the flour, salt and pepper on a 12-inch piece of wax paper
and stir together. Spread the flour out a little and roll each
shank in it so all sides are coated. Shake off the excess.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Starting the Cooking:  &LR; Put the oil in a large heavy-bottom pot
(one with a lid) and turn the heat to medium-high. After about 15
seconds, hold your hand about an inch above the bottom of the pot.
If it feels hot, add the shanks and brown them on all sides,
keeping the heat at medium-high. This will take about 5 to 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When the shanks are all browned, turn the heat to low. Add the
bay leaf, lemon rind, lemon juice, and 1 cup of the water to the
pot. Put the lid on, and simmer the shanks over low heat for 1
hour.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing the Vegetables While the Shanks are Cooking:  &LR; Peel
the carrots and cut crosswise into 11/2-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the papery skin from the onions and cut them into
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse the potatoes, leaving them unpeeled.
</P>
<P>
   When the shanks have cooked for 1 hour, add the carrots, onions,
potatoes and the other 1 cup water to the pot and cook, covered,
for another 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Finishing and Serving the Shanks:  &LR; Remove the lid and pierce
the vegetables with a fork. If they are tender, they are done. The
shanks should also be very tender by now.
</P>
<P>
   Put the shanks on a platter and surround with the vegetables.
Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 615 calories, &LR;   &LR; 42 g protein, 48 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 28 g fat (9 g saturated), 128 mg cholesterol, 675
mg sodium, 4 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; GRAPES WITH SOUR CREAM AND BROWN SUGAR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From ``Learning to Cook With Marion Cunningham'' (Knopf, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds Thompson seedless grapes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sour cream (light sour cream is OK)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup light brown sugar, plus a little extra
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing and Chilling the Grapes:  &LR; Wash the grapes and pat
them dry with a paper towel.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the stems and put the grapes in a medium-size bowl. Cover
with plastic wrap and refrigerate. They should be good and cold
before serving.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Just Before Serving:  &LR; Put the sour cream and 1/2 cup brown
sugar in a small bowl. Using a fork, stir the ingredients together
until smooth. There should be no grainy chunks of brown sugar
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Add the sour cream and brown sugar to the grapes and stir until
all the grapes are evenly coated.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon the grapes into individual serving bowls. Sprinkle about 1
teaspoon brown sugar on top of each serving and serve right away.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 275 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 56 g carbohydrate,
7 &LR;   &LR; g fat (4 g saturated), 13 mg cholesterol, 31 mg sodium, 2 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
