<HEADLINE>
HOPE SPRINGS ETERNAL FROM ISRAELI ELECTION  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Commentary)   (This TIMELY, 475-word ``separate buy'' post-Israeli-election
commentary is from the International Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable
to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``k'' commentary news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 By GIDEON SAMET  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ The crushing fall of Benjamin Netanyahu tells an
amazing Israeli story of a bright man who changed the rules of the
local political game, and became his own victim.
</P>
<P>
   It was not his policies, though they did set Israel back, that
brought about his resonant, pathetic defeat. It was his character.
</P>
<P>
   A child when Israel was born, I have never witnessed an election
campaign here in which the main issue was the incumbent leader's
personality. And for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu was, as The Economist once dubbed him, a serial
bungler, an erratic leader for a nation in urgent need for an
orderly agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The popular slogan, referring to his nickname _ ``Just Not
Bibi'' _ ended the three-year dominance of a flawed politician over
the Israeli scene. This abysmal failure to make good on a vaulting
ambition gave his short career almost Shakespearean dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Netanyahu's self-destructive psyche, the election was
about Israel's political culture.
</P>
<P>
   In as much as they are surprisingly conservative, and still
gripped by tribal allegiances, the majority of Israelis felt they
had had enough.
</P>
<P>
   Enough of the cunning play on their angst over Arab threats.
Enough of their leader's unbearable propensity to alienate almost
all his colleagues and most of Israel's friends in the world, while
engaging his opponents with heated hate rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Opposite Netanyahu, in a meticulous Tony Blair-like campaign,
Ehud Barak smartly grasped the popular urge for reconciliation,
stability and basic common sense.
</P>
<P>
   At times, as his understated tone made some of his TV
appearances seem a disaster, his supporters despaired. But as
Netanyahu was intensifying his populist, distorted attacks on the
``leftist'' elites and on the media, he isolated himself in an
increasingly paranoid campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bibi became a burden. Barak gained momentum. He now enjoys a
rare parliamentary leeway in a political system used to choking
near-ties.
</P>
<P>
   His victory is actually a revival of the late Yitzhak Rabin's
era, which was tragically cut short in the midst of major political
and economic achievements. Barak will now have to renew that
national agenda.
</P>
<P>
   In a vague campaign of soundbites, steered by a host of American
consultants, there was, for example, hardly a mention of the
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations stopped by Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Barak remained opaque on whether his wish for a wide power base
might evolve into an embrace of the religious parties _ and a
cohabitation with the Likud party that poisoned the politics of the
1980s. This will be the stuff of criticism soon awaiting the prime
minister designate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hope is rampant. Never have so many enthusiastic
Israelis thronged in the squares to celebrate on election night, as
if it were Independence Day. They also signaled their expectation
of a new leader who would cut a new national deal. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Gideon Samet, a columnist and member of the board
of the Israeli daily Ha'aretz, contributed this commentary to the
International Herald Tribune.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this TIMELY 475-word commentary from the International
Herald Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1941 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUGS-CHILDREN-2ndTak     05-18 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-CHILDREN-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: can take it. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We want the pharmaceutical companies to provide more
information so more of the good new drugs can benefit children,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies have 20 months to comply with the new FDA
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the FDA asked drug companies to begin testing and
labeling their products for use in children. Manufacturers were
asked to survey existing data and determine whether those data were
sufficient to establish pediatric indications.
</P>
<P>
   However, in 1997, only 37 percent of the new drugs with
potential usefulness for children had some pediatric labeling.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies drag their feet because they say it is very
difficult to do double-blind studies in children, to get a large
group of parents to allow their children to be in a study in which
some will go without treatment.
</P>
<P>
   A double-blind study tests a new drug against a placebo or an
established drug with both the doctors and patients ``blinded'' as
to who is getting which formulation. Such studies are still the
gold standard for testing the effectiveness of new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Also, such studies are not financially beneficial for the drug
companies. Children account for less than 10 percent of their
revenues, Wedemeyer says.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulation requires such testing for new drugs and says
the FDA can also require testing on already-marketed products in
compelling circumstances, such as when a drug is commonly
prescribed for use in children, but the absence of adequate
labeling could pose significant risks.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA has said it will require pediatric testing in certain
classes of drugs such as steroids, anti-depressants, prescription
pain relievers, drugs for stomach and intestinal illnesses, and
asthma drugs. (There currently are no asthma drugs labeled for use
in children under 2.)
</P>
<P>
   For FDA approval of a new drug, pharmaceutical companies are
required to provide data on basic animal research studies as well
as a series of clinical studies showing the drug is safe and
effective. Until about eight years ago, almost all drug testing was
done in adult men.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in 1977, the FDA issued guidelines that effectively
banned women of child-bearing age from participating in early
clinical trials on new drugs. The ban was overturned in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, the FDA first encouraged drug companies to include
children in studies of drugs specifically targeted at children, but
it was not until 1994 that they began encouraging drug companies to
test more drugs on children and to analyze the data that were being
collected so that they could better label drugs for use in
children.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations give drug companies extended exclusivity on
their products in exchange for the pediatric testing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS LIST
</P>
<P>
   The FDA has compiled a list of the 10 drugs most widely
prescribed for children in 1994 that were never tested or approved
for use in children.
</P>
<P>
   Albuterol (for asthma) _ prescribed 1,626,000 times for children
under 12.
</P>
<P>
   Phenergan (for allergic reactions) _ prescribed 663,000 times
for children under 2.
</P>
<P>
   Ampicillin injections (for infection) _ prescribed 639,000 times
for children under 12.
</P>
<P>
   Auralgan otic solution (for ear pain) _ prescribed 600,000 times
for children under 16.
</P>
<P>
   Prozac (for depression and obsessive-compulsive disorder) _
prescribed 349,000 times for children under 16.
</P>
<P>
   Lotrisone cream (for topical treatment of infections) _
prescribed 325,000 times for children under 12.
</P>
<P>
   Intal (for asthma) _ solution prescribed 109,000 times for
children under 2; aerosol prescribed 399,000 times for children
under 5.
</P>
<P>
   Zoloft (for depression) _ prescribed 248,000 times for children
under 16.
</P>
<P>
   Ritalin (for attention-deficit disorders and narcolepsy) _
prescribed 226,000 times for children under 6.
</P>
<P>
   Alupent (for asthma) _ prescribed 184,000 times for children
under 6.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on medical issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7687. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
