<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-AID-0519-COX     05-18 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AID-0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AID AGENCIES: HUMANITARIAN EFFORT IN ALBANIA 'DISORGANIZED'
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trims.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-CLINTON-0519
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, ALBANIA _ Kosovar refugees in Albania are suffering
because of a disorganized relief effort, and many are exhausting
their life savings sustaining themselves, two international aid
groups said in reports issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   One aid agency, British-based Oxfam, said better coordination
between the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees and aid agencies in
Albania and Macedonia is urgently needed to prevent the refugee
crisis from worsening.
</P>
<P>
   The UNHCR frequently has come under attack from aid workers in
the field, but the statement by Oxfam was a rare example of those
complaints taking the form of an official position.
</P>
<P>
   Oxfam said the agency has failed to provide adequate leadership
in coordinating the efforts by scores of relief organizations and
government agencies to build camps for the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our real worry is that the best use of all the goodwill and
resources is not being made and that is failing the refugees now
and possibly even more in the future,'' Oxfam spokesman John
</P>
<P>
   Sargent told Reuters News Agency in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   More than 744,000 refugees have fled Kosovo , according to the
UNHCR. Of those, 433,000 have come to Albania, while 229,300 have
gone to Macedonia. The balance is in Montenegro and
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   UNHCR numbers suggest that more than 300,000 of the refugees in
Albania are staying with host families or in other often ad hoc
arrangements. Another aid group said Tuesday that such families are
extremely vulnerable and in many cases are exhausting their life
savings paying exorbitant rents.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the middle of all the speeches about refugees, these people
feel alone and they will have to help themselves using their life's
savings while people make a profit on them,'' said William Perea, a
physician working with the French relief group Medicins Sans
Frontieres (Doctors Without Borders).
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of refugee conditions, MSF found that most refugees
are with host families, in collection centers waiting to be sent to
long-term camps or in makeshift camps on their own. In the border
town of Kukes, about 60 percent of the refugee families were paying
rent. The average cost was $137 monthly, a large sum for the
refugees, MSF said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin Optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The organization also determined that more than 60 percent of
the relatives missing from the families are males between the ages
of 15 and 54. About half of the missing men were said by their
families to have joined the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army, or KLA.
The balance is unaccounted for. NATO officials have said they
suspect that Serb forces have been rounding up Kosovar fighting-age
men and in some cases executing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the refugees in Albania and Macedonia are to have a chance
at enjoying reasonable conditions, the U.N. refugee agency must
improve on its leadership. It is imperative for the success of the
aid effort that UNHCR is genuinely the lead agency and able to
function efficiently,'' Oxfam said in its report.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Ray Wilkinson, a UNHCR spokesman, acknowledged that the agency
was having difficulties managing the crisis. ``You have to have
organizations that want to be coordinated,'' he said. ``And you
can't be the lead organization if you don't have the funds. We are
at this moment officially broke.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the agency needs as much as $60 million to see it
through the next few weeks, while its donor base has failed to keep
up with demand.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson said the scope of the refugee crisis was beyond what
anyone had expected. ``This took UNHCR by surprise,'' he said.
``And it took everyone else by surprise too.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, British Prime Minister Tony Blair visited Tirana,
where he was greeted warmly by Albanian crowds and officials.
</P>
<P>
   Blair reassured Albanian officials that the West would remain
after the crisis to help Albania rebuild. ``I know well that it is
here that people have had to bear the burden of this crisis,'' he
said. ``Over 50 years ago, we had to rebuild Western Europe; now I
believe that this conflict can be a turning point in this region.
Now we can see here a new future in Albania, one of peace and
democracy and prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the European alliance would not waiver in its
demands for ensuring the refugees return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO has set out its demands,'' Blair said. ``Those demands
must be met. Simply, that (Yugoslav President Slobodan) Milosevic
take his troops out of Kosovo, that an international military force
go in and that the refugees return to their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
