<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEXING ONE HECK OF A HIT STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Those of us who migrated to the Southwest from
somewhat distant and, perhaps, more worldly regions of the country
have learned over time to accept and even appreciate the sometimes
raw, often quirky lack of sophistication we've encountered in our
new neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   How they say no to daylight-saving time, for instance. Or yes to
six-shooters. It's all part of the place's charm, its
guilelessness, its frontier innocence.
</P>
<P>
   But, there are limits.
</P>
<P>
   Even those of us willing to tolerate cactus jelly and string
ties can't idly stand by as the naivete of some Arizona residents
threatens the career and good fortune of another.
</P>
<P>
   I'm speaking, of course, about the reckless and irresponsible
babble surrounding the hitting streak of Arizona Diamondbacks left
fielder Luis Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   During the past week or so Gonzalez has been the subject of
innumerable television and newspaper reports about the streak, each
one giddily announcing the latest hit total.
</P>
<P>
   How could we do that to the man?
</P>
<P>
   Have we never learned that the only sure way to put an end to a
ballplayer's lucky streak is to talk about it?
</P>
<P>
   It's a hex, a spell, a sure-fire jinx.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in the parlance of my old neighborhood, very bad juju.
</P>
<P>
   This is why you never hear the words ``no-hitter'' spoken in a
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Historical reference &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Success in sports, like life, is dictated not only by skill and
smarts, but also by luck.
</P>
<P>
   In the year 1941, Ted Williams finished the season with a
batting average of .406, something no player in the league came
close to achieving that year or since. And yet, he wasn't voted the
league's Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   The award went to Joe DiMaggio, whose average was well below
Williams' but who'd managed, through talent and good fortune, to
string together a 56-game hitting streak.
</P>
<P>
   The streak finally ended when the nationwide frenzy over Joltin'
Joe's hitting put the whammy on it.
</P>
<P>
   Has history taught us nothing?
</P>
<P>
   I can tolerate a state that once elected a governor named Evan
Mecham, who thought pickaninny was an inoffensive word. The same
state in which one community recently elected a legislator named
Barbara Blewster, who says slavery wasn't so bad and Native
Americans aren't so smart.
</P>
<P>
   But a state that doesn't understand the implications of the evil
eye _ something my loving Italian grandmothers called (begin ital)
maloccio (end ital) _ cannot be ignored or glossed over.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities are too frightening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Guarded words &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what would happen if enough people walked outside during
this glorious spring and said, ``Have you noticed we haven't had
any really hot weather yet?''
</P>
<P>
   Three months in which the temperature doesn't drop below 110
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   At night.
</P>
<P>
   You know this.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, as you're driving down Central Avenue, you don't
say, ``Wow, I haven't hit a single red light yet!''
</P>
<P>
   It's why you don't say, ``Honey, we have the only kids in the
neighborhood who haven't gotten chickenpox.''
</P>
<P>
   It's why, around April 15, you never, ever hear a person say,
``There's no way I'd ever get audited.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm afraid it's too late for Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   If the streak hasn't been broken already, it will be soon.
</P>
<P>
   No amount of natural ability can compensate for the cumulative
effects of so much malevolent hoodoo.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the best way to wish Gonzalez well is (begin
ital) not (end ital) to wish him well.
</P>
<P>
   And then show the same indifference to the next ballplayer on a
hot streak.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't true of all professions.
</P>
<P>
   Good or bad luck doesn't affect newspaper writing, for instance.
Over the years, I've learned that a hack's success or lack of it is
determined by his insight, initiative and God-given talent. Nothing
else. For that reason, I've never once had to worry about having my
own work hexed.
</P>
<P>
   Knock on wood. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.monti ni(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
