<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINE-PESSIMISM-FISK-850&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WINGS OF ANGELS WILL NOT SPROUT ON BARAK'S SHOULDERS'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This TIMELY ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS
EXCELLENT ARTICLE OFFERS A 350-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 850. TOTAL
UNCUT VERSION IS 1,350 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ In the dirt of the Sabra and Chatila Palestinian
refugee camp and in Mar Elias, they were not celebrating the
election victory of Israeli Ehud Barak Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Over the entrance to Mar Elias camp, with its open sewers and
old, worn water pipes running down the pavement, there hung an iron
map of Palestine: the original Palestine, Haifa as well as
Ramallah, Tel Aviv as well as Nablus, Jerusalem as well as Jericho,
the whole shebang. And they are not going to get it back.
</P>
<P>
   They would like _ the Palestinians who live among the garbage
here _ to have the same ``right of return'' that U.S. President
Bill Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair have promised to
the Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton and Blair did not intend their promise to apply to
the Palestinians from Haifa and the rest of that part of Palestine
that became Israel in 1948 (nor do they want them to return there).
</P>
<P>
   And when you enter the grotty concrete hovel where Suheil Natour
holds forth, you can see how enormous is the chasm that divides CNN
from reality, which separates ``peace hopes'' from peace _ which
makes Ehud Barak's election a mere footnote to catastrophe for the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The differences between the Likud and Labor are minor,'' the
spokesman for the Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor wants the annexation of 52 percent of the West Bank,
Likud wanted 64 percent _ this is the difference for the
Palestinians.'' Which, for the dispossessed, for the 4 million
Palestinians of the diaspora, is all that matters.
</P>
<P>
   True, Barak wants peace. But everyone wants peace; the
Palestinians and the Israelis. Yet Barak has said that he will not
cede the Arab quarter of Jerusalem to Palestine. So what hope for
Palestine?
</P>
<P>
   It may be peace of a kind that the electorate of Israel has
voted for. But it is not peace in our time.
</P>
<P>
   The Arab world _ the supine, humiliated Arab dictatorships whose
leaders have pleaded for Washington's love and support and money _
welcomed the Labor leader's victory in the Israeli elections.
</P>
<P>
   Out came Egypt's familiar ``hand of peace'' (and oh, if only
President Hosni Mubarak would hold the same kind of free elections
which Israel conducts).
</P>
<P>
   ``Egypt is ready to cooperate with the new Israeli prime
minister to revive the peace process and to change the general
atmosphere in the region which was extremely poisoned over the last
three years,'' the Egyptian foreign minister, Amr Moussa, said.
</P>
<P>
   And from Jordan _ whose Plucky Little King II has prayed for
Benjamin Netanyahu's defeat _ came equally familiar words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' the deputy prime minister, Ayman Majali said,
``we will witness a serious move on the peace process, on the
Palestinian-Israeli track and on the Syrian-Israeli and Lebanese
tracks and hopefully we will witness a serious move for a
comprehensive, just and durable peace in the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   But note the double ``hopefully'' and the reference to a
``just'' peace. And the use of the American phrase ``tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Israelis have been trying to divide the Arabs
into these different tracks. The Palestinians fear Barak will do
just the same.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Yasser Arafat joined in the applause. ``I respect the
choice of this democratic election,'' he said without missing a
heartbeat when he used the word ``democratic'' _ that quality which
Arafat's Palestine so miserably lacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give my best wishes to Barak,'' Arafat chimed.
</P>
<P>
   In the Gulf, many a sheikh will be breathing a similar sigh of
relief. Now that the awful Netanyahu has gone, they can deal with
the nice Barak. Just like that.
</P>
<P>
   But history _ especially Palestinian history _ does not work
like that. If there is to be a Palestinian state _ the only hope
for a real peace _ then the Palestinians will have to have a
capital in part of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   They will have to see an end to occupation, an end to the theft
of Arab land and the continued building of Jewish settlements on
Arab land, an end to the confiscation of Palestinian identity
papers, an end to the demolition of Arab homes.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has promised none of this. Indeed, he may be more
interested in making a peace overture to Syria and Lebanon rather
than Palestine, in leaving Arafat to suffocate for awhile longer in
his Gaza dunghill as the Palestinian leader's popularity sinks even
lower.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Syria still demands, consistently, the return of
the occupied Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   President Hafez Assad had held out (in Syria's negotiations with
the Rabin-Peres Labor government) for a withdrawal of Israeli
troops to the borders of June 4, 1967, a frontier which would give
Damascus that part of Golan which Arafat considers Palestine, the
bit which is the source of water _ the Middle East's gold.
</P>
<P>
   Rabin refused. Barak may accept. So goodbye, Arafat would
conclude, to another bit of Palestine. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (350-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 850) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, a peace with Syria would allow Israel to withdraw
from the cauldron of Lebanon _ ``unconditionally,'' according to
U.N. Security Council Resolution 425, though Barak may have other
ideas _ and save its soldiers from the increasing attacks of
Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has promised to be out of Lebanon in a year. But on the
ground, where it always matters in the Middle East, things do not
seem that easy.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday (don't look for the news reports because it went
unmentioned) Israeli shellfire killed two civilians in the Lebanese
town of Nabatea. The Hezbollah retaliated with Katyusha rockets
into Galilee (wounding Israeli civilians, which did not go
unreported).
</P>
<P>
   And this week the Lebanese resistance movement displayed in
Beirut an entire armored personnel carrier _ captured from Israel's
surrogate ``South Lebanon Army'' militia in southern Lebanon over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the Middle East has changed since Benjamin
Netanyahu came to power in Israel three years ago. President
Mohamed Khatami of Iran _ elected democratically with a far more
devastating popular vote than Barak _ has been meeting King Fahd of
Saudi Arabia after visiting President Assad in Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   For Iran is no longer the pariah of the region, feared by those
Gulf Arabs who so eagerly invited American troops to their
peninsula when Iraqi president Saddam Hussein invaded Kuwait and
became the greatest threat to the region since the last greatest
threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranians are now talking of a ``strong regional alliance''
between Tehran and the Arab Gulf. And they have reason to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The Arab kings and emirs are tired of America's crusade against
Iraq and its sanctions-cull of Iraqi children.
</P>
<P>
   They are weary of Washington's vacillation in the face of
Israel's refusal to abide by the American ``peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   They are distrustful of an America which demands obedience to
U.N. resolutions from Arabs but none from Israel.
</P>
<P>
   If Washington hated Netanyahu but allowed him to get away with
building more settlements, what will it not permit Barak to do? &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONCLUDES) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back, then, to that hovel in the Mar Elias refugee camp Tuesday.
``The Labor government did not block settlements _ it went on
building them,'' Natour said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a genius for prolonging the ``peace process,'' to
create new settlements, to ``Judaicize'' Jerusalem, to create facts
on the ground. The Israelis like to play on differences of interest
between the Arabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Lebanese press took Natour's view, warning readers
that the difference between Labor and Likud is not that great.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wings of angels will not sprout on the shoulders of
Barak,'' the daily ``An Nahar'' warned. ``Claws already decorate
the fingers of Barak.''
</P>
<P>
   Pessimism, of course, comes as easily to the Arabs as optimism
comes to the Israelis. But it's going to be a long haul.
</P>
<P>
   For the Middle East _ and for America _ Barak is better than
Netanyahu. But it is not peace in our time. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
