<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1957 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-RUSSIA-HNS &LR;      05-18 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-RUSSIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA SCHOLARS FAULT CLINTON ADMINISTRATION POLICY IN YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S.-led bombing of Yugoslavia is fanning a
nationalist backlash across Russia that could imperil the future of
democracy there, three Russia scholars, led by Librarian of
Congress James Billington, warned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Billington, joined by Mark Kramer, a Russia studies specialist
at Harvard University, and Michael McFaul, a specialist on Russian
politics at Stanford University, said U.S. strategy in Kosovo is
alienating the next generation of Russian leaders, bolstering
ultra-nationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky and imperiling the chances
that a pragmatic, pro-western regime would win Russia's
presidential elections in June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The allied bombing plays into the hands of Russian nationalists
who argue that the West is trying to exploit Russia's economic and
military weakness by attacking on Russia's doorstep in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks come on the heels of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization's expansion into former Warsaw Pact territory that
once served as a buffer for the former Soviet Union to recruit
Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary as new members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having won the Cold War and having emerged as the only
superpower, I think the United States is in serious danger of
losing this older more basic conflict _ the struggle between
democracy and tyranny,'' Billington told a conference sponsored by
the United States Institute of Peace, a unit of the U.S.
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 foreign policy concern in my view for American
interests should be the future of the core country within the
former Soviet empire,'' Billington said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia is being treated largely as a secondary or even a third
echelon problem on the world scene,'' added Billington, a veteran
Russia scholar who taught at Harvard and Princeton universities
before being named Librarian of Congress, one of the most
prestigious scholarly posts in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Billington said U.S.-led attacks on Yugoslavia in a bid to force
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to accept an allied peace
plan for Kosovo raise the likelihood that Russia will revert to
``authoritarian nationalism,'' at least in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   Billington forecast a ``Pinochet interlude'' in which Russia
could temporarily turn to an authoritarian regime before embarking
anew on a path toward democracy and free enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Billington said he was referring to the 1973 coup in Chile led
by Gen. Augusto Pinochet who seized power from popularly elected
Marxist Salvador Allende. Pinochet then governed Chile ruthlessly
until voters elected a civilian president in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Billington's bleak assessment was echoed by McFaul and Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   McFaul said Russians' antipathy to allied attacks in Kosovo has
transformed public opinion at the grass roots level.
</P>
<P>
   Among Russians aged 18 to 35 _ the next generation of Russian
leaders _ 67 percent now have a negative view of the United States
and only 18 percent have a positive view _ a complete turnabout in
attitudes in just two years, McFaul said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford scholar, leading the Russia domestic politics
project at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace in
Washington, D.C., said NATO attacks on Yugoslavia are enabling
Russian ultra-nationalists to gain enough popularity to meet the
minimum threshold for party representation in the Russian Duma in
the Dec. 19 parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zhirinovsky is the big winner,'' McFaul said.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer, who directs Harvard's project on Cold War Studies, said
Russian nationalists are portraying the bombing of Yugoslavia and
NATO expansion as long suspected encroachments on Russian spheres
of influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``These developments are creating the general sense that Russia
is being encroached upon,'' Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   The scholars suggested that the Clinton administration could
still help Russia avert a catastrophic return to an authoritarian
regime by launching bold steps such as bringing 10,000 Russian
students to the United States each year to study.
</P>
<P>
   Billington suggested launching a multibillion dollar
U.S.-Russian project in Siberia that would produce sorely needed
products for the Russian market. Critics in Russia complain that
much of the foreign investment is directed at extraction of energy
resources such as oil and gas _ products that are exported abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done nothing dramatic to respond to the Russians' time
of troubles,'' Billington said. ``The Russians see us as the land
of big things. We have done very little.''
</P>
<P>
   The scholars' bleak assessment about the future of democracy in
Russia was challenged by former U.S. Ambassador Arthur Hartman, who
represented the Reagan administration in Moscow in the 1980s and
now leads an investment fund with Russian entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chicken Little debate is far from the truth,'' Hartman
declared. ``The sky is not falling over there. People are not out
in the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartman noted that the Russian parliament debated the
impeachment of Russian President Boris Yeltsin within the
provisions of the post-Soviet constitution without resorting to
force.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, the first popularly elected Russian leader in the
nation's 1,000 year history, is due to complete his second term and
turn power over to the winner of the presidential election in June
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, who fought back a communist-led effort to impeach him
on five charges earlier this week, is hoping to win Duma
confirmation of Prime minister-designate Sergei Stepashin on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, the National Research Council issued a
report Tuesday urging that the United States work more aggressively
with Russia for at least another decade to help secure
weapons-grade nuclear materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that terrorist groups or rogue nations have more
opportunity to gain access to Russian plutonium and highly enriched
uranium than previously estimated,'' warned Richard Meserve,
chairman of the council, an arm of the National Academy of Science.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
