<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1968 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POETRY-CENTER-ART-     05-18 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POETRY-CENTER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POETIC ECHOES IN THE TEMPLE: 60 YEARS OF Y AND WHITHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In his wheelchair up on the stage at the 92nd Street
Y on Monday night, Reynolds Price read his poem about a friend who
dreamed that Price could walk again.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Dove read ``Rosa,'' about Rosa Parks:
</P>
<P>
   ``How she sat there,
</P>
<P>
   the time right inside a place
</P>
<P>
   so wrong it was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   They were celebrating the the 60th anniversary of the Y's
Unterberg Poetry Center. Stanley Kunitz, who began coming to the Y
in 1958, looked fit at 93 as he read ``The Layers,'' about the
deaths of old friends:
</P>
<P>
   ``How shall the heart be reconciled
</P>
<P>
   to its feast of losses?
</P>
<P>
   In a rising wind
</P>
<P>
   the manic dust of my friends,
</P>
<P>
   those who fell along the way,
</P>
<P>
   bitterly stings my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Albee, Tony Kushner and Grace Paley were there, too on
the stage of Kaufmann Hall, under the sober frieze with the names
of Beethoven, Jefferson, Shakespeare and Dante written in gold
leaf. Since the center's founding in 1939, Kaufmann Hall, a
templelike place with wood-paneled walls, has had a central
position in the life of poetry in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clearest index of a culture's moral health, the most
immediate register of its language's resources, both are provided
by poetry,'' the center's director, Karl Kirchwey, said in opening
remarks at the celebration. ``Why, then, should poetry be banished
to a lyric or an academic ghetto?''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that poetry has a salutary purpose is at the core of
the center' mission as a place, in the words of its founder, Dr.
William Kolodney, ``to meet the needs of the very few persons in
New York to whom poetry offers the theological, the ethical and the
esthetic equivalents of traditional religion.''
</P>
<P>
   For young poets, giving a reading at the Y has always been a
little like getting into Harvard, and the audience tends to be
severe, prosperous-looking, attentive. ``A grave-looking literary
crowd, frowning in advance of what they were about to hear,'' John
Irving wrote in his novel ``A Widow for One Year,'' in which he
sets a scene at the center. Waiting for the writer to appear, he
wrote, the crowd makes its impatient presence felt ``like a large,
restless animal in a cage.'' The average size of the audience is
about 500 subscribers and single-ticket holders.
</P>
<P>
   Gwendolyn Brooks, Allen Ginsberg, Elizabeth Bishop, Robert
Lowell and Richard Wilbur all read at the Y early in their careers.
And through an award program with The Nation magazine, the center
has showcased the poetry of Lucille Clifton and Mark Strand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The return of the oral tradition is due largely to the work of
the Y and to those who have followed in its footsteps,'' Kunitz
said in an interview before the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The Y also holds writers' workshops and a ``Writers at Work
Live'' series, in which authors are interviewed onstage. Over the
years the center has expanded to offer ``The Tenth Muse,'' a
reading series for experimental poets, who are sometimes introduced
by older distinguished writers. The poetry readings are
co-sponsored with the Academy of American Poets. The Unterberg
Poetry Center, named for a family of donors to its activities, now
has a schools project and a program for adult literacy.
</P>
<P>
   But the poetry center is not just for poets. Mary McCarthy read
from the manuscript of her novel ``The Group'' at the center. Her
friend Hannah Arendt was in the audience at the Y, Ms. McCarthy
once recalled: ``She said, `How are you going to end it?' I told
her I didn't know, and she said: `You begin with a wedding. You
should end with a funeral.' And that's what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Dylan Thomas' play ``Under Milk Wood'' had its first New York
performance there in 1953. Alternately shaking with cold and
burning with fever, Thomas, who was an alcoholic, added new scenes
up to the last minute. John Malcolm Brinnin, then the center's
director, wrote in ``Dylan Thomas in America'' that at a reading of
the play, ``conscious of the whiteness of Dylan's sick face as it
showed through all the lights focused upon it, I could hear, above
the music of his voice, `I have seen the gates of hell.''' Thomas
died shortly after.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol has been a theme in the center's life. Dorothy Parker
was so inebriated when she appeared that she read her work aloud,
bowed to the applause, and then read the whole thing again.
Theodore Roethke was also drunk when he made his last appearance
there. Still, his friend Kunitz remembered, Roethke ``gave a great
reading, dancing like a bear onstage, roaring like a lion.''
</P>
<P>
   The poetry center has been a setting for battles over free
speech. In 1961 Norman Mailer, out on bail after stabbing his wife,
announced he was going to read ``very bad poems,'' some of them
obscene. Mailer said that would just make the audience appreciate
good poetry more.
</P>
<P>
   But Kolodney called Mailer's work ``not poems at all'' but
``obscenity for obscenity's sake'' and rang the down the curtain.
Ginsberg, who had been in the audience, wrote to Kolodney
protesting, ``I place my Spirit as poet working in an ancient
prophetic tradition against yours.'' He demanded an apology for the
treatment of Mailer, otherwise, ``I will not again set foot in the
Temple of the Y because it is a place of Pharisees and money
changers.''
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time another poet, Frederick Seidel, ran into
difficulty. Seidel was 23, and a panel of judges _ Louise Bogan,
Kunitz and Robert Lowell _ had selected him for the center's
1961-62 Helen Burlin Memorial Award. But the president of the Y's
board thought that Seidel's poem ``American in Rome'' libeled
Cardinal Francis Spellman, and asked the poet to change it. Seidel
refused and turned the prize down. The judges resigned in protest,
as did Elizabeth Kray, the center director. For years afterward,
Ms. Bogan, Kunitz and Lowell refused to appear at the center.
</P>
<P>
   As important as poetry is to the Y, the social setting is, too.
It is a place to see and be seen: in the audience, in the lobby and
at receptions after the readings. Poets see one another and
editors. Contacts are made that lead to publication, teaching jobs,
even literary romances.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981 the writer Siri Hustvedt, then a Columbia University
graduate student, attended a reading by Ann Lauterbach and Hayden
Carruth. After the reading, coming out into the lobby, Ms. Hustvedt
caught sight of the novelist Paul Auster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw this very beautiful guy standing there smoking a
cigarette and wearing a leather jacket,'' Ms. Hustvedt said the
other day. ``The myth in our family is that I fell in love in 30
seconds, and it took Paul several hours.'' They later married.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have very tender feelings about the Y,'' Ms. Hustvedt said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
