r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILTEPINE-CHILI-AZR &LR;      05-18 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILTEPINE-CHILI-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILTEPINE CHILI SECURES HOT SPOT IN NATIONAL FOREST  
 (ADV: CHARTABLE MATERIAL AT END) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS ROPP  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUMACACORI, Ariz. - It's no bigger than a pea, but the
diminutive chiltepine chili unleashes a hellfire in the mouth that
makes eyes cross and knees buckle.
</P>
<P>
   Now the searing red-hot mother of all chilies is packing some
serious heat in the political arena. After nearly a decade of
cajoling by ethnobotanists and conservationists, the U.S. Forest
Service has agreed to set aside a wilderness reserve in southern
Arizona to protect a rare U.S. stand of wild chiltepines, which
grow in the Coronado National Forest about 50 miles south of
Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-square-mile chili reserve, expected to be dedicated in
early June, will be the first of its kind set aside on national
forest land, said Suzanne Nelson of Tucson, the reserve project's
director and director of conservation for Native Seeds/SEARCH, a
Tucson-based seed conservation organization.
</P>
<P>
   Why all the hubbub over a chili?
</P>
<P>
   Besides their use in salsas and other foods, chiltepines
(pronounced CHILL-ta-peens) contain an intriguing compound called
capsaicin, found mainly in the seed. It's what gives most hot
peppers their fiery nature. However, scientists have discovered
that capsaicin may also be a potent insecticide and could have
significant medical applications for treating indigestion,
arthritis and mouth cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose the chiltepine we could miss out on even more
uses,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The chiltepine is an old plant known to Incas, Aztecs and
Mayans. It's the wild relative of virtually all our common
commercial peppers, including bell peppers, jalapenos and serranos.
While common in Latin America, the southern Arizona stand of
chiltepines represents its northernmost range.
</P>
<P>
   Chili and capsaicin researcher Joshua Tewksbury of the
University of Montana in Missoula, said the reserve offers
scientists an opportunity to study the ``evolutionary forces'' that
have created the heat in chilies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capsaicin does some bizarre things,'' Tewksbury said. ``It
hooks onto our nerve endings in some way that we sense heat (begin
ital) without (end ital) heat. It's a novel chemical in that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Tewksbury is especially interested in how capsaicin and birds
interact. While irritating (and even deadly) to mammals, capsaicin
appears to have no effect on birds. In fact, Tewksbury believes
birds are primarily responsible for distributing its seeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some birds even prefer these chilies over fruit,'' Tewksbury
said. ``In Mexico they call thrashers chileros. People find chilies
this way by tracking the birds to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Birdseed may someday be treated with capsaicin to discourage
squirrels from looting bird feeders, Tewksbury believes.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers estimate about 1,000 plants grow in the small area
of Santa Cruz County known as Rock Corral Canyon. The plants thrive
in a 3,000-foot enclave among mesquite trees along a basin of
sculpted volcanic rock below the Tumacacori Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   It's a peaceful place where hawks glide on strong afternoon
winds and rainbow cactus light up the rocks with enormous lavender
blooms. There are more cattle here than humans. The road from the
interstate to the chiltepines is only a few miles, but requires a
four-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's unlikely you could find the chiltepines anyway.
They are small scrubby bushes that grow under larger nursery plants
like hackberry trees for protection from sun and frost. Leafing and
fruiting are initiated by summer rains.
</P>
<P>
   Just a handful of miles south in adjacent Sonora, rapid declines
in chiltepines have been reported, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we've been working on for a long time,''
Nelson said. ``This marks the first time the Forest Service has set
aside land solely for the conservation and management of a wild
relative of a domesticated crop.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chiltepine facts &QL; 
For more than 8,000 years, chiltepines have grown in Peru, the
Caribbean, Mexico and isolated pockets in the Southwest. &QL; 
Native American women rubbed chiltepine powder on their nipples to
wean babies. Incas burned them to create noxious smoke as
protection against invaders. &QL; 
Scientists measure chili pepper heat in Scoville units. Green
peppers contain no Scoville units. Jalapenos in salsa range from
1,000 to 10,000 Scoville units. Chiltepines are rated at 75,000
Scoville units. &QL; 
The first chilies appeared as tiny wild berries that grew on vines
in the Amazon jungle. It's believed that birds, immune to the
chilies' heat, gobbled up the berries and distributed the seeds. &QL; 
Harvesters known as chiltepineros pick about 30 tons of chiltepines
a year for salsa and various medicinal purposes. &QL; 
Source: Chiltepine researcher Joshua Tewksbury of the University of
Montana. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
