<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1975 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUGAR19-COX     05-18 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUGAR19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OPPONENTS RENEW THEIR ATTACK ON SUGAR SUPPORT PROGRAM
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the fourth year in a row, lawmakers opposed to
the federal sugar program introduced legislation Tuesday that would
phase it out over three years. They said it would give a break to
taxpayers, consumers and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through price supports, the sugar program keeps the price of
sugar in the United States artificially high,'' said Rep. Dan
Miller, R-Fla., who has led the effort in the past.
</P>
<P>
   A similar bill will be introduced in the Senate by Sens. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y. and Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a special interest program that benefits a handful of
sugar barons at the expense of every man, woman, and child in
America,'' said Schumer, who co-sponsored previous bills with
Miller when he served in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the sugar program chided the sponsors for
continuing to offer legislation that has previously been rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting rid of the program will neither help the Everglades
nor save one penny for consumers, and the House has long understood
that,'' said Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year this proposal is offered, it has been defeated by
ever larger numbers,'' Foley said. ``I wish they would put as much
energy behind saving family farmers as they have in trying to kill
off the farms.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, as part of the major farm bill reauthorization,
the House came within nine votes of eliminating the sugar program.
Last year, the margin was 91 votes.
</P>
<P>
   The bill by Miller and Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., would
reduce the sugar program's loan rate by one cent a pound each year,
from the current level of 18 cents a pound to 14 cents a pound by
2002, and eliminate it after that.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also instructs the president and secretary of
agriculture to adjust import levels, now restricted to assure that
prices remain above the loan rate, to assure an adequate supply of
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. sugar program makes no sense,'' said Rep. George
Miller. ``Consumers pay a billion dollars more in food prices than
they should, thousands of sugar refinery workers have lost their
jobs, and the precious Florida environment is trampled.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalton Yancey, a representative for Florida Sugar Cane League,
said the proposed bill would have a significant national impact on
sugar cane and sugar beet farmers. Yancey added that reducing the
prices for sugar producers would not necessarily mean lower prices
for consumers at the grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
