<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   AIRTRAN _ AirTran's new Boeing 717, still in testing, is at
Hartsfield International Airport for a show and tell. (Thurston,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEDEPOT-EARNINGS _ ATLANTA _ Home Depot Inc., the largest
retailer of home-improvement products, said fiscal first-quarter
profit rose a more-than-expected 45 percent as home sales fueled
demand for flooring, paint and other remodeling supplies. Net
income rose to $489 million, or 32 cents a share, from $337
million, or 22 cents, a year earlier. Home Depot was expected to
earn 28 cents, the average estimate of analysts polled by First
Call Corp. for the period ended May 2. (Bond, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-CABLE _ ATLANTA _ BellSouth wireless cable TV has all
the business it can handle. The company is scrambling to service
every call it gets for it cable tv service but it's still having to
turn away many would be customers. However, mastering this market
is is must if BellSouth is to be a contender in the coming market
of bundled media services including phone, Internet access and
cable TV. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SATELLITE-TV _ ATLANTA _ Satellite TV which plateaued for a
while in local market penetration is on the upswing again.
Consumers dissatified with their local cable provider are drawn to
Direct TV and other satellite service providers who offer up to 150
channels. However, satellite TV's record is much less satisfactory
in the area of Internet access but all that may change with new
technology. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SECURITY-FIRST _ Profile of Security First, an Atlanta company
that just announced a billion-dollar acquisition and an infusion of
$50 million from Intuit. Security First makes software that allows
banks to set up Internet banking for consumers, the wave of the
future. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   IXL-IPO _ The latest Internet IPO should happen during the week
of May 17 When iXL Enterprises goes public. Starting price is
expected to be $10-12, but should rise quickly, although analysts
say the company is as yet little more than a random collection of
Internet services. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Attention brides and grooms: Almost every married
couple fights about money. Among couples who don't fight, one
partner often seethes while the other spends. Money management is
one of those little things that people don't necessarily warn their
children about. A recent survey showed another factor: Only one
young person in every five has taken a course in personal finance,
and one of every six thinks that avoiding money problems is mostly
a matter of luck. Money is a natural thing to argue about. It's
important to our happiness, sometimes crucial to self-esteem and
always in short supply. Wise young people can minimize conflicts by
following some fairly simple guidelines. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
