 A SIXTH NIGHT FOR WB, FOR UNDER-35's ONLY  
 (bl)  
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing its campaign to dominate the television habits of
people under 35, the WB network announced an expansion Tuesday to
six nights a week from five, adding Fridays, in a new fall schedule
that includes six new series, one for each night.
</P>
<P>
   WB executives unabashedly declared their desire to appeal
exclusively to the audience they call ``young adults and future
adults, also known as teens,'' an audience they deliver to
advertisers better than any other network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus is 12-to-34-year-olds and that's it,'' Jamie
Kellner, WB's president, said Tuesday at the annual ritual of
presenting video clips of the next season's lineup to advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   WB's fall schedule keeps its most popular shows in place as
building blocks, for the most part, with the major exception being
``Felicity,'' which will move to Sunday night at 8 p.m. from
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   It will be followed by a New York City-based romantic drama,
``Jack and Jill,'' in which a 20-something man (nicknamed Jill)
moves into an apartment building with his girlfriend, only to be
smitten by another young woman in the building (nicknamed Jack).
</P>
<P>
   The network's most popular show, ``Seventh Heaven,'' which
contrary to marketing strategy has familywide appeal, will remain
on Mondays at 8 p.m., followed by another family drama, ``Safe
Harbor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Safe Harbor'' could be described as ``Seventh Heaven'' moved
to Florida and minus the mother; Gregory Harrison (of ``Trapper
John M.D.'') plays a widower raising four sons.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesdays, ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' will be followed at 9
p.m. by a spinoff show, ``Angel,'' centered on Buffy's former
boyfriend, Angel (David Boreanaz), a vampire tortured by a good
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   WB's other teen-fave show, ``Dawson's Creek,'' stays on
Wednesdays at 8 p.m., but its 9 o'clock companion drama,
``Roswell,'' has more of a ``Buffy'' flavor in that it features a
teen-age boy who, like Buffy, seems normal but has supernatural
powers and uses them to save his pals.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by 20th Century Fox Television, the show landed on WB
instead of Fox, reportedly because WB gave it a full-season
commitment and Fox wanted it only as a potential midseason
replacement show.
</P>
<P>
   The three young witches of ``Charmed'' used to follow
``Dawsons''' but will move to 9 p.m. on Thursday. It will be
preceded by yet another high school drama, ``Popular,'' at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The network also moved its Thursday night sitcom block to
Fridays, minus ``The Wayans Brothers,'' which will be replaced by
the first animated show about teen-agers and 20-somethings. Called
``The Downtowners,' it was created by two writer-producers formerly
with ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is the WB schedule:
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY: 7 p.m., ``Seventh Heaven: Beginnings''; 8, ``Felicity'';
9, ``Jack and Jill.''
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY: 8 p.m., ``Seventh Heaven''; 9, ``Safe Harbor.''
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY: 8 p.m., ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer''; 9, ``Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY: 8 p.m., ``Dawson's Creek''; 9, ``Roswell.''
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY: 8 p.m., ``Popular''; 9, ``Charmed.''
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY: 8 p.m., ``The Steve Harvey Show''; 8:30, ``For Your
Love''; 9, ``The Downtowners''; 9:30, ``The Jamie Foxx Show.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1756EDT &QL; 
