<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ABC-SEASON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC LINEUP REARRANGES HIT SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC announced a fall schedule Tuesday that moves several of its
established shows to new times, adds three comedies and three
dramas, and preserves the network's Friday lineup of child-oriented
shows, once thought to be near extinction for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes certain to arouse curiosity was ABC's switch
of its biggest 8 p.m. hit, ``Dharma and Greg,'' to 9 p.m. and one
of its 9 p.m. hits, ``Spin City,'' to 8 p.m. The network is also
taking the unusual step of starting the season with a new drama,
``Once and Again,'' in the spot occupied by ``NYPD Blue,'' although
the latter will return by November, leaving the new series with
nowhere specific to go _ assuming it has built an audience by then.
</P>
<P>
   ABC will add another new drama from the prolific writer David E.
Kelley and one from Kevin Williamson, the creator of ``Dawson's
Creek'' and the ``Scream'' movies.
</P>
<P>
   The Kelley show (Sundays at 9 p.m.) is ``Snoops,'' a
comedy-drama about three young private investigators in Los Angeles
who use all sorts of high-tech means to gather information without
worrying about any laws they might break in the process. The show
stars Gina Gershon.
</P>
<P>
   The Williamson show is ``Wasteland,'' one of next season's
myriad copies of shows broadcast on WB, which for a network with a
tiny audience is wielding a tsunami of influence through shows like
``Dawson's Creek and ``Felicity.'' ``Wasteland'' (Thursdays at 9)
involves six friends, all single and exploring the dating scene in
Manhattan. One is 27 and still a virgin, still in love with her
former boyfriend. Another member of the group is secretly gay.
</P>
<P>
   A gay character is also prominent in ``Oh Grow Up,'' the comedy
getting the best spot on ABC's schedule, appearing after ``Drew
Carey'' on Wednesdays at 9:30. In this show, a divorced man in his
early 40s with a Peter Pan complex decides to share his home with
two male buddies, one of whom is gay. His 18-year-old daughter
suddenly moves in.
</P>
<P>
   The youth-oriented lineup on Fridays will include one show moved
from Tuesday, ``The Hughleys,'' which goes into the 8 p.m. slot,
and one new comedy, ``Odd Man Out,'' at 9:30. ``Odd Man Out'' is
about a 14-year-old boy living with his mother, aunt and three
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's third new comedy is ``Then Came You'' (Thursdays at 8:30),
about a 34-year-old woman (just inside television's youngest
demographic group for advertiser preferences) who qualifies as an
``older'' woman because she gets involved with a 24-year-old room
service waiter after her marriage breaks up.
</P>
<P>
   The drama getting squeezed into a temporary home on Tuesdays at
10 is one with a formidable pedigree: ``Once and Again,'' the
latest show from Ed Zwick and Marshall Herskovitz of
``Thirtysomething'' and ``My So-Called Life.'' In this series, two
divorced adults (the actors are in their 40s) meet and fall in
love. The show will explore the way their relationship develops and
how it affects their children, still suffering the effects of their
parents' divorces.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in years ABC will challenge NBC's Thursday
lineup by starting out with Drew Carey's ``'Whose Line Is It
Anyway'' at 8, followed by ``Then Came You.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is the ABC schedule:
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY: 8 p.m., ``20/20''; 9, ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY: 8 p.m., ``Spin City;'' 8:30, ``It's Like, You Know'';
9, ``Dharma and Greg'': 9:30, ``Sports Night''; 10, ``NYPD Blue''
(though ``Once and Again'' will start the season here)
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY: 8 p.m., ``Two Guys, A Girl and a Pizza Place''; 8:30,
``The Norm Show''; 9, ``Drew Carey''; 9:30, ``Oh Grow Up''; 10,
``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY: 8 p.m., `'Whose Line Is It Anyway?''; 8:30, ``Then
Came You''; 9, ``Wasteland''; 10, ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY: 8 p.m., ``The Hughleys''; 8:30, ``Boy Meets World''; 9,
``Sabrina''; 9:30, ``Odd Man Out''; 10, ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY: 8 p.m., Movie.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY: 7 p.m., ``Wonderful World of Disney''; 9, ``Snoops'';
10, ``The Practice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
