<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, May 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first significant rainfall of the month will occur in
sections of the Northeast on Wednesday. A combination of moisture
attendant to a cold front and damp onshore winds from the Atlantic
will produce moderate to heavy showers with embedded thunderstorms
over New England and upstate New York. Many places will receive at
least 1/2 inch of rain, and a few spots could get more than 2
inches. Winds in the lower atmosphere blowing from the southeast
will slightly dry on descent of the western slopes of the
Appalachians. As a result, partial sunshine will raise the risk of
thunderstorms in interior valleys such as the Champlain in northern
Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front will progress from the Appalachians at daybreak to
the Atlantic Seaboard by sundown. Scattered thundershowers will
dampen the East Coast ahead of the front, but clouds will break
east of the central Appalachians on Wednesday afternoon. The front
will be followed by noticeably less humid air across the Gulf
states and the interior Southeast. Florida will stay hot with
little or no rain.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant weather will dominate from the Great Lakes through the
Mississippi Valley. The clockwise circulation around high pressure
will direct more humid air back into the Plains. A few
thunderstorms will develop in the Dakotas and over the eastern
Rockies as a Pacific front approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Streamers of cirrus clouds will streak the sky over parts of the
Rockies as moist Pacific air flows over the mountains. Meanwhile,
the Southwest will be sunny, but the Northwest will be dull and
cool at the coast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Rampaging Rivers
</P>
<P>
   Rampaging rivers submerged small towns in northeastern Iowa
under as much as 10 feet of water early Tuesday as major flooding
occurred on the Volga and Turkey Rivers. At the town of Garber near
the confluence of the two rivers, flood waters crested at 30.6 feet
at noon Tuesday, establishing a new record there. Flood stage is 17
feet and the previous record at Garber was 30.1 feet, set on May
15, 1991. Major flooding came on the heels of clusters of heavy
thunderstorms that repeatedly passed over the same areas Sunday and
Monday, dumping as much as 8 inches of rain in places. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
