<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1993 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIMMICK-THEATER-REVIE     05-18 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIMMICK-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER ACTING OUT THE INNER CITY, A WRITER RADIATES INNER PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One would expect Dael Orlandersmith to be angrier in
person. The material in her searing one-woman play is, after all,
largely based on her own experiences, and those experiences are
hard to hear about, let alone live through: a little girl
physically and emotionally abused by her alcoholic mother; a large,
book-loving girl teased by her peers for being big and being
different; a teen-age girl raped by her best friend's father.
</P>
<P>
   You hear the anger in her play ``The Gimmick,'' about two
childhood friends: Alexis, who wants to be a writer, and Jimmy, who
wants to be an artist. You hear it in the pulsing, insistent rhythm
of Ms. Orlandersmith's writing, more poetry than prose:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing what parents can do, how they can beat you and
say it's all right, I gave birth to you, I can beat you, I feed
you, I can beat you, I clothe you, I can beat you, I can talk to
you any way I want, I brought you in this world, I can talk to you
any way I want, I'm trying to teach you, I'll knock your head
off.''
</P>
<P>
   But sitting across a table over coffee the other morning, her
long brown and gold braids falling around her face, Ms.
Orlandersmith seemed strikingly at peace with the issues that roil
her performance at the New York Theater Workshop on East Fourth
Street. It is as if all the rage and pain that animate her play
have been released in her work. She does not live that bitterness
day to day; she appears to have achieved a necessary distance and
perspective. And she wants most of all to be taken seriously for
writing about the struggles of the inner city, not pitied for
having survived them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it has nothing to do with me,'' Ms. Orlandersmith
said. ``I'm a playwright. What interests me is how people can use
their bodies as instruments, their words as tools, to get their
point across.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Orlandersmith, who is 39, has been getting her point across
since 1987, when she gave up on trying to get work as an actress _
having been sent to audition for one too many parts as a welfare
mother _ and started writing her own material. Her first play,
``Liar, Liar,'' was presented at Manhattan Class Company in 1994.
Then came ``Beauty's Daughter'' at the American Place Theater, for
which she won an Obie in 1995. Then the acclaimed ``Monster'' at
the New York Theater Workshop in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In a review in The New York Times this month, Peter Marks said
Ms. Orlandersmith's previous one-woman shows ``now seem to have
been mere rehearsals for the more nuanced narrative of `The
Gimmick.''' He described Ms. Orlandersmith as ``a riveting
combatant in a story, like all war stories, that stamps her as one
who has been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the trials that her characters endure as they come of
age in her play have the raw specificity that only firsthand
knowledge can convey: a young woman self-conscious about her large
size walking into a clothing store and finding nothing on the racks
but ``size 0, size 3, size 5.'' The Mr. Softie ice cream truck as a
symbol of childhood's elusive sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   One of the moments in ``The Gimmick'' that Ms. Orlandersmith
says moves her the most is when Jimmy is watching television,
fantasizing about leaving Harlem for the blue water in the
background on ``American Bandstand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, Alexis. See the water, it's so clean,'' he says in his
small voice. Then Jimmy's father steps in front of the television,
squeezes his son's arm, bringing Jimmy to his knees, saying, ``You
stupid l'il nigga talkin' about how you goin' somewhere an' you
can't even read. Can't even spell ocean. How you gonna find it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The sound of a child's voice,'' Ms. Orlandersmith said in the
interview, ``just the killing of a kid's dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Had she been a different kind of child, Ms. Orlandersmith said,
her mother might have killed her dream. ``She is somebody who
should never have had children,'' Ms. Orlandersmith said. ``One
minute, she said, `I love you,' the next minute, `I wish you were
never born.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I saunter and the rest of the world walks,''
Ms. Orlandersmith continued, ``but it wasn't easy to believe in
myself by myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow Ms. Orlandersmith did develop some self-confidence as
well as the sense that there was a world beyond her neighborhood.
She went downtown to music clubs and museums. She kept diaries. She
kept to herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can look around you and see what not to do,''
she said. ``I knew what was around me wasn't right. I knew I didn't
want to live that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading was her rescue. As a young girl, Ms. Orlandersmith
borrowed books from the library _ even stole them from stores
occasionally _ and read voraciously. ``There were times when I
thought I was mad, as in insane,'' she said. ``Then I read `The
Bluest Eye' by Toni Morrison, `Another Country,' by James Baldwin,
`Sideshow' by Rambeau. And I realized I wasn't crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Orlandersmith is currently working on ``Yellowman,'' a play
about patricide commissioned by the McCarter Theater in Princeton,
N.J., where ``The Gimmick'' originated. And this fall she is due to
begin a yearlong residency at the Long Wharf theater in New Haven,
Conn., where she will develop her play, ``Trickbabies,'' about the
offspring of prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's fearless,'' said Peter Askin, who helped Ms.
Orlandersmith conceive ``The Gimmick'' _ which is directed by Chris
Coleman, and closes Sunday _ and has worked with her on her other
projects. ``She's not only willing to go to some dark places, it
seems that she's eager to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Offstage, Ms. Orlandersmith seems more private about those dark
places. As she speaks, one senses the inside-outside voices that
she herself writes about _ that outside, she is saying, `Don't feel
sorry for me, don't analyze me, my work speaks for itself.' And
inside, there will always be the child saying, ``Like me, take me
seriously, respect my work,'' like Alexis showing her notebook to
Jimmy for the first time:
</P>
<P>
   ``outside I say ``you can read it''
</P>
<P>
   inside I say ``don't laugh at me''
</P>
<P>
   outside I say ``I'm going to be a famous writer one day''
</P>
<P>
   inside I say ``don't laugh at me don't tell the other kids on
the block''
</P>
<P>
   outside I say ``I write a lot even though I'm 8 years old. I
like to write I'm not like these stupid kids around here''
</P>
<P>
   inside I say ``the other kids don't like me. They laugh at me.
Be my friend you read my story and be my friend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
