<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Snow Will Cover Walls In Brooklyn in Summer &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn Museum of Art is offering a last chance to see
``Impressionists in Winter: Effets de Neige,'' an exhibition of
snowy scenes that has already drawn big crowds at the Phillips
Collection in Washington and at the Fine Arts Museums of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition demonstrates how the Impressionists used deep
shadows and various shades of white and gray to explore the visual
characteristics of snow. Over a 30-year period that began in the
mid-1860s, the artists turned out works depicting various aspects
of France in cold weather, from snow-covered rooftops at twilight
to fields of virgin snow in the morning light.
</P>
<P>
   Monet painted his first winter scene in 1865, and eventually
produced more than 140 snow scenes. Pissaro and Sisley soon took up
the theme, followed by Renoir, Caillebotte and Gauguin.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 55 works drawn from more than 20 museums and 20
private collections will be Monet's ``Red Cape,'' which shows his
wife, Camille, through a window; Renoir's ``Skaters in the Bois de
Bologne,'' Sisley's ``Snow Effect at Louveciennes'' and
Caillebotte's ``Rooftops in Snow.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn was not part of the show's original itinerary, and a
few works shown previously will not be on view. But the Brooklyn
Museum has added a few paintings, including Cezanne's ``Melting
Snow, Fontainebleau'' from the Museum of Modern Art, and six
Japanese woodcuts that influenced the Impressionists' snowscapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impressionists in Winter'' will remain at the Brooklyn Museum,
until Aug. 29. The museum is open Wednesday through Sunday. Dated
and timed tickets, which cost $9.50 and $7.50 for seniors and
students (with ID in person only), can be purchased by phone, (877)
946-8379, on the Internet (www.2btech.com/winter) or at the museum.
General information: (718) 638-5000 or www.brooklynart.org.
</P>
<P>
   Judith H. Dobrzynski &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Issues, Then Lifts, A Warning on China &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For several days, the State Department urged Americans to
postpone travel to China because of the angry response to the NATO
forces' bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade. It issued a
travel warning on May 9 because street demonstrations began outside
the American Embassy in Beijing soon after the accidental bombing
in Belgrade on May 7. American businesses were also attacked and
citizens harassed.
</P>
<P>
   On May 13, it rescinded the warning, saying that the security
situation had improved, although the potential still existed for
further violent acts. It urged United States citizens in China to
remain alert and to avoid areas of demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Embassy in Beijing and its consulates in other
cities were shut temporarily in the week after the Belgrade
bombing, but were resuming operations last Monday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The State Department offers travel information at (202)
647-5225, and on the Web at travel.state.gov. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Aquarium Flows From Denver to Asia &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On June 21, Denver joins the growing list of landlocked cities
that have aquariums. The aquarium, Colorado's Ocean Journey, will
feature 15,000 specimens representing more than 300 species of
fish, birds, mammals and invertebrates. Two exhibits will simulate
two major waterways: the Colorado River and the Kampar River in
Sumatra. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the Sumatran habitats recreated in the Indonesian River
Journey exhibit are a rain forest and a coral lagoon. At an
interactive area within a mangrove swamp, visitors can view unusual
species like the upside-down jelly and the archerfish. Two Sumatran
tigers swim in a pool. Where the river ``reaches'' the ocean,
visitors can view sharks and tropical fish above and below. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado River exhibit depicts the journey of the river from
its origins as a mountain stream to the Sea of Cortez. Visitors can
follow the river on its 1,500-mile journey to a wetlands area,
through a canyon and into desert.
</P>
<P>
   At the entrance of the Sea of Cortez exhibit, the surf splashes
above visitors who view the surging tide and a variety of
invertebrate life, and seahorses, squirrelfish and moray eels.
Shorebirds forage for food along the shore near the fabricated
skeletal remains of a gray whale.
</P>
<P>
   The aquarium also features a Sea Otter Cove, with southern sea
otters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's Ocean Journey is at 700 Water Street, just off Exit
211 of Interstate 25, and will be open 9 a.m. to 6:30 p.m. Monday
to Friday and 9 a.m. to 8 p.m. on weekends through Labor Day; 10
a.m. to 6 p.m. daily the rest of the year. Closed Christmas.
Admission is $14.95, $12.95 ages 13 to 17 and 65 and older, and
$6.95 ages 4 to 12. Information: (303) 561-4450 or
www.oceanjourney.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Katherine House &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Pushkin Celebration on His Family's Estate &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aficionados of Russian literature who are visiting Russia next
month can join the anniversary celebration of the national poet,
Aleksandr Pushkin. This year marks the 200th anniversary of the
birth of the poet, who died in a duel in 1837. Pushkinskiye Gory, a
town in the rolling green countryside of the Pskov region, about
225 miles south of St. Petersburg, that is the site of Pushkin's
estate, Mikhailovskoye, is bracing for an onslaught of tourists for
the festivities on June 6. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The directors of the Pushkin Museum Nature Preserve, which
includes Mikhailovskoye and two other estates belonging to
Pushkin's family and close friends, expect up to 500,000 literary
pilgrims. A six-room house set among pine trees and fruit orchards
is a re-creation of the late-18th-century house where Pushkin wrote
``Boris Godunov'' and much of ``Yevgeny Onegin.''
</P>
<P>
   The original structure, which was rebuilt after fires in the
early 20th century, was destroyed by German troops during World War
II. The present building, on the original foundation, dates from
the late '40s, and reproduces the house as it was in Pushkin's day,
with some items he used, like a silver candleholder, dishes and a
samovar.
</P>
<P>
   A peaceful refuge amid the bustle is the white stucco
Svyatogorsky Monastery of the Dormition, where the poet is buried
and where black-robed monks live and pray beneath the monastery's
silver cupolas. On June 6, there will be a procession to Pushkin's
grave to lay a wreath.
</P>
<P>
   Ceremonies surrounding the reopening of Mikhailov-skoye, which
has been closed for over a year, a folk music concert and readings
from Pushkin's works are also scheduled that day. Other events,
including an annual Pushkin literary conference on Aug. 21 and 22
(this year focusing on folklore), are scheduled throughout the
summer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pushkinskiye Gory's 900 hotel beds are booked for June 6 and
well into the summer. There may be rooms available in Pskov, an
hour's drive away, the museum says.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the summer, rooms may be available for about $10 a
night at two guest houses at Mikhailovskoye and at Trigorskoye,
another estate in the museum complex. Visitors can also stay in
Novgorod (where rates run about $150 a night) and St. Petersburg
($150 to $300), both about four and a half hours away.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the museum is $1, $2 for a guided tour. For more
information on lodging and festivities, call the museum's travel
office, (7-81146) 23352, or the museum itself, (7-81146) 21762. The
Pskovintour travel agency in Pskov, (7-8112) 72-00-06, has an
English-speaking staff and can arrange tours and lodging.
</P>
<P>
   Sophia Kishkovsky &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
