</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SHAS-0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SURGING ULTRA-RELIGIOUS PARTY POSES FIRST DILEMMA FOR BARAK
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The election success of an ultra-religious party
intensified Israel's so-called culture war and posed a dilemma
Tuesday for Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak as he tried to form his
government.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis woke up to find, with final tallies in from Monday's
election, that the ultra-Orthodox Shas Party was nearly as large as
the Likud Party, long the No. 2 party in the country. Shas jumped
from 10 seats to 17 seats in the fractious 120-seat parliament,
called the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
   Shas's ascendancy highlighted the growing tension over Israel's
racial and religious politics. Most Israeli's already worry that
the country could be endangered by the rift between Israel's
secular Jews and its religious Jews, who in recent years have
become more powerful and sought more influence over daily life.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the conflict pits the fundamentalist, conservative and
cloistered world of Shas against the liberal, loose and often
hedonistic world of most Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   In Har Nof, a Shas neighborhood of dozens of apartment blocks
and religious schools, little boys with side curls and yamulka's
play on their BMX bicycles while mothers watch in their head
scarves and long skirts -- required for modesty. The scene is
suburban, but there is suspicion of those outside, who, in Shas
eyes, violate Jewish law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of hatred,'' said Shoshana Reisner, a Shas
voter and a mother of three. ``They hate us and they do things to
offend us.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's Labor Party has just 27 seats in parliament and he needs
to form a majority coalition of 61 seats in 45 days. Include Shas,
and he could anger the secular supporters who were key to his
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Exclude Shas, and Barak could create a powerful enemy and
inflame Israel's bitter secular-religious rift.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli news reported Tuesday night that Barak was searching for
a way to include Shas in his government. It could be just a
flirtation, an attempt by Barak to play off against each other all
the smaller parties negotiating to join him. Customarily, parties
demand cabinet posts and other deals to join.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said he would not negotiate with controversial Shas
Party leader Rabbi Aryeh Deri, awaiting appeal on a bribery
conviction. On Tuesday, Deri announced that he was resigning from
parliament, appearing to open the door to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see myself excluding any big party,'' said Natan
Sharansky, head of the party that represents Russian-speaking
Israelis and a member of Barak's coalition team. ``We're talking
about a very big part of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Shas represents Sephardic Jews -- both ultra-religious and
secular. They are the approximately 45 percent of Israel's Jewish
population that is descended from other Middle Eastern and Asian
countries. They feel alienated and mistreated by Jews of European
descent.
</P>
<P>
   Barak campaigned on ending Israel's divisive atmosphere and
representing all Israelis. If he wants to carry out his difficult
agenda, including a revival of the controversial peace negotiations
with the Palestinians, he cannot antagonize any large group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were a small party, you could,'' said political
scientist Eliezer Don-Yehiya of Bar-Ilan University. ``You can't
ignore them now.''
</P>
<P>
   Shas wants in because it depends on government money for its
network of schools and welfare services. It was a member of the
coalitions of prime ministers Yitzhak Rabin and Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   But, secular Israelis are angry that religious students, who
often stay in studies for their lifetimes, get government subsidies
and are exempted from military service.
</P>
<P>
   Ultra-religious Jews, a minority of 5 to 10 percent of the
population, have succeeded in certain closing stores and roads on
the weekly sabbath. They also control government laws concerning
what kinds of marriages and burials are allowed, and that
de-legitimize the less-traditional forms of Judiasm favored among
American Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
