<HEADER>
A2035 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS &LR;      05-18 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT UNION SAYS SOCIAL SECURITY PLAN WOULD COST $25 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's largest union of public employees
warned Tuesday that any effort to move government workers into the
Social Security system would cost them and their employers $25
billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   The result, leaders of the 1.3 million-member American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees Union said,
would be reduced public services and possibly higher taxes as
governments scrambled to make up the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Requiring all public employees to participate in Social
Security would be a huge and costly mistake,'' said Edwin Jayne,
AFSCME associate director of legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The original Social Security Act of 1935 excluded government
workers from the pay-as-you-go Social Security retirement benefit
system. Over time, however, Congress extended such benefits to
public employees not already covered by their state and local
employers' pension plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security Administration estimates that 5 million
workers now are in such pension plans funded by their government
employers and neither pay into nor receive Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Several congressional plans to overhaul Social Security have
advocated incorporating newly hired public employees workers into
Social Security as a way of boosting the system's flagging trust
fund. Under current estimates, the fund will be unable to pay full
benefits starting in 2034.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference here, AFSCME officials unveiled a study
showing how adding the newly hired workers to Social Security would
cost the $25 billion over five years. That figure, said Cathie
Eitelberg, the consultant who authored the study, was derived by
assuming a 9 percent yearly turnover and a 3 percent rise in
payroll each year.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers yielded were recalculated along with the cost to
governments and their workers of paying the 12.4 percent Social
Security payroll tax, which Eitelberg said produced the $25 billion
figure. Adding public employees would extend the life of the Social
Security trust fund by only two years, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jayne and Thomas Lussier, chairman of the Coalition to Preserve
Social Security, an employer-union group formed to fight Social
Security enrollment for government workers, said state and local
governments would have little choice but to reduce services or
raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, inclusion of government workers was part of several
congressional plans to fix Social Security. But support for the
idea has dwindled after a concerted lobbying effort by AFSCME and
the coalition. ``We've been successful in demonstrating the pain is
not worth the gain,'' Lussier said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lussier insisted that in future congressional deliberations
over how best to prop up Social Security. lawmakers might revive
the idea.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Social Security and the existing government-run counterparts
have different structures, Eitelberg explained. Under the
pay-as-you-go Social Security system, payroll taxes of those
working today go to pay the benefits of current retirees. Social
Security is envisioned as part of an individual's retirement
income, to be combined with an employment-based pension plan and
personal savings.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Eitelberg said, state and local government
retirement plans are pre-funded, meaning that workers pay into them
and draw on them as an all-inclusive pension. They are structured
to take care of public employees such as firemen and policemen who
often retire at 55 as the physical demands of their jobs become too
great for them.
</P>
<P>
   Reliance on Social Security, which permits early retirement at
62, would not take care of public employees' retirement income
needs, Eitelberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The study included a chart showing potential impact to
government workers in each state.
</P>
<P>
   For California, with 903,000 public employees not covered by
Social Security, the cost over five years would be $4.1 billion.
For New York, with 90,680 such workers, the cost would be $704
million. For Michigan, with 85,808 workers, the cost would be
$632.4 million. For Texas, with 515,751 such workers, the cost
would be $2.6 billion. For Washington state, with 46,868 workers,
the cost would be $363.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
