<HEADER>
A2050 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-CROSSINGS-SENA     05-18 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-CROSSINGS-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. ABRAHAM RENEWS EFFORT TO SCRAP BORDER-CROSSING PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., announced Tuesday
that he would lead a new effort to kill a program requiring
Canadians and Mexicans traveling to and from the United States to
be logged in and out of the country by U.S. customs and immigration
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham said such a system would delay traffic moving across the
U.S. border by a day or more, effectively shutting down the
U.S.-Canada border and damaging business and tourism in both
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham met Tuesday with Raymond Chretien, Canada's ambassador
to the United States, to discuss legislation he is sponsoring to
cancel the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our own feeling is that it is going backwards,'' Chretien said
of the proposed border-crossing system.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham and Chretien were joined at a news conference by Herb
Dhaliwal, Canada's minister of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of Canadians are waived into the United States
after U.S. immigration officers ask them a few questions, such as
how long they plan to stay in the country. Along the U.S.-Mexico
border, visitors entering the United States are asked to show
identification.
</P>
<P>
   If the new border-crossing system is implemented, however, it
would require border agents to check identification of everyone
entering and leaving the United States from Mexico and Canada and
log that information into a computer.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. agents would also be required to check the identification
of foreigners leaving the United States and log their exit into a
computer. The majority of Canadians and Mexicans are currently not
stopped when they leave the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The new border-crossing program was set up by the 1996
immigration reform law and was intended to cut down on the flow of
illegal drugs and illegal immigrants crossing U.S. borders.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from northern states have been trying to repeal it
ever since, arguing that the system would simply impede traffic at
the borders rather than stop illegal immigration and drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The program was intended to begin last October. The Senate last
year voted to scrap the system, but the House disagreed. Lawmakers
ultimately agreed on a 30-month moratorium on putting the program
into effect until mid-2001.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham said hiring more border-patrol agents to look for drug
smuggling would be more effective than logging people in and out of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., recently introduced identical
legislation in the House that would stop the implementation of the
computerized-border patrol system.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Abraham called for additional U.S. Customs and
Immigration and Naturalization Service personnel to staff
U.S.-Canada border check points in Michigan to help alleviate
increased traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to top U.S. Customs and INS officials, Abraham also
asked for additional inspection lanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some cases a trip that five years ago took 10 to 15 minutes
can now take up to an hour on a typical morning,'' Abraham wrote.
He noted that traffic between Detroit and Windsor, Ontario, has
been growing at 8 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at (202) 298-6920 and
e-mailed at jennifer (at) hearstdc.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
