<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2055 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTINGS-HNS &LR;      05-18 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS COACH CONGRESS ON VIOLENCE IN SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stephen Keene watched helplessly as a fellow
student shot and killed three other teen-agers and wounded his
younger brother Craig at a Kentucky high school in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Keene, 17, recounted his experiences Tuesday before a House
Education subcommittee that was holding a forum on school shootings
like the ones that occurred at Keene's school in Paducah and more
recently at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get over it,'' Keene told about 25 lawmakers who sat
with rapt attention. ``You can hardly control yourself sometimes
because you are crying so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Atteberry said May 21, 1998, was a normal day at his school
in Springfield, Ore. ``The next thing I know I'm laying on the
ground paralyzed, my head filled with a deaf ringing sound.''
</P>
<P>
   On that day, a fellow student opened fire in the cafeteria of
Thurston High, killing two other students.
</P>
<P>
   Atteberry, 17, spent five days in the hospital recovering from a
gunshot wound to his throat, with a bullet was lodged near his
spine. The bullet remains in his body because of the risks of
removing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here today to encourage everyone to help stop school
violence,'' he told the lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers, like the students, grappled with ways to stop
violence while admitting there is no perfect solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we can't solve everything, but we have an
obligation to do everything we can,'' said Rep. Carolyn McCarthy,
D-N.Y., who ran for Congress in 1996 to advocate stronger
gun-control laws. McCarthy's husband was killed and her son was
partially disabled by a gunman on a Long Island commuter train in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the problems are complex,'' McCarthy said. ``But I believe
the easy access to guns is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Anita Wheeler, a student at Western High School in Baltimore,
suggested reducing class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dale Kildee, D-Mich., went further, wondering if the
overall size of schools should be reduced. Columbine High, for
example, has more than 1,800 students.
</P>
<P>
   Keene said that probably wasn't the answer and noted that his
school, Heath High, has about 600 students.
</P>
<P>
   Atteberry said Congress might consider giving schools money to
hire people to monitor hallways and to stop people who are trolling
the hallways when classes are in session.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and students also discussed gun control, and providing
federal support for after-school programs and for hiring more
school counselors.
</P>
<P>
   But Keene said parents have the main responsibility to teach
their children values and morals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't expect the schools to raise our children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Campbell, who is a senior at Columbine High, told the
congressional committee that the schools weren't to blame. He was
not wounded in the April 20 attack, when two Columbine schoolmates
killed a dozen other students and a teacher before taking their own
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that our schools have done as well as they can because
you cannot change or control teen behavior,'' Campbell, 18, said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless Congress is likely to find some way to act against
school violence.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Castle, R-Del., chairman of the House Education
Early Childhood, Youth and Families subcommittee, said the
Columbine case ``galvanized the country'' to do something to
address the recent outbreaks of violence in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
e-mail at jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2056 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-18 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSEMAN SWEENEY HAS HIS JOB ALL SIZED UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ There was a time when Don Sweeney could
rationalize that he was, if not an average-sized defenseman, pretty
darn close to it.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is on a team with both a 6-foot-4-inch, 220-pound
defenseman (Kyle McLaren) and a defenseman out of science fiction
(the 6-7, 240-pound Hal Gill). Compared with those Brobdingnagian
blue liners, 5-10 and 180 seems downright puny.
</P>
<P>
   Is he, you know, envious of these sturdy mates?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that way,'' he shrugs. ``I've always been this
size. I don't know anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   If during his 11 years with the Bruins (two partial and nine
full) the 32-year old Harvard grad has fallen from the middle of
the size pack to the bottom third, or even bottom fourth, so be it.
He's still here, isn't he?
</P>
<P>
   He's here, all right, and he's been playing as well as ever.
When someone thinks of Boston Bruins defensemen, it is only right
and proper to start the discussion with No. 77. Ray Bourque is a
legend, as everyone knows. But Don Sweeney also has a lot to offer.
If any young player would like to bone up on the rudiments of being
a pure defensive defenseman, he would do well to study the quiet
professional who has been one of the team's top performers during
both the Carolina and Buffalo series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is so quick on the puck and so steady,'' salutes Gill.
``And he has come up huge for us in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Sweeney can't imagine being anything other than 5-10,
so, too, is it impossible for the elongated Gill to imagine not
being the biggest man on the ice. And as for being 5-10, 180 and
whacking people . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``There are guys his size, and smaller, who play in the
league,'' Gill points out, ``but not many of them are impact
players. For Donnie to do what he does amazes me. How he gets his
shoulder into guys on checks and drives people. I can't relate to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be challenging for him to play that way,'' adds
McLaren. ``A lot of guys in this league are now 6-2, 6-3, 6-4 and
220, 230 pounds, and Donnie's not that. But no one is more
competitive. He wants to compete and he wants to be in there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was agonizing for Sweeney to miss Game 4 of this series with
a recurrent back injury. Someone might want to play as much as
Sweeney does, but no one wants to play more.
</P>
<P>
   It surprised no one when he willed himself back into action for
Game 5 Sunday. It also surprised no one when he contributed the
goal that tied the game at 1-1 after a bounce off the back of a
linesman contributed to a Buffalo goal in the game's opening 27
seconds. It was Sweeney's third goal of the playoffs, and it made
him a 50-goal man.
</P>
<P>
   That's 50 goals in a combined 841 regular-season and playoff
games.
</P>
<P>
   He has matched a playoff career high with three goals, and it
happens to be one more goal than he scored in 80 regular-season
games. His teammates are starting to wonder why he's been
surpressing this Orr thing buried in his personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to teach me how to put the puck in the corner like
that,'' smiles McLaren. ``But it's been great to see. He has really
stepped it up during the playoffs. His goals have all been big
ones, not empty-netters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys have been kidding about the scoring,'' Sweeney
acknowledges. ``I've said all along that in the playoffs everyone
has to contribute in different areas. A defenseman might score a
goal, and a goal scorer has to check, too. It's all about
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney never was programmed for pro stardom. A 1984
eighth-round pick (166th overall), and even then somewhat
undersized, he had been a fine player at Harvard, but that plus 50
cents gets you the morning paper in the eyes of the NHL. But after
six playoff games in Portland in the spring of '88, he made it to
the big time the following season, bouncing back and forth between
the AHL and the NHL before coming back to Boston in January of '89.
He would spend only 11 more games in the minors before making it
back up for good.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, if anyone told him he was too small, he simply
ignored them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped believing that a long time ago,'' he says. ``For a
while at Harvard I tried to bulk up. But I'm actually lighter now
than I was then, and I'm quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   He may not say a whole lot in the locker room, but when the puck
is dropped he plays with a passion and fury that were born out of
fear and now simply are a reflection of gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might have taken me four or five years to establish myself
fully,'' he maintains. ``I was always afraid for my job in those
days. I'm talking about the difference between taking up space on
the roster and being able to make a real contribution. But I think
all that helped me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never stopped being grateful for being able to play in
the league, and for being able to play with Ray Bourque. I feel as
if I grew up watching him play, and the opportunity to play with
him here in Boston is something I never take for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   He will admit to being amused and fascinated as NHL defensemen
have continued to grow, even as he remains 5-10 and 180.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really see it every preseason,'' he says. ``That's when
every team brings out all its prospects for the exhibition games,
and each year they are getting bigger and bigger. It just amazes me
how big everyone is.''
</P>
<P>
   Big is nice, but the central question remains, ``Can you play?''
Very few of these young monsters will become the 11-year veteran
Don Sweeney is, let alone the 15-year veteran he almost certainly
will be. There must be more to it than size, skating, and shooting
ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart factor always comes into play,'' reminds Don
Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2066 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORBES19-COX     05-18 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FORBES OFFERS PLAN TO CREATE PRIVATIZE RETIREMENT ACCOUNTS
 &HT;    430&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes
offered a plan Tuesday to let workers to privately invest their
Social Security taxes, and challenged Vice President Al Gore to
debate him on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The union bosses might not like my message very much,'' Forbes
said in a speech to small business owners. ``The special interest
lobbyists in Washington may be a little worried about their job
security. But I can guarantee you that no hard-working union
employee would turn down the chance to double or triple his or her
retirement income.
</P>
<P>
   ``No senior citizen _ no matter what his or her politics _ would
deny their children and grandchildren the opportunity to build real
assets if they knew their own Social Security would be safe and
secure,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes offered to debate Social Security reform with Gore before
audiences of union workers in Michigan, senior citizens in Florida
and Arizona, and blacks and Latinos in California.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lahane, the vice president's spokesman, dismissed Forbes'
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an obvious ploy by a second-tier candidate to get some
attention,'' Lahane said. ``If Steve Forbes was really serious
about Social Security, he should begin within his own party, where
the right hand doesn't know what the left hand is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said his plan would fully protect those currently in the
Social Security system and those who would retire in the next 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   Younger people would be offered the choice of whether to stay in
the current system or invest part _ and eventually most _ of the
12.4 percent payroll tax shared by workers and employers in
government-approved 401 (k)-style personal investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would give people the opportunity to take their money out
of the hands of the Washington politicians, and invest it in the
real American economy. That way, they'd retire with far more than
they ever could receive under the current system,'' he said, if
returns matched historic stock market performance.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes would exempt the investment earnings from federal taxes.
He would also eliminate the current reduction in Social Security
benefits for recipients who continue earning wages between ages 65
and 69.
</P>
<P>
   Under his plan, workers would determine their own retirement age
without regard to the level of benefits they would receive.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to private retirement benefits, Forbes said a small
portion of the taxes could be used by workers to purchase their own
disability and life insurance benefits.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is the first major Republican candidate to outline a
proposal for dealing with Social Security, which is projected to be
able to pay full benefits only until 2034. His proposal differs
from that offered by GOP lawmakers in the House, who propose using
the projected federal surplus to finance the individual accounts.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has proposed using a portion of the federal
surplus to reduce the federal debt and credit that reduction toward
the Social Security trust fund. Clinton has also suggested using a
portion of the surplus to offer individual accounts in addition to
the money earmarked for the trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   Gore supports Clinton's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' proposal to replace Social Security with a private
retirement system follows his call in March for reforming the
health care system. He plans to detail his vision of conservatives'
role in the 2000 election in a speech Wednesday in New York. He
speaks this weekend in Georgia on education reform.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes spokesman Greg Mueller told the Associated Press that the
series of speeches reflects Forbes' basic campaign plan: build a
good organization and then focus on the ``politics of substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Forbes' opponents, most notably the front-runners, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas and Elizabeth Dole, have been criticized
for not discussing substantively issues such as Social Security and
health care.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
