<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S ACTING PREMIER PRESSES PARLIAMENT ON REFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's acting prime minister told parliament on
Tuesday that he would demand a vote of confidence in his new
government if it refused to enact economic reforms on which Western
lenders have conditioned billions of dollars in new loans.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Stepashin, President Boris Yeltsin's choice for prime
minister, issued the pledge as he met with major parties in the
Communist-led lower house of parliament, which will vote Wednesday
on his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin would replace parliament's hand-picked prime minister,
Yevgeny Primakov, whom Yeltsin abruptly dismissed last week. In
essence, Stepashin is urging the legislators to adopt the economic
package that Primakov negotiated with the International Monetary
Fund before Yeltsin fired him last week.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov had sent the broad outlines of those reforms to
parliament before being fired, but some items were omitted
entirely, and others were watered-down versions of the promises
made to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF is withholding judgment on the staggered release of $4.5
billion in loans _ enough, basically, to keep Russia from
defaulting on its foreign debt _ until officials see whether
serious reforms are under way. The World Bank has suspended plans
for $3 billion more in loans for infrastructure and social programs
until its board is satisfied that the Stepashin government is
committed to overhauling the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin spoke Tuesday only of the government's promises, and
did not clarify whether he intends to alter the weakened
legislation that Primakov has sent to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this package is rejected, the question of confidence in the
government will have to be raised,'' he said, ``since Russia will
fail to honor its commitments to the IMF that were assumed by the
Primakov government.''
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the package _ new taxes on gasoline and vehicles, and
curbs on politically influential banks, for instance _ will be
unpopular with many legislators, who not only are ideologically
against belt-tightening, but also face re-election in December.
</P>
<P>
   But Stepashin put new pressure on the parliament by hitching the
fate of his government to the reforms.
</P>
<P>
   If the legislators were to reject the package, they would be
hard-pressed to justify a vote in favor of his government. But a
vote of no confidence would not only force Stepashin to resign, but
also would give Yeltsin authority to dissolve the parliament and
call early elections.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators have no stomach for another battle with Yeltsin over
the job of prime minister. They have even less appetite for
dissolving parliament, a move which would deprive them of their
legislative soapboxes in the midst of an election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts once believed that the lower house of parliament
would reject Stepashin, a Yeltsin loyalist. But his prospects have
brightened since Yeltsin beat back an impeachment effort last
weekend and legislators began to conclude that the president holds
the upper hand in the choice of Primakov's successor.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of virtually every major faction said they were
satisfied with Stepashin's presentation Tuesday, in which he
stressed the need to fight crime and establish order in the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, meanwhile, was nowhere to be seen Tuesday and was
apparently ill again, though how seriously was not clear. His aides
issued vague and sometimes conflicting statements on his condition
through out the day.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin missed a scheduled morning meeting with Spanisn Prime
Minister Jose Maria Aznar, instead conducting a 45-minute telephone
conversation with Aznar from a country house outside Moscow.
Yeltsin's aides insisted that the meeting was never planned,
despite its appearance Monday on an official schedule.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Spanish government said in an interview that
the Kremlin had canceled the meeting, explaining that Yeltsin was
bedridden with bronchitis.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's spokesman at first denied that, calling it
``absolutely bewildering'' but later, in an interview with the
Reuters news service, declined to either confirm or deny the
report.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish spokesman said that Yeltsin seemed in good health
during the conversation with Aznar and that their conversation was
lively, ``frank and clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, 68, has not been seen in public since Friday. Saturday,
the day that the lower house of parliament voted on five counts of
impeachment against him, Yeltsin visited a Moscow hospital for what
was described as a routine health exam.
</P>
</TEXT>
