<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, May 23,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JUILLAIRD-MUSIC-SCHOOL (New York) _ How do you get to Carnegie
Hall? Practice hard, for sure, but take care, too, that your mental
and spiritual development keeps pace with the physical and
technical, to produce a well-rounded individual and artist. Those,
more or less, are the directions the Juilliard School is giving to
young musicians, dancers and actors hoping to find their way to
Carnegie and other prestigious stages. By James R. Oestreich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THEWLIS-BESIEGED-FILM (London) _ When actors sign up for a
movie, they rarely have much notion how it _ or they _ will end up
looking on screen. David Thewlis learned that some years ago with
Mike Leigh. He duly followed the British director's ritual of
spending weeks creating a character down to the tiniest detail. He
won the best actor prize at the 1993 Cannes Film Festival for
``Naked.'' His latest film, Bernardo Bertolucci's ``Besieged,''
which opened in New York on Friday, is a minimalist film set almost
entirely in a Roman palazzo, a love story between two people who
are seldom seen together, who barely exchange words and about whom
we learn little. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   HUGH-GRANT-FILMS (London) _ Is Hugh Grant, 38, the very model of
a modern English gentleman? He certainly seemed that way in ``Four
Weddings and a Funeral,'' a hugely successful confection of a film
largely kept afloat by his bachelor character's diffident charm,
self-deprecating wit and endearing air of chronic embarrassment.
Now he has been cast in the same mold in ``Notting Hill,'' a
comedy, opening on Friday, in which he plays the divorced, ironical
owner of a sleepy London bookstore whose life is turned upside down
by the sudden appearance of the world's most famous actress, played
by Julia Roberts. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ENSEMBLE-THEATER (Undated) _ In the last year or so, the London
stage has come to look like a stalker's den or autograph hound's
lair, so marked is the fashion for embellishing productions with
Hollywood faces. But the odd small voice has been heard, asking
what has happened to the principle of ensemble acting, and that
little chorus has recently been joined by a large voice. ``The work
can be the star, the company can be the star,'' declared Trevor
Nunn, director of the National Theater, in March. And he has
proceeded to prove his point with warmly received revivals of
Shakespeare's ``Troilus and Cressida'' and Leonard Bernstein's
musical version of Voltaire's ``Candide.'' These are the opening
offerings in a special season that by late summer will consist of
six plays, involve some 50 actors, and run concurrently with the
other productions in the National's repertory. By Benedict
Nightingale.
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD-NELSON-THEATER (London) _ Displacement and exile are
crucial issues to the American dramatist Richard Nelson, whose
plays, perhaps not coincidentally, usually have their premieres in
England, though their author lives along the Hudson River, north of
New York. Nelson has written about American academics in Britain in
his play ``Some Americans Abroad'' and about Britons living in
America in the more recent ``New England.'' But ``Goodnight
Children Everywhere,'' his latest play, opening Off Broadway on
Wednesday at Playwrights Horizons, marks the first time that Nelson
has written a work wholly about the English and set in England. By
Matt Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER (Undated) _ Theater reviews of ``Via Dolorosa'';
``Amy's View'' and ``The Lonesome West.'' By Vincent Canby.
</P>
<P>
   EAST-IS-EAST-THEATER (London) _ Ayub Khan-Din grew up in the
north of England in suburban Manchester, the eighth of 10 children
born to an English mother and an emigre father from Kashmir,
Pakistan, who between them ran a fish-and-chips shop. The nearest
sibling in the lineup above him was nearly four years older, while
three years separated Khan-Din from his next brother down the row.
And so, recalled the writer and actor, who is now 37: ``I wasn't
part of the older kids or the younger kids. I lived in my own world
and spent a lot of time daydreaming. It paid off in the end.'' For
proof, one need look no further than ``East Is East,'' Khan-Din's
bittersweet, semi-autobiographical comedy about growing up in the
early 1970s in a mixed-race Anglo-Asian household, where there were
often as many as four children to a bed and the toilet was
outdoors. By Matt Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SARGENT-ART (Boston) _ For half his life, from 1890, when he was
at the height of his career, until his death in 1925, John Singer
Sargent was under contract to produce murals and decorative schemes
for public buildings in Boston. The son of an expatriate New
England doctor, Sargent lived mostly in Europe; but in Boston he
had close friends and family, and he visited often. Boston was the
American city closest to his European sensibility; it understood
him best. And thanks to ``Sargent Summer,'' a series of exhibitions
timed to coincide with the last stop of the Sargent retrospective
at the Museum of Fine Arts (June 27 through Sept. 26), Boston is
once again the city where one can come to a new understanding of
the reticent artist and his art. By Deborah Weisgall.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-ARTIST (North Adams, Mass.) _ A new installation will be
introduced here next Sunday by the video artist Tony Oursler.
Titled ``Optics'' and aimed at investigating the origins of sound
and light media, Oursler's new work was commissioned by the
Williams College Museum of Art in nearby Williamstown and the
Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art, called colloquially Mass
MOCA. Oursler's work will have its premiere as part of Mass MOCA's
long awaited opening, also next Sunday. By Ann Wilson Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   CHERMAYETT-PRINTS (East Topsham, Vt.) _ The graphic designer
Ivan Chermayeff, who makes prints from collages of found objects
like old gloves, flattened steel buckets, hole-riddled boards and
rope winders, is now on view at the Ricco/Maresca Gallery in New
York City. By Rita Reif. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-BLUES-RADIO (Undated) _ Every Saturday night, radio
listeners in Istanbul can hear a voice in heavily accented Turkish
welcome them to another evening of blues music. The announcer says,
``Yalniz gercek blues caliyorum,'' which means, ``I only play real
blues.'' I am that announcer. For the last year I've been feeding
the blues habit of educated listeners and, I hope, bringing ever
more Turks into the worldwide family of blues lovers. By Stephen
Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
