<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2074 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINES-COX     05-18 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumers not high on airline service
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The airline industry is now on par with trial lawyers
_ and only slightly above cable TV companies _ in consumer esteem.
</P>
<P>
   That's the conclusion of Consumer Reports magazine's annual
airline service rating in the upcoming June issue.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine jumps on the airline-bashing bandwagon, noting that
``air travelers have become so irate that their treatment at the
hands of airlines has become a national political issue.''
</P>
<P>
   It says service is declining at the biggest carriers, despite
strong profits. Smaller or low-fare carriers now offer comparable
service at better prices, it adds.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine didn't rank airlines numerically but offered a
bottom-line assessment along with category scores.
</P>
<P>
   Of Atlanta-based Delta it said: ``Overall satisfaction has
fallen steeply. . . rarely a low-price leader. . . fewer seats for
frequent fliers than other big airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   A Delta spokesman said the survey may not reflect recent
improvements, notably in on-time performance. Delta handles 80
percent of the traffic at Hartsfield International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The report said rival AirTran ``is about equal to Delta in
overall customer satisfaction, but offers better flight attendant
service and lower fares.''
</P>
<P>
   Highly rated are Midwest Express, a small, all-first-class
carrier based in Milwaukee; no-frills giant Southwest; and
Raleigh-Durham-based Midway.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine combines a variety of measures, including reports
from thousands of Consumer Reports subscribers about flights in
late 1997 and early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-nine percent were ``highly satisfied,'' down from 52
percent in 1994, the magazine said. ``Based on our other surveys of
consumer services . . . only cable TV companies and commercial diet
programs irked them more.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
