<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran's new plane makes early stop in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The world's next new airliner made a stopover Tuesday
in Atlanta, where it's scheduled to enter service this fall with
discount carrier AirTran.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing 717 is essentially a fourth-generation update of the
venerable DC-9, which now makes up the bulk of AirTran's fleet.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran has orders for 50 of the 117-seat jets, with the first
two due for delivery in September and the rest coming over the next
four years.
</P>
<P>
   An initial production model, already painted in AirTran colors,
is undergoing 10 days of simulated service on the carrier's routes
as part of the flight test program.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran hopes the 717 will lower operating costs and dash its
reputation for flying aged equipment. It displayed the plane
Tuesday morning at Hartsfield International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tremendous jump for us,'' said Jerry O.
Beatenbaugh, AirTran's director of liaison engineering with Boeing.
``It's more efficient and reliable, and it's brand new.''
</P>
<P>
   By 2004, AirTran says, the 717 will cut its average fleet age to
9.3 years, from 27.5 years now, as DC-9s and 737s are phased out.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier plans a fall ad campaign touting the new jet. Today,
the test jet will be in New York, where AirTran has invited
financial analysts for a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Outwardly the t-tail, twin-engine jet is nearly identical to its
forebears, the DC-9, MD-80 and MD-90.
</P>
<P>
   The chief differences include a new engine, built by BMW Rolls
Royce, and a state-of-the-art cockpit system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Stars Wars stuff up here,'' said Beatenbaugh,
sitting in the co-pilot's seat and pointing to flat-panel video
screens that display flight and navigation data.
</P>
<P>
   The plane burns 20 percent less fuel than AirTran's DC-9s and
doesn't require as much upkeep as older planes. The plane was
designed as the MD-95 by McDonnell Douglas Corp. before it was
absorbed by Boeing, which redesignated the jet the 717.
</P>
<P>
   ValuJet, which acquired AirTran and adopted its name in 1997,
was the first airline to order the 717.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier, which has had only two profitable quarters since
1997, is still arranging financing for the $20 million 717s.
</P>
<P>
   Executives contend the costs of buying the planes will be more
than offset by lower operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   Cutbacks at Boeing have prompted speculation it might scrap the
717 program because of weak orders and duplication with the
smallest version of the 737. The company says all programs are
under review this year.
</P>
<P>
   But spokesman Warren Lamb said the 717 is designed for shorter
routes than the 737-600. ``It's a high frequency, up-and-down
airplane,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A 50-plane order from TWA this winter boosted the program's
prospects, and two leasing companies have ordered 15.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
