<SLUG> BC-AT-ADAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Adam.com to provide data to Cox
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Adam.com and Cox Interactive Media, both Atlanta
based, announced a deal that will make Adam the provider of health
care information on more than 30 Internet sites operated by Cox
Interactive.
</P>
<P>
   Adam will develop health care content especially for each of the
local markets served by Cox Interactive, sites that include Access
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The companies will share the revenue generated by the health
care pages, said Robert Cramer, chief executive of Adam.com. ``It's
a real partnership. It lets us provide our advertisers with access
to the local market as well as the national market.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam has of late operated somewhat in the shadow of another
Atlanta-based Internet health care company. WebMD Inc., which only
last week pulled back from a high-profile offering of stock, was
poised late Tuesday to detail a merger with Santa Clara,
Calif.-based Healtheon.
</P>
<P>
   Adam views the deal as a business endorsement that contrasts
with the hoopla about WebMD, Cramer said.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Interactive ``wanted to go with the finest provider of
health care information, and this agreement further established
Adam.com as the leading provider of consumer health information on
the Net.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors have also been coming to Adam's side. Shares of
Adam.com stock, which had slipped slightly Tuesday, reached its
52-week high the day before after a long and steady climb. In
November, Adam was trading as low as $2.25 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Interactive's network includes 25 city sites and three
specialty sites, BlackFamilies.com, FASTBALL.com and
GreatOutdoors.com.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Interactive is a unit of Cox Enterprises, which also owns
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
