<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Track to get safety fences in time for Indy eventBy Mark
Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Motor Speedway will extend the height of its
wheel fences before hosting an Indy Racing League event in July.
</P>
<P>
   Speedway Motorsports Inc., the Charlotte-based company that owns
the Hampton facility, announced Tuesday that it also will extend
the fences at its tracks in Concord, N.C., Las Vegas and Fort
Worth, Texas, all of which host IRL events.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes after a May 2 accident killed three
spectators during an IRL race at Lowe's Motor Speedway in Concord.
Three people were killed and eight injured when debris from a
three-car wreck flew into the stands during the VisionAire 500.
</P>
<P>
   The modifications will extend the total height of the fences at
the tracks from approximately 15 feet to 21 feet and extend the
catch fence over the track surface from approximately three feet to
six.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the responsible thing to do,'' said Ed Clark,
president and general manager of AMS. ``We feel that this is a
quality improvement to an already well-constructed fencing system.
We will continue to work with the IRL, other tracks and the racing
community in an effort to make racing events as safe as possible
for all involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press also is reporting that the IRL will begin
requiring wheel-tether systems at next week's Indianapolis 500 in
response to the sport's latest fatal accident involving spectators.
But IRL officials refused Tuesday to confirm their intentions to
start making their teams use restraining cables designed to do a
better job of keeping wheels from snapping free from the vehicles
on impact.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Gapens, spokesman for Lowe's Motor Speedway, said the
taller fences would be installed at his facility before the May 30
Coca-Cola 600 NASCAR race.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
