   With map.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-LIFE-SUPPORT (Orlando, Fla.) _ A judge rules that an Orlando
woman, paralyzed after being shot by her mother who feared going to
a nursing home, may be removed from life support. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   FED (Washington) _ The Federal Reserve put investors and
consumers on notice today that it might raise interest rates in
coming months if it continues to see signs that inflation is
brewing. Although it voted to hold rates steady for now, the
central bank dropped its neutral stance on monetary policy, under
which it considered the possibility of rate cuts and rate increases
to be equally likely, and said it was now leaning toward imposing
higher rates. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-DATACENTERS (Schaumburg, Ill.) _ Internet data centers
are sprouting up across the country in a sure sign of the trend
toward once again housing information and computer power centrally
_ a seeming reversal of the last two decades of computing. The
personal computer defined the industry's recent history and how
computers were used. As personal computers spread rapidly in the
early 1980s, they were seen as engines of individual empowerment
and decentralization of information. But now the Internet is the
technology behind a new economics, tearing down old hierarchies and
flattening corporate organizations _ is fueling a recentralization
of information and a revival of big iron computing. By Steve Lohr
with John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ASSESS (Washington) _ In constitutional law, as in
geology, things can look perfectly stable on the surface _ until
the tectonic plates shift underneath. As the Supreme Court term
heads into its final weeks, the question is whether such a shift
may be underway. In its decision on Monday striking down
California's reduced welfare benefits for newcomers to the state,
the court relied on a portion of the 14th amendment that forbids
states to ``abridge the privileges or immunities of citizens of the
United States.'' This is the long-neglected privileges or
immunities clause, the sudden resurrection of which, by a broad
7-to-2 majority, was certainly one of the most surprising and
perhaps one of the most consequential developments of the term. By
Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton does not rule out
the use of ground troops in Kosovo, but says that the air war needs
more time. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
