</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia school tries to reach championship milestone
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kennesaw State University is one of only two schools
in the nation to win baseball and softball national titles in the
same season. This spring, the school is only a few victories away
from accomplishing the feat for the second time.
</P>
<P>
   The softball team begins play in the eight-team Division II
championship series Thursday in Salem, Va. while the baseball team
continues its quest for a national title Sunday in the eight-team
Division II World Series in Montgomery. The baseball team (46-12),
coached by Mike Sansing, is ranked No. 1, while Scott Whitlock's
softball team takes a 50-5 record and the No. 2 ranking into its
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams have dominated Division II competition in recent
years, the softball team winning consecutive national titles in
1995 and 1996 and the baseball team winning the 1996 title. The
national titles in '96 matched Cal-State Northridge, which won both
Division II titles in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball team, which won the NAIA national title in 1994
before moving to Division II, earned its fourth consecutive berth
in the championship series by winning the South Atlantic Regional
title in Jacksonville last weekend. Led by senior outfielder Jason
Jones, the two-time South Atlantic player of the year, the KSU Owls
hope to improve on last year's national runner-up finish when they
begin tournament play Sunday against Carson Newman (42-12-2).
</P>
<P>
   The softball team, which knocked off No. 1-ranked Columbus State
and Coker in winning the South Atlantic Regional at home last
weekend, will be appearing in the national tournament for the
fourth time in the past five years. Led by All-American pitcher
Christina Caldwell, Kennesaw State will face Merrimack College
(42-4) of North Andover, Mass., on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Earnest Reese writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
