<SLUG> BC-HOMEDEPOT-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Record profits enjoyed by Home Depot
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta-based Home Depot Inc. said first-quarter
profit rose a record 45 percent as customers spent more on building
materials, flooring and home decor.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's response on Tuesday was comparatively mild. The
stock rose 18 3/4 cents to $58.62 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Net income rose to $489 million, or 32 cents a share, from $337
million, or 22 cents, a year earlier. Home Depot was expected to
earn 28 cents a share, according to an average estimate of analysts
polled by First Call Corp. Home Depot has beaten profit forecasts
five quarters in a row and 15 out of the past 21, according to
First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 26 percent to $8.95 billion from $7.12 billion.
Sales at stores open at least a year rose 9 percent. Same-store
sales are a key indicator of a retailer's business because they
don't include new, renovated or closed stores. Specifically, stores
in Atlanta and Dallas were strong performers, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Mortgage rates near 7 percent and rising wages are fueling the
housing market, and sales of existing homes reached a record pace
in March. That drives new customers to Home Depot for lights,
wallpaper and other supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Customers showed a preference for pricier goods in the first
quarter, the company said. The average sale rose 6 percent to $48
as customers tended to buy higher quality products. Average weekly
sales per store rose to $878,000 from $854,000.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's new focus on hiring tradesmen is paying off, said
Ron Brill, executive vice president and chief administrative
officer. Those experienced employees typically sell higher-margin
merchandise, which offsets a spike in wages Home Depot is forced to
pay as it looks for qualified people in a tight labor market, Brill
said.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot, the largest home improvement retailer, continues to
take market share from rival chains that close stores. Home Depot
has an estimated 18 percent share of the $170 billion-a-year U.S.
home-improvement market.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot ended the quarter with nearly 800 stores, including
eight Expo Design Centers. A new concept dubbed Villager's Hardware
opens next month in East Brunswick, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Lowe's Companies Inc., the No. 2 home improvement
retailer, reported a 24 percent increase in first quarter earnings,
including a one-time charge.
</P>
<P>
   The retail industry in general is enjoying a strong first
quarter. Of the 97 retailers that have reported results so far this
quarter, more than 70 percent beat earnings forecasts, according to
First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
