<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOSOVO AT TWO-MONTH MARKER SHAPING UP AS DISASTER FOR CLINTON
TEAM
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-BORDER-0519; KOSOVO-MULE-0519.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the windowless Situation Room beneath the White
House West Wing, President Clinton and his senior national security
team gathered late Monday around a large wooden table to take up
the harrowing nightmare that is Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In black leather armchairs in the dark paneled chamber sat
Madeleine Albright, William Cohen, Samuel Berger, Gen. Hugh Shelton
and a handful of other architects of a high stakes policy bearing
the ominous earmarks of a grim and unmitigated debacle.
</P>
<P>
   From Defense Secretary Cohen and Joint Chiefs of Staff Chairman
Shelton came the update on an air campaign that, after two months
and some 22,000 sorties and more than 10,000 bombs, has seriously
damaged but failed to root out, destroy or even significantly
reduce the estimated 40,000 Serb troops and police that have
ravaged Kosovo in the single worst military onslaught unleashed on
European soil since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   From Secretary of State Albright came the latest on an equally
grisly diplomatic toll: fractured U.S. relations with the world's
most populous nation, China, and the politically and economically
addled possessor of the world's second-largest nuclear arsenal,
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   National Security Advisor Berger pondered the risks of pressing
forward with a campaign hamstrung by the limits of coalition air
power, undercut by hundreds of civilian casualties and stalked at
every turn by the capricious laws of unintended consequences.
</P>
<P>
   And unseen but just as surely present hung the ghastly human
toll of Kosovo, where Serbs have forced an estimated 1.3 million
ethnic Albanians to flee their homes, raped or executed thousands
more, and sacked to ash and rubble more than 300 villages in a tiny
province no larger than the state of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Adjourning what must have been one of the most somber meetings
of his political career, Clinton concluded that there was no
alternative but to press forward with air raids and hope for a
diplomatic breakthrough that might bring the conflict to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very hopeful, obviously, that the diplomatic efforts that
are being made in the State Department and with the Russians will
bear some fruit,'' Clinton told reporters at the White House on
Tuesday. ``But, if they do not, we will continue to press ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago Wednesday, solemn but resolute, Clinton sat in
the Oval Office and explained to the American people why U.S. and
allied warplanes had launched cruise missiles and smart bombs
against Yugoslav forces in the embattled province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We act to protect thousands of innocent people in Kosovo from
a mounting military offensive,'' Clinton said, hauling out colorful
maps to try to help viewers figure out where Kosovo is and why it
matters to the American Heartland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ending this tragedy is a moral imperative,'' Clinton said.
Without NATO action, he added, ``There would be many more massacres
-- tens of thousands more refugees, more victims crying out for
revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Judged strictly by the noble mission enshrined in Clinton's own
words, the NATO campaign to combat Serb aggression has fallen
nothing short of disaster to many military and diplomatic
observers.
</P>
<P>
   Since the NATO strikes began on March 24, an estimated 90
percent of the majority ethnic Albanians in Kosovo have been forced
by terror to flee their homes in the worst mass exodus to haunt
Europe since the collapse of Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   More than 800,000 have taken refuge outside of Kosovo; the rest
are hiding, and probably starving, inside the province, with no
near-term prospects for meaningful relief, according to the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has estimated that more than 4,000 ethnic
Albanians have been executed inside Kosovo -- though impossible to
independently confirm, refugees have given eyewitness accounts of
massacres in more than 70 separate villages and towns -- and up to
100,000 more are missing.
</P>
<P>
   If this is what Clinton had in mind when he launched the strikes
against Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia, he
gave no indication of it then.
</P>
<P>
   ``If President Milosevic will not make peace, we will limit his
ability to make war,'' Clinton assured the country. ``Hopefully Mr.
Milosevic will realize his present course is self-destructive and
unsustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   What White House officials had hoped would be three or four days
of air strikes, though, has turned instead into an escalating
aerial war of attrition waged against a determined and dispersed
ground force hunkered down for a long stand off against NATO
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the daily attempts by the U.S. and NATO public relations
shops to put the best possible face on the operation, the policy
experts struggling to manage the campaign and its fallout concede
that they are struggling to rescue a mission beset by a long string
of enormous setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like trying to judge the outcome of a game at the end of
the second quarter,'' said Deputy National Security Advisor James
Steinberg, maintaining that it's still too early to render a
verdict on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And, said Steinberg, to the extent the going's been tough, the
United States and its NATO allies had no real choice but to strike
at Milosevic's military regime and hope for the best on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a problem that had to be solved,'' Steinberg said in a
telephone interview. ``If you're going to have a stable Europe, you
have to take this on, you can't just wish it away.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
