<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL RESERVE SIGNALS IT IS LEANING TOWARD HIGHER INTEREST
RATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Reserve put investors and consumers on
notice Tuesday that it might raise interest rates in coming months
if it continues to see signs of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Although it voted to hold rates steady for now, the central
bank's policymaking Federal Open Market Committee dropped its
neutral stance on monetary policy, under which it considered the
possibility of rate cuts and rate increases to be equally likely.
Instead, it said it was leaning toward imposing higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   The shift was subtle, but it signaled a clear change in the
Federal Reserve's outlook following three interest rate reductions
last fall in response to the global financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the committee said it was ``concerned about the
potential for a buildup of inflationary imbalances that could
undermine the favorable performance of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors and economists, who considered the odds of such a
shift roughly 50-50, were well prepared for the announcement, which
came just after 2:15 p.m. Tuesday. It rattled Wall Street, but only
briefly. Stocks, which had been up modestly, turned down before
recovering most of their losses. Bond prices fell, and the dollar
dipped slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed took a step without tightening policy, and signaled to
investors in an orderly fashion where they think the risks lie,''
said Joel Prakken, an economist at Macroeconomic Advisors, a
consulting firm. ``They're saying the economy is going too fast
given how low the unemployment rate is.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the move was intended to show that the Federal
Reserve is no longer so worried about a global downturn or a credit
squeeze in the financial markets, and is increasingly concerned by
the possibility that strong domestic growth at a time of low
unemployment could set off an inflationary spiral in prices and
wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The odds are high, although far from 100 percent, that an
upward move in interest rates is coming,'' said Allen Sinai, chief
global economist at Primark Decision Economics, a consulting firm.
``Quite properly and early, the central bank has shifted focus to a
potential inflationary buildup in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   The move came on the heels of the report on Friday that the
Consumer Price Index had risen 0.7 percent in April, the biggest
jump since 1990. And it came just two weeks after Alan Greenspan,
the Federal Reserve chairman, warned in a speech that inflation
remained a threat despite the tremendous economic gains stimulated
by huge investments in new technology during the course of a
business expansion that is now in its ninth year.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing and explaining the move following its meeting
Tuesday, the central bank was employing for the first time a policy
it adopted last fall of revealing shifts in its intentions
immediately. Previously, except when it actually raised or lowered
interest rates, the Federal Reserve had kept changes in its policy
stance secret until after the subsequent meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The new disclosure policy was adopted partly in response to
longstanding calls from Congress and the markets for the Fed to be
more open. But it also gives the Fed more flexibility in preparing
investors and the public for rate changes and avoiding sharp,
destabilizing swings in stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said the Fed could raise rates as soon as its next
policy meeting at the end of next month, especially if there are
further signs of inflation or a further drop in unemployment from
its current rate of 4.3 percent. But economists said that if the
economy begins to cool on its own, the Fed would likely hold off on
any rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   The main short-term rate controlled by the Federal Reserve, the
Federal funds target rate on overnight loans between banks, stands
at 4.75 percent. The discount rate on loans from the Federal
Reserve system to the banks is 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The American economy has been defying predictions of a slowdown
for several years _ it grew at a robust 4.5 percent pace in the
first quarter _ yet until now has generated almost no concrete
signs of incipient inflation despite a declining unemployment rate.
In many ways, the spike in consumer prices last month is an
anomaly, because prices at the producer level, wages and other
indicators of potential bottlenecks, like the portion of factory
capacity being used, show few or no signs of worrisome increases.
</P>
<P>
   Within the Fed, and among economists generally, the situation
has set off a debate about whether the economy can now grow for
sustained periods at higher rates without generating inflation that
traditional models would suggest. Greenspan has been among those
who have made the case that technology-driven increases in
productivity _ or the amount of output generated per worker _ have
improved the economy's non-inflationary growth capacity and allowed
the Fed to avoid rate increases, with one exception, for more than
four years.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan has made clear that his faith in productivity
improvements has its limits, and he is apparently reaching them
now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan and his colleagues on the policy committee, some of
whom have been far less sanguine about inflation than he, also
confront a reviving world economy, and a domestic stock market that
has left people from all walks of life feeling affluent and willing
to spend. As a result, demand is likely to remain strong or
intensify while pressure for wage increases is likely to grow.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed is also facing a rebound in oil prices, which had been
falling or depressed for several years, helping to contain
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In its statement Tuesday, the committee acknowledged that
``increases in costs and core prices have generally remained quite
subdued'' apart from last month's jump in consumer prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``But domestic financial markets have recovered and foreign
economic prospects have improved since the easing of monetary
policy last fall,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against the background of already tight domestic labor markets
and ongoing strength in demand in excess of productivity gains, the
committee recognizes the need to be alert to developments over
coming months that might indicate that financial conditions might
no longer be consistent with containing inflation,'' the statement
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are clearly dangers for the Fed in raising rates,
especially if the increase is seen in the markets and among the
public as hasty. Without any clear evidence of inflation, a rate
increase could fuel political criticism of the Fed and bring
protests from sectors of the economy, like manufacturing and
agriculture, that have been missing out on the general prosperity
of the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   A rate increase could also drive the value of the dollar higher
against other currencies, making imports relatively more attractive
and making it harder for American exporters to compete in foreign
markets. That could make the trade deficit, which has been
expanding rapidly, even worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed also has to be careful not to unsettle the stock market
too much. Although Greenspan has made clear for several years now
that he thinks stock prices may be too high, Fed officials are well
aware that if higher rates puncture the market in a way that leads
to a steep drop, it could pinch off consumer spending and risk
putting the economy into a stall.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, the committee's statement Tuesday
seemed intended in part to dispel the notion that has become
popular among some economists in the last few months that Greenspan
and his colleagues are less inclined to strike at inflation before
it takes root and more likely to wait until they have concrete
evidence of its return before raising rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
