<HEADLINE>
FRENZIED WALL STREET HAS HUMBLE ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA BASS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVILLE, Calif. _ On May 17, 1792, some two dozen brokers,
accustomed to casually meeting on lower Wall Street to exchange
brandy, gossip and bonds, decided to make their arrangement
permanent.
</P>
<P>
   The result of this humble agreement evolved, over time, into the
U.S. securities market. It is the most beloved, hated, feared,
respected and closely watched (never more than at this very moment)
financial community of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Few institutions so perfectly capture the pulse of this decade
as the American securities industry. Dot coms, day traders, Dow
11,000; 80 million Americans owning equities _ all inconceivable 10
years ago _ are today merely part of the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons our consumer-driven economy is so strong is
the ``wealth effect'' _ the direct result of our investments in the
booming bull market of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   That the securities market so typifies '90s America should not
be surprising. The market has reflected the nature and trends of
the U.S. economy right from the start.
</P>
<P>
   For its first 100 years, however, that economy was decidedly
different from today's. Modern corporate structure was unknown; so
was globalization; so was mass consumption.
</P>
<P>
   The market also was different, trading mostly in canal issues
and railroads and long-term government bonds; on one day _ March
16, 1830 _ only 31 shares were traded. The market was different in
other ways, too. Brokers, for instance, were forbidden to spit
(which hasn't changed, but it's no longer a written rule.)
</P>
<P>
   The modern securities market emerged rather late in the 19th
century, when a slew of new and capital-hungry industries _
petroleum, rubber, telephone, steel _ shifted investor interest
into manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   Until World War I, though, most investors were professionals _
financial sophisticates working out of banks or large investment
houses and armed with insider information (or so they hoped).
</P>
<P>
   It was only when war began that the general public entered the
market, mostly through Liberty Bonds sold by the federal government
to help finance military expenses. Nonprofessional investors
relished the Liberty Bond experience. They not only made money but
got credit for being patriotic. When the war ended, they sought to
repeat it, through increasingly fevered involvement in the
securities market.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1920s, that market was on fire, with intense public
interest, shrieking financial headlines and seesawing closing
averages. (Sound familiar?)
</P>
<P>
   More and more businesses, some very well-known, turned to the
market for financing. General Motors, Sears and Union Carbide were
all added to the Dow during this period, joining General Electric _
the oldest Dow member _ and AT&AMP;T. Trading on margin was common _
even encouraged _ as first-time investors, following glib advice
pumped out by so-called experts, groped their way toward a
seemingly limitless future.
</P>
<P>
   The future arrived in 1929 with a crash, plunging the nation
into the Depression and a decade of financial despair. Even today
it haunts (or ought to) the most optimistic investor.
</P>
<P>
   Could it happen again? Parallels between the '20s and '90s are
creepily striking. Both decades are noted for great economic growth
and sound fundamentals; both are noted, further, for rapid
consolidation, increasing globalization and new forms of economic
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Most noteworthy of all, however, is how strongly our
generation's fascination with new technology stocks (eBay and
amazon.com) echoes the '20s speculation in its new technologies:
radio, airplanes and motion pictures, especially talkies.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, just like today, many of the hottest stocks of that
era had shockingly (for their time) high price/earnings ratios and
_ equally shocking, and equally familiar today _ no actual
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But while the question _ could it happen again? _ is worth
repeating, it actually isn't the question we need to ask. For
keeping in mind that the history of the American securities market
has always been, over time, the history of the economy itself, the
real question is: Over the long term, how will the economy do?
</P>
<P>
   For those who believe (and many do) we have entered a new
economic era, then Dow 20,000 already is on the horizon; you should
stop reading this column at once, run to your phone or computer,
and make some investments.
</P>
<P>
   As for those who believe the opposite _ who fear our economy
rests on too much easy money, that inflation has not been tamed,
and that disaster is only an Alan Greenspan comment away _ you
should find out what selling short means.
</P>
</TEXT>
