   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; ENTREPRENEUR BUDGET &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; VENTURE  &LR; _ At this year's Red Herring's Venture conference at Squaw
Valley, entrepreneurs, venture capitalists and other high-tech
afficionados spent little time gazing at the majestic Sierras or
watching the snow melt. One of the few who did, Hans Swildens, a
director of Personify Inc. in San Francisco, learned his lesson. He
broke his ankle riding a snowboard down the Granite Chief run
Sunday afternoon and had to spend the next two days talking to
prospective investors and partners about his interactive marketing
software startup with his leg raised.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 726 invitation-only guests who paid about $2,000
each to attend the popular information technology forum came to get
a leg up on the competition in a different way - by networking
non-stop. By Peter Sinton
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GROW  &LR; _ Peter Sinton's Q&AMP;A column on growing a business.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CISCO  &LR; _ Cisco Systems is moving aggressively into the small
and medium-sized business market, targeting companies that lack
technology. The networking giant is developing curriculum with the
Small Business Adminstration to help companies learn about
everything from PCs to routers. The payoff for Cisco: Potential
future customers. By Deborah Solomon
</P>
