<SLUG> BC-KANEMATSU-CUTBACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANEMATSU, AILING JAPANESE CONGLOMERATE, PLANS MAJOR DOWNSIZING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Kanematsu Corp., a large and financially troubled
Japanese trading conglomerate, on Tuesday announced a three-year
plan to cut more than half of its work force of 17,000, spin off or
farm out assets, and seek forgiveness of more than $3 billion of
bank debt.
</P>
<P>
   The plan announced by Kanematsu officials at a news conference
was one of the most radical overhauls of a major Japanese business
struggling with the country's long recession.
</P>
<P>
   The job cutbacks _ including two-thirds of 1,938 positions at
the parent company _ were taken as an indication that Japan's
unemployment rate, which has reached a new record high almost every
month since the beginning of the year, would continue climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Once a symbol of Japan's economic might, the trading companies
in particular have struggled in recent years because of heavy debts
they had amassed to diversify beyond a now-dwindling role as
middlemen in the global movement of goods.
</P>
<P>
   Kanematsu, the ninth-largest trading company, was known to be in
trouble. But the magnitude of its job reductions and other cutbacks
was considered a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had suspected that the company was effectively bankrupt
since it posted weak six-month results last fall, and its
acknowledgment that it would need the assistance of major creditors
to get back on its feet, including the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi,
validated their suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   Kanematsu president Masao Yosomiya said he would ask banks to
forgive 370 billion yen in debts, or more than $3 billion.
Kanematsu may also try to get its banks and affiliated companies to
buy 20 billion yen in new shares, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trading company sharply lowered its earnings estimate for
the fiscal year that ended on March 31 _ to 100 million yen, or
$811,000 at current exchange rates, from 3 billion yen, or $24.3
million, saying it would have special charges related to its
affiliated companies.
</P>
<P>
   It also reduced its revenue forecast to 2.25 billion yen, a 16.7
percent decline from the previous forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Kanematsu shares plummeted 26 percent in Tokyo on Tuesday
closing at 97 yen.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its overhaul, the company will spin off its
relatively strong textile business and hand over various operations
to affiliates, including chemicals, industrial machinery and the
marketing of fuel and steel products.
</P>
<P>
   The number of companies in the group will be reduced to 70 from
the current 230 through mergers, sales and outright liquidation.
</P>
<P>
   After all the cutting, Kanematsu will focus on food,
telecommunications, electronics, metals and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're chopping the fish into several pieces and hoping some
of the pieces will swim,'' said Matt Aizawa, an analyst who follows
the biggest Japanese trading companies for Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's Investors Service lowered its rating on Kanematsu's
senior debt and said it would keep the company's ratings under
review with an eye toward a further downgrading. ``The rating
downgrade reflects the quickly deteriorating business and financial
fundamentals of the company,'' Moody's said in a statement. ``The
continuing review will focus on the level of financial support from
its bank lenders and the anticipated results of its restructuring
plan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
