</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q and A with Elizabeth Dole
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. _ Elizabeth Dole will bring her undeclared
campaign for the Republican presidential nomination to the Georgia
GOP convention in Augusta Saturday. In advance of that appearance,
Dole, 62, talked from her campaign headquarters overlooking the
Potomac River in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The magnificent view from her office window includes
Washington's National Cathedral, where, she pointed out, she and
former Sen. Bob Dole were married more than 23 years ago. Her
husband provided some unwelcome news this week, voicing concern
about Dole's campaign and telling a reporter that he would like to
give money to a rival.
</P>
<P>
   Dole laughed when the interview began with a question about her
husband:
</P>
<P>
   Q: I hadn't planned to start with this...but what is he up to?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, he's had a little trip to the woodshed, the Dole
woodshed. But the bottom line, as they say, is the interpretation
was not what he intended. He's been out there for so long now
talking about me. He's been very, very supportive. He is prepared
to help in any way to see this happen...He looked pretty good in
the woodshed, though.
</P>
<P>
   Q: He hasn't been . . .
</P>
<P>
   A: Visible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is that going to change?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, yes. Definitely. But he and I both feel it's best for me
to establish myself solo early on. That's the plan. I think that
makes sense. He was the nominee of the party last time. It is my
effort. Bob is in no way directing it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When do you expect to make a decision about whether you are
going to be a candidate? Have you already?
</P>
<P>
   A: You know, I am still in the exploratory stage, but I have
directed my staff to be looking ahead, to be making plans that
maybe mid-summer or early fall we'd move into the next phase.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The issues you've highlighted so far (particularly a more
inclusive view on abortion and support for gun control) have
certainly not been the typical path toward the Republican
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   A: My belief is, you say ... what you think and even people who
disagree with you, they'll respect you for being consistent...I
can't believe there is any reason a person would need an AK-47 or
an Uzi to defend their family or hunt. That to me is a reasonable,
solid position. No reason for any form of cop killer bullets ... I
think my position in New Hampshire was vindicated in terms of child
safety locks because we see the Senate right now very likely to
move forward with mandatory child safety locks. That makes a big
difference in terms of accidental deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On the abortion issue... one of the ways to influence policy
on abortion is to appoint judges who are... pro-life. Are you
willing to make that statement?
</P>
<P>
   A: My view is that you appoint people who are as highly
qualified as you can find, who have the right qualifications,
credentials, skills. I would expect them to share my judicial
philosophy, which is you interpet the Constitution, you don't
legislate from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In 1996, there were stories that you were more acceptable to
social conservatives than your husband was. This time around, at
least early on, that doesn't seem to be.
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not a person who puts my finger up to the wind...My
passion doesn't come from polling. I'm going to speak what I
believe. There may be people in my party who don't agree with that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're the first woman (to be a) serious candidate for the
presidency...
</P>
<P>
   A: I've been on the cutting edge in many different positions in
30 years of service to the public...I was the only woman on the
Federal Trade Commission, but I was not regarded as the woman
commissioner. ..I was the first woman to head the Department of
Transportation and I did ask, because it was very much
male-dominated, how many women did we have in the department...They
said 19 percent were female. At the time they established the
department, it was 18 1/2 percent. They had come up half a
percentage point (in 14 years).
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're going to Georgia this weekend. Are Southerners ready
to vote for a woman for president?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think so. From everything I've heard, yes. The country is
ready and that includes my home territory.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Even some of your supporters in Georgia...intimate that it
wouldn't be such a bad thing if there were a Bush-Dole ticket...
</P>
<P>
   A: Let me clear that up right now... I'm not in this to be vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
