<HEADER>
A2092 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-BLUES-RADIO-AR     05-18 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-BLUES-RADIO-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUDDY WATERS AND BESSIE SMITH COME TO ISTANBUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Acik Radio engineer Serter Alkaya is being sent
to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every Saturday night, radio listeners in Istanbul can hear a
voice in heavily accented Turkish welcome them to another evening
of blues music. The announcer says, ``Yalniz gercek blues
caliyorum,'' which means, ``I only play real blues.''
</P>
<P>
   I am that announcer. For the last year I've been feeding the
blues habit of educated listeners and, I hope, bringing ever more
Turks into the worldwide family of blues lovers.
</P>
<P>
   My show, ``Smokestack Lightnin','' is hardly the first or only
blues show in Turkey. Istanbul is one of the world's most vibrant
and sophisticated cities, and many people here are tuned in to
world culture just as completely as their cousins in London or
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   But as far as I know, I am the first American host of a blues
show in Turkey, the first disk jockey here who not only features
artists like Lightnin' Hopkins, Alberta Hunter, Roosevelt Sykes,
Big Joe Turner and Muddy Waters but who has actually had the
privilege of seeing them perform. All those nights at Boston-area
clubs and college auditoriums in the '60s turned out not to be so
misspent after all.
</P>
<P>
   A generation of Turks has grown up hearing blues-influenced
musicians like Eric Clapton, Johnny Winter and the Blues Brothers.
I don't play music by any of them. My show concentrates on ``real
blues,'' which turns out to mean music that many Turks have never
heard before.
</P>
<P>
   When I first planned my show, I resolved that any artist I
featured would have to fit two categories: black and dead. I've
eased up on the second restriction and have happily featured the
likes of Otis Rush, Honeyboy Edwards and Billy Boy Arnold, not to
mention immortals like John Lee Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   But the only time I broke down and played white musicians was on
a special show dedicated to Robert Johnson; I interspersed his
originals with versions sung by John Hammond, Rory Block and other
gifted contemporary interpreters.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for this is not any kind of exclusionary elitism. My
mission is to broaden the knowledge and taste of my audience. I
want to let listeners know that Mick Jagger did not come up with
``Little Red Rooster'' and that ``Back Door Man'' was not a Jim
Morrison original. (Willie Dixon wrote them both, by the way.)
</P>
<P>
   I try to reach back into blues history and play songs that
reflect the rich variety of this great music. Usually I start with
some uptempo numbers by artists like Little Walter or Howlin' Wolf.
But then I like to dig deeper into my collection. Robert Pete
Williams, Son House, Sleepy John Estes, the Rev. Gary Davis and
Blind Boy Fuller are all regular guests. ``Eski blues en iyi
blues,'' I like to say. ``Old blues is the best blues.''
</P>
<P>
   I do limit myself somewhat. At home I love to listen to the very
raw early blues that have been rescued from ancient 78s, but I
don't want to risk turning my listeners off by pushing music that
is too esoteric.
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorite devices is the birthday tribute. I've got two
scheduled for June, honoring Skip James and Big Bill Broonzy. I've
devoted shows to Mississippi John Hurt, Sonny Boy Williamson, Leroy
Carr, Memphis Slim, Champion Jack Dupree and Sippie Wallace, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Sippie, I also make it a point to play the great
female voices of the blues and have produced several special
tributes to their work. Bessie Smith, Big Maybelle, Memphis Minnie,
Dinah Washington and Koko Taylor (still going strong) are all
repeat visitors to the show.
</P>
<P>
   My commentary is bilingual, and I always try to tell something
about the lives of artists whose music I play. I also explain
rudiments of blues history, working under the assumption that many
Turks like this music but don't know much about it.
</P>
<P>
   People sometimes tell me they love the music they hear on my
show and then ask, ``So what is blues anyway?'' To help orient
them, I often talk about the Southern roots of this music and how
it moved northward and went electric. Most of my listeners probably
don't know what Parchman Farm or Jim Crow means, or why so many
blues songs talk about leavin' home and ramblin' _ or how many
early blues singers had their roots in the Baptist Church. I try to
provide a little context for an audience that I think is eager to
learn.
</P>
<P>
   Another of my devices is to translate verses, so listeners who
don't understand English can share the many messages of the blues.
With help from my bilingual friend Deniz Aral, I've become probably
the first person to provide Turkish lines like ``Ben bir saatlik
bir kadinim, ve bir dakikalik bir adam benim icin iyi degil.''
Which is a rough translation of that great verse by Ida Cox: ``I'm
a one-hour mama, and no one-minute papa ain't the kind of man for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Turks and blues might seem an odd combination, but it ain't
necessarily so. The country's biggest brewery sponsors an annual
blues festival, and artists ranging from Son Seals to Lucky
Peterson draw big crowds. And of course the legendary
Turkish-American producer Ahmet Ertegun, longtime boss of Atlantic
Records, has played a great role in promoting blues around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   My own show could not exist without the emergence in 1995 of a
wonderful station in Istanbul called Acik Radyo, or Open Radio. It
was founded by a group of '60s veterans who wanted to help broaden
the cultural and political programming available to Turks.
</P>
<P>
   The station manager, Omer Madra, has made a great contribution
to his country by providing a forum for all kinds of music, ranging
from baroque to reggae. His own morning show mixes rock classics
with insightful and unorthodox commentary on national and world
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   My compensation, like that of all the announcers at Acik Radyo,
is limited to the fun of playing great music for a highly
appreciative audience. Some listeners tell me they get a kick out
of my mangled Turkish, but most just say they love the music.
</P>
<P>
   My sainted mother came to Istanbul for a visit recently, and
upon finding herself lost one day she stopped for directions at the
local Chamber of Commerce. She got to talking with the lady who
runs the place and told her: ``Maybe you've heard of my son,
Stephen Kinzer. He covers Turkey for The New York Times.''
</P>
<P>
   A flicker of recognition ran across the lady's face, and she
replied: ``Stephen Kinzer? Doesn't he have a blues show on the
radio?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
