<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2099 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENCRYPTION-0519-COX     05-18 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENCRYPTION-0519-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BATTLE LOOMS OVER ENCRYPTION POLICY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Deep tensions between the Clinton administration
and Congress over software encryption policy surfaced at a House
hearing Tuesday, setting the stage for a possible presidential veto
of pending legislation that would lift all software export
controls.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses from the Justice and Commerce departments and the
top-secret National Security Agency told a House subcommittee that
current blockage of software with strong encryption features should
remain in place to deter foreign crooks, drug lords, terrorists and
spies.
</P>
<P>
   But a parade of Republicans and Democrats on the House
International Economic Policy and Trade Subcommittee joined in
calling the administration, as Rep. Richard Burr, R-N.C., put it,
``an ostrich with its head in the lake.''
</P>
<P>
   Encryption is privacy enhancing technology than encodes computer
files and communications much like a combination lock secures a
filing cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   In assailing the administration's stance, Burr and his
colleagues raised the issue of individual privacy and the need to
spur Internet commerce. They stressed that domestic software firms
are falling behind in building strong encryption technology, for
lack of markets, even as American computer systems become
increasingly vulnerable to foreign penetration.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a ludicrous consequence of current policy, Amazon.com must
buy foreign encryption software to sell its wares'' abroad, Rep.
Bob Goodlatte, R. Va., said. He claimed the policy had caused ``a
significant erosion of U.S. dominance of the U.S. software
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislation to reverse the policy, co-sponsored by Goodlatte and
Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., has already attracted 255 supporters in
the 435-member House, including 110 Democrats. Their bill would
offer export relief to such software makers as Microsoft while
barring compulsory ``back doors'' in encryption products, including
those sold for use by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation would have likely passed in 1998 if not for
the implacable opposition of a lone, key figure, Rep. Benjamin
Gilman, R-N.Y., who chairs the full International Relations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman, who attended the subcommittee session, voiced concern
the pending bill ``would make strong encryption all the more
available to our adversaries and would only undermine international
efforts to modernize and improve multilateral export controls.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilman scheduled a closed-door intelligence briefing on the
issue for all House members for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who want to use rich encryption to do something illicit
ultimately have the wherewithal to do it now,'' noted Rep. Robert
Menendez of New Jersey, the ranking Democrat on the panel. ``I get
the sense we're trying to stop something that cannot be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, William Reinsch, Commerce undersecretary for export
administration, said: ``The issue for us is getting into a world
where everybody is using (unbreakable) encryption. Will it be a
world in which wiretaps will be useless?''
</P>
<P>
   While Reinsch conceded that foreigners could readily, if
illegally, buy powerful U.S. encryption software or, legally, buy
similar products designed abroad, he nevertheless argued for
keeping the controls in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never underestimate the stupidity of some of the people we
have to deal with,'' Reinsch said. ``...Just because we can't
succeed completely doesn't mean we should give up,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because somebody speeds through a school zone doesn't
mean you raise the speed limit,'' echoed Barbara McNamara, deputy
director of the National Security Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
