<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 1{ pages on the continuing crisis over
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ A look at what NATO officials now
believe are the goals of the Yugoslavian military: not only has two
months of bombing not broken the Serbs' will, there are indications
that a fundamental shift in strategy is under way. 1,600 words. By
Michael Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Brussels) _ There are new reports that Serbian
forces are digging up mass graves and reburying bodies in single
graves. Also, new figures from the U.S. war crimes envoy on
killings (5,000) and missing men (225,000, double the previous
estimate). By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton does not rule out
ground troops, but says that the air war needs more time. He also
says it's a ``mischaracterization'' to say the administration is
blocking the use of Apache helicopters. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ War fatigue is growing here as
casualties mount under the onslaught of NATO, encouraging a
circumspect political debate and also encouraging the splintered
opposition to plan for a postwar and _ possibly _ even a
post-Milosevic Yugoslavia. These stirrings remain very faint.
President Slobodan Milosevic's allies have been branding all
opposition leaders as ``fifth columnists'' and ``open traitors,''
keeping them from responding on state television or in the main
newspapers. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
