<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARAK-CLONED-CAMPAIGN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEND IN THE CLONES: THE IMPORTED BRAINS BEHIND BARAK  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This TIMELY 800-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW GRICE, LONDON  
 And MARY DEJEVSKY, WASHINGTON  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON AND WASHINGTON _ As Israel was adjusting Tuesday to Ehud
Barak's sweeping electoral triumph over Benjamin Netanyahu, it
emerged that close aides to Tony Blair and Bill Clinton had been
working closely with Barak's Labor Party and transforming it in the
way Blair modernized Britain's New Labor.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Gould, the British Prime Minister's opinion polling guru,
and Stan Greenberg, who does the same job for President Clinton,
have held monthly strategy meetings in Israel for the past two
years with Barak, the newly-elected Israeli prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Confidential documents seen by The Independent reveal the extent
of their work in helping the Israeli Labor Party back to power.
</P>
<P>
   Barak even came to London for a two-day brainstorming session on
how to remodel his image.
</P>
<P>
   The White House Tuesday hailed the election of Barak with
restrained delight but was closer to the election campaign than its
public neutrality suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Greenberg, advising Barak in his planning strategy,
conducting polls and framing advertising, were two other members of
the election team credited with helping Clinton to his first
presidential victory in 1992: James Carville and Robert Shrum.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of a new advance in the Middle East is
especially welcome in Washington, where Clinton is in sore need of
a foreign policy success following the diplomatic setbacks in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of his military service, the question of General
Barak's devotion to the security of Israel is not in question,''
Clinton told reporters Tuesday after a meeting with King Abdullah
of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The direct involvement of Blair and Clinton aides followed an
appeal for help by Daniel Levy, the Tel Aviv-based son of Lord
(Michael) Levy, a close friend and the tennis partner of Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Gould and Greenberg were the architects of the proposal that the
party change its name, even suggesting at one point that it be
called New Labor.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the Labor party kept its name but fought the
election under the One Israel banner, the name of the alliance it
formed with two smaller parties.
</P>
<P>
   How far the new model Labor party made more than a cosmetic
difference to the outcome of the election is doubted by some
Israeli analysts. Barak won, they believe, because so many of the
former prime minister's senior colleagues had been fired or
deserted and set up the Center Party to remove him.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign strategy amounted to keeping his mouth shut and
watching his opponent who presided over a rickety coalition,
self-destruct.
</P>
<P>
   But when they became involved in 1997, Gould and Greenberg
warned that the modernization of Labor was the most important and
difficult task facing the Barak campaign. They recommended the
``dramatic high risk'' strategy pursued by Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Their initial assessment of Labor's prospects was poor. Labor's
combination of ``elitism plus softness on the core security
issues'' was summed up as ``fatal.''
</P>
<P>
   A center-left party must do two things, they advised: ``It must
be the party of the people. This means the party of the new middle
class; the new majority; hard-working; tough-minded. It must win
the center: on security; on crime; on welfare it has to be tough,
not soft.''
</P>
<P>
   Gould and Greenberg warned that Labor was not considered to be
``the party of the people''; the party that could best resolve
social problems or unite the country. Neither was it the ``party of
security or religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gould and Greenberg described Barak's strengths as ``a powerful
and imposing presence; a manifest sense of destiny; the genesis of
a talented team and the innate weakness of Netanyahu, a poor prime
minister tainted by corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Last night Gould said most of the credit should go to Greenberg,
a partner in his London-based political consultancy. ``Stan did an
extraordinary job. He kept faith during a difficult project and got
an incredible result,'' said Gould.
</P>
<P>
   Carville meanwhile _ who was one of Clinton's most bullish
defenders during the Monica Lewinsky affair _ has said in the past
that he accepted the job with Barak in his capacity as a private
consultant and had not asked the White House for approval.
</P>
<P>
   However, he made no secret of the fact that he regularly briefed
Clinton on the progress of the campaign _ briefings that will
doubtless smooth the path of U.S.-Israeli cooperation now.
</P>
<P>
   Among American Jews _ several thousand of whom had taken charter
flights to Israel to cast their vote _ reactions to Barak's victory
reflected the polarization of opinion over Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Given the size of his victory, however, the majority were
expected to rally around Barak, reinforcing calls for peace and
increasing the pressure to establish a durable peace. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this TIMELY 800-word article, it must be purchased from
the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
