<HEADER>
A2123 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANDIDATE-COSTS-COX     05-18 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANDIDATE-COSTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judges debate suit claiming rich candidates have edge
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A panel of federal judges expressed concern Tuesday
over the merits of a novel legal challenge that claims Georgia's
election laws illegally favor wealthy candidates in state political
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, John White, a former state representative from
Albany, filed suit in federal court in Atlanta to force public
campaign financing in state elections.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was dismissed by U.S. District Judge Willis Hunt; on
Tuesday, a three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals heard arguments on the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The case filed by White, who is now a private consultant,
involves his 1996 campaign for the state Senate against Mark
Taylor, who is now lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Using $90,000 of his own money to finance his campaign, Taylor
outspent White $270,000 to $16,000 and outpolled him as well,
getting 58 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   White's lawsuit against the Secretary of State's office, joined
by the Georgia State Conference of NAACP Branches, claims Georgia's
electoral system creates a ``wealth primary'' that violates equal
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without access to wealth, one simply cannot stand a chance to
win an election in Georgia,'' White's attorney, Gregory Luke, told
the three-judge panel. ``The process is not meaningfully open. You
might as well use a jousting match to determine who wins elections
in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Alan Gold, noting that a federal appeals court in San
Francisco already has rejected a similar type of lawsuit,
questioned how the court could order the General Assembly to enact
laws that require public financing of elections. ``Isn't that
really a violation of the separation of powers?'' Gold asked.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Rosemary Barkett also challenged Luke's assertion that
prior rulings by the U.S. Supreme Court gives the appeals court
authority to rule in White's favor. ``Isn't that a stretch?''
Barkett asked.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Allen, a lawyer with the state Attorney General's
Office, admitted that the wealth of a candidate can play a role in
the outcome of an election. But so can the ethnic makeup of a
voting district, a candidate's gender and name recognition, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for White's attempts to force solutions to the problems
facing non-wealthy political candidates, ``maybe it's the right
thing to do,'' Allen said. ``It's a societal problem. But this is
for the Legislature,'' not the courts, to address, she told the
panel.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
