<HEADER>
A2133 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ART-2TAKES-NYT     05-18 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO PURSUE PEACE, BARAK MAY NEED ALLIANCE WITH OPPONENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) (rm) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In the morning after his euphoric victory rally,
Ehud Barak, the new prime minister of Israel, woke up to the
sobering task of cobbling together a coalition broad enough that he
can pursue peace without facing civil strife.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, the Labor Party leader, faced one immediate strategic
decision: whether to take into his government the ultra-Orthodox
Shas Party of Aryeh Deri, who was recently convicted on corruption
charges, or the defeated, demoralized Likud Party of former Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Both Deri and Netanyahu, tight allies, have stepped down as
their party's leaders _ Netanyahu on Monday night, after his
resounding defeat by Barak, and Deri Tuesday night, after his
party's triumphant success in the elections in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Either large opposition party would help the Labor leader make
territorial concessions more acceptable to the nationalists in
Israeli society. And both became more palatable partners without
their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, in his victory speech and at the Western Wall Tuesday,
held himself up as a potential healer for the deep divides in
Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a conciliator,'' said Daniel Ben-Simon, a writer for the
newspaper Haaretz. ``He hugs everyone. He's a man of so many
kisses.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he can tackle society, though, Barak must navigate the
minefields in a newly realigned parliament of 15 parties. The two
major parties, Likud and Labor, both shrank after an election in
which Barak's party did not achieve the resounding personal victory
that Barak scored over Netanyahu by going outside Israel's
traditional party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Labor and its closest allies have fewer seats in Parliament than
Netanyahu's Likud-led alliance, which had been the weakest
governing coalition in Israeli history. But Likud's alliance was
fractious and uneasy from the start, while the center-left
alliances are more natural and reliable.
</P>
<P>
   Mathematically, at least, Barak does not have to reach out to
his political opponents, Shas or Likud, who will surely want
concessions _ in the peace process, perhaps, or in the
secular-religious divide in Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
   Still, overnight, the political landscape here changed.
</P>
<P>
   The right-wing collapsed. The settlers' party dwindled. The
center, including the Russians, blossomed. The secularists formed a
new, large bloc. Standing opposite them, Shas mushroomed into a
major party, sucking away partisans of the Likud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night, we were a clerical, right-wing nation,'' said
Chemi Shalev, a political analyst for the Maariv newspaper.
``Today, we are social democrats and the knights of pluralism.''
</P>
<P>
   The political map in Israeli society used to be drawn around
attitudes toward peace. Those who supported territorial concessions
in exchange for peace were considered left, and those who opposed
them were right.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, as a consensus on peace grows, the battlegrounds
have become more varied. Some think the new Parliament divides into
secular and religious camps, the new frontlines in Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
   In that atmosphere, Israel's political analysts buzzed with
speculation Tuesday about what kind of unlikely political matches
would be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the first call will go to Ariel Sharon,'' the hardline
right-wing Foreign Minister, ``and I would not be surprised if he
will be Israel's next foreign minister, too,'' said Akiva Eldar, a
political columnist for Haaretz.
</P>
<P>
   As unlikely as it may seem to imagine the tough former general
in a center-left government, associates of Barak were wagering on
Sharon's appointment months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's One Israel Party, which includes the Labor Party and the
Gesher Party, which used to be aligned with Likud, won 27 seats in
the new parliament, far short of a 61-seat majority.
</P>
<P>
   Adding the seats of Barak's natural center-left allies, he could
form a majority government with one or more of the small Arab
parties. Because Barak courted and counted on the Arab vote, it is
possible he would bring them into his inner circle. But forming
alliances with Arab parties has been a polarizing decision for past
Labor leaders, and it is one that Barak, intent on unity, might
avoid.
</P>
<P>
   With the Arabs or even with the settlers' party, which has grown
more moderate, Barak could assemble a working coalition. But to
move the peace effort forward, to finalize agreements with the
Palestinians and the Syrians, he needs more than a simple majority.
He needs and wants a broad consensus.
</P>
<P>
   ``To push through a peace agreement with only a slight majority
is an impossibility in Israel,'' said Emanuel Guttman, a political
scientist from Hebrew University.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   It made it easier to contemplate relationships with Likud and
Shas after they lost their troubled leaders in the last two days.
Given that the vote was a resounding repudiation of Netanyahu, few
in Barak's party would have been eager to make a deal with his
Likud.
</P>
<P>
   Already, however, other Likudniks are jockeying to take over as
leader, with Meir Sheetrit, the former coalition whip for
Netanyahu, the first to throw his hat in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Barak's associates rejected the idea of joining hands
with Deri, who awaits sentencing on his bribery conviction. Running
a campaign based on Deri's assertion that he had been persecuted by
the justice system because he is Moroccan-born and religious, Shas
engineered an amazing victory in Monday's elections. It won 17
seats, an increase of 7, making it the third largest party, after
Likud, which fell to 19 with Monday's election losses and the
defection of Gesher to Barak's new party.
</P>
<P>
   Deri took it as a vindication, and stepped down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot continue in a national role,'' he said. ``I will not
serve in parliament.''
</P>
<P>
   With or without Deri, the leftist Meretz party would react
strongly to an alliance with Shas. And many of Barak's
constituents, who grew tired of what they saw as the ultra-Orthodox
stranglehold on Netanyahu's government, would be upset.
</P>
<P>
   Shas, while it supports the peace effort, also believes that the
Jewish homeland should be governed by Jewish law and not by a
secular legal system.
</P>
<P>
   Shas would co-exist uneasily with the Russian immigrant party of
Natan Sharansky. It did in Netanyahu's government. But bitter
tensions between Moroccan and Russian immigrants came to the
surface during the last few months as Yisrael Baaliyah, Sharansky's
party, campaigned to gain hold of the Interior Ministry, long run
by Shas.
</P>
<P>
   Sharanksy's party will undoubtedly join Barak's coalition. It
kept steady at seven seats in the new parliament, while a new
Russian immigrant party, Israel is Our Home, earned four, taking
many voters from Likud.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament is to be sworn in in three weeks, and Barak has 45
days to form a government.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Segev, who writes a column for Haaretz, warns against seeing
a political coalition as a healing agent for society.
</P>
<P>
   ``This or that coalition can change the atmosphere in
politics,'' he said. ``But the struggle over the basic values in
our society does not change that easily.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
