<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-Y2K-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K BILL STALLS IN SENATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bill aimed at limiting lawsuits from year 2000
computer breakdowns was stalled in the Senate on Tuesday, leaving
consumer groups who oppose it and high-tech companies who favor it
wondering whether the legislation is dead for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the bill failed to win enough support in a Senate
vote to continue debate on the measure. The measure is similar to
legislation passed last week by the House that would impose a
90-day waiting period before lawsuits could be filed by consumers
or businesses claiming damages based on so-called Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., finally pulled it
from consideration when Democrats demanded more time to debate
unrelated gun-control amendments to a juvenile justice bill.
</P>
<P>
   An angry Lott, who had hoped to force a vote on the Y2K measure
in the afternoon, later said that the current bill may not be
brought up again.
</P>
<P>
   If the bill dies, he said, it would be ``a devastating blow for
business and industry in this country,'' which could face lawsuits
stemming from problems if computers and other technological
gadgetry fail to register the date correctly when the year 2000
arrives. Unless corrected, computer chip-reliant equipment could
read the date as 1900 because older technology is designed to
recognize only the last two digits of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he would not attempt to bring the bill up again unless
Democrats demonstrate to him that they ``care about this Y2K
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Action on the Y2K legislation has twice been delayed in the
Senate by Democrats opposed to the measure who want to see it
strengthened to protect consumers. Last month, the bill had to be
put aside when several Democrats tried to attach an increase in the
minimum wage to it.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to move the legislation to a vote, Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., its chief sponsor, has agreed to a number of
amendments that would boost consumer protections and has dropped
some of the limits the bill places on punitive damages that could
be sought in Y2K-related lawsuits. He also has dropped a provision
designed to protect individual company directors and officers from
damages.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the changes have not been enough to satisfy consumer
groups and trial lawyers who don't want to see any waiting period
or limits on damages enacted. They also complain, as do lawmakers
who oppose the legislation, that it does little to encourage
businesses to fix potential Y2K-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has also gone on record against the bill, saying
it would limit the rights of consumers and businesses who might
have legitimate claims of damage. The administration has warned in
a letter to Republican leaders that Clinton could end up vetoing
the bill if it passes the Senate because of those concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is backed primarily by California's Silicon
Valley industries and other computer-related companies nationwide
that could be sued if technology they designed fails to work
properly after Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and other lawmakers who support placing limits on the
lawsuits fear that legal proceedings stemming from problems could
far exceed the $22 billion in claims that have been filed since
Congress passed the Superfund bill 20 years ago that forced
companies to begin cleaning up toxic waste and other dump sites
considered an environmental hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Given the fact that so many businesses _ ranging from health
care providers to small ``mom-and-pop'' companies _ have failed to
take corrective action to avert Y2K problems, the sponsors of the
legislation say that damages from lawsuits could run as high as $1
trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and Senate versions of the bill would initiate a
so-called 90-day cooling off period before suits can actually be
filed. The delay is designed to give computer companies and
software developers time to fix any problems that have occurred.
The House bill would also impose restrictions on class-action
lawsuits and limit punitive damages to about $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this bill would reward the people who created the
problem and reward the people who don't take any corrective action
to prevent it,'' said Carlton Carl, a spokesman for the American
Association of Trial Lawyers, which is opposed to the Y2K
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
