<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2137 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ARABS-NYT &LR;      05-18 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ARABS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARABS CELEBRATE BARAK VICTORY BUT EXPECT LITTLE CHANGE IN ISRAELI
POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL    
 c .1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Arabs loved to hate Benjamin Netanyahu, so his
trouncing in Israel's elections was welcomed by many in the Arab
world Tuesday with a kind of triumphalism _ a sense that the
Israelis had finally seen the light.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arabs feel a moral victory,'' said Osama al-Ghazali,
editor of International Politics, an Egyptian magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Netanyahu's policies were futile,'' said Esmat Abdel-Maguid,
secretary general of the Arab League.
</P>
<P>
   And a columnist in Al Ahram, Egypt's leading newspaper, wrote,
``Netanyahu has gone to the place of no return, where he belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the gloating, however, are deep uncertainties about just
what Ehud Barak's victory might mean. Amr Moussa, Egypt's foreign
minister, predicted a ``reactivation'' of the quest for a broader
Middle East peace, but others warned against over-optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak will try to revive peace in all tracks, but no miracles
can be expected,'' said Tahseen Bashir, a former top aide to
President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt. ``He will create a new spirit of
peace, and Israel will get closer to the Arab world, but nothing
more.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the Arabs may one day miss Netanyahu. His
policies, outrageous to most Arabs, meant that whatever went wrong
in Arab-Israeli relations could usually be portrayed as his fault.
Barak is seen by most Arabs as a friendlier face, but he has
signaled a preference for negotiation over confrontation, and that
might make dealing with him a more formidable job.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese newspaper Al Safir went so far as to to warn that
Israel had become ``more dangerous'' under Barak, more of a
centrist, than it has been under Netanyahu, who was seen as
promoting a divisive brand of extremism. ``The flock is back in
formation,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, Arab scholars and other experts said Barak could
put Syria in an awkward position if he exploits the Israeli
weariness with the two-decade-old occupation of southern Lebanon,
which has claimed hundreds of Israeli lives. Barak has pledged to
withdraw all Israeli troops from southern Lebanon by June of next
year, a move that would be welcomed by most Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Tactically, such a move could carry the added advantage of
causing headaches for Syria, which maintains thousands of soldiers
in Lebanon and has used southern Lebanon as a pressure point
against Israel for years. If Israel were to withdraw, there would
be international pressure on Syria to guarantee security along the
Israeli-Lebanese border.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has also signaled that he intends to resume peace talks
with Syria over the Golan Heights, which Israel captured from Syria
in the 1967 Middle East war. There were no talks between the two
nations during Netanyahu's three-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu had insisted that the talks begin anew, a stance that
the Syrians rejected. One approach might be to restart the talks
with Syria where they left off in early 1996, under Shimon Peres,
the last Labor prime minister. By agreeing to a resumption, Barak
would address that complaint, but he would also quickly present
President Hafez Assad of Syria with difficult decisions.
</P>
<P>
   One would be whether to accept the kind of peace offer that
Israel put on the table three years ago _ one that by most accounts
fell just short of Assad's demand for Israel's total withdrawal
from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   The other decision, perhaps just as hard, would be on whether
Syria could go forward with an agreement on the Golan Heights
before Israel and the Palestinians reach their final accord. To do
so might be tempting, but it would be the same kind of separate
peace that Syria condemned when agreements were reached by Egypt,
Jordan and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian government is clearly curious about what Barak
intends. ``He must play his peace cards swiftly, if he has any, and
make his intentions clear,'' the official Syria Times said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, the Syrians seem apprehensive. ``The
peace process will remain suspended if Netanyahu wins,'' the
newspaper Tishreen said on Monday, ``and it will also remain
suspended if Barak does not put an end to the Israel intransigence,
especially about complete withdrawal from the Golan Heights, south
Lebanon, the West Bank and Jerusalem.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Across the region Tuesday, Arab newspapers generally adopted an
attitude of skepticism. ``Netanyahu's defeat should not make us
over-optimistic, as Barak has not presented in his speeches and
statements anything different from Netanyahu,'' was one typical
comment, in an editorial in the Qatar newspaper Asharq.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the intensity of ill will felt by many Arabs toward
Netanyahu meant that Tuesday was a day of relief. In the months
before Netanyahu won his upset victory over Peres, the Middle East
had seemed to many people to be on the brink of a broader peace. In
the years since, it has been mired in stalemate and frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see the tears of defeat in his eyes,'' Ragah
Mohammed, 26, an Egyptian translator, said of Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   And Zahi Hawass, one of Egypt's top archeological officials,
said, ``Last night, I slept deeply for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Egypt and other Arab countries had no preference
about who should win the election. But the Middle East is a region
badly in need of stability and cooperation, and it was clear that
most Arab officials saw Barak as the candidate more likely to
promote both.
</P>
<P>
   As the election results were made official Tuesday, some Arab
officials spoke with fresh candor. ``There are positive signs that
Barak will bring peace,'' said Abdel-Meguid, the top Arab League
official.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in Egypt, the first Arab nation to make peace with Israel
but where many people have never fully accepted the accord,
bitterness could also be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Jews are the same, like Pepsi and Coca-Cola _ not
really very different,'' said Souad Hassouna, 60, a retired
teacher. Still, Mrs. Hassouna added, Barak might be ``a little more
tolerant'' than his defeated rival.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
