<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-N     05-18 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS WELCOME NETANYAHU'S DEFEAT BUT ARE WARY ON BARAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank _ Palestinians from the senior leadership to
the streets of Ramallah on Tuesday welcomed the vote that ousted
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu but stopped well short of
embracing his successor, Ehud Barak, who is viewed nervously as a
hawk in dove's clothing.
</P>
<P>
   From his office in Gaza City, Palestinian National Authority
leader Yasser Arafat telephoned Barak on Tuesday afternoon to
congratulate him on his victory and to get peace talks ``back on
the right track,'' said a spokesman in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a closed-door session of cabinet ministers and
Palestine Liberation Organization leaders, Arafat warned that Barak
``could give us a hard time'' in peace negotiations, participants
said. Arafat stressed that Barak ``is one of Labor's hawks,'' said
Zakaria Alagha, who attended as a member of the PLO executive
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was interrupted by an unexpected phone call from
President Clinton, who told Arafat that U.S. envoys will be
arriving soon to revive the stalled land-for-security pact,
Palestinian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A Palestinian spokesman said Arafat asked Clinton to move
quickly ``to achieve a just, permanent, and comprehensive peace in
the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Alagha said later: ``Look, there was happiness in the room. We
were comforted by the defeat of Netanyahu, who was an obstacle to
the peace process. But we should be careful about Barak, especially
about his statements after the elections.''
</P>
<P>
   While Israelis listening to Barak's victory speeches Monday
night were struck by his emotional insistence on the strategic
benefits of peace, Palestinians interviewed Tuesday noted again and
again his vow not to stray outside ``four red lines'' in final
status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Barak reiterated the four points that were the longstanding
Labor Party policy of the late Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, saying
that Israel would not return to its pre-1967 borders, that it would
not relinquish sovereignty over ``unified'' Jerusalem or major
Jewish settlements in the West Bank, and that it would not permit
any modern military force to be physically located between Israel
and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sentiment on the West Bank was that with new Israeli
leadership, there is some hope of new progress toward a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to defeat Netanyahu, because he stopped the peace
process for three years,'' said Fadel-Ahmad Tahboub, a member of
the Palestinian National Council, as he strolled along a crowded
sidewalk here Tuesday afternoon. ``Maybe it won't be so easy to
deal with Barak, but I doubt it would be worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali Laham, a staff aide at Orient House, the PLO's unofficial
Jerusalem headquarters, agreed. ``Netanyahu is impossible, Barak is
difficult,'' he said. ``That's the difference between them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the storefront coffee houses and falafel stands of Palestine
Avenue in Ramallah, many people professed to see little difference
between the Israeli candidates on the issues that matter to them:
independence, refugees' rights and the future of Jerusalem. And
nobody voluntarily seconded Arafat's public expressions of
``respect'' for the Israeli democratic process.
</P>
<P>
   Yet almost all acknowledged they had intently followed Monday
evening's election results, hoping for the defeat of Netanyahu,
whom they had come to view as an ideological enemy. And most
demonstrated an impressive intimacy with Israeli parliamentary
arithmetic, debating the various permutations of right, left, and
center that could give Barak a governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, they said that had Netanyahu been
re-elected, they would have interpreted it as a final rejection of
the possibility of peace by the broad Israeli public. That did not
happen, and many people in Ramallah said they were convinced that
most Israelis do want a settlement that would cede West Bank land
in exchange for Palestinian actions to insure Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul Halim Abu Sharifeh is a 63-year-old Ramallah resident
whose family hurriedly fled their Mediterranean seaside home in
what is now Israel during the 1948 war of independence, never to
return. He watched Israeli election coverage until well past
midnight, he said, because he believed that Barak's character _
though not his policies _ offered a slight hope for reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Netanyahu's animosity toward Palestinians was obvious to the
whole world,'' he said. ``This man at least is ambiguous.''
</P>
<P>
   In annexed East Jerusalem, a hundred thousand Arabs of voting
age were eligible to vote in the election but refused to
participate because of a longstanding position that Jerusalem is
not part of Israel. The talk there Tuesday was of the resumption of
Jewish home-building projects in old Palestinian neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious that it is because of the elections,'' said a
woman in traditional Muslim dress, who would identify herself only
as Tashrid. ``They want to prove that the power is still in their
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was an unusually peaceful day at Orient House, the
century-old manor that Netanyahu had threatened to close because of
allegedly illegal Palestinian diplomatic activities there.
</P>
<P>
   Just a week ago, Orient House was packed with Palestinian
leaders steeled for a possibly violent confrontation with Israeli
police, who it was feared would be ordered onto the premises by the
government in a pre-election strike. A last-minute court injunction
averted an immediate crisis, and Palestinian officials are waiting
for a ruling on the closure order next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Faisal Husseini, who runs Orient House and has been charged with
the Jerusalem brief in negotiations for the Palestinians, said
Tuesday that he worries that the Netanyahu government may still try
to shut it down before Barak takes office in June. But he suggested
that if legal appeals continued until then, a compromise could be
found.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would not be surprised to find out that Barak is a difficult
negotiator,'' Husseini said in an interview. ``But Netanyahu was
not trying to negotiate. He was trying to dictate.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the seemingly intractable issue of competing claims on
Jerusalem can be settled, Husseini insisted. ``The option of going
forward quickly is there,'' he said. ``We have the support of the
Israeli people, of the Palestinian people, of the United States,
and of the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone here in Ramallah is convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not prefer Netanyahu or Barak, because I don't believe in
peace negotiations,'' said Ayed Shadid, an engineering student, as
he sipped coffee and puffed on a water pipe in a Palestine Avenue
cafe. ``I think we have a long armed struggle ahead of us. But we
need reason to hope, and we can hope that Barak will do
something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
