r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BURCH-COLUMN-TEX     05-18 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BURCH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIEVING CRENSHAW TURNS TO HIS FRIENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
Ben Crenshaw began his MasterCard Colonial preparations yesterday
with a heartfelt hug from Corey Pavin.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he proceeded to the driving range to strike his first golf
shots in a month, Crenshaw collected handshakes and nods from
countless competitors and fans. Like Pavin, all wanted to express
condolences after the death of Crenshaw's father, who lost a long
battle with thyroid cancer last week.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Crenshaw, 85, was buried Thursday in Austin.
Understandably, Crenshaw's emotions still bubble to the surface
when he thinks of the man who introduced him to golf, as well as
longtime mentor Harvey Penick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have been guided by two better people,'' Crenshaw
said, his voice cracking. ``Harvey was like a father figure to
everybody. He was a big influence in my life. But my dad was even
more so.''
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who have walked a mile in Crenshaw's golf spikes
understand the challenge he faces this week, as he attempts to
rejoin the work-a-day world after saying goodbye to a parent.
</P>
<P>
   It's never easy. Reminders are everywhere. The healing process
takes time, but it can be pushed along by encouraging words from
friends.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason why Crenshaw chose to play in his 29th
consecutive Colonial, an event he has won twice at a course that
features galleries filled with familiar faces. To him, it seemed a
comfortable and logical place to rejoin the PGA Tour wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this week had been a different event, I probably would be
skipping it. Absolutely,'' Crenshaw said. ``But the feeling of this
tournament is totally unique. I know a lot of people here, and the
folks have always been so friendly to me. You don't forget those
type of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very comfortable, relaxed place for me to come back to.
That's a nice tonic, right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Crenshaw will be in the thoughts and prayers
of fans and foes this week. As one of the game's classiest
ambassadors, he deserves that.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing that could happen this week would be sweeter, or more
poignant, than a final round with Crenshaw, 47, in the hunt for his
third plaid jacket. But don't expect a repeat of his 1995 Masters
triumph, which Crenshaw won four days after serving as a pallbearer
at Penick's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw hasn't survived a cut this season in six appearances at
PGA Tour events. Instead, he has been banking something far more
precious than paychecks: memories of quality time spent with his
father, his mother and his siblings, Charlie and Bonnie, during the
past month.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother and sister and I spent all the time we could with
Dad, right up to the end. For that, I'm thankful,'' said Crenshaw,
whose most recent competitive event was the Masters (April 8-11).
``Golf hasn't been much of a priority lately. It's been a long way
from my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Crenshaw headed to the driving range and swung a
club for the first time since leaving Augusta, Ga. He knows this
week will be challenging, especially from an emotional standpoint.
He welcomes your good wishes, even if you stop him between shots in
today's pro-am.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a nice thing,'' Crenshaw said. ``It's wonderful if
people want to say something. It's actually helpful and it means a
lot. Believe me, it means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Crenshaw's voice wavered. Always one to wear his
emotions on his sleeve, he reflected on the difficulty of
maintaining his composure during competitive rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just take that as it comes this week. Whatever happens,
happens,'' Crenshaw said. ``I'd like to play well. But mostly, it's
just nice to be back out here with friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, Ben Crenshaw, you'll find plenty of friends
everywhere you turn this week at the MasterCard Colonial.
SPOTLIGHT ON ... Colonial to be Watson's final regular PGA event
Tom Watson, 49, said yesterday he plans for Colonial to be his
final career appearance at a non-major on the PGA Tour. Watson said
his remaining summer schedule will include only the U.S. Open and
British Open. He would add the PGA Championship, Watson said, if
given an exemption.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, said the defending Colonial champ, his summer
will be dedicated to vacation time and preparing himself for the
Senior PGA Tour. Watson turns 50 on Sept. 4, making him eligible to
make his Senior PGA Tour debut at the Comfort Classic (Sept. 10-12)
in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to sit back, take a deep breath and get into the best
mental and physical shape I can get in to come out fast on the
Senior Tour,'' Watson said. ``At this point, that means this will
be the last regular event I'll play before the Senior Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Watson said he became ``sentimental'' while
playing last week in his final GTE Byron Nelson Classic, an event
he won four times, and expects similar feelings this week at
Colonial.
CHIP SHOTS Persistent Pate Steve Pate could be forgiven if he is
starting to feel snakebit on Sunday afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   He has won more money than any nonwinner of the PGA Tour this
season ($1,334,637). But his near-victories have been
unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   Pate lost to Loren Roberts in last week's playoff at the GTE
Byron Nelson Classic after both men established a tournament
scoring record (18-under 262). In January, Pate shot a closing 66
at the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic, but lost by a stroke to David
Duval, who finished with a 59, tying the lowest score in tour
history.
</P>
<P>
   Pate, 37, is philosophic about his close finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you hang around the lead long enough, something good is
going to happen and you'll get a win,'' said Pate, who has finished
fourth or better in four events this season. ``If you can beat
everyone but one guy by seven strokes, eventually something will go
your way. I can't control what Loren did or what Duval did. I just
need to keep plugging away and trust that my time will come.''
Elkington arrives Steve Elkington, who withdrew from last year's
Colonial because of a bout with viral meningitis, arrived yesterday
and practiced on the course. Elkington, who had to withdraw May 1
from the Houston Open because of a meningitis-related relapse,
declined a request to visit the interview room yesterday. He
relayed word through PGA Tour officials that he was feeling fine
and is looking forward to competing at a tour event for the first
time in three weeks. No shutout here Alan Bratton, one of three
Fort Worth residents in the Colonial field, said he is confident
local pros will fare better than at the GTE Byron Nelson Classic.
In Irving, Tarrant County residents were 0-for-7 in surviving the
weekend cut.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the task falls to Bratton, Mark Brooks and Clark
Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the Fort Worth guys can do a little better this
week,'' Bratton said. ``Maybe we were just saving it for the home
crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Bratton, a tour rookie, is making his Colonial debut. Brooks is
10-of-15 in surviving Colonial cuts. Dennis is seven-of-eight.
INSIDE THE NUMBERS Sizing up the field Although glamour boys David
Duval and Tiger Woods are elsewhere this week, the Colonial field
stacks up favorably with predecessors of recent vintage. Below is a
look at the number of top-50 players from the season money list who
have competed in the past five Colonials: Season Top 50 1999 36
1998 35 1997 36 1996 37 1995 42
nn
</P>
