<HEADER>
A2149 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUGS-SAMPLES-1000(2T     05-18 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-SAMPLES-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHARMACEUTICAL FREEBIES AREN'T WHAT THEY USED TO BE ... AND THAT'S
GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I bagged nine ballpoint pens, five sticky-note pads, a name tag
for a stethoscope and an ``automatic printer'' that will stamp a
prescription for Viagra an estimated 2,000 times before it runs out
of ink.
</P>
<P>
   I also stuffed my sack with lots of candy, Combos cheese-filled
pretzels and samples of Aleve, Advil, Bayer and the new Pediatric
Advil Drops, all at this month's big meeting of the Texas Medical
Association in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   It's a far cry from the ``bad ol', good ol' days,'' when drug
companies tried to influence doctors with everything from free
tickets to Dallas Cowboys games to ``frequent flier'' awards,
whereby surgeons could earn points toward, say, a ski vacation each
time they implanted a particular heart valve.
</P>
<P>
   Since they became legal two years ago, TV and radio commercials
have taken a big bite out of advertising budgets, but
pharmaceutical companies still spend most of their promotional
funds _ $2.5 billion last year _ marketing directly to doctors.
</P>
<P>
   But the distribution of drug samples is now regulated by both
the Food and Drug Administration and the ethics policies of
professional medical organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major thing is the drug companies can't give anything that
would amount to more than about $100 as a gift,'' says Dr. Bob
Lanier, a Fort Worth allergist and president-elect of the Tarrant
County Medical Society. ``They can send doctors all over the world
to meetings as consultants within certain rules, such as you make a
presentation or spend a certain amount of time answering questions,
but any sort of gifting can't be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trips don't influence us in private practice,'' Lanier says.
``Does any doctor really want to leave an office where the overhead
goes on day after day (estimated at about $3,000 per day for most
doctors' offices) for an honorarium of $500 and a free trip? What
sense does that make?
</P>
<P>
   ``Payback doesn't happen, not often anyway, not anymore,'' he
says. ``You may get a lot of pens and pencils and note pads, but
that's not going to buy loyalty, and drug companies know that.''
</P>
<P>
   However, sample drugs and ``detail men,'' the drug company
representatives who come bearing the samples, can be a valuable
asset to physicians and their patients, Lanier and other medical
professionals say.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the appropriate information is provided to safely
utilize the medicine, the practice of doctors distributing free
drug samples is not offensive and can be to the patient's benefit,
in several ways,'' says Ed Eason, pharmacist at Cook Children's
Medical Center in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   It may be difficult for a parent with a small child to wait at a
pharmacy for the prescription to be filled, or the pharmacy might
be closed, Eason says.
</P>
<P>
   Free samples also are advantageous from a cost standpoint, he
notes. In some cases, providing free samples is the only way a
child is going to get the medication he needs.
</P>
<P>
   A pediatrician's patients are generally the poorest of the
population. Drug samples can be a godsend for a single mom who has
several sick kids at once, or a young working family without health
insurance, Lanier points out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you need to get a patient started on something right away,
and you look up in your sample closet and see a medicine that will
help the patient's problem, that does influence you _ not from the
standpoint of making money or making the drug company happy, but
being able to help your patient immediately,'' Lanier says. ``It's
human nature to want to help, and you depend in part on your drug
reps to be able to do that. People don't realize how expensive some
of the good, new drugs are.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of drugs approved for the same things _ maybe
four anti-hypertensive drugs or three antihistamines that all work
about the same and have the same side effects, Lanier says. In many
cases, deciding which one to use may come down to, do you have a
sample the patient can try?
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors don't have a lot of experience with some of the new
approved drugs, and often offer samples to see how patients like
them,'' says Lanier. ``Until there is some experience with a drug,
you are a little loathe to try it. You write a 'script for it, and
your patient calls you the next day and says, `This stuff tastes
like hell and makes me sleepy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Drug representatives are a primary source of information for
doctors in this country. They know all the details of how to best
use their products _ that's ``detailing'' _ and often are the first
to report to physicians on problems with the competition.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``They are an incredible resource in a global sense _ not any
one alone, but taken together as a group,'' says Lanier. ``If there
is a negative report published in one of the journals or in the
popular press about a competitor, a detail man is in your office
the next week telling you all about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Academia and the FDA don't like pharmaceutical reps. They
think they give a biased viewpoint _ which they do _ but if you
have time to listen to several of them, you see the pros and cons
of everything. Used correctly, doctors in the field get an
incredible amount of drug information from them.''
</P>
<P>
   At the recent TMA convention, several small-town physicians
asked drug reps to come by their offices with the latest
information and samples.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need them to help keep us up to date on the newest drugs
and provide samples we can give out, particularly to some of our
elderly patients who do not have the money or insurance to cover
new drugs like Viagra,'' said Dr. Brian Kingston, a family practice
physician from Eldorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drug reps can be very helpful. The trick is getting them into
small towns,'' Kingston said.
</P>
<P>
   Drug representatives hosted booths and answered lots of
questions about their products, while handing out goody bags and
gadgets, paper tablets and package inserts, research results and
promotional materials.
</P>
<P>
   The Cheddar cheese-filled Combos seemed a particularly clever
way to promote Amaryl, a new combination therapy for type 2
diabetes. The drug company reps simply attached a small sticker,
advertising their own combo, on the individual snack packages.
</P>
<P>
   I was sorry I missed out on one of the 300 tiny kits used to
repair eyeglasses, stamped with the name, ``Integrated Pathology
Services.'' The detail man representing the lab said visitors were
taking them by the handfuls the first two hours his booth was open.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Policies on drug samples
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Food and Drug Administration: The Prescription Drug and
Marketing Act permits a manufacturer or distributor to distribute
samples to a licensed practitioner or pharmacy of a health care
center by mail, common carrier or other means (marketing
representatives) upon written request.
</P>
<P>
   Certain drug sample records must be maintained by manufacturers.
Manufacturers and distributors must maintain drug samples in a
manner that will prevent their contamination, deterioration or
adulteration.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Pharmacy Association: Says executive director Paul Davis:
``We have a long-standing historical policy of opposing the
dispensing of sample drugs. For a long time we opposed the practice
because it was unregulated. Drugs were sent to salesmen who kept
them in the back seats or trunks of their cars with the sun beating
down 180 degrees, but more and more physicians are requesting drugs
directly from the pharmaceutical company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a problem with physicians providing samples as a
starter dose or to make sure someone is not allergic. We have a
problem with doctors routinely dispensing drugs, but we have a good
state law that prohibits doctors from for-profit dispensing.''
</P>
<P>
   American Medical Association: Continues to support the practice
of physicians providing drug samples to selected patients at no
charge, according to a policy last revised in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA's policy covering ``Gifts to Physicians from Industry,''
updated in June 1996, warns that ``there has been growing concern
about certain gifts'' and says that gifts accepted by physicians
should primarily entail a benefit to patients and should not be of
substantial value.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts of minimal value are permissible as long as they are
related to a physician's work, such as pens and note pads.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Medical Association: Pharmaceutical samples must be
provided to the physician without cost from the manufacturer and
delivered at no cost either directly or indirectly to the patient.
They must be prepackaged by the manufacturer and not repackaged.
They must be marked as samples or recorded in records indicating
they are samples, which records shall be accessible as provided
under state and federal law.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on medical issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
