<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-WOOLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOOLEY FINDS OSTEOPATH HAS JUST THE RIGHT MAGIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ Ah, nothing like a relaxing day off in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Sabres defenseman Jason Woolley arose at the crack of dawn
Monday, plenty of time to play 18 and grab a leisurely lunch at the
club. Except he had other priorities.
</P>
<P>
   His groin, injured against the Bruins in the next-to-last
regular-season game, had ``seized up,'' as he put it, during the
second period Sunday and forced him to miss the rest of Buffalo's
5-3 loss at Boston in Game 5 of the Eastern Conference semifinals.
Not wanting to be a spectator in Game 6, Woolley sought treatment.
But his idea of medical attention didn't involve a stop in the
trainer's room at Marine Midland Arena or a drive to the
neighborhood professional building.
</P>
<P>
   Woolley caught a 6:30 a.m. flight to Detroit, then drove to East
Lansing to visit the doctor in whom he has placed implicit faith
since his college days at Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a torn abdominal muscle seven years ago,'' said Woolley.
``My career was in jeopardy. He fixed it. I've been seeing him for
years.''
</P>
<P>
   And who might this medical marvel be?
</P>
<P>
   ``Last name Brumm,'' said Woolley. ``First name Lynn. Middle
name Magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, this groin guru was just the doctor Woolley
ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked his magic,'' said the defenseman, ``and it loosened
up.''
</P>
<P>
   That was no surprise to the patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's unbelievable,'' said Woolley. ``He's a semiretired
osteopath who still treats Michigan State players. I told him I
won't allow him to retire until I retire.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't a career-threatening problem, but it was bothersome
nonetheless. For the past month, Woolley inadvertently had been
favoring one groin over the other until he finally could take no
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a pulled muscle or anything,'' he said. ``It was a
cartilage out of alignment, like it was steering off the road a
little.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to play through pretty much everything at this time
of year, but there are some injuries that limit you to not being
there. You've got guys who are healthy scratches and are itching to
play, and it's selfish if you're hurt to put yourself in when you
can't really contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   That was no longer an issue after Brumm's ministrations, and the
rejuvenated Woolley headed to the Detroit airport for an
early-evening return to Buffalo and a good night's rest.
</P>
<P>
   Or so he'd planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nightmare,'' he said. ``I got there at 7 and didn't
get in (to Buffalo) until 11:30.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he was continually delayed and frustrated by
airport snags that turned his original itinerary into a travel
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running through there in sandals,'' said Woolley. ``I
had to test the groin a lot earlier than I wanted.'
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it was worth the aggravation. Woolley was at Marine
Midland Tuesday morning, when he joined a handful of teammates for
an optional skate and reported afterward, ``I feel real good. I
don't feel there's any problem now.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was just the elixir the Sabres had been hoping for. Coach
Lindy Ruff gladly included Woolley in his lineup, meaning the
Sabres had the indispensable quarterback of their power play back.
</P>
<P>
   Now if only Dr. Lynn ``Magic'' Brumm made house calls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
