<SLUG> BC-ATWOOD-RESIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP US REFUGEE OFFICIAL TO RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The top US official for managing refugee issues in
the Balkans, who had been nominated to be ambassador to Brazil,
says he is leaving government because of his treatment at the hands
of Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Jesse A. Helms.
</P>
<P>
   J. Brian Atwood, who has spent 30 years in a variety of
Democratic Party and foreign affairs posts, said he has asked the
president to withdraw the ambassadorial nomination because he is
convinced Helms, a North Carolina Republican, would block it
indefinitely in retribution for a political clash between the men
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest in a chain of prominent ambassadorial
nominations to be nixed by Helms, including the nomination of
William Weld to be ambassador to Mexico and that of Robert Pastor
to be the emissary to Panama. The position of chief US delegate to
the United Nations has been vacant throughout the Kosovo crisis
largely because Helms has blocked the nomination of Richard C.
Holbrooke to that post.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said 22 ambassador-level nominations are
pending before the committee. About half of the nominees have not
been given preliminary hearings.
</P>
<P>
   James Foley, a State Department spokesman, refused to comment on
Helms's hobbling of the president's ambassadorial nominees. He said
Secretary of State Albright ``has an excellent relationship with
Senator Helms that's really been one of the hallmarks of her
tenure. . . . She likes and respects the senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms's office referred inquiries to the foreign relations
committee staff, which did not respond.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood, who is 56, said Tuesday that Helms's animus ``clearly
goes back'' to his role in the Clinton administration's successful
effort to defeat a Helms scheme to merge the US Agency for
International Development, the US Information Agency, and the Arms
Control and Disarmament Agency into the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody has to do something about this. It just isn't the
right way to do business,'' said Atwood, who has been administrator
of AID since May 1993. ``I was defending the administration
position. I don't think I violated any of the standards of debate
in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   However, his assertion at the time that it was not up to the
legislative branch to restructure the foreign affairs agencies of
the government, and his statement to senators that ``we shouldn't
accept a plan written by Senator Helms on the back of an envelope''
apparently touched a nerve.
</P>
<P>
   Emissaries dispatched to feel Helms out on the nomination in
recent weeks returned with word that the senator remembered, and
resented, the comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a couple good sources ask him would this just be''
extracting ``a pound of flesh, making me suffer, then letting it
pass, or would it be a William Weld'' _ with the suffering followed
by rejection _ ``and they came back and said `William Weld,' ''
Atwood said. ``I just decided I didn't want to end up the way Weld
did. . . . You have to know the ways of the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources said a complicating factor was that, before the problem
with Helms became apparent, the president designated J. Brady
Anderson, an old associate who was special assistant to Clinton
when the president was governor of Arkansas, to succeed Atwood. The
nomination has not been announced publicly, but is widely known
within the administration, and Anderson already has completed much
of the intense screening given to nominees whose appointments
require senate confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood said he would continue ``for a brief time'' as
administrator of AID and as chairman of the president's Council for
Humanitarian Relief for Kosovo, but ``didn't want people to think
I'd be around through the end of the administration.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Boston University football star said he had no plans
what he will do when he steps out of those jobs ``but I've always
wanted to go back to Wareham (Mass., his hometown).''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think maybe I could be a foreman on the line where people
check the cranberries,'' he joked. ``I honestly would love to come
back to Massachusetts in some capacity. I've done well in
Washington, but it is not home.''
</P>
<P>
   More likely, he could wind up on the foreign policy staff in the
presidential campaign of Vice President Al Gore. He is close to
Gore and Gore's foreign policy adviser, Leon Furth, and while he
said he has not talked with them, ``if I were not in government I'd
want to do what I could to help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2160 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-COX     05-18 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth investigates expansion of reach to include Southeast
U.S.
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To boldly go, where no phone company has gone before.
</P>
<P>
   At least, not exactly. BellSouth has been talking with satellite
companies in the hope of expanding its television service from a
handful of cities to the entire Southeast. Other phone providers
have partnerships with satellite companies, but BellSouth would
sell its own Americast service via satellite delivery. And by using
satellites, BellSouth's service could also seek out new customers,
who live behind trees and hills in homes where signals from
earthboundantennas cannot reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just a theory,'' said Phil Jacobs, president of
BellSouth Georgia. ``We are seriously considering alternative
distribution methods for our Americast programming and this appears
to be a realistic alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based BellSouth has kept the possibility of a satellite
strategy secret, and negotiations might still fall through. But if
BellSouth does make a deal, it would be buying the capacity to
blanket the southeast _ or even the rest of the United States _
with signals. The move would be both dramatic defense and audacious
offense. BellSouth would likely spend tens of millions of dollars
in the hope of increasing the loyalty of customers it already has
for phone service, while stretching to supply services it now
offers to only a relative handful.
</P>
<P>
   For a company that typically tries to please investors with
steady profits gleaned mostly from its core business in local phone
service, launch of a space strategy for television would be bold.
No other regional phone company has launched its own service,
although others, including Bell Atlantic and SBC, have signed
partnerships in which the satellite company's service is marketed
to their customers, said analyst Bruce Leichtman. ``This is
different. They would need their own hardware and that is not
inexpensive. This is a major, major effort if they do this. This
would be very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has only tinkered with television, offering it now via
``wireless cable.'' The service is broadcast only from towers, so
transmissions can be blocked by hills, trees and _ after a few
dozen miles _ the curve of the earth. Moreover, the earth-based
service requires purchase of a franchise license. BellSouth's
Americast service is now offered wirelessly in Orlando, Atlanta,
New Orleans and Jacksonville. BellSouth provides the service via
high-speed wires in Vestavia Hills, Ala. and Daniel Island, S.C. To
be a customer for BellSouth's wireless service, a customer must
have a receiver placed on a roof or tree that has an unobstructed
view to a broadcast antenna. In metro Atlanta, there are four.
Standard installation costs about $100, and basic service _ more
than 100 channels of television, music and pay-per-view movies,
runs $36.49 a month.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth was thrilled last summer to have tens of thousands of
calls from potential customers who either hated their cable company
or just wanted to check out the new service. But bad news was soon
evident: thousands of consumers lived too far away, or in gullies,
or on the back sides of hills or behind so many trees that the
signal couldn't get through.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been frustration. For BellSouth, knowing that
millions of dollars in potential monthly revenue were perched just
out of reach. And for some customers, being offered something they
could not get. But with a satellite, BellSouth's signal could reach
out and touch virtually any U.S. household.
</P>
<P>
   That capability would thrust BellSouth into a new arena, giving
it a way to woo millions of customers who now get television from
cable companies. Leichtman said. ``But they'd be competing as much
with DirecTV and Echo as with the cable companies. This is highly
aggressive and it's risky to be the third (direct broadcast
satellite) provider. I'm not sure why they would do this instead of
partnering with DBS.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jacobs said a partnership could not take full advantage of
either the brand name or the Americast programming that BellSouth
has been marketing. ``We've negotiated for content and built what
we think is a superior product. We've already got a stake in the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the move parallels previous BellSouth decisions to
make sure that a product is labeled BellSouth. When it was time to
offer Internet service, BellSouth could have repackaged an existing
provider. Instead, BellSouth built its own _ albeit with
behind-the-scenes aid from IBM. After a zig-zag strategy on paging,
BellSouth bought RAM Mobile Data but operates it as a subsidiary
that uses the BellSouth name.
</P>
<P>
   As a defensive gambit, satellite could add one more key service
that BellSouth customers could receive under the BellSouth name.
And _ so the reasoning goes _ the more services a customer has with
BellSouth, the less likely a switch to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   And increasingly, there are choices.
</P>
<P>
   Other competitive phone companies are offering bundles of
services in competition with the Bells, but most have focused on
business customers. Even if _ like MGC Communications _ they do
serve residents, they still do not string wires to customer homes,
and they lease the use of that ``last mile'' from BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to cable companies, a customer could leave the
BellSouth network completely.
</P>
<P>
   The Bells have expected for years that they would eventually
face a souped-up offering from cable companies. By upgrading their
systems, cable companies could provide high-speed Internet access,
digital television and phone service too. But only a fraction of
cable lines have been retooled, giving the phone companies an
opportunity to trot out new services themselves and cement
relationships with customers. BellSouth's negotiations with the
satellite companies have been under way for months. But perhaps
they have a new urgency now that AT&AMP;T's has slammed more than $100
billion on the table to buy two of the nation's top cable
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense for BellSouth to not only expand its product
mix but also find new ways to deliver advanced services to
customers,'' said telecommunications analyst Jeff Kagan. ``This is
important for them to remain competitive in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   A satellite ploy poses several dangers. First, is financial. If
BellSouth spends too much on equipment and satellite leases, and if
customers do not immediately flock to the service, profits could be
hurt. BellSouth has in the past been reluctant to make investments
that would dilute earnings. In the wake of the AT&AMP;T purchase of
MediaOne, BellSouth officials dismissed calls for dramatically
higher investment, arguing that they can do what is needed without
sacrificing even short-term earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Bacurin, analyst with JC Bradford &AMP; Co. said that dilution
of earnings depends on ``the scale and scope'' of the satellite
investment. ``My guess is, if they do this, they'd have to do it
aggressively. They are going to have to hit this hard and fast.''
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom chief executive Bernard Ebbers has generally been
able to persuade investors to stay on board as he spends billions
to get the market position he wants. AT&AMP;T too, once a conservative
stock, has managed a face-lift that lets shareholders think of it
as a growth company. To keep investors from jumping ship, BellSouth
too must repackage its image, and satellite could help convince
Wall Street of the need to think big and spend big _ even if it
means a short-term whack to earnings, Bacurin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie did it. AT&AMP;T is going to do it. The Bells have to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and the cable companies are betting on one wire _ the
upgraded cable that may take years and billions of dollars to
complete, but will in a single connection offer customers phone,
video and high-speed Internet access. BellSouth is headed toward a
kind of mix and match, with phone and high-speed service over
digital subscriber lines and television via the air _ whether by
satellite or not.
</P>
<P>
   If a deal can be forged as hoped, BellSouth could be in the
satellite business by early next year. With that plan, the company
can vow to give customers through the Southeast a smorgasbord of
choices, Jacobs said. ``I am looking at it as what the market
wants. We intend to maintain our leadership position in the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
