<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-RIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTLERS WASTE NO TIME CHALLENGING BARAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (With ISRAEL and related stories) 
(mk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Laying down a challenge to Ehud Barak a day after he
was elected Israel's prime minister, Jewish settlers began digging
foundations Tuesday for a new housing complex in an Arab
neighborhood of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The project, which has drawn protests from Palestinians and
expressions of concern from the Clinton administration, is financed
by Dr. Irving Moskowitz, an Orthodox Jewish millionaire from Miami
who has paid for other Jewish settlement projects in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The start of work came as settlement leaders and the rest of the
political right in Israel were reeling from the election of Barak,
the Labor Party leader, and from a poor showing by rightist parties
in the vote for Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Casting about for an effective strategy to challenge Barak with
a weakened parliamentary opposition, some rightist leaders are
contemplating a return to street protests and settlement actions.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's move in Jerusalem appeared to be the first shot of a
new campaign. A bulldozer rumbled onto a plot owned by Moskowitz in
the Ras al-Amud neighborhood at the foot of the Mount of Olives,
and began carving out a trench in the rocky soil.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the construction of 132 housing units in the
neighborhood where about 11,000 Palestinians live. A building
permit has been issued by the Jerusalem Municipality, and a
spokesman for Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who was defeated
in the election on Monday, said he had no grounds to intervene
unless there was a danger to public security.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has pressed Netanyahu to block
construction at the site, arguing that it could prejudice future
negotiations on Jerusalem as part of a final peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians view East Jerusalem, which was captured by Israel
in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war, as the capital of a future
Palestinian state. Israel asserts that it will forever remain part
of its indivisible capital, a claim reaffirmed by Barak in his
victory speech on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Matti Dan, a representative of Moskowitz and a leader of the
Ateret Cohanim settlement group, contended that the work had been
delayed until after Monday's balloting to avoid inflaming the
election campaign, but he suggested that it was a signal to Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The next prime minister, he noted, had ``declared that he would
preserve a united Jerusalem, and I don't believe that he will
change his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Moskowitz said in a written statement that the changes in the
neighborhood were ``in complete harmony with the concept of an
eternally united Jerusalem under exclusive Jewish sovereignty _ an
idea endorsed by all Jewish political parties and Jewish prime
ministerial candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's victory has sent shock waves through the settlement
movement. Pinchas Wallerstein, the chairman of the Settlers
Council, the umbrella organization of the Jewish settlers'
movement, announced his resignation, saying he bore some of the
responsibility for the parliamentary maneuvering that toppled
Netanyahu's government and brought early elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``That move was a mistake,'' he said, referring to the vote
against Netanyahu by rightist lawmakers opposed to relinquishing
West Bank land under the Wye River Memorandum signed with the
Palestinians in October.
</P>
<P>
   A group of eight legislators who joined forces to form a new
rightist party, the National Union, managed to garner only three
parliamentary seats in the election, indicating that the
overwhelming majority of Israelis had accepted the idea of ceding
West Bank land for peace.
</P>
<P>
   The National Religious Party, another group that speaks for the
settlers, went from nine parliamentary seats to five after losing
some of its members to the National Union. Recriminations flew
Tuesday between members of both parties as they blamed each other
for their poor showing.
</P>
<P>
   Hanan Porat, one of the defectors to the National Union,
attributed his party's showing to public indifference after the Wye
agreement was frozen by Netanyahu in the months before the
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strange silence in those days prevented the public from
realizing that there was a critical issue on the agenda,'' Porat
said. ``We failed to raise it with sufficient intensity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
