<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2166 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLEET-DIVEST-BOS &LR;      05-18 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-DIVEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET DETAILS SALE OF BRANCHES IN MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a key step in its planned merger with BankBoston
Corp., Fleet Financial Group Inc. unveiled Tuesday a detailed
branch sale plan that makes the largest bank divestiture proposal
in US history even bigger.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, crafted to meet antitrust requirements, calls for 292
Fleet and BankBoston branches throughout New England, with $12.5
billion in deposits and $5 billion in commercial loans, to be sold
in three lots. Fleet originally had envisioned selling around 270
branches.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, spelled out in a regulatory filing by Fleet,
permits one buyer to make a play for all three lots. It also allows
smaller local banks to bid for a tiny part of the deposit portion
of those packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really talking about two types of divestiture,'' said
Duncan Johnson, a lawyer with Providence-based Edwards &AMP; Angell.
</P>
<P>
   But smaller banks, which are hankering for a stab at the assets,
might not want to jump up and dance just yet.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful that regulators are keen to see a new, large competitor
in New England to compete with the combined Fleet-BankBoston, Fleet
has structured its divestiture plan in ways that make it difficult
or impractical for many smaller banks to bid. As such, the two
types of divestiture may yet yield one result _ a giant,
out-of-region buyer that instantly gains access to one of banking's
most lucrative markets by buying everything up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The likelihood of seeing assets go in small packages runs into
all sorts of'' hurdles, Johnson said, referring to minimum capital
requirements or local bidders located too far afield of the assets
on offer. ``Fleet may well have (out of region) bidders that want
everything in sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet said its divestiture proposal exceeds regulatory
requirements on market concentration, which in Massachusetts limit
any one bank to no more than 30 percent of deposits. In
Massachusetts, the largest of the New England markets, Fleet said
its proposal exceeded Federal Reserve guidelines by 37 percent;
overall, Fleet says it is selling $4 billion more in deposits than
required.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two companies wanted a proposal that is so reasonable that
regulators can't turn it down,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet and BankBoston propose to sell:
</P>
<P>
   --A Massachusetts/New Hampshire lot, comprising 209 Fleet
branches (196 in Massachusetts) with $8.7 billion in deposits, 416
automated teller machines, and $1.8 billion in small and
middle-market loans. Viewed as a stand-alone institution, the lot
constitutes the largest divestiture in US history and will rank
among the top 50 banks in the country. Approximately $7.2 billion
of the divested amount is in the Boston market. The package
excludes $5.4 billion in deposits related to Fleet's Advanta Corp.
credit card unit.
</P>
<P>
   --A Rhode Island lot, with 46 BankBoston branches and two Fleet
branches, all with $2.2 billion in deposits and $223 million in
loans.
</P>
<P>
   --A Connecticut lot, comprising 33 BankBoston branches, mainly
in Hartford and Torrington, with $1.5 billion in deposits and $150
million in loans.
</P>
<P>
   As they seek regulatory approval to combine into the nation's
eighth-largest bank, Fleet and BankBoston are waging a battle on
two fronts. On the local side, community banks are fighting to
avoid being muscled out of the market by a big bank from outside
the region. On the federal side _ the main focus _ the two banks
are working to appease the Federal Reserve Board and the Justice
Department, both of which want a major new competitor in the
region. The $16 billion merger of New England's two largest banks,
announced in March, marks the first time that a major region will
be left without two large banks. Citizens Financial Group Inc.,
which will become the area's second largest player after the deal,
is still only a fraction of the combined bank's size.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet and BankBoston do not plan any divestitures in New Haven,
New London, Fairfield, Greenfield, Springfield, Portland,
Manchester, or West Palm Beach, Fla. The two banks are likely to
close or relocate overlapping branches in those markets, Fleet
spokesman James Mahoney said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet filed its divestiture proposal with state banking
regulators in four New England states and the Federal Reserve Bank
of Boston. The Fed has 30 days to raise objections. Fleet plans to
send out bidding applications in the next two weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
