u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FED-RATES-BOS &LR;      05-18 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED STANDS PAT ON RATES, BUT ISSUES WARNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal Reserve policy makers Tuesday put the
nation on notice that they might raise interest rates soon in an
attempt to fight inflation. But they said prices were not rising
enough that they had to act right away.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks plummeted on the prospect of higher rates, which would
slow the economy. The Dow Jones industrial average had gained 77
points by early afternoon, but the Fed announcement triggered a
112-point fall. The Dow ended the day down 16.52, closing at
10,836.95.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a warning from the Fed,'' said Oscar Gonzalez, an
economist at John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance in Boston. ``If
inflation is not yet at our doorstep, it's certainly not too far
away. So, I think this was an appropriate warning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's policy making body, the Federal Open Market Committee,
voted during a closed-door meeting to make no change in the target
federal funds rate, which is now 4.75 percent. That is the rate
banks charge each other on overnight loans, but it also influences
a variety of other short-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the committee released a brief statement
saying it ``was concerned about the potential for a buildup of
inflationary imbalances that could undermine the favorable
performance of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of that fear, the committee is now ``tilted toward the
possibility'' of raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation has remained low in recent years, a remarkable
development given that labor markets are tight, which tends to
force businesses to raise wages, and Americans are on a spending
spree, which tends to allow businesses to raise prices.
</P>
<P>
   Economists have suggested that a jump in business productivity
has helped keep price increases to a minimum, as businesses can
turn out more goods with the same amount of resources.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists also note that the Asian financial crisis has
cut the demand for oil, copper, corn, and other commodities
steeply, sending prices to record lows and helping keep inflation
in check.
</P>
<P>
   But that could change. In its statement, the Fed committee said
``foreign economic prospects have improved,'' suggesting that Asian
nations and others caught in the global economic downturn might
begin buying goods again, prompting the prices of both commodities
and finished goods to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Labor Department reported the largest one-month
spike in inflation in nine years. Consumer prices rose 0.7 percent
in April, the department said, and was up 0.4 percent even after
the volatile food and energy components were stripped out.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Commerce Department reported that construction of
new homes fell 10.1 percent in April, the biggest drop in nearly
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said the figures did not signal an economic slowdown
or decline in consumer spending. Instead, they said, an
unseasonably warm winter had probably shifted some construction
usually done in the spring to the winter months.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Fed's job is to fight inflation, which erodes the
value of wages and adds uncertainty to the economy. The Fed can
tame inflation by raising interest rates, which raises the cost of
borrowing money.
</P>
<P>
   People then buy fewer items on credit, and businesses borrow
less money for expansion. As the economy cools, workers have less
power to demand higher wages, and businesses cannot raise prices as
easily _ keeping inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts now expect the Fed panel to raise interest rates
in the next six months, though it may wait until August rather than
act at its next meeting, June 29 and 30. But there is no guarantee
a rate hike will occur. Cynthia Latta, chief US economist at
Standard &AMP; Poor's/DRI, a Lexington, Mass. forecasting firm, noted
that the Fed Tuesday said only that it had ``tilted toward the
possiblity'' of higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very hedged statement,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tuesday's developments showed that for the Fed, talk is a
form of action and can move markets. The Fed has been using talk as
a tool more often in recent years. Once notoriously silent about
its intentions, the Fed recently adopted a policy of releasing
statements about its views and possible future actions.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts suggested that the Fed wanted to ``jawbone''
the bond market into raising rates, which would cool the economy in
the same way Fed rate hikes would. In this way, the Fed could
achieve its goal without actually taking action. ``I think the Fed
would be quite happy to have the bond market do that, do its work
for it,'' said Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Latta and other analysts said the Fed was compelled to signal in
some way that it was concerned about inflation. If not, it would
lose credibility as an inflation fighter, and investors and
businesses might feel it was insufficiently guarding against
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is very concerned about inflation,'' Latta said.
``They think it's a problem. So they would have reacted badly if
the Fed showed no concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Allan Meltzer, an economist at Carnegie Mellon University in
Pittsburgh, believes the Fed has shown insufficient concern about
inflation. He is chairman of the Shadow Open Market Committee,
which follows Fed actions and has recommended an interest rate
increase for about six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're behind the curve, in my judgment, and have let things
get a little out of hand _ not terribly, but a little out of
hand,'' Meltzer said, referring to recent signs of rising
inflation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
