<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABDULLAH-ISRAEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JORDAN KING CONFIDENT PEACE EFFORT WILL BE RENEWED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ King Abdullah of Jordan expressed confidence
Tuesday that Middle East peace efforts will be revived following
the election of Labor party leader Ehud Barak as Israeli prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   On his first visit to the White House since he assumed the
throne after the death of his father, King Hussein, Abdullah said
Barak's victory over Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu left him
``very, very optimistic'' about the prospects for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see eye to eye on many issues, and we're very optimistic of
taking the peace process forward,'' he said, adding that he met
with Barak in Jordan shortly before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah made his comments during a photo session with President
Clinton in the Oval Office. Jordan, a key player in the peace
process, is a significant US ally in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who had a close relationship with the king's father
until his death Feb. 7, has said that Hussein, despite his poor
health, helped move forward the peace talks at the Wye River
Plantation in Maryland last year during the critical final hours.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah's renewed optimism about peace in the Middle East
parallels the US government's belief that the change in Israel's
leadership may help break a months-long deadlock between the
Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   US officials are anxious to resume talks on the shape of a final
settlement for the Palestinians, and the timetable for
implementation of the Wye agreement that would have Israel pull
back from another 13.1 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed a one-year period for completing the
``final status'' talks, which would plow over some of the most
thorny issues in the Arab-Israeli conflict. They include Jewish
settlements, the borders and status of a Palestinian entity, rival
claims to Arab East Jerusalem and the fate of Palestinian refugees
in the diaspora.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Abdullah both telephoned Barak after he defeated
Netanyahu in Monday's election, 56 percent to 43 percent. Clinton
also telephoned Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat Tuesday to
reaffirm the US interest in moving the peace process forward, a
senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   The president said the push for peace wouldn't begin immediately
but would have to wait until Barak has had time to put together a
new government, which could determine the tenor of peace talks. ``I
think General Barak is entitled to a few days to put a government
together,'' Clinton said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said he was encouraged that Barak has shown ``an
intention to continue the peace process. And if he's willing to do
it, I think that we're certainly both willing to do it and we're
hopeful that we'll have a chance to do so,'' Clinton said as the
37-year-old monarch sat at his side.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that while work remains on the final status
issues in the Wye accord, ``I think the roadmap is out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say they expect Abdullah to follow in
his father's footsteps and play an active role in peace talks. ``I
think it is the universal sense on the American side that the king
has already grown in office, even in just these short several
months,'' the administration official said. ``And as a leader, he
has already shown an impressive ability to stand up in a tough
neighborhood and make himself a player.''
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders also discussed Jordan's faltering economy. ``We
are also very committed to Jordan's economic renewal,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
