<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYRD FAMILY VOWS TO KEEP FIGHTING FOR PASSAGE OF TEXAS HATE CRIMES
BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The family of a black man who was dragged behind
a pickup until his body broke into pieces vowed Tuesday to keep
working for passage of a state hate crimes bill named in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the state Senate failed to pass the proposed James
Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Act last week, ``we don't consider it as a
defeat,'' said Byrd's daughter, Francis Renee Mullins, 28, of
Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   She pledged to return to Texas next year after the birth of her
second child, expected in October, to lobby legislators for passage
of the bill. ``We're going to go to the legislators and ask them,
`what if it was your father, or brother or son, or even your pet,'
because not even an animal should be treated this way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her cousin, Darrell Verrett, of Houston, agreed that the family
will continue to fight for the bill, ``if it takes a couple of
years or a couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's mother, Stella Byrd, said she realizes that the bill
``can't help my son, but it might help some other mother from going
through what I went through.'' She said the bill might mean
``people won't be afraid to go to school or to go to church.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have increased the penalties for certain crimes
if they were motivated by hate; murder and capital murder cases
would not have been affected.
</P>
<P>
   Mullins said she was disappointed the bill didn't pass, but
stopped short of blaming Senate Republicans who opposed the bill
because it included gays and lesbians among the groups that are
specified as potential victims of hate crimes. ``Republicans,
they're humans too,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Verrett said he and other family members often worked until 2
a.m. to try to convince legislators to approve the bill or to help
work out compromises that would get the bill passed. ``I am
confident that it will some day be passed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush never promised to back the bill, Mullins
said, but did assure her that he would give it serious
consideration if it made it to his desk. She said President Clinton
``assured us he would do everything in his power'' to get it
passed.
</P>
<P>
   She said her father always told her there's a time and place for
everything. ``There'll be a time for this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's father, James Byrd Sr., said his family holds no
bitterness toward anybody over the death of his son, but wants
justice. ``We're not cowards either,'' he said. ``We want to live
together in peace and harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray met with Mullins
and Verrett earlier in the day amid speculation that political
leaders wanted them to call off their press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said he never asked them to call off the press conference,
but asked them to refrain from making statements that may impact
getting juries in the upcoming trials of two men accused of Byrd's
murder. Mullins and Verrett said they never felt pressured not to
talk.
</P>
<P>
   In response to reporters' questions in Austin, the Department of
Public Safety on Tuesday afternoon also issued a denial that any
officers had urged the family to cancel the press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said legislators had asked him and Jasper Sheriff Billy
Rowles to make statements or campaign for the Byrd bill, but they
refused, he said, because their job is to enforce the law, not make
it. ``You've got to stay focused,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One man, John William ``Bill'' King, 24, has already been
sentenced to death for Byrd's murder. The trial of Lawrence Russell
Brewer Jr., 32, is scheduled to begin in August in Bryan. Shawn
Berry, 24, is due to be tried in Jasper in October.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
