<HEADER>
A2172 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-HIGHHOPES-TEX     05-18 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HIGHHOPES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SUPPORTERS DOING ALL BUT MEASURING WHITE HOUSE CURTAINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ From the Capitol in Austin to the marbled
corridors of Washington power, supporters of Gov. George W. Bush
have all but begun measuring the curtains at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that it's a long way to November _ 2000 _ or that
there is a GOP nomination contest to contend with first.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the many blown leads in U.S. political history,
confidence is running so high in some circles that there is already
talk of a Cabinet-in-waiting and a unified Republican agenda for
the George W. Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Legislature is moving to clarify the state
constitution to ensure what Bush's would-be successor, Lt. Gov.
Rick Perry, called an ``orderly transfer of power.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only are people assuming he's going to win, I think most
of them have already served in the Bush administration and have
started thinking about which college they want to teach at,'' said
Bill Miller, an Austin political consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and other observers recognize that Bush could win. The
huge campaign war chest and unprecedented endorsements he has
gathered even though he hasn't formally announced his candidacy
have cemented his reputation as a formidable contender.
</P>
<P>
   But experts warn that the overconfidence and high expectations
surrounding his candidacy underscore the danger of assuming
anything about presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people forget is there are nine other candidates and
hundreds of staffers for those candidates who are plotting 24 hours
a day on how to take George W. down,'' said Larry Sabato, a
University of Virginia political analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is far from a done deal. There could be some shocked
egos,'' he said. ``Voters do not like to be taken for granted. They
want to be the ones making the decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in an exchange with reporters last week, emphasized that
he is taking nothing for granted. For example, he disputed the
notion that he is formulating an agenda with members of Congress
for a unified 2000 agenda _ months before a presidential nominee is
selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's presumptuous at this point and time for any
candidate to be trying to figure out a general election strategy
when someone doesn't have the nomination,'' Bush said. ``First
things first. I've got to get out there and start shaking hands and
looking people in the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush's operatives have readily disclosed that
discussions, focusing both on 2000 politics and 2001 policy, have
been under way on the Bush network.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Roy Blunt, R-Mo., a member of Bush's exploratory committee,
told the Capitol Hill newspaper Roll Call that congressional
leaders are trying to create ``not only an election strategy but a
governance strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes told The New York Times
that the talks centered on ``the agenda that would emerge from the
2000 presidential campaign should Governor Bush be elected
president.''
</P>
<P>
   If friendly members of Congress seem confident of a Bush
presidency, their enthusiasm has nothing on some Texas lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty much a bygone conclusion, at least in my
perception, that (Bush) will be the next president,'' said state
Sen. Ken Armbrister, a conservative Democrat from Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   Armbrister is one of several people who may be players in the
succession battle that would emerge should Bush move on to higher
political ground.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, anticipating the possibility of a vacancy in the
governor's office, is expected to give final approval as early as
Wednesday to a constitutional amendment that would ensure that
Perry vacates his old job if he becomes governor under that
scenario. The amendment is subject to the voters' approval.
</P>
<P>
   Current language could be interpreted to read that the
lieutenant governor could keep both jobs. The new language would
require senators to conduct an internal election to pick a new
lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation's eyes are focused on Texas and our great
governor,'' Perry said in a written statement. ``So this is an
appropriate time to consider the orderly transfer of power.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of a vacancy in the lieutenant governor's office
has touched off a subtle campaign for the job _ somewhat like House
speaker races _ several senators have said.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. John Whitmire, D-Houston, said members are bending
over backward to be nice to each other so they'll have some chits
to cash in if there is an opening to fill.
</P>
<P>
   He said members have been taking each other to dinner and taking
full advantage of any ``opportunities to show leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like some of those folks, when they get up there and
they have the gavel on the podium for a little while, it seems like
they just stand a little more erect than they used to,'' Whitmire
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the warnings about high expectations, some in the
Bush camp say it beats being on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Michican Gov. John Engler, who has helped pull in endorsements
and money for the governor, said that candidates should ``always
guard against overconfidence,'' but that at least the Bush camp has
something to be confident about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize that sort of the higher up in the polls you are the
more is exposed and being shot at by everyone else,'' he said.
``But again, I'd rather be there than down at the bottom trying to
get on a poll or having made two inches of headway.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
