<SLUG> BC-SCOUTS-GAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY SCOUT OFFICIALS, UNITARIANS REOPEN GAY ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Accusing the Boy Scouts of America of discrimination, the
Unitarian Universalist Association Tuesday vowed to defy the
organization's latest order to stop giving religious awards to
scouts who are Unitarians.
</P>
<P>
   After apparently reaching a compromise on a dispute that has
raged between the two groups over their opposing views on gays, the
Boy Scouts of America revoked the authority it had again granted
the Unitarians to give out the awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they intend to start ripping badges off scout uniforms when
our children earn a religious award, they are going to look very
peculiar,'' said John A. Buehrens, president of the
250,000-denomination. ``We will continue to award the badge and our
young people will continue to earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Unitarian officials had agreed to remove all
language in a church manual that promoted gay rights and criticized
the Boy Scouts views on homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The Boy Scouts consider homosexuality immoral and forbid gays
from joining the organization. Last May, the Scouts, reacting to
the ``Religion in Life'' manual, told the Unitarians not to give
out the award.
</P>
<P>
   But as part of what Unitarians say was their agreement with the
Boy Scouts, church officials would include a separate statement
when it distributes the religion manual making it clear the
Unitarians strongly disagree with the Boy Scouts position on gays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Boy Scout officials sat here in my office and said it was
okay,'' Buehrens said. A liberal denomination with historical roots
in New England, the Unitarian Universalist Association is
headquartered in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But a Boy Scouts spokesman said the separate document was never
discussed as part of any compromise. ``It was not discussed in the
meeting,'' said Gregg Shields. ``That document reopens the whole
issue of using boys as a venue to air the Unitarian Universalist
Association's objection to scouting's commitment to duty, to God
and to traditional family values.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Buehrens, ``It's clear to me that we are being
discriminated against because we have some principles that make
them uncomfortable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
