<HEADER>
A2187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-Y2K-COX     05-18 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-Y2K-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta insists air system safe, but perception a worry
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What worries Delta Air Lines is not the millennium bug
but people's perception of it.
</P>
<P>
   All of the airline's critical computer systems have been fixed
to recognize and process the year 2000. Yet there are increasing
reports in the media that people are scared to fly after the first
of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our biggest concern,'' says Walter Taylor, vice
president of airline operation systems and Y2K program manager at
Delta. ``We're worried that people will be afraid to fly even
though our airlines and air system is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   That prompted an aggressive Delta publicity campaign. The idea
is to counter the perception flying will be unsafe because of the
millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting people out to speak about what we've done about
Y2K to the public and industry groups,'' says Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Flying Delta would have been problematic if the Atlanta-based
airline had done nothing to address the millennium bug. This bug
hinders computers large and small from recognizing dates after the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For Delta, that would have meant computer reservation systems
spitting out wrong information or shutting down. That's why the
airline moved early to stomp out this bug. It hasn't been easy or
cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Delta budgeted $125 million to identify potential Y2K problems
and fix them.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the hard part wasn't fixing the bug. The hard part was
analyzing how that fix would ripple through the computer systems as
a whole. In short, the trick was to identify any unintended
consequences from the fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge is making sure you've taken care of the
entire problem,'' says Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The next challenge was designing a reliable testing program to
make sure Delta had caught every problem. Designing a good test
took two months alone last summer, says Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is for Delta to ensure that its suppliers and the
Federal Aviation Administration are also progressing on fixing Y2K
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're meeting with all our suppliers face to face,'' says
Taylor. ``Boeing has told us in writing that its planes are safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is also pleased with what the FAA has done. ``The FAA has
done a good job in fixing the technical problems,'' says Taylor.
``But it hasn't done such a good job in conveying that message to
the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
