<HEADLINE>
U.S., JORDAN HOPE BARAK VICTORY REVIVES PEACE PROCESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Jordan's King Abdullah, both
advocates of revived Middle East peace talks, welcomed Tuesday the
election of a new Israeli prime minister as an opportunity get the
process back on track.
</P>
<P>
   The election of Labor Party candidate Ehud Barak, Israel's most
decorated soldier, over incumbent Benjamin Netanyahu has raised
hopes with the administration that a regional settlement may be
possible. Barak also has signaled his willingness to negotiate with
Syria and Lebanon as well as the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said Clinton and King Abdullah
``expressed confidence that the Middle East peace process will now
be reinvigorated and strengthened, and hopefully brought to a
successful conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters he was encouraged because ``the whole
issue of the peace process was an issue (in the elections); and I
think because of his military service the question of General
Barak's devotion to the security of Israel is not in question.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, sitting beside King Abdullah prior to their
private meeting, said Barak ``has evidenced an intention to
continue the peace process. And if he's willing to do it, I think
that we're certainly both willing to do it and we're hopeful that
we'll have a chance to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   King Abdullah noted Barak visited Jordan recently. ``We see eye
to eye on many issues, and we're very optimistic of taking the
peace process forward,'' the King said. He called the Israeli
elections ``very, very optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to reassure
him that the United States remained committed to the Wye River
Accords, which calls on Israel to withdraw from additional portions
of the West Bank and sets out a timetable for additional
negotiations on such critical issues as the status of Jerusalem and
of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an accord at Wye to implement, and we have a lot of
work to do on the final status issues,'' Clinton told reporters.
``I think the road map is out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton publicly expressed no feelings about Netanyahu's defeat,
but the White House undoubtedly will be glad to see him go.
Netanyahu, head of the Likud Party and a favorite of Christian
conservatives in the United States, came under fire from
hard-liners within his coalition after signing the Wye River
accord. He, in turn, accused Palestinians of doing too little on
the security front and suspended implementation of agreement only
weeks after signing it.
</P>
<P>
   A personal appeal by Clinton stopped Arafat from declaring
statehood for Palestine on May 4, the original deadline for
completing the so-called final status talks. Such a declaration
likely would have rattled the Israeli elections.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said the president looks
forward to the Israeli-Palestinian peace track moving
expeditiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to move forward on this process as quickly as
possible. And I can tell you that the president has a very high
sense of urgency about it. He is invigorated by the prospects of
getting back to work on this,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House visit was the first by King Abdullah who
inherited his position upon the death of his father, King Hussein,
in February. King Hussein, though suffering from cancer at the
time, was instrumental in convincing the Israelis and Palestinians
to sign the Wye River accord.
</P>
<P>
   King Hussein's death came at a critical time for Middle East
peace negotiations, but administration officials said King Abdullah
is following in his father's footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is the universal sense on the American side that
the King has already grown in office, even in these short several
months. And as a leader he has already shown an impressive ability
to stand up in a tough neighborhood and make himself a player,'' a
senior aide said.
</P>
<P>
   King Abdullah also was seeking economic support for his county,
which is having economic problems. Clinton agreed to seek support
from European nations for either debt forgiveness or restructuring
to relieve the burden on Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
