<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-CUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS MAKING SPENDING CUTS IT ADMITS ARE PAINFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans on Tuesday completed a
plan to cut domestic spending by tens of billions of dollars next
year. Their leaders warned it would cause ``sticker shock'' and
political pain. The White House called it ``a blueprint for
political chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Slashing domestic spending by 11 percent might seem strange at a
time of budget surpluses and economic prosperity. But in 1997,
Congress and the White House agreed to spending caps to force down
federal expenditures. They are now chafing under the restraints
they embraced.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts will come in spending categories covering education,
job training, housing, health and human services, environmental
protection, medical and high-tech research, diplomacy and foreign
aid, among other federal programs. These follow $53 billion in
domestic spending reductions since the Republicans won control of
Congress in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all knew this was going to be painful,'' said House
Majority Leader Dick Armey on Tuesday. He said there would be
``sticker shock now in realizing just how difficult it will be'' to
stick to the spending caps.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, the House Appropriations Committee will slice
up a $538 billion budget pie _ what's left of the $1.75 trillion
budget after paying for mandatory programs like Medicare _ for its
13 subcommittees. Under its plan, the Pentagon will receive about
$270 billion _ more than half the money. Every other government
agency would receive an aggregate of about $268 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's final spending draft for fiscal 2000, which will
be formally approved Wednesday, contains $26.3 billion in cuts for
domestic spending, about 11 percent less than what Congress meted
out for this year, and a $18.9 billion increase for the military,
up about 7.5 percent, committee members said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress are moaning, ```Oh, oh, oh, we can't live up
to that,''' said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott. ``It's tough,
but it ought to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, along with some congressional Republicans
and Democrats, warned that the plan could lead to political
confrontation and presidential vetoes. Some predicted a repeat of
last year's spending stalemate, which ended in a frenzied,
last-minute omnibus spending bill larded with $21 billion in
extras. Others remembered the standoff that led to a government
shutdown in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican budget is a blueprint for chaos,'' said White
House Budget Director Jacob Lew. ``These allocations are a sign of
that. They would have unacceptable consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats point out that the caps have shrunk domestic
non-defense spending down to its smallest share of the national
economy since 1962. They also helped create a budget surplus, but
at a cost. Not all Republicans agree they still make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's hardly a member of Congress that doesn't realize the
caps will be lifted,'' said Rep. John Edward Porter of Illinois, a
senior Republican on the Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But lifting the caps could violate solemn promises made by
Republican leaders. It could result in more spending taken from
surplus Social Security funds, and it could blunt Republican plans
for tax cuts, splintering two of the biggest planks in their
political platform for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Porter is one of 13 House Appropriations subcommittee chairmen _
they are called Congress' college of cardinals _ who will divide
the $538 billion in discretionary spending Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   His subcommittee, which oversees labor, education and health
programs, would receive nearly $11 billion less than last year. The
subcommittee overseeing the Veterans Administration and the
Department of Housing and Urban Development would take a $5.8
billion cut; the one overseeing the Commerce, State and Justice
Departments, a $2.8 billion cut; the Interior Department, $2.7
billion; foreign operations, $2.4 billion. The subcommittees must
figure out how to divide their allocations and pay for their
programs under the caps before the fiscal year ends on Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, at least, the caps were irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   The House was set to pass an emergency spending bill of nearly
$15 billion, twice what President Clinton requested, financing
NATO's air war in Yugoslavia, relief for refugees in Kosovo, and
aid for disaster victims in the United States and Central America,
along with billions in military projects.
</P>
<P>
   About $13 billion will come from surplus Social Security funds.
That money is designated as an emergency appropriation, meaning it
does not count under the spending caps. Most of the rest will come
from food stamp and low-income housing funds designated as surplus
and unlikely to be spent this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will take up the bill later this week. Clinton has
indicated he will sign it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
