<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2197 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SARGENT-ART-2TAKES-$A     05-18 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SARGENT-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SARGENT TURNED HIS BACK ON FASHION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Deborah Weisgall's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was
about the photographer Abelardo Morell.  
 By DEBORAH WEISGALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For half his life, from 1890, when he was at the height
of his career, until his death in 1925, John Singer Sargent was
under contract to produce murals and decorative schemes for public
buildings in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The son of an expatriate New England doctor, Sargent lived
mostly in Europe; but in Boston he had close friends and family,
and he visited often. Boston was the American city closest to his
European sensibility; it understood him best.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to ``Sargent Summer,'' a series of exhibitions timed
to coincide with the last stop of the Sargent retrospective at the
Museum of Fine Arts (June 27 through Sept. 26), Boston is once
again the city where one can come to a new understanding of the
reticent artist and his art.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition at the Fogg Art Museum, ``Sargent in the Studio:
Drawings, Sketchbooks and Oil Sketches'' (June 10 through Sept. 5),
drawn from its own collections, focuses on the private Sargent, on
the work he made for himself, including many preparatory studies
and the model for the Boston Public Library murals.
</P>
<P>
   The show begins with sketchbooks Sargent kept from the time he
was 16, with highly accomplished penciled landscapes punctuated
with impish caricatures. It includes a breathtaking watercolor
study for his notorious ``Madame X'' (Madame Gautreau), which
captures the lady's hawklike allure.
</P>
<P>
   The Fogg also owns a group of oil sketches that Sargent made on
a trip to Morocco at the beginning of his career. A bath house, a
street scene: the paint seems brushed quick as thought; the
atmosphere is intimate, charged with sensuality as Sargent embraces
North Africa's heat and light and its exotic interiors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sargent: The Late Landscapes'' at the Isabella Stewart Gardner
Museum (through Sept. 26), considers the artist during the years
1905 to 1917, when he had for the most part grown weary of painting
the portraits of the rich and famous that had made his reputation
on both continents. Sargent spent half of every year traveling; at
the outbreak of the World War I he was detained in the Austrian
Tyrol. During the war, he spent some time in America, and traveled
to Florida and the Canadian Rockies. ``Yoho Falls,'' which Gardner
commissioned from his expedition West, anchors the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoors, Sargent looked close, seeking pattern, light and
emotional effect: the rocky violence of a swath cut by an
avalanche, a waterfall's incessant, maddening spray and thunder.
Like the waterlilies that his friend Monet was painting at this
time, Sargent's landscapes verge on claustrophobia. Everything _
rocks, water, foliage _ strains against the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Erica Hirschler, associate curator of paintings at the Museum of
Fine Arts, points out that in these paintings, the difference
between oil and watercolor blurs. Sargent leaves canvas bare,
startling and white, as if it were paper, or he lays on watercolor
dry and thick. Figures _ Sargent almost always traveled with
friends and family _ melt into the landscape, dappled with light
like leaves and tree trunks, painted in the same palette of blues,
browns and greens.
</P>
<P>
   Grandeur in landscape never interested Sargent, but in his
murals he sought monumentality. Boston, of course, is where the
murals are on permanent exhibition. They are surprising, often
astonishing, often dazzling, and so unlike Sargent's more familiar
images that it is possible to look right at them and not recognize
the hand that painted them.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they are good is a complicated question. They are
important; Sargent considered these cycles, painted for the Boston
Public Library, Widener Library at Harvard and the Museum of Fine
Arts, an increasingly significant part of his work.
</P>
<P>
   In 1907, Sargent announced his retirement from painting
portraits, largely to concentrate on murals. But even the critics
and art historians who were his contemporaries disagreed with
Sargent's own assessment of those projects; Bernard Berenson
condemned the work for the Museum of Fine Arts as ``inappropriate''
and ``ladylike.'' Heavy with allegory and message, the murals were
painted in a style that was already out of date.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, however, cared little for the new. The Armory Show of
1913 came here before it went to New York, but Bostonians ignored
Duchamp and Matisse and their revolutionary art. While the Boston
exhibitions will not expose Sargent as an American fauve, they will
reveal how difficult it is to label him.
</P>
<P>
   In 1910, Roger Fry, the influential British critic, listed
Sargent among the post-Impressionists. Sargent was furious and said
so publicly. As a young man in Paris, he had exhibited with the
Impressionists, but in 1884, he left Paris, stung by the scandal
his radical portrait of Madame Gautreau had caused. And he had
always hedged his bets by also sending paintings to the traditional
Salon.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 20th century, which seems more interested in
life than in art, Sargent's elusiveness remains frustrating. He
dropped no hints of secrets in letters or art and rarely alluded to
how life affected him. He never married, but remained close to his
sister Emily.
</P>
<P>
   Tongue-tied and awkward in society, he was funny and
affectionate with his friends (Henry James, Gardner and Gabriel
Faure, among others) as his portraits of them attest. He was a fine
pianist and said he never read a newspaper. He painted both men and
women with sensual delight.
</P>
<P>
   As in ``The Chess Game'' or ``Cashmere,'' both in the Museum of
Fine Arts show, whose models he knew well, he transformed anyone he
loved into gorgeous design. He felt with his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Sargent grew up surrounded by art, not people. His American
parents dragged him (as James' parents dragged their children) from
city to city, through museums and cathedrals. By the time Sargent
was 16, he knew he would be an artist. He had a gift for intimacy.
His portraits and landscapes glimmer with perceptions, as if
Sargent had seized a moment of narrative and painted it trailing
hints of befores and afters.
</P>
<P>
   But Sargent also knew intimately the grand mosaics in Ravenna,
the frescoes of the Sistine Chapel, Last Judgments and Expulsions
from Eden, the Elgin Marbles, Egyptian pharaohs and Assyrian winged
lions.
</P>
<P>
   He measured himself against this art. When Charles McKim, the
architect of the Boston Public Library, asked him to decorate its
third floor, Sargent saw his chance. He worked on the library
murals until 1919. He traveled to Palestine and Egypt _ it was
assumed that the inhabitants had not changed since biblical times _
to sketch figures. He made more than 1,500 studies, many on view
this summer, which trace the passage from private observation to
public decoration.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sargent's design in the library (on view June 7 to July 30;
formal tours of the murals on Saturdays, June 26 through Sept. 25)
comprises a Hebraic End and a Christian End. The Hebraic End is a
fabulous mix of ancient images: bull-bodied Moloch, caged by gilt
spears tipped with hands, Astarte bedecked with glass jewels,
Egyptians oppressing the Hebrews, all surrounded by verses from
Psalm 106. Below this, Moses holds the gilded Ten Commandments; a
Frieze of Prophets surrounds him, each name inscribed in Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian End is similarly condensed, a sculptured
Crucifixion (Sargent seems to have made all these himself) with
Adam and Eve catching Christ's blood and all three entwined in the
Serpent; Mary caged by gilt candles and attended by angels and
texts. In between the ends lie Heaven, Hell and the Last Judgment;
Sargent did pages of sketches of chains for the judgment scales.
The ghost of Michelangelo hovers.
</P>
<P>
   The wonderfully appropriate underlying theme must be, as Mary
Crawford Volk, an independent art historian, suggests in the
retrospective's catalog, the Word. The hall is badly lighted, but
Sargent's intensity, his passion for images deconstructed and
recombined, illuminates the design. In this post-modern age, it is
once again beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Sargent went from the library to the museum. Once again, he
designed the entire installation, paintings and sculptures,
requiring major architectural adjustments in the rotunda to
accommodate his cycle of classical myths. He finished in 1925.
Classicism was in the air. Picasso was painting his enormous,
toga-draped women; in that context, Sargent's scenes willfully
ignore the world.
</P>
<P>
   When restoration of the murals began, it was discovered that the
plaster had been painted over during the 1940s, obliterating
Sargent's color scheme and the delicate, painted shading he applied
to bas reliefs and decorative detail. As Carol Troyen, associate
curator of painting at the Museum of Fine Arts, explains, Sargent's
murals make sense as part of a grand decorative scheme, appropriate
to the Beaux-Arts building.
</P>
<P>
   Sargent died on the eve of his departure for Boston to attend
the unveiling of his murals at the Museum of Fine Arts. The next
year, writing on Sargent's memorial exhibition at the Royal Academy
in London, Roger Fry, not for the first time, called Sargent a
fusty, elitist, superficial, postcard-view-painting conservative.
</P>
<P>
   His murals, Fry continued, were especially bad. This attack,
soon taken up in America, still finds echoes today, although
against the evidence of the dazzling, profoundly mysterious and
satisfying beauty of Sargent's paintings, it seems irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   But the large, flat figures of the murals seem antithetical to
the luminosity, grace and plotted spontaneity of Sargent's
watercolors and oils. Viewing them from the restorers' scaffolding
reveals the subtle shading of a cloak, next to dripped paint he
didn't bother to erase. From a distance, both drip and shadow
vanish. There is a sense of detachment about these images; in a
similar way, ``Gassed,'' the huge painting he produced for the
British War Memorials Committee, seems, at first, detached.
</P>
<P>
   Sargent spent four months at the front in 1918, sketching under
his white umbrella (which the Americans camouflaged); he contracted
influenza and was laid up in an army hospital with the wounded; his
niece had been killed by a bomb. He experienced war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gassed,'' 20 feet long, shows a line of blinded soldiers
staggering across a field, moving against an elegiac, golden
sunset. Each grips the shoulder of the man in front. In the
distance, carefree young men play soccer and little airplanes soar
in the serene sky like a flock of birds.
</P>
<P>
   This was a scene Sargent had witnessed. It must have been
horrible. For Sargent, the procession resonated with art: with
Breughel's image of the blind leading the blind, with Rodin's
``Burghers of Calais.'' The soldiers lying on the field in the
foreground sprawl like centurions at Golgotha. That is how Sargent
experienced: through Breughel and Rodin, through art. Knowing these
antecedents, the work changes and gathers power.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his life, Sargent, the most seductive of artists,
might simply have painted for himself. Like Monet, Sargent knew
that he was considered old-fashioned.
</P>
<P>
   He titled one of the rotunda murals ``Painting, Sculpture and
Architecture Protected From Time by Athena.'' He based the figure
of Architecture, according to Ms. Troyen, on Michelangelo's
``Bruges Madonna.'' Painting, in her classical drapery and
contemporary face, leans against Architecture's sturdy shoulder.
Here were the gods Sargent worshipped. The painting could be his
plea, and his credo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
