<HEADLINE>
WATSON RECALLS THE SHOT, OTHER NOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS, KEVIN LYONS and J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ Tom Watson said he has yet to venture out to
the hole where he made his most memorable shot: the par-4 No. 9.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, Watson's off-balance second shot out of the fairway
bunker to within 10 feet for birdie landed him among the event's
shot-making legends.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's 8-iron approach carried into a gust of wind and over
water to the green.
</P>
<P>
   The shot evoked a thunderous roar from the final-day gallery and
carried Watson through the final nine holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way,'' Watson said. ``I hope I'm not in that
bunker again. I wouldn't want to try to replay that shot. It was
one of the most timely and critical shots I've ever played. It was
a three-shot swing.''
Leonard's spare caddie Having just competed in the GTE Byron Nelson
Classic last weekend, Justin Leonard gave his regular caddie, Bob
Riefke, the day off and employed University of Texas student Blake
Smith during yesterday's shootout. The significance? Smith is the
son of Royal Oaks Country Club head pro Randy Smith, who serves as
Leonard's instructor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always use a different guy on this,'' Leonard said. ``Bob
drove home to Austin for a bit. Blake had a free day and wanted to
come out.''
Feeling comfortable Defending Colonial champion Tom Watson teamed
with Peter Jacobsen yesterday to take third place in the MasterCard
Colonial shootout, which featured an alternate-shot format.
</P>
<P>
   Though it was Watson's tee shot into the sand at No. 17 that
doomed the twosome, Watson said he felt comfortable about defending
his title.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel a little more confident about your play when you won
on the same course the year before,'' Watson said. ``You feel like
you know how to play the golf course. It is just a matter of
getting your golf swing ready to do that.''
Austin north? Had someone unknowingly strolled up to the group in
yesterday's MasterCard Colonial shootout, they might have thought
the University of Texas golf team was practicing.
</P>
<P>
   There were three bags in the event with the UT logo longhorn on
the side. The field of 12 included former Texas stars Mark Brooks,
Bob Estes and Justin Leonard, who won the shootout with Davis Love
III.
Simpson withdraws 1987 U.S. Open champion Scott Simpson withdrew
from the MasterCard Colonial field yesterday, leaving the event
with 112 players.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson has played at Colonial 16 times, his best finish coming
in 1994 when he took second, losing in a playoff to Nick Price.
This marks only the fifth time since 1979 that Simpson hasn't
played at Colonial. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
