<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2206 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEETING-VOTED-OUT-BOS     05-18 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEETING-VOTED-OUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRTHPLACE OF TOWN MEETING VOTES IN COUNCIL SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEYMOUTH, Mass. _ Voters in this cradle of direct democracy _
where the town meeting has ruled since the days of the Pilgrims _
are scrapping that folksy form of government practiced continuously
here since 1624.
</P>
<P>
   In an election whose opposing symbols were the quill pen and the
Internet, Weymouth voters have logged on to the digital age, and
will elect its first full-time mayor and an 11-member town council
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving on,'' said Wilfred Mathewson, vice chairman of
the Weymouth Historical Commission. ``It's too bad. But, here
again, it's democracy in action. I may not like it, but it's
happened. And we just have to work with it.''
</P>
<P>
   By a wide margin, Weymouth voters on Monday approved a sweeping
rewrite of the town charter that proponents say will mean more
efficient and more accountable government. Opponents argued that it
will leave local government in the handful of a few lawmakers, more
susceptible to outside influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The town meeting gave Weymouth a sense of community that we're
going to lose,'' said Peg Goudy, an opponent of the charter changes
and a member of the board of selectmen. ``I wanted to see changes
in the existing form of government without throwing the baby out
with the bathwater.''
</P>
<P>
   With Monday's vote, Weymouth becomes the 48th Massachusetts
municipality to adopt a city form of government, though it will
officially continue to call itself a town. There are 303 Bay State
communities with either an open or a representative town meeting,
according to the Massachusetts Municipal Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had it for 375 years and now it's history,'' said Frank
Fryer, Weymouth's town clerk for 23 years. ``It's the passing of an
era _ sure.''
</P>
<P>
   That era began, local historians say, in the spring of 1624 when
a ``few hardy souls'' chose local officers and gave themselves the
right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably were deciding where to bury their dead and where
they were going to plant corn _ that type of thing,'' said
Mathewson.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, in what will be one the last decisions of a Weymouth
town meeting, voters earlier this month appropriated $485,000 for
the purchase of the land where that first meeting is believed to
have been conducted.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial to the archetypal form of New England democracy is
planned for the site near the present-day Sea Street, which in 1624
was part of Wessagusset, the community renamed Weymouth in 1635.
</P>
<P>
   While that folksy, face-to-face government quickly became a
Yankee institution, symbolized in this century by artist Norman
Rockwell's sentimental tribute to citizen-lawmakers, it is
sometimes a cumbersome way of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unstructured with everybody yelling out. There was no
organization to it,'' said Ann Venturo, a five-year Weymouth
resident, who has attended town meetings and Tuesday was watching
her toddler on a swing at a local park. ``Nobody could really talk
or get their point across,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Victor S. DeSantis, associate professor of political science at
Bridgewater State College, said with Weymouth's population at
55,000, its payroll at 1,700 local employees, and its budget
approaching $100 million, change was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems and the challenges that face government at this
point exceed the average citizen's ability to walk in unprepared
and make multi-million dollar decisions with about five minutes
preparation,'' DeSantis said. ``We're at the point now where this
romanticized version of the volunteer citizen-in-action coming in
after planting season to do these things in the off-season is just
not working.''
</P>
<P>
   The change is the most dramatic for Weymouth since the town
abandoned its open town meeting in 1921 for a representative town
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The drive for revision began more than two years ago, after a
series of financial improprities that led to the conviction of an
office manager in the treasurer-collector's office and a
data-processing official who served a six month sentence for
funneling town funds to a private firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no quaint Norman Rockwell picture that's been painted
in Weymouth over the last 10 years,'' said state Senator Robert L.
Hedlund, a Weymouth Republican and a possible mayoral candidate.
``The problems have been well publicized. The reporting
relationships between the various boards have been dysfunctional.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedlund said he will make a decision soon about whether he'll
seek to become Weymouth's first mayor. William E. Ryan, chairman of
the board of selectmen, said it's likely he'll run.
</P>
<P>
   Weymouth's decision means that John P. Reilly will be the last
in a long line of town-meeting moderators, the official who
controlled _ or tried to control _ debates during often chaotic
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what will be lost will be citizen access,'' said
Reilly, who has reviewed old town-meeting minutes that document
Weymouth's decision to, among other things, send six shillings to
help pay for the soldiers under General George Washington's
command.
</P>
<P>
   ``The town meeting is a piece of history,'' said Reilly,
``that's no longer in existence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
