<SLUG> BC-INVENTORS-FRAUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SAYS 3 COMPANIES DEFRAUDED INVENTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- They answered the ads by the thousands, aspiring
inventors with their latest gizmos and gadgets, like an
air-conditioned suit and a fork that tames binge eating.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that they'd built that better mousetrap, the basement
tinkerers eagerly handed over as much as $11,000 to a Westfield
company that promised an honest appraisal of their bright ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But what they got instead, according to federal officials, was a
package of worthless patenting and marketing services that cost
34,000 people more than $60 million over a 14-year period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing successful about these companies was the
unparalled size and scope of their scam,'' US Attorney Donald K.
Stern said Tuesday in announcing the indictment of 10 people
involved in the alleged scam. ``The dreams of small inventors were
exploited by this cynical and cruel hoax.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment for mail fraud followed a four-year investigation
by US Postal inspectors and Internal Revenue Service agents, who
targeted three now-defunct invention promotion companies, two in
western Massachusetts and one in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said one of the companies, American Inventors Corp. of
Westfield, amassed more than $58 million in revenues and another,
American Institute for Reasearch and Development, also of
Westfield, collected $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   From 1982 through 1996, the companies spent millions on
advertising, seeking out inventors on radio and in national
publications such as USA Today, Reader's Digest and TV Guide. Mass
mailings encouraged inventors to call an 800 number to obtain a
free, professional assessment of their ideas.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 alone, AIC mailed out more than 100,000 information
packets to inventors encouraging them to send in their invention
ideas, according to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Once they'd done so, a salesperson would call and urge the
inventor to pay an initial fee of $169 to $289 to cover the cost of
a patent attorney's opinion letter and a market analysis. If both
were favorable, the inventor would be asked to buy a package of
patenting and marketing services, according to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The patent attorney letters were positive ``almost 100 percent
of the time,'' according to authorities, and the marketing analysis
was a ``boilerplate'' report that included no research specific to
a proposed invention. And the market report always concluded that
the invention had sales potential.
</P>
<P>
   Among those defrauded were people whose inventions included a
retractable electrical plug; a night sight for a rifle using a
flashlight, fishing line and tritium; and a bag made of recycled
jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the ``Gastronony Tube Holder,'' the ``Air
Conditioned Suit,'' the ``Thumb Hold Nail Clipper,'' the ``Binge
Buster Fork'' and the ``Hook and Loop Dickey.''
</P>
<P>
   Charged in connection with the scheme were Ronald Boulerice, 60,
of Russell, former owner and president of American Inventors
Corporation; his daughter, Laurie Boulerice, 35, of Easthampton,
former vice-president of American Inventors Corp.; John Samson, 59,
of West Hatfield, former president of American Institute for
Research and Development of Westfield; John Hoime, 49, of
Westfield, Diane Tagliavini, 46, of Westfield, patent attorney Leon
Gilden, 52, formerly of Spokane, Wash.; Jeffrey Rehbein, 33, of
Longmeadow, Scott Favreau, 35, of Springfield, and Ben Abel, 60, of
Brattleboro.
</P>
<P>
   In court Tuesday, Ronald Boulerice was held without bail pending
a detention hearing Wednesday. Authorities were searching in Oregon
for Gilden, the lawyer. The eight other defendants were released on
personal bonds, ranging from $10,000 to $100,000 by US Magistrate
Judge Kenneth P. Neiman.
</P>
<P>
   Gilden, the patent lawyer, allegedly falsely generated and filed
patent applications, some of which altered inventors' ideas without
their permission to avoid having to honor the company's promise of
a money-back guarantee if it could not obtain a patent for the
invention.
</P>
<P>
   Inventors were also falsely told that brochures describing their
inventions were distributed to manufacturers, according to
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The company told inventors that it shared in the financial risk
and made its money by sharing in royalties and through agreements
with manufacturers. In fact, according to prosecutors, its profits
came solely from up-front service fees charged to inventors,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   In a second indictment, Ronald Boulerice, his daughter, Laurie,
another daughter, Lisa Boulerice, are accused of filing false tax
returns to disguise a payroll kickback scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Boulderice also allegedly created a sham corporation,
Massachusetts Patent Services and set up an invoice scheme which
allowed him to skim $151,000 from the company and give the money to
his daughter Laurie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
