<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PARLIAMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVIDED PARLIAMENT SHADOWS BARAK VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The morning after winning a landslide victory,
Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak prayed at Jerusalem's
Western Wall, the spiritual center of Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, he laid a wreath at the grave of former Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin, now a secular shrine to Barak's mentor, who
was assassinated by a Jewish extremist opposed to his vision of
peace.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's visit Tuesday to these two sites symbolized his effort
to move forward on peace and to heal the deep rift between Israel's
secular and religious Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's voting was a mandate for Barak personally, but it
underscored a widening gulf between Israelis who envision a secular
democracy and the ultra-Orthodox who insist on a religious state.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday it was already clear that the bitter divisions will
present the first test of Barak's vows to form a strong coalition
government of unity and change, and could undermine his ability to
run the country effectively if he fails to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Both camps, the secular and the ultra-Orthodox, dramatically
increased their strength in Israel's 120-member parliament. And, at
this moment, each refuses to sit in a government with the other.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful ultra-Orthodox Shas Party, mostly first- and
second-generation North African immigrants, made gains in the
election, increasing its representation in the parliament from 10
seats to 17.
</P>
<P>
   That means Shas has only two seats fewer than the established
Likud Party which was headed by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
until his, and the party's, defeat Monday. Likud lost more than
one-third of its 32 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Shas party leader, Aryeh Deri, has stunned Israel's
establishment with his success in empowering Israel's Sephardim,
Jewish immigrants from North Africa and Arab states. Deri is a
classic political boss who has provided services for his
constituents, much as James Michael Curley did for Boston's Irish.
And like Curley, he has had trouble with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Deri was sentenced to four years in prison for
corruption, bribery and fraud. He has portrayed himself as a victim
of trumped-up charges from a judicial system controlled by the
elite intent on stopping his effort to help the Sephardic
underclass. Tuesday, he said he would step down from the leadership
of the party to ``reflect on the social and spiritual fiber'' of
the party while he awaits an appeal on his case.
</P>
<P>
   But many saw a deal in the making. Israel's TV and radio news
broadcasts were buzzing Tuesday with the possiblity that Barak may,
now that Deri has stepped down, invite Shas into his coalition,
recognizing that Shas's new power was a force to be reckoned with.
The rumors infuriated the secular left, which worked hard to elect
Barak in large part because of his promise to end the
disproportionate influence of the ultra-Orthodox in Netanyahu's
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will drive the left crazy, but bringing Shas into the
coalition cannot be ruled out,'' said Daniel Ben-Simone, who writes
on ethnic and religious politics for Israel's leading newspaper,
Ha'aretz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak knows he needs the rabbis to put a blessing on the peace
process, or he will not be able to get it through,'' said
Ben-Simone.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts were dismissive, saying it was a trial balloon by
Barak's camp. Many said they believed Barak was more likely to
bring members of the weakened Likud Party into his coalition to
build unity.
</P>
<P>
   As political analyst Zeev Chafetz put it, ``Deri is the third
rail of Israeli politics; anyone who touches him gets burned. It
just happened to Netanyahu. So Barak would be stupid to bring him
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ascendant party is called Change, whose leader Yosef
``Tommy'' Lapid, a veteran journalist, staked out a new ground in
Israeli politics by fashioning a message that was harshly
anti-religious. Not represented in the outgoing Knesset, Change won
six seats in the election.
</P>
<P>
   The far-left party Meretz won nine seats and has also bitterly
opposed the surging influence of the ultra-Orthodox in politics.
The two parties reflected a strong sentiment among secular voters.
</P>
<P>
   Change's Lapid said, ``I want to be minister of justice, there
is too much ultra-Orthodox influence on our justice system. If
Barak invites Shas into the coalition, we will stay in opposition.
. . . We will see it as a betrayal, a deep betrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Michael Melchior, who was elected to a seat in the
parliament on Barak's One Israel list of candidates, stood by Barak
Tuesday at the Western Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Melchior has become an ambassador for Barak's spirit of
inclusion for the religious in the traditionally secular Labor
party. ``One Israel wants to find a new basis for dialogue between
the religious and the secular,'' he said. ``We want to end the
religious arm twisting.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Aliza Marcus contributed to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
