<HEADER>
A2220 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOBIE-ARREST-COX     05-18 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOBIE-ARREST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Accused leader of Florida drug gang captured
 &HT;    By Joshua B. Good
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Investigators say Kenneth ``Boobie'' Williams ruled a
vast drug empire with fear.
</P>
<P>
   Police claim Williams armed members of the Boobie Boys, his gang
of cocaine dealers with AK-47 rifles, which they used to shoot down
rival dealers. In one case they killed a 5-year-old boy and the
boy's mother who were in the car with a rival drug dealer, who was
also killed, according to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Before his capture Monday in a DeKalb County, Ga. apartment,
Williams, 28, was looking to bring his murderous management style
to Atlanta, said Barry D. Golden, a deputy U.S. marshal from Miami
who spent the last 16 months hunting down Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think part of the reason he moved shop to Atlanta was we had
turned up the heat in Miami. It was too hot for him in Miami,''
Golden said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that heat was America's Most Wanted. The TV show ran
features on Williams five times.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a federal grand jury in Miami indicted Williams, along
with 14 other members of his gang, including a Miami-Dade police
detective. The 13-count indictment lists the murder of the boy and
his family and two other men as part of the Boobie Boys's pattern
of furthering their drug enterprise. Investigators say the Boobie
Boys cocaine network moved $89 million worth of cocaine from the
Bahamas and Panama to Florida, Georgia, W. Virginia, Pennsylvania,
New York, Michigan and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Williams has not been charged with any of the 35 murders
his group is suspected of carrying out, said Sgt. Tony Monheim, a
supervisor with the Miami-Dade police homicide bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feds are on their regular witch hunt,'' said J. Malik
Abdullah Frederick, a defense attorney who represented Williams
during the suspect's first appearance in federal court in Atlanta
Tuesday. ``There is nothing in the indictment that accuses or even
alleges my client has committed murder.''
</P>
<P>
   But, once he arrives in Florida, where the federal trial is to
be held, detectives plan to obtain additional charges against
Williams in connection with six murders, Monheim said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are six murders where he was the triggerman,'' Monheim
said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has not been charged with any homicides in Georgia,
either. However, DeKalb police are looking at Williams in
connection with the discovery of a blood-covered car that was left
on I-20 in March. The driver of that car was a Miami drug dealer
who was to meet Williams, said DeKalb County police homicide Sgt.
Weyman Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Police have not found a body. ``All we've got is a bloody car,''
Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Wright said he hopes federal authorities will supply
more information about the I-20 bloody car case now that Williams
is in custody.
</P>
<P>
   DeKalb police say they found two kilograms of cocaine in the
apartment where Williams was arrested Tuesday. In addition to
Williams, police also arrested Zaevon Stevens, 32.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Williams's Boobie Boys gang have been charged in
connection with 13 homicides in Miami, said Miami-Dade Police
homicide Detective Jeff Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Williams's alleged accomplices, Arthur Pless and Ben
Johnson, allegedly used a semiautomatic rifle and handgun to shoot
up the car of Otis Green, a rival drug dealer. That drive-by
slaying happened in Miami on May 17, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Green's car was his girlfriend, Alice Mae Gardner, and
her son, Michael Frazier, a 5-year-old. All three died. A fourth
person in the car survived, Monheim said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives had tried to link Williams to another massacre, this
one in Georgia, Lewis said. On Jan. 30, 1998, in Walthourville,
Georgia, south of Savannah, six people died in a backwoods crack
house. They were shot and stabbed. A seventh was found shot to
death on the nearby Fort Stewart Army reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the seven victims were from Liberty City, a neighborhood
in Miami where the Boobie Boys sold crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis said investigators were not able to link Williams to
those slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was charged with a murder in Miami in 1988. That charge
was reduced to dangerous act and Williams spent one year in prison,
Golden said.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua B. Good writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
