<HEADER>
A2221 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EAST-IS-EAST-THEATER-     05-18 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAST-IS-EAST-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EAST IS EAST, AND WEST IS AN OFF BROADWAY STAGE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Matt Wolf is the London theater critic for Variety and a regular
writer on the arts from London.  
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Ayub Khan-Din grew up in the north of England in
suburban Manchester, the eighth of 10 children born to an English
mother and an emigre father from Pakistan, who between them ran a
fish-and-chips shop.
</P>
<P>
   The nearest sibling in the lineup above him was nearly four
years older, while three years separated Khan-Din from his next
brother down the row. And so, recalled the writer and actor, who is
now 37: ``I wasn't part of the older kids or the younger kids. I
lived in my own world and spent a lot of time daydreaming. It paid
off in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   For proof, one need look no further than ``East Is East,''
Khan-Din's bittersweet, semi-autobiographical comedy about growing
up in the early 1970s in a mixed-race Anglo-Asian household, where
there were often as many as four children to a bed and the toilet
was outdoors. (Khan-Din did not have a bed to himself until he was
9.)
</P>
<P>
   ``East Is East'' was acclaimed when it opened two years ago in
London at the Royal Court Theater. On Tuesday, the play opens at
the Manhattan Theater Club as a co-production between that Off
Broadway company and the New Group.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Elliott, artistic chief of the New Group, directs a cast
headed by Jenny Sterlin as Ella Khan, the feisty mother of six (a
seventh child is referred to as having gone off to live on his
own), and Edward A. Hajj as Ella's husband, George, the prideful
father who has left a first wife in Pakistan and still clings,
sometimes ferociously, to the customs of his native country.
</P>
<P>
   The play, Khan-Din's first, which he began almost 15 years ago
as something to do when he wasn't working as an actor, has won
various awards, including best West End play from the Writers'
Guild of Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   A funny and moving low-budget film version was screened May 14
in the Directors' Fortnight section of the current Cannes Film
Festival and will be distributed by Miramax in the United States
later this year. The director, Damien O'Donnell, is a first-time
filmmaker; Linda Bassett, the play's original Ella, once again
heads the cast.
</P>
<P>
   At the time he wrote the play, Khan-Din was not long out of the
Mountview drama school in London. His mother had recently died of
Alzheimer's disease and, he said: ``I wanted a kind of memorial.
Which started me thinking about the problems we had gone through
and the area that we all grew up in'' _ working-class Salford,
where his was virtually the only Asian family. (Khan-Din's father
died in 1990 at the age of 84.)
</P>
<P>
   But whereas some memory plays (think Tennessee Williams and
Eugene O'Neill, for starters) are etched in acid and tears,
Khan-Din's mixes in compassion for a family confronting such
culturally divisive issues as arranged marriages, a son's desire to
become an artist and the circumcision of the youngest boy, Sajit,
who is as close as the play gets to a stand-in for the author.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anger is there,'' said Khan-Din, an amiable
conversationalist who is stockier now than in his leading-man days
as the pleasure-loving accountant, Sammy, in ``Sammy and Rosie Get
Laid,'' Stephen Frears' 1987 film. ``But you can get your message
across much stronger, I think, through humor and showing humanity.
That's the only way an audience is going to come in. And if you're
not going to get an audience, at the end of the day, your play is a
dead duck.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Rickson, the artistic director of the Royal Court, which was
a co-producer of ``East Is East'' with the Birmingham Repertory
Theater and the Asian theater company Tamasha, praised ``the
wonderful, chaotic human energy'' of the play.
</P>
<P>
   Khan-Din, Rickson said, ``is an innate dramatist.'' So it is no
surprise to hear that the writer is preparing two more plays for
the Court. The first, ``Last Dance at Dum Dum,'' a commercial
co-venture, starts performances on the West End on July 8.
</P>
<P>
   Sudha Bhuchar, a former actress who co-founded Tamasha 10 years
ago, was responsible for encouraging Khan-Din to pull ``East Is
East'' out of a drawer and submit it to the series of workshops and
drafts that eventually led to a full production.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Ayub was really reluctant at first,'' Ms. Bhuchar recalled.
But, she said of the play, ``I feel in a sense it transcends race;
it's about people more than anything.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Khan-Din believes the current climate for Asian work
``represents quite a change.'' Notwithstanding Hanif Kureishi's
highly regarded screenplay for the 1985 ``My Beautiful
Laundrette,'' Khan-Din said, a decade or so ago ``the only thing
you ever saw about Asians was always about the girl who didn't want
to get married, and I was usually the guy she didn't want to get
married to.''
</P>
<P>
   Khan-Din is also at work on the other Royal Court commission,
entitled ``So Soon, So Soon,'' and an original screenplay,
``Belmondo Sahib,'' a romantic comedy set in London and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   So busy is he as a writer that this onetime soap opera star has
set up a production company called Raboon Pictures with Buki
Armstrong, his Anglo-Nigerian girlfriend and business partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing gives me the thrill that I used to get when I first
started acting,'' Khan-Din said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, ``East Is East'' marks a first collaboration
between the long-established Manhattan Theater Club and the New
Group, a relatively recent addition to the city's theatrical scene.
The New Group has had its greatest successes with two plays
(``Ecstasy'' in 1995 and ``Goose-Pimples'' in 1997) by the English
writer Mike Leigh. Elliott chose and directed both.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievably original,'' Elliott said about ``East Is
East'' by telephone from New York. ``When you read it, you think,
`What is this?' And then you find out most of it is true, so that
really increases your interest. You just know where this play is
coming from _ the warmth and heart and love and rage that are in
this family.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott added that his company's success with British plays _
Stephen Bill's ``Curtains'' in 1996 included _ had happened more by
default than by design. ``When you do something a couple of
times,'' said the director, who is 36, ``and people like it, then
you start getting sent all these British plays _ and they are
good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude toward theater writing is so different over
there,'' he said. ``They still take it seriously, where our young
writers are making the transition to television and film.'' (So,
for that matter, is Elliott, who has directed his first movie, an
independent film entitled ``A Map of the World,'' for release later
this year. Based on the Jane Hamilton novel of the same name, it
stars Sigourney Weaver and Julianne Moore.)
</P>
<P>
   With ``East Is East,'' the Manhattan Theater Club may benefit
from some of the freshness and energy that have characterized the
New Group over its six years at a time when the older organization
is confronting _ and hardly uniquely _ a graying subscription
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here at MTC and everybody in New York is aware of
the problem of subscription audiences,'' said Lynne Meadow, the
artistic director of the Manhattan Theater Club. She said she had
been talking to other smaller companies, like the Drama Dept. and
the Atlantic Theater Company, about similar partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``When dealing with some of the newer groups,'' Ms. Meadow said,
``there is a support we can give that is special for them, and a
vitality, for example that Scott has, that is great for us. It's a
wonderful mixture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
