<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2225 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-ARTIST-ART-2TAK     05-18 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ARTIST-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MULTIPLEX OF A MUSEUM TURNS ON THE LIGHTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Ann Wilson Lloyd's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was on
the artist Teresita Fernandez.  
 By ANN WILSON LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH ADAMS, Mass. _ The Visavox was a proto-television device
developed here in the 1920s by the electronics wizard Frank
Sprague, founder of the Sprague Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   The appliance was more accurately a personal cinema,
synchronizing sound and image for the first time, but awkwardly
requiring you to stick your head up inside a box. Among Sprague's
more successful products before the plant closed in 1986 were
capacitors that enable radio, television and other appliances to
spring to life at the flip of a switch.
</P>
<P>
   This electronic trivia is relevant for the way it meshes with a
new installation to be introduced here next Sunday by the video
artist Tony Oursler. Titled ``Optics'' and aimed at investigating
the origins of sound and light media, Oursler's new work was
commissioned by the Williams College Museum of Art in nearby
Williamstown and the Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art,
called colloquially Mass MOCA, which is what the sprawling, former
Sprague plant has become.
</P>
<P>
   Oursler's work will have its premiere as part of Mass MOCA's
long awaited opening, also next Sunday. After more than a decade of
honing a workable formula, the institution _ five huge,
19th-century mill buildings out of 27 available at the site _ will
become the Northeast's newest, and the nation's largest,
contemporary museum and high-tech performance center.
</P>
<P>
   It will have a black-box theater that seats 650, an outdoor
cinema and courtyards filled with artists' installations and sound
works. Joseph Thompson, Mass MOCA's director, calls the place a
cultural laboratory. His ambitious, multifaceted concept would
probably do Frank Sprague proud.
</P>
<P>
   It was serendipitous timing that Oursler was chosen to help
inaugurate Mass MOCA, said Deborah Rothschild, the curator of the
Williams College Museum, where Oursler's midcareer traveling survey
is on view though Oct. 24. ``We were looking for a way to
collaborate with Mass MOCA and also for a way to allow Tony to make
new work,'' Ms. Rothschild said. ``His work is appealing on many
levels; it's lively and actively involves the audience. We thought
it would fit Mass MOCA's combined purposes well.''
</P>
<P>
   Oursler calls ``Optics'' his audiovisual treatise on a spectrum
of phenomena _ mythology, the origins of science, early distrust of
theatrical entertainments and the mysteries of sound and light.
``All these came together for me in this installation,'' he said.
``I wanted to create a loose chain of optics, mimicking, for
instance, how TV takes light and turns it into electricity, and
then into a coded signal, which is then represented to the viewer
who decodes it again culturally.''
</P>
<P>
   Though not finished as of this writing, Oursler's new work
promises to be a departure from what his audience knows best:
projections of hectoring, neurotic characters onto puppets and rag
dolls; whining, talking heads and disembodied blinking eyeballs
that simulate a psycho ward of sadly funny misfits. About two dozen
of these characteristic pieces are on view at the Williams College
Museum exhibition, where some of his earliest television
installations have also been reconstructed, revealing, in their
haphazard quirkiness, the roots of Oursler's obsessions.
</P>
<P>
   If Oursler has pulled back from television specifically, and
from examining our complicities with the electronic personas that
demonically invade our lives, his refocus on proto-media has
flushed devils out of the historical details. Part of his
installation at Mass MOCA will feature small glass Lucifers lurking
around various lighting devices and drawing attention to the odd
behavior of light.
</P>
<P>
   One little devil appears to be crawling into a utility lamp,
mischievously leading one's eye into the glare. Viewed indirectly,
the light seems to pop out the tip of his tail.
</P>
<P>
   Devils cropped up everywhere when Oursler researched early sound
and light experiments, he said. Part of his installation will
include a homemade camera obscura with a hand-ground lens. Through
it, people are rendered as small, fuzzy, moving figures that, apart
from being upside down, are akin to early television figures.
</P>
<P>
   The history of the camera obscura, traceable to the 13th
century, depicts engravings of cavorting devils in the imagery,
Oursler said: ``Somehow they connected devils with the lens
transparency. To me, that connects to Lucifer as light, and the
battle we've had with media that goes on to this day.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by early films in which moral dilemmas are often
portrayed by devils wrestling angels, he is shooting a video of two
costumed friends battling it out amid puffs of smoke and other
primitive theatrics. Other segments of Oursler's installation will
include a new video projection in which a camera interacts with
aberrant light that causes auras or coronas around figures, effects
that filmmakers try to eliminate.
</P>
<P>
   Oursler plans to remove the figures and keep the
mystical-looking flares. A digitally animated video of morphing
imagery, to be projected on arranged objects, is also under
development. ``It will be a frieze based on a kind of meta-history
of technology, almost a WPA mural based on sensory research,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The video was made in collaboration with the digital-animation
firm Kleiser-Walczak Construction Co., one of Mass MOCA's newly
installed commercial tenants, and another reason the Williams
College Museum wanted Oursler to be able to develop new work at
Mass MOCA.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
