<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2226 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      05-18 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVS OFFER TO TALK KOSOVO SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ As two captured Yugoslav soldiers were handed over to
Serb authorities Tuesday without fanfare, a senior Yugoslav
diplomat here said Yugoslavia was prepared to negotiate a
settlement to the conflict over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO officials charged that that Yugoslav authorities are
digging up mass graves of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo in a
systematic effort to destroy evidence that could be used against
them in war crimes trials. The officials emphasized that NATO's
goal is Serb capitulation, not negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the diplomatic efforts to end the fighting are
heating up on many fronts. In Belgrade, Foreign Ministry spokesman
Nebojsa Vujovic, the former charge d'affaires of the Yugoslav
embassy in Washington, made some of the most conciliatory comments
in weeks, telling reporters here that his country was ready to
negotiate an end to the fighting as long as it respected
Yugoslavia's ``territorial integrity,'' meaning that Kosovo
province, 90 percent of whose residents are ethnic Albanians, would
remain part of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Vujovic also insisted that after nearly two months of bombing,
Yugoslavia had emerged as the moral victor in what has become a
bloody standoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could a nation of 11 million be a loser when the
mightiest, the most developed countries in the world and the
mightiest military alliance is conducting a high-tech war for
almost two months?'' he asked. Vujovic said Yugoslavia considered a
basis for negotiations to be the peace plan put forward by the
Group of Eight nations, the subject of intense diplomatic efforts
in Bonn and Helsinki Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, in Washington, a State Department official said that
the United States and its NATO allies ``don't envision a
negotiation. We demand acceptance'' of the alliance's oft-stated
conditions for ending the conflict, which include creation of an
environment in which about 900,000 refugees who have fled Kosovo to
escape either Serb persecutions of NATO bombs can return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Negotiation means compromise, watering down, `you give me
this, I give you that.' We are not going to negotiate,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The key issue in any resolution is the presence of a
substantial, NATO-dominated military group in a Kosovo emptied of
Yugoslav-Serb forces. There has been no hint from the Yugoslav side
that it would accept such a military presence, while the NATO side
says that, without it, the refugees will not feel secure enough to
return.
</P>
<P>
   However, German, Italian, and Russian leaders Tuesday floated
various ideas for a bombing pause, and Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari gaining stature as a possible broker of understanding
among Russians, Americans, Yugoslavs.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Group of Eight _ seven rich industrial
nations, plus Russia _ are meeting in Bonn Wednesday as part of an
effort to forge a United Nations Security Council resolution which
could be the outline for an end to the conflict over Kosovo. The
State Department official said Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott, who has been meeting with Ahtisaari and Russian special
envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin in Helsinki for the same purpose, may
also be in Bonn Wednesday to brief the G-8 representatives of those
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Foley said NATO officials have
been ``reading signs coming out of Belgrade for several weeks now''
indicting that growing numbers of political and military leaders
there believe President Slobodan Milosevic should accept the
alliance's conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see these as signs that, indeed, the NATO air campaign is
working,'' he said. ``The diplomatic solution can come quickly'' is
Milosevic is willing to do that.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Tuesday, the 56th day of fighting:
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the vaunted Apache attack helicopters
that were to have added a unique punch to NATO's air campaign are
unlikely to see combat over Kosovo anytime soon. The risk to pilots
is simply too great, he suggested, and when the weather is good the
job can be done just as well with A-10 jets. The Pentagon
dispatched more of the A-10s to the region.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with reporters during a photo session in the Oval
Office, Clinton declined to rule out the use of ground troops in
Kosovo combat. ``I think the air war has accomplished quite a bit
and there's a lot more that it can accomplish,'' Clinton said. ``I
and everyone else has always said that we intend to see our
objectives achieved, and that we have not and will not take any
option off the table.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials in Brussels of trying to cover up evidence of
massacres of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo by ordering villagers to
dig up mass graves and bury the bodies separately. David Scheffer,
a US ambassador-at-large for war crimes, also said there is
increasing evidence that Serbs have used ethnic Albanians during
the conflict as human shields. Military sources predicted that
Milosevic might soon declare a cease-fire in hope of winning a
bombing pause, but they said NATO would dismiss such a move as a
trick.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's diplomatic activity occurred against the backdrop of a
subdued prisoner release. Two Yugoslav soldiers who were captured
in separate incidents last month by the rebel Kosovo Liberation
Army were released to Yugoslav authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoners, who were passed by the KLA to the Albanian
government and eventually to the US Army, had been held at the US
base at Mannheim, Germany. They were moved Tuesday to Budapest, the
Hungarian capital, where they were turned over to officials from
the International Committee of the Red Cross. They were then driven
by Red Cross officials to the Yugoslav border.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at Roeszke, the Hungarian side of the border crossing
where the soliders were handed over to Yugoslav authorities, Red
Cross spokeswoman Nadya Kebir said the two soldiers appeared to
have been well-treated during their detention. They were named as
Boban Milen Kovic and Sesko Tairovic, both privates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were in good condition,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Red Cross officials interviewed the two soldiers
Tuesday ``to make sure they really wanted to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, when Defense Secretary William Cohen first
disclosed that President Clinton had asked him to review releasing
the two Yugoslav soldiers, some US officials had said that one of
the soldiers was reluctant to return to Yugoslavia, apparently
because his Albanian captors had videotaped him accusing fellow
soldiers of engaging in summary executions and the rape of
refugees. The propaganda tape was released to Western news outlets,
including the BBC.
</P>
<P>
   Kebir sidestepped questions about one of the soldier's supposed
reservations, saying only that Red Cross officials were convinced
that the two soldiers genuinely wanted to return to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the attention paid here by the
government-controlled media to the release more than three weeks
ago of three US soldiers who had been captured while on patrol
along the Macedonia-Serbia border, Tuesday's release of the
Yugoslav soldiers barely merited a mention on Serbian television
Tuesday night. US officials, meanwhile, insisted that the release
of the two Yugoslav soldiers was not a quid pro quo for the release
of the US servicemen, which was organized by Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Cullen reported from Belgrade; Radin from Washington. Wire service
material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
