<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2227 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-ARTIST-ART-2NDT     05-18 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ARTIST-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NORTH ADAMS, Mass.: Mass MOCA.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kleiser-Walczak, formerly based in California, produced the
special effects for the 3-D opera ``Monsters of Grace,'' by Philip
Glass and Robert Wilson, which will be presented at Mass MOCA on
July 17. (The full summer programming is available on the Internet
at www.massmoca.org.)
</P>
<P>
   Down the vast hallways from Oursler's new piece are newly
installed monumental works, few of them ever likely to fit into
conventional museums. Robert Rauschenberg's marathon painting,
``1/4 Mile or 2 Furlong Piece'' (1984-1999), lent by the artist,
has its own gallery the length of a football field. Large, rarely
seen works by John Chamberlain, Joseph Beuys, Bruce Nauman, James
Rosenquist, Mario Merz, Dan Flavin and Carl Andre, are also on loan
for various tenures from several institutions.
</P>
<P>
   These galleries represent what remains of Mass MOCA's original
plan to be a home for oversize contemporary art that Thomas Krens
envisioned here back in 1985. Krens, who became director of the
Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, headed the Williams College Museum of
Art at the time.
</P>
<P>
   As Mass MOCA's mission evolved over the years, the Guggenheim's
role gradually diminished. It is now simply one of several lenders
of large artworks, said Thompson, who is also an alumnus of the
Williams College Museum.
</P>
<P>
   These rooms, large enough to swallow up art leviathans, are
themselves a grand spectacle finessed back from near ruin by the
architectural firm Bruner/Cott &AMP; Associates of Cambridge, Mass.
Practicing minimal intervention, their efforts, in one vast
gallery, include a center row of old wooden support posts chopped
into stubs left hanging from the ceiling like a spine.
</P>
<P>
   These are spanned by interlacing steel cables creating a
graceful trussed ceiling. Throughout, a century-old patina of paint
and fugitive markings denote former rooms, floor levels, doors and
windows that bear elegant witness to the past. If romance can be
mined from America's industrial age, the mother lode is here.
</P>
<P>
   Around 100,000 square feet of space will eventually be leased to
compatible commercial tenants, like Kleiser-Walczak, generating up
to $1.2 million a year, Thompson said, to offset operating costs.
Revenues from the performances will help, though the cultural
economy here is seasonal, and Mass MOCA's avant-garde programming
unproven as a draw.
</P>
<P>
   Additional visual art that Thompson has commissioned for Mass
MOCA is, like Oursler's, in keeping with the museum's revised
mission as a place for experimental new media and
cross-disciplinary investigations. ``Ghost Catching,'' a video
installation of images of the dancer Bill T. Jones digitally
multiplied into an ensemble is a prime example.
</P>
<P>
   Others are off site and temporary, like billboards by Sue Coe,
Gary Simmons and Leon Golub, placed along nearby highways; some
will become part of Mass MOCA's somewhat ephemeral collection.
</P>
<P>
   These include two sound pieces from previous exhibitions that
already exist and a new work, ``Music for a Quarry,'' by Walter
Fahndrich, in an abandoned marble works outside town. Others are
``The Visitations,'' an installation by Ron Kuivila in an
unrenovated building that was left with dropped tools and rusting
equipment still in place, and ``Tree Logic,'' a large outdoor piece
by Natalie Jeremijenko sure to make arborists cringe. Six trees
have been strung up in high rigging, roots skyward in containers,
where they are expected to pit gravity against phototropic forces.
</P>
<P>
   Back up in Oursler's galleries, he tells the tale of the
so-called ``lightning room'' during Sprague's occupation of the
site. It was where electronic components were jolted by
thunderbolts to see how they stood up. Residents of North Adams
recall seeing flashes through the lightning room's glass-block wall
as they drove past, invoking a mad-scientist scenario that the
artist relishes. ``This was a room I couldn't refuse,'' Oursler
says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
