A2229 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTORIST-SHOT-COX     05-18 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTORIST-SHOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Man shot on interstate dies at hospital
 &HT;    By Will Anderson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMYRNA, Ga. _ Noe Soto Diaz was found unconscious inside his
wrecked car on Interstate 75 early Tuesday, shot once in the face
and once in the chest. He died at 4:05 a.m. after being taken to
Grady Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Police called for the public's help in locating a gold or
cream-colored vehicle, possibly a compact car.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators think the victim's bullet-riddled 1993 black Honda
Civic scraped the vehicle before it swerved onto the shoulder of
the southbound lanes near Windy Hill Road and struck a retaining
wall around 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some physical evidence to indicate there could have
been a collision,'' said Cobb County police Lt. George Hatfield,
who is in charge of the department's traffic enforcement unit.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb County police will be camped along I-75 again today _ after
the morning rush hour _ to reconstruct what they think happened.
They will be relying on measurements marked with spray paint on
Tuesday, as well as using a computer program that provides a model
of how the wreck may have occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives Tuesday night still did not know if the shooting was
a random act of violence, a case of extreme road rage or a vendetta
carried out against the young Hispanic driver.
</P>
<P>
   More than 12 hours after the accident scene caused gridlock on
the interstate, police located a cousin of Diaz who identified him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were more than two forms of identification with
different names on them, in addition to the registration of the
car,'' said Cobb police spokesman Dana Pierce. ``He did not own the
car, and the car was not reported stolen.''
</P>
<P>
   Police found Diaz after they received a 911 call at 12:56 a.m.
reporting a car broken down in the interstate's far right lane.
</P>
<P>
   After an initial inspection of the crime scene in the dark,
police returned to the area during daylight hours to search for
evidence. They closed the far right lane for about 45 minutes and a
second lane for another 15 minutes, which was enough to clog the
interstate and cause a delay for rushhour commuters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like to got out there and block traffic,'' said Cobb
police Lt. George Hatfield, who is in charge of the department's
traffic enforcement unit. ``But if you wait a long time, with the
volume of traffic, you're going to lose evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   It paid off when investigators found bullet casings strewn on
the pavement and evidence that another vehicle _ possibly the
killer's _ had collided with the victim's car.
</P>
<P>
   Several shots were fired into the driver's side of the vehicle
from outside the car, according to Cobb police spokesman Andrew
Marchetta.
</P>
<P>
   No drugs or weapons were found inside the Honda, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police declined to speculate on the motive of the slaying, but
Hatfield said it would an extemely unusual case if the killer
turned out to be an enraged driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just from my perspective, it doesn't look like road rage,''
Hatfield said. ``But there's some evidence it could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Police are asking anyone in the area of I-75 southbound between
the South Marietta Parkway and Windy Hill Road (north of Atlanta)
between midnight and 1 a.m. Tuesday to contact police at
770-499-3945.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
