<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELL'S EARNINGS RISE BY 42 PERCENT IN 1ST QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dell Computer Corp. posted first-quarter earnings Tuesday that
matched analysts' estimates, but the results disappointed some
investors.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended April 30, Dell reported earnings of $434
million, or 16 cents a diluted share, up 42 percent from $305
million, or 11 cents a share, in the period a year earlier. Revenue
rose 41 percent, to $5.54 billion from $3.92 billion. Per-share
figures reflect a reduction in shares outstanding because of stock
buybacks.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expected Dell to earn 16 cents a share, according to
First Call Corp., which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Before Dell reported its results, its shares closed at $44.0625,
up 81.25 cents, in NASDAQ trading. But in after-hours trading, they
sank as low as $41.375. Some analysts expected Dell to exceed
estimates after Hewlett-Packard Co. reported earnings Monday that
beat Wall Street estimates in large part because of strong sales of
personal computers. Dell shares are down 20 percent from their
52-week high of $55.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that drop came from a selloff prompted by fourth-quarter
revenue growth that slowed from historically high levels. In the
first quarter, Dell's revenue growth rate of 41 percent met
analysts' expectations and represented a partial recovery from the
38 percent in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But Daniel Kunstler, an analyst with J.P. Morgan, said the sales
growth appeared to have come at a price. ``They squeaked through
with the revenue growth the Street wanted and hit the earnings
number, but gross margins look spooky,'' he said, noting that
profit margin had slipped to 21.5 percent in the quarter from 22.5
percent in the fourth quarter. ``It looks like average selling
prices are coming down, or pricing pressure was up.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell vice chairman Kevin Rollins said in a telephone interview
that the company had taken the gross margin number down in order to
be more aggressive in the market. Gross margin is off from the
fourth quarter ``and that is what we signaled we would do last
quarter,'' he said. ``We think our financial model is now back in
line with what it should be,'' he said, noting that net income as a
percentage of revenue was 7.8 percent, equal to the figure in the
quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   While Dell's growth rate is down substantially from the average
of 56 percent it had attained in the previous eight quarters, the
company still led its major competitors in unit, revenue and profit
growth during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Dell cited a report by International Data Corp. showing that it
had advanced to the No. 2 position in worldwide market share,
behind Compaq Computer, and that the company's business grew at
about two-and-a-half times the estimated industry rate.
</P>
<P>
   As always, Dell officials credited the strength of their direct
sales model, in which the company bypasses distributors and dealers
and builds each computer to order. Because the company holds very
little inventory, it takes advantage of lower component costs, and
is always selling a fresher product, which can command a higher
profit margin. Dell said sales from its Web site exceeded $18
million a day during the quarter, accounting for 30 percent of
overall revenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
