<SLUG> BC-LOEHMANN-BANKRUPTCY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOUNT RETAIL CHAIN LOEHMANN'S FILES FOR CHAPTER 11 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Loehmann's Inc., the New York-based retailer that offers
designer apparel at bargain prices, filed for bankruptcy protection
Tuesday in Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
   The long-troubled chain, whose first store opened in 1920, said
it had assets of $188.7 million and liabilities of $184.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, chairman and chief executive Robert
Friedman said, ``The decision to file for Chapter 11, while
difficult, represents the most viable option for restructuring our
company.''
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy filing had been anticipated for several reasons.
On Monday, the retailer failed to make a $5.5 million interest
payment to creditors. In addition, Loehmann's lost more than $5
million last year on sales of $432 million; the retailer's chief
financial officer, Dennis Hernreich, resigned abruptly on April 30
without explanation; on May 12, Moody's Investors Service Inc.
downgraded its debt to a status lower than junk, and at about the
same time many of the company's vendors stopped shipping to
Loehmann's.
</P>
<P>
   Loehmann's has been faced with increasing competition for its
off-price niche of the market. Department stores, under pressure to
compete with discounters and outlet malls, have increasingly been
offering shoppers deep discounts on seasonal merchandise. And
Loehmann's has been losing out on designer leftovers to other
larger off-price merchants.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, TJX Co., owner of both T.J. Maxx and Marshall's,
which did $8 billion in sales last year, has been aggressively
scooping up the best of the offerings from name houses like Ralph
Lauren and Donna Karan.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman said the filing would not have an impact on the
day-to-day operations of its 69 stores. It has nine stores in New
York state, including four in New York City; six stores in New
Jersey, and two in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman, however, said, it was ``too early to say
what will happen'' to either the stores or Loehmann's 2,500
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Loehmann's announced that it had secured $75 million of
debtor-in-possession financing from Congress Financial Corp.,
subject to approval from the bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the increasing competitive environment, however, analysts
and stockholders say Loehmann's suffered from repeated management
missteps. Up until 1997, the Bronx-based chain was expanding both
the number of stores it operated as well as the size of the stores.
The Manhattan flagship store on lower Seventh Avenue, for example,
is nearly 60,000 square feet, almost four times the size of the
chain's first stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems as if management never grasped the seriousness of the
problems, or even their very nature,'' said Kurt Barnard, president
of Barnard's Retail Trend Report.
</P>
<P>
   The company was founded in 1920 by Frieda Loehmann, who
patrolled the fashion district and then resold her finds in a small
store on Bedford Avenue in Brooklyn. After her death in 1962, her
son, Charles, opened a second store on Fordham Road in the Bronx
and headed the company as it expanded. It went public in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   After numerous changes in ownership, Loehmann's Inc. went public
for a second time in May 1996 at $17 a share. At first, its brand
name propelled its stock to a strong run on Wall Street _ it went
as high as $30.25 in November of that year. But soon after, sales
lagged and the stock fell. It closed at 93.75 cents Monday on
NASDAQ.
</P>
<P>
   Loehmann's biggest creditors are the holders of notes that
Loehmann's sold in 1997 for a total of $95 million; Fleet Financial
Services, , which is owed $7.85 million, and CIT Commercial, which
is owed $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The creditors also include such well-known fashion names as
Donna Karan, Jones Apparel Group, Kasper ASL Ltd., Calvin Klein and
Harve Benard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
