</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-IMMIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG TRIES TO LIMIT COURT RULING ON RESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Desperate to stem a possible flood of migrants from
mainland China, Hong Kong said Tuesday that it would ask the
Chinese government to overturn, in effect, a court ruling that
granted Hong Kong residency to more than a million people.
</P>
<P>
   The request, to reinterpret the provisions of the Hong Kong
constitution that were the basis of the ruling, is tantamount to
asking Beijing to overrule Hong Kong's highest court. The move has
touched off a storm of protest from legal experts and pro-democracy
politicians here. They say it will sabotage the rule of law in the
former British colony.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Hong Kong, Tung Chee-hwa, said Tuesday
that he had no choice but to appeal to China to resolve a growing
immigration crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us would like happy family reunions,'' Tung said at a
news conference. ``Who wouldn't? But what we face is a problem of
unplanned population growth, which Hong Kong, as a society, will be
unable to bear.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Chinese government grants the request, officials here
estimate that the number of mainland Chinese eligible for residency
would drop, to less than 200,000 from 1.67 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tung has warned that allowing 1.6 million people into Hong Kong
would impose a calamitous burden on the enclave, which has 6.8
million people, overcrowding schools and hospitals, swelling
unemployment, lowering living standards and costing the government
$91 billion in additional capital spending.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said that in seeking to quell an immigration crisis, the
government had instead caused a legal crisis. By appealing to
Beijing, they said, Hong Kong was subverting the authority of its
courts and jeopardizing its role as a citadel of Western-style
legal practices within China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government lost in court,'' said Margaret Ng, a lawyer and
member of the Legislature. ``So it went off to Beijing to use
political means to overturn the ruling. It shows a government that
refuses to be bound by laws as interpreted by the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Tung denied that Hong Kong was undermining its courts. He said
the National People's Congress in China had the right to
reinterpret provisions of the Hong Kong constitution, the Basic
Law. But he said such a tool should be used sparingly, and only in
extraordinary situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have looked at all the options, and this seems to be the
only way out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem deepened in January, when the Court of Final Appeal
granted residency to children born in mainland China who have at
least one parent who lives in Hong Kong. The court said the right
of residency applied to children regardless of whether the parent
was a Hong Kong resident before or after their births.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was attacked almost immediately. Chinese officials
said the court seemed to be asserting authority over that of the
central government in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure, the court issued an extraordinary clarification
that affirmed that China still had the ultimate legal authority.
</P>
<P>
   But that left the substance of the ruling intact. At first, the
Hong Kong government said it was not interested in challenging the
substance. Yet officials soon announced that 1.6 million mainland
Chinese migrants could pour across the border.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Hong Kong government say it exaggerated the
potential numbers and economic effects in a campaign to scare the
public and drum up support for its legal appeal to China.
</P>
<P>
   For mainland Chinese to obtain residency in Hong Kong, they
would have to show proof of parentage. That would be difficult for
the 1.1 million illegitimate children included in the Hong Kong
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   If the government goal was to generate support, it was
remarkably successful. Nearly 80 percent of Hong Kong residents
support reducing the number of potential migrants, even if it means
challenging the ruling, said a poll by the Hong Kong Policy
Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   One option for resolving the crisis would be for China to amend
the Hong Kong constitution. But Chinese officials are loath to
change the document, which they largely drafted.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, an amendment would have wait at least until the
National People's Congress holds its next annual meeting in March.
Tung said Hong Kong could not afford to wait that long.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the government said the critics were not adjusting
to the realities of being part of a country with a legal system
sharply different to the English common-law system that prevails in
Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
