<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD-PROOF HANDGUN LOCKS GET BIPARTISAN BACKING IN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an act that seemed unlikely before last month's
school shooting in Colorado, Senate Republicans Tuesday joined
Democrats in approving a plan to require child safety locks on
newly purchased handguns.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, House Speaker Dennis Hastert said he backed a
Democratic plan long championed by Senator Edward M. Kennedy and
others to raise the minimum age for gun purchasers to 21 from 18.
While licensed gun dealers already are prohibited from selling to
people under the age of 21, unlicensed sellers such as private
individuals and gun-show dealers face no such prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   These two actions, combined with more gun control votes expected
Wednesday, signaled that the gun lobby has lost considerable clout
in the wake of a series of shootings by students at schools across
the country, most recently at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, for example, a similar Senate proposal requiring gun
safety locks received only 39 votes and was rejected by all but
three Republicans. Tuesday, the Senate voted 78-20 for an amendment
to the juvenile crime bill to require that new handguns be sold
either with a safety lock or case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows unquestionably that the horror of what took place in
Littleton has had its effect,'' said Senator John Chafee, the Rhode
Island Republican who co-sponsored the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   To gain support for the measure, sponsors included limited
liability protections to gun owners who lock their guns. But the
sponsors played down the liability provision, noting that gun
owners are not liable under current law. Nonetheless, the liability
provision served a political purpose, giving many Republicans a
reason to switch from last year's position and back the measure,
sponsors said.
</P>
<P>
   The two Massachusetts senators, Kennedy and Senator John F.
Kerry, supported the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association, which opposed last year's
measure on gun safety locks, dropped its opposition Tuesday, saying
the amendment had been adequately modified with the liability
provision. ``We did not oppose it,'' said NRA spokesman Bill
Powers. Asked if the Littleton shooting had changed the dynamic on
gun control, he said, ``Ask the senators.''
</P>
<P>
   During hours of emotional debate Tuesday, senators favoring gun
control cited cases in which children have used a gun and
accidentally killed themselves or someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just last weekend, a 7-year-old boy named Brian Welch killed
himself accidentally with a gun he found in his father's drawer,''
said Senator Herb Kohl, the Wisconsin Democrat who introduced the
safety-locks amendment. ``What do we say to Brian's family if we
cannot take steps as reasonable as this one?''
</P>
<P>
   Kohl attributed passage of the measure to the shooting at
Columbine High School in which two students killed 13 people before
killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that, in the wake of Littleton, both sides have
grown up a bit: Democrats in finally acknowledging that culture may
have something to do with juvenile violence today, and Republicans
in finally endorsing reasonable measures to take handguns out of
the hands of kids who shouldn't have them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure does have loopholes, however. It applies only to
handguns and only to those sold after the legislation would be
signed into law. In addition, it does not require purchasers to
keep the safety device on the guns, although they are encouraged to
do so. The legislation left it up to gun manufacturers to design
the safety devices.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the measure is a major step beyond current law, which
requires only the option for gun purchasers to get a safety lock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so long overdue it is ludicrous,'' said Naomi Paiss,
spokeswoman for Handgun Control. But, she said, ``it would have
been better if it included long guns.'' She said her organization's
long-term goal is to make guns themselves childproof, noting that
everything from aspirin bottles to teddy bears are regulated for
child safety, ``while guns are immune from that.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood began to shift against the gun lobby last Wednesday,
after Senate Republicans faced criticism for rejecting a proposal
requiring background checks on people buying weapons at gun shows.
Republicans reversed themselves the following day.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, in an interview Tuesday with the Associated Press,
thrust himself into the gun debate by backing a requirement for gun
purchasers to be 21 years old and backing a measure to mandate
background checks at gun shows, which is already required at retail
establishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just saying 21 is basically a standard of adulthood, and
there's probably a uniformity that fits there,'' Hastert said.
``You have kids who can't buy alcohol till they're 21 years of age,
but they can go out and buy a handgun, and I believe there needs to
be some conformity to those types of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law already prevents licensed gun dealers from selling
to those under 21, but Hastert went further than that because
unlicensed gun sellers are allowed to sell to those under 21. For
example, a person under 21 currently can buy a gun from a friend or
private seller at a gun show.
</P>
<P>
   Handgun Control's Paiss said raising the purchase age to 21
would be a significant move because 18- and 19-year-olds commit
more violent crime than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton promptly seized upon Hasert's statement,
applauding the speaker's effort to ``raise the age of handgun
ownership from 18 to 21.'' However, Hastert spokesman John Feehery
said the speaker's comment applied only to gun sales, not gun
possession.
</P>
<P>
   In other votes Tuesday, the Senate agreed to provisions that
would stiffen penalties for gang members who commit offenses and
for wearing body armor while committing a crime.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is scheduled Wednesday to consider other gun-control
amendments and could vote on final passage of the overriding
juvenile crime bill. If it passes, the bill then goes to the House
for consideration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
