<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2244 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICHARD-NELSON-THEATE     05-18 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICHARD-NELSON-THEATER-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF THE ENGLISH IN ENGLAND, BY AN AMERICAN FOR AMERICANS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Displacement and exile are crucial issues to the
American dramatist Richard Nelson, whose plays, perhaps not
coincidentally, usually have their premieres in England, though
their author lives along the Hudson River, north of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has written about American academics in Britain in his
play ``Some Americans Abroad'' and about Britons living in America
in the more recent ``New England.'' Both originated with the Royal
Shakespeare Company, his de facto home, which has presented nine of
his plays. (``Some Americans Abroad'' was seen at Lincoln Center in
1990 and ``New England'' at the Manhattan Theater Club in 1995.)
</P>
<P>
   But ``Goodnight Children Everywhere,'' his latest play, opening
Off Broadway on Wednesday at Playwrights Horizons, marks the first
time that Nelson has written a work wholly about the English and
set in England _ in a South London apartment, to be exact, in the
late spring of 1945, near the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely a risk,'' said the author, 48, by telephone
from New York one recent morning. ``I knew I was touching on very
sensitive self-myths of the English personality, as defined by
World War II, since there was probably no more self-defining time
for the British.'' The play received mixed reviews in its Royal
Shakespeare debut in Stratford-on-Avon in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Among those much taken with it was Trevor Nunn, artistic
director of the Royal National Theater, who was head of the Royal
Shakespeare when Nelson first began working there more than a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that audiences would pretty much swear that it was
written by an English writer simply because its idiom is so
unforced and light and isn't thrown away,'' Nunn said, praising
Nelson's gift for ``writing in shades'' rather than black and
white.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, said Nelson, who is directing the new production,
preview audiences are perceiving it ``as much more about people and
children than about Englishness.'' The title is taken from a
popular wartime song that itself echoes a well-known closing line
used during the war by a BBC radio announcer, Derek McCulloch, on a
program called ``Children's Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   To English audiences, then, the phrase ``Goodnight Children
Everywhere'' evokes a nostalgia for the period while at the same
time hinting at the requiem for childhood that the play in part
describes.
</P>
<P>
   The story involves the return of a family's youngest child,
Peter, 17, who was sent to Canada for six years for safety during
the war. He is reunited with his three sisters in their parents'
apartment, the parents having died during his absence.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the sisters spent part of their own childhoods in the
countryside, away from the bombs falling on London. One, now
pregnant, is married to a doctor (played by Jon De Vries), whose
child by a former wife has died. The dislocation of individuals by
events beyond their control is another underlying theme of the
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my continued portrayals of people who are outsiders and
exiles and out of time and out of place,'' Nelson said, ``stories
of adolescence are very much part of that: who feels more out of
time and out of place than an adolescent?''
</P>
<P>
   The New York company includes Chris Stafford as the sexually
curious Peter, who must tellingly function as boy, brother and man
all at once, and Heather Goldenhersh, Kali Rocha and Robin Weigert
as the siblings who echo a trio of provincial Russian sisters in a
play written a century ago. If Chekhov overtly flavors ``Goodnight
Children Everywhere,'' so, too, does Strindberg, whom Nelson has
also adapted.
</P>
<P>
   It is Strindberg whom Nelson mentions in explaining an
incestuous encounter in the play. ``The multiplicity of motivation
for every action is indicative of our time,'` he said, paraphrasing
Strindberg, who was referring to the 1880s. ``But I think the same
is very true for us. To look for one clear motivation is the wrong
way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for the first time, Nelson said, he favors a drama built on
ambiguity and complexity that doesn't wear its theme on its sleeve.
Whatever other resonances ``Goodnight Children Everywhere'' offers,
Nelson said, it presents a synopsis of a life. ``In one sense,'' he
said, ``it's about a boy who goes through his entire adolescence in
two and a half days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
