<SLUG> BC-MA-AMBULANCES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT SEEKS DAMAGES FROM FORD IN AMBULANCE BREAKDOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a, f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The stories are the same from Boston to the Berkshires
and all the way south to Nantucket: Ford ambulances constantly
breaking down without warning, stranding patients and frustrating
emergency workers.
</P>
<P>
   Now some 100 ambulance companies and municipalities throughout
Massachusetts have banded together to urge a federal judge to
accept their class-action suit against Ford Motor Co., the nation's
largest manufacturer of vehicles built for use as ambulances.
</P>
<P>
   They claim that drive belts on the 1992, 1993 and 1994 Econoline
and F-Series ambulances frequently flew off the vehicles, yet Ford
ignored the problem for years.
</P>
<P>
   They also claim transmissions on the ambulances are defective,
requiring premature and frequent replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time the belt broke when the ambulance was on a highway
and there was a heart-attack patient on board,'' Chris Sampson,
president of the Swansea Ambulance Corp., wrote in a court document
detailing numerous problems with the nonprofit group's 1992 Ford
F350 ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown forced the patient to wait by the side of the road
for 15 minutes until another ambulance arrived, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Ford say the company acknowledged a problem with
the accessory drive-belt on some of its ambulances in 1996,
offering to replace the part and reimburse owners for the cost of
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's lawyers insist there is no evidence of a ``common
defect'' in the ambulances and blame the chronic transmission
problems on ambulance companies for ``failure to properly care for
and repair their vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   But Weston Fire Chief John Thorburn says the department's 1992
Ford Econoline Ambulance is ``the most unreliable ambulance'' he's
seen in his 38 years on the job.
</P>
<P>
   And Boston officials say they finally switched from Ford to
Chevrolet after constant problems and costly repairs to the city's
Ford ambulances.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of small towns, saying they don't have the resources to
take on the Detroit giant, are asking the court to allow them to
sign onto a suit filed against Ford several years ago by three
family-owned ambulance companies _ Professional Ambulance and
Oxygen Service in Cambridge, Action Ambulance Service in Stoneham
and Fallon Service in Milton.
</P>
<P>
   Those companies are seeking hundreds of thousands of dollars in
repair costs, transmission replacements and lost revenue from Ford
in a suit filed in US District Court in Boston that alleges breach
of warranty and unfair and deceptive practices.
</P>
<P>
   During a hearing Monday in Boston before US District Judge
George A. O'Toole Jr., Attorney Lynn E. Parseghian, of the
Washington, D.C. firm of O'Melveny &AMP; Myers, which represents Ford,
argued that a class-action suit would ``create a monster.''
</P>
<P>
   Parseghian said a class-action trial would embroil the court in
a ``morass of individual issues,'' involving hundreds of vehicles
and thousands of complaints.
</P>
<P>
   But Attorney Joanne D'Alcomo, of the Boston law firm of
Schneider, Reilly, Zabin &AMP; Costello, who represents the ambulance
companies, said it would be a burden to force small towns that own
one ambulance to sue Ford individually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say that Ford knowingly sent out these vehicles, knowing
they were going to break down, knowing patients would be inside,''
D'Alcomo said.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alcomo urged the judge to grant class certification to anyone
who bought a 1992, 1993, or 1994 Ford Econoline or F-Series van,
equipped with an ambulance preparation package, a 7.3-liter diesel
engine and a E40D transmission.
</P>
<P>
   O'Toole has taken the matter under advisement.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is one of just a few manufacturers that builds chassis,
incomplete vans and trucks containing an engine and wheel base,
which are converted to ambulances by independent companies.
</P>
<P>
   The suit focuses on Ford-manufactured parts: a serpentine belt
drive and transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ford acknowledged problems with the serpentine belt in
1996, D'Alcomo said the company knew about them years earlier but
continued to sell ambulances with the defective belts. Ford denies
any common problem with its transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman Fire Chief Timothy P. Travers said the town's only
ambulance, a 1994 Ford Econoline van, had driven only 13,000 miles
when its transmission needed to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transmission has operated so roughly because of shifting
problems that patients riding in the ambulance complained of
discomfort,'' Travers wrote in court documents.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that Ford has denied the existence of a problem
in the ambulance transmissions, D'Alcomo said Ford ``leaped into
action'' when a large armored truck company with a fleet of 500
Ford trucks complained about the same transmission.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alcomo said documents show that Ford gave the armored truck
company 10 free transmissions, then split the cost of replacing
other transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the ambulance industry did capture Ford's attention more
than a decade ago. In 1987, Ford recalled 22,000 ambulances to
correct safety-related fuel problems that caused at least two dozen
fires and 15 injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
