<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AIMS TO RESTART MIDEAST PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House lost little time Tuesday in trying
to capitalize on Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak's victory
to invigorate stalled Middle East peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who congratulated Barak by phone Monday
night, spoke Tuesday to three other key players: King Abdullah of
Jordan, President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters before a long-scheduled meeting in the
White House with Abdullah, Clinton said the ``road map'' was laid
out for implementing accords between Israel and the Palestinians
that were reached at the Wye River Plantation in Maryland last
October, as well as for ``final status'' talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're certainly both willing to do it,'' Clinton said
of his and Barak's intentions to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they expected the State
Department's chief Middle East negotiator, Dennis Ross, to visit
the region soon. But they said it had not yet been decided whether
Ross would wait until Barak had finished forming his government _ a
process that could take weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was a new mood of promise, officials cautioned
that expectations should not get out of hand just because Barak is
perceived to be more receptive toward reaching a final agreement
with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Fundamental differences remain between Israel and the
Palestinians on the vital issues of security relations between
Israel and the Palestinians, the status of Jerusalem and the return
of Palestinian refugees, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should expect this can be solved overnight,'' a White
House official said. ``Our expectations should not be similar to
the size of Barak's landslide. But we do feel a renewed sense of
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of this hope came from the fact that with Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's defeat, there was suddenly more contact
between leaders in the region, the official said. For example,
Barak spoke Tuesday with both Arafat and Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Abdullah was outspoken in his enthusiasm for
Barak. ``We're very, very optimistic,'' he said. ``We see eye to
eye on many issues and we're very optimistic of taking the peace
process forward.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed fairly clear, officials said, that once Barak forms a
government, he will be able to finish carrying out the Wye
agreements that Netanyahu only partially fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   Under that accord, Israel agreed to withdraw from 13 percent
more of the West Bank in three phases over a 12-week period.
Netanyahu withdrew from 2 percent before his government collapsed
and he called elections last December.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Arafat in April, Clinton called on Israel and the
Palestinians to complete final status talks within a year.
</P>
<P>
   He also said in the letter that he would convene a new set of
peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians within six months
after the Israeli elections.
</P>
<P>
   The new peace talks, aimed at kick-starting the negotiations
over the final-status questions, would be in Washington and would
most likely be called much sooner than in six months, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   There were some suggestions Tuesday among analysts outside the
administration that the talks Clinton outlined in his letter might
be broadened to include Jordan and Egypt. Mubarak is scheduled to
meet with Clinton at the White House on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Another theme that has re-emerged with Barak's victory is the
administration's goal _ and Barak's desire _ to restart talks
between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Syria wants Israel to give back the Golan Heights, which were
captured in the 1967 war. Israel wants Syria, which effectively
controls the Lebanese government, to stop backing the Hezbollah
forces that attack Israeli soldiers in the southern part of
Lebanon, which Israel occupies. Barak announced during his election
campaign that, if he was elected, he would start negotiations to
withdraw the Israeli soldiers from Lebanon within the next year.
</P>
<P>
   For Barak to tackle two sets of negotiations _ with the
Palestinians and with the Syrians _ may prove to be overly
ambitious, even though the administration is encouraging such a
move, Middle East experts said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Singer, who was a negotiator for the Israelis on the Oslo
accords, the initial peace agreement with the Palestinians, and is
now a lawyer in Washington, said Tuesday that it had proved
difficult for the the late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin to
pursue separate negotiations with the Syrians and the Palestinians.
He predicted that it would prove difficult for Barak, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak will want to do both,'' Singer said. ``But it is
impossible to do both, to make the Israeli government understand
two such important peace treaties. The collective Israeli belly
cannot digest both.''
</P>
<P>
   On the negotiations with the Palestinians, the administration's
goal of settling the major questions in one year, even with Barak
as prime minister, may be unrealistic, said Robert Satloff, the
executive director of the Washington Institute for Near East
Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Satloff, who has spent the last three months in Israel, said
that the ``atmospherics'' for negotiations with Arafat would
improve with Barak at the table but that in some respects Barak is
tougher than Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a more credible negotiating partner, but Arafat knows
that Barak is no dove,'' Satloff said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
