<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2248 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-REVIEW19-COX     05-18 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-REVIEW19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stunning effects, new themes redeem flaws in ``Star Wars:
Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace''
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The long wait to return to a galaxy far, far away ends at 12:01
a.m. Wednesday, with the release of the first new Star Wars film in
16 years. The highly anticipated first prequel to George Lucas'
original space-opera trilogy can't possibly live up to astronomical
fan expectations and at times falls far short. But once the mythic
sci-fi adventure film blasts off for the familiar desert planet of
Tatooine, ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' becomes a
thoroughly enjoyable trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Episode I,'' which introduces the future Darth Vader as a
selfless, 9-year-old slave boy named Anakin Skywalker and Obi-Wan
Kenobi as an apprentice Jedi Knight, was devised by Lucas more than
22 years ago as a back story for the original Star Wars. He began
developing his outline in 1994, creating a new trilogy that will
follow Anakin's fall to the dark side of the Force, before his
redemption by his son, Luke.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas realizes his vision with a stunning array of richly
detailed computer-generated characters and sets that take
filmmaking to an astonishing new level. He also deepens the saga's
religious aspects, introducing Anakin as the ``chosen one'' who
will bring balance to the Force. But the lord of the ``Star Wars''
universe almost scuttles his achievement with lame, childish humor
aimed to please young kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phantom Menace'' _ whose title recalls the old Saturday
adventure serials from which Lucas draws inspiration _ follows a
story arc similar to the original film. It begins with a galactic
conflict; concerns an idealistic boy who dreams of leaving home to
find his destiny among the stars; involves the training of a young
Jedi Knight; and ends with a climactic battle akin to the
destruction of the Death Star.
</P>
<P>
   Jedi Knight Qui-Gon Jinn (Liam Neeson) and his apprentice,
Obi-Wan (Ewan McGregor), are dispatched to resolve a blockade of
the peaceful planet Naboo by the greedy Trade Federation. Its
Neimoidian officials talk like characters from the Japanese samurai
epics that also imbue Lucas' cosmic parable of good vs. evil.
</P>
<P>
   Shadowy Sith Lord Darth Sidious orders the Neimoidian viceroy to
kill the Jedi ambassadors. After a brief but exciting clash with
battle and destroyer droids, the Jedi escape to the planet Naboo to
warn Queen Amidala (Natalie Portman) of an impending invasion by a
robot army. It's here that ``The Phantom Menace'' falters.
</P>
<P>
   Qui-Gon saves the life of a clumsy, floppy-eared creature named
Jar Jar Binks (voiced by Ahmed Best), whose race, the Gungan, live
in breathtaking underwater cities on Naboo. Designed to appeal to
children and provide comic relief, Jar Jar is the film's biggest
flaw. He's annoying, his pidgin dialect is impossible to understand
and his pratfall-laden gags aren't funny. Give me a growling
Wookiee any day.
</P>
<P>
   The secondary digital characters who inhabit Tatooine _ such as
the menacing Podrace champion, Sebulba, and Anakin's gruff, winged
owner, Watto _ are much more convincing than Qui-Gon's unwelcome
sidekick. The adrenaline-throttling Podrace, which pays homage to
Ben Hur's chariot dash, also features cameos by Sand People, Jawas
and Jabba the Hutt.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen's sleek, chrome ship is forced to land on Tatooine,
where she is tracked by Sidious' lethal apprentice, Darth Maul (Ray
Park). There, Qui-Gon discovers young Anakin, an aspiring Podracer
with Jedi reflexes, in whom the Force is unusually strong. ``The
chosen one he may be, but grave danger I sense in his training,''
Jedi Master Yoda (Frank Oz) later ominously tells Obi-Wan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phantom Menace'' sets the stage for Episodes II and III by
planting seeds of romance between Anakin and 14-year-old Amidala,
who will someday give birth to Luke and Leia, and establishing the
sly political ambition of seemingly well-meaning Senator Palpatine
(Ian McDiarmid, reprising his role from Return of the Jedi).
</P>
<P>
   Lucas focuses on symbiotic relationships in this first chapter,
tying the notion of two life forms living together for mutual
advantage to his underlying theme of balance. ``Always two there
are,'' Yoda says of the Sith Lords. ``No more, no less.'' The Jedi
Knight and his apprentice share a similar synergy. The Gungan and
Naboo people who inhabit the besieged planet are forced to pull
together to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Directing his first film in 22 years, Lucas makes heavy use of
his trademark wipe dissolves to cut among ``Episode I'''s multiple
storylines and short scenes. The performances come second to
lightsaber duels and starfighter battles, yet Neeson (''Schindler's
List'') carries himself with a strong, sage bearing, while McGregor
(''Trainspotting'') nicely approximates the speech of the elder
Obi-Wan, Alec Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   Like Anakin's Podracer, ``The Phantom Menace'' gets off to a
faulty start, but soon recovers and races to a rousing finish.
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: B
</P>
<P>
   (A _ Excellent; B _ Good; C _ Fair; D _ Poor; F _ Abysmal)
</P>
<P>
   Dave Larsen writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
