<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2249 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-ART-NYT &LR;      05-18 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, UNDER GROWING PRESSURE, LEAVES OPTION OF GROUND TROOPS
OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: More to be filed by 9:30 p.m.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under increasing public pressure to resolve the
conflict in Kosovo, President Clinton said Tuesday that he would
not rule out the use of ground troops but that he was hopeful that
diplomatic efforts under way with the Russians would be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I and everyone else has always said that we intend to see our
objectives achieved and that we have not and will not take any
option off the table,'' Clinton told reporters at the White House
when asked if he was reconsidering the use of ground troops to
expel Yugoslav forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   While administration officials insisted that the president's
comments did not signal a change of policy, Clinton has come under
increasing pressure, particularly from Britain, to consider ground
troops. The air war went into its 55th day Tuesday without having
achieved its goals. Britain is worried that troops need to be
deployed by June in order to prevent a catastrophe this winter for
the Kosovar refugees who have been forced from their homes and are
living in tent encampments.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Clinton had indicated only that he approved of the
Pentagon and NATO decision to update a military assessment of a
need for ground troops, as well as other military options like the
size of a peacekeeping force. His aides and military officials have
repeatedly insisted that ground troops were not a viable option,
while acknowledging that the Pentagon, as a matter of course, has
reviewed contingencies, including land combat.
</P>
<P>
   The British foreign minister, Robin Cook, appeared to soften his
stance on the need for ground troops Tuesday, after he failed to
sway his NATO allies in Brussels on Monday. He is still planning to
come to Washington on Thursday, though, to press the case.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and the Pentagon continued to press the air campaign
Tuesday night, although poor weather restricted airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended those strikes Tuesday, insisting that ``we
ought to stay with the strategy that we have and work it through to
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The renewed discussion of ground troops, combined with a
measurable slip in American public support for the NATO air
campaign, is prompting the Clinton administration to scramble to
find a diplomatic solution to the conflict before the use of ground
troops becomes inevitable and raises the possibility of American
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the pressure for a diplomatic solution is a sense that
the unity of the NATO alliance is increasingly fractious. Several
countries, including Italy and Greece, have been fretting about the
lengthy bombing campaign and its strains on domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Tuesday: ``I am very hopeful, obviously, that the
diplomatic efforts that are being made in the State Department and
with the Russians will bear some fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks between Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott; the
special Russian envoy to the Balkans, Victor Chernomyrdin, and
President Martii Ahtisaari of Finland, were to continue on
Wednesday morning. The talks have centered on ways to approach
Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, about proposals that
would lead to an end to the bombing campaign and the withdrawal of
Yugoslav forces from Kosovo. Finland is not part of NATO but is a
member of the European Union and will lead the union starting this
summer, giving it extra clout in any peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and NATO have been discussing the possible composition of
an international security force that would return the refugees to
Kosovo, and have disagreed recently over when to stop the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   While the president has avoided committing ground troops, he has
pledged that the United States would send soldiers as part of a
peacekeeping force when the war is over. A Pentagon spokesman said
Tuesday that that peacekeeping force would probably involve 45,000
to 50,000 soldiers, instead of the 28,000 contemplated before the
air war in Yugoslavia began, and that America would provide between
10 percent and 15 percent of those troops _ or 4,500 to 7,500.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the talks Tuesday, Talbott told reporters, ``These
are very tough issues but serious people are working on them.'' He
declined to give details of the talks. Some reports suggested that
Chernomyrdin would go to Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, later this
week.
</P>
<P>
   While the shuttle diplomacy has yielded little so far, NATO's
airing of differences over ground troops and the president's remark
could be seen as a signal to Milosevic that NATO would not relent
in its campaign.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
