<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Thursday, May
19, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   JOBS-SEATTLE (Seattle) _ Puget Sound area joblessness continued
to fall last month, even as Boeing continued to lay off workers and
growth of the economy in other areas slowed. State figures released
today showed unemployment at 4.6 percent, compared with 5 percent a
month earlier. That's the lowest unemployment in 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Virgin. (Story will move in the ``a'' and ``f''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   FORBES-SEATTLE (Seattle) _ You did it again, Seattle. A national
magazine has ranked you No. 1 in the nation. This time, Forbes
magazine says Seattle topped 162 metropolitan areas across the
nation in growth in jobs, income and output in the area's high
technology industries, including aerospace. The city is ``hot'' and
leads the nation in the ``new economy,'' based on brainpower, as
opposed to the ``old economy,'' based on materials supplies,
factories and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Gorlick. (Story will move in the ``a'' and ``f''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   WHALE (NEAH BAY, Wash.) _ After hours of celebration and hours
spent carving up the whale, Makah say on Tuesday they have a
``spiritual hangover.'' Four tribal cooks are at work beginning the
task of rendering some of the blubber and preparing the meat for a
huge multi-tribe potlatch on Saturday. Meanwhile, the tribe plans
to sink the carcass in the bay and let the crabs pick it clean,
then move the bones to their cultural museum. Protesters say they
will be back the next time the Makah hunt, possibly this fall.
</P>
<P>
   By Mike Barber and Rebekah Denn. (Story will move in the ``a''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-CONGESTION (Undated) _ Serious congestion at the
U.S.-Canada border would ``seriously worsen'' with severe
consequences for trade, tourism and cooperation unless Congress
repeals a controversial requirement of its 1996 immigration law, 21
mayors warned in a letter Tuesday. Spearheaded by Seattle Mayor
Paul Schell, the Cascadia Mayors Conference warning came as senior
Canadian officials appeared in Washington, D.C., to press the case
for repeal of Section 110 of the 1996 Immigration Act. Section 110
would, in essence, require that U.S.-bound Canadians get out of
their cars and offer proof of identity, as well as stop and
formally check out of the United States when headed north again.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly and Michael Paulson. (Story will move in the
``i'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-CHINA (Washington, D.C.) _ The United States should pay
compensation to China for bombing its embassy and should dispatch
Defense Secretary William Cohen to explain what went wrong, U.S.
Sen. Patty Murray said Tuesday. But Murray, in a speech on the
Senate floor, said the bombing should not be used as an excuse by
critics in either country who want to cut off the relationship
between the U.S. and China.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story will move in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-ABC (Undated) _ ABC, famous for placing good shows on
Saturdays and then canceling them after nobody watched, will
address the problem next fall by eliminating all series on Saturday
nights in favor of three-hour movies.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-WB (Undated) _ Acting more and more like the big boys, The WB
adds a sixth night of programming next fall: Fridays. And, while
the network of Michigan J. Frog is still aiming at the hearts of
young viewers, some of its new programming for the 1999-2000 season
demonstrates an interest in people beyond their teens. But not too
far beyond.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) _ Seattle hosts the Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   By Tyler Kepner. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-THIEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Woody Woodward places a call to
Neah Bay in hopes of landing the hard-throwing right-hander from
the Makah tribe.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
