<HEADER>
A2254 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-HNS &LR;      05-18 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A MAN OF HIS WORD,' BARAK SEEN AS A BRILLIANT, CAUTIOUS
POLITICIAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Once, the story goes, Ehud Barak's wife came home,
found a woman's dress in her husband's closet and traces of
lipstick on his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   When she tried to awaken him for an explanation, all he said
was, ``Let me sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning Nava Barak learned that her husband, who
commanded an elite commando unit, had dressed as a woman and landed
on the beach in Beirut with several of his men. They were all
driven to the hideout of Palestinians who had participated in the
massacre of 11 Israeli Olympic athletes in Munich.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's commandos killed three of the Palestinians who
masterminded the operation. It was 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The story, retold by Ilan Kfir in his biography, ``Barak _
Soldier Number One,'' speaks volumes about the man who became
Israel's new prime minister Monday night by defeating Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's most decorated soldier, Barak has earned a James
Bond-like reputation for daring. To many Israelis, his name is
synonymous with the bold missions that are part of Israeli legend.
</P>
<P>
   But he's also known for his brilliance and his reserve, and he
sometimes unintentionally comes across as arrogant, stiff and cold
_ the kind of guy who would tell a worried wife to let him be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the nature of a special agent,'' Kfir, who had
nothing but praise for Barak, said. ``He's naturally suspicious. It
takes him a long time to get to know people.''
</P>
<P>
   His traits of daring and reticence are likely to guide the prime
minister-elect in any negotiations with the Palestinians and the
Syrians, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   A hawkish dove in Israel's political universe, Barak served 35
years in the Israeli army as a platoon leader, tank-battalion chief
and senior intelligence analyst before becoming a lieutenant
general and army chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he oversaw Israel's withdrawal from the Gaza Strip and
the West Bank town of Jericho and likes to boast that he played a
key role in the negotiations with Jordan that led to a peace deal
the same year.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, Barak's ideas for peace with the Palestinians are not
that much different from his predecessor's. Barak, like Netanyahu,
wants Israeli sovereignty over Jerusalem, a majority of West Bank
settlements to stay under Israeli control and a demilitarized
Palestinian entity.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Netanyahu, Barak believes that Israel is strong
enough to trade land for peace because it has the advantages of a
productive economy, a stable government and a powerful military.
</P>
<P>
   During the five-month election campaign, Barak surrounded
himself with military advisers who agreed with Barak's platform
that Israel is in a position to cede territory for peace.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, he wrapped himself in the mantle of the late
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who was assassinated by a Jewish
extremist in 1995. Many Israelis say Barak's strong character and
military background remind them of Rabin, who was also a former
chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He appeals to Israelis as a man of his word, a more reliable
man than Netanyahu,'' said Yaron Ezrahi, a political analyst at
Jerusalem's Hebrew University. ``This is a class of man in line
with Rabin.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1942 on a remote ``kibbutz,'' or collective farm, near
the Lebanese border, Barak grew up on another ``kibbutz'' near Tel
Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   His parents believed in building Israel into a socialist state.
His father fled Russia to Palestine in 1912 after the Cossacks
killed his parents. His grandparents on his mother's side died in
the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Barak showed signs of genius and an aptitude for the
piano. He was one of a few children selected for music lessons and
is now an accomplished classical pianist _ a talent that helped him
win votes from Russian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   As he grew older, Barak exhibited a keen intelligence, but it
made him lazy in school and often got him into trouble. Once, Kfir
relates, Barak was called on to read a composition he was supposed
to have written for class. He ``read'' instead from a blank paper.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, his teachers got tired of such pranks. ``They kicked
him out of school because he thought he was too smart, he was
behaving like these lessons were boring for him,'' said Kfir.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Barak received a high school diploma while serving in
the army. Then he went on to study mathematics and physics at
Hebrew University in Jerusalem. A decade later, he earned a
Master's degree in systems analysis from Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, he made a name for himself on his first commando
mission, masterminding the rescue operation of an airliner at Lod
Airport in Tel Aviv that had been hijacked by Palestinians.
Netanyahu was a young soldier under Barak's command.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Barak dressed as a woman and sneaked through the
streets of Beirut to lead the raid against the Palestinians
involved in the Munich massacre.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, he helped plan the raid on Entebbe, Uganda, when
Israeli commandos rescued passengers on a plane hijacked by
Palestinians and Germans.
</P>
<P>
   His political rise has been astoundingly rapid. He was interior
minister in Rabin's government, then foreign minister under Shimon
Peres after Rabin's assassination. In 1997, with roughly two years
political experience under his belt, he won the leadership of the
Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   While he was daring as a soldier, Barak has been described as
``overly cautious'' as a politician. But such caution could serve
him well when he guides his government toward tough decisions in
negotiations with the Palestinians, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   Most say they expect Barak to carve his own political legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be flexible on some items and on some items he's
going to be a hard-liner,'' said Kfir. ``But he's going to be
genuine, he's going to be honest _ not like Netanyahu.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
