<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER STAR HEADED TO OUR FIRMAMENT?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bay Area's roster of Hollywood celebrities _ you'll know
them, in lines at the DMV, by their baseball hats and dark
sunglasses _ may be lengthening.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Benjamin Bratt &LR;  has left ``Law &AMP; Order,'' and the New York
Daily News reports that he's rumored to be heading back to San
Francisco, where he grew up (and put in stints at University of
California and ACT).
</P>
<P>
   Bratt's girlfriend is  &UR; Julia Roberts &LR; , who told the Daily News,
``I'll follow him anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ David Felger &LR; , president of the company that runs the  &UR; Paula &LR; 
 &UR; Jones &LR;  Celebrity Psychic Network, says it's off to a slow start.
Jones' contract gives her a 90-day trial run as hotline
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   _ A man whose cottage industry is the construction of crossword
puzzles is rejoicing about this week's election of  &UR; Ehud &LR; 
 &UR; Barak &LR;  as Israeli prime minister. Both his first and last names
constitute a ``great combination of unlikely letters,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Mick Jagger &LR;  has convinced  &UR; Jerry Hall &LR;  that they should talk
to a marriage counselor, reports the Daily Mail of London. MSNBC's
 &UR; Jeannette Walls &LR;  puts it differently: She says Jagger is seeking
treatment for sex addiction.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Post says  &UR; Minnie Driver &LR;  has gotten engaged to
 &UR; Josh Brolin &LR; , which makes  &UR; Barbra Streisand  &LR; her future
mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Joe DiMaggio &LR; 's last heartthrob was TV newswoman  &UR; Elizabeth &LR; 
 &UR; Vargas &LR; , whom he first saw on TV in 1996, says the New York Daily
News. A friend who was at dinner with the pair the night they met
face-to-face, &LR;  said, ``Joe wasn't the most loquacious guy. But with
Elizabeth, you couldn't shut him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a story about  &UR; Joe DiMaggio Jr. &LR;  in the current issue
of Esquire says that when he played football with his prep school
team in the '50s, in a New Jersey town about 50 miles from New
York, his father ``never bothered'' to attend a game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stuff magazine, a new periodical that combines the virtues of
Playboy and Boys' Life, reports on the advent of Pedal 'n' Play, an
exercise bike wired to a slot machine. These will soon be available
on Carnival cruises and casinos in Atlantic City and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAFETY FIRST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sydney Goldstein &LR; , who produces City Arts &AMP; Lectures, says she
was required to provide two metal detectors, 20 plainclothes
security people and two bomb-sniffing dogs for  &UR; Salman Rushdie &LR; 's
talk on May 5. The reaction of the crowd to all the security was
anything but annoyed, she says. ``People found it rather
glamorous.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein says she fears more for the safety of woman warrior
 &UR; Germaine Greer &LR; , who's coming here on June 8 and who's fierce
enough to make Rushdie seem like Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOUGH JEWS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rich Cohen &LR; , author of ``Tough Jews'' (Vintage; $13), a study
of Jewish gangsters and the relationships between fathers and sons,
was in San Francisco last week in conjunction with the paperback
publication of the book. We asked him whether Jewish gangsters are
different from other gangsters:
</P>
<P>
   ``They were unique,'' said Cohen, ``in that they really didn't
pass it on to their kids in any way. They raised their kids with
the idea that for them, organized crime was a short cut to the
American dream, to get their kids into law school or medical
school.'' Making a lot of money was a way of cheating ``to even up
the score. For that reason, it became just one generation that
became gangsters. There's no equivalent of  &UR; John &LR; 
 &UR; Gotti Jr. &LR;  among Jewish gangsters. I think that is kind of
unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said his understanding of gangster violence in the '20s,
'30s and '40s doesn't give him any insight into violence among
young people today. Gangsters of old were violent to ``get out of
the slums, to help their children.'' The shooters in Littleton,
Colo., by contrast, had already arrived at the middle-class heaven
that old-fashioned gangsters could only imagine in their dreams.
``What happened at Littleton would be more mind-boggling to the
gangsters than anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went into Kosovo, I don't know that we knew what was
going to happen, that we'd be there like this. We don't like to
negotiate with bad people. We just like to get rid of them. ... I
think you need to negotiate with them first, and then if you get
some kind of agreement and they don't stick to it, then you maybe
take action. ... Not a single person was killed in war during the
Carter administration. Peace is harder than war.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rosalynn Carter, quoted in the Washington Post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
