<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-COMMEWNT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALLAS AWAITS HIS DAY IN THE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ The job is watching, learning, filing it all
away for a future date, but the timeline is invisible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something John Vanbiesbrouck once said stuck with me,'' said
Bruins netminder Rob Tallas. ``As a goalie, he said, you're always
a student of the game. It's not like, click, one day you've got it
all figured out. Instead, you keep learning, and you get better
with age.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas, now 26 years old, was back filling the tutorial seat
here Tuesday night as teammate Byron Dafoe started his 12th
consecutive playoff game. In three seasons, Tallas has yet to play
a postseason minute. A sometimes equal partner with Dafoe during
the regular season, he has been relegated to understudy _ a job
that requires its own degree of readiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prepare like I'm going to play,'' said Tallas. ``I take the
morning skate, eat the pregame meal, and get in the nap. I'm not
paid to sit on the bench, take the night off, look around the
stands, and enjoy myself. I take it seriously. It's the only way
you can approach it. I'm paid to be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be prepared to play the biggest game you could
imagine in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   And you just never know. In Game 5 of the Bruins-Sabres series
Sunday, ex-UMass-Lowell netminder Dwayne Roloson didn't believe
he'd be playing in the Buffalo net. After 40 minutes, however,
coach Lindy Ruff pulled starter Dominik Hasek, and Roloson moved
from backup to front line.
</P>
<P>
   Roloson entered with the Sabres in a 4-1 deficit. By late in the
period, the Sabres had cut the deficit to a goal and were threating
to tie with Roloson pulled for an extra attacker. He was back in
the cage in the final seconds when Jason Allison potted his second
goal of the postseason for the 5-3 final.
</P>
<P>
   On the Boston bench, Tallas couldn't help but feel a touch of
envy toward the 29-year-old Roloson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited for him, but at the same time, I'd love to be in
that situation,'' said Tallas, who knows Roloson from their days in
the American Hockey League. ``Sometimes I wonder if, say, we had a
big lead late in the game, maybe Burnsie (coach Pat Burns) would
put me in for five minutes _ I'd love that.''
</P>
<P>
   As Tallas talked to a reporter, Burns happened by the backup
goalie's locker. Kiddingly, he stopped in his tracks and said to
the scribe, ``You're talking to Tallie? Is there something I should
know?''
</P>
<P>
   Not five minutes later, veteran wing Steve Heinze wandered by
and added, ``Geez, they're talking to you?''
</P>
<P>
   All good fun, of course, because Tallas is among the most-liked
players in the room. The coach and his teammates know it's no fun
being the designated sitter, especially at the most exciting time
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tallas, Burns gave a lot of thought to starting him
in last year's playoffs, following a 3-0 loss to the Capitals in
Game 4 at Boston. After some deliberation, and talking with both
goalies, Burns kept Dafoe on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right move _ Byron got the shutout,'' said Tallas, ``and
kept me on the sidelines a little longer.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tallas doesn't see a minute in the Boston cage this
postseason, there's a chance he'll never play again for the Bruins.
He undoubtedly will be left exposed for the June expansion draft
that will stock the Atlanta Thrashers. The Bruins don't have to
expose a netminder, but if they chose to protect both Dafoe and
Tallas, they would be able to protect fewer forwards and/or
defensemen. In all likelihood, Tallas will be left available, with
the Bruins prepared to promote John Grahame, their No. 1 netminder
all season in Providence (AHL).
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like I get calls every day about that,'' said Tallas,
signed by Boston as a free agent in '95 and invited to camp as an
extra body with little chance of making it to the big leagues.
``Some people tell me, `Hey, you're going to Atlanta.' Some say
Atlanta will draft me and then trade me right away. Then I hear I'm
staying here. So, I don't know what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``What concerns me most, the big thing is to be part of this
time right now. This is the place I want to be, both now and in the
future. When June comes, if it's somewhere else, well, I'll deal
with it at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   When the puck was dropped, Tallas and Roloson were in their
appointed spots, taking up the end of their respective benches.
Dafoe was in the Boston net. The great Hasek, considered the game's
best netminder the past three seasons, fronted the Buffalo cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at the age now, 26, I'd like to be a No. 1 goalie in the
next couple of years,'' said Tallas. ``When Byron got here, he was
at the age I am right now, so it worked for him.''
</P>
<P>
   But here in the playoff season of 1999, Tallas remains a student
of the game. The arena has been his classroom, the sheet of ice his
blackboard. One day class will end. But for now, he waits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2054EDT &QL; 
