<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2260 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-LIFE-SUPPORT-NYT &LR;      05-18 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-LIFE-SUPPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ALLOWS PARALYZED WOMAN TO DIE; MOTHER FACES MURDER CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Georgette Smith will be allowed to die, as she
wishes, but not until she helps prosecutors build a murder case
against her own mother, who she said has robbed her of the will to
live.
</P>
<P>
   A Florida judge ruled Tuesday that the 42-year-old Ms. Smith,
who was left paralyzed from the neck down in March when her
68-year-old mother shot her in the spine, will be allowed to have
her life support disconnected on Wednesday after 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, doctors will remove from Ms. Smith the ventilator
that is keeping her alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, don't leave me this way,'' Ms. Smith pleaded to the judge
in her deposition, saying she understood that her decision was
expected to result in murder charges against her mother, Shirley
Egan. Police say Ms. Egan shot her daughter on March 8 when she
heard her say that she wanted to place her in a nursing home. Ms.
Egan remains in custody.
</P>
<P>
   After Lucerne Medical Center, where she is a patient, refused to
disconnect her life support, Ms. Smith sued to compel them to let
her die. She got what she wanted here Tuesday in Orange County
Court when Judge Richard Conrad ruled that she could be taken off a
ventilator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Smith has made a difficult choice, a choice which she has
the right to make,'' Conrad wrote, in his ruling. ``This court has
found that she is competent to make that choice.''
</P>
<P>
   But the judge ruled that she must wait until 5 p.m. on
Wednesday. That will give prosecutors, who spent 45 minutes
interviewing Ms. Smith in the hospital Tuesday, more time to
interview her and gather evidence in what is expected to be one of
the most unusual legal battles in this state's history.
</P>
<P>
   Although the judge issued an order barring both sides in the
case from speaking about it, prosecutors here have said they will
likely file murder charges against Ms. Egan, who has already been
charged with attempted first-degree murder and aggravated battery
causing great bodily harm.
</P>
<P>
   An Orange County grand jury is expected to decide sometime in
the coming moths if Ms. Egan, a frail, 4-foot-11, 85-pound woman
who is blind in one eye, can be tried for killing her daughter when
it was her daughter's decision to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do is wink my eyes, wiggle my nose and wiggle my
tongue,'' Ms. Smith said in the written deposition her lawyers
submitted last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't move any other part of my body. I want to die because
I can't live this way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a case of immense sadness, said investigators and family
members, and perhaps the first of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   While there have been many cases in which a criminal's actions
led, after months or years, to suicides or death from lingering
effects from an attack _ leading to murder indictments and
convictions _ it might, legal experts say, be the first in which a
person of sound mind has chosen to be unhooked from life support,
knowing the consequences of the act to herself, and her attacker.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Ms. Smith was shot on March 8 in the Rosewood
Village Apartments in Orlando when she, her boyfriend and Ms. Egan
were talking about placing the elderly woman, who had emphysema and
had recently been hurt in a car crash, in a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Smith stepped away to get paperwork on a nursing home,
Ms. Egan fired a handgun at her, prosecutors said. It is not clear
how she got the gun.
</P>
<P>
   The bullet lodged in her neck and severed her spine at the
second vertebra. Then Ms. Egan fired the gun again, this time at
Ms. Smith's boyfriend, Larry Videlock, barely missing him, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Ms. Egan has said the elderly woman did not mean to
hurt her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith can speak, but only with great effort, but is unable
to swallow and must be fed by a tube. She has no control of her
bodily functions, and is at risk, doctors said, of pneumonia,
ulcers, infections and bed sores.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said her condition is irreversible, and a psychiatric
evaluation found her to be mentally competent.
</P>
<P>
   Her daughters, Candace Smith, 22, and Joeleen Hill, 19, said it
was their mother's choice to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't want to finish her life this way,'' said Candace
Smith in court last week.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother's death, if prosecutors follow through on their
plans to file murder charges, will be the beginning of a legal
struggle over intent, and responsibility: Did Ms. Egan end her
daughter's life, even though it was her daughter's decision to die?
</P>
<P>
   David Orentlicher, a professor of law at Indiana University and
co-director of the Center for Law and Health, said there is a long
history of murder charges and convictions stemming from crimes that
did not immediately result in death. In the late 1800s, a man was
injured in the leg by another man, refused to have his leg
amputated when gangrene set in, and died. His attacker was
convicted of murder.
</P>
<P>
   And in the 1930s, a woman who was raped later committed suicide
because she could not live with the shame. Her attacker was
convicted of murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks pretty clear,'' said Orenlicher. ``The law points
in that direction'' of a successful prosecution for murder in the
Florida case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, are they doing something that is so
unreasonable that it's not fair to blame to shooter,'' he said.
``In this case, we've got a well-recognized reason for refusing
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be held responsible for someone else's death unless
you cause that death,'' said Peter Arenella, a professor of
criminal law at the University of California in Los Angeles. ``The
daughter made a conscious decision to end her life, and should be
held to be the actual cause of death. It would be difficult for
prosecutors to persuade jurors that the attack caused her death.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Brafman, a prominent New York City defense lawyers,
agrees. ``It would be a very difficult legal theory,'' he said of
the prosecution. ``Because an argument could be made that an
affirmative decision to end the life is a not a direct consequence
of the shooting, but the result of an intervening force.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
