<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2261 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-NYT &LR;      05-18 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS OPEN THE BORDER AND EXPEL KOSOVARS TO MACEDONIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVID ROHDE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ Emerging from the darkness without warning, a
mile-long column of 80 tractors carrying between 1,000 and 1,500
Kosovo Albanian men, women and children abruptly arrived at this
remote border crossing at 8:15 p.m. Tuesday, aid workers said.
</P>
<P>
   Another group of more than 900 refugees crossed the border
earlier Tuesday afternoon. Together, they made up the largest
exodus of Albanians from Kosovo into Macedonia in 10 days. And the
exhausted refugees arriving here report that Yugoslav forces have
begun a new wave of mass expulsions in southeastern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees who arrived Tuesday afternoon said the Serbian
police were expelling Albanians from the Kosovo town of Urosevac
and the villages of Zlatar and Drobesh _ communities where
thousands of people already forced from their homes in other towns
and villages had taken shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Albanians from across Kosovo who have been
turned back from the Macedonian border by Yugoslav forces in the
last 10 days are believed to be hiding in southeastern Kosovo
waiting for a chance to flee.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces have followed a pattern of expelling thousands
of Albanians from Kosovo and then closing the border with no
warning. The reason for the pattern is not known, but Western
diplomats here have speculated that the Serbs clear out certain
areas for military purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees arriving Tuesday from Urosevac reported that more and
more Yugoslav Army units were occupying houses, schools, mosques
and even hospitals in the town in an effort to avoid being visible
targets for NATO air attacks.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the refugees said, the police went from house to
house in some neighborhoods and ordered Albanians to flee,
prompting several hundred people to board a train to Macedonia
Tuesday morning. After not permitting people to cross the border
for most of the last 10 days, Yugoslav border guards allowed all
900 people on the train to cross.
</P>
<P>
   Muharem Raci, 58, said he fled from Urosevac Tuesday after a
terrifying attack by Serbian police officers. ``We came because
they nearly killed us yesterday,'' he said. ``They came to our
house and put a machine gun to my throat and threatened to kill
me.''
</P>
<P>
   In Drobesh and Zlatar, two villages roughly 10 miles east of
Urosevac, Yugoslav soldiers surrounded the communities Tuesday
morning and ordered everyone to leave, refugees said.
</P>
<P>
   In Drobesh, the refugees said, the soldiers ordered all
residents to gather in the center of the village. There, the men
and women were separated. While the Serbs shouted taunts of, ``You
asked for NATO, go to NATO!'' they robbed the women and beat the
men.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 60 villagers were loaded into a bus that ferried them to
the border Tuesday afternoon, the refugees said. Hundreds of others
were left behind. The refugees who made it to the border said they
did not know what happened to the others.
</P>
<P>
   Xhezide Qitaku, 27, who was among those expelled from Drobesh
Tuesday, said the soldiers had arrested her two brothers and
dragged them out of the house where they were staying. Her family,
she said, fled to Drobesh eight months ago from the Drenica region
of Kosovo, the birthplace of the Albanian separatist rebel group,
the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   When she went out of the house to protest after her brothers
were seized, she said, the soldiers told Ms. Qitaku that her
brothers were already dead. When she left the house a second time,
she said, they beat her.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kicked me two times,'' she said. ``They said I was KLA
and had to be beaten.''
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian police officers prevented reporters from speaking
with the refugees arriving here from Zlatar Tuesday night. Aid
organizations here say they worry that food supplies inside Kosovo
may be dwindling. But Gavin Newton, an aid worker with the group
Action Against Hunger, said the refugees arriving Tuesday night
were cold, hungry and tired, but not malnourished.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are hungry, but they're still in generally good
condition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Astrid van Genderen Stort, a border monitor here from the U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees, said she believed that large
numbers of refugees could be again headed toward Macedonia and
could again arrive with little warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people on the tractors said they didn't know what was
behind them,'' she said Tuesday night. ``I don't know when it's
going to stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
