<HEADER>
A2263 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2TAKES-AR     05-18 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS POSITIONING TROOPS FOR GROUND WAR, INTELLIGENCE OFFICIALS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) (rm) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Anticipating that NATO may eventually launch
a ground offensive, Yugoslav army brigades have been stationed
along the likely attack routes from Macedonia and Albania and are
trying to fortify the border, according to allied officials.
</P>
<P>
   The positioning of the Serbian forces represents a marked shift
in Yugoslavia's military strategy from overseeing the expulsion of
ethnic Albanians from Kosovo to preparing for a prolonged battle,
and focusing on blocking incursions by NATO troops as well as rebel
fighters of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   It also signals that while two months of allied air strikes has
weakened Serb forces, it has not broken their will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the army is worried about defending the major passes
into Kosovo,'' an allied intelligence official said. ``Most of the
army is committed to digging in, mining and fortifying.''
</P>
<P>
   With the British again urging NATO to consider a land attack to
hasten an end to the crisis and return the refugees before the
winter, the Yugoslav army's preparations complicate the allied
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Even Britain draws the line at sending in NATO troops in the
face of a well-armed, organized Serb resistance. London has said it
will support a ground attack if air raids over the next several
months manage to weaken Yugoslav troops to the point that they pose
only scattered opposition.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO air strikes are taking a heavy toll on the Serbian
military, there are no indications that the Yugoslav forces are
about to crack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a conscript army, and there is a pretty unhappy group of
soldiers out there right now,'' the intelligence official said.
``Most of these guys should have been released in December and they
did not get paid last month because the paymaster did not get
through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the bottom line is that you still got an intact army out
there,'' he added. ``Are they ready to mutiny? No. Are they ready
to desert in mass? No. Do they feel good about what they have done?
Probably the officers do. And they are digging in.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons why Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic's military commanders are making preparations to fight on
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav strategy reflects anxiety over the 13,000 British,
French and German troops in Macedonia. They are part of a larger
NATO force that is being assembled for a potential peacekeeping
mission in Kosovo, but they could serve in an invasion force as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade may also be aiming to gain negotiating leverage with
NATO by setting the stage for the appearance of bloody ground war.
That was a tactic Saddam Hussein used before the 1991 Persian Gulf
war, but with little success.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it is a response to the Kosovo Liberation Army, which
is still infiltrating the province from Albania. Despite its
assaults against the ethnic Albanian population in Kosovo, the
Serbian military has yet to deal a mortal blow the KLA _ its
original objective.
</P>
<P>
   Sealing the border with Macedonia has become a top priority of
the Serbian military. Yugoslav army troops have been laying mines,
trying to block attack routes from Skopje and Kumanov in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   They have also positioned themselves to defend the route from
Skopje through the Kacanik Valley to Podujevo in Kosovo. It is the
most direct approach to the heart of the province, and the Yugoslav
army has put three brigades _ a force of about 12,000 troops _ in
its path.
</P>
<P>
   NATO intelligence says the Yugoslav army has its 243rd Brigade
near the border town of Deneral Jankovic. Behind it is the 252nd
Brigade, an armored unit, which is stationed between Urosevac and
Pristina. The 211th Brigade is in the rear, near Podujevo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They believe NATO is coming,'' the allied intelligence
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian border has also been a major worry for Yugoslav
generals because KLA partisans have been infiltrating through seven
mountain passes along that frontier.
</P>
<P>
   There are between 6,000 and 10,000 KLA fighters inside Kosovo,
NATO estimates. They are not only operating from western Kosovo but
from mountainous areas in north central and south central areas of
the province.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav military is ``desperate to close that border and
knows it cannot win unless it does so,'' the NATO intelligence
officer said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has an Army task force of 5,000, equipped with
Apache helicopters and surface-to-surface missiles in Albania. So
far, however, President Clinton has not given Gen. Wesley Clark,
NATO's supreme commander, permission to send the Apaches into
combat against Serb troops near Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The southwestern Kosovo city of Djakovica, the scene of some of
the most intensive assaults against ethnic Albanians, is a key town
near the Albanian border. Trying to seal off the Albanian border,
the Yugoslav military has deployed the 125th Brigade north of
Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the 549th Brigade is hunkered down to the south between
Djakovica and Prizren, another town in southwestern Kosovo that
sits on a major route from Albania. To fortify his position, the
Serb commander in Prizren has dragooned civilians, put them in
military uniforms and ordered them to dig trenches.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav commanders also have a reserve of 13,000 to 15,000
infantry troops in nearby towns in Montenegro and Serbia, which
could be drawn on in the event of a NATO attack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)  &LR;  With the army concentrating on
countering a NATO land attack, the special police from the Yugoslav
interior minister have been assigned the primary task of
maintaining control of central Kovoso.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav army, however, has been been involved in some
fighting against the KLA in the Kosovo interior. It has laid a
minefield on a road that runs north from Pristina to Podujevo to
try to box in KLA forces in the north central part of the province.
</P>
<P>
   There is no formal cooperation between the KLA and NATO, but the
allied air strikes have made it more difficult for Serbs to fight
the Albanian guerrillas. When the Serbs try to gather their tanks
and artillery to attack the Albanians, NATO planes bomb them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OPTIONAL TRIM)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   While the Serbian forces have not cracked, there are signs of
low morale within their ranks and even unrest in Serbia, NATO says.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials said today that there were two demonstrations
in recent days, one at Alexandrovac where 1,000 people tried to
prevent the departure of reservists to Kosovo. At Krusevac, 3,000
angry protesters demanded that reservists in Kosovo be sent home.
</P>
<P>
   Some intelligence analysts, in fact, believe that Belgrade's
much publicized announcement of a limited troop pull out may have
been directed as much at reassuring its own military as it was on
public opinion in the West. The aim, they say, was to assure its
Serb troops in Kosovo that their ordeal in Kosovo will not go on
indefinitely.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
