<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2265 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2NDTAKE-N     05-18 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BRUSSELS: on indefinitely.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   None of this is likely to mean that President Milosevic is about
to yield to NATO's demands or that the conflict will soon come to
an end. In Belgrade Tuesday, a foreign ministry official said
Yugoslavia is ready to discuss a deal to end the conflict. But it
is far from clear whether Milosevic is close to meeting NATO's
terms.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs, however, are not the only ones trying to seal off the
frontier. Seeking to weaken the Serb military and drive it out of
Kosovo, NATO has tried to cut the Serb troops in Kosovo from their
supply lines from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy is to cut this guy off in Kosovo and impede them
from moving supplies from the middle of the country to the south of
the country,'' Gen. John Jumper, the head of the U.S. Air Force in
Europe, said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will that increase the pressure on Belgrade to yield to
NATO's demands, NATO believes, but it is likely to prompt the Serb
troops to come out of their hiding places, making them vulnerable
to NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   But shutting off the supplies has not been easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo is about 50 percent cut off,'' another senior military
officer said. ``There are innumerable roads.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied planes have destroyed the two rail lines to Kovoso, a
major setback for the Yugoslav army, which is heavily dependent on
rail traffic. The only functioning rail line is between Pristina
and Deneral Jankovic, which the Serbs have used to shuttle refugees
back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has also pummeled the roads and bridges from Mitrovica in
northern Kosovo to Raska, Serbia, all but cutting off that attack
route. Bridges between Podujevo and Nis in Serbia have also been
attacked, though Serb units have still been able to get supplies
through.
</P>
<P>
   With the allies trying to avoid attacks on Montenegro, which is
part of Yugoslavia but whose pro-Western government is striving to
stay independent of Belgrade's control, some of the routes to that
region are open as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a complex mission and will take patience,'' Jumper said
of the air campaign. ``It will take some time to get the fielded
forces to the point where we have a decisive impact on his ability
and willingness to pursue these atrocities.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how long the war might continue, Jumper gave a terse
response: ``months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
