<HEADER>
A2266 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROW-SFCHRON &LR;      05-18 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 How to Get VC Firms' Attention
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I would like to start an Internet business and am
interested in strategies for getting noticed by venture capital
firms?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  It isn't easy, especially if you don't have an
entrepreneurial track record or contacts in the investment world.
Good ideas are not enough. Even a brilliantly crafted business plan
may not get you through the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually no one looks at business plans that come in over the
transom,'' said Mark Radcliffe, a senior partner at the law firm
Gray Cary Ware &AMP; Freidenrich, which caters to venture firms and the
companies they back. If you don't have an in with VCs, he suggests
consulting with a law, accounting or consulting firm that does and
let them help with the introductions.
</P>
<P>
   It's often possible to get a first meeting free with these
professionals. But success is certainly not guaranteed. Radcliffe
said he referred three entrepreneurs to VCs in the past two weeks
but turned away five others.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't hear back from professionals you've contacted, it
probably means they don't think much of your idea.
</P>
<P>
   You might have better luck running your idea past the Service
Corps of Retired Executives or the growing number of private
wealthy investor groups, known as angels.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what sort of Internet concept you have, but there
are a lot of ideas out there and yours better be fresh and have
some real potential.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Braziel, chairman of Altra Energy Technologies of
Houston, says, ``You better know the industry you are serving.''
His firm delivers gas, electricity and liquid fuels over the
Internet and has raised $47.5 million of private equity.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he observes, ``The Internet is just pipes.'' That
means you can't just put information on a bulletin board and expect
to make money. Braziel stresses the importance of ``helping your
customers be more profitable, save money, or both.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for those seeking venture capital is that there is
plenty available. Red Herring magazine noted at its information
technology investing conference at Squaw Valley yesterday that 139
new funds were formed last year with $17.3 billion committed to
them by institutional investors. That was up 47.5 percent from the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   The not-so-good news is that venture capital investors are
betting a lot more money on each of their investments and are
therefore less tolerant of mistakes. At the same time, the pressure
to get from idea to product to market more quickly has never been
so intense.
</P>
<P>
   How to Be an E-CEO
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does it take to be a great e-commerce CEO?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Ross Garber, founder and chairman of Vignette of Austin,
Texas, should know. The customer relationship management software
company he started four years ago went public in February and now
is worth $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the Red Herring conference, Garber said the days of
product-based marketing plans are over. Now it's essential to have
a great business model. ``It's like playing chess instead of
checkers'' he noted, and the model is constantly changing.
</P>
<P>
   He also recommends creating a company that has soul. For
Vignette, whose customers include Charles Schwab and US West, this
means realizing it's important to satisfy not just employees, but
their families. After particularly arduous projects, Vignette sends
cookie bouquets to spouses.
</P>
<P>
   Even though you may be shy, as Garber was in school, learn to
stand out. To separate yourself from the pack, you need to lead a
crusade.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, don't expect entrepreneurship to be a panacea. Garber
thought it would be when, at age 12, he got his first Commodore Pet
computer and envisioned becoming an entrepreneur. He thought he'd
be like the Pied Piper and lead folks out of the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he recalls his first 2-1/2 years as CEO were ``the
hardest, most miserable thing I've ever done in my life.'' The
responsibility for other peoples' lives and livelihoods is what
worried Garber most. Nine months ago, he gave up the CEO job and is
now happier focusing on strategic issues and coaching.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
