<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS WILL SIT OUT THIS SERIES AGAINST RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- There was no sadness detectable in his voice. Roger
Clemens in a Yankee uniform was just another visiting ballplayer in
Fenway Park vowing to be ready when it is his turn to face the Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens made another return to Fenway Tuesday night, his first
time here in a Yankee uniform, and drew a crowd. But the drama of
the moment was diminished when it was confirmed that he will not
face his former team Thursday. Instead, the righthander will return
from a stint on the disabled list Friday in Chicago. If all goes
well, Clemens and the Red Sox should meet next Wednesday, in Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees cited weather forecasts _ which call for rain in the
next two days _ as a major factor in holding back Clemens, who has
been on the DL since April 28 with a strained left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I badly want to pitch,'' declared Clemens. ``I want to pitch
first and then go out there and be effective and be healthy. That's
my main concern. If that is also their concern, so be it. It would
have been fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has had fun here before in a visiting uniform. He won Cy
Young Awards each of the last two years with the Toronto Blue Jays,
beating the Red Sox once each year. In his first time back to
Boston, July of 1997, he struck out 16 batters in a 3-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   His trade to New York this spring was another jolt to Boston
fans, but if they wish to boo him, they probably won't get a chance
until the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been back before and wearing a visiting uniform,'' said
Clemens. ``So I don't think things are that different. It's always
exciting to come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``But around here (with New York), it's the big picture that
matters. You work toward August and September to get yourself in
position to do well. I won't pitch any harder than I would at any
other stadium. There won't be that many more distractions here than
there would be in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was deft at avoiding the sensitive questions. He would
not address his Red Sox days. In that he was firm. But he did wax
poetic about being a Yankee and playing for a team that may be able
to deliver the World Series title that has eluded him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting on the pinstripes is everything I expected from spring
training on,'' he said. ``I'm back where the history means
something. It's everything you expect. I'm not satisfied, but I'm
very happy. I just need to get back out there, know that my legs
are under me and I can be healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I take the mound, guys are going to come at me for what
I've done in the game. Or what I did over the years. Also, what
this team accomplished last year. Everybody comes at you extremely
hard. You notice that from teams you didn't expect to put up a big
fight. They put up a great challenge to you.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Yankee, Clemens added, he is back in a part of the baseball
world where the fans count.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to perform and get people excited,'' he said. ``In
Boston and New York, they make their own excitement. If you do
well, it's great. If not, they let you know it, too. It's fun to be
in the middle of it.''
</P>
<P>
   With the All-Star Game in Boston this summer, Clemens has
another opportunity to pitch before the Fenway faithful in
pinstripes, though the injury and a slow start (2-0, 5.47 ERA) will
hurt his chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the All-Star Game, if it happens, great,'' said
Clemens. ``If not, I have some other plans. My boys have some games
planned and obviously I will be doing something with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
