<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISCO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Cisco to Help Small Firms Get Net Savvy
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
While Internet startups and ``dot com'' companies dominate the
news, many smaller businesses still aren't participating in the
information technology revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Eyeing a potential new customer base, Cisco Systems is working
to get small and medium-size businesses online and technologically
savvy.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose networking giant will announce today that it is
working with the San Francisco office of the Small Business
Association and the Small Business Development Center to help
companies use the Internet to conduct everyday business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope is to familiarize small business with the benefits of
doing business over the Internet,'' said Gary Marshall, economic
development specialist with the SBA.
</P>
<P>
   The SBA is working with Cisco to help small companies develop,
design and maintain Web sites. Cisco is providing free 10-megabyte
Web sites and Internet accounts to 250 small Bay Area businesses
that complete a series of free SBA courses. The classes focus on
areas such as e-commerce and doing business on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco also is developing a series of free courses to be held
around the Bay Area in conjunction with the Small Business
Development Center, a one-stop shop for small businesses partially
funded by the SBA. The seminars, which start next month, aim to
help companies learn to use the Internet as a money-saving tool and
a way to maintain customer relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great opportunity to educate small businesses about
how technology can help them save money and operate their business
more efficiently,'' said Eugene Lee, a vice president in Cisco's
small and medium business division.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a great opportunity for Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   As these small businesses become more familiar with the Internet
and start to migrate their business online, Cisco can benefit from
the relationships it's formed.
</P>
<P>
   The companies potentially could turn to Cisco to buy the routers
and other networking gear they'll need to maintain a Web presence
and conduct business on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to establish ourselves as a leading provider to small
businesses,'' said Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco traditionally has focused on large, corporate customers,
but there is a finite number of those companies. There are between
6.5 million and 13.5 million small and medium-size businesses in
the United States, representing a new, lucrative opportunity for
Cisco and other networking companies, industry watchers said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
For information on the SBA courses, call (415) 744-6771 or visit
 &LR; www.tixtogo.com/go/sba. &LR;  For information on the SBDC seminars,
call (888) 726-2712 or visit  &LR; www.siliconvalley-sbdc.org.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
