<HEADLINE>
THE WB ROLLS OUT SIX NEW SHOWS AND ADDS FRIDAY TO ITS LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Acting more and more like the big boys, The WB adds a sixth
night of programming next fall: Fridays. And, while the network of
Michigan J. Frog is still aiming at the hearts of young viewers,
some of its new programming for the 1999-2000 season demonstrates
an interest in people beyond their teens. But not too far beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The WB on Tuesday said it will introduce six new prime-time
shows next season, all but one of them of the hourlong variety. It
also will move ``Felicity'' to Sundays, so the new series ``Angel''
can follow its stablemate, ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' on
Tuesdays. ``Charmed'' will move from Wednesdays to Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   A summary of The WB's new fall series:
</P>
<P>
   Jack &AMP; Jill. A one-hour romantic comedy about a woman named
Jack, as in Jacqueline Barrett (Amelia Heinle), and a man named
Jill, as in David Jillefsky (Ivan Sergei). Best character name:
Can't do much better when she's Jack and he's Jill.
</P>
<P>
   Safe Harbor. Family drama featuring Gregory Harrison as the
sheriff _ and the widowed father of four boys _ in a seaside
Florida town. Best character name: Grandma (Rue McClanahan), owner
of the motel where the sheriff and his boys live.
</P>
<P>
   Angel. Hourlong spinoff from ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.''
Buffy's boyfriend, Angel (David Boreanaz), takes on the forces of
evil in Los Angeles. Best character name: ``Buffy'' transferee
Cordelia Chase, only because her real name, Charisma Carpenter, is
even better.
</P>
<P>
   Roswell. One-hour sci-fi drama about aliens trying to pass as
normal teens in Roswell, N.M. Best character name: Isabel
(Katherine Heigl), one of the kids orphaned after the crash of an
alien spaceship.
</P>
<P>
   Popular. One-hour comedy/drama about teens and the quest to be
cool. Best character name: Actually, it's the school they attend,
Jacqueline Kennedy High School.
</P>
<P>
   The Downtowners. Half-hour animated comedy about teens and
twenty-somethings living in the big city. Best character name:
Posey Tyler (voiced by Vicki Lewis).
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that some of the foregoing will crash and burn before
we've put up our 2000 calendars, The WB also announced three
midseason series. One is the comedy ``Zoe, Duncan, Jack &AMP; Jane,''
which premiered this season but isn't on the fall schedule. The
others are ``D.C.,'' a drama co-produced by Dick Wolf (``Law &AMP;
Order'') about recent college graduates making a living in the
nation's capital, and ``Baby Blues,'' an animated comedy about
suburban parenting based on the syndicated comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the WB's prime-time lineup for 1999-2000, with new
series in bold type (times listed are Seattle time):
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   7-8 p.m.: ``7th Heaven: Beginnings''
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``Felicity''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``Jack &AMP; Jill''
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``7th Heaven''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``Safe Harbor''
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``Angel''
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``Dawson's Creek''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``Roswell''
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``Popular''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``Charmed''
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-8:30 p.m.: ``The Steve Harvey Show''
</P>
<P>
   8:30-9 p.m.: ``For Your Love''
</P>
<P>
   9-9:30 p.m.: ``The Downtowners''
</P>
<P>
   9:30-10 p.m.: ``The Jamie Foxx Show''
</P>
</TEXT>
