<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-PORN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN MOVES TO BAN CHILD PROSTITUTION AND PORNOGRAPHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Japanese Parliament on Tuesday enacted a law that
aims at banning child prostitution and child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Its passage was a victory for international law enforcement
officials, who have long been critical of Japan's lax laws against
sex with children and child pornography, and for a band of women
legislators here who have fought for two years to overcome strong
opposition to the law on the ground that it would inhibit free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very happy,'' said Mayumi Moriyama, a veteran lawmaker
who coaxed Japan's fractious opposition parties into signing on to
the bill. ``After two years of work, really hard work, we've done
it, and I'm very pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   The law, which is to go into effect later this year, punishes
those found guilty of paying for sex with children 17 and younger,
and bans the sale, distribution, production, possession, import and
export of child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Current laws are vague and require a victim to file a complaint
before police can take action. Producers of child pornography have
found it easy to evade existing laws by avoiding pictures that show
intercourse and blacking out eyes and portions of some body parts.
</P>
<P>
   Newsstands and bookstores here stock a selection of magazines
featuring glossy photos of little girls in swimsuits or short
skirts, with slightly suggestive close-ups of thighs, crotches and
buttocks not quite completely covered by panties.
</P>
<P>
   There are also more blatant magazines with titles like
``Lolita'' and ``After School Play Mates'' _ featuring pictures of
girls who appear to range in age from 5 or 6 to women in their late
teens and early 20s in various states of dress and undress _ that
are fairly easy to buy in bookstores near red-light districts.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese companies have arranged tours to Asian countries whose
overriding aim is to introduce men to children with whom they can
have sex, although more stringent laws against child prostitution
in countries like Thailand and the Philippines have made such trips
rare.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the explosive growth of the Internet, with its
ability to facilitate wide distribution of images, that put Japan
on the map as the leading source of child pornography. Interpol,
the international police agency, has estimated that between 70
percent and 80 percent of the child pornography available on the
Internet came from Japanese sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some figures say 80 percent and some say 20 percent; we really
don't know a good way of measuring it,'' said Keiji Goto, an
official at the National Police Agency who campaigned on behalf of
more stringent laws. ``But it is sure that Japan is the No. 1
provider of child pornography on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign parents in Tokyo were complaining that their children
were stumbling across child pornography when searching for web
sites related to ``Japanese teens'' or ``Japanese dolls,''
according to the Rev. Jacques La Pointe, a Franciscan priest who
campaigned vigorously to raise awareness of the issue among
Japanese policy-makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disgusting what you can find on the Internet without even
trying,'' said Jacques, who was recently transferred to a diocese
in New York but only after wrangling a meeting to discuss the issue
with Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   Junko Miyamoto, of the Japanese branch of the international
watchdog group End Prostitution in Asian Tourism, has worked on the
campaign to strengthen Japanese laws against the sexual
exploitation of children for the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   She welcomed the passage of the law but cautioned that while it
will make child prostitution and pornography more difficult in
Japan, it is full of loopholes that were the inevitable result of
the battle to get the bill through the Parliament. The Democratic
Party, Japan's largest opposition party, raised several objections
to the bill, contending that it would infringe on freedom of speech
and expression, although it ultimately signed on to make it law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have just cleared the first step, and it was a great first
step,'' Ms. Miyamoto said. ``But now we must make sure it is
enforced strictly to protect children from commercial sexual
abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   She declined to identify the law's weaknesses, saying to do so
would be to help those seeking to exploit children. ``All I can say
is that it's not enough to stop abuse on the Internet, that's for
sure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Moriyama said the law would be reviewed in three years with
an eye toward strengthening it. ``We will not stop our efforts to
work on it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the business of distributing child pornography have
clearly scaled back their operations. A Japanese web site that
Jacques had been monitoring recently closed down, posting a notice
saying that it unwittingly may have distributed sexual pictures of
children under 18.
</P>
<P>
   Masashi Sekiguchi, who works for a major publisher of child and
adult pornography, said the law would definitely have a negative
impact on the business, which was already suffering. Strict laws
against child prostitution and pornography in countries like
Thailand and the Philippines, where many of the photos used in
magazines featuring child pornography are shot, have made it
difficult to obtain pictures of young girls.
</P>
<P>
   A gently smiling nude Asian girl, who looked to be 11 or 12
years old, stared up from the cover of a magazine on his coffee
table. He said most of the pictures in the magazine were taken four
or five years ago, before strict laws were enacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally object to making money by the exploitation of
nude children,'' Sekiguchi said. ``But our company orders us to
produce such books because they are very profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he also worried that the law would curtail the
publication of innocent photos of children. ``Look at this,''
Sekiguchi said, pointing to a photo of a fully clothed little
Japanese girl licking a popsicle stick. ``I think this is simply
lovely and beautiful. You can't associate it with a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Rei Sayama, the pen name of a writer who writes pornographic
articles and stories, said he worried that the suppression of child
pornography would give rise to more violent crimes against
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say that Japan is the only country in the world
where child pornography is legal,'' Sayama said. ``I understand
that must seem strange to foreign eyes, but there is a reason for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He contended that in Japanese culture, there is no historical
sense of criminality in child pornography. ``The typical Western
attitude is to resist the idea of having young girls as sex
objects,'' he said. ``But over several hundreds of years of
Japanese culture and history, little girls have been accepted as
sex objects. It's part of the cultural heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Sekiguchi objected. ``Japan hasn't until recently had a notion
that children could be sex objects,'' he said. ``Until recently,
most little children _ unless they were children of rich farmers _
would run around almost naked during the summer, and adults never
looked at them as sex objects.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CEMETERY-THEFT-NYT &LR;      05-18 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEMETERY-THEFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIFFANY GLASS EXPERT ACCUSED OF TRAFFICKING WITH MAUSOLEUM THIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y., Ohio)   (bl)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alastair Duncan has long been regarded as one of the
world's leading experts on Tiffany stained glass. A former
consultant to Christie's auction house here, he has written books
and articles on the subject, and has advised the FBI in its
investigations into thefts involving the valuable objects.
</P>
<P>
   But federal authorities in Manhattan said it was Duncan who
profited from some of the most brazen thefts of the stained glass,
as they accused him on Tuesday of conspiring with others to buy
Tiffany windows from a grave robber and offering the glass for sale
overseas for hundreds of thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the authorities said, Duncan bought a 9-foot
Tiffany stained-glass window, knowing that it had been stolen from
a mausoleum at a Brooklyn cemetery. He then arranged for it to be
sold to a buyer in Japan for $219,000, the authorities said. In
another case, he was accused of trying to sell another Tiffany
stained-glass window that had been stolen from a cemetery in
Valhalla.
</P>
<P>
   His arrest highlights what cemetery experts say has become a
rising concern around the country: the vulnerability of expensive
art objects that families have used to decorate mausoleums for more
than a century.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, 57, stood silently in U.S. District Court in Manhattan
on Tuesday as a magistrate ordered him released on $100,000 bond.
Duncan said he had no comment, and his lawyer, Peter Vigeland, said
only, ``We look forward to the opportunity to contest these charges
in court.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a national problem,'' said Meg Winslow, curator of
historical collections at Mount Auburn Cemetery in Cambridge,
Mass., who cited the lack of security in many cemeteries, the
growing market for the valuable glass and other commemorative
objects, and the failure of cemeteries to document the art objects
that adorn their mausoleums.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so easy to steal, to sell, and to get away with it,'' Ms.
Winslow said.
</P>
<P>
   Another expert, Katie Karrick, who publishes a newsletter on
cemetery art and history called ``Tomb With a View,'' said that
Tiffany stained-glass windows have been particularly coveted by
thieves since the 1960s, when the market in the valuable glass
began to heat up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to cemeteries around the country,'' she said, ``and
every time I see a mausoleum that has a blank window in back, just
filled in with clear glass, I assume first that there was once a
valuable window in there that's been stolen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Karrick, who also works as a historian the Lake View
Cemetery in Cleveland, whose chapel was designed by Louis Comfort
Tiffany, said she consulted with Duncan some time ago about the
work of the famous craftsman and that he could not have been more
generous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard anything but good things about him,'' Ms.
Karrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan once spoke about the popularity of Tiffany stained-glass
windows in cemeteries, explaining in a newspaper interview that at
the turn of the century, it was fashionable for affluent families
to commission windows from Tiffany for family mausoleums.
</P>
<P>
   But the government said Tuesday that Duncan, who also made money
buying and selling the valuable glass, began having dealings in
1998 with a grave robber who had been stealing Tiffany stained
glass and other objects from cemeteries, mausoleums and graveyards
in the New York region.
</P>
<P>
   The grave robber was not identified in the indictment. But
prosecutors said he had once worked in a cemetery and had kept a
set of master keys for cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said Duncan was warned at one point that the
grave robber's stained glass had been stolen but continued to
encourage him to seek out valuable stained glass.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, as far back as 1992 or 1993, the
grave robber had stolen a 9-foot Tiffany stained-glass window from
a mausoleum in the private Salem Fields Cemetery in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment does not say from whose tomb the window was
stolen, but the cemetery is owned by Temple Emanu-El on Fifth
Avenue and is the final resting place of members of such prominent
families as the Warburgs, Guggenheims, Lewisohns, Strauses and
Loebs.
</P>
<P>
   The government said the grave robber kept and stored the window
until 1998. Because of its size, it was worth hundreds of thousands
of dollars, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany's glass has become valuable, the authorities and other
experts said, because many of his stained-glass windows and other
art objects are enshrined in churches and mausoleums, which rarely
sell them. Tiffany died in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   With the supply finite and the demand high, mausoleums are
especially vulnerable to theft, the authorities said, because of
their minimal security and the fact that in many cases, family
members have also moved away or died, leaving the valuable objects
under the supervision of only the cemetery's caretakers.
</P>
<P>
   The government said that Duncan decided to take advantage of
what it called the ``large and lucrative market for Tiffany stained
glass,'' and he ``turned to suppliers legal and illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the indictment said, Duncan, in conversations with a
middleman who was also not identified, first learned of the
nine-foot window that had been stolen from Salem Fields.
</P>
<P>
   The middleman told Duncan that the window was stolen and
expressed concern that the sale could not be made, the indictment
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Duncan checked a computerized database of stolen art
objects, called the Art Loss Register, the indictment said, and
found no record of the window. The authorities say he then told the
middleman that they could go ahead with the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Working as equal partners, Duncan and the middleman inspected
the window, which had suffered cracks and damage, and ultimately
negotiated a price with the grave robber of $60,000, the indictment
said.
</P>
<P>
   The grave robber was quoted in the indictment as telling them
that ``it would be impossible to sell the window in the United
States because the window bore identifying numbers or marks that
would alert United States authorities if the window were sold
through a reputable auction house.''
</P>
<P>
   But the middleman told the grave robber not to worry because the
sale was being made to the overseas buyer, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   The middleman ultimately paid the grave robber $30,000 in cash
and $30,000 in checks written on Duncan's account, the indictment
said.
</P>
<P>
   When the grave robber complained that he could not cash the
checks because he did not have a bank account, Duncan accompanied
him to a Citibank branch, and asked a bank employee to cash the
checks for him, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   It says that the nine-foot window was restored in Manhattan and
then shipped to the buyer in Japan. In November 1998, Duncan
received a wire payment of $219,000, which he split with the
middleman, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
