r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENTURE-SFCHRON &LR;      05-18 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Nonstop Networking at Tech Conference
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Squaw Valley, Calif. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Entrepreneurs, venture capitalists and other high-tech aficionados
at Red Herring's Venture '99 conference here had little time to
gaze at the majestic Sierra or enjoy what's left of the snow.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Swildens, a director of Personify Inc. in San Francisco,
was one of the few who did, and he learned his lesson. He broke his
ankle riding a snowboard down the Granite Chief run Sunday
afternoon and spent the next two days talking to prospective
investors and partners about his interactive marketing software
startup with his leg raised.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 726 invitation-only guests who paid about $2,000
each to attend the popular two-day information technology forum
came to get a leg up on the competition in a different way _ by
networking nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years, the number of publicly traded
information-technology companies has more than doubled and more
than 10,000 additional companies have been privately financed.
</P>
<P>
   That has boosted the fortunes of countless entrepreneurs and
investors. It has also been a boon for Red Herring, a privately
held San Francisco company whose magazine of the same name covers
high-tech startups and is expected to eventually launch its own
public stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   Elton Sherwin, venture capitalist and author of ``The Silicon
Valley Way,'' said conferences such as Red Herring's are the most
efficient way to meet the right people. ``After two days, I have
150 business cards,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the conference business has gotten so big that a San
Francisco startup called Conferenza is making a business of
tracking and reviewing the quality of the events.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a $3.5 billion-a-year business,'' said Conferenza
Editor Doug Van Kirk. ``We've identified 680 technology events and
the fees for these exclusive events range from $2,000 to $5,000. He
added that it's almost like the Grateful Dead attracting 10,000 to
15,000 ``hard core conference junkies'' to 10 or more events a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Red Herring holds seven such conferences a year. They are the
company's main moneymaker, not its slick monthly magazine. In
addition to the high fees charged attendees, sponsors such as
Arthur Andersen and Microsoft pay tens of thousands of dollars to
rub elbows with current and prospective customers and partners.
</P>
<P>
   Those who mingled at the plush Resort at Squaw Creek were
treated to presentations by many of Red Herring's latest list of
greatest 50 private companies in the digital universe and 10 new
companies on the leading edge.
</P>
<P>
   They also packed dark conference rooms to hear luminaries such
as Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Internet analyst Mary Meeker, Sun
Microsystems Chief Science Officer John Gage and successful
Internet entrepreneurs discuss such major issues as whether
e-commerce companies can sustain huge stock market valuations if
they continue to lose money. (The consensus is that they can't.)
</P>
<P>
   But what drew the most interest from attendees was the
one-on-one, high-tech dating game.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Mantra Technologies of San Francisco. It wanted to
attend Red Herring's conference a year ago but was rebuffed because
it was too puny.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the company, whose patented text analysis technology
helps Internet users find sites of interest more easily, was
allowed to take a booth for $7,500. It also used the conference to
announce two deals with other Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Company President David Hultman said the cost was well worth it.
Mantra is interested in raising venture capital and got to meet
partners from Adobe Capital, Benchmark, Interwest, Mayfield and
other funds as well as talk with the CEOs of potential Internet
partners.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Third Voice, a Redwood City company that started
last year with $5.5 million from venture capital firms Draper
Fisher Jurvetson and Mayfield Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The company took the occasion to announce its product. Rather
than relegate messages to chat rooms or message boards, the product
allows Internet users to post comments directly on any Web site and
then share them with other users.
</P>
<P>
   By presenting its story at Red Herring's conference, the
28-employee company was able to get the word out to the ``in
crowd'' and meet potential clients such as Microsoft and America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   For Gary Hultquist, chairman of Titanium Memory Systems in
Milpitas, the conference represented an opportunity to search for
potential strategic partners like Compaq, Dell or Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-year-old company has raised $5 million from Titanium
Metals Inc. and $2 million from angel investors to produce
high-performance titanium memory disks that can spin faster than
those made of other materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a partnership with a supplier and want similar
relationships with users,'' said Hultquist.
</P>
<P>
   Little entrepreneurs and VC firms are not the only ones spending
more time and bucks at conferences. So are many high-tech giants
that are striving to cultivate relationships with up-and-coming
firms and become more entrepreneurial themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard, for example, has set up a unit to invest in
Internet entrepreneurs outside the company as well as help
employees inside the company develop ideas that might eventually be
spun off as separate businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional business models don't work in the Internet
space,'' said Feisal Mosleh, director of business development for
HP's Internet business unit. ``You can't take 18 months to launch
an Internet business,'' he noted. ``And you have to give up the
mind-set that new products have to generate revenues the first year
and profits in the second.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosleh's unit has identified about 10 of HP's own technologies,
such as customer relationship management software, that might be
spun off as freestanding companies. It also has invested a few
million each with about three outside entrepreneurs and is looking
to place bets on dozens more as well as work with venture firms to
help fund some of its own technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for financial partners, entrepreneurial partners,
marketing partners and friendships that can help us own more of the
e-services ecosystem,'' Mosleh explained.
</P>
<P>
   Mosleh not only attends Red Herring conferences but similar
forums sponsored by Technologic Partners, Garage.com (which
includes angel investors) and investment banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
