</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Kernel of Controversy at Biotech Forum
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Tom Abate &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Seattle _ A small band of protesters beating drums and dressed as
mutant ears of corn provided a cultural counterpoint to the 5,000
suit-clad biotech executives and scientists gathered here for the
industry's largest annual trade show.
</P>
<P>
   The 75 protesters marched outside the BIO '99 conference at
Washington State Convention Center to call attention to their fears
that genetically modified crops could pose risks to humans. That
position is rejected by biotech industry experts, who say Americans
have been eating genetically enhanced soybeans and other crops for
a decade with no ill effects.
</P>
<P>
   The protest, though noisy, went largely unnoticed by most trade
show attendees, who were preoccupied with the gloomy financial
outlook for biotech.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The five-day BIO '99 event, sponsored by the Biotechnology
Industry Organization, is the industry's largest annual gathering.
In addition to commercial exhibits of lab tools, the show features
dozens of seminars on topics ranging from how to secure venture
financing to how fruit fly genes can help us understand human
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever executives filled a meeting room, talk quickly centered
on the chronic cash shortage threatening hundreds of small biotech
firms and how young companies are coping with the fact that stock
investors have abandoned biotech in favor of the Internet
</P>
<P>
   ``When times are really bad, you get a huge showing at meetings
like this,'' said Richard Schneider of Seattle's Domain Associates
venture fund, after his talk about VC financing was moved to a
larger hall.
</P>
<P>
   Another Seattle venture capitalist, Robert Nelson of Arch
Venture Partners, summed up the industry's woes. Wall Street money
managers have stopped buying small biotech firms, shutting off the
flow not just of stock funds, but of private venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of only five or six venture firms in the whole country
that are willing to take the lead in funding'' new biotech
startups, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   With no end in sight to the funding drought that began last
summer, biotech startups must dramatically change how they do
business, said Doros Platika, chief executive of Ontogeny Inc., a
Massachusetts firm working on cancer drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Platika said young firms used to raise money to run the clinical
trials needed to win Food and Drug Administration approval for new
drugs. But that can take five years and cost $500 million, and
startups no longer have that time or money. So they sell their best
ideas to large drug companies and keep looking for new
breakthroughs in hopes that Wall Street will rediscover biotech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet bubble can't last forever,'' Platika said, adding
that demographic trends favor drugs and other biotech products.
``The Baby Boomers are aging; the nation will soon look like
Florida,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A more upbeat attitude pervaded the scientific panels where
researchers discussed promising fields like genomics, the use of
genes to predict or cure diseases and biologic traits.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Rubin, a geneticist at the University of California at
Berkeley, drew an overflow crowd in the 300-seat hall where he
explained how fruit fly studies help guide research on the genetic
causes of human diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Though far simpler biologically than humans, fruit flies have
many of the same basic genes as us higher life forms, Rubin said.
Because fruit flies go through their life cycle in 10 days, they
are ideal for studies of genetic mutations _ such as how a given
gene makes flies more sensitive to light over successive
generations. Studies like these might provide clues about inherited
blindness.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the controversy at the show occurred outside at the
demonstration. During one presentation yesterday, San Francisco
investment banker Steve Burrill reminded attendees that in Europe,
protests against genetically enhanced crops have sparked much
larger protests. Although Burrill thinks the protesters are wrong,
he warned that the uproar over so-called ``Frankenstein foods has
the potential to swamp the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Speakers at a seminar on clinical trials also discussed another
touchy subject yesterday. Earlier this week, a New York Times
investigation revealed that doctors routinely are paid to enroll
patients in clinical trials of new drugs and that in some
instances, unethical researchers have faked results to keep earning
study fees.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Newman of PharmaNet Inc., a New Jersey firm that conducts
clinical trials, said it is only fair that doctors get paid to
administer test drugs to patient volunteers, and he insisted that
the safeguards in place ensure that fraud is rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my 20 years in the industry,'' Newman said, ``we've made
mistakes, but there are many checks and balances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
