<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TURKEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUG OF WAR OVER A SCARF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each troubled society has its own symbols of conflict, and when
software engineer Merve Kavakci refused to remove her head scarf to
take the parliamentary oath as a new deputy in the Turkish
Parliament, the scarf became an emblem of the social and political
struggle between Turkey's Islamicists and its secularists.
</P>
<P>
   It is a conflict that means different things to different
people. For Turks who wish to preserve the secularizing tradition
of Kemal Ataturk, the founder of modern Turkey, the head scarf
symbolizes a defiant challenge from the Islamicists of Kavakci's
Virtue Party.
</P>
<P>
   For the Islamicists, the government's ban against the wearing of
head scarves in universities and government offices signifies an
intolerable intrusion into the religious life of Turkish Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Between the heirs of Ataturk and proponents of an Islamic
society, no middle ground seems possible. Secularists are fiercely
proud that Ataturk conferred on women the right to vote and a civil
status equal to men's. They regard the conquest of equal rights for
women as an achievement that defines the nationhood of modern
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   By depriving Kavakci of both her seat in Parliament and her
Turkish citizenship _ ostensibly because she acquired US
citizenship without the permission of Turkish authorities _ the
government was declaring that she could not simultaneously be a
good Turk and a good Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   Her symbolic act incited Turkey's president, Suleyman Demirel,
to accuse her of being an agent of foreign countries. Iran was the
one he named. In Iran, Ayatollah Ahmad Jannati, member of the
powerful Council of Guardians, derided Turkish authorities for
being ``so dogmatic, antireligious, and antifreedom that they
cannot tolerate half a meter of fabric on a woman's head.''
</P>
<P>
   The preferred American solution would be to let Turkish women
wear what they like while preserving all the civil rights Ataturk
instituted for them. But the American mentality may not be well
suited to understand the symbolic conflict over a lawmaker's head
scarf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
