<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUGH-GRANT-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUSHING AND FUMBLING, YET VERY SURE OF HIMSELF  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Is Hugh Grant the very model of a modern English
gentleman?
</P>
<P>
   He certainly seemed that way in ``Four Weddings and a Funeral,''
a hugely successful confection of a film largely kept afloat by his
bachelor character's diffident charm, self-deprecating wit and
endearing air of chronic embarrassment. (Grant's hair, which
flopped spectacularly onto his forehead in a patently non-American
way, played a fine supporting role in that 1994 movie.)
</P>
<P>
   Now he has been cast in the same mold in ``Notting Hill,'' a
comedy, opening on Friday, in which he plays the divorced, ironical
owner of a sleepy London bookstore whose life is turned upside down
by the sudden appearance of the world's most famous actress, played
by Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence exists that there is another side to Grant, 38,
however. There is his long-term relationship with his glamorous
girlfriend, the model, actress and producer Elizabeth Hurley, who
recently appeared in a British newspaper under the headline ``What
on earth will Liz Hurley wear next?'' along with photographic
evidence of her predilection for bosom-baring, thigh-skimming,
skintight outfits.
</P>
<P>
   There is also, of course, the memory of a notorious incident on
Sunset Boulevard in 1995, when Grant was charged with performing
``lewd acts'' with a prostitute who had the tabloid-friendly name
Divine Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there are the roles in which he has played against
type: the comically uptight husband in the strange Roman Polanski
film ``Bitter Moon'' (1992); the young Anglican priest in
``Sirens'' (1994); the earnest doctor who uncovers a murderous
scheme in ``Extreme Measures'' (1996), which was the first movie
produced by Simian Films, the company he and Ms. Hurley run
together. And finally, there is his own account of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``These roles play into a certain fantasy of what people want
English people to be,'' Grant said, referring to his characters in
``Four Weddings'' and ``Notting Hill.'' ``Whereas half the time, as
you know, we're vomiting beer and beating people up. I know I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in his chaotic office at Simian Films in central
London, preppily dressed in beige trousers, blue sweater, brown
suede shoes _ the ultrapolite, ultrahandsome Grant seemed an
unlikely candidate for a barroom brawl. He said ``Sorry?'' when he
lost his train of thought, and in a discussion of English accents,
he blushed with embarrassment at the memory of Prime Minister Tony
Blair's pseudopopulist effort to adopt a London street accent on a
talk show last year.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said that he detested the baseball caps he wears in a stab
at anonymity but that he would ``look even more of a prat if I wore
a fedora.''
</P>
<P>
   And when asked about Divine Brown, Grant made it clear that he
would prefer being strung up by his fingertips to being drawn into
public self-analysis of any kind. He raked his fingers through his
hair, only to have it fall back in his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God, people go through far worse things in their lives,''
he said, looking pained. ``You just take it on the chin.'' (In
fact, he pleaded no contest to the charges, paid a modest fine and
made an abject apology on Jay Leno's ``Tonight Show.'')
</P>
<P>
   Richard Curtis, who wrote ``Four Weddings'' as well as ``Notting
Hill,'' for which he also worked as executive producer, said he had
always had Grant in mind for the second film. ``He's always aware
that he's pretending; he doesn't get in so deep in it that he
completely believes he is the character,'' Curtis said. ``I love
him for his lack of responsibility, for his lack of feeling that
he's in a deeply serious business. On the set he gives out the
feeling that it's all good fun _ although I did notice that his
script was absolutely full of notes to himself on his character and
how he should say the lines.''
</P>
<P>
   He seems unlikely to say it himself (``He's happy to say at the
end of each take, `I'm the worst actor in the world,''' Curtis
said), but this is a particularly good time for Hugh Grant.
``Notting Hill'' doesn't pretend to be a vast departure from ``Four
Weddings'' _ in both movies, Grant falls in love with an elusive,
out-of-his-league American woman against a backdrop of controlled
comic mayhem _ but advance word has been close to ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   So confident are the filmmakers that they boldly rescheduled its
release to fall just nine days after the opening of ``Star Wars:
Episode One _ The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Another film, ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' which was produced by Simian
and which also stars Grant as a charming English auctioneer in New
York who finds himself in a pickle with the Mafia when he becomes
engaged to a mobster's daughter (Jeanne Tripplehorn), is also
playing to raves from test audiences; it opens on Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   And Grant recently found out that he's wanted for Woody Allen's
next film, one of those untitled projects that even the actors know
nothing about.
</P>
<P>
   Grant came to acting almost by accident, or at least that's what
he says (he has another very English trait: an inability to admit
to achievement through hard work). Born into a family he describes
as ``impoverished gentlefolk,'' he went to a local school in
Hammersmith, west London, where he briefly dipped into a street
accent of his own before graduating from Oxford with a degree in
English literature.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
