<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELFARE WISDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In dusting off a 130-year-old, long-forgotten provision of the
14th Amendment, the Supreme Court has placed a barrier in the way
of social jingoists who would target the poor for discriminatory
treatment. The court's protection of a class of welfare recipients
was a small step, but one of fundamental decency. And the principle
involved may have implications beyond welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   The case centered on a California law limiting public assistance
for recently arrived residents to the amount they would have
received in their home states. The court overturned the law in a
7-2 vote because it violated the 14th Amendment's requirement that
states accord the same standing to all citizens, newcomers and
natives alike.
</P>
<P>
   The provision is a sound one. The discriminatory treatment
mapped out by California _ and 15 other states, including Vermont,
Rhode Island, and New Hampshire _ was an expression of hostility to
the poor who move to other states in search of a better life.
California defended the action as a way to save $10.9 million in a
$2.9 billion annual welfare budget. Justice John Paul Stevens, who
wrote the majority opinion, exposed the hypocrisy of the claim by
pointing out that a similar saving could have been made by reducing
the monthly payments to all recipients by 72 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist, in dissenting, pointed out a
weakness in the majority's argument by finding no difference
between the welfare rule and similar state-imposed limitations on
gaining the right to vote, divorce, or lower tuition rates in
colleges and universities. His dissent may open the way to
challenges of those rules as well.
</P>
<P>
   While the principle of state control is firmly established and
contributes to lively debate about competing concepts of tax
policy, education, and similar issues, discrimination among classes
of citizens is unacceptable. The court has done a service with the
ruling. In the process, it has helped a small group of people who
are in demonstrable need of equal treatment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Z
</P>
</TEXT>
