<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFERS-EYESURGERY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLFERS FIND LASER SURGERY A SIGHT FOR POOR EYES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ Fred Funk never envisioned a turnaround in his
golf game. He simply wanted to regain the ability to read a bedside
alarm clock without squinting.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But two days after undergoing laser eye surgery, Funk found
himself atop the leader board at the 1998 Kemper Open. He finished
third.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Funk broke a two-year victory drought, winning
the Deposit Guaranty Golf Classic. Three months after that, Funk
finished second at the Buick Challenge. By the time the 1998 season
ended, Funk had carved out his first $1 million season in 10 years
on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, Funk is puzzled by the golfer's equivalent of the
chicken-and-egg riddle: Which came first, better swings or a better
view of those swings? But he knows that laser eye surgery, for the
nearsighted golfer, has a lot in common with chicken soup for the
infirm player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure hasn't hurt,'' said Funk, who ranks 43rd on the season
money list with $436,453 heading into the opening round of the
MasterCard Colonial tomorrow at Colonial Country Club. ``I've
played some awfully good golf since I had it done. It's certainly
been a factor in my game getting better, but I don't know how
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Funk is among a growing group of golfers who have undergone a
surgical procedure called laser in situ keratomileusis, or LASIK,
in the past two years. Some, such as Funk and Fort Worth resident
Mark Brooks, have enjoyed tangible turnarounds in their on-course
performance. Others have not.
</P>
<P>
   But the procedure has been deemed enough of a success that it is
gaining popularity among professional athletes. Colonial
competitors Corey Pavin, Paul Stankowski, Kenny Perry and Tom Kite
have undergone LASIK since the start of the 1998 season. In the
past year, they've been joined by Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman,
race-car driver Bryan Herta and a slew of major-league baseball
players, including Wade Boggs, Wally Joyner, Bernard Gilkey and Al
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure, known as a ``flap and zap'' in the medical
industry, involves a surgeon folding back tissue from the surface
of the eyeball while a laser reshapes the cornea to improve the
patient's vision to 20-20 or better. Industry analysts predicted
that more than 725,000 LASIK procedures will be done this year in
the United States, compared with 22,000 when the surgery was
introduced in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors caution that some people are not candidates for the
surgery, which costs about $2,000 per eye, and that there are
risks. In some cases, the correction might not be permanent. And
there is no proven correlation between improved vision and improved
athletic performance.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one thing is certain, said Brooks, who underwent the
procedure April 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worth it, from a quality-of-life standpoint,'' said
Brooks, who waved goodbye to corrective lenses after 25 years. ``In
my mind, what I did is permanent. But even if you told me, `We'll
give you 20-20, but you have to go through the surgery every five
years to keep it,' I'd still do it. There's no question it's an
advantage to see better.''
</P>
<P>
   The early effects on Brooks' golf game are encouraging. Since
undergoing the surgery, Brooks has broken or matched par in seven
consecutive rounds at PGA Tour events, his longest stretch of the
season. Pavin, a two-time Colonial champ who had his eyes done in
November, has won more money at tour events this season ($270,029)
than in the previous two combined.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said he finds himself backing off fewer putts since the
surgery. Pavin said his judgment of distance might be more acute.
But both emphasized that the difference in vision quality is
minimal when compared with how they saw the world through
prescription contact lenses.
</P>
<P>
   The joy, however, rests in not having to fumble for glasses in
the middle of the night and not worrying about lost or torn
contacts. For Kite, who had worn glasses for 36 years before having
the LASIK procedure in January 1998, the payoff comes in improved
peripheral vision and in not having to wipe lenses when playing in
rain. For allergy sufferers such as Brooks and Tom Byrum, the
surgery can cut back on watery eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Byrum, who finished 51st Sunday in the GTE Byron Nelson Classic,
said he is able to keep his eyes clear during rounds with
prescription eye drops that he could not take while wearing
contacts. Like Brooks and Stankowski, he also finds himself making
quicker, truer reads on the greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're putting, you stare at the line so much that your
contacts tend to dry out,'' Byrum said. ``So you blink to try and
make them comfortable, and sometimes it doesn't work. I used to hit
a lot of putts with one eye closed, but that's not a distraction
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Most players said the procedure, which takes a matter of
seconds, is painless and has resulted in immediate vision
improvement with no side effects. Perry, however, had to stare into
the laser for a second time after his initial session did not
produce the desired correction in October 1998. Since then, Perry
said he has struggled with depth perception and relied on his
caddie to read more putts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he wouldn't change anything about the experience, Perry
said, because his allergy concerns have been minimized.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been awesome. My eyes aren't irritated when I play. I
don't get junk in my contacts anymore,'' said Perry, who is 95th on
the money list ($195,690) after finishing 58th in 1998. ``I'm just
going through an adjustment period. Over time, I think everything
will settle in. At first, I thought I did the wrong thing. Now, I
know I did the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stankowski, a Flower Mound resident, is equally convinced. He
underwent the procedure last summer in Dallas while 25 prospective
patients watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some second thoughts right before the surgery. Having a
guy cut on your eyeball is not a pleasant thought,'' Stankowski
said. ``But I knew the success rate was phenomenal and I figured,
`Why not?' If it works, I'll be hassle-free for a long time. If
not, I'll go into broadcasting.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his PGA Tour success rate dipped immediately after the
surgery, Stankowski is far from the broadcast booth. He finished
96th on last season's money list, down 75 spots from 1997, but has
rebounded to No. 81 heading into Colonial, with $235,114 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Said Brooks: ``It's not something you do for your golf game.
It's something you do for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   But if your golf game improves along with it, no one on the PGA
Tour will blink back tears of regret.
</P>
<P>
   Eye-catching results The money-list positions of selected
players in the MasterCard Colonial in their last full season before
undergoing laser eye surgery compared with their immediate,
postsurgical results: Player Before (year) After (year) Mark Brooks
129th (1998) 66th (1999) Corey Pavin 155th (1998) 68th (1999) Fred
Funk 38th (1997) 23rd (1998) Paul Stankowski 21st (1997) 96th
(1998) Kenny Perry 58th (1998) 95th (1999) Tom Kite 35th (1997)
159th (1998)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
