<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2286 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUGH-GRANT-FILMS-2NDT     05-18 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUGH-GRANT-FILMS-2NDTAKE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LONDON: English literature.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was all set to pursue a master's degree in the history of art
at the Courtauld Institute when, he said, he decided to take a
``joke detour into acting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be a laugh,'' he said. ``I ended up in the
Nottingham Playhouse, playing parts like Tree in Wind and Third
Shouting Peasant.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling restless, he and some friends set up a comedy review,
``The Jockeys of Norfolk'' (the title is from a throwaway
Shakespeare line), which was a huge hit in fringe theater but
bombed on television.
</P>
<P>
   From there came roles in films like ``Maurice,'' as well as a
selection of American television projects, including Judith
Krantz's ``Till We Meet Again,'' in which he played Courtney Cox's
brother, and ``Our Sons,'' a movie of the week in which he was cast
as gay man whose lover was dying of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   And then came his ``slough of unemployment,'' during which Grant
whiled away his days at the London Library, matching activity to
mood by writing a novel called ``Slack,'' about ``a person whose
life has nothing in it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to write something in the morning and think, `I'm a
genius,' then go out for a chicken sandwich and come back and throw
it away,'' Grant said. He was at a low ebb when he was called in to
read for Mike Newell's ``Four Weddings'': ``I was told that the
casting director said, `You'll meet Hugh Grant for this part over
my dead body.'''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Curtis had his doubts. ``He came in claiming that he
was on his last legs, that acting was no job for an adult to do,''
Curtis said. ``And I was against him, because I thought he might be
too posh. But he wasn't. Casting him was the luckiest break in my
career.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Four Weddings'' had a budget of about $5 million and was shot
in 36 days. ``There were scenes that we shot where literally we had
five minutes to get through a two-page scene,'' Grant recalled
fondly. ``Someone would say, `Stand against the wall!' and we'd all
stand against the wall and say our lines.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, ``Notting Hill,'' directed by Roger Michell, had a
budget of $43 million, considerable star power in Grant and Ms.
Roberts and a luxurious 10-week shooting schedule. ``I could have
put the trailer I had in `Four Weddings' into the fridge of my
trailer in `Notting Hill,''' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   Joking aside, it would be a mistake to underestimate Grant, his
friends say, particularly in his newfound role as producer. ``There
was a funny new look in his eyes when he talked about `Mickey Blue
Eyes,' a responsibility and maturity that I'm not used to in him,''
Curtis said.
</P>
<P>
   And underneath what she described as an ``incredibly charming,
slightly amusing, fumbling and self-deprecating person,'' Ms.
Roberts found her co-star to have more gravitas than his screen
persona, or even he, would allow. ``Hugh is a formidable person
with a very strong sense of self,'' she said. ``He's incredibly
clear about who he is and what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Has success changed Hugh Grant? Of course it has: after the
interview, he caught the Concorde to New York and then spent the
evening with Ms. Hurley at the VH1 Divas Live '99 concert at the
Beacon Theater, where Ms. Hurley introduced one of the singers.
(Versace sent over a suit for him to wear, while Ms. Hurley,
according to The Daily Mail, appeared in a daringly bare ``sideless
dress.'')
</P>
<P>
   But that's not really him, he says. ``I still think like an
unemployed actor living in Hammersmith,'' Grant said. ``If someone
said to me, `I'm sorry, Hugh, but a law's just been passed and
you're not allowed to act anymore in your life,' I'd be thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   There's always the London Library, and the career that never
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just go back to my sad old fantasy about writing a book.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
