<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2287 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEWLIS-BESIEGED-FILM     05-18 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEWLIS-BESIEGED-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR AN ACTOR, A ROLE IS AN ENIGMA TILL THE FINAL CUT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When actors sign up for a movie, they rarely have much
notion how it _ or they _ will end up looking on screen. David
Thewlis learned that some years ago with Mike Leigh. He duly
followed the British director's ritual of spending weeks creating a
character down to the tiniest detail.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Life Is Sweet,'' he was reduced to licking chocolate off
Jane Horrocks' breasts. With ``Naked,'' on the other hand, he won
the best actor prize at the 1993 Cannes Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   With his latest film, Bernardo Bertolucci's ``Besieged,'' which
opened in New York on Friday, Thewlis was equally unsure what to
expect. It is a minimalist film set almost entirely in a Roman
palazzo, a love story between two people who are seldom seen
together, who barely exchange words and about whom we learn little.
But this time, at least, Thewlis was pleasantly surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were making it, I sometimes forgot Bertolucci was
directing it and I worried that it would be very dull or it
wouldn't work or there was something implausible about the whole
scenario,'' he recalled in a recent conversation in a central
London hotel. ``When I saw it, I really liked it and it surprised
me because I felt I was watching something totally new. I was in it
and Thandie Newton was in it, but it didn't feel like the film we
had made.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie, adapted by Bertolucci and his wife, Clare Peploe,
from James Lasdun's short story ``The Siege,'' is about a British
pianist, Kinsky, who lives beside the Spanish Steps in a crumbling
mansion full of paintings and sculptures. He takes on as his
part-time housekeeper a beautiful young African woman, Shandurai
(Ms. Newton), who needs a home while she studies medicine.
</P>
<P>
   We learn that she fled to Rome from her native country after her
husband was arrested for opposing a grisly dictatorship. But Kinsky
falls for her long before she reveals she is married.
</P>
<P>
   While he plays his piano upstairs and she plays African music
downstairs, they gradually grow used to each other, although, ever
the gentleman, Kinsky makes no further advances. Shandurai notices
with puzzlement, however, that his art objects are slowly
disappearing from his house. When his beloved piano is finally
taken away, she realizes that he is raising money to buy her
husband's freedom. Whether he is doing this out of altruism or to
win Shandurai's love is never clear. In the end, it does not
matter.
</P>
<P>
   The $3 million film, Bertolucci's first since ``Stealing
Beauty,'' is a far cry from some of his recent big-screen
extravaganzas like ``The Last Emperor,'' ``The Sheltering Sky'' and
``Little Buddha.'' Rather, in its intimacy, it seems closer to his
much earlier ``Last Tango in Paris,'' although that film's sexual
violence is replaced here by gentle sensuality, perhaps the
difference between Bertolucci, age 32, and Bertolucci, age 59.
</P>
<P>
   Bertolucci said he had cast Thewlis as Kinsky because he liked
him in ``Naked,'' but also because he wanted someone ``in the great
tradition of English eccentricity'' to draw a sharp contrast with
Ms. Newton's Shandurai.
</P>
<P>
   `At the beginning of the film, he exhibits a kind of fantastic
awkwardness,'' Bertolucci said in a telephone interview from Rome,
where he was recovering from back surgery. ``In the dusty, decadent
atmosphere of this house, you have tapestries, paintings, carpets,
old furniture, a piano and you also have him. He is part of that
world of European culture. And in the end, he becomes kind of
attractive. But I wanted Kinsky to be mysterious even to the actor
playing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Why is he living in this big house? How did this situation arise
in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   ``The only hint was that Kinsky had inherited the mansion from
an aunt,'' Thewlis, 36, recalled. ``But Bernardo was very much into
letting it remain an enigma. Certainly not the Mike Leigh approach.
But I was happy with that. I don't think it's always necessary to
plot a whole back story.''
</P>
<P>
   It was necessary, however, for Thewlis to learn to play the
piano, at least sufficiently for the camera to pan from his face to
his hands on more than one occasion. The Italian composer Alessio
Vlad, who also wrote some of the movie score, was his teacher. And
the result, Thewlis said proudly, is a fair rendering of 45 seconds
of Grieg, 45 seconds of Mozart and 45 seconds of Bach.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that he was musical. In fact, growing up in the
northern seaside resort of Blackpool, he had originally planned to
become a rock star. With two friends, he formed a small band: he
wrote, sang and played the guitar. But when the friends decided to
go to drama school in London, he followed suit, although he had
never before thought of acting as a career.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After drama school he had no trouble finding work, in
commercials, on the stage, and eventually in some movies. He worked
first with Mike Leigh in the late 1980s in a short film, ``The
Short and Curlies,'' in which he played a man who told bad jokes.
In ``Life Is Sweet'' (1990), he was the chocolate licker. Then,
with ``Naked'' (1993), he made his name as Johnny, a drifter turned
manic philosopher who roams the streets and minds of London.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my films grow out of the strength of the people
involved,'' Leigh explained, ``and `Naked' evolved when I
recognized an actor who could do this extraordinary thing of both
creating this character without sentimentality and getting inside
the guy's brain. David is a tremendously original and intelligent
and committed actor. That's the truth of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thewlis, though, initially considered his role in ``Naked'' a
sort of compensation for ending up with just two scenes in ``Life
Is Sweet'' after doing ``all that famous research.'' But when the
film came out, earning him best actor awards from the New York Film
Critics Circle and the National Society of Film Critics as well as
the Cannes jury, everything changed.
</P>
<P>
   ```Naked' propelled me into a whole other league,'' he said.
``America started calling. I went over to Los Angeles and met all
those people, and I started doing a few American films of various
levels of quality. A couple of years ago, I made a decision to come
back home. I always kept a place here, but I hung out in Los
Angeles longer than I probably should have done.''
</P>
<P>
   The results were mixed. He appeared in Rob Cohen's
``Dragonheart'' and Michael Hoffman's ``Restoration,'' and he did a
comic turn in the Coen brothers' movie ``The Big Lebowski.'' He was
also in two films savaged by critics: Agnieszka Holland's ``Total
Eclipse,'' in which he played Verlaine to Leonardo DiCaprio's
Rimbaud, and John Frankenheimer's ``Island of Dr. Moreau,'' with
Marlon Brando, which he cheerfully called ``one of the worst films
ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Brad Pitt's climbing companion in Jean-Jacques
Annaud's ``Seven Years in Tibet,'' Thewlis at least enjoyed
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the experience,'' he recalled. ``A massive beautiful
adventure. I don't think it is a great film, but it was six months
in Argentina, Canada and some serious mountain climbing training in
Austria.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Thewlis appeared in ``Divorcing Jack,'' a comedy
about Northern Ireland's Troubles, which has not been released in
the United States. He is also preparing to play a London hoodlum in
a new movie called, ``Gangster No. 1.'' But his mind seems
elsewhere. After what he describes as a series of disastrous
relationships, he is determined to make a success of his new
relationship with a British actress.
</P>
<P>
   And to avoid disrupting it, he even postponed directing his
first film, ``Cheeky,'' for which he also wrote the screenplay.
``It's not my ambition to direct lots of films,'' he said. ``I
think if I direct one film in my whole life, why rush it?''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, at his home overlooking Hampstead Heath, he is working
on his first novel, which was commissioned by a British publisher
and has the working title of ``The Blind Man's Story.'' The
introspection required of writing seems to suit his reflective
personality. Acting, he said, is simply a convenient way of making
money while he explores other avenues. But he has not forgotten
that every film is a gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``My next one has a great, great script,'' he said. ``That's the
sort of thing you say when you're about to start. `It's a great
script.''' He paused and smiled mischievously. ``Then when it comes
out, you say, `I don't know why I did it. It's a disaster.' You
just never know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
