<HEADLINE>
PRIME MINISTER-ELECT BARAK PREACHES UNITY, PEACE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see Israel-Barak) 
 
By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The day after his landslide election victory, Prime
Minister-elect Ehud Barak made pilgrimages Tuesday to the holiest
site in Judaism and the grave of assassinated leader Yitzhak Rabin
_ preaching messages of national unity and peace with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``A circle has been closed here at the grave of Yitzhak Rabin,''
said Barak, 57. ``A possibility has been opened to fulfill the
legacy of Yitzhak Rabin, and I am committed to that path.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabin, who signed two peace treaties with the Palestinians, was
assassinated in 1995 by an ultranationalist opposed to giving up
land for peace.
</P>
<P>
   At the Western Wall, Judaism's most sacred site, Barak said,
``Just as we knew how to come together in the most difficult of
tests, including the painful and wrenching test of liberating
Jerusalem and returning to the Wall, it is right we should apply
this same spirit of unity to life in Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The symbolic visits to the Western Wall _ believed to be part of
the wall that surrounded Herod's temple _ and Rabin's grave
underscored Barak's promise that he would be a leader for all
Israelis and would bring peace to the country.
</P>
<P>
   Barak won election Monday with 56 percent of the vote, ousting
conservative Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who received 43.9
percent of the vote
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-nine percent of Israel's voters turned out.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after the elections, bulldozers resumed work at two
controversial building sites in areas of Jerusalem claimed by
Palestinians, Har Homa and Ras el-Amud.
</P>
<P>
   Work at both sites had prompted Palestinian demonstrations when
they began more than a year ago and, in the case of Har Homa, led
to a breakdown in the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians, who hope to make east Jerusalem the capital of
their future state, called on Barak to halt the construction of the
Jewish housing areas being built by settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is expected to begin tough negotiations Sunday to form a
coalition government that will include his One Israel Party, which
received 27 seats, making it the largest group in the 120-member
Parliament, or Knesset, and several other smaller parties.
</P>
<P>
   A potential coalition partner that appeared unlikely only 24
hours earlier was the right-wing Likud Party, headed by Netanyahu
until he resigned minutes after a grueling defeat Monday night. The
Likud won only 19 seats, down from 32 it had held in a three-way
coalition. It is the second-largest party in the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Sharon, a security hawk and foreign minister in
Netanyahu's government, was nominated as acting party head. Party
delegates will vote on a temporary leader May 25.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said he hoped to bring enough political allies into the
governing coalition to be able to move ahead with a comfortable
majority behind him when he enters talks with the Palestinians. A
broad coalition would also make it easier to reach a deal with the
Syrians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to form the widest government possible,'' said Yossi
Beilin, a top Labor Party official who helped craft the first two
peace agreements with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Other probable coalition partners included the left-wing Meretz
Party, which has nine seats; the Russian Immigrants Party, led by
Natan Sharansky, which took seven seats; the Center Party, led by
former Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, which has six seats, and
a new workers' party, which received two seats.
</P>
<P>
   It was not known whether the country's third-largest party,
Shas, would be asked to enter coalition negotiations. Shas, which
won 17 seats in the new Parliament, represents ultra-Orthodox Jews
from Middle Eastern countries.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Barak's left-wing allies have threatened to stay out
of a coalition if it invited Shas to join. The party controlled
religious matters in Netanyahu's administration, provoking the ire
of some of Israel's secular parties, including the newly formed
Shinui, or Change, Party, headed by Yosef ``Tommy'' Lapid. The
party, which advertised an anti-religious platform, won six seats
in the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Barak had said earlier that he would not begin negotiations with
Shas as long as its leader, Aryeh Deri, stayed on. He had been
convicted of corruption charges. In a surprise development Tuesday,
Deri stepped down, making it easier for Shas' other leaders to
petition Barak to join his coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Four parties are likely to remain in the opposition. They
include the pro-settlement National Religious Party, which dwindled
to five seats; the ultra-Orthodox United Torah Judaism, which also
took five seats; the ultra-nationalist Herut Party, which won three
seats, and a second Russian immigrant party, called Israel-Our
Home, which gained four seats.
</P>
<P>
   The three Arab parties _ United Arab List, Haddash and Balad _
received five, three and two seats, respectively. They are not
expected to join the government.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has 45 days to form a coalition, but many analysts
predicted that he will try to put together a government by June 7,
when the Knesset is due back in session.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Palestinian President Yasser Arafat called Barak to
congratulate him.
</P>
<P>
   Some senior Palestinian officials said they were concerned about
what they termed troubling signs that there was little substantive
difference in the basic positions held by Barak and Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak's tough statements, which were made in the euphoria of
victory, are a source of concern for us,'' said Arafat's economic
adviser, Khaled Salam. ``They are rejected and unjustified.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
