<HEADLINE>
STATE'S UNEMPLOYMENT RATE FOR APRIL WAS LOWEST IN 33 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL VIRGIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boeing keeps cutting, job growth in the Seattle area keeps
slowing, but the state still managed to post its lowest April
unemployment rate in 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Employment Security Department said Tuesday the jobless rate
was 4.4 percent in April, down from 5 percent in March and just
under the 4.5 percent reported for the state in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the unemployment rate (not seasonally adjusted) was
4 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   That 4.4 percent rate came despite another month of heavy
cutting by The Boeing Co. In fact, the aircraft and parts category
showed the heaviest month-to-month drop _ 2,600 workers _ since
Boeing began cutting back its work force 10 months ago. Aircraft
employment is now down 11,100 jobs, or 10 percent from its peak,
the department said.
</P>
<P>
   That helped pull year-to-year job growth in the Seattle
metropolitan area (defined as King, Snohomish and Island counties)
to 2 percent, meaning that job growth for the state as a whole, at
2.6 percent, is actually higher; for many months the Seattle area
was growing faster. Higher-than-normal hiring in construction and
services is credited with the expansion of overall statewide
employment.
</P>
<P>
   But if job growth is slowing, why isn't the unemployment rate in
the Seattle area budging? For April the jobless rate was 3.1
percent, down from the 3.4 percent reported for March and about
even with the 3 percent reported a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors are at work. One is that the numbers are
preliminary and could be revised. Another is that the economy is,
in fact, still growing, and there's some trickle-down effect from
expansion in industries like aerospace and software. Unemployment
usually drops in spring and summer anyway, as seasonal businesses
open and start hiring.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is that job growth and the unemployment rate
aren't directly connected. As Roberta Pauer, the department's
regional labor economist for the Seattle area, noted in a recent
analysis, the unemployment rate merely measures the number of
unemployed workers, divided by the size of the labor force _
including those who are employed as well as those seeking work. The
number of jobs in the area isn't directly a part of the
calculation.
</P>
<P>
   Both components of the unemployment rate are affected by people
moving into or out of the region, Pauer wrote. Because the economy
in the rest of the country is doing well, there are fewer people
being pushed to this area without jobs but looking for work. News
of Boeing cuts, meanwhile, reduces the pull of those coming to this
region without a job already lined up.
</P>
<P>
   From April 1998 to April 1999, the Seattle -area's labor force
grew at just 1.8 percent. From April 1997 to April 1998, the labor
force grew at 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a Puget Sound labor force growing much more modestly than
a few years ago as in-migration has subsided, our local
unemployment rate remains low despite our slowing economy,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate for Tacoma and Pierce County was 4 percent
in April, down from 4.6 percent in March and 4.4 percent in April
1998. In Bremerton and Kitsap County, the jobless rate was 4.6
percent in April, 5.1 percent in March and 5 percent a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
