<HEADER>
A2295 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-BOTTLE-BOMB-COX     05-18 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-BOTTLE-BOMB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students return to Ohio school where bottle bomb exploded
 &HT;    By Margo Rutledge Kissell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENE COUNTY, Ohio _ It wasn't the upbeat motivational speech
Ben Holaday had planned to deliver to the Ankeney Junior High
School students.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, tears welled in his eyes at times as he stood Tuesday
before about 285 ninth-graders sitting on gymnasium bleachers, one
day after a bottle bomb exploded in the Beavercreek school's
crowded cafeteria, causing the 880-student school to be evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   No students or teachers were injured, but a security guard
suffered minor burns when she touched the device that two students
allegedly made and brought to school. The teens _ a 16-year-old boy
and a 14-year-old boy _ were charged with delinquency counts of
inducing panic and criminal damaging. They remain in the Greene
County Juvenile Detention Center and are scheduled to be arraigned
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While Holaday, a former police officer, has spent the past 10
years giving motivational talks to hundreds of thousands of kids
across the country, Monday's incident hit close to home for him:
His 15-year-old son, Ben, is a ninth-grader at Ankeney. Holaday
told the students he was ``absolutely terrified'' when he saw a
news helicopter hovering near the school and arrived to find police
and fire trucks there and the school cordoned off with yellow
police tape.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said about 25 students more than normal were
absent from school Tuesday and Holaday said fear probably kept them
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to let fear control us and we are not going
to let this incident change our way of life and make us afraid,''
he told students in the warm gymnasium that was so quiet throughout
his 30-minute speech that one could hear the hum from the ceiling
lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to become a bunch of scared deer lifting our
head up at every sound that goes on and we are not going to run in
fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Ninth-grader Emily Reinhart, 15, was moved by Holaday's speech.
``I think he really hit home for some people,'' she said, adding
she still feels safe at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Principal David Elliott told the students that two suspects
spent the night behind bars and appeared in court Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not going to see them anymore. They won't be back here
this year,'' he told seventh-, eighth- and ninth-grade assemblies.
Suspension hearings have not yet been held, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Beavercreek Police Sgt. George Moody said the 14-year-old came
to the police station Monday evening with his parents to turn
himself in. Greene County Juvenile Court Judge Robert Hutcheson on
Tuesday returned the two students to the detention center until
Thursday's arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys representing the teens said neither has had
significant disciplinary problems in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Hutcheson, who already had five other Greene County students
come before him for making serious threats at school in recent
weeks, suggested parents need to have frank discussions with their
children about the implications of such threats because of
heightened awareness since the Littleton, Colo., tragedy, where 15
died.
</P>
<P>
   ``The panic button gets pushed when these stunts get pulled. It
keeps everyone on edge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Prosecutor Sigurd Peterson said authorities think the
two teens worked together to create the homemade bottle bomb
containing some sort of chemical cleaning agent that will be
analyzed at the Miami Valley Crime Lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``They filled the bottle before going to school and then went to
school and did some final preparations, then placed the bottle in
the trash can in the cafeteria and shortly thereafter there was the
explosion,'' Peterson said. ``This was not something done on the
spur of the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The teens could be committed to the Department of Youth Services
until age 21 if convicted of inducing panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caused panic throughout the entire school, it had to be
evacuated. Given the current situation, I think the school and
everyone responded very appropriately to this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott told the students they will have school every day until
the end of the school year, June 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are the people who will determine what the last 22 days of
school are like, whether they are going to be peaceful days or
whether they are going to be chaotic days,'' Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   Margo Rutledge Kissell writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
