<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; COMBAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO wound up the eighth week of its air campaign with heavy
air raids across Serbia.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO accused Serbian forces of trying to cover up evidence of
massacres by having bodies removed from mass graves and reburied.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIPLOMACY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott met Russia's Balkans
envoy in Helsinki. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan criticized the
United States for taking military action without Security Council
consent and China and Russia for ignoring ethnic purges.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER DEVELOPMENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Two Serbian soldiers held by the United States were returned
to Yugoslavia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Two members of a U.N. team in Yugoslavia to assess civilian
needs were injured in a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE WEB &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict is available from The New
York Times on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2300 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-ART-2NDTA     05-18 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: its campaign. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton said that while he believed NATO's airstrikes had been
effective, ``I don't think that we or our allies should take any
options off the table and that has been my position from the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton has said from the March 24 start of the air war that
he had ``no intention'' of sending ground forces into a hostile
environment in the Balkans. As he explained in an interview on
March 31, ``The thing that bothers me about introducing ground
troops into a hostile situation _ into Kosovo and into the Balkans
_ is the prospect of never being able to get them out.''
</P>
<P>
   And three weeks ago he squelched an attempt by Britain to
reintroduce the topic at the NATO summit in Washington. Asked at a
news conference April 24 if a buildup of troops was preparation for
a ground invasion, the president said, ``No. The short answer is
no.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's disinclination to use ground troops has been
sufficiently clear that numerous military analysts, and retired
Gen. Colin Powell, have criticized the position as a strategic
blunder for signaling to the enemy just how far the allies would
go.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman, asserted Tuesday that
the president was not shifting his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it's prudent to always consider all of your options and
stay updated, which we are, given the assessments that are going
on, there's no change in our policy,'' he said. ``The president
believes we're going to get to where we need to get through the air
campaign and that we will get the conditions that we've laid out.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the air campaign was effective because it was
driving Milosevic toward negotiations. ``You've seen reports today
out of Belgrade that senior government officials are talking about
wanting a diplomatic solution, trying to find a way out,'' Lockhart
said. ``It's because the campaign is working.''
</P>
<P>
   But the administration is concerned, as Clinton said last week,
that ``refugee fatigue'' may be settling in among the public, and a
new poll from the Pew Research Center shows that while a majority
of Americans still support the war, that support has ebbed over the
last month. The Pew survey reflects similar findings in other polls
conducted recently.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of American participation in the conflict has fallen to
53 percent from 62 percent in mid-April, the poll found. Fewer
Americans _ 32 percent _ are paying very close attention to the war
now than were just three weeks ago, and among them, support has
dropped 21 percent so that a majority now oppose airstrikes
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is really wavering,'' said Andrew Kohut, director
of the center. ``That wavering is a combination of concern about
the unintended casualties and that the public doesn't think we're
winning.'' The public is almost evenly divided over whether to send
ground troops, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who has been a strong critic of the
administration's reluctance to use ground force, said that he
believed Clinton would seek some sort of settlement before sending
in ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're under great pressure,'' McCain, who is seeking the
Republican nomination for president, said in an interview Tuesday.
``I think they'll frantically seek a deal _ a dirty compromise _
and spin it and hope the Dow continues to go up. The whole thing is
very dispiriting.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberals too are adding their voice to the call for ground
troops. Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, said ground troops would be needed
to force Milosevic to yield to bend to NATO demands. ``I am not
convinced that air power alone will get his forces out of Kosovo,''
Harkin said Tuesday after a three-day trip to the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Mellman, a Democratic pollster, said that these polls
``are making a mountain out of a molehill of changes in public
opinion.'' He added, ``You have some high-profile things like the
Chinese embassy thing and it causes a blip. Nobody's enthusiastic
about war. But there is certainly not anything like majority
opposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
