A2302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-18 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: TORTURE OR SUICIDE ATTEMPT?
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said the imprisoned husband of former Prime
Minister Benazir Bhutto, Asif Ali Zardari, cut his own neck with a
broken glass in a suicide attempt during an interrogation. Ms.
Bhutto issued a statement accusing the government of trying to kill
her husband. Zardari was recently sentenced to five years in prison
on corruption charges and is accused of killing his wife's
estranged brother, Murtaza, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Hari Kumar
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: JAILED EDITOR ALLOWED A VISIT
</P>
<P>
   An imprisoned newspaper editor, Najam Sethi, will be allowed a
visit by his wife, children and attorney, the Supreme Court has
ruled. The journalist was arrested May 8 for alleged anti-state
crimes and has been held incommunicado.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Barry Bearak
</P>
<P>
   NEPAL: HOPE FOR A MANDATE
</P>
<P>
   Early election returns have raised hopes in the Nepali Congress
party that it will win a majority of the lower house's 205 seats,
ending five years of revolving-door coalition governments. In 132
races where votes have been counted, the party has won 33 seats and
leads in another 45, according to the Election Commission. Its main
rival, the Communist Party of Nepal-United Marxist-Leninist, has
won 17 seats and leads in 32 races.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Barry Bearak
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA: MINE TREATY RATIFIED
</P>
<P>
   The legislature ratified the Ottawa Convention, an international
treaty banning the manufacture and use of land mines. Cambodia
remains one of the most heavily mined countries in the world. More
than 1,000 people were killed or maimed last year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Seth Mydans
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN, BRITAIN: RELATIONS RESUMED
</P>
<P>
   The two countries marked an end to a 20-year rift by restoring
ambassadorial relations. The move followed Iran's decision last
September to distance itself from threats against Salman Rushdie,
the author sentenced to death by Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini in
1989 for blasphemy against Islam. The new British ambassador,
Nicholas Browne, is the first that Britain has dispatched to Iran
since the Islamic revolution of 1979. Gholamreza Ansari will be the
Iranian ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Douglas Jehl
</P>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: ALTERED CROPS APPROVED
</P>
<P>
   The government has lifted its prohibition on the cultivation of
genetically altered crops, paving the way for the local subsidiary
the of Monsanto Corporation to begin selling modified seeds to
soybean farmers. Brazil is the world's second-largest grower of
soybeans, behind the U.S. Approval of the herbicide-resistant seeds
had been fought by environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Larry Rohter
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: VIOLENCE IN STUDENT STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   Three student leaders of a strike that has shut down the
National Autonomous University of Mexico who were abducted and
beaten in the last week accused strike opponents of organizing the
attacks. Students are protesting the first tuition increase in 51
years.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Rick Wills
</P>
<P>
   COMOROS
</P>
<P>
   FRENCHMAN FACES PRISON
</P>
<P>
   A French prosecutor asked for a 12-to-15-year sentence for Bob
Denard, a 70-year-old former mercenary on trial for killing
President Ahmed Abdallah in 1989. Denard, who has been involved in
uprisings in the Belgian Congo, Angola and elsewhere, commanded the
Comoros presidential guard at the time of the killing. He had
denied that he shot Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Marlise Simons
</P>
