<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOINOVICH-BALKAN-TRIP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio Senator calls for bombing stoppage
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. George Voinovich returned from a weekend in
the Balkans and by renewed his call for an immediate halt in the
bombing campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Republican has sternly opposed the NATO strategy
of using bombs to get Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to
relinquish military control of Kosovo, and said Tuesday that peace
should be given another chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that we have nothing to lose,'' Voinovich said,
``and at least we can say we've given that one another try.''
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich, who is of Serbian and Slovenia ancestry, spent three
days meeting with officials in Bulgaria and Turkey _ two border
countries _ in addition to visiting a refugee camp in Albania and a
military briefing in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   He said leaders of neighboring countries told him they oppose a
ground war, which has been contemplated, but no provisions have
been made for invasion. They're eager to see the hostilities end at
the bargaining table, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In effect, the whole region's economy has been shut down,''
Voinovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich echoed the concerns of others who have traveled to the
Balkans, including U.S. Rep. Tony Hall (D-Dayton, Ohio) in saying
that the tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians living in tent
cities will need more food and other provisions as their time in
the camps drags on.
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday, U.S. Rep. David L. Hobson (R-Springfield, Ohio)
announced that he will lead a group on a weekend trip to the
region.
</P>
<P>
   But Voinovich wasn't swayed from his opposition to the air war
after visiting a refugee camp. He said he told NATO Commander Gen.
Wesley Clark that he wants to stop the bombing long enough to spark
peace talks, but Clark told him he would oppose relenting on the
air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich wants NATO to drop leaflets on Belgrade, explaining
that the war is not against them but their leader. By taking a
``five or six'' day break in the bombing, Voinovich said NATO would
be showing the Serbian people that they aren't the targets of the
military action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be pausing to let things develop diplomatically,''
Voinovich said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Milosevic might be willing to end his military
crusade to clear Albanians out of Kosovo if NATO appeals to the
``better instincts of the man'' by halting the air war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bombing has been very effective,'' Voinovich said. ``He
can see the handwriting on the wall and this could be a way for him
to extricate himself from the situation and save face.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Voinovich said, the only option is to pound away with
no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been 55 days and nothing has changed,'' he said. ``How
many more? Ten? Fifteen? Thirty days?''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
