<SLUG> BC-SOC-SOCCER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY CROWDS THINNING OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Galaxy crowds are looking more and
more like those old Los Angeles Aztecs crowds of the 1970's.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Aztec players would kick soccer balls into the stands
for fans to keep. The crowds were so small at the Rose Bowl, I
would pick an empty section and have a free ball awaiting me.
</P>
<P>
   There are no free balls anymore, but take away the Galaxy's
first two games -- the season opener (17,343) and its doubleheader
with the U.S. Women's National team (27,034) -- and what do you
have left?
</P>
<P>
   Aztec-type crowds.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy has averaged 10,967 its past three games, far short
of its combined average of 17,795 the first three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   When San Jose and El Salvadoran Raul Diaz Arce came to the Rose
Bowl April 3 for a head-to-head meeting with fellow Salvadoran
Mauricio Cienfuegos of the Galaxy, L.A. drew 16,700.
</P>
<P>
   But against Columbus on April 8, a record-low 4,825 were on
hand. And Saturday, 11,378 were in attendance with Carlos
Valderrama and Tampa Bay in town.
</P>
<P>
   Bart Brown, past president of the East L.A. Futbol Foundation
and director of player development for the non-profit L.A. Soccer
foundation, has an explanation for the recent decline.
</P>
<P>
   Brown feels that since Denver-based billionaire Philip F.
Anschutz purchased the club for $26 million in October, the Galaxy
has distanced itself from the Hispanic community. Therefore, he
says, the Hispanic community has distanced itself from the Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The silence from the Spanish-speaking press has been
deafening,'' Brown said. ``A shame equaled only by the new Galaxy's
disdain for the Hispanic market.''
</P>
<P>
   When Galaxy President Tim Leiweke was introduced last October,
many wondered how the Galaxy would market itself to the Spanish
audience. During the Galaxy's first three seasons, former Galaxy
president Daniel Villanueva had strong ties to the Spanish
community.
</P>
<P>
   He built the team around the makeup of the city. In 1996, it had
an Ecuadoran (Eduardo Hurtado), El Salvadoran (Mauricio Cienfuegos)
and a Mexican (Jorge Campos).
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Villanueva acquired Guatemalan Martin Machon and also
brought in Mexican scoring champion Carlos Hermosillo last season.
</P>
<P>
   Only Hermosillo and Cienfuegos remain and Hermosillo doesn't
return to the team until next month.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Leiweke promised the Hispanic audience wouldn't be
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an idiot; I look at the fan base,'' Leiweke said at
the time. ``The Hispanic community is No. 1. We start there and we
end there and although there are other parts of the fan base we
have to pat attention to, I want the Hispanic community to
understand they have my full attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Do they? Leiweke is no different than a lot of MLS' executives,
who admit their soccer knowledge is limited.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer America's Paul Gardener suggested that MLS' governing
body ``is devoid of anyone with a deep knowledge of the sport it's
supposed to be promoting.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy general manager Sergio Del Prado said that season ticket
sales from last year are almost identical to this season. In fact,
they are exactly four tickets shy of last season's total on season
ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of fans, however, stem from walk-up sales. And walk-up
sales generally come from the Hispanic market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked at that (lack of Hispanic sales) and it's a huge
concern on our part,'' said Del Prado. ``The Hispanic crowd was a
crowd that came without the Galaxy courting it or doing anything
(in years past). We have been advertising in the Hispanic media,
but until Hermosillo gets here, we'll do everything we can to reach
that crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be hard with only Cienfuegos as its only marquee foreign
attraction in the mean time.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Galaxy has a foreign roster spot available for
the team to exercise, Del Prado doesn't expect it to be filled by a
marquee Hispanic player this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world that would be the solution,'' Del Prado
said about introducing a recognized foreigner. ``But I don't think
this late in the season we'll find one impact player for both our
team and our attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even without a star player from their (Hispanics) homeland, I
think that (Hispanic) crowd is price-conscious for one. And they're
also very fickle as to how we're performing on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting more Hispanic families, but we're missing the
17- to 30-year-old male who's out with his buddies.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if the Galaxy starts winning and scoring, maybe
everything would change. It doesn't help that they're the worst
scoring team in the league (five goals in nine games) with 4-5
mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win, people show up,'' said Del Prado. ``We'll have
to see what happens when they turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   MLS vice president of player relations Ivan Gazidis said the
league is still working on a way for Los Angeles to sign former
UCLA striker Seth George, drafted by the Galaxy in the second round
of the 1999 college draft.
</P>
<P>
   George is not with the 1860 Munich German club he signed with
after college, but the club still owns his rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``No progress ... Seth is under contract in Europe,'' said
Gazidis. ``We don't propose to pay a transfer fee. Right now we're
waiting for that situation to resolve itself, but we're hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy also released 17-year-old Ecuadoran Jaime Estupian,
leaving a foreign slot available, but as Del Prado suggested, there
are no immediate plans to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Galaxy has not asked us about a player,'' said Gazidis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
