<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEWLETT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HP Unfurls Its Battle Plan for Storming Into E-Commerce
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Henry Norr &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Internet commerce is moving to a new stage, according to
Hewlett-Packard, and this time around, the Palo Alto computer giant
aims to play a starring role.
</P>
<P>
   A day after releasing an unexpectedly strong earnings report for
its second fiscal quarter, the company yesterday rolled out a new
vision, new technologies and new buzzwords for what HP executives
called ``Internet Chapter 2.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy focuses on providing tools for building
``e-services,'' sophisticated new online sites that will make it
easier for companies and end users to find the goods and services
that best meet their changing needs.
</P>
<P>
   One element of the plan is ``apps on tap,'' software services
such as accounting and inventory management that businesses could
use over the Web as needed. Instead of having to buy, install and
manage all the necessary software on their own machines, they would
pay on the basis of actual usage. HP officials called the scheme
``outsourcing your incompetences.''
</P>
<P>
   One example is e-mail, which is increasingly critical for many
companies yet also increasingly difficult to manage. HP said it has
formed alliances with both Microsoft and PSINet, a large
business-oriented Internet service provider, to offer e-mail
services to other companies tired of the hassle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been a major player on the Internet all along,'' said
Lewis Platt, HP's soon-to-retire CEO. ``But it's true we haven't
been very good at merchandising what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's announcements were intended to change all that. The
new strategy, worked out over the past six months, has ``spread
like wildfire'' through the company, giving its diverse businesses
a common direction, Platt said.
</P>
<P>
   One key piece of the new plan is a software technology called
``E-speak,'' which will allow Web developers to knit together
different applications to perform complex tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Companies or users who want to make travel arrangements via the
Web, for example, typically have to check several sites to compare
availability and prices for airline tickets, hotel rooms, car
rentals and entertainment options. And if the trip has to be
postponed, the user has to go back and start all over again.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, the user only would need enter a description of
the planned trip, and E-speak-enabled software automatically would
locate all sites offering relevant services and select those that
best match the customer's goals and priorities.
</P>
<P>
   If a flight is canceled or delayed, the software automatically
would offer the user a choice of several alternative plans, then
make all the new reservations and arrangements required.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-speak is only a conceptual architecture at this point,''
said Harry Fenik, vice president of Zona Research in Redwood City.
``It's a good one, in the sense that this is the kind of thing that
needs to be done, but it remains to be seen whether this framework
or something else will become ubiquitous.''
</P>
<P>
   E-speak is based on technology that's been under development in
HP labs for more than five years, officials said. But the company
doesn't intend to keep it to itself: It already has posted the
basic software code on the Web, and late this year, it plans to
release an open-source version that customers and even competitors
will be able to build into their own products.
</P>
<P>
   How then will HP make money on the technology? Part of the
answer, according to Ann Livermore, chief executive of HP's
Enterprise Computing Business, is that innovative Web business will
see that HP understands their needs so will look to it for other
products, such as servers and security and management software.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole new set of baby gorillas out there, and we
want to help them grow up to be the 800-pound kind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, according to Livermore, HP is developing new
business models under which it will provide hardware, software and
services in exchange for a percentage of the customer's revenues
from online transactions. It's relatively easy for HP to move to
the new model because it already has its own financing business _
an advantage many of its competitors lack.
</P>
<P>
   Archrival Sun Microsystems, for example, can't make
transaction-based deals of this kind because it has no financing
arm, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sun is sitting kind of stuck in a boat without a paddle,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Monday's positive earnings report, HP closed at
$96, up $7.25, after flirting with a high of $97.56.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
