<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARPER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Sharper Image Shelves Plan to Sharpen Image
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The new president of Sharper Image said yesterday that the firm has
suspended plans to redesign its stores because the updated look
hasn't improved sales.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Wan, now second in command after founder and chief
executive Richard Thalheimer, said the San Francisco electronic
gadget retailer also has scaled back its store-opening plans for
this year to five new stores from 10 because it can't afford the
high rents landlords are asking.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been any lift in comps to justify'' more
remodels, said Wan, referring to comparable-store sales, or sales
at stores that have been open one year or more, the primary gauge
of retail success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure why'' the more spacious-feeling beige stores are
not selling more merchandise than the old gray ones, said Wan, a
veteran Sharper Image executive who was promoted last month from
chief operating officer to president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Sharper Image opened four new stores and remodeled
five. It will continue to remodel existing stores when required for
lease renewals, and it will build stores at new locations in the
updated style. Currently, just 11 of the 89 Sharper Image stores
have the new look.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Gassman, an analyst with Davenport &AMP; Co., said he likes
the clean, new design of the stores, which like the old ones sell
gizmos such as a self-cleaning cat litter box, a CD player that can
be played in the shower, and an inflatable kayak. The problem seems
to be that there isn't enough merchandise on the shelf, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the theory was that they would reduce the amount of
product per square foot, so people would focus on particular items,
play with them and buy them,'' said Gassman. ``That may have
happened, but I think they may have gone overboard with lowering
the product density.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparable store sales have been erratic, declining in January
and February and then jumping 10 percent in March and 11 percent in
April. Wan attributed problems early in the year to shortages of
hot items. She said she does not expect double-digit sales
increases to continue.
</P>
<P>
   For fiscal 1998, comparable store sales rose a healthy 5.3
percent, up from 1.1 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Direct-mail sales, which last year accounted for 29 percent of
Sharper Image's $243 million in revenues, were hurt earlier this
year when the company cut catalog costs in an attempt to get a
higher return, Wan said.
</P>
<P>
   The January-February catalog was cut to 52 pages from 84, and
fewer catalogs were mailed. But sales declined along with costs,
leaving the return flat, said Wan. The catalogs now are back to
their original size and circulation levels, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wan said her goals for this year are to expand Sharper Image's
distribution system before the Christmas season, to make its Web
site more customer friendly and to expand sales of products
developed in-house.
</P>
<P>
   Those proprietary products, which carry higher margins than
merchandise bought from outside vendors, constitute 8 percent of
Sharper Image sales in 1997 and 18 percent in 1998. The company
currently is achieving its target of 25 percent for 1999, said Wan.
</P>
<P>
   Sharper Image's Web site continues to rack up strong sales,
growing in triple digits each month since February. Web sales last
year totaled $4.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sharper Image is preparing for a Web sale of leftover
merchandise from its Home Collection catalog, which was
discontinued earlier this year amid plummeting sales.
</P>
<P>
   The Home Collection failed in part because it was too difficult
and expensive to ship large pieces of furniture, said Wan. But she
said smaller pieces might sell well over the Web.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2127EDT &QL; 
