s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-2TAKES-     05-18 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO PLAYS ILLUMINATE EACH OTHER AND THEIR AUTHOR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The British playwright David Hare, now at the Booth Theater in
``Via Dolorosa,'' his own one-man play about the Arab-Israeli
stalemate, reports with some amused chagrin Dame Judi Dench's
response to his performance, which marks his debut as a
professional actor.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, Dame Judi, a longtime pro and a legitimate
Dame, is starring in Hare's ``Amy's View'' at the Ethel Barrymore.
Though both productions were hits in London earlier, Dame Judi
apparently hadn't had a chance to catch ``Via Dolorosa'' until she
came to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been saying to me for some time now,'' Hare told James
Barron of The New York Times, ``that I must write a play in which
we can act'' together. Though after seeing ``Via Dolorosa,'' he
said, she seemed to have cooled on the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mmm,'' Hare quoted her as having said, ``I don't think I want
to be in a play with you. You don't act. There's not a single
choice you make in the course of an evening that any professional
actor would make. It's moving, but I don't feel that what I do and
what you do have any professional kinship.''
</P>
<P>
   This sounds very much like good-natured ribbing from an admiring
star who may have received a certain amount of constructive
criticism from the playwright during rehearsals, possibly through
Richard Eyre, the director.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it also calls attention to Hare's approach to theater and,
indeed, to the vast differences between ``Via Dolorosa'' and to
virtually every other Hare play American audiences have had the
opportunity to see. That would recently include not only ``Amy's
View,'' but also ``The Judas Kiss,'' a consideration of the fate of
Oscar Wilde, which opened in New York just a year ago, and, to a
somewhat lesser extent, ``The Blue Room.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the playwright's chilly, sardonic variation on ``La
Ronde,'' the Schnitzler classic, in which a discreetly nude Nicole
Kidman helped to sell out a limited Broadway engagement earlier
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom has the latest work of an established playwright been
available in such quantity on Broadway within such a short period
of time. For many of us, it has been a learning experience of the
sort that only repertory theaters can offer. It is as if Hare had
decided to supplement three more or less conventional plays
(``Amy's View,'' ``The Blue Room'' and ``The Judas Kiss'') with a
fascinating, extended career footnote (``Via Dolorosa'').
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, he allows us free entry into the mind _ the
playwright's hidden storage vault _ where he keeps the raw material
that later goes into his plays.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, of course, ``Via Dolorosa'' is no footnote. It is a
major work in its own right: not fiction but reportage, being
Hare's first-person account of his three fact-finding trips to
Israel and the West Bank when he was pondering the writing of a
play to illustrate the problems there. Somewhere along the way,
however, he decided that what he calls ``theater of fiction'' would
not be adequate to the task.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he wrote a 90-minute monologue in which he, as himself,
an uncommitted, skeptical outsider, a native of a land where
passion has become theoretical, reports on the religious, ethnic,
social and economic contradictions that have led to this most
passionate of stalemates.
</P>
<P>
   Dame Judi is right. Hare doesn't portray himself with the skill
and nuances that a pro might bring to the role, which is all to the
good. There is nothing seductive about his performance that might
distance the audience from the full import of what he is saying.
Yet he brings to intense, dramatic life the dozens of remarkable
characters he meets en route, all the while keeping up a running
commentary of his own thoughts, which issue from a mind infinitely
curious and committed only to common sense and justice. Such are
the luxuries, he acknowledges, available to the outsider passing
through.
</P>
<P>
   Now, New Yorkers have the luxury of seeing ``Amy's View'' and
``Via Dolorosa'' back to back in such a way that each serves to
illuminate the other. You have to make your plans quickly, though:
``Via Dolorosa,'' which is directed by Stephen Daldry, closes on
June 13.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Amy's View,'' Hare has created fictional characters into
which, like a ventriloquist, he throws his disguised voice to make
points that are often dramatic but not always consistent with the
characters who express them. On the other hand, there is never any
doubt in ``Via Dolorosa'' about the validity of the characters or
about the playwright's reactions to them. Writing in the first
person, he is a superb reporter with a gift for locating the vivid
detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amy's View'' is an updated version of the kind of star vehicle
I associate with the pre-World War II American theater. That was
when actresses on the order of Katherine Cornell, Tallulah Bankhead
and Ina Claire wouldn't be caught dead onstage at the curtain's
rise, but would make great, sweeping dramatic entrances intended to
provoke adoring applause.
</P>
<P>
   Dame Judi's entrance in ``Amy's View'' is not quite so
self-conscious, but the buildup for it is perfectly timed and the
response to it warm. The performance that follows is big, showy
and, I suspect, infinitely satisfying to American audiences. They
are ready to salute the star who played Queen Victoria in ``Mrs.
Brown'' (for which she should have received the Oscar last year)
and this year's Oscar-winning best-supporting actress for
``Shakespeare in Love,'' in which she plays Queen Elizabeth I.
</P>
<P>
   Dame Judi doesn't disappoint. Hare has written a rich role for
her in ``Amy's View'': Esme Allen, a great, dedicated star of the
London theater whose daughter, Amy, falls fatally in love with a
young man named Dominic who represents everything crass in
contemporary culture. In the 16 years covered by the play, Dominic,
a part-time correspondent for tabloid journals, hustles his way
first to celebrity as a television arts critic and then to
financial and critical success as a director of movies that are
described as if they might be Quentin Tarantino spinoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amy's View'' is actually about more things than can easily be
absorbed in one viewing, though it reads more coherently than it
plays. Among other things, it's about Esme's abiding faith in the
theater as opposed to Dominic's commitment to getting ahead in the
more popular arts. Theater is mind and conscience. Movies and
television are pure sensation.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Hare explores Esme's horror that Amy should
marry Dominic in full acceptance of the fact that he can never love
her to the degree that she loves him, which is a brief replay of
the theme spelled out at somewhat greater length in ``The Judas
Kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   Rapacious capitalism, as exemplified by Lloyd's of London, also
figures prominently in a plot that seems to wander from one
would-be big emotional scene to another until the end. At that
point, magically, Hare delivers a coda that helps to make all that
has gone before seem worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
