<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROVIDIAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 S.F. D.A. Probing Providian
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Providian Financial Corp., the giant San Francisco credit card
lender that targets customers with tarnished credit histories, is
under investigation for possible consumer fraud by the city
district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The allegations are that there are unfair business
practices,'' district attorney's office spokesman Clarence Johnson
said. ``This is something that came to our attention several months
ago. We got a lot of complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors haven't collected enough evidence yet to determine
whether to level criminal charges against Providian, the nation's
ninth-largest credit card issuer and one of the city's fastest
growing financial businesses. If the office decides not to
prosecute, it could file a civil suit or drop the matter entirely,
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to specify what alleged abuses the district
attorney's office is probing, except to say they involve a range of
practices in the sale of credit cards, disclosure of terms and
collection of debt.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the probe, Providian spokeswoman Laurie Cole said in
a prepared statement: ``If the district attorney's office is
conducting an investigation, we will cooperate fully.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole said, ``We're confident we are in compliance with all laws
and regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   The probe of Providian, first reported by KRON-TV, comes as
credit card issuers nationwide face heightened scrutiny. Consumer
groups accuse them of boosting profits by loading up on late
charges and other fees, while concealing from customers vital
information about their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is considering amendments to federal bankruptcy
legislation, supported by the Clinton administration, that would
require credit card issuers to display terms more prominently on
applications, including information about fees.
</P>
<P>
   Providian was created in 1997 when a Kentucky insurance company
spun off its consumer finance unit. The company established itself
as a credit card powerhouse by doing business with customers of
different credit ratings while specializing in those with poor
credit records. Providian has a reputation for finding innovative
ways of squeezing payments from them.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock has more than doubled in the last 18 months,
as Providian has jumped from 12th to ninth place among credit card
lenders nationwide, according to the Nilson Report, a trade
publication.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, though, Providian has become a lightning rod for
consumer anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the distinction of creating more consumer complaints
than any other company in the Bay Area,'' said Pat Wallace,
president of Oakland's Better Business Bureau, who said his agency
had received about 850 letters from irate customers.
</P>
<P>
   Providian says the number of complaints forwarded to it by the
bureau is less than the number the agency says it gets. ``It
appears customer dissatisfaction levels are being exaggerated,''
said Cole.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time she added, ``We are taking every question and
criticism into careful account.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer complaints about Providian run across the board, from
allegedly deceptive credit card solicitations to failure to
properly post payments.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Pena, a 29-year-old Fremont resident, said Providian sent
her a credit card even though she told a telemarketer she wasn't
interested. She sent the card back, but still received a bill with
monthly charges.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately the company dropped the charges. But Pena said it
denied her request to remove the account from her record with
credit bureaus. ``They refused to take it off,'' Pena said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Providian complaints concern the company's
requirement that some customers buy ``credit protection'' for
amounts up to $12.95 a month. Unlike most credit insurance
programs, which pay down outstanding balances if a borrower becomes
disabled or loses a job, Providian promises only to freeze the
account so that finance charges and fees no longer accrue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting complaints that they advertise they have no
annual fee, but that's like an annual fee,'' said Wallace. ``Their
disclosure is pathetic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
