<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO FAR, DODGER BLUE NO BIG CREW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With almost a fourth of the baseball season concluded, it now is
official that the Los Angeles Dodgers just might rank as the most
underachieving team in the major leagues in light of their
monstrous $87 million payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Where is Fred Claire when we need him?
</P>
<P>
   I realize it might be slightly too early to make a definitive
assessment on these win-a-game, lose-a-game,
sleep-walk-through-a-game Dodgers, but you'd think Fox would be
getting far more value for its money than it has been receiving
from overpaid laborers who oftentimes seem lazier than a bunch of
firemen on a fishing trip to Cabo San Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   How can the San Francisco Giants, with their puny small-market
payroll that barely exceeds Kevin Brown's annual salary, be in
first place in the N.L. West Division even with their superstar
outfielder, Barry Bonds, long gone with a bum elbow?
</P>
<P>
   Why, even the Arizona Diamondbacks have been matching the
Dodgers, a most embarrassing phenomenon since the Diamondbacks have
been in existence a grand total of two years.
</P>
<P>
   The new Dodger general manager, Mr. Kevin Malone, predicted
before the season that this Dodger team had World Series destiny
embroidered all over its blue flannel uniforms, quite reassuring
rhetoric to patrons of a franchise that hasn't won a post-season
game since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   And, who knows, the Dodgers still might wind up in the Fall
Classic, if, by some wild stretch of the imagination, their
illustrious catcher, Todd Hundley, is able to throw out a base
runner or two between now and October.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers look to me like a hastily constructed team without
careful regard to chemistry in which there are some exceptional
individual parts like Kevin Brown and Gary Sheffield and Raul
Mondesi and some other parts that are best left unnamed so as not
to cause anyone lingering public embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   I don't pose as a baseball scientist, but I do know this much
about the game: you're never going to rival the '27 Yankees, or
even the '98 Yankees, or even the '97 Florida Marlins if you're not
strong up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Shhh, let's keep this a secret from Kevin Malone's employers,
who are going to have to pay more than $5 million this season in
revenue sharing for exceeding the salary cap, but the Dodgers have
two insufferably ordinary shortstops in Mark Grudzielanek and Jose
Vizcaino, an aging center fielder, Devon White, who might be too
prone to injury, and a catcher, Mr. Hundley, who can make Rosie
O'Donnell look swift on the base paths.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's quite early, the weather hasn't turned hot yet, and
the celebrated Dodger pitching staff figures to get stronger as the
season progresses.
</P>
<P>
   At least Chan Ho Park (3-3, 5.32 ERA) and Carlos Perez (1-4,
6.23 ERA) should improve on their shabby early season antics in
which they've given rousing impersonations of Anaheim Angel
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   But at least Davey Johnson's counterpart down the Santa Ana
Freeway, Terry Collins, can offer a few legitimate excuses for his
Angels' lame beginning to a season of great promise.
</P>
<P>
   His team has been cursed by the usual spate of injuries starting
with the preseason departures of its shortstop, Gary DiSarcina, and
center fielder, Jim Edmonds, to the two-week absence of Mo Vaughn
to the recent sidelining of Tim Salmon.
</P>
<P>
   And no one expected the Angels to be a serious World Series
challenger, anyway, not with a pitching staff that, with the
possible exception of Chuck Finley, is comprised of a variety of
mediocrities either too old, too brittle and/or just too easy to
hit.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, I personally like Tim Belcher even though he once
threatened to tear out my heart I thought it was nicely
presumptuous on his part to perceive that I had one for my
questioning the strength of his heart. But the aging fellow now
possesses an ERA, 8.78, that looks as though it belongs on either
the Richter Scale or the Dow Jones Averages.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure anyone is shaking his noggin in frustration over
the plight of the Angels because no one ever expects anything but
disappointment from a team whose legacy is steeped in
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the erratic play of the Dodgers has caused
severe discomfort among their followers, not to mention among those
team executives like Kevin Malone and Bob (Don't Call Me Rocky)
Graziano who have raided Rupert Murdoch's bulging coffers to put
together this high-priced group.
</P>
<P>
   The expectations of the Dodgers, with their obscenely bloated
payroll, still are at a dizzying level, despite the modest
achievements of a team that eventually should pull away from its
competitors in the West because of its pitching staff that,
notwithstanding the feeble production of Messrs. Park and Perez,
still has the potential to be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   But at the moment, these Dodgers don't give you the impression
of being destined for anything other than constant ridicule, which
they will inevitably endure if they continue to flounder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2128EDT &QL; 
