<HEADER>
A2316 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-2NDTAKE     05-18 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-2NDTAKE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: seem worthwhile.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dame Judi is splendid and great fun to watch as an actress who
is most actressy and out of touch in real life, whether dealing
with those she loves or even with a bankruptcy that might send a
more ordinary woman into a permanent nervous breakdown. Only at the
end of ``Amy's View,'' when she is about to go onstage in a hit
play that has arrived late in her career, is the essence of the
woman revealed. The scene is a stunner and is, I suspect, the
reason that people come away from ``Amy's View'' with such fond
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Esme, none of the characters in the play has the
startling authenticity of those recalled by Hare, acting David
Hare, in ``Via Dolorosa.'' Like so many characters in earlier Hare
plays, those in ``Amy's View'' tend to sound like mouthpieces. Yet
``Via Dolorosa'' is so good that it invites us to attend to all his
other work with greater care. It reveals the playwright to be a man
of piercing wit, understanding and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amy's View'' has the manner of a play that has been
laboriously built and furnished, not out of creative urgency but
out of a need to provide temporary shelter for the author's
colleagues and himself.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see if the critical success of ``Via
Dolorosa'' has any effect on the direction Hare's work takes in the
future. Most encouraging is the fact that he is still taking
chances, still in the process of growing, still exploring new ways
of expression. He is alive and well and restless. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I hope New York audiences don't fail ``The Lonesome West,'' now
at the Lyceum Theater. If anything, this third play in Martin
McDonagh's Irish trilogy set in Leenane is more satisfying and less
tricky than the initial installment, ``The Beauty Queen of
Leenane,'' which closed not long ago, having won Tonys for three of
its actors and its director last season.
</P>
<P>
   That McDonagh is still a young playwright (he is 29) is apparent
in ``The Lonesome West,'' which replays the manners and, to a
certain extent, even the central situation of ``Beauty Queen.''
However, the denouement of ``The Lonesome West'' does not depend on
something as lame as an undelivered letter.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is another dreary Godforsaken farmhouse in County
Galway in the west of Ireland, inhabited this time by two aging
bachelors, Coleman Connor (Maeliosa Stafford), a brutish lout, and
his brother, Valene (Brian F. O'Byrne), a fussy fellow who collects
plaster figurines of saints as his passport to heaven. The two
deeply loathe each other but, at the start of the play, they have
become forever locked together.
</P>
<P>
   They have just buried their not so dear old dad, who died
suddenly when Coleman, in a rage, shot him at point-blank range. In
return for Valene's testimony that it was simply an unfortunate
household accident, Coleman has deeded his brother his share of
their father's money and is now dependent on the stingy Valene not
only for his freedom, but also for food, drink and the clothes on
his back.
</P>
<P>
   Surveying all, aware of everything, but himself unable to cope
with a parish where murder and other antisocial activities are
endemic, is Father Welsh (David Ganly). He is a young man who, in a
more shapely play, might have been its central figure. Welsh is not
a comic character. He is a sweet-natured fellow who has gone into
the church as a last resort. It's there, and it provides a living
in a land not bursting with opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Father Welsh hangs around Coleman and Valene because they are
free with their booze, and because he genuinely likes them. As the
rest of the parish goes about its dark business, the priest drinks
with Coleman and Valene and tries to save them from their mutual
hatred.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that frightens the priest more than the Leenane
bloodshed is the adoring, openly available presence of Girleen
Kelleher (Dawn Bradfield). She is a pretty young thing who, knowing
Welsh's squeamishness about sex, can't resist talking dirty to him.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of ``The Lonesome West'' is devoted to the furious
sparring of Coleman and Valene, it is the ineffectual, alcoholic
Father Welsh, a nascent independent thinker, who dominates the
play. His gradual awakening to the hell he inhabits is the backbone
of ``The Lonesome West,'' providing a subtext for a work that
otherwise would be merely the Irish equivalent to the kind of
hillbilly cartoons Esquire used to run.
</P>
<P>
   Garry Hynes, who staged ``Beauty Queen,'' is also the director
of ``The Lonesome West,'' which is beautifully acted by Stafford,
O'Byrne, Ms. Bradfield and, particularly, Ganly. Still to come: the
second play in the Leenane Trilogy, ``A Skull in Connemara.''
</P>
<P>
   In one way and another, McDonagh is out to destroy the old
Hollywood vision that rural Ireland is a land of jolly, avuncular
Barry Fitzgeralds. McDonagh's message: let your daughters run free,
but lock up your firearms and all instruments blunt and sharp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
