<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2320 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GORE-ART-NYT     05-18 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS TARGET GORE, USING RIDICULE AS A WEAPON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Exclusive)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After years of battling with President Clinton,
House Republicans are shifting their sights to Vice President Al
Gore, and using ridicule as their weapon of choice.
</P>
<P>
   The office of House Majority Leader Dick Armey has become an
unofficial clearinghouse of anti-Gore press releases and activity,
with Armey mocking Gore over his pronouncements on air travel, the
Internet and traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, House conservatives plan to enter the fray. Four or
five members of the ``Conservative Action Team'' are to go to the
House floor after the day's business and, with television cameras
running, give readings of what they consider to be the most
provocative, or perhaps most inscrutable, sections of ``Earth in
the Balance,'' Gore's 1992 book on the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The readings will come after another slap at Gore. A bill
authorizing programs for NASA scheduled to be voted on by the House
on Wednesday has been stripped of money for the Triana project,
Gore's proposal to have a live video image of the Earth spinning in
black space transmitted 24 hours a day on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have shifted the $32 million into medical
research. ``If we're just going to put satellites up and look at
Earth, that's silly,'' said Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash. ``It
just happens to be a bad project dreamed up by Mr. Gore. It doesn't
matter to me who came up with the nutty idea; it's a nutty idea
that should go.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey, trying hard to stay deadpan, Tuesday distributed to
reporters a list of Web sites that already carry pictures of the
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on Gore, the leading candidate for the Democratic
presidential nomination, is a sign of how presidential politics is
seeping into Congress a full year and a half before the election.
This is traditionally the time when partisan passions are running
less strongly and serious legislation has more of a chance. But
Congress has moved directly from the bitterness of impeachment to
the passions of the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a spokesman for Gore, said Tuesday that
Republicans are going after the vice president because they
``recognize this guy is an extremely strong candidate and they want
to derail a compelling story.'' And he accused the House
Republicans of lacking an agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no message of their own that's an affirmative
message or a positive message,'' he said. ``If they spent one-tenth
of the effort they spend attacking us on doing some positive things
you might actually see some positive legislation coming out of the
Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Republicans complain that President Clinton is
devoting himself to the election of Gore and a Democratic-led House
instead of seeking common cause with Republicans on issues like
Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   For years Congress ran multiple investigations of Clinton. But
with Gore, Republicans are betting that well-timed ridicule can be
more devastating than any inquiry. In essence, they are trying to
do to him what Democrats tried to do to former Vice President Dan
Quayle: make him the foil for comedians on late-night television.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Republican side, we are more sensitive to this, having
watched what happened to Quayle,'' said Rep. David McIntosh,
R-Ind., a former Quayle aide who is one of the organizers of the
readings from Gore's book. ``You can't make somebody funny when
they are not providing the material,'' he said, adding that Gore
``provides a lot of it.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Gore, for example, proposed a federal traffic hot line,
Armey said, ``Next we'll have traffic reports from Air Force Two
and a sports ticker on the White House lawn. Why should anyone have
to call Washington to get their local bus schedule?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's assertion recently that he had been instrumental in the
creating the Internet provoked jokes not only from Armey and Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott but also from the House Science
Committee. ``Delusions of Grandeur: Vice President Gore Takes
Credit for Creating the Internet,'' said a statement from the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   And when Rep. John Doolittle, R-Calif., took to the House floor
just before Earth Day, he gave a preview of what the conservatives
would sound like Wednesday. He read from Gore's book an assertion
that the century's two world wars, the Holocaust, nuclear weapons
and ``global environmental crisis have led many of us to wonder if
survival, much less, enlightened, joyous and hopeful living, is
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Doolittle asked, ``Does any reasonable person really sit here
and wonder if survival is even possible? I mean, this is
unimaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone in Congress runs short of lines, the Republican
National Committee puts out a regular fax and e-mail feature called
``The World According to Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehane was dismissive of the mockery. ``We can stand after six
and a half years and say we have a stronger economy and cleaner
environment and that absolutely terrifies the Republicans,'' he
said. Geoffrey Garin, a Democratic pollster, described the
Republican efforts as ``a distraction for Gore'' but said, ``This
is petty politics as opposed to grand politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the disputes do involve policy. Gore has put particular
emphasis on his environmental record and is now pushing for
preservation of open space, a reduction of traffic congestion and
easier commutes.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republicans came into office determined to roll back
regulation, much of it related to the environment. Many of them see
Gore's new initiatives on sprawl as an infringement on property
rights. Armey's aides are preparing a memorandum for House
Republicans to take with them over the Memorial Day recess telling
them how to talk about Gore's anti-sprawl initiatives. They might
say, for example, that people might have to ride a bus to work
instead of a car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
