<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FED LEAVES RATES ALONE BUT HINTS AT INCREASE LATER
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve left interest rates steady but put investors
and consumers on notice that it might raise them in coming months
if it continued to see signs of increasing inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in stance by the central bank's policy-making
committee _ from neutral to leaning toward higher rates _ was
subtle but signaled a clear change in the Fed's outlook from last
fall, when it cut rates three times in response to the global
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's announcement sent stock and bond prices tumbling, but
they recovered much of their losses. The Dow industrial average
fell 16.52 points, to 10,836.95. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index fell 6.17 points, to 1,333.32, and the NASDAQ composite index
declined 3.48 points, to 2,558.36.
</P>
<P>
   LOEHMANN'S FILES FOR BANKRUPTCY
</P>
<P>
   Loehmann's, the Bronx-based retailer that offers designer
apparel at bargain prices, filed for bankruptcy protection. The
company said the filing would not have an effect on the day-to-day
operations of its 69 stores. A company spokesman, however, said it
was too early to say what will happen to either the stores or
Loehmann's 2,500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL COMPUTERS MAKE COMEBACK
</P>
<P>
   In the engine rooms of the Internet, like a huge datacenter run
by IBM in Illinois, row upon row of powerful computers manage the
Web sites and electronic commerce operations of giant companies and
organizations _ a seeming reversal of the last two decades'
emphasis on individual personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. PENNEY ANNOUNCES INITIATIVES
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Penney reported lower first-quarter earnings but announced
two initiatives that could raise as much as $6 billion in revenue.
The company said it was looking to sell its credit card business
and also said it planned to sell a 20 percent stake in Eckerd, a
fast-growing drugstore chain, to the public as a tracking stock.
The news sent the company's previously lagging stock price up 9.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   DELL'S PROFIT MATCHES EXPECTATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer posted first-quarter earnings that matched
analysts' estimates, but the results disappointed some investors
and sent shares lower in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   CALPERS AGREES TO RISE IN PREMIUMS
</P>
<P>
   In the first sign that the cost of health care insurance could
rise 9 percent to 11 percent next year, the California Public
Employees Retirement System, the nation's second-biggest buyer of
health benefits, said that it had agreed to an average increase of
9.7 percent in premiums for government workers.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE DAIMLERCHRYSLER SMARTS
</P>
<P>
   Eight months after its introduction, the snub-nosed Smart, or as
the little car is known informally, the ``Swatchmobile,'' has
become a billion-dollar headache for its parent, DaimlerChrysler.
The two-seat ``city car'' was intended to be safe, maneuverable and
spacious, but customers have complained it slides on snow and ice,
and sales have lagged.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT AND XEROX IN ALLIANCE
</P>
<P>
   Xerox and Microsoft announced an alliance aimed at bridging the
worlds of paper documents and computers. Microsoft will license a
Web-surfing technology developed by Xerox, and Xerox will
incorporate Embedded NT, a version of Microsoft's Windows NT
operating system, in its high-end copying systems.
</P>
<P>
   GTE SHAREHOLDERS APPROVE DEAL
</P>
<P>
   GTE shareholders approved the $52.9 billion merger with Bell
Atlantic, whose shareholders are to vote Wednesday. The deal, like
the US West-Global Crossing agreement, focuses attention on
regulatory challenges to the Bells' ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   BIG CANADIAN COPPER MINE SHUT
</P>
<P>
   Canada's largest copper mine, the Highland Valley mine in
south-central British Columbia, has been closed indefinitely after
the unionized work force's rejection of a cost-cutting contract.
The mine accounts for 1.5 percent of global output and is
considered one of the world's highest-cost producers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
