<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2327 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-GUNS-HNS &LR;      05-18 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES AMENDMENT REQUIRING SAFETY LOCKS AS GOP DEBATES GUN
MEASURES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Tuesday revived consideration of a
juvenile crime bill by passing an amendment that would require
trigger locks or ``safe storage devices'' to be sold with all
handguns.
</P>
<P>
   The vote of 78-20 illustrated just how sensitive Republicans
have become to criticism in the aftermath of the Littleton, Colo.,
school violence that they are in the pocket of the National Rifle
Association, which has been opposed to most gun-control measures.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-four Republicans joined with 44 Democrats to pass the
bill. The 20 who voted against it were Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans had sought to block the amendment, sponsored by
Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., and other Democrat-sponsored gun control
measures because of opposition from the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   But a public backlash to a Republican vote in the Senate last
week against requiring background checks on buyers at gun shows _
action that was later reversed _ forced some GOP lawmakers to
reconsider their opposition to Kohl's measure, which requires that
safety locks and devices be sold with the weapons and leaves the
decision on whether to use them with the gun owners.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's measure is aimed at reducing access to handguns by
children and especially teen-agers, who are responsible for
committing an estimated 7,000 violent crimes each year using guns
taken from their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks before the vote, Kohl observed that the recent
incident at Columbine High School in Littleton had forced both
Republicans and Democrats to get more serious about gun-control
measures as one way to help curb youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that, in the wake of Littleton, both sides have
grown up a bit: Democrats in acknowledging that culture may have
something to do with juvenile violence today; and Republicans in
finally endorsing reasonable measures to take handguns out of the
hands of kids who shouldn't have them,'' Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment passed as part of a larger bill aimed at
strengthening laws dealing with juvenile crime. The senators also
approved measures providing for tougher penalties for gang members
who commit crimes and young offenders who wear body armor.
</P>
<P>
   The juvenile crime bill, nearly two years in the making, was in
danger of being pulled from the floor Tuesday because of Democratic
objections to Republican efforts aimed at limiting the number of
amendments that could be offered. The Democrats accused the GOP
leadership of trying to prevent them from attaching even modest gun
control measures to the legislation, although Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott insisted that he wanted only to get ``the bill
done'' by expediting the debate.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats insisted that Lott, R-Miss., was trying to end
debate on a bill that had already caused the GOP considerable
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority leader wants this bill to fade away without a
roar or a whimper and without any Republican blame,'' said Sen.
Patrick Leahy, D-Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy was referring to an incident last week in which the
Republican majority voted to kill a Democratic bill requiring
background checks for buyers at gun shows. The Republicans later
reversed themselves by passing a weaker version of the bill that
critics say will allow criminals to skirt the checks.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are now trying to force additional votes on the
background check measure in order to close new loopholes that they
insist have been written into the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican reversal, however, has caused an uproar within
the party over gun-control issues. Republicans are struggling to
find a middle ground where they can appear to be tougher on gun
control without alienating the NRA and other key constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of that struggle was apparent Tuesday in the House,
where Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., suggested in an interview
with The Associated Press that lawmakers should consider raising
the age for legal possession of handguns from 18 to 21. He also
came out strongly in favor of requiring background checks for all
sales at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there needs to be uniformity in what they do at gun
shows and what they do in a retail business,'' Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just saying 21 is basically a standard of adulthood, and
there's probably a uniformity that fits there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The comments were striking coming in the wake of the Senate vote
on gun shows last week and given the fact that he has opposed
gun-control legislation in the past. His remarks also highlighted
how Republicans are trying to carve out a more moderate position on
gun-control measures in the aftermath of the public outrage over
the Columbine shooting and bombing incident in which 12 students
and a teacher were killed by two students who also took their own
lives.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released by the White House, President Clinton
commended Hastert ``for agreeing that we should close the gun show
loophole and raise the age of handgun ownership from 18 to 21.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, who will travel Thursday to Littleton, called on
the Senate to ``put progress over politics and give its strong
backing to these reasonable measures to keep guns out of the hands
of children and criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called the support for Kohl's bill ``a courageous,
common sense vote that will help prevent tragic shootings and
gun-related accidents in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, who voted against both the 1993 Brady law that
initiated a three-day waiting period for handgun buyers and created
an instant background check and 1994 legislation banning assault
weapons, said he expects a vote later this year in the House on new
gun control legislation as part of efforts to stiffen juvenile
crime penalties
</P>
<P>
   But House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, suggested Tuesday
that any juvenile justice legislation that has a strong gun control
component may face tough opposition from the Republican
rank-and-file in the House, regardless of what position the leaders
take.
</P>
<P>
   He said in order to win approval by the House, the bill will
have to focus more on enforcing current gun laws and dealing with
cultural problems that lead to violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody I've discussed this with is looking beyond this
singular set of (gun control) issues,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
