   (NYT29) DULLES, Virg. -- May 18, 1999 -- INTERNET-DATACENTERS-2,
5-18 --One of America Online's two huge computer server farms. The
sites can supply information to as many as one million home users
simultaneously. Internet data centers are sprouting up across the
country in a sure sign of the trend toward once again housing
information and computer power centrally; a seeming reversal of the
last two decades of computing. (Carol T. Powers/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- May 18, 1999 -- LOEHMANN-BANKRUPTCY, 5-18 --
Loehmann's says its bankruptcy filing Tuesday will not impact daily
operations at its 69 stores, including its Manhattan flagship. The
long-troubled chain, whose first store opened in 1920, says it had
assets of $188.7 million and liabilities of $184.1 million.
(Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) DETROIT -- May 18, 1999 -- DETROIT-MURDER, 5-18 --
Demonstrators on Monday picketing the gas station in Detroit where
the police say an unarmed black man was beaten to death last
Friday. The protesters have demanded that the gas station be closed
and have vowed not to allow the station to reopen unless it changes
hands and is run by blacks. (Peter Yates/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) CHICAGO -- May 18, 1999 -- CAMPUS-CRAZIES, 5-18 -- Carl
Malmstrom, a senior at the University of Chicago, throws a keg in
one of the odd events at the annual Scavenger Hunt. The event is a
yearly celebration of looniness at a campus far better known for
its Nobel laureates. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) SCHAUMBURG, Ill. -- May 18, 1999 --
INTERNET-DATACENTERS, 5-18 -- Walter Grom in the huge data center
run by I.B.M. Such computer centers, known as server farms, are the
unglamorous side of the Internet revolution. Internet data centers
are sprouting up across the country in a sure sign of the trend
toward once again housing information and computer power centrally;
a seeming reversal of the last two decades of computing. (Todd
Buchanan/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- May 18, 1999 -- WINE-BROKERS, 5-18 -- There
are 50 different sets of state regulations governing interstate
shipment of wine. At this moment they are on a collision course
with an explosion in direct marketing of wine and other spirits
through catalogs, wine clubs and the Internet as consumers have
turned into aficionados. One of the unintended consequences has
been the growth of an industry in California that barely existed a
few years ago: third-party shipping of wine. (Igor Vishnyakov/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- May 18, 1999 -- WINE-CONGRESS, 5-18 --
Chardonnay by Mail? Maybe not. Propelled in part by increased
alcohol sales on the Internet, intensive campaigns to further
restrict wine distribution are afoot in state legislatures and in
Washington. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- May 18, 1999 -- GIMMICK-THEATER-REVIEW, 5-18
-- Dael Orlandersmith performing in ``The Gimmick.'' The material
in her searing one-woman play is largely based on her own
experiences, and those experiences are hard to hear about, let
alone live through. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- May 18, 1999 -- HOLOCAUST-MUSEUM, 5-18 --
