The homey caramel taste has long satisfied the Hispanic sweet tooth
and is suddenly finding a wider audience. It has the potential to
rival vanilla and chocolate. ( Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- May 18, 1999 -- DULCE-1, 5-18 -- Rafael
Palomino, a Colombian and the chef and owner of Sonora, uses dulce
de leche (pronounced DOOL-say duh LAY-chay) in many dishes. The
smooth caramel taste has become a favorite among chefs. And home
cooks may soon find it is as handy to have in the kitchen as
chocolate sauce, to spoon over ice cream or slather on waffles, as
a substitute for honey in baking recipes or as a glaze for bananas
or cakes. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
