<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- May 18, 1999 -- PAPILLOTE-2, 5-18 --
Salvatore Anzalone makes seafood spaghetti in parchment at Bondi
Ristorante. Although restaurants know how much panache en papillote
- named for the parchment paper that encloses the food in an
envelope - brings to a dish, there is an additional beauty, one
appreciated by too few home cooks: it is fast and uncomplicated in
its execution, once you get the knack and understand the principles
that underlie the method. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- May 18, 1999 -- PAPILLOTE-1, 5-18 --
Jean-Georges Vongerichten, the chef at Jean Georges, preparing what
he calls ``Jiffy Pop for black bass.'' The cooking method known as
en papillote - for the parchment paper that encloses the food in an
envelope - has held its own through any number of culinary
fashions. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ACTON, Mass. -- May 18, 1999 -- PIANO-PRODIGY-BOS, 5-18
-- Bronika Kushkuley practices at her home. Kushkuley is a prodigy,
an 11-year-old performer who has cut a self-titled CD, is featured
on her own Web page, has performed across Europe, and triumphed at
international competitions from Washington to Italy. (Frank
O'Brien/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- May 18, 1999 -- NY-POETRY-CENTER, 5-18 --
Stanley Kunitz reading during the 60th anniversary celebration of
the 92nd Street Y's Unterberg Poetry Center. ``The clearest index
of a culture's moral health, the most immediate register of its
language's resources, both are provided by poetry,'' the center's
director, Karl Kirchwey, says in opening remarks at the
celebration. ``Why, then, should poetry be banished to a lyric or
an academic ghetto?'' (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SEKONOS, Macedonia -- May 18, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1,
5-18 -- Newly arriving ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo try to
revive a woman who fainted on a bus arriving at a refugee camp on
Tuesday. About 1,000 ethnic Albanians crossed into Macedonia
Tuesday and aid agencies said refugees were now being driven out of
Kosovo not only by Serb terror but also by fear of starvation.
(Andrew Testa/New York Times Photo) LITE
