<P>
   (NYT4) NEAH BAY, Wash. -- May 18, 1999 -- INDIANS-WHALE-3, 5-17
-- Makah whalers tie the gray whale they harpooned to the stern of
their fishing boat on Monday. The Makah Indian tribe on Monday
conducted the first legal killing of a gray whale in American
waters in nearly 75 years. (Grant Haller/Seattle Post
Intelligencer)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEAH BAY, Wash. -- May 18, 1999 -- INDIANS-WHALE-2, 5-17
-- A gray whale harpooned by Makah whalers is pulled behind their
fishing boat on Monday. The Makah Indian tribe on Monday conducted
the first legal killing of a gray whale in American waters in
nearly 75 years. (Jeff Larsen/Seattle Post Intelligencer) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEAH BAY, Wash. -- May 18, 1999 -- INDIANS-WHALE-1, 5-17
-- Makah whalers grimace as they pull on ropes attatched to a gray
whale they harpooned on Monday. The whale sank after the kill and
had to be raised to the surface using compressed air and muscle
power. The Makah Indian tribe on Monday conducted the first legal
killing of a gray whale in American waters in nearly 75 years.
(Grant Haller/Seattle Post Intelligencer)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- May 18, 1999 -- OBIT-DEMETRIOU-B&AMP;W, 05-17 --
Kyriacos Demetriou cuts a clients hair at his Upper West Side
barber shop in 1976. During his 40 years in this shop on Broadway
between 103rd and 104th streets, the shop and its owner became an
institution. Demetriou, who died on Friday at 80, donated many of
his shops furnishings to the Museum of the City of New York when he
retired in 1996. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
