<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      05-18 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO INTERIOR MINISTER RESIGNS TO RUN IN NOVEMBER PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A day after the governing party voted to pick its
presidential candidate in a primary election, the man who is widely
believed to be President Ernesto Zedillo's preferred choice
announced Tuesday that he would resign his post to run for the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate, Interior Minister Francisco Labastida Ochoa, has
been the first among equals in the president's cabinet, with
oversight over all domestic political affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the longstanding system in which presidents have
``tapped'' their successors, five successive presidents who held
office from the 1940s through the '70s selected their interior
ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida said he would hand in his resignation to Zedillo on
Thursday, when he returns from a trip to California. Zedillo did
not announce who would succeed Labastida as interior minister.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Labastida, who is 42, was not unexpected.
Although Zedillo has endorsed no candidate, numerous political
commentators have for three months been seeing signs in the often
murky political tea leaves that Labastida is ``el bueno,'' the good
one _ the term for the president's candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Labastida's supporters have turned his trips
outside Mexico City, ostensibly on Interior Ministry business, into
virtual campaign appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's announcement was greeted by one of the usual signs
that a candidate has the backing of the party establishment _
statements of support from the Labor Congress, one of the
party-controlled labor federations.
</P>
<P>
   The early campaign period has traditionally been a delicate
moment, when the Institutional Revolutionary Party candidates, who
have won 11 elections in a row, begin distancing themselves from
the incumbents while seeking to retain their favor and backing.
</P>
<P>
   In making his announcement in a hotel convention room packed
with hundreds of cheering supporters, Labastida said, ``I will
always recognize in Ernesto Zedillo his patriotism, his honesty,
his great dedication to the service of the best causes of our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   As party leaders drafted nominating rules, they faced frequent
criticism from two of Labastida's rivals, former Gov. Manuel
Bartlett Diaz of Puebla and Gov. Roberto Madrazo Pintado of
Tabasco, both of whom have been actively campaigning since Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The two have repeatedly voiced suspicions that new nominating
rules might be rigged to favor the president's candidate, arousing
speculation that either politician might eventually wound the party
by leaving its ranks. Bartlett calmed those fears Tuesday, praising
the rules as a triumph of longtime efforts to strengthen democracy
in the party, although he warned that irregularities could occur in
the primary, scheduled for Nov. 7, if the rules are not fairly
applied.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are good rules,'' Bartlett said. ``I'll stay in this
nominating process until the end. I'm going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo remained silent on his plans. And so did another
potential contender, Gov. Miguel Aleman Velasco of Veracruz, who
has pledged to clarify weeks of ambiguity about his intentions.
Aleman is the son of the former president who presided over the
postwar boom years, and polls show that his legendary name would
make him a formidable candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Aleman encouraged Veracruzanos to call his office to
advise him whether to run. On Monday, he said that most callers
were urging him to stay in Veracruz, and Mexican commentators have
interpreted other recent events, too, as signs that he will not
run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
