   (NYT16) JERUSALEM -- May 18, 1999 -- ISRAEL, 5-18 -- Ehud Barak,
the newly elected prime minister of Israel, and his wife Navah,
embrace Leah Rabin, widow of Yitzak Rabin, at Rabin's grave on
Tuesday. Barak defeated Benjamin Netanyahu Monday in national
elections. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- May 18, 1999 -- CONGRESS-GUNS, 5-18 --
Sen. Orin Hatch is flanked by Manus Cooney, chief counsel on the
Senate Judiciairy committee, left, and Ed Haden, a counsel on the
committee, right, during a hallway meeting outside the room where a
Republican policy luncheon was being held on Capitol Hill, Tuesday.
Democrats and Republicans on the Senate were working behind closed
doors to cut a deal for a limited number of additional amendments,
and a limited debate, so that they could bring the juvenile crime
bill to a final vote. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) TASK FORCE HAWK, Albania -- May 18, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MULE-COX, 05-18 -- Members of an Apache maintenance crew
cruise back from the flightline in the Army's newest weapon against
the mud, a four-wheel-drive Kawasaki Mule. The use of Mules to
transport Apache crews originated several years ago with an Army
special ops helicopter unit called the ``Nightstalkers,'' based at
Fort Campbell, KY. (Joseph P. Albright/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- May 18, 1999 -- PASTA-SAUCE-2, 5-18 -- Alex
Goren says the aroma of his Bolognese meat sauce is ``the smell of
the Italian heart.'' Goren's sauce is ``the best ragu Bolognese
I've ever tasted,'' he says, adding that ``no one makes a better
Neopolitan'' than himself. (Susan Farley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 18, 1999 -- PASTA-SAUCE-1, 5-18 --
Sandro Manzo believes that to love Italy is to love a sauce with
lots of tomatoes, but little meat. ``People from the north - so
fussy, so stingy,'' he says. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
