<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- May 18, 1999 -- PAPILLOTE-2, 5-18 --
Salvatore Anzalone makes seafood spaghetti in parchment at Bondi
Ristorante. Although restaurants know how much panache en papillote
- named for the parchment paper that encloses the food in an
envelope - brings to a dish, there is an additional beauty, one
appreciated by too few home cooks: it is fast and uncomplicated in
its execution, once you get the knack and understand the principles
that underlie the method. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- May 18, 1999 -- PAPILLOTE-1, 5-18 --
Jean-Georges Vongerichten, the chef at Jean Georges, preparing what
he calls ``Jiffy Pop for black bass.'' The cooking method known as
en papillote - for the parchment paper that encloses the food in an
envelope - has held its own through any number of culinary
fashions. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
