<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ART-NYT     05-18 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES BILL REQUIRING SAFETY DEVICES FOR HANDGUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By a lopsided vote of 78-20, the Senate on Tuesday
approved a measure that would require that child safety devices be
included with each of the millions of handguns sold by licensed
dealers in the United States every year.
</P>
<P>
   Only last July, the Senate defeated a similar proposal by a vote
of 61-39. The starkly different outcome this time around was the
latest illustration of federal lawmakers' keener appetite for gun
control after the school shooting in Littleton, Colo., in April.
</P>
<P>
   Another example of that change came in the announcement Tuesday
that House Speaker Dennis Hastert supported several of the new gun
control measures under consideration by the Senate. The House has
yet to consider gun control legislation this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert spokesman John Feehery said Tuesday that the speaker
personally favored mandatory background checks on all buyers at gun
shows, which is a provision in a measure the Senate passed last
week. Feehery said Hastert also supported an increase in the
minimum age for legal possession of a handgun to 21 from 18, a
provision in a proposal the Senate will probably consider this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Feehery stressed that Hastert's opinions were personal and that
the speaker would take the temperature of other Republicans in the
House before promoting any particular legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert had not articulated his feelings about those specific
issues previously, but he had voted in the past against several
successful pieces of gun control legislation, like mandatory
waiting periods for handgun purchases and a ban on many types of
assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In yet another sign of movement by Republicans in Congress,
House Majority Leader Dick Armey said Tuesday that gun control
measures might be allowed to reach the floor of the House in
connection with a juvenile crime bill still in the House Judiciary
Committee. House Republicans had previously said that such measures
were inappropriate additions to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The measure on child safety devices that passed the Senate on
Tuesday was an amendment to a broader juvenile crime bill with an
uncertain fate. Republicans and Democrats were still struggling
Tuesday night to reach some agreement on how much more time the
Senate would devote to the bill and how many more amendments
Republicans and Democrats would be permitted to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott reiterated Tuesday that he
would put the bill on the shelf for the time being if it could not
be brought to a final vote soon, but instead of setting a firm
deadline, Lott merely talked about getting the bill to a final vote
this week.
</P>
<P>
   The bill has become the vehicle for several gun control
amendments, of which the one requiring the sale of child safety
devices was only the latest. Both Republicans and Democrats
attributed the success of that measure, whose principal sponsor was
Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., to changes in the political climate
surrounding gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it shows unquestionably that the horror of what took
place in Littleton, Colo., has had its effect,'' said Sen. John
Chafee, R-R.I., a co-sponsor of Kohl's amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee was one of only three Republicans who supported a version
of the amendment last July. Fifty-two Republicans opposed it then,
as did nine Democrats. Thirty-six Democrats supported it.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's vote, 34 Republicans and 44 Democrats voted in
favor of the amendment. Twenty Republicans opposed it. One
Republican and one Democrat were absent.
</P>
<P>
   Senators who switched their positions between then and now gave
a variety of reasons, from subtle differences in the two versions
of the measure to a heightened concern, bred by the bloodshed at
several schools in recent years, over children's access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel it's the right thing to do,'' said Sen. Gordon
Smith, R- Ore., who voted for child safety devices Tuesday but
against them last year.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that the series of school shootings that culminated
with Littleton ``have a lot of us looking for ways to promote
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to understand what helps, what makes a
difference,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who voted against child safety devices again this
time said the mandatory measure was unnecessary, because such
devices were already available in all gun shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody wants them, they can buy them,'' said Senator Don
Nickles of Oklahoma, the majority whip. ``They're out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Those Republicans who supported the amendment got clear
permission from party leaders. Lott voted for it, and the
Republican managing the debate on the juvenile crime bill, Sen.
Orrin Hatch of Utah, signed onto the amendment as a co-sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's measure applies only to licensed gun dealers, as opposed
to casual sellers, and requires that they include something like a
secure storage container or trigger lock with the sale of every
handgun. According to Handgun Control Inc., a gun control advocacy
group, licensed dealers sell about 2 million handguns annually.
</P>
<P>
   The principal changes in the measure between last year and this
one were minor. In a concession to Republicans, the amendment that
passed Tuesday would grant qualified protection from liability for
owners whose handguns end up causing damage despite the proper use
of a safety device.
</P>
<P>
   This year's version leaves the kind of safety device with a
handgun to a dealer's discretion; last year's required that the
device meet the handgun manufacturer's approval. Wayne La Pierre,
executive vice president of the National Rifle Association, said
today that the organization did not oppose the amendment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
