<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2336 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT &LR;      05-18 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGES REINSTATE CHARGES OVER CAMPAIGN DONATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a victory for the Justice Department's campaign
finance investigation, a federal appeals court panel on Tuesday
reinstated five criminal charges against a Democratic fund-raiser
that had been thrown out by a district court judge.
</P>
<P>
   A unanimous three-judge panel of the United States Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit ruled that a Federal
District Court judge erred in September 1998 when he dismissed five
of six campaign-related charges against the fund-raiser, Maria
Hsia. The five charges accused her of causing false statements to
be filed in reports to federal election officials.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruled that Judge Paul L. Friedman was wrong in
relying on the First Amendment's broad protections of religious
expression and free speech in dismissing the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see no constitutional difficulty in use of the statutes
against the conduct alleged here,'' wrote Judge Stephen F. Williams
in Tuesday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also ruled that Friedman had incorrectly required
prosecutors to show that Ms. Hsia knew she was breaking the law.
The appeals court ruled that prosecutors merely had to show that
she knew her statements were false when she misidentified donors to
election officials.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was appointed to the federal appellate bench by
President Ronald Reagan in the 1980's, was joined in the ruling by
Judges Judith W. Rogers and David S. Tatel, who were appointed by
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ruling applies only to Ms. Hsia, it appears highly
likely that it will lead to the reinstatement of similar charges
against two other Democratic fund-raisers, Yah Lin Trie, a longtime
friend of President Clinton, and Pauline Kanchanalak, a Thai
businesswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's spokesman, Myron Marlin, said that
prosecutors were pleased by the decision. ``This means we can press
ahead on these charges not only in this case but in other cases,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hsia's lawyer, Nancy Luque, said that she would appeal the
ruling to the full Circuit Court or the Supreme Court. ``I'm
disappointed that the Court of Appeals did not see the wisdom of
Judge Friedman's analysis premised as it was on important First
Amendment freedoms,'' Ms. Luque said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling could provide a lift to the Justice Department, which
has brought only a few major cases after nearly three years of
investigation into Democratic campaign finance abuses in 1996.
Republicans in Congress have criticized the department's handling
of the inquiry, focusing on Attorney General Janet Reno's refusal
to allow an outside prosecutor to investigate any aspect of the
campaign finance issue.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, it appeared that Friedman's rulings in campaign
finance cases would seriously undercut the Justice Department's
efforts. In one ruling he described the government's efforts as an
``Alice in Wonderland'' interpretation of the law to allow
prosecutors to charge Ms. Hsia with a felony instead of a
misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman's rulings symbolized the dilemma confronting
prosecutors in trying to bring criminal cases using election laws
that the judge said had been intentionally engineered by Congress
to be weak and permit exactly the kind of fund-raising excesses at
the heart of the campaign finance case.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's ruling recast the atmosphere surrounding the Hsia,
Trie and Kanchanalak cases, validating the legal theories behind
the government's indictments and reviving the prospect that Ms.
Hsia, along with Trie and Ms. Kanchanalak, would be tried for the
crime of causing campaign committees to file false statements to
the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Hsia's case, the reinstated charges center directly on
her fund-raising activities. They accuse her of disguising
contributions to the Clinton-Gore campaign and other Federal
candidates between 1993 and 1996 by providing election officials
with the names of contributors who were not the true source of
donations.
</P>
<P>
   The straw donors actually concealed legally questionable
contributors like the International Buddhist Progress Society,
which operates the Hsi Lai Temple in California. The temple was the
host of an April 1996 fund-raiser attended by Vice President Al
Gore, who was named as an unindicted co-conspirator when Ms. Hsia
was indicted last year.
</P>
<P>
   The one charge among the original six that had stood against Ms.
Hsia was for conspiracy involving $65,000 in illegal contributions
by the temple.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
