<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2343 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      05-18 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES BILL BANNING MOST SUITS AGAINST GUNMAKERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The House on Tuesday gave final approval to a
bill banning most governmental lawsuits against gunmakers, and
defeated an amendment calling for criminal background checks at gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 717 by Sen. Jon Lindsay, R-Houston, would prevent
cities, counties and other entities from suing manufacturers and
sellers of firearms and ammunition for the public costs associated
with gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   Already passed in the Senate, the bill was approved 107-39 in
the House. It now goes to Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our chance to send a signal that in Texas we believe
in individual responsibility, and that the money-hungry trial
lawyers need to be sent packing to find another industry,'' said
Rep. Rick Green, R-Dripping Springs, sponsor of the bill in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's opponents offered various amendments, including one
that would allow cities to block gun show sales made without a
criminal background check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a gun person, I like guns,'' said Rep. Jim Dunnam, D-Waco,
who offered the amendment. But I don't think I should be able to
buy a gun without a background check.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier attempts to advance measures calling for such background
checks have failed both at the committee level and in the Senate.
The House defeated Dunnam's amendment 89-54.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the bill would prevent Texas jurisdictions from
joining a nationwide trend, modeled on successful litigation
against tobacco companies, forcing gunmakers to pay for the public
costs of violence from guns.
</P>
<P>
   Most suits in other states claim the industry is negligent for
not including more safety features. Damages are sought for
governmental expenses on police and emergency services, hospital
treatment and prosecutions related to gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   Exceptions in Texas would allow governmental entities to seek
legislative permission to file such lawsuits. In all other
instances, cities and counties could still sue for defective
equipment and any resulting injury or death.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would not prevent private individuals from suing
gunmakers for any other reason. In addition, the bill would allow
the Texas attorney general to sue on behalf of the state or any
other governmental unit.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents argued that the bill's provisions amounted to a
special immunity from liability for a particularly powerful private
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am amazed we have a bill so strongly in favor to protect a
special interest group,'' said Rep. Juan Hinojosa, D-McAllen. ``I
have never seen a bill like this in my 14 years in the
Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of the recent tragedies in this country, instead of
trying to find ways to reduce the number of guns available to
criminals and to juveniles, here we are trying to find ways to
protect the gun industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation's supporters, which include the National Rifle
Association, Texas State Rifle Association and gun sellers, argue
that such lawsuits are an attempt to impose gun policy through the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   During the past several months, New Orleans, Chicago, Miami-Dade
County, Atlanta and Bridgeport, Conn., have filed suits claiming
the gun companies are legally responsible for the harm their
products cause.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Legislature passed a bill similar to Lindsay's,
forcing a showdown between the state and the mayor of Atlanta over
the future of that city's litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Although no Texas jurisdiction has launched such a lawsuit,
opponents of the bill, including Texans Against Gun Violence, have
said the state should preserve the right to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sylvester Turner, D-Houston, tried to amend the bill to
allow any city or county that wished to pursue such a case to let
the voters decide.
</P>
<P>
   Turner challenged supporters of ``local control'' to vote for
his amendment, arguing members could protect the gun lobby and
still allow constituents to decide whether to sue them. The
amendment failed.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's opponents outside of the Legislature expanded beyond
the gun lobby in Texas to include tort reformers, who characterized
the wave of litigation against gunmakers as a money-making ploy by
trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Opelt, Houston-based executive director of Citizens Against
Lawsuit Abuse, said many industries have limited immunity from such
legal actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The makers of light aircraft and the providers of raw
materials for implanted medical devices have been granted special
protections,'' Opelt said. ``These are mistargeted lawsuits,''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Mayor Lee Brown and Harris County Attorney Michael P.
Fleming have passed on requests by anti-gun organizations to
initiate lawsuits on behalf of local taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a Scripps Howard Texas Poll found that 94 percent of
Texans do not blame gun makers for gun violence, and more than
two-thirds oppose letting cities and counties sue for damages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
