<HEADLINE>
STOCKS AND SPEECHES FATTEN WALLETS OF PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Their bottom lines expanded by a booming stock
market and lucrative speaking fees, six of the candidates for
president reported assets of more than $1 million, according to
financial disclosure forms filed this week.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the way was Steve Forbes, the publisher, who reported
assets worth more than $19 million, much of it in stocks and three
properties in his hometown, Bedminster, N.J. Forbes, a Republican,
also received more than $644,000 last year from 24 speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, who is challenging Vice
President Al Gore for the Democratic nomination, reported assets of
at least $5.7 million and income of more than $2.6 million last
year, most of it from speaking fees.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has reported assets of $1.4 million to $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, the former president of the American Red Cross
who is seeking the Republican nomination, reported assets of more
than $6 million. Mrs. Dole received $1.6 million from speeches over
the past 17 months, but gave $1.1 million of that to a charity, the
Elizabeth Dole Charitable Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Alexander, the former Tennessee governor who is also
running for the Republican nomination, reported assets worth more
than $6.8 million and nearly $1 million from the merger of a
company he helped start in 1987 with an investment of $6,300.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, Republican of Arizona, and his wife, Cindy,
reported assets of more than $9.7 million, which includes his
investments in a Phoenix beer distributor and several other
businesses in his home state. McCain also reported donating a
$70,833 book advance to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Four other Republican candidates, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas,
the conservative activist Gary Bauer, former Vice President Dan
Quayle and the commentator Pat Buchanan have been given 45-day
extensions to file their reports.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley reported owning several million dollars in stocks and
bonds, including more than $1 million in the BankAmerica Corp. He
received $1.6 million for 64 speeches, $171,042 for lectures at
Stanford University, the University of Maryland and Notre Dame
University, and $126,953 in pension payments from the National
Basketball Association and the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He also received $431,250 as a consultant, mainly on
international economic issues, to the Morgan Guaranty Trust Co.,
J.P. Morgan Services and the Gartner Group of Stamford, Conn.
Bradley has ended his relationship with the three companies, an
aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley reported owning property in Athens, 80 acres of
unimproved land in Nova Scotia, Canada, and a house in Washington,
part of which he rents.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who is expected to self-finance much of his campaign,
reported receiving $42,007 from a family farm in Bedminster and a
$2.2 million salary from Forbes Family Holdings, the family's
publishing company, of which Forbes is president and editor in
chief. He also reported liabilities of more than $4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Mrs. Dole's assets were in stocks and bonds, including
more than $1 million in a Riggs Prime Money Market Fund. Her
husband, former Senator Bob Dole, reported that his consulting
company, Bob Dole Enterprises, was worth more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander reported receiving $970,000 from the merger last year
of Bright Horizons Family Solutions, a Cambridge, Mass., company
that provides day care services to businesses, which he helped
start in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   He received $420,000 from stock options he was given as a board
member of the Learning Co., a company in Cambridge, Mass., that
produces educational software, according to the report. And
Alexander received $235,000 for serving as a director of three
other companies, $88,000 in legal fees and $76,000 in speaking
fees.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his home, he reported owning two rental
properties in Knoxville and a vacation house on 35 acres in
Walland, Tenn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
