u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPECIAL-PROSECUTORS-N     05-18 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIAL-PROSECUTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROCEDURES PROPOSED FOR NEW SPECIAL PROSECUTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bipartisan commission headed by two former Senate
majority leaders recommended Tuesday that when the independent
counsel law expires next month, it be replaced with new procedures
allowing the attorney general to appoint special prosecutors to
investigate whether top officials had committed crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the special prosecutor would have full
authority to conduct grand jury proceedings, issue indictments,
conduct trials and appeal decisions. But in contrast with the
current system, the attorney general would have considerable
control over the scope, cost and length of the investigations.
</P>
<P>
   In a preface to the report, the former majority leaders, Bob
Dole, a Republican from Kansas, and George J. Mitchell, a Democrat
from Maine, said they had set out to consider how the independent
counsel statute should be revised if Congress decided to renew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now evident,'' the former Senators said, that ``the act
will not be renewed. The focus of our report is thus now on the
inescapable question of what should follow next month's final
sunset of the act.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little political support for the existing law, which
expires on June 30. Most Republicans in Congress never thought much
of the law in the first place. And most Democrats believe that
Kenneth W. Starr exceeded proper bounds in his investigation of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The commission was organized by the Brookings Institution and
the American Enterprise Institute, leading research centers here.
The findings and recommendations were spelled out in an article by
Dole and Mitchell on the Op-Ed page of The New York Times on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general has the authority to name special
prosecutors, but the commission proposed that the procedures be
spelled out in law.
</P>
<P>
   It recommended that the attorney general appoint a special
prosecutor when a normal Justice Department investigation would
pose a conflict of interest. The prosecutor would have full
authority to conduct an independent investigation, bring charges
and try cases.
</P>
<P>
   But after two years and each year after that, the attorney
general would be required to review the work of the prosecutor and
decide whether the investigation should continue or be ended.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Dole and Mitchell, the commission members were
Zoe Baird, president of the Markle Foundation; Drew S. Days III, a
former solicitor general and assistant attorney general; Carla
Anderson Hills, former United States trade representative and
secretary of Housing and Urban Development; former Rep. Bill Paxon,
R-N.Y.; John G. Roberts Jr., former deputy solicitor general;
former Rep. David E. Skaggs, D-Colo.; former Attorney General
Richard Thornburgh; and Mark H. Tuohey III, who was deputy
independent counsel in the Whitewater investigation in 1994 and
1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2156EDT &QL; 
