<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2349 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-COMETS-HNS &LR;      05-18 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The telephone had been the enemy, lying so frustratingly silent for
months, never bringing the anticipated news that the collapse of
the American Basketball League had been just a nightmare.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Then it rang, alerting Kara Wolters that future paychecks would
be forthcoming not just from the solvent WNBA but from the two-time
defending league champion Comets.
</P>
<P>
   Wolters, a 6-7 center who in 1995 helped Connecticut become only
the second undefeated NCAA women's champion, on May 4 had been
picked in the third round, the 36th player taken in the deepest
draft the WNBA has conducted.
</P>
<P>
   But the phone call from Comets coach/general manager Van
Chancellor was anticlimactic. Wolters had been monitoring the draft
through the Internet and knew of her fate before chatting with
Chancellor. Nothing could dent her excitement, though, including a
call that came far later than she imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of funny when he called me,'' Wolters said
Tuesday. ``He said, `Big 'un, I've been tryin' to get ahold of ya.'
I was excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous at the draft. I was a little surprised
that I went so late. But the more I thought about it later, I was
so pleased and excited to be in Houston, it was OK that I went so
late.''
</P>
<P>
   There would be another phone conversation that day, one that
sent Wolters' spirits even higher. Jennifer Rizzotti, Wolters' 5-6
former teammate at Connecticut and with the ABL New England
Blizzard, was taken by the Comets in the fourth round, the 48th of
50 players selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ecstatic about being in Houston and playing for such a
terrific team and for such a great coach,'' Wolters said. ``And on
top of everything, I have Jen Rizzotti here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolters is uncertain who called whom with the good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were both trying to track each other down,'' she said.
``When I heard her name called (in the draft), it was like a sigh
of relief. I was thinking, `Yes! I've got my buddy with me.' I was
so excited we got to go together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like we were rookies again. And we get to go
through the experience together. We have each other. That makes it
a little easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wolters-Rizzotti portion of the UConn Connection has been
yoked for the better part of the past five years. Wolters was the
Final Four Most Valuable Player in 1995 when the Huskies beat
perennial powerhouse Tennessee to complete a 35-0 season and grab
the school's first and only NCAA crown.
</P>
<P>
   She was the Big East and Associated Press Player of the Year in
1996-97 and graduated as Connecticut's all-time leading rebounder.
</P>
<P>
   Rizzotti has a similar rsum. She was the Wade Trophy recipient
in 1996, the AP Player of the Year for '95-96 and the Francis
Pomeroy Naismith Award winner that same season.
</P>
<P>
   Wolters and Rizzotti were reunited for more than two years on
the pro level as members of the Blizzard, which routinely set
attendance records in the ABL.
</P>
<P>
   And what could be better than extending the UConn Connection to
Houston and chasing a WNBA championship ring along with Cynthia
Cooper, Sheryl Swoopes and Tina Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fantastic to play for such a phenomenal team,'' Rizzotti
said. ``It's hard to believe that of all the 50 (draftees) to get
drafted by the 12 different (WNBA) teams, we are on the same team
again. It's a nice little coincidence for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolters and Rizzotti have weathered the spectrum of emotions
over the past six months to arrive on coincidence's doorstep. There
was the sadness and disappointment of this past December when, five
days before Christmas, news arrived that the ABL, barely 2{ years
old, was closing its doors and filing for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a very good Christmas for all of us,'' Rizzotti
said. ``It was probably the first time that most of us would
probably rather have not been home for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've bounced back from it. I think all of the players
wanted to be in one league anyway. So it just happened a little
sooner than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the former ABL players, Wolters and Rizzotti
weren't left in the cold when the league folded. They could take
solace from the knowledge each was talented enough to gain more
than casual notice from the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   But that was tinged with frustration when the animosity between
the WNBA and its newly formed players union postponed the draft for
a week and threatened to scuttle the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an emotional roller coaster,'' Rizzotti said, ``from
being shocked and disappointed at the league folding, to getting
back in the mindset of working out, getting ready. Having to wait
and see where I was going to get drafted, that was pretty
nerve-racking. But I'm excited to come down here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little bit of anxiety to know where I'm going to fit
in. But so far, it's been great.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been an up-and-down journey. And neither is assured a
berth on the Comets' 11-player roster.
</P>
<P>
   But they've played the waiting game before. What's another few
weeks? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
