<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY LABELS `ROBIN HOOD' SCHOOL PLAN IN TEXAS A SUCCESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ The so-called Robin Hood school funding
plan that shifted money from rich districts to poor ones has closed
the performance gap in the state's basic skills test, a new study
concludes.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas A&AMP;M University study indicates the plan has brought
parity to the results of the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills,
lifting the scores of poorer, largely minority districts over the
past several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the purposes of Robin Hood was to take away the
advantages of wealthy districts in terms of TAAS scores,'' said
Kenneth Meier, a Texas A&AMP;M professor and director of the Texas
Educational Excellence Project, which directed the study. ``Our
conclusion is that it's been a success.''
</P>
<P>
   The study is believed to be the first of its kind to examine the
impact of the Robin Hood law on academic performance in Texas and
is a validation of sorts for those who battled arduously for equal
funding. Approved in 1993, equalization stemmed from a lawsuit by
the state's poor school districts, most notably San Antonio's
largely Hispanic Edgewood school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We argued that students in poor districts would do better
under a fairer distribution of funds,'' said Al Kauffman, a lawyer
with the Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund who
represented Edgewood. ``To the extent it's moving in that
direction, we're happy to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kauffman added that the very schools that benefited from
equalization still face enormous challenges, among them lagging ACT
and SAT scores, high dropout rates and poor college enrollment
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which included all Texas school districts, examined
the effect of the school funding plan on the performance of Anglo,
Hispanic, African-American and low-income students in the basic
skills test. It found that equalization not only eliminated the
advantages of local money but also increased the importance of
state money in shaping student performance.
</P>
<P>
   While Meier and his colleagues say they have established a clear
link between school funding and academic performance, others are
skeptical. Such a relationship has long been called into question
in the academic field, and at least one University of Texas scholar
describes it as ``weak and small.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If national researchers have had a very hard time finding any
independent effect of money on student outcomes, I am suspicious of
Meier et al not only claiming that money matters, but that
equalization also matters,'' said Jay Greene, a University of Texas
professor and expert on public education.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 Houston Chronicle series on Edgewood concluded that
hundreds of millions of dollars in Robin Hood money had made little
difference in that San Antonio district. Though TAAS scores were
higher, Edgewood had failed to close the gap with the state
average.
</P>
<P>
   While most experts agree that equalization is essentially good,
they are divided over whether school funding is a legitimate means
for education reform. Detractors in Texas and nationwide are
increasingly looking toward solutions such as increased competition
among schools and vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Edgewood is the site of potentially the
largest private voucher experiment in the country, with a
pro-voucher group giving out $50 million in scholarships for
district residents to enroll in mostly private schools. The results
of that effort will not be known for several years.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas A&AMP;M study found that students in Texas school
districts with higher local revenue performed better on TAAS during
the 1994-95 school year than those students in poorer districts.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, in the 1996-97 school year, the study found no
relationship between district wealth and the basic skills test for
any students, among them Anglos, Hispanics, African-Americans and
students of low income.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we were primarily interested in the effects of local
revenues and district wealth on student performance, we were
careful to control for a variety of other inputs known to shape
student performance,'' said Jerry Polinard, a University of Texas
Pan American scholar, who participated in the study.
</P>
<P>
   Among those other factors: average teacher salaries, teacher
experience and student-teacher ratios.
</P>
<P>
   But Greene criticized the methodology of the study, saying Meier
and his colleagues are inferring their results from changes over
time, when in fact many things change over time. He proposed a
study that seeks to establish whether states with a greater degree
of equal funding have better test scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that if they want to prove something about
equalization, they should measure it directly,'' Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   Meier, however, dismissed the criticism, saying sarcastically
that the change in academic performance among poorer students might
be attributed to sunspots. He likened equal funding to a level
playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a positive sign that the state's school finance system is
moving in a direction where local wealth is redistributed to ensure
that no particular student group will reap its advantages to the
exclusion of others,'' Meier said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
