<SLUG> BC-DETROIT-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK MAN'S DEATH RAISES RACIAL TENSIONS IN DETROIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The beating death of an unarmed black man in front of
his children at a neighborhood gas station has sparked four days of
protests here that have brought into the open the festering racial
tensions between blacks and Arab-Americans who own many small
businesses in the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   The black man, Kalvin Porter, 34, got into a fight with two
Arab-American clerks at the gas station Friday after one made an
inappropriate remark to Porter's 12-year-old stepdaughter, police
said. Porter, who was also accompanied by his four young children,
was then beaten to death by the clerks, one of whom was carrying a
lug wrench, according to police reports and Detroit Police Chief
Benny Napoleon. The clerks, Fadhel Mazeb, 46, and Adel Altam, 26,
were charged with second-degree murder and pleaded not guilty. They
remain in custody.
</P>
<P>
   The incident has drawn nightly demonstrations by up to 200
people since Friday, with protesters demanding that the gas station
be closed. They vow not to allow the station to reopen unless it
changes hands and is run by blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Porter's death is a tragic example of festering problems
of ill will and ill feelings'' between African-Americans and some
Arab-American store operators, said the Rev. Wendell Anthony,
president of the Detroit chapter of the NAACP. ``The
African-American community has too long been the victim of
mistreatment and disrespect by some who operate and work in stores
and gas stations in our neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Arab-American leaders said Porter's death was not a racial
matter. ``How many Arab-Americans have been killed in their
stores?'' asked Osama Siblani, publisher and editor of the
Arab-American News, a weekly newspaper. The paper is published in
the Detroit suburb of Dearborn, the center of the nation's largest
Arab-American community.
</P>
<P>
   Siblani said 500 Arab-Americans had been killed in the Detroit
area, mostly by African-Americans, in the last decade. ``But you
didn't see Arab-Americans demonstrating in front of
African-American churches, he added.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter was killed at a Sunoco station on the city's east side,
in a neighborhood where buildings are guarded by fences with razor
wire. In intermittent rain, about 35 protesters gathered at the
station Monday night carrying signs reading ``Don't burn them down,
shut them down,'' and ``Arabs killed our brother.'' Passing cars
and tractor-trailers honked in support as they drove past the
picket line.
</P>
<P>
   One protester, Minister Malik Shabazz, said Porter's death hit a
nerve because of racial and class tensions between African-American
residents and Arab-American merchants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They own the stores, we are the customers,'' said Shabazz, who
is black.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters told of being harassed by attendants at the gas
station, which also functioned as the neighborhood grocery store.
Eric Hansard, 19, who lives a few blocks away, said clerks so often
accused him and other teen-agers of stealing that he stopped
shopping at the store. Others told of poor treatment at other
Arab-American-owned stores elsewhere in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers stood guard as the station owner, Steve Mallah,
watched the demonstration from his darkened gas station and said he
did not blame the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a tragedy here,'' Mallah said. ``I feel for his
family.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mallah, who has owned the store for 10 years and said he had
never had problems with anyone in the neighborhood, added that the
two clerks charged in the beating were in custody, while he and his
store were caught up in the larger atmosphere of racial tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here in the business not to kill people or to fight with
people,'' Mallah said. ``I'm here to make a living. By shutting
down the station, they don't solve any problems. They just make
another victim _ which is me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
