<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-PREMIUMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALPERS ALLOWS INCREASES IN HEALTH PREMIUMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Minn.)   (af)  
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first sign that the cost of health care insurance could
rise 9 percent to 11 percent again next year, the nation's
second-biggest buyer of health benefits said Tuesday that it had
agreed to an average increase of 9.7 percent in premiums for
California's state and local government workers.
</P>
<P>
   The California Public Employees Retirement System, which
negotiates coverage for a million people, said Kaiser Permanente,
the financially troubled health maintenance organization that
covers some 400,000 people in the system, would get the largest
increase, an average 11.7 percent. That is on top of 10.75 percent
for 1999 for Kaiser, which has been losing about $1 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said the increases would lift profits for
managed care companies, many of which have had low profit margins.
But a group that bargains for 21 big California employers has been
exploring long-range strategies that include bypassing HMOs and
dealing directly with hospitals and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   In bargaining for big increases, the HMOs said they had to pay
more to struggling groups of California doctors and hospitals, some
pushed to the brink of bankruptcy after years of relatively low
payments.
</P>
<P>
   But Edward Keaney, a health care analyst at Volpe Brown Whelan &AMP;
Co. in San Francisco, said that even 1 percent added to HMO profits
would be significant for companies like Foundation Health Systems,
which has margins of about 2.5 percent, and Pacificare, which is in
the 4 percent range.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying costs for hospitals and doctors have been rising
5 percent to 6 percent, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Stanley, health benefits administrator for Calpers, the
No. 2 public buyer of health insurance after the federal
government, said the agency would require health plans to report
how much of the increase is sent to their parent companies and how
much is spent on health care.
</P>
<P>
   She said some public employees might switch to lower-cost plans
from Kaiser and the Healthnet unit of Foundation Health, which is
raising premiums 9.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Blaine Bos, a principal with the William M. Mercer consulting
firm, said employers would be taking a hard look at costs and
typically would increase employees' share of premiums and other
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Powers, executive director of the Pacific Business
Group on Health, said her employer members were frustrated because
the health plans were ``more focused on Wall Street than in
partnering with us for fundamental changes'' to contain costs.
</P>
<P>
   Her group bargains with HMOs for 21 big companies, which often
set the pattern for three million HMO members. She said her group
recently held talks with employers in Minnesota who have bypassed
HMOs and deal directly with doctor and hospital groups. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
