<SLUG> BC-PENNEY-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENNEY PLANS INITIATIVES TO RAISE $6 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   J.C. Penney reported lower first-quarter earnings Tuesday but
announced two initiatives that could raise as much as $6 billion in
revenue. The news sent the company's previously lagging stock price
up 9.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended May 1, the retailer reported net income of
$167 million, or 61 cents a diluted share, compared with $174
million, or 64 cents a share, in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The results were 8 cents better than Wall Street expectations,
according to First Call Corp., which tracks company earnings, but
hardly impressive because they come at a time when many other
retail chains have reported unusually robust earnings gains.
</P>
<P>
   But Penney, based in Plano, Texas, kept its stock from taking a
hit by announcing the two revenue-raising initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   First, the company said it was looking to sell its credit card
business. Penney is the fourth-biggest store card issuer, with
receivables of about $3.71 billion at the end of the quarter. The
company expects to get roughly a dollar for every dollar of
receivables and to use the proceeds to pay down its debt. Theda
Page-Whitehead, a company spokeswoman, said negotiations were under
way, but she declined to identify the potential purchaser.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company said it would sell a 20 percent stake
in Eckerd Corp., a fast-growing drug store chain, to the public as
a tracking stock, which will reflect Eckerd's financial results and
will not include Penney's other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Eckerd, which has 2,900 stores in 22 states, had sales of $10.3
billion last year. But the chain's operating income for the year
ended Jan. 31 was $254 million, down 26.8 percent from results in
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate the sale of Eckerd stock could raise $1
billion to $2 billion. The proceeds will be used to buy back stock,
the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Penney's motives in selling a stake in Eckerd are clearly to
unlock some of the unit's value. The department store's stock
trades at about 18 times estimated earnings, whereas stocks for big
drug store chains trade at much higher multiples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drug stores at this size are trading at a multiple of 44 times
earnings,'' said Burt Flickinger III, a retail consultant with
Reach Marketing in Westport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The initiatives, which the company expects to complete in the
fourth quarter, were treated as generally good news by Wall Street,
where Penney's shares rose $4.4375, to $50.125, in heavy trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first move that this management has done in a long
while to show it cares about creating shareholder value,'' said
Dana Cohen, a retail analyst with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But some thought that the response was too optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reaction to stock is completely overblown compared with
the magnitude of the announcements,'' said Richard Church, a retail
analyst with Salomon Smith Barney. ``The sale of the receivables
portfolio is going to generate fewer savings than most people
believe. I don't think there is going to be any impact on earnings
per share. What you save in interest expense you give up in credit
income.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also raised concerns that Penney was using sleights of
hand to distract investors from more fundamental problems.
Certainly, the nation's second-largest retailer has been
struggling. Sales growth has remained stagnant as discounters like
Target, a unit of Dayton Hudson, and Old Navy, a unit of Gap Inc.,
which sells hip low-price speciality clothing, are stealing its
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that is glaringly absent is any kind of sign that
they are going to do better with the core business,'' said Kurt
Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report. ``They are
pushing the stock price up for now, but a year from now the problem
will be the same, because the company has a complete lack of
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   But Penney's chief executive, James Oesterreicher, said, not for
the first time, that the department store was on the verge of a
turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the month of April our top eight brands had revenue
increases in the double digits,'' he said. Penney's private brands
include St. John's Bay and Arizona Jean Co. Oesterreicher said the
company would continue to emphasize these speciality brands and
predicted sales in stores open a year, a key measure of sales
growth, would be positive for the company's third and fourth
quarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
