<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-LIMITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL PANEL CALLS FOR MORE LIMITS ON LEGAL GAMBLING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pressing toward a mid-June deadline, a federal
commission Tuesday recommended several restrictions on legalized
gambling, including a call for states to consider ``gambling impact
statements'' before approving new lotteries, casinos, or
racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   A day after urging a ban on any wagering on collegiate sports,
which currently is allowed in Nevada and Oregon, the National
Gambling Impact Study Commission also decided to recommend tighter
restrictions on state-run lotteries and more regulation of casino
gambling, including on Indian reservations.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-member commission cautioned against allowing
financially troubled pari-mutuel facilities to expand their
operations to include casino gambling, a tactic similar to what was
proposed two years ago at Sam Houston Race Park in northwest
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Created two years ago, the commission has no authority to
implement any of its recommendations. Instead, they will be
included in a report, due June 18, to the president, Congress,
state governors and Indian tribal governments.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's final meeting before submitting its report is set
for June 2-3 in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, commissioners postponed action on a proposal to push
for barring gambling interests from donating to elected officials'
campaign funds. Also put off was a proposal rebuking American
Indian casinos that refused to respond to a commission survey about
their gaming operations.
</P>
<P>
   The commission earlier approved recommendations to ban Internet
gambling and wagering by anyone younger than 21. The panel also
wants casinos and lotteries to post notices explaining the odds of
winning at various games and the dangers and risks of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the commission voted 5-4 to slow two decades of
rapid growth in legalized gambling by suggesting a nationwide
moratorium on new casinos, lotteries, and pari-mutuel wagering
operations. Since then, three states have moved toward legalizing
casinos and three others have taken steps toward going into the
lottery business.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the commission voted to recommend that state and
local governments be required to consider forecasts of the social
and economic effects on communities before legalizing any form of
gambling or adding a gaming facility. The forecasts would be much
like the environmental studies required before streams can be
dammed or land can be developed.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Robert Loescher, an Alaska businessman,
characterized the impact statement as anti-business and an obstacle
to communities and companies wanting to engage in legal activity.
``This becomes a holdup ... a delay,'' he complained.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner John Wilhelm, president of the Hotel Employees and
Restaurant Employees Union, agreed, but added: ``I don't think
that's bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Among recommendations that commissioners approved for their
report are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Tougher truth-in-advertising laws aimed at lotteries and
tribal gambling operations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ending aggressive advertising campaigns by state lotteries
designed to woo young and lower-income Americans.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barring state lotteries from moving into casino-style instant
games, such as video poker and slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   _ Removing ``convenience gambling'' machines, such as video
poker, from neighborhood stores and taverns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Banning automated teller machines from race tracks and
casinos.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prohibiting casino ``cruises to nowhere'' unless they are
allowed by the states in which the ships dock.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spending a portion of state tax or tribal proceeds from casino
operations on researching, preventing and treating problem
gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Preventing horse-track operators and other pari-mutuel
operations from introducing casino-style gaming to help bail out
economically troubled facilities or competing with other forms of
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Until two years ago, Houston businessman Charles Hurwitz lobbied
the Texas Legislature to allow him to add card-game wagering, such
as poker and blackjack, at Sam Houston Race Park as it emerged from
bankruptcy. Hurwitz did not seek approval for other casino-style
gambling, like roulette wheels or craps. State lawmakers turned him
down. The track currently reports operating at a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's decision by the commission to push for an end to all
legalized gambling on collegiate sports rankled Rep. Jim Gibbons, a
Nevada Republican who predicted the proposal would never be enacted
by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``This proposal has about as much chance of becoming law as I
have of hitting a home run off Greg Maddux,'' Gibbons said Tuesday,
referring to the Atlanta Braves' near-perennial Cy Young winner.
``This recommendation is a clear violation of states' rights. I
will forcefully fight it if it is introduced in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
