<HEADER>
A2363 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVEREST-CLIMB-COX     05-18 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVEREST-CLIMB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LBJ High Grad Phones Austin Students From Mt. Everest Summit
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Austinite Jacek Maselko stood Tuesday on the
roof of the world _ the summit of Mount Everest _ joining more than
1,000 people who have reached the peak since 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Maselko, 29, believed to be the first Austinite to reach the
summit of the 29,028-foot mountain, climbed for about five hours
Tuesday to accomplish the feat. His ascent comes 46 years after Sir
Edmund Hillary and Tenzing Norgay made it to the top.
</P>
<P>
   A biologist and part owner of Patagonia Mountain Agency reached
the summit with his client Tadeusz Kudelski, and his boss, Ryszard
Pawlowski, a veteran Everest summiteer who followed them. He also
took along with him students of the LBJ Science Academy in Austin,
via the Internet and satellite phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   When he reached the summit Tuesday, Maselko gulped oxygen from a
portable bottle and then _ finding the speech that he had
momentarily lost _ described for the awed Austin students his view
from the top of Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he could see was clouds,'' said 16-year-old Lindsay
Zuloaga. ``He was above everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Maselko is a 1989 LBJ High School graduate who frequently led
adventuresome science students on thrilling trips to Guadalupe Peak
and other Texas climbing haunts.
</P>
<P>
   As he braved the below-zero temperatures and tortuous winds of
Mount Everest, students tracked his progress daily and kept in
touch through satellite phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   In his call to students Tuesday, static on the phone consumed
most of Maselko's words. But Zuloaga and eight other students,
seven parents and LBJ science teacher Jackson Pace got the message.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when Maselko clearly said ``Sic 'em Jags,'' a
reference to the northeast Austin school's mascot, the Jaguar.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was really inspiring,'' said Pace, who coordinated the
students' share of the adventure and spent Monday night with them
in the LBJ Science Academy's office so they could take the 3:10
a.m. call.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all exhausted,'' said Sarah Parks, 15, ``so we could
sympathize with what they were going through.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a sunny Tuesday afternoon on Everest when Maselko and the
others reached the summit, where daytime temperatures are tens of
degrees below zero. Maselko let a Polish client precede him to the
summit.
</P>
<P>
   His group had been delayed almost a week by a snowstorm that
reportedly cost the lives of two members of some of the 23 other
commercial groups ascending the Himalayan mountain this spring. But
Maselko and the others stayed atop Everest only an hour, coming
down when a growing wind made it dangerous to linger.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens have died in expeditions up Mount Everest, including
eight during a May 1996 expedition. While Maselko was making his
summit, a group of climbers discovered the frozen body of British
mountaineer George Mallory, who died in 1924 while trying to reach
the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday morning, Pace got confirmation that the climbers
were safely back at Camp 3 on Everest's north flank.
</P>
<P>
   Maselko plans to call the Science Academy students again today
but it will be later this summer, on a planned visit to Austin,
before he can show them the pebbles he took as mementoes from the
top of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Stanley writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
