<SLUG> BC-DEAD-BILLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE INACTION KILLS DOZENS OF TEXAS BILLS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Hate crimes legislation wasn't the only casualty
of last weekend's deadline for Senate committees to approve House
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of other bills that cleared the House were killed by
Senate inaction, including proposals to exempt school supplies from
sales taxes and prohibit the Legislature from meeting on the
national holiday honoring the late Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the stranded House bills theoretically could
resurface as amendments to still-viable measures, many appeared
moribund for this legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dead. The bill is dead,'' Rep. Ron Wilson, D-Houston,
said Tuesday, describing his failed proposal to ban open containers
of alcohol in vehicles on public roads.
</P>
<P>
   Also perishing in a Senate committee was House Bill 209 by Rep.
Henry Cuellar, D-Laredo, creating a sales tax holiday for the
purchase of school supplies in August. The concept isn't absolutely
dead, however, because Cuellar said he would try to incorporate the
tax break into other tax-relief measures that remain viable.
</P>
<P>
   Even some bills that have made it through one round of approval
in both chambers were in danger of dying over unresolved
differences, including a proposal to allow the Texas Lottery
Commission to increase prizes on scratch-off games.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery proposal, House Bill 844 by Wilson, is hung up on a
dispute over the Senate's demand that lottery advertising be
reduced. A House-Senate negotiating committee has been attempting
to resolve differences since May 12, with a deadline for action of
May 29. The session ends May 31.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson also authored the open-container ban, House Bill 3555,
which was part of a sweeping alcohol regulation measure. House
members amended it to ban minors in bars and to prohibit liquor
sales in sexually oriented businesses, prompting one senator to
``tag'' the bill in committee, delaying its consideration past the
May 14 deadline for Senate committee approval.
</P>
<P>
   The minors in bars proposal also was contained in House Bill 106
by Rep. Leo Alvarado, D-San Antonio, whose free-standing bill was
approved in the House only to perish in a Senate committee Friday.
The same fate was shared by a stand-alone bill banning open
containers in vehicles, House Bill 487 by Rep. Fred Hill,
R-Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Other House-approved bills that hit fatal speedbumps in the
Senate late last week:
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 275 by Rep. George ``Buddy'' West, R-Odessa,
limiting prisoners' recreational amenities.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 537 by Rep. Debra Danburg, D-Houston, regulating
telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 687 by Rep. Fred Bosse, D-Houston, to make Texans
ages 65-67 eligible for free fishing licenses.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 749 by Rep. Leticia Van de Putte, D-San Antonio,
barring sale of some perishable food and drug items at flea
markets.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 1155 by Rep. Ron Lewis, revising health regulations
for the tanning industry.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 1200 by Rep. Joe Crabb, R-Atascocita, to allow
deannexation elections.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 1708 by Rep. Glen Maxey, D-Austin, creating a
maximum charge of $75 for an unrequested tow.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 1827, by Rep. Scott Hochberg, D-Houston, requiring
driver's licenses to have a space for listing an emergency contact.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 2420 by Rep. Joe Driver, R-Garland, to limit
``junk'' or unsolicited faxes.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 2554 by Rep. Charles Jones, R-College Station,
creating special license plates for members of the Air Force Escape
and Evasion Society.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 3552 by Rep. Helen Giddings, D-Dallas, barring the
Legislature from meeting on MLK Day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
