<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-PHONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD ACTION COULD HIKE ONLINE USERS' PHONE COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a decision that some fear will drive up the cost of
going on line, a split state board is preparing to let Bell
Atlantic off the hook for millions of dollars in fees it pays to
companies that handle a large volume of Internet phone traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said the state Department of Telecommunications and
Energy is expected to side with Bell Atlantic on a 3-2 vote,
although officials Tuesday cautioned that the wording of the
decision has not been completed and changes could still occur.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute revolves around the definition of a local call and,
according to some industry officials, the outcome is likely to
revamp the underlying economics of Internet access by telephone in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they rule that way, I predict rates will go up,'' said
Frank Gangi, president of a Quincy-based company that handles
Internet-bound phone traffic for about 1 million people in
Massachusetts and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Under current rules, Gangi's company, Global NAPs, receives
about $1 million a month in so-called reciprocal compensation fees
from Bell Atlantic for helping to handle the Internet-bound phone
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   If state regulators side with Bell Atlantic, those fees will dry
up and Gangi says he will be forced to hike the prices he charges
Internet service providers. Those providers, he says, will be
forced to increase the rates they charge their customers or pull
out of some markets entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Every day across the state, consumers dial local phone numbers
to gain access to the Internet. Right now, many of those calls are
carried initially by Bell Atlantic to a competing phone company,
like Global NAPs, which then routes the calls to an Internet
service provider that connects the customer to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Under contracts Bell Atlantic has with these competing phone
companies, it is required to charge its customer for the call and
use a portion of the money it collects to compensate its competitor
for completing the call.
</P>
<P>
   But Bell Atlantic is required to pay the compensation only if
the call is local. The question facing the Department of
Telecommunications and Energy is whether a call that ends up on the
Internet is truly local.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the DTE ruled that the Internet connections were
local and that Bell Atlantic should pay the reciprocal compensation
fees, which average about a penny a minute.
</P>
<P>
   In February, however, the Federal Communications Commission held
that the calls were long distance but left it up to individual
states to decide whether the current compensation arrangement
should be changed. The FCC said it planned to come up with a new
compensation arrangement sometime in the future.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the FCC decision, state regulators here began
studying the issue again. In the meantime, Bell Atlantic was
ordered to place the bulk of its payments in escrow pending the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, the soon-to-be-released state decision
will hold that the calls are not local and that Bell Atlantic is
not required to make the payments. The decision is also expected to
allow Bell Atlantic to recover the funds in escrow.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday, sources said the DTE majority consisted of Paul
Vasington, James Connelly, and Robert Keating. Those opposed to the
ruling were chairman Janet Gail Besser and Eugene Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time the five-member board has split on any
issue, although the sources said the board was in general agreement
on most of the fundamental issues.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the dissenters apparently have agreed that the
calls are not local but argue Bell Atlantic should continue to
escrow the fees while the agency launches a formal inquiry into how
the competing phone companies should be compensated.
</P>
<P>
   That way, Bell Atlantic and its competitors would both have an
incentive to reach a settlement on the payment issue.
</P>
<P>
   A Bell Atlantic spokesman said Tuesday the company had heard
nothing from DTE. Earlier, Bell Atlantic said that, if it did not
prevail, it would seek to recover the cost of the fees in its rates
from all of its customers, not just those seeking Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic officials said it would make as much as $150
million in reciprocal compensation payments this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gangi, who said he had heard nothing official from DTE, said a
ruling in favor of Bell Atlantic would run counter to what other
states have done. He said 10 other states have ruled on this issue
and in each case the state has decided that the reciprocal
compensation fees should continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
