<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2372 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADES-BABBITT-CO     05-18 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-BABBITT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    White House muscle behind Everglades plan
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Armed with the nation's biggest environmental
restoration proposal and its most complex plan for rescuing
imperiled species, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt pledged Tuesday
that the White House will crusade for the Everglades on Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are out there at the very frontier of science and
restoration,'' Babbitt told more than 300 scientists, engineers,
activists and government leaders. Then he signed a plan aimed at
saving 68 species in South and Central Florida _ ranging from
Florida's state animal, the panther, to plants such as the papery
whitlow-wort.
</P>
<P>
   The species plan, plus a $7.8 billion Everglades restoration
proposal set to go to Congress in July, are the bulwark of the
Clinton administration's efforts to rescue South Florida's
environment. Both are a dramatic break from decades of failed
attempts to protect species and habitats one at a time, Babbitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not pulling any cookbooks off the shelf,'' he added.
``We are doing something brand-new.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd applauded. But afterward, some asked questions:
</P>
<P>
   Where, in the species plan's 2,000 pages, are the teeth needed
to save the species' habitat from development?
</P>
<P>
   Where is the panel of national experts who are supposed to
review the $7.8 billion proposal _ a promise Babbitt made earlier
this year to soothe some skeptical scientists?
</P>
<P>
   How can the government's grand plans succeed when disagreements
among federal agencies have stalled some modest Everglades projects
for years?
</P>
<P>
   The species plan, which has no cost estimate, contains
information on endangered plants, animals and habitat in 19
counties. Local planners can use the data to find ways to protect
the species _ or at least to avoid running afoul of the Endangered
Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of even one species usually masks a deeper problem,
Babbitt said _ the demise of a complex web of plants and animals
that can affect the way people enjoy the outdoors, even their whole
quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   Robert P. King writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
