<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TAX-SILVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX REPEAL UNDERSCORES SILVER'S BALANCING ACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ For five years as the speaker of the state
Assembly, Sheldon Silver has struggled, often against a torrent of
Republican criticism, to deliver this message: His Democrats are
not the party of taxes, and are not solely the party of New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's vote to repeal the commuter tax in New York, a levy
on suburbanites who work in the city, Silver saw a perfect
opportunity to put some muscle behind the message. Lawmakers in
both parties expected the speaker to play his most enduring role,
defender of the city's interests, and block the repeal. Instead, he
embraced it, and the repeal passed.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Silver happily conceded that the
politics of the Assembly's 98-member Democratic conference had
shaped his strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it important for us to stand up and say, `We're not
only about the city, we're about the suburbs, and about upstate as
well,''' he said. ``We had 19 suburban members who needed this.
They needed it for their political advancement. And we in the city
needed them satisfied so they could spend another day supporting
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue illustrated the daily balancing act that Silver's job
entails. He must weigh the interests of city, suburban and upstate
Assembly members against one another; find an equilibrium among the
aims of liberals, moderates and conservatives, and choose between
heartfelt views and more politically expedient positions.
</P>
<P>
   He holds together the fractious Democratic conference that hails
mostly from New York City, while standing up for the city at a time
when New York has a Republican governor and a Republican-controlled
state Senate with few urban allegiances.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the speaker came down on the side of protecting
suburban Democrats whose constituents pay the tax, rather than the
city. That decision will cost the city up to $360 million a year in
revenue, but it was made more palatable by the city's $2 billion
budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Silver's call drew loud protests from some city Democrats and
from New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was, in terms of the city, a very big hit, and I think we
could have at least demanded something in return,'' said
Assemblywoman Deborah Glick, a Manhattan Democrat who voted against
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Tuesday that the issue would force him to alter a
budget that included significant tax cuts. ``What we'll also have
to do, probably, is delay the tax cuts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for those who voted for the bill, ``I can't believe it isn't
going to be an issue, unless they are so safe and so secure that
their constituents don't care if they're voting against their
interests,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   The famously tight-lipped Silver was more secretive than usual
this time, announcing his decision to reporters last week without
first consulting or warning his colleagues. That left some New York
City Democrats fuming that he had not only hurt the city, but had
slighted them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would have been better if there was more time to
discuss the issue,'' said Assemblyman Jeffrey Dinowitz, a Bronx
Democrat who voted against the repeal.
</P>
<P>
   But even his critics on this issue conceded that Silver has been
a steadfast protector of the city, particularly against budget cuts
proposed by Gov. George Pataki. The speaker insured that the
property tax program being phased in around the state includes a
cut in the city income tax. The pre-kindergarten and class-size
reduction programs he pushed into law directed more than half the
money to the city. And in perhaps his most triumphant moment, he
beat back a Republican attempt to undo rent regulations two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   City Democrats, particularly the Assembly's more liberal
members, often complain that Silver is too driven by concern for
the ``marginals'' _ members from suburban and upstate swing
districts who cannot afford to be perceived as liberal or beholden
to the city. Some city Democrats said the commuter tax was a
particularly egregious example, in that it directly harmed the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for helping somebody else in the conference, but I
don't want to get hurt at the same time,'' Dinowitz said. ``Is the
mayor now going to cut services? Is he going to eliminate some of
the tax cuts? Either way, my constituents suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   But many Democrats Tuesday insisted that Silver has made the
regional partnership a fairly equal one, and that this was one
issue Democrats could not afford to cede.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have fallen into the Republicans' trap and gone against
this would have been politically catastrophic,'' said Assemblyman
Richard Brodsky, a Westchester County Democrat who advocated
repealing the tax. ``He who controls the suburbs controls the
state. Shelly knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver said Tuesday that there was never much question that he
would approve the repeal, and quickly. It was important, he said,
``to show we are a statewide conference, and that they are not
going to paint us into a profile that they want us to be in, which
is, `Don't worry, Shelly will pick up the city.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
