<SLUG> BC-CT-POLICE-RACISM-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARTFORD POLICE CHIEF SAYS RACISM ON THE FORCE MUST END 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ With racial tensions rising after the fatal
shooting last month of a black teen-ager by a white police officer,
the Hartford police chief announced Tuesday that he had become
convinced that his force was infected with racism.
</P>
<P>
   He urged white officers to take steps to change their mind-set,
suggesting that they refuse to attend social gatherings unless
black or Hispanic people were present.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Joseph F. Croughwell Jr., who is white, acknowledged that
his statements might be considered tardy. But he said his
department would have to repair its own problems before it could
hope for better relations with black and Hispanic residents, many
of whom have complained that they fear and resent the police since
last month's shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not stand for a continuation of racism within this
department,'' he said. ``I don't think we're at the point where
we're going to die from a cancer, but if we don't remove it and we
don't take care of it, we certainly could.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief, who had not made a public statement since the day the
boy, Aquan Salmon, 14, was shot, said he reached this conclusion
after an emotional presentation last week by several black
ministers who had counseled minority group officers in the
predominantly white police department.
</P>
<P>
   The ministers told him, he said, that the force's two black
commanders had endured racial bias from subordinates. He added
``there were totally false, factless, baseless rumors being passed
throughout the department about the actions'' of one of the two
commanders. The other 10 commanders are white.
</P>
<P>
   He said other black supervisors felt that their orders were
being disobeyed because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want everybody to start thinking about what they may do,
including myself, to perpetuate a perception or an attitude that's
racist,'' Croughwell said. ``For example, let us not go to a social
gathering unless we know that there are going to be people of color
at that social gathering. Let us start thinking about some of the
things we do, some of the things we say. I think that's a first
step.'' He had no other suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   The chief's extraordinary admission won praise from some
community leaders, but vindicated those whose complaints about his
department have been greeted with silence for the last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of the situation, I believe, has hit him flat in
the face,'' said Larry Charles, the executive director of One Chane
Inc., a neighborhood group. ``The ugliness of his department is now
fully exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Nora Wyatt Jr., a rally organizer, said: ``Right now
this community is tense. This community is on edge. And anything
that the chief can do to make it whole should help.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Stewart, the executive director of the National Organization
of Black Law Enforcement Executives, said the chief's directive was
unusual, since most departments resist dealing with racial problems
unless forced to. Such problems have got increasing attention since
the death of Amadou Diallo in New York and the admission by New
Jersey officials that state troopers have singled out
minority-group motorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``A wake-up call like that is usually only in response to a
civil suit or the Department of Justice trying to put a consent
decree on you,'' Stewart said. ``It's a gutsy move.''
</P>
<P>
   Although 68 percent of Hartford's 135,000 residents are black or
Hispanic, 63 percent of the 471 police officers are white. Since
Aquan was shot in the back on April 13, black leaders have held
continual protests, counseling meetings and strategy sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Robert Allan, who shot the boy, has said he thought
Aquan was reaching for a gun. A gun-shaped cigarette lighter was
found nearby.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Gov. John Rowland went to a Hartford church to
face questions from Aquan's neighbors and relatives. They said they
were still angry about the boy's death, and feared that the
investigation into the shooting would not produce a just result.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland had ordered the state police to take over the
investigation after the Hartford police failed to ask the state
police to step in, as other departments have when an officer was
involved in a controversial shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The department is also undergoing a corruption investigation by
federal prosecutors. The week before Aquan's shooting, four current
and former Hartford officers were indicted on charges that they had
been part of a scheme to use the threat of arrest to extort sexual
favors from prostitutes. Prosecutors expect to bring additional
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Croughwell said he had also been told that members of a group of
black and Hispanic officers, the Hartford Guardians, had been
treated with prejudice by white officers. He said the incidents
were under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   STORY CAN HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Cornell Lewis, a black leader who appeared with the
chief at a news conference Tuesday morning, said later that a
typical incident involved a white officer who would walk past a
black supervisor to whom he should turn in a report, and give it to
a white supervisor instead.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis asserted that Croughwell himself was involved in a similar
incident. Lewis said he had been told that a white officer had
received an assignment he did not want from one of the two black
commanders, Deborah Barrows, the assistant chief for patrol
operations. The white officer is said to have had the order
overturned after a call was placed on his behalf to Croughwell, who
was in California.
</P>
<P>
   Croughwell denied countermanding the assistant chief's order.
Chief Barrows appeared with him Tuesday, along with the
department's other ranking black official, James Berry, the deputy
chief for the North End. That section is one of three police
divisions in the city and the one where Aquan lived.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
