u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS &LR;      05-18 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$70M PATRIOTS STADIUM FUNDING BILL STAGGERS TO PASSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The four-year political battle over funding for a New
England Patriots stadium reached its dramatic denouement Tuesday
when the Legislature passed a $70 million bill that Governor Paul
Cellucci said he would sign next week.
</P>
<P>
   But even on a day when it looked like the skids had been well
greased for final approval, the measure hit what could have been a
fatal snag.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-hour ordeal began when the House approved the bill,
but only after changing the legislation in a way that could have
jeopardized the crucial 2001 timeframe for completing a $225
million privately financed replacement for Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the bill was restored to its original intent, but
not before sending a scare through both branches.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham, stunned by the day's
events, said the stadium issue has been ``like riding a roller
coaster being strapped in backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, after the Senate approved the bill without debate 36-1,
the Chelsea Democrat added: ``All's well that ends well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots declined to comment, saying they still have not
read the legislation authorizing $70 million for road, sewer and,
other infrastructure improvements along Route 1. In return, the
team would pay the state $1 million a year, and satellite parking
lots must pay the state $400,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran smiled when it was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long, long, saga in Massachusetts,'' the Mattapan
Democrat said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, out of concern for a trailer park on land
where the new facility is planned, the House deleted language that
would have forced dozens of residents to relocate within 180 days,
instead giving them two years. Kraft owns the land and will need it
cleared to make way for the open-air stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives also refused language that would have rushed an
environmental review so the facility could be built by 2001.
Another amendment was thrown in requiring the team to study moving
its Smithfield, R.I., pre-season training camp to Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But Birmingham, mystified over the last-minute changes to a bill
that leaders of both branches had already agreed upon after intense
negotiation, called the revisions ``fatal'' and refused to adopt
them. The Senate passed the measure without the House changes, and
pressured Finneran to restore the bill to its original form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reached out to the speaker because I recognized these
amendments put the entire Patriots agreement in peril,'' Birmingham
said. The House gave in, and passed the bill 123-23.
</P>
<P>
   The original debate in the House spanned three hours, during
which there was plenty of rhetorical hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   One representative implied the Patriots had the cultural
significance of Paul Revere and Plymouth Rock. There were also
statements of support for practical reasons. Repesentative Barbara
Hyland, a Foxborough Republican, said the measure would actually
improve sewer and water problems in the town of 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the compelling monologue delivered by
Finneran on the floor of the House, which, over the years, has
voted on a handful of different stadium proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Finneran's hard-line stance against the state buying
land around Foxboro Stadium brought legislative action to a halt
and nearly pushed the Patriots into the arms of Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker -- whose sharp comments about Kraft in the past led
some to believe there was personal animosity between the two --
issued a lengthy screed about society's skewed priorities, about
principles and precedents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The members of this House have been maligned in an
extraordinary way, for doing what I think is appropriate,''
Finneran said emphatically. ``We have to manage in a prudent and
responsible way other people's money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, in the final analysis, it's a very positive
conclusion to a long, long, torturous debate that has affected the
deliberation of this chamber in many, many matters,'' Finneran
said.
</P>
<P>
   Members gave him a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   But Representative Christopher Hodgkins, a Lee Democrat,
punctured the serious tone in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding me?'' Hodgkins said, springing to his feet.
``We're talking like this issue is a big moral issue?...This is
nothing but the big boys in the back rooms making the deals with
professional sports.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
