<SLUG> BC-BABBITT-EVERGLADES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. UNVEILS PLAN TO AID 68 SPECIES IN EVERGLADES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt Tuesday
unveiled an ambitious plan to save more than 68 endangered and
threatened species in South Florida, taking a regional approach to
disappearing wildlife that the Clinton administration hopes will
become a national model.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a forum of scientists involved in the restoration of
Florida Everglades, Babbitt called the plan ``an unprecedented,
pioneering effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2,400-page document, which looks a bit like a wildlife
encyclopedia, lays out a blueprint for restoring natural habitat
across 26,000 square miles in southern Florida, and saving dozens
of threatened species, including the manatee, the American
crocodile and plants like Small's milkpea and the deltoid splurge.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said the government's hope was to depart from the
piecemeal approach of adopting harsh legal tactics to save each
species as it nears extinction, sometimes to the detriment of other
species and often at the cost of economic development.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have learned is you can't do these issues one species
at a time,'' Babbitt said. ``That's the significance of this plan
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, federal authorities would work with developers
and local governments to reach agreements on setting aside habitats
for endangered species before construction projects get under way,
rather than suing them to stop projects after they are started. In
most cases, the developers would then be released from the
obligation to protect endangered species on the land designated for
development.
</P>
<P>
   Federal wildlife officials said the idea was to shape
development in a way that sets aside and preserves habitats for all
species, rather than fighting politically divisive battles in court
over a single bird or fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we are doing it right this time,'' Babbitt said.
``We are putting it up on the front end. We're not going to sit
back and take the dog-in-the-manger stance, saying you go and do
your thing and then let us say, `No!'''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have tried similar tactics with considerable
success in the old-growth forests of the Pacific Northwest and
along the coastal sage lands of Southern California. But Babbitt
said the Florida plan was the largest initiative of its kind ever
tried, and the first to deal with a vast aquatic ecosystem like the
Everglades and Florida Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The health of the Everglades has been deteriorating for decades.
The flood control system the Army built in the 1950s drained
thousands of acres for farmland, splintered the marsh prairies with
dikes and canals, and severed the wetlands in the south from Lake
Okeechobee, thus stopping the slow, shallow flow of water that was
the lifeblood of the system.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement comes as Congress is preparing to debate
a $7.8 billion public works project this summer aimed at restoring
the Everglades to ecological health. That project, known as the
``Restudy,'' involves building dozens of large reservoirs, both
above and below ground, and revamping the canals and dikes to
restore the natural flow of water to the wetlands and into Florida
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservationists said the public works projects going to
Congress in July would be much more important to stopping the
decline of threatened species than Babbitt's plan. Unless the
erratic flow of water into the Everglades can be fixed, there is
little hope many of the endangered species will make it.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lee of the Florida Audubon Society, said, ``If we can't
put the water back in the Everglades, and we are not able to
re-establish the natural flow of water, then the steps recommended
in the recovery plan are not going to be sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   But other ecologists said Babbitt's approach marks a
breakthrough in environmental policy. In the past, they said,
conservationists had been forced to sue to protect a single species
under the Endangered Species Act in order to save the larger
ecosystem. Naturalists championed the survival of the spotted owl,
for instance, to protect the old growth forests of the Northwest,
and the fight over the lowly snail darter was in reality a battle
over the future of the Little Tennessee River.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear precisely how the wildlife recovery plan will
be implemented as the state and federal governments move ahead with
the larger effort to restore the Everglades. Several projects aimed
at restoring the habitat in the marshes have become bogged down for
years in local political battles and disagreements among federal
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
