<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL CERTAIN HE WON'T HAVE SECOND BAD GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Outside, a thunderstorm battered the Alamodome on
Monday night, while inside, the San Antonio Spurs somehow bottled
up a human tornado. But the Los Angeles Lakers felt no chill in the
aftermath, wrapping themselves in the warmest of security blankets
_ the knowledge that Shaquille O'Neal can't be bottled for long.
</P>
<P>
   As O'Neal himself noted last week, after making 9 of 22 shots in
a loss to Houston, he never has two bad games in a row. He bounced
back with a 37-point game.
</P>
<P>
   So as the Lakers stare at their first series deficit of the
postseason, 0-1 to the Spurs, they exude a confidence that borders
on cockiness. They know things will be different in Game 2 at the
Alamodome tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gonna be fine,'' coach Kurt Rambis said of O'Neal.
``We're going to show him the tape, show him what they're doing,
and we're going to put the players in different scenarios so (the
Spurs) are not going to be able just lock into him as easy....
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's going to play better. There's no doubt in my mind
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Either by scoring or by passing. That's the typical double-edged
sword of double- and triple-teaming O'Neal, who averaged 4.0
assists in the 3-1 series victory over Houston. But finding the
open shooter just got tougher, by about 14 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs alternately send combos of Tim Duncan, David Robinson
and Will Perdue _ 7 feet each _ at O'Neal, then mix it up with a
digging guard here and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have two 7-footers coming at you,'' said Glen Rice,
``the only way you can see people is if you're on the ground and
trying to roll the ball out.''
</P>
<P>
   Short of that strategy, the Lakers will try to get O'Neal to
make his move sooner, passing or going to the hoop before his sight
lines become 1-inch slits between black-and-white jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you beat one 7-footer you've still got to face another
7-footer. That's a tough proposition for anybody,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Noted Robert Horry: ``When they stretch out, that's 10 feet of
space they're taking up. He's just got to do something to get those
guys out of the way to give him more room.''
</P>
<P>
   It will help, too, if the Lakers' perimeter players fulfill
their responsibilities. Too often Monday, they reverted to standing
and watching after feeding the ball to O'Neal. And when they were
available for a kick-out, they were missing shots, hitting 38
percent of their field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that shouldn't be surprising. The Spurs were No.1 in the
NBA this year in field-goal percentage allowed (.402) and third in
points allowed (84.7).
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do a much better job at not being predictable with
what we're doing,'' Rambis said. ``We played so well whenever we
weren't predictable, even in (Monday's) game. But any time we
locked in and sent up a red flag _ `this is what were running' _
they knew exactly how they were gonna double-team and exactly what
they were gonna do. So we just have to do a much better job at
moving the basketball and not being predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've just become a real nice defensive team. The outside
players trust that their back is gonna be covered, so they get out
and pressure and harass, and they know that Robinson and Duncan are
gonna clog up the paint.''
</P>
<P>
   And contain O'Neal's spins to the hoop, his so-called ``Black
Tornado'' move.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was certainly hacked more often than whistles blew, and
his frustration showed when he committed his second, third and
fourth fouls in two minutes of the third quarter. His fourth was a
dropped hammer that sent Duncan to the floor and earned O'Neal a
flagrant foul.
</P>
<P>
   A day after verbally accosting referee Steve Javie, then
reportedly smashing a VCR in the locker room, O'Neal calmly vowed
to adjust his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to guard Shaq is to break the rules that the NBA
is supposed to enforce, but they're not enforcing them,'' he said.
``I'll just have to play a little bit smarter myself.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, O'Neal doesn't play two bad games in a row. Even the
Spurs know better than to assume otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect every game to go like we planned,'' Robinson said,
``but that's what makes him an All-Star, he can come back any night
and have a good game. It's just one game. There's no trend that's
started yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
