<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2397 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRADE-RAMSEY-COLUMN-S     05-18 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-RAMSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIP YOUR HAT TO IMPORTS - OUR EXPORT INDUSTRY NEEDS THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carla Hills, former U.S. trade representative, remarked last
week to the Asia Society and the Seattle Rotary Club that neither
the Democrats nor the Republicans had stood up in the 1996
elections for open trade.
</P>
<P>
   Even politicians and chief executives who thump for trade most
often argue from an export perspective. President Clinton, who
speaks for the pro-trade wing of the Democratic Party, has a
President's Export Council. Washington journalist Greg Rushford
asks in his trade policy newsletter, ``Can anyone imagine President
Clinton creating an Import Council?''
</P>
<P>
   Exports create jobs. How many times have we heard that? But do
imports destroy jobs? If exports are good, are imports bad?
</P>
<P>
   I asked Hills about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just infuriates me,'' she said. ``Remember, we fought a
war in 1991 for the privilege of importing oil. We import
technology, we import raw materials, we import know-how that make
us more competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment's thought should convince anyone that this is so.
Consider Seattle-based Starbucks Coffee. It is a huge contributor
to the prosperity of Seattle, with revenue filtering in from all
over North America, and now even from Japan and China. Most of the
value of a cup of coffee is in the roasting and the serving, but it
is based entirely on imported beans.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks' espresso machines are imported, too _ from Italy.
(The ones the stores use have final assembly in Ballard, a
neighborhood in Seattle.) Lots of companies in Seattlle depend on
imported equipment. We have microbreweries with vats from Germany
and bakeries with ovens from France. Paper mills use machines from
Sweden. Our biggest fishing boats use filleting machines from
Germany and fish-mincing equipment from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's labor. To pick our apples, which we export to
Asia and Mexico, we import the labor of Mexicans. In Seattle, our
software and biotechnology companies import cranial capacity from
India, Taiwan, Japan, Britain and dozens of other places, which
thereby suffer from ``brain drains.''
</P>
<P>
   Our export industry not only needs imported inputs, they need
imported competition. If Caterpillar doesn't face Komatsu here, it
will have less of a chance in markets abroad.
</P>
<P>
   We're still arguing from the export perspective. We import to
export. It is the argument used to sell NAFTA: that if we tear down
the walls with Canada and Mexico, we will export more, and create
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Worriers over the ``great sucking sound'' prophesied we would
import more, and destroy jobs. In fact, we have imported and
exported more, and in the process of becoming more specialized and
efficient, shifted jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Free trade has made Americans more efficient. But efficiency
does not reliably create jobs; it reliably creates wealth. (People
can have jobs at any level of efficiency. Look at India.)
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan understands that. The chairman of the Federal
Reserve Board spoke recently in Dallas, and said, ``We try to
promote free trade on the mistaken ground that it will create
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Trade, Greenspan said, creates and destroys jobs. It opens
opportunities for some and creates problems for others. It is part
of what he called the ``continuous churning of an economy in which
the new replaces the old.'' What it reliably creates is profits,
and, for labor with flexibility, skills and bargaining power, high
wages.
</P>
<P>
   The value of wages depends on what's available to buy, which
once again depends on imports. My son's baseball team cap is from
Bangladesh and his mitt is from the Philippines. His soccer ball is
from Pakistan and his bicycle is from China.
</P>
<P>
   Each of them could be made in the United States, and perhaps
with fewer labor hours. With our machines, we could probably make
most of the things we import with fewer labor hours. But there is
only so much labor to go around; it is virtually fully employed
already; and Americans have chosen, probably wisely, to produce
other things with it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to importing relatively freely, Americans also have
chosen to build a distribution and retailing system without peer.
That stretches our incomes. Consider a comparison from this week's
Asiaweek magazine in Hong Kong. The gross domestic product of Japan
is $33,800 per person, and of the United States, $29,950. Based on
official exchange rates, Japan is ahead of us. Adjusted for what
consumers can buy, Japan shrinks to $23,105, 23 percent behind the
$30,025 figure for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   So tip your hat to imports. They may get no respect from
politicians, who relate to us by what we sell rather than what we
buy. Someday, they'll notice that we need to do both.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
