<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENER WAS BENCHMARK FOR LAKERS' BAD BENCH PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A poor outing from Shaquille O'Neal, the Los
Angeles Lakers can occasionally survive. But couple that with a
nonexistent effort from the Lakers' role players, and they'll lose
the way they did Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   They need more than O'Neal's 21 points, but perhaps more
important, the Lakers need more than the two points, five rebounds
and two assists they got from their bench. That's little to show
for 62 minutes of combined play by Rick Fox, Robert Horry, Derek
Harper and Sean Rooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have a bench, you're not gonna win ballgames,''
Horry said, ``but sometimes the bench doesn't always need to score
points.''
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't even keep pace with their Spurs counterparts,
who totaled 17 points and 15 rebounds, led by Will Perdue's six and
nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has to step it up,'' coach Kurt Rambis said. ``We
want big performances, special performances, out of two or three
guys every night. A good example for them is Perdue. He came in and
did a real good job for them. We need somebody doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who went 0 for 5, said the Spurs' smothering defense denied
the Lakers quality shots, and the Lakers didn't respond well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think we weren't as fluid as we would have liked to
have been as a unit and we didn't do the things we've done in the
past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth impression: They won the game, but the Spurs were
impressed with the new-and-improved Lakers, who they routed by 27
points less than a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Greg Popovich called them ``a very good Laker team, a team
that's totally different from the one we played last time. They're
so much more disciplined, their spacing is so much better, and
they're so damn talented, it's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurs guard Avery Johnson agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much better. Much better. Much better,'' he said. ``They're so
much more unselfish, they're playing much better defense and right
now they seem like they're all about winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Healing: A day after scoring 21 points, Glen Rice said his sore
right elbow is fine, if not fully recovered. He practiced without
limitations Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elbow is feeling pretty good,'' he said. ``I wouldn't say
it's at 100 percent, but it's pretty close.''
</P>
<P>
   What's the point: For the first time in a long time, the Lakers
used Kobe Bryant at point guard late in Monday's game, trying to
take advantage of the smaller Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I was gonna try to get some post-ups. That was one
of the main intentions,'' Bryant said. ``Probably in Game 2, if
they have Avery Johnson out there, we'll probably do the same thing
again, take little Avery down to the box.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
