<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESS RECALLS LOUIMA IN AGONY AT POLICE STATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Brooklyn teen-ager who had been in a police station
holding cell testified Tuesday that he heard banging and screaming
in a restroom next door at the time prosecutors say Abner Louima
was being tortured there by officers.
</P>
<P>
   The witness, Connelle Lugg, 19, said a police officer then
pushed Louima, his pants down and blood flowing from cuts on his
face, into the cell and told him to get on his knees. There, Lugg
said, amid the stench of feces on his underwear, Louima lay down on
the floor, moaned in pain and asked to be taken to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Lugg gave his harrowing description in a soft, steady voice in a
hushed courtroom in federal district court in Brooklyn, at the
trial of four officers from the 70th Precinct. They are accused of
brutalizing Louima, 32, a Haitian immigrant who was arrested in a
melee outside a Flatbush nightclub in August 1997 and was
mistakenly believed to have punched one of the officers.
</P>
<P>
   When an ambulance crew eventually arrived and gave Louima a
chair to sit in, Lugg said, ``he was touching his head and stomach
and screaming,'' until the officer who had placed him in the cell
returned, pulled away the chair, told him with an obscenity to shut
up and took Louima's picture.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a prosecutor to identify the officer, Lugg looked
quickly toward the defense table and picked out the ``man in the
brown jacket'' _ Officer Justin A. Volpe, who is charged with
torturing Louima by ramming a stick into his rectum and then into
his mouth in the station house restroom.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that Louima suffered a torn rectum and bladder,
requiring two months of hospitalization and three operations, after
Volpe attacked him with the stick while another officer on trial,
Charles Schwarz, held him down.
</P>
<P>
   The two other officers, Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese, are
charged with joining Volpe and Schwarz in beating Louima in a
police car before he was taken to the station house. Prosecutors
say a fifth defendant, Sgt. Michael Bellomo, tried to cover up the
beating in the police car.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Lugg took the witness stand Tuesday, a detective who
had shown him pictures of police officers several days after the
reported attack on Louima testified that Lugg had said at one point
that ``he didn't recognize anybody'' in a group of photos including
Volpe's.
</P>
<P>
   But at another point, Det. Darren Bullock said, Lugg told him
that Volpe ``looked familiar'' as the officer who brought Louima
into the cell. The detective told Volpe's lawyer, Marvyn M.
Kornberg, that he did not consider that a positive identification.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg also sought to raise doubts about Lugg's credibility by
suggesting that he was testifying for the prosecution in return for
a reward in his own case. Lugg was being held at the station house
on charges of possession of a dangerous weapon and menacing.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyer noted that Lugg testified before a federal
grand jury looking into the case on Nov. 12, 1997, two days after
the state charges against him were dismissed. That grand jury
eventually indicted the officers, in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Kornberg also sought to gain information helpful to the
defense from Lugg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he ever tell anyone, in your presence, that someone stuck
a stick in his rectum?'' Kornberg asked the teen-ager, referring to
Louima.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Lugg replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he ever tell anyone, in your presence, that he was
sodomized?'' ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Officer Volpe have a stick when he brought Louima in the
cell?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in answering questions from one of the prosecutors,
Alan Vinegrad, an assistant U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, Lugg said
that at one point before an ambulance arrived for Louima, another
officer entered the cell, took off Louima's handcuffs and ``told
him to pull up his pants.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and defense lawyers have identified that man as
Bruder, whose lawyer has portrayed him as a ``Good Samaritan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
