<HEADER>
A2409 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAERSK-COMPETITION-LA     05-18 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAERSK-COMPETITION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A., LONG BEACH PORTS IN HIGH_STAKES CHESS GAME FOR MAERSK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Annual rent payments of $12 million or more are
only the tip of the iceberg in a competition between the ports of
Long Beach and Los Angeles to win one of the world's largest cargo
companies as a tenant.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles officials are attempting to lure Maersk Pacific Ltd.
to leave its Long Beach home and move to the new Pier 400 facility
being built at a cost of some $360 million and scheduled to open in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   If Maersk moves to Los Angeles, the city will be in line for
additional millions in revenue because of cargo coming through the
port and extra gains based on the company's future expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The two harbors' fight over the Danish shipping firm is part of
an ongoing effort to find customers for an expanded Los Angeles
port as international trade becomes one of the prime movers of the
local economy. Money is at stake as well as supremacy in the
nation's shipping world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maersk is one of several customers we're looking at and in the
negotiation phase with,'' said Barbara Yamamoto, spokeswoman for
the Los Angeles Harbor. ``We're looking at anyone who can move the
volumes of cargo through the port.''
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach spokesman Art Wong said, however, that the port was
trying to accommodate Maersk in its need for more acreage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their lease expires in 2003, and they have been looking for
more room,'' Wong said. ``We are trying to accommodate them and all
our other shipping lines who are looking for more space.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine Los Angeles would like very much to get them.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials could not provide immediate estimates of the total
value of Maersk to its host port, but at the least it pays $12
million a year in rent to Long Beach. That's the base amount Los
Angeles would expect, with increases depending on the amount of
land the company needs.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the income would be determined partly by how much cargo
Maersk brings in each year.
</P>
<P>
   In Long Beach, Wong said, once the cargo shipped in reaches a
certain point, the company pays the port a percentage. Exact
figures on the amount of cargo brought in are not available because
they are considered proprietary, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
   Maersk is one of the world's largest cargo operators, with
offices in more than 250 cities _ its U.S. headquarters is in New
Jersey _ and 100 ships.
</P>
<P>
   Maersk spokesman Tom Boyd said he could not comment on any
details of negotiations with Los Angeles or whether the company
would leave Long Beach. But, he said, various ports are always in
contact with the firm to get some of its business.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach, which is the nation's busiest port, has had some
problems in recent years in being able to expand. It had sought to
use a former Navy site in its efforts to win a contract with the
Chinese Ocean Shipping Co. but was turned down by the Defense
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles officials have been talking to COSCO ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Economic Development Corp.
of Los Angeles County, said Maersk officials have wanted to expand
in recent years to meet the demand from Asia but have been unable
to find the space in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are increasing their capacity in the Pacific, and they
keep building larger and larger terminals,'' Kyser said. ``With
Pier 400, Los Angeles has tremendous bargaining power.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand that this is a major game of chess
with millions of dollars involved. Long Beach and Los Angeles are
the two most attractive ports on the West Coast because they have
access to the rest of the United States and even Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   That attraction will increase with the completion of the Alameda
Corridor project, a $2 billion high-speed dedicated roadway from
the ports to Union Station.
</P>
<P>
   Kyser said the two ports have been alternating being tops in the
nation in terms of cargo _ a competition that has resulted in both
ports being profitable compared with others along the West Coast,
such as Oakland, Seattle and Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big growth the past couple of years has been international
trade, and that's going to continue,'' Kyser said. ``Hollywood is
down now, but the international trade is expected to continue to
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Wong said he doubted Maersk had many permanent employees _
perhaps under 100 _ but that hundreds of jobs are created with the
hiring of longshoremen every time a ship comes to port.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
