<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-STANLEY-PLOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLOT TWIST IN UNUSUAL MORGAN STANLEY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The case of Christian Curry was already strange
enough, with the lurid photographs and the forged e-mails and
allegations of racism and homophobia within one of Wall Street's
biggest firms.
</P>
<P>
   Curry, once an analyst for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, last
April accused the company of dismissing him because explicit
photographs of him were published in an adult magazine for gay men.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, Morgan Stanley officials told the authorities of a
plot by Curry to plant racist e-mail in their computers. Curry was
arrested and charged with forgery within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes this unexpected plot twist: The Manhattan district
attorney's office Tuesday dropped all criminal charges against
Curry, saying that Morgan Stanley had paid $10,000 to the
prosecution's star witness in the forgery plot.
</P>
<P>
   The witness had set up a meeting in August 1998 between Curry
and an undercover officer who was posing as a computer hacker,
officials said. Days later, Curry was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, within days of the defendant's arrest, officials at
Morgan Stanley wired a $10,000 payment into an account designated
by the confidential informant,'' Assistant District Attorney Leroy
Frazer said Tuesday in Criminal Court in Manhattan. ``Morgan
Stanley officials withheld from this office information regarding
the facts and circumstances of this payment.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than being viewed as the victims of a plot by Curry,
officials at Morgan Stanley _ along with the informer _ find
themselves the subject of an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we're concerned, the case against Christian Curry is
over,'' said Daniel Castleman, chief of the investigation division
in the district attorney's office. ``I cannot discuss the conduct
of either the confidential informant or the officials at Morgan
Stanley as that is a matter under investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley officials declined to respond to Tuesday's
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley hired Curry in July 1997, assigning him to its
real estate investment banking division.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a year later, Curry said, photographs that he had posed
for while he was a student at Columbia University were published
without his knowledge in Playguy, an adult magazine for gay men.
Word of the photographs quickly spread at Morgan Stanley, and Curry
was dismissed from his job days later.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley officials said he was dismissed for abusing
company expense accounts, but Curry suspected otherwise, and his
lawyers gave Morgan Stanley a deadline to respond to his
grievances.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought he was a homosexual, OK, and I also think they
had a problem with him being black,'' said Curry's civil lawyer,
Benedict Morelli, adding that his client is not gay.
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting Morgan Stanley's response, lawyers said, Curry began
discussing the e-mail plot with a college acquaintance who did not
work at Morgan Stanley, C. Joseph Luethke.
</P>
<P>
   Curry's criminal lawyer, Earl Rawlins, acknowledged that Curry
had offered $200 to the undercover officer to plant phony e-mail _
``You always look for an edge,'' he explained _ but he contended
that Curry was entrapped by Luethke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee whiz, you can do a lot of persuasion for $10,000,''
Rawlins said.
</P>
<P>
   According to prosecutors, Luethke reported his discussions with
Curry first to Morgan Stanley, then to police, who began to
investigate along with the district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Morgan Stanley officials nor Luethke told
investigators that they were discussing the matter with each other,
or of their ``ongoing negotiations'' about ``possible pecuniary
payments,'' Frazer, the assistant district attorney, said Tuesday.
This omission tarnished the credibility of the Morgan Stanley
officials and the informer, Luethke, as witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Luethke denied that Morgan Stanley had
paid him in connection with his efforts as an informer against
Curry.
</P>
<P>
   Curry, 24, now working as a model in Beverly Hills, Calif.,
declined to comment Tuesday, referring all questions to his
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Rawlins described his client as relieved that he no longer faces
the threat of prison: Curry, who had been arrested one day before
the deadline his lawyers had given Morgan Stanley to respond to his
grievances, had been charged with forgery, conspiracy, attempted
trespass of a computer and attempted coercion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district attorney's office saw through this darn thing and
that's kind of good,'' Rawlins said.
</P>
<P>
   Morelli, Curry's civil lawyer, also reacted with glee, saying he
planned to file a $1.35 billion lawsuit against Morgan Stanley in
New York state Supreme Court Wednesday, alleging libel, human
rights violations and conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things were done to him,'' Morelli said when asked
how Curry's firing justified $1.35 billion in compensation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
