<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-XEROX-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XEROX-MICROSOFT DEAL LINKS VARIETY OF TECHNOLOGIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Wash.)   (af)  
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Xerox and Microsoft Tuesday announced an
alliance aimed at bridging the worlds of paper documents and
computers.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the new relationship the Microsoft Corp. will license
a Web surfing technology developed at the Xerox Corp.'s Palo Alto
Research Center, and Xerox will incorporate Embedded NT, a version
of Microsoft's Windows NT operating system, in a future generation
of its high-end copying systems.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox officials said the Microsoft deal would have no impact on
a similiar agreement Xerox has with Sun Microsystems, whose
computers power a number of Xerox product lines.
</P>
<P>
   However, Xerox said Tuesday that it would switch to Intel Corp.
processors to power its high-end Document Centre corporate printing
technology, which has until now been based on the PowerPC
microprocessor jointly developed by the International Business
Machines Corp., Motorola and Apple Computer Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost-value trade-offs are in favor of Embedded NT,'' said
Rick Thoman, Xerox's president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies said they would also build linkages between
Document Centre and Microsoft's Exchange e-mail server that would
enable users to view scanned paper documents on their computers as
editable text.
</P>
<P>
   Although the reliability of Windows NT has been questioned in
so-called mission-critical industrial applications, the company has
succeeded in persuading hardware developers to use it in a wide
variety of devices, ranging from point-of-sale systems to computer
routers and airline avionics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Microsoft was embarrassed after the Navy's Yorktown
Aegis missile cruiser ended up dead in the water after a software
failure related to Windows NT. The company says it has since
improved the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Tuesday that the deal also offered evidence that
Xerox was improving the management of its technologies. The company
has long been criticized for being too slow in commercializing
technologies it develops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xerox is taking a much healthier view of its technology and
how it fits in the PC world,'' said Mark Anderson, an industry
consultant at Technology Alliance Partners.
</P>
<P>
   The new Xerox-Microsoft relationship focuses on a set of
technologies that have been priorities for both companies _
so-called knowledge management software and systems designed to
organize information and documents in ways that make data more
accessible and understandable within large organizations.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Tuesday's announcement Microsoft has licensed Web
Forager, a Xerox technology that allows a user to page through
information on the Internet much as a reader would leaf through the
pages of a book.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox and Microsoft have not in the past been strong allies.
Charles Simonyi, who while at Xerox PARC helped develop what is
known as a wysiwyg _ for ``what-you-see is-what-you-get'' _ text
editor called Bravo, left to become the lead developer for
Microsoft Word, leading to accusations that Microsoft had built its
word processing software around a Xerox invention.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, when Apple Computer sued Microsoft for copyright
infringement, contending that the Windows operating system stole
the look and feel of the Macintosh, Microsoft's chairman, Bill
Gates, asserted that in fact both companies had borrowed technology
developed at Xerox's PARC laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, Thoman said, ``nobody has any hard feelings about
something that happened 20 years ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
