<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MEDICAID-IMMIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE VOIDS N.Y. LAW CURBING MEDICAID BENEFITS FOR IMMIGRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state judge has struck down a law that has denied
Medicaid benefits to thousands of needy legal immigrants in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The state law, passed in 1997, barred most poor immigrants who
arrived after Aug. 4, 1996, from receiving Medicaid coverage for
nonemergency illnesses for five years.
</P>
<P>
   The law, however, granted exemptions for immigrants living in
nursing homes or suffering from AIDS as of September 1997, while
denying coverage to other sickly newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   Calling that distinction arbitrary, Justice Sheila Abdus-Salaam
of state Supreme Court in Manhattan said the rules violated the
equal protection statutes of the federal and state constitutions.
States cannot choose which poor people will receive aid, she said,
ruling that the law ``discriminates against many legal immigrants
and places vital public assistance benefits beyond their reach.''
</P>
<P>
   In her opinion, which was released Monday, Judge Abdus-Salaam
said the law also violated a state statute that requires New York
to provide aid and support to the needy.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the poor called the ruling a victory for
immigrants, citing the cases of people who were denied Medicaid
coverage while suffering from kidney failure, paralysis and other
ailments. The advocates said the decision makes thousands of legal
immigrants eligible for Medicaid for the first time since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   State officials, who had argued that providing health care to
all immigrants would lead to reductions in Medicaid benefits to
U.S. citizens, said they had not yet decided whether to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the process of reviewing the decision and beyond that
we really can't speculate,'' John Signor, a spokesman for the state
Health Department, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   New York enacted the statute in response to the federal welfare
law, which barred the use of federal funds for Medicaid benefits
for legal immigrants. State officials said it would cost New York
more than $33 million to cover the bills of the estimated 100,000
needy immigrants eligible for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``To meet this financial burden, the state would have had little
choice but to allocate monies from other social service programs,
reduce benefits to all Medicaid recipients, or otherwise increase
revenues through taxes, fees and assessments,'' lawyers for the
state argued in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Abdus-Salaam ruled that the U.S. Supreme Court had
already barred states from using limited finances as a rationale
for discriminating among equal classes of people.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates echoed that assessment. ``The state is not able to
pick and choose among its favorite immigrants,'' said Elisabeth
Benjamin, a lawyer for the Legal Aid Society, which filed the
lawsuit against the state last October. ``The state must treat all
immigrants and all state residents equally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0479 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2414 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-1STLD-WRI     05-18 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, UNDER GROWING PRESSURE, LEAVES OPTION OF GROUND TROOPS
OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert update on airstrikes in 6th graf, beginning: NATO
and the Pentagon ...)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under increasing public pressure to resolve the
conflict in Kosovo, President Clinton said Tuesday that he would
not rule out the use of ground troops but that he was hopeful that
diplomatic efforts under way with the Russians would be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I and everyone else has always said that we intend to see our
objectives achieved and that we have not and will not take any
option off the table,'' Clinton told reporters at the White House
when asked if he was reconsidering the use of ground troops to
expel Yugoslav forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   While administration officials insisted that the president's
comments did not signal a change of policy, Clinton has come under
increasing pressure, particularly from Britain, to consider ground
troops. The air war went into its 55th day Tuesday without having
achieved its goals. Britain is worried that troops need to be
deployed by June in order to prevent a catastrophe this winter for
the Kosovar refugees who have been forced from their homes and are
living in tent encampments.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Clinton had indicated only that he approved of the
Pentagon and NATO decision to update a military assessment of a
need for ground troops, as well as other military options like the
size of a peacekeeping force. His aides and military officials have
repeatedly insisted that ground troops were not a viable option,
while acknowledging that the Pentagon, as a matter of course, has
reviewed contingencies, including land combat.
</P>
<P>
   The British foreign minister, Robin Cook, appeared to soften his
stance on the need for ground troops Tuesday, after he failed to
sway his NATO allies in Brussels on Monday. He is still planning to
come to Washington on Thursday, though, to press the case.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and the Pentagon continued to press the air campaign
Tuesday night, although poor weather restricted airstrikes. NATO
said that its missiles hit an empty fuel-storage depot a mile
southwest of the center of Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, and that
warplanes pounded the area around Prizren in Kosovo. The Yugoslav
media said that NATO missiles hit at least four cities, killing a
woman and injuring 12 people.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended the strikes Tuesday, insisting that ``we ought
to stay with the strategy that we have and work it through to the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   The renewed discussion of ground troops, combined with a
measurable slip in American public support for the NATO air
campaign, is prompting the Clinton administration to scramble to
find a diplomatic solution to the conflict before the use of ground
troops becomes inevitable and raises the possibility of American
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the pressure for a diplomatic solution is a sense that
the unity of the NATO alliance is increasingly fractious. Several
countries, including Italy and Greece, have been fretting about the
lengthy bombing campaign and its strains on domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Tuesday: ``I am very hopeful, obviously, that the
diplomatic efforts that are being made in the State Department and
with the Russians will bear some fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks between Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott; the
special Russian envoy to the Balkans, Victor Chernomyrdin, and
President Martii Ahtisaari of Finland, were to continue on
Wednesday morning. The talks have centered on ways to approach
Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, about proposals that
would lead to an end to the bombing campaign and the withdrawal of
Yugoslav forces from Kosovo. Finland is not part of NATO but is a
member of the European Union and will lead the union starting this
summer, giving it extra clout in any peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and NATO have been discussing the possible composition of
an international security force that would return the refugees to
Kosovo, and have disagreed recently over when to stop the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   While the president has avoided committing ground troops, he has
pledged that the United States would send soldiers as part of a
peacekeeping force when the war is over. A Pentagon spokesman said
Tuesday that that peacekeeping force would probably involve 45,000
to 50,000 soldiers, instead of the 28,000 contemplated before the
air war in Yugoslavia began, and that America would provide between
10 percent and 15 percent of those troops _ or 4,500 to 7,500.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the talks Tuesday, Talbott told reporters, ``These
are very tough issues but serious people are working on them.'' He
declined to give details of the talks. Some reports suggested that
Chernomyrdin would go to Belgrade later this week.
</P>
<P>
   While the shuttle diplomacy has yielded little so far, NATO's
airing of differences over ground troops and the president's remark
could be seen as a signal to Milosevic that NATO would not relent
in its campaign.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that while he believed NATO's airstrikes had been
effective, ``I don't think that we or our allies should take any
options off the table and that has been my position from the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton has said from the March 24 start of the air war that
he had ``no intention'' of sending ground forces into a hostile
environment in the Balkans. As he explained in an interview on
March 31, ``The thing that bothers me about introducing ground
troops into a hostile situation _ into Kosovo and into the Balkans
_ is the prospect of never being able to get them out.''
</P>
<P>
   And three weeks ago he squelched an attempt by Britain to
reintroduce the topic at the NATO summit in Washington. Asked at a
news conference April 24 if a buildup of troops was preparation for
a ground invasion, the president said, ``No. The short answer is
no.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's disinclination to use ground troops has been
sufficiently clear that numerous military analysts, and retired
Gen. Colin Powell, have criticized the position as a strategic
blunder for signaling to the enemy just how far the allies would
go.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman, asserted Tuesday that
the president was not shifting his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it's prudent to always consider all of your options and
stay updated, which we are, given the assessments that are going
on, there's no change in our policy,'' he said. ``The president
believes we're going to get to where we need to get through the air
campaign and that we will get the conditions that we've laid out.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the air campaign was effective because it was
driving Milosevic toward negotiations. ``You've seen reports today
out of Belgrade that senior government officials are talking about
wanting a diplomatic solution, trying to find a way out,'' Lockhart
said. ``It's because the campaign is working.''
</P>
<P>
   But the administration is concerned, as Clinton said last week,
that ``refugee fatigue'' may be settling in among the public, and a
new poll from the Pew Research Center shows that while a majority
of Americans still support the war, that support has ebbed over the
last month. The Pew survey reflects similar findings in other polls
conducted recently.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of American participation in the conflict has fallen to
53 percent from 62 percent in mid-April, the poll found. Fewer
Americans _ 32 percent _ are paying very close attention to the war
now than were just three weeks ago, and among them, support has
dropped 21 percent so that a majority now oppose airstrikes
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is really wavering,'' said Andrew Kohut, director
of the center. ``That wavering is a combination of concern about
the unintended casualties and that the public doesn't think we're
winning.'' The public is almost evenly divided over whether to send
ground troops, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who has been a strong critic of the
administration's reluctance to use ground force, said that he
believed Clinton would seek some sort of settlement before sending
in ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're under great pressure,'' McCain, who is seeking the
Republican nomination for president, said in an interview Tuesday.
``I think they'll frantically seek a deal _ a dirty compromise _
and spin it and hope the Dow continues to go up. The whole thing is
very dispiriting.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberals too are adding their voice to the call for ground
troops. Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, said ground troops would be needed
to force Milosevic to yield to bend to NATO demands. ``I am not
convinced that air power alone will get his forces out of Kosovo,''
Harkin said Tuesday after a three-day trip to the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Mellman, a Democratic pollster, said that these polls
``are making a mountain out of a molehill of changes in public
opinion.'' He added, ``You have some high-profile things like the
Chinese embassy thing and it causes a blip. Nobody's enthusiastic
about war. But there is certainly not anything like majority
opposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
