A2416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      05-18 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SURVEY OF PASSENGERS FINDS THAT THE AIRLINES DO INDEED HAVE A
CUSTOMER-SATISFACTION PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Warranted or not, the image problem of airlines continues. The
latest critics are subscribers to Consumer Reports, who, according
to the June issue of the magazine, rate airlines ``only slightly
more favorably than they do cable TV companies and commercial diet
programs _ cellar dwellers in the magazine's customer satisfaction
rankings.''
</P>
<P>
   Among their complaints are the cutback in passenger amenities at
a time when profits are soaring for the major airlines. The sense
of dissatisfaction extends to meals, with Consumer Reports saying
that the average spending fell more than 26 percent between 1992
and 1998 _ to $4.16 a passenger from $5.67.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine used its survey results as well as performance data
from the Transportation Department to rate 18 airlines. Midwest
Express, the regional airline based in Milwaukee, scored highest in
satisfaction, but, the magazine said, ``its passengers paid for the
pampering with comparatively high fares.''
</P>
<P>
   Three low-fare airlines, Aloha, Midway and Southwest, were cited
for ``a superior combination of price and service.'' At the bottom
of the rankings, according to the magazine's subscribers, were
American, Delta and United, with many other major airlines not far
behind. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines is offering discounts of as much as 60 percent
for travel that begins on Friday or Saturday of the Memorial Day
weekend and returns that Sunday or Monday. Every state but Hawaii
is included, as is Canada. Other airlines are expected to follow
suit.
</P>
<P>
   From July 2 through Sept. 6, United will add 2,107 seats a week
to Hawaii from the mainland, by starting a daily San Francisco-Maui
round trip and by substituting a 747-400 for a smaller DC-10 on its
San Francisco-Kona route.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, United will fly three daily nonstops to Hawaii from
both Los Angeles and San Francisco. Starting next month, United
will offer discounted round-trip business fares to Hawaii. These
include San Francisco to Honolulu, starting June 10, for $799; San
Francisco-Kona, starting July 2, $899; and Los Angeles-Honolulu,
starting July 11, $799. Restrictions apply.
</P>
<P>
   American Eagle, the American Airlines regional carrier, will
begin service July 29 between La Guardia Airport in New York and
Cleveland, offering six daily round trips on 50-seat jets. Eagle
gained the coveted takeoff and landing slots with its purchase of
Business Express earlier this year. The planes have leather seats,
a wardrobe closet for hanging bags, and check-in at the gate for
larger carry-on items, which can be reclaimed on the jetbridge upon
landing.
</P>
<P>
   American Express said the typical business fare during the first
quarter of this year was almost four times the lowest discount
fare. By contrast, three years ago the disparity was only two and a
half times the discount fare.
</P>
<P>
   The Minneapolis-St. Paul airport opened a conference center for
business travelers this Monday, on the mezzanine level of the
Lindbergh Terminal. In addition to eight conference rooms,
including one that can accommodate 100 people, the center is
equipped with data ports and telephones, while printing, copying,
shipping, catering and other business services are available. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 hotels in the United States and Britain are making
newspapers from around the world available to guests by about 6:30
a.m. the same day _ an innovation made possible by transmitting the
contents of the papers to Xerox document technology centers in
major cities, where they are printed. The papers include The Times
of London, The Miami Herald, The Atlanta Constitution, The New York
Daily News, Liberation (France), Handelsblatt (Germany) as well as
papers from Austria, Brazil, Poland, Russia and Spain. Another
paper is Bloomberg News, the first time Bloomberg's financial news
service has been published in newspaper format.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels involved so far include the Regency, Regal United Nations
Plaza, Kitano and Millennium Broadway in New York, the Monaco in
Chicago, the Renaissance Mayflower in Washington and the Regent
Beverly Wilshire in Los Angeles. Press Point, a New York-based
company prints and distributes the papers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
