<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOTHEBY-AUCTION-NYT &LR;      05-18 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOTHEBY-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CLASSICS FROM '60s ARE BIG DRAW AT SOTHEBY'S SALE  
(jt) 
 By CAROL VOGEL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Strong examples of classic contemporary artists _
household names like Warhol, Calder and Bacon _ were snapped up in
short order at Sotheby's sale of contemporary art Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``People came to shop,'' said Christophe van de Weghe, a
Manhattan dealer who works at the Gagosian Gallery. ``Buyers knew
what they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Buyers also knew what they didn't want, often leaving lesser
examples of artists like Motherwell, de Kooning, and Georg Baselitz
unsold, sometimes without even one a bid, sometimes with a bottom
fisher curiously testing how little a work would sell for.
</P>
<P>
   The sale totaled $25.4 million, right in the middle of its $21
million to $29 million estimate. Of the 52 works offered, 12 failed
to find buyers.
</P>
<P>
   It was predominantly works from the 1960s that stirred the
crowded salesroom into spirited bidding. Sotheby's seating chart
read like a who's who of contemporary art collectors, many of whom
actually bid for themselves. But as has been true recently, the
most expensive works were sold to unidentified telephone bidders.
</P>
<P>
   The sale featured several important Warhols, two of which were
part of the group of contemporary works being sold Tuesday night
from the estate of the German collector Helmut Kraetz. An
unidentified telephone bidder and Eli Broad, the Los Angeles
collector, both tried to buy ``Marlon,'' a 1966 silkscreen of
Marlon Brando from a photographic still taken from the 1954 movie
``The Wild One.'' Estimated to sell for $1.5 million to $2 million,
it became the evening's second most expensive painting, selling to
the telephone bidder for $2.6 million. The same buyer won another
bitter bidding battle, paying $1.6 million for the artist's 1962
``Campbell's Soup Can (Chicken With Rice),'' an early version of
the famous image in which the artist used handmade stencils to
create the can and the lettering and a rubber stamp for the yellow
stars that line the bottom of the can. The price was twice its
$800,000 high estimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marlon'' was from the Kraetz collection. So was , `Suicide'' a
1964 monotype on paper from the artist's much-sought-after disaster
series. Eight bidders tried hard to buy ``Suicide,'' which finally
sold for a whopping $717,500 to an unidentified bidder sitting in
the far back of the salesroom. The price was nearly five times its
high $150,000 estimate.
</P>
<P>
   (Final prices include the auction house's commission, 15 percent
of the first $50,000 plus 10 percent of the rest. Estimates do not
reflect commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   The evening's most expensive painting, and one of the rarest,
was Lucian Freud's ``Painter's Mother'' (1982-1984) in which he
painted his mother clad in white and lying on her bed. It was a
historically important painting, but not necessarily a commercial
one. Before the sale art historians had compared it to the famous
painting of Whistler's mother because the Freud shows the sitter
gazing into a world of her own, and the artist, like Whistler, used
rectangular planes of light to create a shadowy interior. There
were few bidders after the painting, which sold for $3.3 million to
Richard Nagy of the Dover Street Gallery in London. Calder was well
represented Tuesday night but the results were mixed. By far one of
the most interesting examples of his work to come up at auction in
decades was ``Constellation,'' commissioned in 1943 by Philip
Johnson and his sister Theodate Severns for Hidden House, their
Manhattan house. ( Johnson eventually gave the Calder to his
sister.) Three serious bidders tried to take the sculpture home.
Made of painted wood and wire, it was estimated to fetch $600,000
to $800,000 but eventually made more than twice its high estimate,
selling to an unidentified collector for $1.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Two standing mobiles, however, sold for below their low
estimates. ``White Dots on Red and Blue,'' (1951) which was
estimated to bring $300,000 to $400,000, sold for $227,500 to an
unidentified telephone bidder. Another standing mobile, which the
artist made 21 years later, ``Trepied'' (1972) was estimated to
sell for $1.5 million to $2 million. Larry Gagosian, the Manhattan
dealer, bought it for $1.5 million. ``The Glory Folk (Maquette)''
which includes both a stabile and a mobile and was created as a
maquette for a stage design for John Butler's ballet ``The Glory
Folk, performed at Spoleto in 1962, failed to sell at all. No one
was willing to pay more than $320,000, too far under its $400,000
low estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth Kelly, one artist who has been getting a lot of
attention recently because important examples of his work have
recently been bought by both the Museum of Modern Art in New York
and the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art, was represented Tuesday
night. ``Red White,'' a 1966 painting of two red elliptical shapes,
was fought over by Broad, Anthony D'Offay, the London dealer, and
Douglas Cramer, the television producer, collector and trustee at
the Museum of Modern Art. Cramer finally bought the painting for
$662,500, just above its $600,000 high estimate.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few auction seasons, there have been many water
scenes by Gerhard Richter. Tuesday night Richter's ``Four Forest
Lake,'' (1969) a foggy photo-based painting, estimated to sell for
$1 million to $1.5 million, was bought by Simon de Pury, the former
chairman of Sotheby's Europe who is now a private dealer, for $1
million. e Pury didn't have to reach Tuesday night. But at
Sotheby's in London last summer he paid $2.3 million, three times
the high estimate for one of the artist's seascapes, painted a year
later. Basquiat is another artist whose works have been plentiful
at auction over the last year. ``Grillo'' (1984) four large panels
in an altarlike progression with a chaotic array of symbols, text
and images in the first and third panels and references to urban
life throughout, was estimated at $900,000 to $1.2 million, and an
unidentified telephone bidder was willing to pay $1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was sublime really went through the roof,'' said Tobias
Meyer, head of Sotheby's contemporary art worldwide. ``What didn't
sell was simply not good enough and collectors knew it.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
