<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-SEATTLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES MAGAIZINE RANKS SEATTLE NO. 1 IN GROWTH OF `NEW ECONOMIES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ARTHUR C. GORLICK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ You did it again, Seattle. A major magazine ranks you
No. 1 in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Forbes magazine says Seattle topped 162 metropolitan
areas in growth in jobs, income and output in the area's high
technology industries, including aerospace, computer software,
biotech, telecommunications, Internet companies and others.
</P>
<P>
   The city leads the nation in growth in this ``new economy,''
based on brainpower, as opposed to the ``old economy,'' based on
materials supplies, factories and transportation, Forbes reports.
</P>
<P>
   In its listing of the ``Top 50 places for business and
careers,'' Seattle ranked substantially ahead of No. 2 Austin,
Texas, using the complex formula employed by Forbes, a team of
economists from the Milken Institute of Santa Monica, Calif., and
Los Angeles-based economist David Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   Other metropolitan areas ranking high on Forbes' list include
No. 3 Dallas; No. 4 Ventura, Calif.; No. 5 Oakland, Calif.; No. 6
Middlesex-Somerset-Hunterdon, N.J.; No. 7 Denver; No. 8 San Jose,
Calif.; No. 9 Houston; and No. 10 Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The May 31 issue of Forbes contains the rankings but provides
little information about Seattle, its high tech industries or about
how Forbes and its economists reached their conclusions that
Seattle tops other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Forbes devotes most of the text of its report on ``Best
Places'' to San Diego, which ranked No. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news on Seattle is out there and we didn't feel
compelled to devote particular text resources to telling people
that Seattle is hot,'' said Tim Ferguson, Forbes' West Coast Bureau
supervisor of the report.
</P>
<P>
   Economists used by Forbes examined statistics compiled by the
Bureau of Labor Statistics, the Census Bureau's Bureau of Economic
Affairs and U.S. government output data through the 1990s, Ferguson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle's preeminence is a reflection of its momentum, its
breadth of technologies it has sustained during its growth and
prosperity during the 1990s,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine also examined average wage and salary increases and
average job growth in high-tech industries in the two most recent
years available ``to catch the most recent momentum,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perry Wong, a Milken Institute research associate who helped
crunch some of the numbers in the study, said the high-tech
industries now reflect the diversity and strength of any region's
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle ranked high in all of the growth areas,'' Wong said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth in employment in these high technology sectors, the
increase in wages and output reflect the industrial health of the
area. As one sector, such as aerospace, weakens the others are able
to sustain the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists most familiar with the Puget Sound region tended to
agree with the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we really deserve that good reputation,'' said
Washington state Chief Economist Chang Mook Sohn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been noticing and monitoring developments in scientific
technology and in many ways we are way ahead of many parts of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and other computer software companies in the region,
along with area-based wholesale and retail companies such as
Costco, Nordstrom and Starbucks, ``are all leading-edge companies
and clearly show us the power of being able to offset setbacks by
Boeing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dick Conway, an economic consultant focused on the Puget
Sound region, had some reservations about the Forbes/Milken
Institute study.
</P>
<P>
   By measuring growth only, the study fails to reflect the actual
size of high tech industries in metropolitan areas, Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it difficult to compare Seattle and Ventura, Calif.,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a relatively small base to begin with, it doesn't
take more than a few things to make things happen. Still, it is
useful to see where and what is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The rapid growth of Seattle-area computer software companies in
the early 1990s ``kept the region out of recession when Boeing was
having difficulties,'' Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   Other magazines have been ranking the Seattle area at the top or
near the top of numerous lists in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle topped Fortune magazine's ``Best Cities'' lists in 1992
and 1996 and was No. 4 on the magazine's list in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle-area companies such as Microsoft, REI, Eddie Bauer,
Nordstrom and Starbucks also ranked high on Fortune magazine's list
of ``Best places to work'' in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0484 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-HAWKS-NYT &LR;      05-18 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HAWKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS BEAT HAWKS, 100-92 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On Sunday, Allan Houston sprinted defiantly down the
Miami Arena floor and punched his fist into the air after his
dramatic shot eliminated the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   That look of confidence and edge of arrogance did not vanish
over a 48-hour period. It only bubbled up inside of him, and poured
out onto the Atlanta Hawks' Georgia Dome floor. Houston scored a
career-high 34 points on Tuesday night to lead the New York Knicks
to a 100-92 victory in Game 1 of their four-of-seven-game
second-round series and ripped the home-court advantage from the
Hawks' hands.
</P>
<P>
   Showing no signs of overindulging themselves since their victory
over the Heat on Sunday, the Knicks did not need to ride Patrick
Ewing. With Ewing in foul trouble, and resting his weary body on
the bench most of the night, the Knicks leaned on their offensive
twosome, Houston and Latrell Sprewell. They alternated surges.
Sprewell scored 17 of his 31 points in the first half, while
Houston came up with 15 of his points to stop the Hawks' momentum
in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Smith led the Hawks in scoring with 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   Just two days ago, the Knicks were on an emotional high after
Houston's game-winning shot eliminated their bitter rival, the
Miami Heat. There was celebrating and euphoria; and it was a threat
to the Knicks' mental approach entering their game against the
Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   They have no playoff history with the Hawks, no built-in
hostility to draw on, no bitterness lingering from the past. All of
that concerned Coach Jeff Van Gundy, who was less than satisfied
with the Knicks' preparation for this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our opportunity right now to do something,'' Van Gundy
said before the game. `'You don't waste a minute, you don't waste a
quarter and you certainly can't waste a game to get right because
of something you did 48 hours ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks did not seem like a team ready for a mental meltdown
at the start of the game. It was after they built an 11-point lead
with 7:40 left in the first half when the trouble began, and it
ended with the Hawks hitting three consecutive 3-pointers to go
ahead, 50-48, at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the Knicks were teetering on losing interest in the
game, Houston came forward and scored 15 third-quarter points to
pull the Knicks out of a temporary funk and an 8-point deficit and
help them take a 80-73 lead after the third period.
</P>
<P>
   This after the Hawks came out of the halftime break and turned
to Smith. He was just 2 for 8 in the first half, but he had a hair
more focus and determination as he reeled off 7 straight points and
helped put the Hawks ahead, 60-52, with 9:01 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have had trouble during the third period all season.
But this time, they showed resolve as they charged right back by
abusing the matchup of Smith on Kurt Thomas. Smith, who had picked
up four fouls early in the third, briefly moved off of Houston and
guarded Thomas. Two jumpers later, Thomas had scored 4 points on
the Knicks' 8-0 run to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after Smith missed a jumper, the Knicks ran down the floor
and Houston found Charlie Ward on the perimeter open for a
3-pointer that gave New York a 65-62 lead with 5:08 left in the
third. The Knicks' run extended to 12-4 after a jumper by Houston
fell with 2:30 left.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the game, the Knicks went up and they came down with
Sprewell. In the first half, he nailed contorted runners, baseline
jumpers and drove for layups without fear of Dikembe Mutombo.
Scoring 17 points in his first 12 minutes on the floor, he was
electric.
</P>
<P>
   His lethargic defense, though, gave the Hawks a chance to bolt
back into this game. His man, Chris Crawford, became the unlikely
source of offense for a Hawks team that watched Smith miss six of
his first seven shots and get into foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Once Sprewell began to miss, the Hawks capitalized. Sprewell was
late in getting back to defend as Crawford hit two of the Hawks'
three consecutive 3-pointers. Crawford, who scored 20 first-half
points, fed a 14-2 run that was ripped off in just 3:10.
</P>
<P>
   The run was punctuated with a 3-pointer from Crawford with 2:38
left in the first half, a shot that gave the Hawks a lightening
quick 48-46 lead.
</P>
<P>
   All the Knicks had done to shake off their Miami hangover was
erased by the unassuming Crawford. It didn't matter that the Knicks
were shredding the Hawks' stiff defense by hitting 50 percent of
their shots in the first half. It didn't matter that the Knicks had
done their damage with Ewing sitting out much of the first half
with foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks led at the half by 2 after making 6 for 12 from
3-point range.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0485 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
