to sustain the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists most familiar with the Puget Sound region tended to
agree with the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we really deserve that good reputation,'' said
Washington state Chief Economist Chang Mook Sohn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been noticing and monitoring developments in scientific
technology and in many ways we are way ahead of many parts of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and other computer software companies in the region,
along with area-based wholesale and retail companies such as
Costco, Nordstrom and Starbucks, ``are all leading-edge companies
and clearly show us the power of being able to offset setbacks by
Boeing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dick Conway, an economic consultant focused on the Puget
Sound region, had some reservations about the Forbes/Milken
Institute study.
</P>
<P>
   By measuring growth only, the study fails to reflect the actual
size of high tech industries in metropolitan areas, Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it difficult to compare Seattle and Ventura, Calif.,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a relatively small base to begin with, it doesn't
take more than a few things to make things happen. Still, it is
useful to see where and what is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The rapid growth of Seattle-area computer software companies in
the early 1990s ``kept the region out of recession when Boeing was
having difficulties,'' Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   Other magazines have been ranking the Seattle area at the top or
near the top of numerous lists in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle topped Fortune magazine's ``Best Cities'' lists in 1992
and 1996 and was No. 4 on the magazine's list in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle-area companies such as Microsoft, REI, Eddie Bauer,
Nordstrom and Starbucks also ranked high on Fortune magazine's list
of ``Best places to work'' in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990518.0486 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2545 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAYLE-AZR &LR;      05-18 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E TO TARGET `LEGAL ARISTOCRATS' AS FACTOR IN SOCIAL DECLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle will try to reignite the
political debate over morality Wednesday by taking a slap at
``legal aristocrats'' and ``child rights zealots'' he says are
partly to blame for a degeneration of American culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legal aristocracy has got to be held accountable,'' Quayle
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech before the Commonwealth Club in San Francisco
Wednesday, Quayle will lambaste specific groups of legal activists
for encouraging lawsuits against parents and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand we want parental accountability and on the
other hand we want children to sue their parents,'' he said. ``It's
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Educators, too, are intimidated by the legal climate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teachers are afraid of lawsuits if they have discipline,'' he
asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle will also accuse federal judges of blocking Americans
from fully practicing their religious faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (lawyers and judges) have undermined the core elements of
our society,'' he said, adding that he plans to ``shake that crowd
up a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   In the address, Quayle will return to familiar political
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1992 speech entitled ``The Poverty of Values,'' Quayle
excoriated the TV sitcom character Murphy Brown for being part of
an entertainment climate that accepted, even glamorized, single
motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's speech, on the seven-year anniversary of that talk,
will be delivered in the same location.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 talk sparked a furious debate among conservatives,
academics and entertainers about the legitimacy of blaming
television for societal ills, and later, about the propriety of
single parenthood itself.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Quayle will blast federal judges and such groups as
the American Civil Liberties Union for, in his view, preventing
Americans from practicing their faith in public places such as
schools and courtrooms by coming down too hard on the separation of
church and state.
</P>
<P>
   And he will cite the aftermath of the shootings at Columbine
High School in Littleton, Colo., where, according to Quayle,
families and teachers pulled together through prayer but are
ironically foreclosed from praying in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an indictment of the legal system as opposed to the
entertainment community this time around,'' said Quayle's media
adviser Fred Davis, who helped craft the speech.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle and his wife, Marilyn, are lawyers, which gives them room
to speak, said Quayle's press secretary, Jonathan Baron.
</P>
<P>
   While Quayle is not likely to dwell on the Murphy Brown episode,
his staff has billed the address as the sequel to a blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sparked the political debate which has dominated the
decade,'' Baron said, referring to the Murphy Brown speech. ``Dan
Quayle won the debate over the debate and the next step is winning
the actual battle over the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said he's not worried about appearing too harsh by
targeting specific organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ordinary suspects may not like it, but tough,'' Quayle
said. ``But the average American will. And teachers will.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not say he is trying to convey he is more conservative
than his fellow GOP candidates, but did remark, ``I'm not sure how
many other people could or would make this speech that I'm going to
make.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Quayle reaches too far right, he risks being cut off from
centrist voters, one political observer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still trying to corral the religious right and trying to
expand it,'' said Richard Pious, professor of political science at
Columbia University. ``But the more religious it is the more he's
got to worry that he's going to alienate the base.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle may also be looking for a boost out of a political
morass.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign raised more than $2 million in the first quarter of
the primary election cycle, but ended the quarter in debt.
</P>
<P>
   And only 6 percent of Republicans supported him for their
party's nomination in a CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll released early
this month.
</P>
<P>
   That gave him a tie with billionaire Steve Forbes, but left him
far behind former Red Cross President Elizabeth Dole and the
front-runner, Texas. Gov. George W. Bush, who logged 42 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
