A2552 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-INSURANCE-AZR &LR;      05-18 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-INSURANCE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA IS WORST IN HEALTH COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESCOTT, Ariz. _ The portion of Arizonans who don't have
medical insurance has grown to 28 percent, ranking Arizona worst in
the nation for uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   And some participants at 74th Arizona Town Hall on future health
care in Arizona say they hope the statistic will spark political
attention to the problem. The 150 participants are in Prescott for
the four-day event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was bad when 15 to 17 percent of Arizonans were
uninsured,'' said Dr. Scott Gorman of Phoenix, interim executive
director of Mayo Health Plan Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only hope it is now finally on the radar screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Participants learned that uninsured Arizonans don't have access
to preventive medicine. They wait until their condition is acute,
then go to a hospital emergency room for treatment. In most Arizona
towns and cities, the emergency rooms are seriously overcrowded.
And an increasing flow of illegal immigration is also adding to the
ranks of the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing a real influx of undocumented people into the
state now,'' said Lee Knaeble, a Hereford business owner who is on
the Sierra Vista Community Hospital Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could mean more people showing up at emergency rooms
because that is the only way they can access health care.''
</P>
<P>
   But the real problem isn't immigration, said many at the Town
Hall. It's unaffordable health care.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Groseta of Cottonwood, a third-generation cattle rancher
and chairman of the board of Northern Arizona Health Care, said
most of the workers in managerial positions at large ranches and
farms had insurance 10 to 15 years ago. Now, fewer than 50 percent
do. Even fewer ranch and farm hands have it, and their work is more
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe resident Ron Lee, executive director of the Arizona
Commission on Indian Affairs, agreed that workplace health
insurance is where the system is failing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona has one of the lowest unemployment rates in the
U.S.,'' he said. ``How can we have one of the highest rates of
uninsured?''
</P>
<P>
   The growth of low-paying service-sector jobs is seen as the
basic factor driving the health insurance crisis. Also, the rise of
contract work is pushing many people who work full time out of
insurance plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes all the way up to the banking industry,'' Groseta
said. ``We have to do something soon: More people are falling off
the insurance wagon every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Groseta believes legislation providing tax and other incentives
for employers to provide insurance plans to more workers is needed.
</P>
<P>
   So are insurance pools where the uninsured or underinsured could
buy affordable insurance as part of a group, participants said.
</P>
<P>
   Some agreed more money needs to be directed toward preventive
care. A system of community clinics, providing preventive care on a
walk-in basis, is seen by some as a needed step in repairing
Arizona's public health conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Among other recommendations being discussed is a call to the
Legislature to allow more people to participate in the Arizona
Health Care Cost Containment System, or AHCCCS. Raising the
eligibility level for AHCCCS to 200 percent of the poverty rate
would allow more working poor to be covered by health insurance,
some believe.
</P>
<P>
   Because Arizona's elderly population is expected to double
during the next 30 years, a system of preventive care would help
keep older people healthier, so that their final years will not be
characterized by expensive chronic diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Weisbuch, director of the Maricopa County Public Health
Department, said that old age is not necessarily a time of
expensive health care, if preventive medicine has been available
consistently through a person's life. Yet only 2 percent of money
spent nationally on health care every year is spent on prevention,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other participants argued for the better use of affordable
alternative therapies that have proved effective but are not paid
for by insurance.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third Town Hall in the past 16 years to look at
health care in Arizona, said Shirley Agnos, Arizona Town Hall
president. While the subject of health care in Arizona keeps
popping up, the nature of the discussion has changed, she added.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, before many Arizonans were enrolled in HMOs,
employers and their insurers were at the mercy of medical
providers, who were continually raising prices. The rise of health
maintenance organizations shifted the debate: It became employee
and employer against the HMO, and the HMO against the hospital and
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   At a 1993 Town Hall on health care, Arizonans were expecting the
Clinton administration to produce some form of national health
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Hurst was at the Arizona Town Hall on health in the
1980s. At that time, only a few people understood the complicated
health issues, he said. This is a more educated crowd, in part
because of the Clinton health care debate. He believes there is
less finger-pointing than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The Town Hall wraps up Wednesday with the approval of public
policy recommendations that will be sent to legislators, the
governor and the media. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-18-99 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
