<SLUG> BC-BBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BEACH ST. ACE GALLO IS MOUND OF ANGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'd like to introduce you to two fellows on Dave Snow's Long
Beach State baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's Mike Gallo. He's a senior left-handed starting
pitcher, the ace of Snow's staff and the Big West's pitcher of the
year. Mike is 10-2, has a 2.13 earned run average, and has held
opposing batters to a .247 average, which is several leagues below
sea level in the college baseball world. He'll start one of the
three games the Dirtbags play this week at Blair Field against No.
1-ranked Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Pepe. He's the guy in the Dirtbag dugout moving at
the speed of Taz, talking up his teammates, razing opponents,
chatting with fans. When time calls for rally caps or deuces, Pepe
is at the forefront of the assembly. He's a collegiate baseball bon
vivant.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Snow likes both guys immensely. The only thing that worries
him is the possibility of asking Mike Gallo to pitch and Pepe
somehow getting the ball.
</P>
<P>
   By now you've realized that Mike Gallo and Pepe are one and the
same, a bonus baby with two separate but integral spirits rolled
into one.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo the pitcher is the epitome of what anyone would want on a
team. He's tough, competitive and courageous. ``When Mike is on the
mound, the team knows it has a shot to win,'' said his catcher,
Bryan Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Pepe the team captain is a wild and crazy guy, the epitome of
Dirtbag spirit and confidence, characteristics that turns
individuals into a team. ``It's tougher than pitching,'' Pepe said.
``I get so into the games. I can't sit still. I was already amped
to pitched Sunday by Saturday night.''
</P>
<P>
   It will surprise you not in the least then to know that the 49er
coaches are told to make sure Gallo stays away from candies and
sweets 24 hours before he pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``My outlook on life is to live it to the fullest,'' said Pepe.
``I can't be mean to people. I treat everyone as my a best friend
until I figure out what they're like. I don't want enemies. I want
everyone to like me as a person and as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gosh, baseball, it's just a game. Guys get paid to play this
game? Amazing. I'd play for a penny.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you give him that penny and hand him the ball, he becomes
Mike Gallo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm on the mound, I'm a different person, an angry
person,'' said Gallo. ``Whoever steps into the batters box is my
enemy. It could be my dad, and I'd want to make him look stupid.
Before games, I can be a real jerk, and you do not want to face me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after games? Those guys are my best friends. That's one
thing I like about college baseball. You get to know the guys you
play against.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Sunday's 15-3 win against Fullerton for example. When the
two teams met for postgame handshakes, Gallo was conspicuous in the
way he shook each hand firmly. He even hugged some of the Titans.
One of the huggee's was Ryan Owens, who bombed Gallo twice for solo
home runs. ``I told him he owed me dinner,'' said Gallo.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers owe Gallo a lot. Their trip to Omaha for the College
World Series last season came at the same time that Gallo matured
as a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo threw a complete game shutout of Fullerton in the Big West
tournament, then beat Stanford 5-1 in the Western regional to get
to Omaha. He made two CWS starts against Miami, holding the
hard-hitting 'Canes to three runs each time. His 10 wins this
season include two versus Fullerton and one against defending NCAA
champ USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a high-energy guy, very competitive,'' said Snow of
Gallo. ``The big task was getting him turned into a bonafide
pitcher, channeling that energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``His emotions used to work against him. The ball would take
off, he wouldn't have any command. Late last year, he started
making it a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach has done a great job keeping me at mid-level, not too
pumped up,'' said Gallo. ``He knows how to deal with whatever
personality a guy has. And the skills he teaches you are life
skills, whether you're playing baseball or working a desk job.
Outside of my parents, he's been the most influential person in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow gave Gallo his nickname. It came in 1997, Gallo's first
season as a 49er, after Snow got a look at Gallo's hyperactive
ways. The name has two roots depending on who tells the story: He
was named Pepe because he was always peppy, or because one of the
Gallo winemakers allegedly was named Pepe.
</P>
<P>
   A running joke during 1997 practice sessions would have Snow
asking Gallo, who was always running around the field doing
something, for the location of a blue ball bag. ``Pepe, got that
blue ball bag?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves Pepe when he's not pitching,'' said Gallo with a
laugh. ``He likes messing with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallo played for Dan Peters' perennially successful program at
Long Beach Millikan High School, but he mostly played right field.
He pitched only 26 innings as a senior on a staff that included
Nick Bierbrodt and Eric Ireland. Bierbrodt was a first-round draft
pick by Arizona and is now pitching AA, and Ireland is expected to
jump to to Houston's AA team this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo, whose mom is a concessions supervisor at Los Alamitos
Race Track and whose dad works in advertising (he once worked at
the Press Telegram), chose to attend Long Beach City College after
high school so he could continue to play baseball and start work on
a communications degree, with an eventual goal of becoming a
sportscaster.
</P>
<P>
   It was there that Viking coach Casey Crook suggested Gallo
become a full-time pitcher. ``He took the bat out of my hand. He
said I had a strong arm and that it happened to be my left arm, and
that those two things could get me into the pros a lot quicker than
a stick,'' said Gallo.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo was named the Vikings' player of the year. ``I learned my
good mechanics (at LBCC),'' Gallo said. ``But all I had was a
fastball, curve and a weak change. The curve was pretty weak, too.
What got me through was good movement and hitting spots. But I was
basically a thrower. I didn't grasp the concept of pitching until I
got to Long Beach State.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow used Gallo exclusively as a spot reliever his first season,
working him 21 fr 1/3 innings in 22 appearances, mostly against
left-handed hitters. ``I accepted that role, but I never got
comfortable with it,'' Gallo said.
</P>
<P>
   He relieved for half of 1998 before moving into the rotation. By
then, he had developed a slider -- ``It's been so money for me'' --
and improved his changeup.
</P>
<P>
   After the College World Series, Gallo spent the offseason
working to get in better shape and gaining more command of his
pitches. He knew he would need one more season of college work
before he would have any pro draft potential, and at 10-2, he's had
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is all this a shock? Not really,'' Gallo said. ``It was always
my dream to be the best in whatever I do. I set a goal for myself
before the season to be the best pitcher in the nation. I've never
taken anything for granted, and I approach every game as if it will
be my last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that's a roof,'' said Gallo. Or maybe it was Pepe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
