<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: VAN GUNDY HAS EARNED A NEW TERM 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like jets stacked up in a holding pattern, everybody
is waiting, waiting, waiting, to see what happens with the Knicks.
Nobody can go anywhere until they stop performing their erratic
loop-the-loops.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of this backup is Jeff Van Gundy, the current coach of
the Knicks and, if there is any justice in this world, the future
coach, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are not going anywhere for a while. They began their
four-of-seven-game series on Tuuesday night in the looming Georgia
Dome, and outran the weary outmanned Hawks,100-92, in what could be
a rewarding war of attrition. The Knicks' season now goes at least
until Wednesday, and quite likely well beyond. In the meantime,
everybody's doing circles over some generic Allentown.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches, general managers, agents, players, real-estate agents,
moving companies, everybody is dependent on how it all turns out
with these accidental tourists of the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   Where is Phil Jackson going? Who coaches the Lakers? Will Don
Casey, another respected lifer, get the shot he earned with the
Nets? Would Patrick Ewing really go home to play for Washington
rather than play for Jackson? It sounds like fun, messing up
everybody's plans.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy looked like a goner a month ago with the Knicks
playing without a flight plan. But they won six of their last eight
games to qualify for the playoffs, and then defeated Miami by the
capricious roll of a soft sweet shot by Allan Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes life is like that. The Knicks have eliminated Pat
Riley, the designated archenemy at the top of the chain of command,
and that is worth something. But Van Gundy's track record is longer
and more substantial than one lucky roll.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since he came in as an assistant under Stu Jackson a full
10 years ago, Van Gundy has been an astute observer. The hard work
_ tossing a million passes to John Starks in practice _ is a given.
Van Gundy also learned stuff from John MacLeod, Riley and Don
Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   It was Nelson, during his short and weird regime, who was asked
by Charlie Rose where the next generation of great coaches were.
Nelson told an incredulous Rose that he had one on his staff.
Nelson did not last a season, and Van Gundy got the job, and he has
taken the Knicks into the second round all four years.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching the second round should get Van Gundy a contract
extension. Yes, the Knicks were dreadful to watch most of this
short season, but then again, so was the whole league. It's not
much fun watching millionaires exercise, is it? Or, as the fan
shouted as he emerged from the Garden last Friday, ``I paid 90
bucks for this?''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the Knicks regrouped in Miami on Sunday. This was the
team Ernie Grunfeld built _ with Marcus Camby providing a jolt of
energy, and Latrell Sprewell leading the Knicks in scoring in the
first round, and flicking the ball away from Tim Hardaway for the
winning possession.
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld is back in New Jersey, the victim of a late-season
purge by Dave Checketts. Grunfeld and Van Gundy were not on the
same page, so the general manager was dropped. It's not a credit to
anybody that they could not work it out.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has his flaws, particularly a creaky halfcourt offense
as well as underestimating Buck Williams last year, leading to
Buck's retirement. He is the latest in a long line of coaches
unable to spark any imagination in Ewing's game, but, far more
important, Van Gundy has Ewing's total loyalty and respect, which
led to Ewing's courageous stand last Sunday in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever it is who owns Madison Square Garden must be sure to
really know Jeff Van Gundy before making a gesture toward a big
name to be blared all over the air waves. (I think the current
bunch has something to do with television.)
</P>
<P>
   The new owners must recognize that Van Gundy is not only one of
the most intelligent coaches (he was accepted to Yale, a magna cum
laude graduate of Nazareth College) but also a man of character.
</P>
<P>
   Before this past Friday's game in the Garden, Van Gundy found
time to thank a patron who has been paying for the same expensive
seat as long as Van Gundy has been working there.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by fellow patrons what the conversation had been about,
the fan blurted, ``I think Jeff just said goodbye.'' But then the
Knicks stunned the Rileys and reached the second round. Van Gundy
should have earned an extension. Everybody else spins in circles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
