<HEADLINE>
U.S., CANADA WARN OF DELAYS, HAVOC THAT BORDER LAW WOULD CREATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY AND MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congestion at the Canadian border regularly results in hours of
delays, and it will get even worse with severe impacts on trade and
tourism unless Congress gets rid of a controversial immigration
requirement, U.S. and Canadian officials warned yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Delays at the crossing at Blaine could reach 12 hours or more if
Section 110 of the 1996 Immigration Act is ever enforced, experts
told the Cascadia Mayors Conference recently.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's warnings came in a letter to Congress from Seattle
Mayor Paul Schell and other U.S. and Canadian mayors, and in a
Washington, D.C., news conference held by Canada's ambassador to
the United States and other senior officials.
</P>
<P>
   Section 110 would, in essence, require that U.S.-bound Canadians
get out of their cars and offer proof of identity, as well as stop
and formally check out of the United States when they head north
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability to travel within the region is a critical
prerequisite for greater cooperation and coordination,'' said the
letter, signed by Schell, Victoria, B.C., Mayor Bob Cross and
Bellingham Mayor Mark Asmundson on behalf of 21 mayors in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Cascadia cities would be negatively impacted by this
requirement,'' they wrote to senior members of the Senate and House
judiciary committees.
</P>
<P>
   The computerized alien identification program was scheduled to
go into effect last October. But Congress voted to delay
implementation of Section 110 until March 30, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a deadline that has been extended until 2001 but we
have to make sure that the issue remains alive and hopefully
resolved in 1999. It seems to be generally recognized that if we
wait too long, it might be even more difficult in 2000,'' Raymond
Chretien, Canada's ambassador to the United States, said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., has introduced a bill to repeal
Section 110. The measure has 25 co-sponsors, including Sens. Patty
Murray, D-Wash., and Slade Gorton, R-Wash. No action has been taken
this year although the Senate voted twice last year for repeal.
</P>
<P>
   Repeal has been blocked in Congress' lower chamber by the House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Section 110 has an influential defender in Rep. Lamar Smith,
R-Texas, chairman of the House Judiciary Committee's immigration
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent hearing, Smith argued that identification is needed
to counter the upsurge in organized smuggling of illegal immigrants
across the 4,000-mile border with Canada, and the surge in
marijuana traffic from British Columbia into the United State.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Washington, D.C., news conference yesterday, Abraham
argued that the border checks would not work. Along with five
checkpoints in northwest Washington, the bridges and tunnel linking
Detroit with Windsor, Ontario, are the most heavily traveled
crossings along the U.S.-Canada border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be very expensive, it will cause huge economic
problems and lost jobs,'' Abraham said. ``I don't think that any of
the alleged benefits of it will be realized, because there is no
way that anybody who has come forward has demonstrated that this
system can work ... to address any of the purported problems it is
supposed to address.''
</P>
<P>
   Implementation of Section 110 ``would effectively close the
borders,'' Jim Kohnke, an executive with Totem Ocean Trailer
Express, told Northwest mayors at a meeting in Victoria, B.C.,
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Canada do more than $1 billion worth of
business across the border each day. Even with the Canadian
dollar's drop in value, Whatcom County takes in $500 million each
year from north-of-the-border visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Border crossing delays has been a major issue in the region.
Last year, the Bellingham Herald criticized Rep. Jack Metcalf,
R-Wash., for his lethargy in dealing with the threat posed by
Section 110.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 million people go through U.S.-Canada border
checkpoints each year, Canada's revenue minister Herb Dhaliwal
noted yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, with the limited resources we have, it would be
impossible to create new infrastructures and new facilities to deal
with such an onerous task as having everyone report,'' said
Dhaliwal, a member of Canada's parliament from Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Section 110, the mayors wrote yesterday, ``We often
face serious delays in crossing the U.S.-Canadian border under
current U.S. procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayors appealed for additional inspectors from the
Immigration and Naturalization Service and the Customs Service to
address ``the backlogs and delays that already exist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
