<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2563 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-HNS &LR;      05-18 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEDILLO'S FAVORITE WILL TRY TO SUCCEED HIM IN MEXICO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL RILEY 
and DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A day after Mexico's long-ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party adopted sweeping reforms in the way it selects
its presidential candidate, the man widely believed to be President
Ernesto Zedillo's choice as successor formally jumped into the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am taking the most important decision of my life,'' Interior
Minister Francisco Labastida Ochoa said in a packed hotel ballroom
Tuesday. ``I've decided to present my candidacy for president of
the republic.''
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the most dramatic effort yet to transform itself from
what once was called ``the perfect dictatorship,'' the PRI's
leadership on Monday approved plans to choose its nominee for next
year's presidential race in an open primary Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules adopted by party leaders, any registered voter
can take part in the secret, nationwide balloting. The candidate
who wins in the largest number of 300 electoral districts will be
the party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the past seven decades, the PRI presidential
candidate has been tapped by the sitting president and has gone on
to win in national elections. The party has controlled the
presidency since 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida is one of four serious contenders for the PRI
candidacy. The others are Tabasco Gov. Roberto Madrazo; Manuel
Bartlett, a hard-line former Interior minister and state governor;
and Veracruz Gov. Miguel Aleman.
</P>
<P>
   Although Labastida is considered the favorite of Zedillo, he
faces strong challenges from the other three candidates. Madrazo
and Bartlett, both tied to ruling-party hard-liners, have been
blitzing the airwaves with political ads for weeks, and Madrazo has
surged in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   According to the rules governing the primary, the PRI's
presidential hopefuls must resign or take a leave of absence from
government positions by June 15. Labastida said Tuesday that he has
tendered his resignation as Interior minister without indicating
when it will take effect.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate who wins the PRI's nomination will likely face
Guanajuato Gov. Vicente Fox of the center-right National Action
Party and left-leaning Mexico City Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas in the
July 2000 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   A poll released Tuesday by Indemerc Louis Harris polling firm
puts Fox ahead of Cardenas and all the announced PRI contenders
except Madrazo, against whom he's running 5 percentage points
behind.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's new presidential primary ends a long tradition in
which a sitting president, who also served as the ruling party's de
facto leader, hand-picked his own successor. While that process,
known as the dedazo, or ``big finger,'' lacked democratic niceties,
it kept the succession process under control and the party's
internal rivalries under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   But the PRI's grip on power has eroded in the past 12 years.
Many members have deserted to opposition parties, which now control
about a third of Mexico's 31 states as well as Mexico City. The
ruling party lost control of the Congress in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   PRI officials point to the new primary as proof that the PRI is
responding to changes washing across Mexican politics and society.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unity of the party is important, not just for the PRI but
for Mexico,'' said Fernando Solana, a former Education minister and
senator who now holds a top party post. ``Naturally, not everyone
in the party is in agreement with an opening of this nature.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary opens the possibility of an all-out fight among
competing factions, which often have had little in common except
the party name. But analysts say the primary also represents the
PRI's best hope for holding onto power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just having the primary. It convinces people that the
party is really changing,'' said Gabriel Gonzalez, director of
Americas-Mexico, a political consulting firm that works closely
with the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   With suspicions running high that any revision of the nomination
process would be more show than real, analysts said the PRI had
little alternative but to profoundly change it.
</P>
<P>
   Its clear that party mandarins went out of their way to ensure
that there would be little room for primary losers to complain
about the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The requirements for entering the primary _ including the
endorsement of a number of party bosses and rank-and-file members _
are loose enough to include any serious contender. The process will
be overseen by Fernando Gutierrez Barrios, a tough former Interior
minister and state governor widely respected in PRI ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to allay concerns that official favoritism or drug money
could influence the race, PRI leaders said they would set a limit
on primary campaign spending and have a review board track
contributions and their origins.
</P>
<P>
   For a party once known for a willingness to steal elections when
necessary, the PRI's sudden option for openness may have more to do
with self-interest than with a new commitment to the democratic
ideal.
</P>
<P>
   Electoral reforms over the last 10 years have all but guaranteed
the end of the PRI's political monopoly, making it virtually
impossible to swing elections through the party machine and
traditional vote-fixing.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of Zedillo's term in 1994, the party has
been experimenting with ways to select candidates for state
elections. PRI leaders found that the primaries used in several
gubernatorial elections were successful.
</P>
<P>
   Still, rules for the new primary also bear the signs of
presidential influence, which could tilt the outcome to insiders
like Labastida, some analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The official primary campaign will start in August, and
televised ads will be forbidden until then. That will help
Labastida recover from weak public recognition while hurting
``outsiders'' such as Madrazo, who already have run a flurry of TV
ads.
</P>
<P>
   And because the winner will be determined by electoral district
and not by total vote, the rules may help negate regional strengths
held by such hopefuls as Madrazo or Bartlett. An open vote also
raises the specter that opposition parties could organize members
to vote for the candidate they would prefer to face.
</P>
<P>
   But most observers view the rules as a revolution of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a risk, but democracy entails both risk and
opportunity,'' said Sergio Martinez, director of the Colosio
Foundation, the PRI's think tank.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
