<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-18 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2564 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-CUTS-N     05-18 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-CUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL GOP MAKING SPENDING CUTS IT ADMITS ARE PAINFUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans in Congress completed a plan on Tuesday
to cut domestic spending by tens of billions of dollars next year.
Their leaders warned that it would cause ``sticker shock'' and
political pain. The White House called it ``a blueprint for
political chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutting domestic spending by 11 percent might seem strange at a
time of budget surpluses and economic prosperity. But in 1997,
Congress and the White House agreed to spending caps to force down
federal spending. They are now chafing under the restraints they
embraced.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts will come in spending categories covering education,
job training, housing, health and human services, environmental
protection, medical and technological research, diplomacy and
foreign aid, among other federal programs. These follow $53 billion
in cuts in domestic spending since the Republicans won control of
Congress in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all knew this was going to be painful,'' the House majority
leader, Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said there would be ``sticker shock now in realizing just
how difficult it will be'' to stay within the spending caps.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning the House Appropriations Committee will
slice up a $538 billion budget pie _ what is left of the $1.75
trillion budget after paying for mandatory programs like Medicare _
for its 13 subcommittees. Under the committee's plan, the Defense
Department will receive about $270 billion, more than half the
money. Every other government agency would receive an aggregate of
about $268 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's final spending draft for the fiscal year 2000,
which will be formally approved on Wednesday, contains $26.3
billion in cuts for domestic spending, about 11 percent less than
what Congress meted out for this year, and a $18.9 billion increase
for the military, up about 7.5 percent, committee members said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress are moaning, ```Oh, oh, oh, we can't live up
to that,''' said the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott of
Mississippi. ``It's tough, but it ought to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, along with some Republicans and Democrats
in Congress, warned that the plan could lead to political
confrontation and presidential vetoes. Some predicted a repeat of
last year's spending stalemate, which ended in a frenzied,
last-minute omnibus spending bill larded with $21 billion in
extras. Others remembered the standoff that led to a partial
shutdown of the government in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican budget is a blueprint for chaos,'' said Jacob
J. Lew, the White House budget director. ``These allocations are a
sign of that. They would have unacceptable consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say the caps have shrunk domestic nonmilitary spending
to its smallest share of the national economy since 1962. They also
helped create a budget surplus, but at a cost. Not all Republicans
agree that they still make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's hardly a member of Congress that doesn't realize the
caps will be lifted,'' said Rep. John Edward Porter of Illinois, a
senior Republican on the Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But lifting the caps could violate promises made by Republican
leaders. It could result in more spending taken from surplus Social
Security funds, and it could blunt Republican plans for tax cuts,
splintering two of the biggest planks in their political platform
for the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Porter is one of 13 House Appropriations subcommittee chairmen _
they are called Congress' ``college of cardinals'' _ who will
divide the $538 billion in discretionary spending on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Porter's subcommittee, which oversees labor, education and
health programs, would receive nearly $11 billion less than last
year. The subcommittee overseeing the Veterans Administration and
the Department of Housing and Urban Development would take a $5.8
billion cut; the one overseeing the Commerce, State and Justice
Departments, a $2.8 billion cut; the Interior Department, $2.7
billion; foreign operations, $2.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittees must figure out how to divide their
allocations and pay for their programs under the caps before the
current fiscal year ends next Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, at least, the caps were irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 269 to 158, with 152 Republicans and 117 Democrats
voting in favor, the House on Tuesday night passed an emergency
spending bill of nearly $15 billion, twice what Clinton requested,
financing NATO's air war in Yugoslavia, relief for refugees in
Kosovo and aid for disaster victims in the United States and
Central America, along with billions in military projects.
</P>
<P>
   About $13 billion will come from surplus Social Security funds.
That money is designated as an emergency appropriation, meaning it
does not count under the spending caps. Most of the rest will come
from food stamp and low-income housing funds designated as surplus
and unlikely to be spent this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will take up the bill on Thursday. The president has
indicated he will sign it.
</P>
</TEXT>
